var P_HTM = [];
P_HTM[1]="*Namo tassa bhagavato arahato sammāsambuddhassa* **";
P_HTM[2]="*Dīghanikāyo* **";
P_HTM[3]="*Sīlakkhandhavaggapāḷi* **";
P_HTM[4]="*01. Brahmajālasutta  - The Prime Net * **";
P_HTM[5]="*1. Paribbājakakathā**1. Talk on Wanderers*";
P_HTM[6]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[7]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā antarā ca rājagahaṃ antarā ca nāḷandaṃ addhānamaggappaṭipanno hoti mahatā bhikkhusaṃghena saddhiṃ pañcamattehi bhikkhusatehi.**At one time the Buddha was traveling along the road between Rājagaha and Nālanda together with a large Saṅgha of around five hundred mendicants.*";
P_HTM[8]="*Suppiyopi kho paribbājako antarā ca rājagahaṃ antarā ca nāḷandaṃ addhānamaggappaṭipanno hoti saddhiṃ antevāsinā brahmadattena māṇavena.**The wanderer Suppiya was also traveling along the same road, together with his pupil, the brahmin student Brahmadatta.*";
P_HTM[9]="*Tatra sudaṃ suppiyo paribbājako anekapariyāyena buddhassa avaṇṇaṃ bhāsati, dhammassa avaṇṇaṃ bhāsati, saṃghassa avaṇṇaṃ bhāsati;**Meanwhile, Suppiya criticized the Buddha, the teaching, and the Saṅgha in many ways,*";
P_HTM[10]="*suppiyassa pana paribbājakassa antevāsī brahmadatto māṇavo anekapariyāyena buddhassa vaṇṇaṃ bhāsati, dhammassa vaṇṇaṃ bhāsati, saṃghassa vaṇṇaṃ bhāsati.**but his pupil Brahmadatta praised them in many ways.*";
P_HTM[11]="*Itiha te ubho ācariyantevāsī aññamaññassa ujuvipaccanīkavādā bhagavantaṃ piṭṭhito piṭṭhito anubandhā honti bhikkhusaṃghañca.**And so both teacher and pupil followed behind the Buddha and the Saṅgha of mendicants directly contradicting each other.*";
P_HTM[12]="*Atha kho bhagavā ambalaṭṭhikāyaṃ rājāgārake ekarattivāsaṃ upagacchi saddhiṃ bhikkhusaṃghena.**Then the Buddha took up residence for the night in the royal rest-house in Ambalaṭṭhikā together with the Saṅgha of mendicants.*";
P_HTM[13]="*Suppiyopi kho paribbājako ambalaṭṭhikāyaṃ rājāgārake ekarattivāsaṃ upagacchi antevāsinā brahmadattena māṇavena.**And Suppiya and Brahmadatta did likewise.*";
P_HTM[14]="*Tatrapi sudaṃ suppiyo paribbājako anekapariyāyena buddhassa avaṇṇaṃ bhāsati, dhammassa avaṇṇaṃ bhāsati, saṃghassa avaṇṇaṃ bhāsati;**There too, Suppiya criticized the Buddha, the teaching, and the Saṅgha in many ways,*";
P_HTM[15]="*suppiyassa pana paribbājakassa antevāsī brahmadatto māṇavo anekapariyāyena buddhassa vaṇṇaṃ bhāsati, dhammassa vaṇṇaṃ bhāsati, saṃghassa vaṇṇaṃ bhāsati.**but his pupil Brahmadatta praised them in many ways.*";
P_HTM[16]="*Itiha te ubho ācariyantevāsī aññamaññassa ujuvipaccanīkavādā viharanti.**And so both teacher and pupil kept on directly contradicting each other.*";
P_HTM[17]="*Atha kho sambahulānaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ rattiyā paccūsasamayaṃ paccuṭṭhitānaṃ maṇḍalamāḷe sannisinnānaṃ sannipatitānaṃ ayaṃ saṅkhiyadhammo udapādi:**Then several mendicants rose at the crack of dawn and sat together in the pavilion, where the topic of evaluation came up:*";
P_HTM[18]="*“acchariyaṃ, āvuso, abbhutaṃ, āvuso, yāvañcidaṃ tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena sattānaṃ nānādhimuttikatā suppaṭividitā.**“It’s incredible, reverends, it’s amazing how the diverse attitudes of sentient beings have been clearly comprehended by the Blessed One, who knows and sees, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha.*";
P_HTM[19]="*Ayañhi suppiyo paribbājako anekapariyāyena buddhassa avaṇṇaṃ bhāsati, dhammassa avaṇṇaṃ bhāsati, saṅghassa avaṇṇaṃ bhāsati;**For this Suppiya criticizes the Buddha, the teaching, and the Saṅgha in many ways,*";
P_HTM[20]="*suppiyassa pana paribbājakassa antevāsī brahmadatto māṇavo anekapariyāyena buddhassa vaṇṇaṃ bhāsati, dhammassa vaṇṇaṃ bhāsati, saṅghassa vaṇṇaṃ bhāsati.**while his pupil Brahmadatta praises them in many ways.*";
P_HTM[21]="*Itihame ubho ācariyantevāsī aññamaññassa ujuvipaccanīkavādā bhagavantaṃ piṭṭhito piṭṭhito anubandhā honti bhikkhusaṅghañcā”ti.**And so both teacher and pupil followed behind the Buddha and the Saṅgha of mendicants directly contradicting each other.”*";
P_HTM[22]="*Atha kho bhagavā tesaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ imaṃ saṅkhiyadhammaṃ viditvā yena maṇḍalamāḷo tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdi. Nisajja kho bhagavā bhikkhū āmantesi:**When the Buddha found out about this discussion on evaluation among the mendicants, he went to the pavilion, where he sat on the seat spread out and addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[23]="*“kāya nuttha, bhikkhave, etarahi kathāya sannisinnā sannipatitā, kā ca pana vo antarākathā vippakatā”ti?**“Mendicants, what were you sitting talking about just now? What conversation was left unfinished?”*";
P_HTM[24]="*Evaṃ vutte, te bhikkhū bhagavantaṃ etadavocuṃ:**The mendicants told him what had happened, adding,*";
P_HTM[25]="*“idha, bhante, amhākaṃ rattiyā paccūsasamayaṃ paccuṭṭhitānaṃ maṇḍalamāḷe sannisinnānaṃ sannipatitānaṃ ayaṃ saṅkhiyadhammo udapādi:* **";
P_HTM[26]="*‘acchariyaṃ, āvuso, abbhutaṃ, āvuso, yāvañcidaṃ tena bhagavatā jānatā passatā arahatā sammāsambuddhena sattānaṃ nānādhimuttikatā suppaṭividitā.* **";
P_HTM[27]="*Ayañhi suppiyo paribbājako anekapariyāyena buddhassa avaṇṇaṃ bhāsati, dhammassa avaṇṇaṃ bhāsati, saṅghassa avaṇṇaṃ bhāsati;* **";
P_HTM[28]="*suppiyassa pana paribbājakassa antevāsī brahmadatto māṇavo anekapariyāyena buddhassa vaṇṇaṃ bhāsati, dhammassa vaṇṇaṃ bhāsati, saṅghassa vaṇṇaṃ bhāsati.* **";
P_HTM[29]="*Itihame ubho ācariyantevāsī aññamaññassa ujuvipaccanīkavādā bhagavantaṃ piṭṭhito piṭṭhito anubandhā honti bhikkhusaṅghañcā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[30]="*Ayaṃ kho no, bhante, antarākathā vippakatā, atha bhagavā anuppatto”ti.**“This was our conversation that was unfinished when the Buddha arrived.”*";
P_HTM[31]="*“Mamaṃ vā, bhikkhave, pare avaṇṇaṃ bhāseyyuṃ, dhammassa vā avaṇṇaṃ bhāseyyuṃ, saṅghassa vā avaṇṇaṃ bhāseyyuṃ, tatra tumhehi na āghāto na appaccayo na cetaso anabhiraddhi karaṇīyā.**“Mendicants, if others criticize me, the teaching, or the Saṅgha, don’t make yourselves resentful, bitter, and exasperated.*";
P_HTM[32]="*Mamaṃ vā, bhikkhave, pare avaṇṇaṃ bhāseyyuṃ, dhammassa vā avaṇṇaṃ bhāseyyuṃ, saṅghassa vā avaṇṇaṃ bhāseyyuṃ, tatra ce tumhe assatha kupitā vā anattamanā vā, tumhaṃ yevassa tena antarāyo.**You’ll get angry and upset, which would be an obstacle for you alone.*";
P_HTM[33]="*Mamaṃ vā, bhikkhave, pare avaṇṇaṃ bhāseyyuṃ, dhammassa vā avaṇṇaṃ bhāseyyuṃ, saṅghassa vā avaṇṇaṃ bhāseyyuṃ, tatra ce tumhe assatha kupitā vā anattamanā vā, api nu tumhe paresaṃ subhāsitaṃ dubbhāsitaṃ ājāneyyāthā”ti?**If others were to criticize me, the teaching, or the Saṅgha, and you got angry and upset, would you be able to understand whether they spoke well or poorly?”*";
P_HTM[34]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante”.**“No, sir.”*";
P_HTM[35]="*“Mamaṃ vā, bhikkhave, pare avaṇṇaṃ bhāseyyuṃ, dhammassa vā avaṇṇaṃ bhāseyyuṃ, saṅghassa vā avaṇṇaṃ bhāseyyuṃ, tatra tumhehi abhūtaṃ abhūtato nibbeṭhetabbaṃ:**“If others criticize me, the teaching, or the Saṅgha, you should explain that what is untrue is in fact untrue:*";
P_HTM[36]="*‘itipetaṃ abhūtaṃ, itipetaṃ atacchaṃ, natthi cetaṃ amhesu, na ca panetaṃ amhesu saṃvijjatī’ti.**‘This is why that’s untrue, this is why that’s false. There’s no such thing in us, it’s not found among us.’*";
P_HTM[37]="*Mamaṃ vā, bhikkhave, pare vaṇṇaṃ bhāseyyuṃ, dhammassa vā vaṇṇaṃ bhāseyyuṃ, saṃghassa vā vaṇṇaṃ bhāseyyuṃ, tatra tumhehi na ānando na somanassaṃ na cetaso uppilāvitattaṃ karaṇīyaṃ.**If others praise me, the teaching, or the Saṅgha, don’t make yourselves thrilled, elated, and excited.*";
P_HTM[38]="*Mamaṃ vā, bhikkhave, pare vaṇṇaṃ bhāseyyuṃ, dhammassa vā vaṇṇaṃ bhāseyyuṃ, saṃghassa vā vaṇṇaṃ bhāseyyuṃ, tatra ce tumhe assatha ānandino sumanā uppilāvitā tumhaṃ yevassa tena antarāyo.**You’ll get thrilled, elated, and excited, which would be an obstacle for you alone.*";
P_HTM[39]="*Mamaṃ vā, bhikkhave, pare vaṇṇaṃ bhāseyyuṃ, dhammassa vā vaṇṇaṃ bhāseyyuṃ, saṃghassa vā vaṇṇaṃ bhāseyyuṃ, tatra tumhehi bhūtaṃ bhūtato paṭijānitabbaṃ:**If others praise me, the teaching, or the Saṅgha, you should acknowledge that what is true is in fact true:*";
P_HTM[40]="*‘itipetaṃ bhūtaṃ, itipetaṃ tacchaṃ, atthi cetaṃ amhesu, saṃvijjati ca panetaṃ amhesū’ti.**‘This is why that’s true, this is why that’s correct. There is such a thing in us, it is found among us.’*";
P_HTM[41]="*2. Sīla**2. Ethics*";
P_HTM[42]="*2.1. Cūḷasīla**2.1. The Shorter Section on Ethics*";
P_HTM[43]="*Appamattakaṃ kho panetaṃ, bhikkhave, oramattakaṃ sīlamattakaṃ, yena puthujjano tathāgatassa vaṇṇaṃ vadamāno vadeyya.**When an ordinary person speaks praise of the Realized One, they speak only of trivial, insignificant details of mere ethics.*";
P_HTM[44]="*Katamañca taṃ, bhikkhave, appamattakaṃ oramattakaṃ sīlamattakaṃ, yena puthujjano tathāgatassa vaṇṇaṃ vadamāno vadeyya?**And what are the trivial, insignificant details of mere ethics that an ordinary person speaks of?*";
P_HTM[45]="*‘Pāṇātipātaṃ pahāya pāṇātipātā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo nihitadaṇḍo, nihitasattho, lajjī, dayāpanno, sabbapāṇabhūtahitānukampī viharatī’ti—**‘The ascetic Gotama has given up killing living creatures. He has renounced the rod and the sword. He’s scrupulous and kind, living full of compassion for all living beings.’*";
P_HTM[46]="*iti vā hi, bhikkhave, puthujjano tathāgatassa vaṇṇaṃ vadamāno vadeyya.**Such is an ordinary person’s praise of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[47]="*‘Adinnādānaṃ pahāya adinnādānā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo dinnādāyī dinnapāṭikaṅkhī, athenena sucibhūtena attanā viharatī’ti—**‘The ascetic Gotama has given up stealing. He takes only what’s given, and expects only what’s given. He keeps himself clean by not thieving.’*";
P_HTM[48]="*iti vā hi, bhikkhave, puthujjano tathāgatassa vaṇṇaṃ vadamāno vadeyya.**Such is an ordinary person’s praise of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[49]="*‘Abrahmacariyaṃ pahāya brahmacārī samaṇo gotamo ārācārī virato methunā gāmadhammā’ti—**‘The ascetic Gotama has given up unchastity. He is celibate, set apart, avoiding the common practice of sex.’*";
P_HTM[50]="*iti vā hi, bhikkhave, puthujjano tathāgatassa vaṇṇaṃ vadamāno vadeyya.**Such is an ordinary person’s praise of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[51]="*‘Musāvādaṃ pahāya musāvādā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo saccavādī saccasandho theto paccayiko avisaṃvādako lokassā’ti—**‘The ascetic Gotama has given up lying. He speaks the truth and sticks to the truth. He’s honest and trustworthy, and doesn’t trick the world with his words.’*";
P_HTM[52]="*iti vā hi, bhikkhave, puthujjano tathāgatassa vaṇṇaṃ vadamāno vadeyya.**Such is an ordinary person’s praise of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[53]="*‘Pisuṇaṃ vācaṃ pahāya pisuṇāya vācāya paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo, ito sutvā na amutra akkhātā imesaṃ bhedāya, amutra vā sutvā na imesaṃ akkhātā amūsaṃ bhedāya. Iti bhinnānaṃ vā sandhātā, sahitānaṃ vā anuppadātā samaggārāmo samaggarato samagganandī samaggakaraṇiṃ vācaṃ bhāsitā’ti—**‘The ascetic Gotama has given up divisive speech. He doesn’t repeat in one place what he heard in another so as to divide people against each other. Instead, he reconciles those who are divided, supporting unity, delighting in harmony, loving harmony, speaking words that promote harmony.’*";
P_HTM[54]="*iti vā hi, bhikkhave, puthujjano tathāgatassa vaṇṇaṃ vadamāno vadeyya.**Such is an ordinary person’s praise of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[55]="*‘Pharusaṃ vācaṃ pahāya pharusāya vācāya paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo, yā sā vācā nelā kaṇṇasukhā pemanīyā hadayaṅgamā porī bahujanakantā bahujanamanāpā tathārūpiṃ vācaṃ bhāsitā’ti—**‘The ascetic Gotama has given up harsh speech. He speaks in a way that’s mellow, pleasing to the ear, lovely, going to the heart, polite, likable and agreeable to the people.’*";
P_HTM[56]="*iti vā hi, bhikkhave, puthujjano tathāgatassa vaṇṇaṃ vadamāno vadeyya.**Such is an ordinary person’s praise of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[57]="*‘Samphappalāpaṃ pahāya samphappalāpā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo kālavādī bhūtavādī atthavādī dhammavādī vinayavādī, nidhānavatiṃ vācaṃ bhāsitā kālena sāpadesaṃ pariyantavatiṃ atthasaṃhitan’ti—**‘The ascetic Gotama has given up talking nonsense. His words are timely, true, and meaningful, in line with the teaching and training. He says things at the right time which are valuable, reasonable, succinct, and beneficial.’*";
P_HTM[58]="*iti vā hi, bhikkhave, puthujjano tathāgatassa vaṇṇaṃ vadamāno vadeyya.**Such is an ordinary person’s praise of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[59]="*‘Bījagāmabhūtagāmasamārambhā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo’ti—**‘The ascetic Gotama refrains from injuring plants and seeds.’*";
P_HTM[60]="*iti vā hi, bhikkhave … pe ….* **";
P_HTM[61]="*‘Ekabhattiko samaṇo gotamo rattūparato virato vikālabhojanā ….**‘He eats in one part of the day, abstaining from eating at night and food at the wrong time.’*";
P_HTM[62]="*Naccagītavāditavisūkadassanā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo ….**‘He refrains from dancing, singing, music, and seeing shows.’*";
P_HTM[63]="*Mālāgandhavilepanadhāraṇamaṇḍanavibhūsanaṭṭhānā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo ….**‘He refrains from beautifying and adorning himself with garlands, perfumes, and makeup.’*";
P_HTM[64]="*Uccāsayanamahāsayanā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo ….**‘He refrains from high and luxurious beds.’*";
P_HTM[65]="*Jātarūparajatapaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo ….**‘He refrains from receiving gold and money,*";
P_HTM[66]="*Āmakadhaññapaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo ….**raw grains,*";
P_HTM[67]="*Āmakamaṃsapaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo ….**raw meat,*";
P_HTM[68]="*Itthikumārikapaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo ….**women and girls,*";
P_HTM[69]="*Dāsidāsapaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo ….**male and female bondservants,*";
P_HTM[70]="*Ajeḷakapaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo ….**goats and sheep,*";
P_HTM[71]="*Kukkuṭasūkarapaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo ….**chickens and pigs,*";
P_HTM[72]="*Hatthigavassavaḷavapaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo ….**elephants, cows, horses, and mares,*";
P_HTM[73]="*Khettavatthupaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo ….**and fields and land.’*";
P_HTM[74]="*Dūteyyapahiṇagamanānuyogā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo ….**‘He refrains from running errands and messages;*";
P_HTM[75]="*Kayavikkayā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo ….**buying and selling;*";
P_HTM[76]="*Tulākūṭakaṃsakūṭamānakūṭā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo ….**falsifying weights, metals, or measures;*";
P_HTM[77]="*Ukkoṭanavañcananikatisāciyogā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo ….**bribery, fraud, cheating, and duplicity;*";
P_HTM[78]="*Chedanavadhabandhanaviparāmosaālopasahasākārā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo’ti—**mutilation, murder, abduction, banditry, plunder, and violence.’*";
P_HTM[79]="*iti vā hi, bhikkhave, puthujjano tathāgatassa vaṇṇaṃ vadamāno vadeyya.**Such is an ordinary person’s praise of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[80]="*Cūḷasīlaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ.**The shorter section on ethics is finished.*";
P_HTM[81]="*2.2. Majjhimasīla**2.2. The Middle Section on Ethics*";
P_HTM[82]="*‘Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpaṃ bījagāmabhūtagāmasamārambhaṃ anuyuttā viharanti,**‘There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still engage in injuring plants and seeds.*";
P_HTM[83]="*seyyathidaṃ—mūlabījaṃ khandhabījaṃ phaḷubījaṃ aggabījaṃ bījabījameva pañcamaṃ;**These include plants propagated from roots, stems, cuttings, or joints; and those from regular seeds as the fifth.*";
P_HTM[84]="*iti evarūpā bījagāmabhūtagāmasamārambhā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo’ti—**The ascetic Gotama refrains from such injury to plants and seeds.’*";
P_HTM[85]="*iti vā hi, bhikkhave, puthujjano tathāgatassa vaṇṇaṃ vadamāno vadeyya.**Such is an ordinary person’s praise of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[86]="*‘Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpaṃ sannidhikāraparibhogaṃ anuyuttā viharanti,**‘There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still engage in storing up goods for their own use.*";
P_HTM[87]="*seyyathidaṃ—annasannidhiṃ pānasannidhiṃ vatthasannidhiṃ yānasannidhiṃ sayanasannidhiṃ gandhasannidhiṃ āmisasannidhiṃ**This includes such things as food, drink, clothes, vehicles, bedding, fragrance, and material possessions.*";
P_HTM[88]="*iti vā iti evarūpā sannidhikāraparibhogā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo’ti—**The ascetic Gotama refrains from storing up such goods.’*";
P_HTM[89]="*iti vā hi, bhikkhave, puthujjano tathāgatassa vaṇṇaṃ vadamāno vadeyya.**Such is an ordinary person’s praise of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[90]="*‘Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpaṃ visūkadassanaṃ anuyuttā viharanti,**‘There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still engage in seeing shows.*";
P_HTM[91]="*seyyathidaṃ—naccaṃ gītaṃ vāditaṃ pekkhaṃ akkhānaṃ pāṇissaraṃ vetāḷaṃ kumbhathūṇaṃ sobhanakaṃ caṇḍālaṃ vaṃsaṃ dhovanaṃ hatthiyuddhaṃ assayuddhaṃ mahiṃsayuddhaṃ usabhayuddhaṃ ajayuddhaṃ meṇḍayuddhaṃ kukkuṭayuddhaṃ vaṭṭakayuddhaṃ daṇḍayuddhaṃ muṭṭhiyuddhaṃ nibbuddhaṃ uyyodhikaṃ balaggaṃ senābyūhaṃ anīkadassanaṃ**This includes such things as dancing, singing, music, performances, and storytelling; clapping, gongs, and kettle-drums; art exhibitions and acrobatic displays; battles of elephants, horses, buffaloes, bulls, goats, rams, chickens, and quails; staff-fights, boxing, and wrestling; combat, roll calls of the armed forces, battle-formations, and regimental reviews.*";
P_HTM[92]="*iti vā iti evarūpā visūkadassanā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo’ti—**The ascetic Gotama refrains from such shows.’*";
P_HTM[93]="*iti vā hi, bhikkhave, puthujjano tathāgatassa vaṇṇaṃ vadamāno vadeyya.**Such is an ordinary person’s praise of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[94]="*‘Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpaṃ jūtappamādaṭṭhānānuyogaṃ anuyuttā viharanti,**‘There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still engage in gambling that causes negligence.*";
P_HTM[95]="*seyyathidaṃ—aṭṭhapadaṃ dasapadaṃ ākāsaṃ parihārapathaṃ santikaṃ khalikaṃ ghaṭikaṃ salākahatthaṃ akkhaṃ paṅgacīraṃ vaṅkakaṃ mokkhacikaṃ ciṅgulikaṃ pattāḷhakaṃ rathakaṃ dhanukaṃ akkharikaṃ manesikaṃ yathāvajjaṃ**This includes such things as checkers, draughts, checkers in the air, hopscotch, spillikins, board-games, tip-cat, drawing straws, dice, leaf-flutes, toy plows, somersaults, pinwheels, toy measures, toy carts, toy bows, guessing words from syllables, and guessing another’s thoughts.*";
P_HTM[96]="*iti vā iti evarūpā jūtappamādaṭṭhānānuyogā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo’ti—**The ascetic Gotama refrains from such gambling.’*";
P_HTM[97]="*iti vā hi, bhikkhave, puthujjano tathāgatassa vaṇṇaṃ vadamāno vadeyya.**Such is an ordinary person’s praise of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[98]="*‘Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpaṃ uccāsayanamahāsayanaṃ anuyuttā viharanti,**‘There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still make use of high and luxurious bedding.*";
P_HTM[99]="*seyyathidaṃ—āsandiṃ pallaṅkaṃ gonakaṃ cittakaṃ paṭikaṃ paṭalikaṃ tūlikaṃ vikatikaṃ uddalomiṃ ekantalomiṃ kaṭṭissaṃ koseyyaṃ kuttakaṃ hatthattharaṃ assattharaṃ rathattharaṃ ajinappaveṇiṃ kadalimigapavarapaccattharaṇaṃ sauttaracchadaṃ ubhatolohitakūpadhānaṃ**This includes such things as sofas, couches, woolen covers—shag-piled, colorful, white, embroidered with flowers, quilted, embroidered with animals, double- or single-fringed—and silk covers studded with gems, as well as silken sheets, woven carpets, rugs for elephants, horses, or chariots, antelope hide rugs, and spreads of fine deer hide, with a canopy above and red cushions at both ends.*";
P_HTM[100]="*iti vā iti evarūpā uccāsayanamahāsayanā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo’ti—**The ascetic Gotama refrains from such bedding.’*";
P_HTM[101]="*iti vā hi, bhikkhave, puthujjano tathāgatassa vaṇṇaṃ vadamāno vadeyya.**Such is an ordinary person’s praise of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[102]="*‘Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpaṃ maṇḍanavibhūsanaṭṭhānānuyogaṃ anuyuttā viharanti, seyyathidaṃ—**‘There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still engage in beautifying and adorning themselves with garlands, fragrance, and makeup.*";
P_HTM[103]="*ucchādanaṃ parimaddanaṃ nhāpanaṃ sambāhanaṃ ādāsaṃ añjanaṃ mālāgandhavilepanaṃ mukhacuṇṇaṃ mukhalepanaṃ hatthabandhaṃ sikhābandhaṃ daṇḍaṃ nāḷikaṃ asiṃ chattaṃ citrupāhanaṃ uṇhīsaṃ maṇiṃ vālabījaniṃ odātāni vatthāni dīghadasāni**This includes such things as applying beauty products by anointing, massaging, bathing, and rubbing; mirrors, ointments, garlands, fragrances, and makeup; face-powder, foundation, bracelets, headbands, fancy walking-sticks or containers, rapiers, parasols, fancy sandals, turbans, jewelry, chowries, and long-fringed white robes.*";
P_HTM[104]="*iti vā iti evarūpā maṇḍanavibhūsanaṭṭhānānuyogā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo’ti—**The ascetic Gotama refrains from such beautification and adornment.’*";
P_HTM[105]="*iti vā hi, bhikkhave, puthujjano tathāgatassa vaṇṇaṃ vadamāno vadeyya.**Such is an ordinary person’s praise of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[106]="*‘Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpaṃ tiracchānakathaṃ anuyuttā viharanti,**‘There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still engage in unworthy talk. This includes such topics as*";
P_HTM[107]="*seyyathidaṃ—rājakathaṃ corakathaṃ mahāmattakathaṃ senākathaṃ bhayakathaṃ yuddhakathaṃ annakathaṃ pānakathaṃ vatthakathaṃ sayanakathaṃ mālākathaṃ gandhakathaṃ ñātikathaṃ yānakathaṃ gāmakathaṃ nigamakathaṃ nagarakathaṃ janapadakathaṃ itthikathaṃ sūrakathaṃ visikhākathaṃ kumbhaṭṭhānakathaṃ pubbapetakathaṃ nānattakathaṃ lokakkhāyikaṃ samuddakkhāyikaṃ itibhavābhavakathaṃ**talk about kings, bandits, and ministers; talk about armies, threats, and wars; talk about food, drink, clothes, and beds; talk about garlands and fragrances; talk about family, vehicles, villages, towns, cities, and countries; talk about women and heroes; street talk and well talk; talk about the departed; motley talk; tales of land and sea; and talk about being reborn in this or that state of existence.*";
P_HTM[108]="*iti vā iti evarūpāya tiracchānakathāya paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo’ti—**The ascetic Gotama refrains from such unworthy talk.’*";
P_HTM[109]="*iti vā hi, bhikkhave, puthujjano tathāgatassa vaṇṇaṃ vadamāno vadeyya.**Such is an ordinary person’s praise of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[110]="*‘Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpaṃ viggāhikakathaṃ anuyuttā viharanti,**‘There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still engage in arguments.*";
P_HTM[111]="*seyyathidaṃ—na tvaṃ imaṃ dhammavinayaṃ ājānāsi, ahaṃ imaṃ dhammavinayaṃ ājānāmi, kiṃ tvaṃ imaṃ dhammavinayaṃ ājānissasi, micchā paṭipanno tvamasi, ahamasmi sammā paṭipanno, sahitaṃ me, asahitaṃ te, purevacanīyaṃ pacchā avaca, pacchāvacanīyaṃ pure avaca, adhiciṇṇaṃ te viparāvattaṃ, āropito te vādo, niggahito tvamasi, cara vādappamokkhāya, nibbeṭhehi vā sace pahosīti**They say such things as: “You don’t understand this teaching and training. I understand this teaching and training. What, you understand this teaching and training? You’re practicing wrong. I’m practicing right. I stay on topic, you don’t. You said last what you should have said first. You said first what you should have said last. What you’ve thought so much about has been disproved. Your doctrine is refuted. Go on, save your doctrine! You’re trapped; get yourself out of this—if you can!”*";
P_HTM[112]="*iti vā iti evarūpāya viggāhikakathāya paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo’ti—**The ascetic Gotama refrains from such argumentative talk.’*";
P_HTM[113]="*iti vā hi, bhikkhave, puthujjano tathāgatassa vaṇṇaṃ vadamāno vadeyya.**Such is an ordinary person’s praise of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[114]="*‘Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpaṃ dūteyyapahiṇagamanānuyogaṃ anuyuttā viharanti,**‘There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still engage in running errands and messages.*";
P_HTM[115]="*seyyathidaṃ—raññaṃ, rājamahāmattānaṃ, khattiyānaṃ, brāhmaṇānaṃ, gahapatikānaṃ, kumārānaṃ “idha gaccha, amutrāgaccha, idaṃ hara, amutra idaṃ āharā”ti**This includes running errands for rulers, ministers, aristocrats, brahmins, householders, or princes who say: “Go here, go there. Take this, bring that from there.”*";
P_HTM[116]="*iti vā iti evarūpā dūteyyapahiṇagamanānuyogā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo’ti—**The ascetic Gotama refrains from such errands.’*";
P_HTM[117]="*iti vā hi, bhikkhave, puthujjano tathāgatassa vaṇṇaṃ vadamāno vadeyya.**Such is an ordinary person’s praise of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[118]="*‘Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te kuhakā ca honti, lapakā ca nemittikā ca nippesikā ca, lābhena lābhaṃ nijigīsitāro ca**‘There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still engage in deceit, flattery, hinting, and belittling, and using material possessions to pursue other material possessions.*";
P_HTM[119]="*iti evarūpā kuhanalapanā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo’ti—**The ascetic Gotama refrains from such deceit and flattery.’*";
P_HTM[120]="*iti vā hi, bhikkhave, puthujjano tathāgatassa vaṇṇaṃ vadamāno vadeyya.**Such is an ordinary person’s praise of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[121]="*Majjhimasīlaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ.**The middle section on ethics is finished.*";
P_HTM[122]="*2.3. Mahāsīla**2.3. The Large Section on Ethics*";
P_HTM[123]="*‘Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpāya tiracchānavijjāya micchājīvena jīvitaṃ kappenti,**‘There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still earn a living by unworthy branches of knowledge, by wrong livelihood.*";
P_HTM[124]="*seyyathidaṃ—aṅgaṃ nimittaṃ uppātaṃ supinaṃ lakkhaṇaṃ mūsikacchinnaṃ aggihomaṃ dabbihomaṃ thusahomaṃ kaṇahomaṃ taṇḍulahomaṃ sappihomaṃ telahomaṃ mukhahomaṃ lohitahomaṃ aṅgavijjā vatthuvijjā khattavijjā sivavijjā bhūtavijjā bhūrivijjā ahivijjā visavijjā vicchikavijjā mūsikavijjā sakuṇavijjā vāyasavijjā pakkajjhānaṃ saraparittāṇaṃ migacakkaṃ**This includes such fields as limb-reading, omenology, divining celestial portents, interpreting dreams, divining bodily marks, divining holes in cloth gnawed by mice, fire offerings, ladle offerings, offerings of husks, rice powder, rice, ghee, or oil; offerings from the mouth, blood sacrifices, palmistry; geomancy for building sites, fields, and cemeteries; exorcisms, earth magic, snake charming, poisons; the crafts of the scorpion, the rat, the bird, and the crow; prophesying life span, chanting for protection, and animal cries.*";
P_HTM[125]="*iti vā iti evarūpāya tiracchānavijjāya micchājīvā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo’ti—**The ascetic Gotama refrains from such unworthy branches of knowledge, such wrong livelihood.’*";
P_HTM[126]="*iti vā hi, bhikkhave, puthujjano tathāgatassa vaṇṇaṃ vadamāno vadeyya.**Such is an ordinary person’s praise of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[127]="*‘Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpāya tiracchānavijjāya micchājīvena jīvitaṃ kappenti,**‘There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still earn a living by unworthy branches of knowledge, by wrong livelihood.*";
P_HTM[128]="*seyyathidaṃ—maṇilakkhaṇaṃ vatthalakkhaṇaṃ daṇḍalakkhaṇaṃ satthalakkhaṇaṃ asilakkhaṇaṃ usulakkhaṇaṃ dhanulakkhaṇaṃ āvudhalakkhaṇaṃ itthilakkhaṇaṃ purisalakkhaṇaṃ kumāralakkhaṇaṃ kumārilakkhaṇaṃ dāsalakkhaṇaṃ dāsilakkhaṇaṃ hatthilakkhaṇaṃ assalakkhaṇaṃ mahiṃsalakkhaṇaṃ usabhalakkhaṇaṃ golakkhaṇaṃ ajalakkhaṇaṃ meṇḍalakkhaṇaṃ kukkuṭalakkhaṇaṃ vaṭṭakalakkhaṇaṃ godhālakkhaṇaṃ kaṇṇikālakkhaṇaṃ kacchapalakkhaṇaṃ migalakkhaṇaṃ**This includes reading the marks of gems, cloth, clubs, swords, spears, arrows, weapons, women, men, boys, girls, male and female bondservants, elephants, horses, buffaloes, bulls, cows, goats, rams, chickens, quails, monitor lizards, rabbits, tortoises, or deer.*";
P_HTM[129]="*iti vā iti evarūpāya tiracchānavijjāya micchājīvā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo’ti—**The ascetic Gotama refrains from such unworthy branches of knowledge, such wrong livelihood.’*";
P_HTM[130]="*iti vā hi, bhikkhave, puthujjano tathāgatassa vaṇṇaṃ vadamāno vadeyya.**Such is an ordinary person’s praise of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[131]="*‘Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpāya tiracchānavijjāya micchājīvena jīvitaṃ kappenti,**‘There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still earn a living by unworthy branches of knowledge, by wrong livelihood.*";
P_HTM[132]="*seyyathidaṃ—raññaṃ niyyānaṃ bhavissati, raññaṃ aniyyānaṃ bhavissati, abbhantarānaṃ raññaṃ upayānaṃ bhavissati, bāhirānaṃ raññaṃ apayānaṃ bhavissati, bāhirānaṃ raññaṃ upayānaṃ bhavissati, abbhantarānaṃ raññaṃ apayānaṃ bhavissati, abbhantarānaṃ raññaṃ jayo bhavissati, bāhirānaṃ raññaṃ parājayo bhavissati, bāhirānaṃ raññaṃ jayo bhavissati, abbhantarānaṃ raññaṃ parājayo bhavissati, iti imassa jayo bhavissati, imassa parājayo bhavissati**This includes making predictions that the king will march forth or march back; or that our king will attack and the enemy king will retreat, or vice versa; or that our king will triumph and the enemy king will be defeated, or vice versa; and so there will be victory for one and defeat for the other.*";
P_HTM[133]="*iti vā iti evarūpāya tiracchānavijjāya micchājīvā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo’ti—**The ascetic Gotama refrains from such unworthy branches of knowledge, such wrong livelihood.’*";
P_HTM[134]="*iti vā hi, bhikkhave, puthujjano tathāgatassa vaṇṇaṃ vadamāno vadeyya.**Such is an ordinary person’s praise of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[135]="*‘Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpāya tiracchānavijjāya micchājīvena jīvitaṃ kappenti,**‘There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still earn a living by unworthy branches of knowledge, by wrong livelihood.*";
P_HTM[136]="*seyyathidaṃ—candaggāho bhavissati, sūriyaggāho bhavissati, nakkhattaggāho bhavissati, candimasūriyānaṃ pathagamanaṃ bhavissati, candimasūriyānaṃ uppathagamanaṃ bhavissati, nakkhattānaṃ pathagamanaṃ bhavissati, nakkhattānaṃ uppathagamanaṃ bhavissati, ukkāpāto bhavissati, disāḍāho bhavissati, bhūmicālo bhavissati, devadudrabhi bhavissati, candimasūriyanakkhattānaṃ uggamanaṃ ogamanaṃ saṃkilesaṃ vodānaṃ bhavissati, evaṃvipāko candaggāho bhavissati, evaṃvipāko sūriyaggāho bhavissati, evaṃvipāko nakkhattaggāho bhavissati, evaṃvipākaṃ candimasūriyānaṃ pathagamanaṃ bhavissati, evaṃvipākaṃ candimasūriyānaṃ uppathagamanaṃ bhavissati, evaṃvipākaṃ nakkhattānaṃ pathagamanaṃ bhavissati, evaṃvipākaṃ nakkhattānaṃ uppathagamanaṃ bhavissati, evaṃvipāko ukkāpāto bhavissati, evaṃvipāko disāḍāho bhavissati, evaṃvipāko bhūmicālo bhavissati, evaṃvipāko devadudrabhi bhavissati, evaṃvipākaṃ candimasūriyanakkhattānaṃ uggamanaṃ ogamanaṃ saṃkilesaṃ vodānaṃ bhavissati**This includes making predictions that there will be an eclipse of the moon, or sun, or stars; that the sun, moon, and stars will be in conjunction or in opposition; that there will be a meteor shower, a fiery sky, an earthquake, thunder; that there will be a rising, a setting, a darkening, a brightening of the moon, sun, and stars. And it also includes making predictions about the results of all such phenomena.*";
P_HTM[137]="*iti vā iti evarūpāya tiracchānavijjāya micchājīvā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo’ti—**The ascetic Gotama refrains from such unworthy branches of knowledge, such wrong livelihood.’*";
P_HTM[138]="*iti vā hi, bhikkhave, puthujjano tathāgatassa vaṇṇaṃ vadamāno vadeyya.**Such is an ordinary person’s praise of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[139]="*‘Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpāya tiracchānavijjāya micchājīvena jīvitaṃ kappenti,**‘There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still earn a living by unworthy branches of knowledge, by wrong livelihood.*";
P_HTM[140]="*seyyathidaṃ—suvuṭṭhikā bhavissati, dubbuṭṭhikā bhavissati, subhikkhaṃ bhavissati, dubbhikkhaṃ bhavissati, khemaṃ bhavissati, bhayaṃ bhavissati, rogo bhavissati, ārogyaṃ bhavissati, muddā, gaṇanā, saṅkhānaṃ, kāveyyaṃ, lokāyataṃ**This includes predicting whether there will be plenty of rain or drought; plenty to eat or famine; an abundant harvest or a bad harvest; security or peril; sickness or health. It also includes such occupations as computing, accounting, calculating, poetry, and cosmology.*";
P_HTM[141]="*iti vā iti evarūpāya tiracchānavijjāya micchājīvā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo’ti—**The ascetic Gotama refrains from such unworthy branches of knowledge, such wrong livelihood.’*";
P_HTM[142]="*iti vā hi, bhikkhave, puthujjano tathāgatassa vaṇṇaṃ vadamāno vadeyya.**Such is an ordinary person’s praise of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[143]="*‘Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpāya tiracchānavijjāya micchājīvena jīvitaṃ kappenti,**‘There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still earn a living by unworthy branches of knowledge, by wrong livelihood.*";
P_HTM[144]="*seyyathidaṃ—āvāhanaṃ vivāhanaṃ saṃvaraṇaṃ vivaraṇaṃ saṃkiraṇaṃ vikiraṇaṃ subhagakaraṇaṃ dubbhagakaraṇaṃ viruddhagabbhakaraṇaṃ jivhānibandhanaṃ hanusaṃhananaṃ hatthābhijappanaṃ hanujappanaṃ kaṇṇajappanaṃ ādāsapañhaṃ kumārikapañhaṃ devapañhaṃ ādiccupaṭṭhānaṃ mahatupaṭṭhānaṃ abbhujjalanaṃ sirivhāyanaṃ**This includes making arrangements for giving and taking in marriage; for engagement and divorce; and for scattering rice inwards or outwards at the wedding ceremony. It also includes casting spells for good or bad luck, curses to prevent conception, bind the tongue, or lock the jaws; charms for the hands and ears; questioning a mirror, a girl, or a god as an oracle; worshiping the sun, worshiping the Great One, breathing fire, and invoking Siri, the goddess of luck.*";
P_HTM[145]="*iti vā iti evarūpāya tiracchānavijjāya micchājīvā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo’ti—**The ascetic Gotama refrains from such unworthy branches of knowledge, such wrong livelihood.’*";
P_HTM[146]="*iti vā hi, bhikkhave, puthujjano tathāgatassa vaṇṇaṃ vadamāno vadeyya.**Such is an ordinary person’s praise of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[147]="*‘Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpāya tiracchānavijjāya micchājīvena jīvitaṃ kappenti,**‘There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still earn a living by unworthy branches of knowledge, by wrong livelihood.*";
P_HTM[148]="*seyyathidaṃ—santikammaṃ paṇidhikammaṃ bhūtakammaṃ bhūrikammaṃ vassakammaṃ vossakammaṃ vatthukammaṃ vatthuparikammaṃ ācamanaṃ nhāpanaṃ juhanaṃ vamanaṃ virecanaṃ uddhaṃvirecanaṃ adhovirecanaṃ sīsavirecanaṃ kaṇṇatelaṃ nettatappanaṃ natthukammaṃ añjanaṃ paccañjanaṃ sālākiyaṃ sallakattiyaṃ dārakatikicchā mūlabhesajjānaṃ anuppadānaṃ osadhīnaṃ paṭimokkho**This includes rites for propitiation, for granting wishes, for ghosts, for the earth, for rain, for property settlement, and for preparing and consecrating house sites, and rites involving rinsing and bathing, and oblations. It also includes administering emetics, purgatives, expectorants, and phlegmagogues; administering ear-oils, eye restoratives, nasal medicine, ointments, and counter-ointments; surgery with needle and scalpel, treating children, prescribing root medicines, and binding on herbs.*";
P_HTM[149]="*iti vā iti evarūpāya tiracchānavijjāya micchājīvā paṭivirato samaṇo gotamo’ti—**The ascetic Gotama refrains from such unworthy branches of knowledge, such wrong livelihood.’*";
P_HTM[150]="*iti vā hi, bhikkhave, puthujjano tathāgatassa vaṇṇaṃ vadamāno vadeyya.**Such is an ordinary person’s praise of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[151]="*Idaṃ kho, bhikkhave, appamattakaṃ oramattakaṃ sīlamattakaṃ, yena puthujjano tathāgatassa vaṇṇaṃ vadamāno vadeyya.**These are the trivial, insignificant details of mere ethics that an ordinary person speaks of when they speak praise of the Realized One.*";
P_HTM[152]="*Mahāsīlaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ.**The longer section on ethics is finished.*";
P_HTM[153]="*3. Diṭṭhi**3. Views*";
P_HTM[154]="*3.1. Pubbantakappika**3.1. Theories About the Past*";
P_HTM[155]="*Atthi, bhikkhave, aññeva dhammā gambhīrā duddasā duranubodhā santā paṇītā atakkāvacarā nipuṇā paṇḍitavedanīyā, ye tathāgato sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedeti, yehi tathāgatassa yathābhuccaṃ vaṇṇaṃ sammā vadamānā vadeyyuṃ.**There are other principles—deep, hard to see, hard to understand, peaceful, sublime, beyond the scope of reason, subtle, comprehensible to the astute—which the Realized One makes known after realizing them with his own insight. Those who genuinely praise the Realized One would rightly speak of these things.*";
P_HTM[156]="*Katame ca te, bhikkhave, dhammā gambhīrā duddasā duranubodhā santā paṇītā atakkāvacarā nipuṇā paṇḍitavedanīyā, ye tathāgato sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedeti, yehi tathāgatassa yathābhuccaṃ vaṇṇaṃ sammā vadamānā vadeyyuṃ?**And what are these principles?*";
P_HTM[157]="*Santi, bhikkhave, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā pubbantakappikā pubbantānudiṭṭhino, pubbantaṃ ārabbha anekavihitāni adhimuttipadāni abhivadanti aṭṭhārasahi vatthūhi.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who theorize about the past, and assert various hypotheses concerning the past on eighteen grounds.*";
P_HTM[158]="*Te ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha pubbantakappikā pubbantānudiṭṭhino pubbantaṃ ārabbha anekavihitāni adhimuttipadāni abhivadanti aṭṭhārasahi vatthūhi?**And what are the eighteen grounds on which they rely?*";
P_HTM[159]="*3.1.1. Sassatavāda**3.1.1. Eternalism*";
P_HTM[160]="*Santi, bhikkhave, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā sassatavādā, sassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti catūhi vatthūhi.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who are eternalists, who assert that the self and the cosmos are eternal on four grounds.*";
P_HTM[161]="*Te ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha sassatavādā sassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti catūhi vatthūhi?**And what are the four grounds on which they rely?*";
P_HTM[162]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati, yathāsamāhite citte () anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati.**It’s when some ascetic or brahmin—by dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus—experiences an immersion of the heart of such a kind that they recollect their many kinds of past lives.*";
P_HTM[163]="*Seyyathidaṃ—ekampi jātiṃ dvepi jātiyo tissopi jātiyo catassopi jātiyo pañcapi jātiyo dasapi jātiyo vīsampi jātiyo tiṃsampi jātiyo cattālīsampi jātiyo paññāsampi jātiyo jātisatampi jātisahassampi jātisatasahassampi anekānipi jātisatāni anekānipi jātisahassāni anekānipi jātisatasahassāni: ‘amutrāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṃgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto, so tato cuto amutra udapādiṃ; tatrāpāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṃgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto, so tato cuto idhūpapanno’ti. Iti sākāraṃ sauddesaṃ anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati.**That is: one, two, three, four, five, ten, twenty, thirty, forty, fifty, a hundred, a thousand, a hundred thousand rebirths; many eons of the cosmos contracting, many eons of the cosmos expanding, many eons of the cosmos contracting and expanding. They remember: ‘There, I was named this, my clan was that, I looked like this, and that was my food. This was how I felt pleasure and pain, and that was how my life ended. When I passed away from that place I was reborn somewhere else. There, too, I was named this, my clan was that, I looked like this, and that was my food. This was how I felt pleasure and pain, and that was how my life ended. When I passed away from that place I was reborn here.’ And so they recollect their many kinds of past lives, with features and details.*";
P_HTM[164]="*So evamāha:**They say:*";
P_HTM[165]="*‘sassato attā ca loko ca vañjho kūṭaṭṭho esikaṭṭhāyiṭṭhito;**‘The self and the cosmos are eternal, barren, steady as a mountain peak, standing firm like a pillar.*";
P_HTM[166]="*te ca sattā sandhāvanti saṃsaranti cavanti upapajjanti, atthi tveva sassatisamaṃ.**They remain the same for all eternity, while these sentient beings wander and transmigrate and pass away and rearise.*";
P_HTM[167]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[168]="*Ahañhi ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusāmi, yathāsamāhite citte anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarāmi.**Because by dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus I experience an immersion of the heart of such a kind that I recollect my many kinds of past lives,*";
P_HTM[169]="*Seyyathidaṃ—ekampi jātiṃ dvepi jātiyo tissopi jātiyo catassopi jātiyo pañcapi jātiyo dasapi jātiyo vīsampi jātiyo tiṃsampi jātiyo cattālīsampi jātiyo paññāsampi jātiyo jātisatampi jātisahassampi jātisatasahassampi anekānipi jātisatāni anekānipi jātisahassāni anekānipi jātisatasahassāni: “amutrāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṅgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto, so tato cuto amutra udapādiṃ; tatrāpāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṅgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto, so tato cuto idhūpapanno”ti. Iti sākāraṃ sauddesaṃ anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarāmi.**with features and details.*";
P_HTM[170]="*Imināmahaṃ etaṃ jānāmi:**Because of this I know:*";
P_HTM[171]="*“yathā sassato attā ca loko ca vañjho kūṭaṭṭho esikaṭṭhāyiṭṭhito;**“The self and the cosmos are eternal, barren, steady as a mountain peak, standing firm like a pillar.*";
P_HTM[172]="*te ca sattā sandhāvanti saṃsaranti cavanti upapajjanti, atthi tveva sassatisaman”’ti.**They remain the same for all eternity, while these sentient beings wander and transmigrate and pass away and rearise.’*";
P_HTM[173]="*Idaṃ, bhikkhave, paṭhamaṃ ṭhānaṃ, yaṃ āgamma yaṃ ārabbha eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā sassatavādā sassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti. (1: 1)**This is the first ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely to assert that the self and the cosmos are eternal.*";
P_HTM[174]="*Dutiye ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha sassatavādā sassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti?**And what is the second ground on which they rely?*";
P_HTM[175]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati, yathāsamāhite citte anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati.**It’s when some ascetic or brahmin—by dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus—experiences an immersion of the heart of such a kind that they recollect their many kinds of past lives.*";
P_HTM[176]="*Seyyathidaṃ—ekampi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭaṃ dvepi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭāni tīṇipi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭāni cattāripi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭāni pañcapi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭāni dasapi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭāni: ‘amutrāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṅgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto, so tato cuto amutra udapādiṃ; tatrāpāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṅgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto, so tato cuto idhūpapanno’ti. Iti sākāraṃ sauddesaṃ anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati.**That is: one eon of the cosmos contracting and expanding; two, three, four, five, or ten eons of the cosmos contracting and expanding. They remember: ‘There, I was named this, my clan was that, I looked like this, and that was my food. This was how I felt pleasure and pain, and that was how my life ended. When I passed away from that place I was reborn somewhere else. There, too, I was named this, my clan was that, I looked like this, and that was my food. This was how I felt pleasure and pain, and that was how my life ended. When I passed away from that place I was reborn here.’ And so they recollect their many kinds of past lives, with features and details.*";
P_HTM[177]="*So evamāha:**They say:*";
P_HTM[178]="*‘sassato attā ca loko ca vañjho kūṭaṭṭho esikaṭṭhāyiṭṭhito;**‘The self and the cosmos are eternal, barren, steady as a mountain peak, standing firm like a pillar.*";
P_HTM[179]="*te ca sattā sandhāvanti saṃsaranti cavanti upapajjanti, atthi tveva sassatisamaṃ.**They remain the same for all eternity, while these sentient beings wander and transmigrate and pass away and rearise.*";
P_HTM[180]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[181]="*Ahañhi ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusāmi yathāsamāhite citte anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarāmi.**Because by dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus I experience an immersion of the heart of such a kind that I recollect my many kinds of past lives,*";
P_HTM[182]="*Seyyathidaṃ—ekampi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭaṃ dvepi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭāni tīṇipi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭāni cattāripi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭāni pañcapi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭāni dasapi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭāni: “amutrāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṅgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto, so tato cuto amutra udapādiṃ; tatrāpāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṅgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto, so tato cuto idhūpapanno”ti. Iti sākāraṃ sauddesaṃ anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarāmi.**with features and details.*";
P_HTM[183]="*Imināmahaṃ etaṃ jānāmi:**Because of this I know:*";
P_HTM[184]="*“yathā sassato attā ca loko ca vañjho kūṭaṭṭho esikaṭṭhāyiṭṭhito, te ca sattā sandhāvanti saṃsaranti cavanti upapajjanti, atthi tveva sassatisaman”’ti.**“The self and the cosmos are eternal, barren, steady as a mountain peak, standing firm like a pillar. They remain the same for all eternity, while these sentient beings wander and transmigrate and pass away and rearise.”’*";
P_HTM[185]="*Idaṃ, bhikkhave, dutiyaṃ ṭhānaṃ, yaṃ āgamma yaṃ ārabbha eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā sassatavādā sassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti. (2: 2)**This is the second ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely to assert that the self and the cosmos are eternal.*";
P_HTM[186]="*Tatiye ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha sassatavādā sassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti?**And what is the third ground on which they rely?*";
P_HTM[187]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati, yathāsamāhite citte anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati.**It’s when some ascetic or brahmin—by dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus—experiences an immersion of the heart of such a kind that they recollect their many kinds of past lives.*";
P_HTM[188]="*Seyyathidaṃ—dasapi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭāni vīsampi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭāni tiṃsampi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭāni cattālīsampi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭāni: ‘amutrāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṅgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto, so tato cuto amutra udapādiṃ; tatrāpāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṅgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto, so tato cuto idhūpapanno’ti. Iti sākāraṃ sauddesaṃ anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati.**That is: ten eons of the cosmos contracting and expanding; twenty, thirty, or forty eons of the cosmos contracting and expanding. They remember: ‘There, I was named this, my clan was that, I looked like this, and that was my food. This was how I felt pleasure and pain, and that was how my life ended. When I passed away from that place I was reborn somewhere else. There, too, I was named this, my clan was that, I looked like this, and that was my food. This was how I felt pleasure and pain, and that was how my life ended. When I passed away from that place I was reborn here.’ And so they recollect their many kinds of past lives, with features and details.*";
P_HTM[189]="*So evamāha:**They say:*";
P_HTM[190]="*‘sassato attā ca loko ca vañjho kūṭaṭṭho esikaṭṭhāyiṭṭhito;**‘The self and the cosmos are eternal, barren, steady as a mountain peak, standing firm like a pillar.*";
P_HTM[191]="*te ca sattā sandhāvanti saṃsaranti cavanti upapajjanti, atthi tveva sassatisamaṃ.**They remain the same for all eternity, while these sentient beings wander and transmigrate and pass away and rearise.*";
P_HTM[192]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[193]="*Ahañhi ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusāmi, yathāsamāhite citte anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarāmi.**Because by dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus I experience an immersion of the heart of such a kind that I recollect my many kinds of past lives,*";
P_HTM[194]="*Seyyathidaṃ—dasapi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭāni vīsampi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭāni tiṃsampi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭāni cattālīsampi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭāni: “amutrāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṅgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto, so tato cuto amutra udapādiṃ; tatrāpāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṅgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto, so tato cuto idhūpapanno”ti. Iti sākāraṃ sauddesaṃ anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarāmi.**with features and details.*";
P_HTM[195]="*Imināmahaṃ etaṃ jānāmi:**Because of this I know:*";
P_HTM[196]="*“yathā sassato attā ca loko ca vañjho kūṭaṭṭho esikaṭṭhāyiṭṭhito, te ca sattā sandhāvanti saṃsaranti cavanti upapajjanti, atthi tveva sassatisaman”’ti.**“The self and the cosmos are eternal, barren, steady as a mountain peak, standing firm like a pillar. They remain the same for all eternity, while these sentient beings wander and transmigrate and pass away and rearise.”’*";
P_HTM[197]="*Idaṃ, bhikkhave, tatiyaṃ ṭhānaṃ, yaṃ āgamma yaṃ ārabbha eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā sassatavādā sassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti. (3: 3)**This is the third ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely to assert that the self and the cosmos are eternal.*";
P_HTM[198]="*Catutthe ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha sassatavādā sassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti?**And what is the fourth ground on which they rely?*";
P_HTM[199]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā takkī hoti vīmaṃsī, so takkapariyāhataṃ vīmaṃsānucaritaṃ sayaṃ paṭibhānaṃ evamāha:**It’s when some ascetic or brahmin relies on logic and inquiry. They speak of what they have worked out by logic, following a line of inquiry, expressing their own perspective:*";
P_HTM[200]="*‘sassato attā ca loko ca vañjho kūṭaṭṭho esikaṭṭhāyiṭṭhito;**‘The self and the cosmos are eternal, barren, steady as a mountain peak, standing firm like a pillar.*";
P_HTM[201]="*te ca sattā sandhāvanti saṃsaranti cavanti upapajjanti, atthi tveva sassatisaman’ti.**They remain the same for all eternity, while these sentient beings wander and transmigrate and pass away and rearise.’*";
P_HTM[202]="*Idaṃ, bhikkhave, catutthaṃ ṭhānaṃ, yaṃ āgamma yaṃ ārabbha eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā sassatavādā sassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti. (4: 4)**This is the fourth ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely to assert that the self and the cosmos are eternal.*";
P_HTM[203]="*Imehi kho te, bhikkhave, samaṇabrāhmaṇā sassatavādā sassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti catūhi vatthūhi.**These are the four grounds on which those ascetics and brahmins assert that the self and the cosmos are eternal.*";
P_HTM[204]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā sassatavādā sassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti, sabbe te imeheva catūhi vatthūhi, etesaṃ vā aññatarena; natthi ito bahiddhā.**Any ascetics and brahmins who assert that the self and the cosmos are eternal do so on one or other of these four grounds. Outside of this there is none.*";
P_HTM[205]="*Tayidaṃ, bhikkhave, tathāgato pajānāti:**The Realized One understands this:*";
P_HTM[206]="*‘ime diṭṭhiṭṭhānā evaṃgahitā evaṃparāmaṭṭhā evaṃgatikā bhavanti evaṃabhisamparāyā’ti,**‘If you hold on to and attach to these grounds for views it leads to such and such a destiny in the next life.’*";
P_HTM[207]="*tañca tathāgato pajānāti, tato ca uttaritaraṃ pajānāti; tañca pajānanaṃ na parāmasati, aparāmasato cassa paccattaññeva nibbuti viditā.**He understands this, and what goes beyond this. Yet since he does not misapprehend that understanding, he has realized extinguishment within himself.*";
P_HTM[208]="*Vedanānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ viditvā anupādāvimutto, bhikkhave, tathāgato.**Having truly understood the origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape from feelings, the Realized One is freed through not grasping.*";
P_HTM[209]="*Ime kho te, bhikkhave, dhammā gambhīrā duddasā duranubodhā santā paṇītā atakkāvacarā nipuṇā paṇḍitavedanīyā, ye tathāgato sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedeti, yehi tathāgatassa yathābhuccaṃ vaṇṇaṃ sammā vadamānā vadeyyuṃ.**These are the principles—deep, hard to see, hard to understand, peaceful, sublime, beyond the scope of reason, subtle, comprehensible to the astute—which the Realized One makes known after realizing them with his own insight. And those who genuinely praise the Realized One would rightly speak of these things.*";
P_HTM[210]="*Paṭhamabhāṇavāro.* **";
P_HTM[211]="*3.1.2. Ekaccasassatavāda**3.1.2. Partial Eternalism*";
P_HTM[212]="*Santi, bhikkhave, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā ekaccasassatikā ekaccaasassatikā ekaccaṃ sassataṃ ekaccaṃ asassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti catūhi vatthūhi.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who are partial eternalists, who assert that the self and the cosmos are partially eternal and partially not eternal on four grounds.*";
P_HTM[213]="*Te ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha ekaccasassatikā ekaccaasassatikā ekaccaṃ sassataṃ ekaccaṃ asassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti catūhi vatthūhi?**And what are the four grounds on which they rely?*";
P_HTM[214]="*Hoti kho so, bhikkhave, samayo, yaṃ kadāci karahaci dīghassa addhuno accayena ayaṃ loko saṃvaṭṭati.**There comes a time when, after a very long period has passed, this cosmos contracts.*";
P_HTM[215]="*Saṃvaṭṭamāne loke yebhuyyena sattā ābhassarasaṃvattanikā honti.**As the cosmos contracts, sentient beings are mostly headed for the realm of streaming radiance.*";
P_HTM[216]="*Te tattha honti manomayā pītibhakkhā sayaṃpabhā antalikkhacarā subhaṭṭhāyino, ciraṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ tiṭṭhanti.**There they are mind-made, feeding on rapture, self-luminous, moving through the sky, steadily glorious, and they remain like that for a very long time.*";
P_HTM[217]="*Hoti kho so, bhikkhave, samayo, yaṃ kadāci karahaci dīghassa addhuno accayena ayaṃ loko vivaṭṭati.**There comes a time when, after a very long period has passed, this cosmos expands.*";
P_HTM[218]="*Vivaṭṭamāne loke suññaṃ brahmavimānaṃ pātubhavati.**As it expands an empty mansion of Brahmā appears.*";
P_HTM[219]="*Atha kho aññataro satto āyukkhayā vā puññakkhayā vā ābhassarakāyā cavitvā suññaṃ brahmavimānaṃ upapajjati.**Then a certain sentient being—due to the running out of their life-span or merit—passes away from that host of radiant deities and is reborn in that empty mansion of Brahmā.*";
P_HTM[220]="*So tattha hoti manomayo pītibhakkho sayampabho antalikkhacaro subhaṭṭhāyī, ciraṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ tiṭṭhati.**There they are mind-made, feeding on rapture, self-luminous, moving through the sky, steadily glorious, and they remain like that for a very long time.*";
P_HTM[221]="*Tassa tattha ekakassa dīgharattaṃ nivusitattā anabhirati paritassanā uppajjati:**But after staying there all alone for a long time, they become dissatisfied and anxious:*";
P_HTM[222]="*‘aho vata aññepi sattā itthattaṃ āgaccheyyun’ti.**‘Oh, if only another being would come to this state of existence.’*";
P_HTM[223]="*Atha aññepi sattā āyukkhayā vā puññakkhayā vā ābhassarakāyā cavitvā brahmavimānaṃ upapajjanti tassa sattassa sahabyataṃ.**Then other sentient beings—due to the running out of their life-span or merit—pass away from that host of radiant deities and are reborn in that empty mansion of Brahmā in company with that being.*";
P_HTM[224]="*Tepi tattha honti manomayā pītibhakkhā sayaṃpabhā antalikkhacarā subhaṭṭhāyino, ciraṃ dīghamaddhānaṃ tiṭṭhanti.**There they too are mind-made, feeding on rapture, self-luminous, moving through the sky, steadily glorious, and they remain like that for a very long time.*";
P_HTM[225]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, yo so satto paṭhamaṃ upapanno tassa evaṃ hoti:**Now, the being who was reborn there first thinks:*";
P_HTM[226]="*‘ahamasmi brahmā mahābrahmā abhibhū anabhibhūto aññadatthudaso vasavattī issaro kattā nimmātā seṭṭho sajitā vasī pitā bhūtabhabyānaṃ.**‘I am Brahmā, the Great Brahmā, the Undefeated, the Champion, the Universal Seer, the Wielder of Power, the Lord God, the Maker, the Author, the Best, the Begetter, the Controller, the Father of those who have been born and those yet to be born.*";
P_HTM[227]="*Mayā ime sattā nimmitā.**These beings were created by me!*";
P_HTM[228]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[229]="*Mamañhi pubbe etadahosi:**Because first I thought:*";
P_HTM[230]="*“aho vata aññepi sattā itthattaṃ āgaccheyyun”ti.**“Oh, if only another being would come to this state of existence.”*";
P_HTM[231]="*Iti mama ca manopaṇidhi, ime ca sattā itthattaṃ āgatā’ti.**Such was my heart’s wish, and then these creatures came to this state of existence.’*";
P_HTM[232]="*Yepi te sattā pacchā upapannā, tesampi evaṃ hoti:**And the beings who were reborn there later also think:*";
P_HTM[233]="*‘ayaṃ kho bhavaṃ brahmā mahābrahmā abhibhū anabhibhūto aññadatthudaso vasavattī issaro kattā nimmātā seṭṭho sajitā vasī pitā bhūtabhabyānaṃ.**‘This must be Brahmā, the Great Brahmā, the Undefeated, the Champion, the Universal Seer, the Wielder of Power, the Lord God, the Maker, the Author, the Best, the Begetter, the Controller, the Father of those who have been born and those yet to be born.*";
P_HTM[234]="*Iminā mayaṃ bhotā brahmunā nimmitā.**And we have been created by him.*";
P_HTM[235]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[236]="*Imañhi mayaṃ addasāma idha paṭhamaṃ upapannaṃ, mayaṃ panamha pacchā upapannā’ti.**Because we see that he was reborn here first, and we arrived later.’*";
P_HTM[237]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, yo so satto paṭhamaṃ upapanno, so dīghāyukataro ca hoti vaṇṇavantataro ca mahesakkhataro ca.**And the being who was reborn first is more long-lived, beautiful, and illustrious than those who arrived later.*";
P_HTM[238]="*Ye pana te sattā pacchā upapannā, te appāyukatarā ca honti dubbaṇṇatarā ca appesakkhatarā ca.* **";
P_HTM[239]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, bhikkhave, vijjati, yaṃ aññataro satto tamhā kāyā cavitvā itthattaṃ āgacchati.**It’s possible that one of those beings passes away from that host and is reborn in this state of existence.*";
P_HTM[240]="*Itthattaṃ āgato samāno agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajati.**Having done so, they go forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[241]="*Agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajito samāno ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati, yathāsamāhite citte taṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati, tato paraṃ nānussarati.**By dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus, they experience an immersion of the heart of such a kind that they recollect that past life, but no further.*";
P_HTM[242]="*So evamāha:**They say:*";
P_HTM[243]="*‘yo kho so bhavaṃ brahmā mahābrahmā abhibhū anabhibhūto aññadatthudaso vasavattī issaro kattā nimmātā seṭṭho sajitā vasī pitā bhūtabhabyānaṃ, yena mayaṃ bhotā brahmunā nimmitā, so nicco dhuvo sassato avipariṇāmadhammo sassatisamaṃ tatheva ṭhassati.**‘He who is Brahmā—the Great Brahmā, the Undefeated, the Champion, the Universal Seer, the Wielder of Power, the Lord God, the Maker, the Author, the Best, the Begetter, the Controller, the Father of those who have been born and those yet to be born—is permanent, everlasting, eternal, imperishable, remaining the same for all eternity.*";
P_HTM[244]="*Ye pana mayaṃ ahumhā tena bhotā brahmunā nimmitā, te mayaṃ aniccā addhuvā appāyukā cavanadhammā itthattaṃ āgatā’ti.**We who were created by that Brahmā are impermanent, not lasting, short-lived, perishable, and have come to this state of existence.*";
P_HTM[245]="*Idaṃ, bhikkhave, paṭhamaṃ ṭhānaṃ, yaṃ āgamma yaṃ ārabbha eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā ekaccasassatikā ekaccaasassatikā ekaccaṃ sassataṃ ekaccaṃ asassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti. (1: 5)**This is the first ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely to assert that the self and the cosmos are partially eternal.*";
P_HTM[246]="*Dutiye ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha ekaccasassatikā ekaccaasassatikā ekaccaṃ sassataṃ ekaccaṃ asassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti?**And what is the second ground on which they rely?*";
P_HTM[247]="*Santi, bhikkhave, khiḍḍāpadosikā nāma devā, te ativelaṃ hassakhiḍḍāratidhammasamāpannā viharanti. Tesaṃ ativelaṃ hassakhiḍḍāratidhammasamāpannānaṃ viharataṃ sati sammussati. Satiyā sammosā te devā tamhā kāyā cavanti.**There are gods named ‘depraved by play.’ They spend too much time laughing, playing, and making merry. And in doing so, they lose their mindfulness, and they pass away from that host of gods.*";
P_HTM[248]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, bhikkhave, vijjati yaṃ aññataro satto tamhā kāyā cavitvā itthattaṃ āgacchati.**It’s possible that one of those beings passes away from that host and is reborn in this state of existence.*";
P_HTM[249]="*Itthattaṃ āgato samāno agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajati.**Having done so, they go forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[250]="*Agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajito samāno ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati, yathāsamāhite citte taṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati, tato paraṃ nānussarati.**By dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus, they experience an immersion of the heart of such a kind that they recollect that past life, but no further.*";
P_HTM[251]="*So evamāha:**They say:*";
P_HTM[252]="*‘ye kho te bhonto devā na khiḍḍāpadosikā, te na ativelaṃ hassakhiḍḍāratidhammasamāpannā viharanti. Tesaṃ na ativelaṃ hassakhiḍḍāratidhammasamāpannānaṃ viharataṃ sati na sammussati. Satiyā asammosā te devā tamhā kāyā na cavanti;**‘The gods not depraved by play don’t spend too much time laughing, playing, and making merry. So they don’t lose their mindfulness, and don’t pass away from that host of gods.*";
P_HTM[253]="*niccā dhuvā sassatā avipariṇāmadhammā sassatisamaṃ tatheva ṭhassanti.**They are permanent, everlasting, eternal, imperishable, remaining the same for all eternity.*";
P_HTM[254]="*Ye pana mayaṃ ahumhā khiḍḍāpadosikā, te mayaṃ ativelaṃ hassakhiḍḍāratidhammasamāpannā viharimhā. Tesaṃ no ativelaṃ hassakhiḍḍāratidhammasamāpannānaṃ viharataṃ sati sammussati. Satiyā sammosā evaṃ mayaṃ tamhā kāyā cutā**But we who were depraved by play spent too much time laughing, playing, and making merry. In doing so, we lost our mindfulness, and passed away from that host of gods.*";
P_HTM[255]="*aniccā addhuvā appāyukā cavanadhammā itthattaṃ āgatā’ti.**We are impermanent, not lasting, short-lived, perishable, and have come to this state of existence.’*";
P_HTM[256]="*Idaṃ, bhikkhave, dutiyaṃ ṭhānaṃ, yaṃ āgamma yaṃ ārabbha eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā ekaccasassatikā ekaccaasassatikā ekaccaṃ sassataṃ ekaccaṃ asassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti. (2: 6)**This is the second ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely to assert that the self and the cosmos are partially eternal.*";
P_HTM[257]="*Tatiye ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha ekaccasassatikā ekaccaasassatikā ekaccaṃ sassataṃ ekaccaṃ asassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti?**And what is the third ground on which they rely?*";
P_HTM[258]="*Santi, bhikkhave, manopadosikā nāma devā, te ativelaṃ aññamaññaṃ upanijjhāyanti. Te ativelaṃ aññamaññaṃ upanijjhāyantā aññamaññamhi cittāni padūsenti. Te aññamaññaṃ paduṭṭhacittā kilantakāyā kilantacittā. Te devā tamhā kāyā cavanti.**There are gods named ‘malevolent’. They spend too much time gazing at each other, so they grow angry with each other, and their bodies and minds get tired. They pass away from that host of gods.*";
P_HTM[259]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, bhikkhave, vijjati yaṃ aññataro satto tamhā kāyā cavitvā itthattaṃ āgacchati.**It’s possible that one of those beings passes away from that host and is reborn in this state of existence.*";
P_HTM[260]="*Itthattaṃ āgato samāno agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajati.**Having done so, they go forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[261]="*Agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajito samāno ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati, yathāsamāhite citte taṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati, tato paraṃ nānussarati.**By dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus, they experience an immersion of the heart of such a kind that they recollect that past life, but no further.*";
P_HTM[262]="*So evamāha:**They say:*";
P_HTM[263]="*‘ye kho te bhonto devā na manopadosikā, te nātivelaṃ aññamaññaṃ upanijjhāyanti. Te nātivelaṃ aññamaññaṃ upanijjhāyantā aññamaññamhi cittāni nappadūsenti. Te aññamaññaṃ appaduṭṭhacittā akilantakāyā akilantacittā. Te devā tamhā kāyā na cavanti,**‘The gods who are not malevolent don’t spend too much time gazing at each other, so they don’t grow angry with each other, their bodies and minds don’t get tired, and they don’t pass away from that host of gods.*";
P_HTM[264]="*niccā dhuvā sassatā avipariṇāmadhammā sassatisamaṃ tatheva ṭhassanti.**They are permanent, everlasting, eternal, imperishable, remaining the same for all eternity.*";
P_HTM[265]="*Ye pana mayaṃ ahumhā manopadosikā, te mayaṃ ativelaṃ aññamaññaṃ upanijjhāyimhā. Te mayaṃ ativelaṃ aññamaññaṃ upanijjhāyantā aññamaññamhi cittāni padūsimhā, te mayaṃ aññamaññaṃ paduṭṭhacittā kilantakāyā kilantacittā. Evaṃ mayaṃ tamhā kāyā cutā**But we who were malevolent spent too much time gazing at each other, we grew angry with each other, our bodies and minds got tired, and we passed away from that host of gods.*";
P_HTM[266]="*aniccā addhuvā appāyukā cavanadhammā itthattaṃ āgatā’ti.**We are impermanent, not lasting, short-lived, perishable, and have come to this state of existence.’*";
P_HTM[267]="*Idaṃ, bhikkhave, tatiyaṃ ṭhānaṃ, yaṃ āgamma yaṃ ārabbha eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā ekaccasassatikā ekaccaasassatikā ekaccaṃ sassataṃ ekaccaṃ asassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti. (3: 7)**This is the third ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely to assert that the self and the cosmos are partially eternal.*";
P_HTM[268]="*Catutthe ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha ekaccasassatikā ekaccaasassatikā ekaccaṃ sassataṃ ekaccaṃ asassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti?**And what is the fourth ground on which they rely?*";
P_HTM[269]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā takkī hoti vīmaṃsī. So takkapariyāhataṃ vīmaṃsānucaritaṃ sayampaṭibhānaṃ evamāha:**It’s when some ascetic or brahmin relies on logic and inquiry. They speak of what they have worked out by logic, following a line of inquiry, expressing their own perspective:*";
P_HTM[270]="*‘yaṃ kho idaṃ vuccati cakkhuṃ itipi sotaṃ itipi ghānaṃ itipi jivhā itipi kāyo itipi, ayaṃ attā anicco addhuvo asassato vipariṇāmadhammo.**‘That which is called “the eye” or “the ear” or “the nose” or “the tongue” or “the body”: that self is impermanent, not lasting, transient, perishable.*";
P_HTM[271]="*Yañca kho idaṃ vuccati cittanti vā manoti vā viññāṇanti vā ayaṃ attā nicco dhuvo sassato avipariṇāmadhammo sassatisamaṃ tatheva ṭhassatī’ti.**That which is called “mind” or “sentience” or “consciousness”: that self is permanent, everlasting, eternal, imperishable, remaining the same for all eternity.’*";
P_HTM[272]="*Idaṃ, bhikkhave, catutthaṃ ṭhānaṃ, yaṃ āgamma yaṃ ārabbha eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā ekaccasassatikā ekaccaasassatikā ekaccaṃ sassataṃ ekaccaṃ asassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti. (4: 8)**This is the fourth ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely to assert that the self and the cosmos are partially eternal.*";
P_HTM[273]="*Imehi kho te, bhikkhave, samaṇabrāhmaṇā ekaccasassatikā ekaccaasassatikā ekaccaṃ sassataṃ ekaccaṃ asassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti catūhi vatthūhi.**These are the four grounds on which those ascetics and brahmins assert that the self and the cosmos are partially eternal and partially not eternal.*";
P_HTM[274]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā ekaccasassatikā ekaccaasassatikā ekaccaṃ sassataṃ ekaccaṃ asassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti, sabbe te imeheva catūhi vatthūhi, etesaṃ vā aññatarena; natthi ito bahiddhā.**Any ascetics and brahmins who assert that the self and the cosmos are partially eternal and partially not eternal do so on one or other of these four grounds. Outside of this there is none.*";
P_HTM[275]="*Tayidaṃ, bhikkhave, tathāgato pajānāti:**The Realized One understands this:*";
P_HTM[276]="*‘ime diṭṭhiṭṭhānā evaṅgahitā evaṃparāmaṭṭhā evaṅgatikā bhavanti evaṃabhisamparāyā’ti.**‘If you hold on to and attach to these grounds for views it leads to such and such a destiny in the next life.’*";
P_HTM[277]="*Tañca tathāgato pajānāti, tato ca uttaritaraṃ pajānāti, tañca pajānanaṃ na parāmasati, aparāmasato cassa paccattaññeva nibbuti viditā.**He understands this, and what goes beyond this. Yet since he does not misapprehend that understanding, he has realized extinguishment within himself.*";
P_HTM[278]="*Vedanānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ viditvā anupādāvimutto, bhikkhave, tathāgato.**Having truly understood the origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape from feelings, the Realized One is freed through not grasping.*";
P_HTM[279]="*Ime kho te, bhikkhave, dhammā gambhīrā duddasā duranubodhā santā paṇītā atakkāvacarā nipuṇā paṇḍitavedanīyā, ye tathāgato sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedeti, yehi tathāgatassa yathābhuccaṃ vaṇṇaṃ sammā vadamānā vadeyyuṃ.**These are the principles—deep, hard to see, hard to understand, peaceful, sublime, beyond the scope of reason, subtle, comprehensible to the astute—which the Realized One makes known after realizing them with his own insight. And those who genuinely praise the Realized One would rightly speak of these things.*";
P_HTM[280]="*3.1.3. Antānantavāda**3.1.3. The Cosmos is Finite or Infinite*";
P_HTM[281]="*Santi, bhikkhave, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā antānantikā antānantaṃ lokassa paññapenti catūhi vatthūhi.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who theorize about size, and assert that the cosmos is finite or infinite on four grounds.*";
P_HTM[282]="*Te ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha antānantikā antānantaṃ lokassa paññapenti catūhi vatthūhi?**And what are the four grounds on which they rely?*";
P_HTM[283]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati, yathāsamāhite citte antasaññī lokasmiṃ viharati.**It’s when some ascetic or brahmin—by dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus—experiences an immersion of the heart of such a kind that they meditate perceiving the cosmos as finite.*";
P_HTM[284]="*So evamāha:**They say:*";
P_HTM[285]="*‘antavā ayaṃ loko parivaṭumo.**‘The cosmos is finite and bounded.*";
P_HTM[286]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[287]="*Ahañhi ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusāmi, yathāsamāhite citte antasaññī lokasmiṃ viharāmi.**Because by dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus I experience an immersion of the heart of such a kind that I meditate perceiving the cosmos as finite.*";
P_HTM[288]="*Imināmahaṃ etaṃ jānāmi:**Because of this I know:*";
P_HTM[289]="*“yathā antavā ayaṃ loko parivaṭumo”’ti.**“The cosmos is finite and bounded.”’*";
P_HTM[290]="*Idaṃ, bhikkhave, paṭhamaṃ ṭhānaṃ, yaṃ āgamma yaṃ ārabbha eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā antānantikā antānantaṃ lokassa paññapenti. (1: 9)**This is the first ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely to assert that the cosmos is finite or infinite.*";
P_HTM[291]="*Dutiye ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha antānantikā antānantaṃ lokassa paññapenti?**And what is the second ground on which they rely?*";
P_HTM[292]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati, yathāsamāhite citte anantasaññī lokasmiṃ viharati.**It’s when some ascetic or brahmin—by dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus—experiences an immersion of the heart of such a kind that they meditate perceiving the cosmos as infinite.*";
P_HTM[293]="*So evamāha:**They say:*";
P_HTM[294]="*‘ananto ayaṃ loko apariyanto.**‘The cosmos is infinite and unbounded.*";
P_HTM[295]="*Ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā evamāhaṃsu:**The ascetics and brahmins who say that*";
P_HTM[296]="*“antavā ayaṃ loko parivaṭumo”ti, tesaṃ musā.**the cosmos is finite are wrong.*";
P_HTM[297]="*Ananto ayaṃ loko apariyanto.**The cosmos is infinite and unbounded.*";
P_HTM[298]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[299]="*Ahañhi ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusāmi, yathāsamāhite citte anantasaññī lokasmiṃ viharāmi.**Because by dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus I experience an immersion of the heart of such a kind that I meditate perceiving the cosmos as infinite.*";
P_HTM[300]="*Imināmahaṃ etaṃ jānāmi:**Because of this I know:*";
P_HTM[301]="*“yathā ananto ayaṃ loko apariyanto”’ti.**“The cosmos is infinite and unbounded.”’*";
P_HTM[302]="*Idaṃ, bhikkhave, dutiyaṃ ṭhānaṃ, yaṃ āgamma yaṃ ārabbha eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā antānantikā antānantaṃ lokassa paññapenti. (2: 10)**This is the second ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely to assert that the cosmos is finite or infinite.*";
P_HTM[303]="*Tatiye ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha antānantikā antānantaṃ lokassa paññapenti?**And what is the third ground on which they rely?*";
P_HTM[304]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati, yathāsamāhite citte uddhamadho antasaññī lokasmiṃ viharati, tiriyaṃ anantasaññī.**It’s when some ascetic or brahmin—by dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus—experiences an immersion of the heart of such a kind that they meditate perceiving the cosmos as finite vertically but infinite horizontally.*";
P_HTM[305]="*So evamāha:**They say:*";
P_HTM[306]="*‘antavā ca ayaṃ loko ananto ca.**‘The cosmos is both finite and infinite.*";
P_HTM[307]="*Ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā evamāhaṃsu:**The ascetics and brahmins who say that*";
P_HTM[308]="*“antavā ayaṃ loko parivaṭumo”ti, tesaṃ musā.**the cosmos is finite are wrong,*";
P_HTM[309]="*Yepi te samaṇabrāhmaṇā evamāhaṃsu:**and so are those who say that*";
P_HTM[310]="*“ananto ayaṃ loko apariyanto”ti, tesampi musā.**the cosmos is infinite.*";
P_HTM[311]="*Antavā ca ayaṃ loko ananto ca.**The cosmos is both finite and infinite.*";
P_HTM[312]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[313]="*Ahañhi ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusāmi, yathāsamāhite citte uddhamadho antasaññī lokasmiṃ viharāmi, tiriyaṃ anantasaññī.**Because by dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus I experience an immersion of the heart of such a kind that I meditate perceiving the cosmos as finite vertically but infinite horizontally.*";
P_HTM[314]="*Imināmahaṃ etaṃ jānāmi:**Because of this I know:*";
P_HTM[315]="*“yathā antavā ca ayaṃ loko ananto cā”’ti.**“The cosmos is both finite and infinite.”’*";
P_HTM[316]="*Idaṃ, bhikkhave, tatiyaṃ ṭhānaṃ, yaṃ āgamma yaṃ ārabbha eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā antānantikā antānantaṃ lokassa paññapenti. (3: 11)**This is the third ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely to assert that the cosmos is finite or infinite.*";
P_HTM[317]="*Catutthe ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha antānantikā antānantaṃ lokassa paññapenti?**And what is the fourth ground on which they rely?*";
P_HTM[318]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā takkī hoti vīmaṃsī. So takkapariyāhataṃ vīmaṃsānucaritaṃ sayampaṭibhānaṃ evamāha:**It’s when some ascetic or brahmin relies on logic and inquiry. They speak of what they have worked out by logic, following a line of inquiry, expressing their own perspective:*";
P_HTM[319]="*‘nevāyaṃ loko antavā, na panānanto.**‘The cosmos is neither finite nor infinite.*";
P_HTM[320]="*Ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā evamāhaṃsu:**The ascetics and brahmins who say that*";
P_HTM[321]="*“antavā ayaṃ loko parivaṭumo”ti, tesaṃ musā.**the cosmos is finite are wrong,*";
P_HTM[322]="*Yepi te samaṇabrāhmaṇā evamāhaṃsu:**as are those who say that*";
P_HTM[323]="*“ananto ayaṃ loko apariyanto”ti, tesampi musā.**the cosmos is infinite,*";
P_HTM[324]="*Yepi te samaṇabrāhmaṇā evamāhaṃsu:**and also those who say that*";
P_HTM[325]="*“antavā ca ayaṃ loko ananto cā”ti, tesampi musā.**the cosmos is both finite and infinite.*";
P_HTM[326]="*Nevāyaṃ loko antavā, na panānanto’ti.**The cosmos is neither finite nor infinite.’*";
P_HTM[327]="*Idaṃ, bhikkhave, catutthaṃ ṭhānaṃ, yaṃ āgamma yaṃ ārabbha eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā antānantikā antānantaṃ lokassa paññapenti. (4: 12)**This is the fourth ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely to assert that the cosmos is finite or infinite.*";
P_HTM[328]="*Imehi kho te, bhikkhave, samaṇabrāhmaṇā antānantikā antānantaṃ lokassa paññapenti catūhi vatthūhi.**These are the four grounds on which those ascetics and brahmins assert that the cosmos is finite or infinite.*";
P_HTM[329]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā antānantikā antānantaṃ lokassa paññapenti, sabbe te imeheva catūhi vatthūhi, etesaṃ vā aññatarena; natthi ito bahiddhā.**Any ascetics and brahmins who assert that the cosmos is finite or infinite do so on one or other of these four grounds. Outside of this there is none.*";
P_HTM[330]="*Tayidaṃ, bhikkhave, tathāgato pajānāti:**The Realized One understands this:*";
P_HTM[331]="*‘ime diṭṭhiṭṭhānā evaṅgahitā evaṃparāmaṭṭhā evaṅgatikā bhavanti evaṃabhisamparāyā’ti.**‘If you hold on to and attach to these grounds for views it leads to such and such a destiny in the next life.’*";
P_HTM[332]="*Tañca tathāgato pajānāti, tato ca uttaritaraṃ pajānāti, tañca pajānanaṃ na parāmasati, aparāmasato cassa paccattaññeva nibbuti viditā.**He understands this, and what goes beyond this. Yet since he does not misapprehend that understanding, he has realized extinguishment within himself.*";
P_HTM[333]="*Vedanānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ viditvā anupādāvimutto, bhikkhave, tathāgato.**Having truly understood the origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape from feelings, the Realized One is freed through not grasping.*";
P_HTM[334]="*Ime kho te, bhikkhave, dhammā gambhīrā duddasā duranubodhā santā paṇītā atakkāvacarā nipuṇā paṇḍitavedanīyā, ye tathāgato sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedeti, yehi tathāgatassa yathābhuccaṃ vaṇṇaṃ sammā vadamānā vadeyyuṃ.**These are the principles—deep, hard to see, hard to understand, peaceful, sublime, beyond the scope of reason, subtle, comprehensible to the astute—which the Realized One makes known after realizing them with his own insight. And those who genuinely praise the Realized One would rightly speak of these things.*";
P_HTM[335]="*3.1.4. Amarāvikkhepavāda**3.1.4. Equivocators*";
P_HTM[336]="*Santi, bhikkhave, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā amarāvikkhepikā, tattha tattha pañhaṃ puṭṭhā samānā vācāvikkhepaṃ āpajjanti amarāvikkhepaṃ catūhi vatthūhi.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who are equivocators. Whenever they’re asked a question, they resort to evasiveness and equivocation on four grounds.*";
P_HTM[337]="*Te ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha amarāvikkhepikā tattha tattha pañhaṃ puṭṭhā samānā vācāvikkhepaṃ āpajjanti amarāvikkhepaṃ catūhi vatthūhi?**And what are the four grounds on which they rely?*";
P_HTM[338]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā ‘idaṃ kusalan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti, ‘idaṃ akusalan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**It’s when some ascetic or brahmin doesn’t truly understand what is skillful and what is unskillful.*";
P_HTM[339]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[340]="*‘ahaṃ kho “idaṃ kusalan”ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāmi, “idaṃ akusalan”ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāmi.**‘I don’t truly understand what is skillful and what is unskillful.*";
P_HTM[341]="*Ahañce kho pana “idaṃ kusalan”ti yathābhūtaṃ appajānanto, “idaṃ akusalan”ti yathābhūtaṃ appajānanto, “idaṃ kusalan”ti vā byākareyyaṃ, “idaṃ akusalan”ti vā byākareyyaṃ, taṃ mamassa musā.**If I were to declare that something was skillful or unskillful I might be wrong.*";
P_HTM[342]="*Yaṃ mamassa musā, so mamassa vighāto.**That would be stressful for me,*";
P_HTM[343]="*Yo mamassa vighāto so mamassa antarāyo’ti.**and that stress would be an obstacle.’*";
P_HTM[344]="*Iti so musāvādabhayā musāvādaparijegucchā nevidaṃ kusalanti byākaroti, na panidaṃ akusalanti byākaroti, tattha tattha pañhaṃ puṭṭho samāno vācāvikkhepaṃ āpajjati amarāvikkhepaṃ:**So from fear and disgust with false speech they avoid stating whether something is skillful or unskillful. Whenever they’re asked a question, they resort to evasiveness and equivocation:*";
P_HTM[345]="*‘evantipi me no; tathātipi me no; aññathātipi me no; notipi me no; no notipi me no’ti.**‘I don’t say it’s like this. I don’t say it’s like that. I don’t say it’s otherwise. I don’t say it’s not so. And I don’t deny it’s not so.’*";
P_HTM[346]="*Idaṃ, bhikkhave, paṭhamaṃ ṭhānaṃ, yaṃ āgamma yaṃ ārabbha eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā amarāvikkhepikā tattha tattha pañhaṃ puṭṭhā samānā vācāvikkhepaṃ āpajjanti amarāvikkhepaṃ. (1: 13)**This is the first ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely when resorting to evasiveness and equivocation.*";
P_HTM[347]="*Dutiye ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha amarāvikkhepikā tattha tattha pañhaṃ puṭṭhā samānā vācāvikkhepaṃ āpajjanti amarāvikkhepaṃ?**And what is the second ground on which they rely?*";
P_HTM[348]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā ‘idaṃ kusalan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti, ‘idaṃ akusalan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**It’s when some ascetic or brahmin doesn’t truly understand what is skillful and what is unskillful.*";
P_HTM[349]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[350]="*‘ahaṃ kho “idaṃ kusalan”ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāmi, “idaṃ akusalan”ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāmi.**‘I don’t truly understand what is skillful and what is unskillful.*";
P_HTM[351]="*Ahañce kho pana “idaṃ kusalan”ti yathābhūtaṃ appajānanto, “idaṃ akusalan”ti yathābhūtaṃ appajānanto, “idaṃ kusalan”ti vā byākareyyaṃ, “idaṃ akusalan”ti vā byākareyyaṃ, tattha me assa chando vā rāgo vā doso vā paṭigho vā.**If I were to declare that something was skillful or unskillful I might feel desire or greed or hate or repulsion.*";
P_HTM[352]="*Yattha me assa chando vā rāgo vā doso vā paṭigho vā, taṃ mamassa upādānaṃ.**That would be grasping on my part.*";
P_HTM[353]="*Yaṃ mamassa upādānaṃ, so mamassa vighāto.**That would be stressful for me,*";
P_HTM[354]="*Yo mamassa vighāto, so mamassa antarāyo’ti.**and that stress would be an obstacle.’*";
P_HTM[355]="*Iti so upādānabhayā upādānaparijegucchā nevidaṃ kusalanti byākaroti, na panidaṃ akusalanti byākaroti, tattha tattha pañhaṃ puṭṭho samāno vācāvikkhepaṃ āpajjati amarāvikkhepaṃ:**So from fear and disgust with grasping they avoid stating whether something is skillful or unskillful. Whenever they’re asked a question, they resort to evasiveness and equivocation:*";
P_HTM[356]="*‘evantipi me no; tathātipi me no; aññathātipi me no; notipi me no; no notipi me no’ti.**‘I don’t say it’s like this. I don’t say it’s like that. I don’t say it’s otherwise. I don’t say it’s not so. And I don’t deny it’s not so.’*";
P_HTM[357]="*Idaṃ, bhikkhave, dutiyaṃ ṭhānaṃ, yaṃ āgamma yaṃ ārabbha eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā amarāvikkhepikā tattha tattha pañhaṃ puṭṭhā samānā vācāvikkhepaṃ āpajjanti amarāvikkhepaṃ. (2: 14)**This is the second ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely when resorting to evasiveness and equivocation.*";
P_HTM[358]="*Tatiye ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha amarāvikkhepikā tattha tattha pañhaṃ puṭṭhā samānā vācāvikkhepaṃ āpajjanti amarāvikkhepaṃ?**And what is the third ground on which they rely?*";
P_HTM[359]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā ‘idaṃ kusalan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti, ‘idaṃ akusalan’ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāti.**It’s when some ascetic or brahmin doesn’t truly understand what is skillful and what is unskillful.*";
P_HTM[360]="*Tassa evaṃ hoti:**They think:*";
P_HTM[361]="*‘ahaṃ kho “idaṃ kusalan”ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāmi, “idaṃ akusalan”ti yathābhūtaṃ nappajānāmi.**‘I don’t truly understand what is skillful and what is unskillful.*";
P_HTM[362]="*Ahañce kho pana “idaṃ kusalan”ti yathābhūtaṃ appajānanto “idaṃ akusalan”ti yathābhūtaṃ appajānanto “idaṃ kusalan”ti vā byākareyyaṃ, “idaṃ akusalan”ti vā byākareyyaṃ;**Suppose I were to declare that something was skillful or unskillful.*";
P_HTM[363]="*santi hi kho samaṇabrāhmaṇā paṇḍitā nipuṇā kataparappavādā vālavedhirūpā, te bhindantā maññe caranti paññāgatena diṭṭhigatāni,**There are clever ascetics and brahmins who are subtle, accomplished in the doctrines of others, hair-splitters. You’d think they live to demolish convictions with their intellect.*";
P_HTM[364]="*te maṃ tattha samanuyuñjeyyuṃ samanugāheyyuṃ samanubhāseyyuṃ.**They might pursue, press, and grill me about that.*";
P_HTM[365]="*Ye maṃ tattha samanuyuñjeyyuṃ samanugāheyyuṃ samanubhāseyyuṃ, tesāhaṃ na sampāyeyyaṃ.**I’d be stumped by such a grilling.*";
P_HTM[366]="*Yesāhaṃ na sampāyeyyaṃ, so mamassa vighāto.**That would be stressful for me,*";
P_HTM[367]="*Yo mamassa vighāto, so mamassa antarāyo’ti.**and that stress would be an obstacle.’*";
P_HTM[368]="*Iti so anuyogabhayā anuyogaparijegucchā nevidaṃ kusalanti byākaroti, na panidaṃ akusalanti byākaroti, tattha tattha pañhaṃ puṭṭho samāno vācāvikkhepaṃ āpajjati amarāvikkhepaṃ:**So from fear and disgust with examination they avoid stating whether something is skillful or unskillful. Whenever they’re asked a question, they resort to evasiveness and equivocation:*";
P_HTM[369]="*‘evantipi me no; tathātipi me no; aññathātipi me no; notipi me no; no notipi me no’ti.**‘I don’t say it’s like this. I don’t say it’s like that. I don’t say it’s otherwise. I don’t say it’s not so. And I don’t deny it’s not so.’*";
P_HTM[370]="*Idaṃ, bhikkhave, tatiyaṃ ṭhānaṃ, yaṃ āgamma yaṃ ārabbha eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā amarāvikkhepikā tattha tattha pañhaṃ puṭṭhā samānā vācāvikkhepaṃ āpajjanti amarāvikkhepaṃ. (3: 15)**This is the third ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely when resorting to evasiveness and equivocation.*";
P_HTM[371]="*Catutthe ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha amarāvikkhepikā tattha tattha pañhaṃ puṭṭhā samānā vācāvikkhepaṃ āpajjanti amarāvikkhepaṃ?**And what is the fourth ground on which they rely?*";
P_HTM[372]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā mando hoti momūho.**It’s when some ascetic or brahmin is dull and stupid.*";
P_HTM[373]="*So mandattā momūhattā tattha tattha pañhaṃ puṭṭho samāno vācāvikkhepaṃ āpajjati amarāvikkhepaṃ:**Because of that, whenever they’re asked a question, they resort to evasiveness and equivocation:*";
P_HTM[374]="*‘atthi paro loko’ti iti ce maṃ pucchasi, ‘atthi paro loko’ti iti ce me assa, ‘atthi paro loko’ti iti te naṃ byākareyyaṃ,**‘Suppose you were to ask me whether there is another world. If I believed there was, I would say so.*";
P_HTM[375]="*‘evantipi me no, tathātipi me no, aññathātipi me no, notipi me no, no notipi me no’ti.**But I don’t say it’s like this. I don’t say it’s like that. I don’t say it’s otherwise. I don’t say it’s not so. And I don’t deny it’s not so.*";
P_HTM[376]="*‘Natthi paro loko … pe …**Suppose you were to ask me whether there is no other world …*";
P_HTM[377]="*‘atthi ca natthi ca paro loko … pe …**whether there both is and is not another world …*";
P_HTM[378]="*‘nevatthi na natthi paro loko … pe …**whether there neither is nor is not another world …*";
P_HTM[379]="*‘atthi sattā opapātikā … pe …**whether there are beings who are reborn spontaneously …*";
P_HTM[380]="*‘natthi sattā opapātikā … pe …**whether there are not beings who are reborn spontaneously …*";
P_HTM[381]="*‘atthi ca natthi ca sattā opapātikā … pe …**whether there both are and are not beings who are reborn spontaneously …*";
P_HTM[382]="*‘nevatthi na natthi sattā opapātikā … pe …**whether there neither are nor are not beings who are reborn spontaneously …*";
P_HTM[383]="*‘atthi sukatadukkaṭānaṃ kammānaṃ phalaṃ vipāko … pe …**whether there is fruit and result of good and bad deeds …*";
P_HTM[384]="*‘natthi sukatadukkaṭānaṃ kammānaṃ phalaṃ vipāko … pe …**whether there is not fruit and result of good and bad deeds …*";
P_HTM[385]="*‘atthi ca natthi ca sukatadukkaṭānaṃ kammānaṃ phalaṃ vipāko … pe …**whether there both is and is not fruit and result of good and bad deeds …*";
P_HTM[386]="*‘nevatthi na natthi sukatadukkaṭānaṃ kammānaṃ phalaṃ vipāko … pe …**whether there neither is nor is not fruit and result of good and bad deeds …*";
P_HTM[387]="*‘hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā … pe …**whether a Realized One exists after death …*";
P_HTM[388]="*‘na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā … pe …**whether a Realized One doesn’t exist after death …*";
P_HTM[389]="*‘hoti ca na ca hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā … pe …**whether a Realized One both exists and doesn’t exist after death …*";
P_HTM[390]="*‘neva hoti na na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā’ti iti ce maṃ pucchasi, ‘neva hoti na na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā’ti iti ce me assa, ‘neva hoti na na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā’ti iti te naṃ byākareyyaṃ,**whether a Realized One neither exists nor doesn’t exist after death. If I believed there was, I would say so.*";
P_HTM[391]="*‘evantipi me no, tathātipi me no, aññathātipi me no, notipi me no, no notipi me no’ti.**But I don’t say it’s like this. I don’t say it’s like that. I don’t say it’s otherwise. I don’t say it’s not so. And I don’t deny it’s not so.’*";
P_HTM[392]="*Idaṃ, bhikkhave, catutthaṃ ṭhānaṃ, yaṃ āgamma yaṃ ārabbha eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā amarāvikkhepikā tattha tattha pañhaṃ puṭṭhā samānā vācāvikkhepaṃ āpajjanti amarāvikkhepaṃ. (4: 16)**This is the fourth ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely when resorting to evasiveness and equivocation.*";
P_HTM[393]="*Imehi kho te, bhikkhave, samaṇabrāhmaṇā amarāvikkhepikā tattha tattha pañhaṃ puṭṭhā samānā vācāvikkhepaṃ āpajjanti amarāvikkhepaṃ catūhi vatthūhi.**These are the four grounds on which those ascetics and brahmins who are equivocators resort to evasiveness and equivocation whenever they’re asked a question.*";
P_HTM[394]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā amarāvikkhepikā tattha tattha pañhaṃ puṭṭhā samānā vācāvikkhepaṃ āpajjanti amarāvikkhepaṃ, sabbe te imeheva catūhi vatthūhi, etesaṃ vā aññatarena, natthi ito bahiddhā …**Any ascetics and brahmins who resort to equivocation do so on one or other of these four grounds. Outside of this there is none.*";
P_HTM[395]="*pe …**The Realized One understands this …*";
P_HTM[396]="*yehi tathāgatassa yathābhuccaṃ vaṇṇaṃ sammā vadamānā vadeyyuṃ.**And those who genuinely praise the Realized One would rightly speak of these things.*";
P_HTM[397]="*3.1.5. Adhiccasamuppannavāda**3.1.5. Doctrines of Origination by Chance*";
P_HTM[398]="*Santi, bhikkhave, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā adhiccasamuppannikā adhiccasamuppannaṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti dvīhi vatthūhi.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who theorize about chance. They assert that the self and the cosmos arose by chance on two grounds.*";
P_HTM[399]="*Te ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha adhiccasamuppannikā adhiccasamuppannaṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti dvīhi vatthūhi?**And what are the two grounds on which they rely?*";
P_HTM[400]="*Santi, bhikkhave, asaññasattā nāma devā.**There are gods named ‘non-percipient beings’.*";
P_HTM[401]="*Saññuppādā ca pana te devā tamhā kāyā cavanti.**When perception arises they pass away from that host of gods.*";
P_HTM[402]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, bhikkhave, vijjati, yaṃ aññataro satto tamhā kāyā cavitvā itthattaṃ āgacchati.**It’s possible that one of those beings passes away from that host and is reborn in this state of existence.*";
P_HTM[403]="*Itthattaṃ āgato samāno agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajati.**Having done so, they go forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[404]="*Agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajito samāno ātappamanvāya padhānamanvāya anuyogamanvāya appamādamanvāya sammāmanasikāramanvāya tathārūpaṃ cetosamādhiṃ phusati, yathāsamāhite citte saññuppādaṃ anussarati, tato paraṃ nānussarati.**By dint of keen, resolute, committed, and diligent effort, and right focus, they experience an immersion of the heart of such a kind that they recollect the arising of perception, but no further.*";
P_HTM[405]="*So evamāha:**They say:*";
P_HTM[406]="*‘adhiccasamuppanno attā ca loko ca.**‘The self and the cosmos arose by chance.*";
P_HTM[407]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[408]="*Ahañhi pubbe nāhosiṃ, somhi etarahi ahutvā santatāya pariṇato’ti.**Because formerly I didn’t exist. Now, having not been, I’ve sprung into existence.’*";
P_HTM[409]="*Idaṃ, bhikkhave, paṭhamaṃ ṭhānaṃ, yaṃ āgamma yaṃ ārabbha eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā adhiccasamuppannikā adhiccasamuppannaṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti. (1: 17)**This is the first ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely to assert that the self and the cosmos arose by chance.*";
P_HTM[410]="*Dutiye ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha adhiccasamuppannikā adhiccasamuppannaṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti?**And what is the second ground on which they rely?*";
P_HTM[411]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā takkī hoti vīmaṃsī.**It’s when some ascetic or brahmin relies on logic and inquiry.*";
P_HTM[412]="*So takkapariyāhataṃ vīmaṃsānucaritaṃ sayampaṭibhānaṃ evamāha:**They speak of what they have worked out by logic, following a line of inquiry, expressing their own perspective:*";
P_HTM[413]="*‘adhiccasamuppanno attā ca loko cā’ti.**‘The self and the cosmos arose by chance.’*";
P_HTM[414]="*Idaṃ, bhikkhave, dutiyaṃ ṭhānaṃ, yaṃ āgamma yaṃ ārabbha eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā adhiccasamuppannikā adhiccasamuppannaṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti. (2: 18)**This is the second ground on which some ascetics and brahmins rely to assert that the self and the cosmos arose by chance.*";
P_HTM[415]="*Imehi kho te, bhikkhave, samaṇabrāhmaṇā adhiccasamuppannikā adhiccasamuppannaṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti dvīhi vatthūhi.**These are the two grounds on which those ascetics and brahmins who theorize about chance assert that the self and the cosmos arose by chance.*";
P_HTM[416]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā adhiccasamuppannikā adhiccasamuppannaṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti, sabbe te imeheva dvīhi vatthūhi, etesaṃ vā aññatarena, natthi ito bahiddhā …**Any ascetics and brahmins who theorize about chance do so on one or other of these two grounds. Outside of this there is none.*";
P_HTM[417]="*pe …**The Realized One understands this …*";
P_HTM[418]="*yehi tathāgatassa yathābhuccaṃ vaṇṇaṃ sammā vadamānā vadeyyuṃ.**And those who genuinely praise the Realized One would rightly speak of these things.*";
P_HTM[419]="*Imehi kho te, bhikkhave, samaṇabrāhmaṇā pubbantakappikā pubbantānudiṭṭhino pubbantaṃ ārabbha anekavihitāni adhimuttipadāni abhivadanti aṭṭhārasahi vatthūhi.**These are the eighteen grounds on which those ascetics and brahmins who theorize about the past assert various hypotheses concerning the past.*";
P_HTM[420]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā pubbantakappikā pubbantānudiṭṭhino pubbantamārabbha anekavihitāni adhimuttipadāni abhivadanti, sabbe te imeheva aṭṭhārasahi vatthūhi, etesaṃ vā aññatarena, natthi ito bahiddhā.**Any ascetics and brahmins who theorize about the past do so on one or other of these eighteen grounds. Outside of this there is none.*";
P_HTM[421]="*Tayidaṃ, bhikkhave, tathāgato pajānāti:**The Realized One understands this:*";
P_HTM[422]="*‘ime diṭṭhiṭṭhānā evaṅgahitā evaṃparāmaṭṭhā evaṅgatikā bhavanti evaṃabhisamparāyā’ti.**‘If you hold on to and attach to these grounds for views it leads to such and such a destiny in the next life.’*";
P_HTM[423]="*Tañca tathāgato pajānāti, tato ca uttaritaraṃ pajānāti, tañca pajānanaṃ na parāmasati, aparāmasato cassa paccattaññeva nibbuti viditā.**He understands this, and what goes beyond this. Yet since he does not misapprehend that understanding, he has realized extinguishment within himself.*";
P_HTM[424]="*Vedanānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ viditvā anupādāvimutto, bhikkhave, tathāgato.**Having truly understood the origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape from feelings, the Realized One is freed through not grasping.*";
P_HTM[425]="*Ime kho te, bhikkhave, dhammā gambhīrā duddasā duranubodhā santā paṇītā atakkāvacarā nipuṇā paṇḍitavedanīyā, ye tathāgato sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedeti, yehi tathāgatassa yathābhuccaṃ vaṇṇaṃ sammā vadamānā vadeyyuṃ.**These are the principles—deep, hard to see, hard to understand, peaceful, sublime, beyond the scope of reason, subtle, comprehensible to the astute—which the Realized One makes known after realizing them with his own insight. And those who genuinely praise the Realized One would rightly speak of these things.*";
P_HTM[426]="*Dutiyabhāṇavāro.* **";
P_HTM[427]="*3.2. Aparantakappika**3.2. Theories About the Future*";
P_HTM[428]="*Santi, bhikkhave, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā aparantakappikā aparantānudiṭṭhino, aparantaṃ ārabbha anekavihitāni adhimuttipadāni abhivadanti catucattārīsāya vatthūhi.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who theorize about the future, and assert various hypotheses concerning the future on forty-four grounds.*";
P_HTM[429]="*Te ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha aparantakappikā aparantānudiṭṭhino aparantaṃ ārabbha anekavihitāni adhimuttipadāni abhivadanti catucattārīsāya vatthūhi?**And what are the forty-four grounds on which they rely?*";
P_HTM[430]="*3.2.1. Saññīvāda**3.2.1. Percipient Life After Death*";
P_HTM[431]="*Santi, bhikkhave, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā uddhamāghātanikā saññīvādā uddhamāghātanaṃ saññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti soḷasahi vatthūhi.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who say there is life after death, and assert that the self lives on after death in a percipient form on sixteen grounds.*";
P_HTM[432]="*Te ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha uddhamāghātanikā saññīvādā uddhamāghātanaṃ saññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti soḷasahi vatthūhi?**And what are the sixteen grounds on which they rely?*";
P_HTM[433]="*‘Rūpī attā hoti arogo paraṃ maraṇā saññī’ti naṃ paññapenti. (1: 19)**They assert: ‘The self is sound and percipient after death, and it is physical …*";
P_HTM[434]="*‘Arūpī attā hoti arogo paraṃ maraṇā saññī’ti naṃ paññapenti. (2: 20)**non-physical …*";
P_HTM[435]="*‘Rūpī ca arūpī ca attā hoti … pe …. (3: 21)**both physical and non-physical …*";
P_HTM[436]="*‘Nevarūpī nārūpī attā hoti …. (4: 22)**neither physical nor non-physical …*";
P_HTM[437]="*‘Antavā attā hoti …. (5: 23)**finite …*";
P_HTM[438]="*‘Anantavā attā hoti …. (6: 24)**infinite …*";
P_HTM[439]="*‘Antavā ca anantavā ca attā hoti …. (7: 25)**both finite and infinite …*";
P_HTM[440]="*‘Nevantavā nānantavā attā hoti …. (8: 26)**neither finite nor infinite …*";
P_HTM[441]="*‘Ekattasaññī attā hoti …. (9: 27)**of unified perception …*";
P_HTM[442]="*‘Nānattasaññī attā hoti …. (10: 28)**of diverse perception …*";
P_HTM[443]="*‘Parittasaññī attā hoti …. (11: 29)**of limited perception …*";
P_HTM[444]="*‘Appamāṇasaññī attā hoti …. (12: 30)**of limitless perception …*";
P_HTM[445]="*‘Ekantasukhī attā hoti …. (13: 31)**experiences nothing but happiness …*";
P_HTM[446]="*‘Ekantadukkhī attā hoti …. (14: 32)**experiences nothing but suffering …*";
P_HTM[447]="*‘Sukhadukkhī attā hoti …. (15: 33)**experiences both happiness and suffering …*";
P_HTM[448]="*‘Adukkhamasukhī attā hoti arogo paraṃ maraṇā saññī’ti naṃ paññapenti. (16: 34)**experiences neither happiness nor suffering.’*";
P_HTM[449]="*Imehi kho te, bhikkhave, samaṇabrāhmaṇā uddhamāghātanikā saññīvādā uddhamāghātanaṃ saññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti soḷasahi vatthūhi.**These are the sixteen grounds on which those ascetics and brahmins assert that the self lives on after death in a percipient form.*";
P_HTM[450]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā uddhamāghātanikā saññīvādā uddhamāghātanaṃ saññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti, sabbe te imeheva soḷasahi vatthūhi, etesaṃ vā aññatarena, natthi ito bahiddhā …**Any ascetics and brahmins who assert that the self lives on after death in a percipient form do so on one or other of these sixteen grounds. Outside of this there is none.*";
P_HTM[451]="*pe …**The Realized One understands this …*";
P_HTM[452]="*yehi tathāgatassa yathābhuccaṃ vaṇṇaṃ sammā vadamānā vadeyyuṃ.**And those who genuinely praise the Realized One would rightly speak of these things.*";
P_HTM[453]="*3.2.2. Asaññīvāda**3.2.2. Non-Percipient Life After Death*";
P_HTM[454]="*Santi, bhikkhave, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā uddhamāghātanikā asaññīvādā uddhamāghātanaṃ asaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti aṭṭhahi vatthūhi.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who say there is life after death, and assert that the self lives on after death in a non-percipient form on eight grounds.*";
P_HTM[455]="*Te ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha uddhamāghātanikā asaññīvādā uddhamāghātanaṃ asaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti aṭṭhahi vatthūhi?**And what are the eight grounds on which they rely?*";
P_HTM[456]="*‘Rūpī attā hoti arogo paraṃ maraṇā asaññī’ti naṃ paññapenti. (1: 35)**They assert: ‘The self is sound and non-percipient after death, and it is physical …*";
P_HTM[457]="*‘Arūpī attā hoti arogo paraṃ maraṇā asaññī’ti naṃ paññapenti. (2: 36)**non-physical …*";
P_HTM[458]="*‘Rūpī ca arūpī ca attā hoti … pe …. (3: 37)**both physical and non-physical …*";
P_HTM[459]="*‘Nevarūpī nārūpī attā hoti …. (4: 38)**neither physical nor non-physical …*";
P_HTM[460]="*‘Antavā attā hoti …. (5: 39)**finite …*";
P_HTM[461]="*‘Anantavā attā hoti …. (6: 40)**infinite …*";
P_HTM[462]="*‘Antavā ca anantavā ca attā hoti …. (7: 41)**both finite and infinite …*";
P_HTM[463]="*‘Nevantavā nānantavā attā hoti arogo paraṃ maraṇā asaññī’ti naṃ paññapenti. (8: 42)**neither finite nor infinite.’*";
P_HTM[464]="*Imehi kho te, bhikkhave, samaṇabrāhmaṇā uddhamāghātanikā asaññīvādā uddhamāghātanaṃ asaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti aṭṭhahi vatthūhi.**These are the eight grounds on which those ascetics and brahmins assert that the self lives on after death in a non-percipient form.*";
P_HTM[465]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā uddhamāghātanikā asaññīvādā uddhamāghātanaṃ asaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti, sabbe te imeheva aṭṭhahi vatthūhi, etesaṃ vā aññatarena, natthi ito bahiddhā …**Any ascetics and brahmins who assert that the self lives on after death in a non-percipient form do so on one or other of these eight grounds. Outside of this there is none.*";
P_HTM[466]="*pe …**The Realized One understands this …*";
P_HTM[467]="*yehi tathāgatassa yathābhuccaṃ vaṇṇaṃ sammā vadamānā vadeyyuṃ.**And those who genuinely praise the Realized One would rightly speak of these things.*";
P_HTM[468]="*3.2.3. Nevasaññīnāsaññīvāda**3.2.3. Neither Percipient Nor Non-Percipient Life After Death*";
P_HTM[469]="*Santi, bhikkhave, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā uddhamāghātanikā nevasaññīnāsaññīvādā, uddhamāghātanaṃ nevasaññīnāsaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti aṭṭhahi vatthūhi.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who say there is life after death, and assert that the self lives on after death in a neither percipient nor non-percipient form on eight grounds.*";
P_HTM[470]="*Te ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha uddhamāghātanikā nevasaññīnāsaññīvādā uddhamāghātanaṃ nevasaññīnāsaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti aṭṭhahi vatthūhi?**And what are the eight grounds on which they rely?*";
P_HTM[471]="*‘Rūpī attā hoti arogo paraṃ maraṇā nevasaññīnāsaññī’ti naṃ paññapenti. (1: 43)**They assert: ‘The self is sound and neither percipient nor non-percipient after death, and it is physical …*";
P_HTM[472]="*‘Arūpī attā hoti … pe …. (2: 44)**non-physical …*";
P_HTM[473]="*‘Rūpī ca arūpī ca attā hoti …. (3: 45)**both physical and non-physical …*";
P_HTM[474]="*‘Nevarūpī nārūpī attā hoti …. (4: 46)**neither physical nor non-physical …*";
P_HTM[475]="*‘Antavā attā hoti …. (5: 47)**finite …*";
P_HTM[476]="*‘Anantavā attā hoti …. (6: 48)**infinite …*";
P_HTM[477]="*‘Antavā ca anantavā ca attā hoti …. (7: 49)**both finite and infinite …*";
P_HTM[478]="*‘Nevantavā nānantavā attā hoti arogo paraṃ maraṇā nevasaññīnāsaññī’ti naṃ paññapenti. (8: 50)**neither finite nor infinite.’*";
P_HTM[479]="*Imehi kho te, bhikkhave, samaṇabrāhmaṇā uddhamāghātanikā nevasaññīnāsaññīvādā uddhamāghātanaṃ nevasaññīnāsaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti aṭṭhahi vatthūhi.**These are the eight grounds on which those ascetics and brahmins assert that the self lives on after death in a neither percipient nor non-percipient form.*";
P_HTM[480]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā uddhamāghātanikā nevasaññīnāsaññīvādā uddhamāghātanaṃ nevasaññīnāsaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti, sabbe te imeheva aṭṭhahi vatthūhi …**Any ascetics and brahmins who assert that the self lives on after death in a neither percipient nor non-percipient form do so on one or other of these eight grounds. Outside of this there is none.*";
P_HTM[481]="*pe …**The Realized One understands this …*";
P_HTM[482]="*yehi tathāgatassa yathābhuccaṃ vaṇṇaṃ sammā vadamānā vadeyyuṃ.**And those who genuinely praise the Realized One would rightly speak of these things.*";
P_HTM[483]="*3.2.4. Ucchedavāda**3.2.4. Annihilationism*";
P_HTM[484]="*Santi, bhikkhave, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā ucchedavādā sato sattassa ucchedaṃ vināsaṃ vibhavaṃ paññapenti sattahi vatthūhi.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who are annihilationists. They assert the annihilation, eradication, and obliteration of an existing being on seven grounds.*";
P_HTM[485]="*Te ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha ucchedavādā sato sattassa ucchedaṃ vināsaṃ vibhavaṃ paññapenti sattahi vatthūhi?**And what are the seven grounds on which they rely?*";
P_HTM[486]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā evaṃvādī hoti evaṃdiṭṭhi:**There are some ascetics and brahmins who have this doctrine and view:*";
P_HTM[487]="*‘yato kho, bho, ayaṃ attā rūpī cātumahābhūtiko mātāpettikasambhavo kāyassa bhedā ucchijjati vinassati, na hoti paraṃ maraṇā, ettāvatā kho, bho, ayaṃ attā sammā samucchinno hotī’ti.**‘This self is physical, made up of the four primary elements, and produced by mother and father. Since it’s annihilated and destroyed when the body breaks up, and doesn’t exist after death, that’s how this self becomes rightly annihilated.’*";
P_HTM[488]="*Ittheke sato sattassa ucchedaṃ vināsaṃ vibhavaṃ paññapenti. (1: 51)**That is how some assert the annihilation of an existing being.*";
P_HTM[489]="*Tamañño evamāha:**But someone else says to them:*";
P_HTM[490]="*‘atthi kho, bho, eso attā, yaṃ tvaṃ vadesi, neso natthīti vadāmi;**‘That self of which you speak does exist, I don’t deny it.*";
P_HTM[491]="*no ca kho, bho, ayaṃ attā ettāvatā sammā samucchinno hoti.**But that’s not how this self becomes rightly annihilated.*";
P_HTM[492]="*Atthi kho, bho, añño attā dibbo rūpī kāmāvacaro kabaḷīkārāhārabhakkho.**There is another self that is divine, physical, sensual, consuming solid food.*";
P_HTM[493]="*Taṃ tvaṃ na jānāsi na passasi.**You don’t know or see that.*";
P_HTM[494]="*Tamahaṃ jānāmi passāmi.**But I know it and see it.*";
P_HTM[495]="*So kho, bho, attā yato kāyassa bhedā ucchijjati vinassati, na hoti paraṃ maraṇā, ettāvatā kho, bho, ayaṃ attā sammā samucchinno hotī’ti.**Since this self is annihilated and destroyed when the body breaks up, and doesn’t exist after death, that’s how this self becomes rightly annihilated.’*";
P_HTM[496]="*Ittheke sato sattassa ucchedaṃ vināsaṃ vibhavaṃ paññapenti. (2: 52)**That is how some assert the annihilation of an existing being.*";
P_HTM[497]="*Tamañño evamāha:**But someone else says to them:*";
P_HTM[498]="*‘atthi kho, bho, eso attā, yaṃ tvaṃ vadesi, neso natthīti vadāmi;**‘That self of which you speak does exist, I don’t deny it.*";
P_HTM[499]="*no ca kho, bho, ayaṃ attā ettāvatā sammā samucchinno hoti.**But that’s not how this self becomes rightly annihilated.*";
P_HTM[500]="*Atthi kho, bho, añño attā dibbo rūpī manomayo sabbaṅgapaccaṅgī ahīnindriyo.**There is another self that is divine, physical, mind-made, complete in all its various parts, not deficient in any faculty.*";
P_HTM[501]="*Taṃ tvaṃ na jānāsi na passasi.**You don’t know or see that.*";
P_HTM[502]="*Tamahaṃ jānāmi passāmi.**But I know it and see it.*";
P_HTM[503]="*So kho, bho, attā yato kāyassa bhedā ucchijjati vinassati, na hoti paraṃ maraṇā, ettāvatā kho, bho, ayaṃ attā sammā samucchinno hotī’ti.**Since this self is annihilated and destroyed when the body breaks up, and doesn’t exist after death, that’s how this self becomes rightly annihilated.’*";
P_HTM[504]="*Ittheke sato sattassa ucchedaṃ vināsaṃ vibhavaṃ paññapenti. (3: 53)**That is how some assert the annihilation of an existing being.*";
P_HTM[505]="*Tamañño evamāha:**But someone else says to them:*";
P_HTM[506]="*‘atthi kho, bho, eso attā, yaṃ tvaṃ vadesi, neso natthīti vadāmi;**‘That self of which you speak does exist, I don’t deny it.*";
P_HTM[507]="*no ca kho, bho, ayaṃ attā ettāvatā sammā samucchinno hoti.**But that’s not how this self becomes rightly annihilated.*";
P_HTM[508]="*Atthi kho, bho, añño attā sabbaso rūpasaññānaṃ samatikkamā paṭighasaññānaṃ atthaṅgamā nānattasaññānaṃ amanasikārā “ananto ākāso”ti ākāsānañcāyatanūpago.**There is another self which has gone totally beyond perceptions of form. With the ending of perceptions of impingement, not focusing on perceptions of diversity, aware that “space is infinite”, it’s reborn in the dimension of infinite space.*";
P_HTM[509]="*Taṃ tvaṃ na jānāsi na passasi.**You don’t know or see that.*";
P_HTM[510]="*Tamahaṃ jānāmi passāmi.**But I know it and see it.*";
P_HTM[511]="*So kho, bho, attā yato kāyassa bhedā ucchijjati vinassati, na hoti paraṃ maraṇā, ettāvatā kho, bho, ayaṃ attā sammā samucchinno hotī’ti.**Since this self is annihilated and destroyed when the body breaks up, and doesn’t exist after death, that’s how this self becomes rightly annihilated.’*";
P_HTM[512]="*Ittheke sato sattassa ucchedaṃ vināsaṃ vibhavaṃ paññapenti. (4: 54)**That is how some assert the annihilation of an existing being.*";
P_HTM[513]="*Tamañño evamāha:**But someone else says to them:*";
P_HTM[514]="*‘atthi kho, bho, eso attā yaṃ tvaṃ vadesi, neso natthīti vadāmi;**‘That self of which you speak does exist, I don’t deny it.*";
P_HTM[515]="*no ca kho, bho, ayaṃ attā ettāvatā sammā samucchinno hoti.**But that’s not how this self becomes rightly annihilated.*";
P_HTM[516]="*Atthi kho, bho, añño attā sabbaso ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma “anantaṃ viññāṇan”ti viññāṇañcāyatanūpago.**There is another self which has gone totally beyond the dimension of infinite space. Aware that “consciousness is infinite”, it’s reborn in the dimension of infinite consciousness.*";
P_HTM[517]="*Taṃ tvaṃ na jānāsi na passasi.**You don’t know or see that.*";
P_HTM[518]="*Tamahaṃ jānāmi passāmi.**But I know it and see it.*";
P_HTM[519]="*So kho, bho, attā yato kāyassa bhedā ucchijjati vinassati, na hoti paraṃ maraṇā, ettāvatā kho, bho, ayaṃ attā sammā samucchinno hotī’ti.**Since this self is annihilated and destroyed when the body breaks up, and doesn’t exist after death, that’s how this self becomes rightly annihilated.’*";
P_HTM[520]="*Ittheke sato sattassa ucchedaṃ vināsaṃ vibhavaṃ paññapenti. (5: 55)**That is how some assert the annihilation of an existing being.*";
P_HTM[521]="*Tamañño evamāha:**But someone else says to them:*";
P_HTM[522]="*‘atthi kho, bho, so attā, yaṃ tvaṃ vadesi, neso natthīti vadāmi;**‘That self of which you speak does exist, I don’t deny it.*";
P_HTM[523]="*no ca kho, bho, ayaṃ attā ettāvatā sammā samucchinno hoti.**But that’s not how this self becomes rightly annihilated.*";
P_HTM[524]="*Atthi kho, bho, añño attā sabbaso viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma “natthi kiñcī”ti ākiñcaññāyatanūpago.**There is another self that has gone totally beyond the dimension of infinite consciousness. Aware that “there is nothing at all”, it’s been reborn in the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[525]="*Taṃ tvaṃ na jānāsi na passasi.**You don’t know or see that.*";
P_HTM[526]="*Tamahaṃ jānāmi passāmi.**But I know it and see it.*";
P_HTM[527]="*So kho, bho, attā yato kāyassa bhedā ucchijjati vinassati, na hoti paraṃ maraṇā, ettāvatā kho, bho, ayaṃ attā sammā samucchinno hotī’ti.**Since this self is annihilated and destroyed when the body breaks up, and doesn’t exist after death, that’s how this self becomes rightly annihilated.’*";
P_HTM[528]="*Ittheke sato sattassa ucchedaṃ vināsaṃ vibhavaṃ paññapenti. (6: 56)**That is how some assert the annihilation of an existing being.*";
P_HTM[529]="*Tamañño evamāha:**But someone else says to them:*";
P_HTM[530]="*‘atthi kho, bho, eso attā, yaṃ tvaṃ vadesi, neso natthīti vadāmi;**‘That self of which you speak does exist, I don’t deny it.*";
P_HTM[531]="*no ca kho, bho, ayaṃ attā ettāvatā sammā samucchinno hoti.**But that’s not how this self becomes rightly annihilated.*";
P_HTM[532]="*Atthi kho, bho, añño attā sabbaso ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ samatikkamma “santametaṃ paṇītametan”ti nevasaññānāsaññāyatanūpago.**There is another self that has gone totally beyond the dimension of nothingness. Aware that “this is peaceful, this is sublime”, it’s been reborn in the dimension of neither perception nor non-perception.*";
P_HTM[533]="*Taṃ tvaṃ na jānāsi na passasi.**You don’t know or see that.*";
P_HTM[534]="*Tamahaṃ jānāmi passāmi.**But I know it and see it.*";
P_HTM[535]="*So kho, bho, attā yato kāyassa bhedā ucchijjati vinassati, na hoti paraṃ maraṇā, ettāvatā kho, bho, ayaṃ attā sammā samucchinno hotī’ti.**Since this self is annihilated and destroyed when the body breaks up, and doesn’t exist after death, that’s how this self becomes rightly annihilated.’*";
P_HTM[536]="*Ittheke sato sattassa ucchedaṃ vināsaṃ vibhavaṃ paññapenti. (7: 57)**That is how some assert the annihilation of an existing being.*";
P_HTM[537]="*Imehi kho te, bhikkhave, samaṇabrāhmaṇā ucchedavādā sato sattassa ucchedaṃ vināsaṃ vibhavaṃ paññapenti sattahi vatthūhi.**These are the seven grounds on which those ascetics and brahmins assert the annihilation, eradication, and obliteration of an existing being.*";
P_HTM[538]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā ucchedavādā sato sattassa ucchedaṃ vināsaṃ vibhavaṃ paññapenti, sabbe te imeheva sattahi vatthūhi …**Any ascetics and brahmins who assert the annihilation, eradication, and obliteration of an existing being do so on one or other of these seven grounds. Outside of this there is none.*";
P_HTM[539]="*pe …**The Realized One understands this …*";
P_HTM[540]="*yehi tathāgatassa yathābhuccaṃ vaṇṇaṃ sammā vadamānā vadeyyuṃ.**And those who genuinely praise the Realized One would rightly speak of these things.*";
P_HTM[541]="*3.2.5. Diṭṭhadhammanibbānavāda**3.2.5. Extinguishment in the Present Life*";
P_HTM[542]="*Santi, bhikkhave, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā diṭṭhadhammanibbānavādā sato sattassa paramadiṭṭhadhammanibbānaṃ paññapenti pañcahi vatthūhi.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who speak of extinguishment in the present life. They assert the ultimate extinguishment of an existing being in the present life on five grounds.*";
P_HTM[543]="*Te ca bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā kimāgamma kimārabbha diṭṭhadhammanibbānavādā sato sattassa paramadiṭṭhadhammanibbānaṃ paññapenti pañcahi vatthūhi?**And what are the five grounds on which they rely?*";
P_HTM[544]="*Idha, bhikkhave, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā evaṃvādī hoti evaṃdiṭṭhi:**There are some ascetics and brahmins who have this doctrine and view:*";
P_HTM[545]="*‘yato kho, bho, ayaṃ attā pañcahi kāmaguṇehi samappito samaṅgībhūto paricāreti, ettāvatā kho, bho, ayaṃ attā paramadiṭṭhadhammanibbānaṃ patto hotī’ti.**‘When this self amuses itself, supplied and provided with the five kinds of sensual stimulation, that’s how this self attains ultimate extinguishment in the present life.’*";
P_HTM[546]="*Ittheke sato sattassa paramadiṭṭhadhammanibbānaṃ paññapenti. (1: 58)**That is how some assert the extinguishment of an existing being in the present life.*";
P_HTM[547]="*Tamañño evamāha:**But someone else says to them:*";
P_HTM[548]="*‘atthi kho, bho, eso attā, yaṃ tvaṃ vadesi, neso natthīti vadāmi;**‘That self of which you speak does exist, I don’t deny it.*";
P_HTM[549]="*no ca kho, bho, ayaṃ attā ettāvatā paramadiṭṭhadhammanibbānaṃ patto hoti.**But that’s not how this self attains ultimate extinguishment in the present life.*";
P_HTM[550]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[551]="*Kāmā hi, bho, aniccā dukkhā vipariṇāmadhammā, tesaṃ vipariṇāmaññathābhāvā uppajjanti sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā.**Because sensual pleasures are impermanent, suffering, and perishable. Their decay and perishing give rise to sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress.*";
P_HTM[552]="*Yato kho, bho, ayaṃ attā vivicceva kāmehi vivicca akusalehi dhammehi savitakkaṃ savicāraṃ vivekajaṃ pītisukhaṃ paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati, ettāvatā kho, bho, ayaṃ attā paramadiṭṭhadhammanibbānaṃ patto hotī’ti.**Quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, this self enters and remains in the first absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of seclusion, while placing the mind and keeping it connected. That’s how this self attains ultimate extinguishment in the present life.’*";
P_HTM[553]="*Ittheke sato sattassa paramadiṭṭhadhammanibbānaṃ paññapenti. (2: 59)**That is how some assert the extinguishment of an existing being in the present life.*";
P_HTM[554]="*Tamañño evamāha:**But someone else says to them:*";
P_HTM[555]="*‘atthi kho, bho, eso attā, yaṃ tvaṃ vadesi, neso natthīti vadāmi;**‘That self of which you speak does exist, I don’t deny it.*";
P_HTM[556]="*no ca kho, bho, ayaṃ attā ettāvatā paramadiṭṭhadhammanibbānaṃ patto hoti.**But that’s not how this self attains ultimate extinguishment in the present life.*";
P_HTM[557]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[558]="*Yadeva tattha vitakkitaṃ vicāritaṃ, etenetaṃ oḷārikaṃ akkhāyati.**Because the placing of the mind and the keeping it connected there are coarse.*";
P_HTM[559]="*Yato kho, bho, ayaṃ attā vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā ajjhattaṃ sampasādanaṃ cetaso ekodibhāvaṃ avitakkaṃ avicāraṃ samādhijaṃ pītisukhaṃ dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati, ettāvatā kho, bho, ayaṃ attā paramadiṭṭhadhammanibbānaṃ patto hotī’ti.**But when the placing of the mind and keeping it connected are stilled, this self enters and remains in the second absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of immersion, with internal clarity and confidence, and unified mind, without placing the mind and keeping it connected. That’s how this self attains ultimate extinguishment in the present life.’*";
P_HTM[560]="*Ittheke sato sattassa paramadiṭṭhadhammanibbānaṃ paññapenti. (3: 60)**That is how some assert the extinguishment of an existing being in the present life.*";
P_HTM[561]="*Tamañño evamāha:**But someone else says to them:*";
P_HTM[562]="*‘atthi kho, bho, eso attā, yaṃ tvaṃ vadesi, neso natthīti vadāmi;**‘That self of which you speak does exist, I don’t deny it.*";
P_HTM[563]="*no ca kho, bho, ayaṃ attā ettāvatā paramadiṭṭhadhammanibbānaṃ patto hoti.**But that’s not how this self attains ultimate extinguishment in the present life.*";
P_HTM[564]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[565]="*Yadeva tattha pītigataṃ cetaso uppilāvitattaṃ, etenetaṃ oḷārikaṃ akkhāyati.**Because the rapture and emotional excitement there are coarse.*";
P_HTM[566]="*Yato kho, bho, ayaṃ attā pītiyā ca virāgā upekkhako ca viharati, sato ca sampajāno, sukhañca kāyena paṭisaṃvedeti, yaṃ taṃ ariyā ācikkhanti “upekkhako satimā sukhavihārī”ti, tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati, ettāvatā kho, bho, ayaṃ attā paramadiṭṭhadhammanibbānaṃ patto hotī’ti.**But with the fading away of rapture, this self enters and remains in the third absorption, where it meditates with equanimity, mindful and aware, personally experiencing the bliss of which the noble ones declare, “Equanimous and mindful, one meditates in bliss”. That’s how this self attains ultimate extinguishment in the present life.’*";
P_HTM[567]="*Ittheke sato sattassa paramadiṭṭhadhammanibbānaṃ paññapenti. (4: 61)**That is how some assert the extinguishment of an existing being in the present life.*";
P_HTM[568]="*Tamañño evamāha:**But someone else says to them:*";
P_HTM[569]="*‘atthi kho, bho, eso attā, yaṃ tvaṃ vadesi, neso natthīti vadāmi;**‘That self of which you speak does exist, I don’t deny it.*";
P_HTM[570]="*no ca kho, bho, ayaṃ attā ettāvatā paramadiṭṭhadhammanibbānaṃ patto hoti.**But that’s not how this self attains ultimate extinguishment in the present life.*";
P_HTM[571]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[572]="*Yadeva tattha sukhamiti cetaso ābhogo, etenetaṃ oḷārikaṃ akkhāyati.**Because the bliss and enjoyment there are coarse.*";
P_HTM[573]="*Yato kho, bho, ayaṃ attā sukhassa ca pahānā dukkhassa ca pahānā pubbeva somanassadomanassānaṃ atthaṅgamā adukkhamasukhaṃ upekkhāsatipārisuddhiṃ catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati, ettāvatā kho, bho, ayaṃ attā paramadiṭṭhadhammanibbānaṃ patto hotī’ti.**But giving up pleasure and pain, and ending former happiness and sadness, this self enters and remains in the fourth absorption, without pleasure or pain, with pure equanimity and mindfulness. That’s how this self attains ultimate extinguishment in the present life.’*";
P_HTM[574]="*Ittheke sato sattassa paramadiṭṭhadhammanibbānaṃ paññapenti. (5: 62)**That is how some assert the extinguishment of an existing being in the present life.*";
P_HTM[575]="*Imehi kho te, bhikkhave, samaṇabrāhmaṇā diṭṭhadhammanibbānavādā sato sattassa paramadiṭṭhadhammanibbānaṃ paññapenti pañcahi vatthūhi.**These are the five grounds on which those ascetics and brahmins assert the ultimate extinguishment of an existing being in the present life.*";
P_HTM[576]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā diṭṭhadhammanibbānavādā sato sattassa paramadiṭṭhadhammanibbānaṃ paññapenti, sabbe te imeheva pañcahi vatthūhi …**Any ascetics and brahmins who assert the ultimate extinguishment of an existing being in the present life do so on one or other of these five grounds. Outside of this there is none.*";
P_HTM[577]="*pe …**The Realized One understands this …*";
P_HTM[578]="*yehi tathāgatassa yathābhuccaṃ vaṇṇaṃ sammā vadamānā vadeyyuṃ.**And those who genuinely praise the Realized One would rightly speak of these things.*";
P_HTM[579]="*Imehi kho te, bhikkhave, samaṇabrāhmaṇā aparantakappikā aparantānudiṭṭhino aparantaṃ ārabbha anekavihitāni adhimuttipadāni abhivadanti catucattārīsāya vatthūhi.**These are the forty-four grounds on which those ascetics and brahmins who theorize about the future assert various hypotheses concerning the future.*";
P_HTM[580]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā aparantakappikā aparantānudiṭṭhino aparantaṃ ārabbha anekavihitāni adhimuttipadāni abhivadanti, sabbe te imeheva catucattārīsāya vatthūhi …**Any ascetics and brahmins who theorize about the future do so on one or other of these forty-four grounds. Outside of this there is none.*";
P_HTM[581]="*pe …**The Realized One understands this …*";
P_HTM[582]="*yehi tathāgatassa yathābhuccaṃ vaṇṇaṃ sammā vadamānā vadeyyuṃ.**And those who genuinely praise the Realized One would rightly speak of these things.*";
P_HTM[583]="*Imehi kho te, bhikkhave, samaṇabrāhmaṇā pubbantakappikā ca aparantakappikā ca pubbantāparantakappikā ca pubbantāparantānudiṭṭhino pubbantāparantaṃ ārabbha anekavihitāni adhimuttipadāni abhivadanti dvāsaṭṭhiyā vatthūhi.**These are the sixty-two grounds on which those ascetics and brahmins who theorize about the past and the future assert various hypotheses concerning the past and the future.*";
P_HTM[584]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā pubbantakappikā vā aparantakappikā vā pubbantāparantakappikā vā pubbantāparantānudiṭṭhino pubbantāparantaṃ ārabbha anekavihitāni adhimuttipadāni abhivadanti, sabbe te imeheva dvāsaṭṭhiyā vatthūhi, etesaṃ vā aññatarena; natthi ito bahiddhā.**Any ascetics and brahmins who theorize about the past or the future do so on one or other of these sixty-two grounds. Outside of this there is none.*";
P_HTM[585]="*Tayidaṃ, bhikkhave, tathāgato pajānāti:**The Realized One understands this:*";
P_HTM[586]="*‘ime diṭṭhiṭṭhānā evaṅgahitā evaṃparāmaṭṭhā evaṅgatikā bhavanti evaṃabhisamparāyā’ti.**‘If you hold on to and attach to these grounds for views it leads to such and such a destiny in the next life.’*";
P_HTM[587]="*Tañca tathāgato pajānāti, tato ca uttaritaraṃ pajānāti, tañca pajānanaṃ na parāmasati, aparāmasato cassa paccattaññeva nibbuti viditā.**He understands this, and what goes beyond this. Yet since he does not misapprehend that understanding, he has realized extinguishment within himself.*";
P_HTM[588]="*Vedanānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ viditvā anupādāvimutto, bhikkhave, tathāgato.**Having truly understood the origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape from feelings, the Realized One is freed through not grasping.*";
P_HTM[589]="*Ime kho te, bhikkhave, dhammā gambhīrā duddasā duranubodhā santā paṇītā atakkāvacarā nipuṇā paṇḍitavedanīyā, ye tathāgato sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedeti, yehi tathāgatassa yathābhuccaṃ vaṇṇaṃ sammā vadamānā vadeyyuṃ.**These are the principles—deep, hard to see, hard to understand, peaceful, sublime, beyond the scope of reason, subtle, comprehensible to the astute—which the Realized One makes known after realizing them with his own insight. And those who genuinely praise the Realized One would rightly speak of these things.*";
P_HTM[590]="*4. Attālokapaññattivatthu**4. The Grounds For Assertions About the Self and the Cosmos*";
P_HTM[591]="*4.1. Paritassitavipphanditavāra**4.1. Anxiety and Evasiveness*";
P_HTM[592]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā sassatavādā sassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti catūhi vatthūhi, tadapi tesaṃ bhavataṃ samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ ajānataṃ apassataṃ vedayitaṃ taṇhāgatānaṃ paritassitavipphanditameva.**Now, these things are only the feeling of those who do not know or see, the agitation and evasiveness of those under the sway of craving. Namely, when those ascetics and brahmins assert that the self and the cosmos are eternal on four grounds …*";
P_HTM[593]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā ekaccasassatikā ekaccaasassatikā ekaccaṃ sassataṃ ekaccaṃ asassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti catūhi vatthūhi, tadapi tesaṃ bhavataṃ samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ ajānataṃ apassataṃ vedayitaṃ taṇhāgatānaṃ paritassitavipphanditameva.**partially eternal on four grounds …*";
P_HTM[594]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā antānantikā antānantaṃ lokassa paññapenti catūhi vatthūhi, tadapi tesaṃ bhavataṃ samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ ajānataṃ apassataṃ vedayitaṃ taṇhāgatānaṃ paritassitavipphanditameva.**finite or infinite on four grounds …*";
P_HTM[595]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā amarāvikkhepikā tattha tattha pañhaṃ puṭṭhā samānā vācāvikkhepaṃ āpajjanti amarāvikkhepaṃ catūhi vatthūhi, tadapi tesaṃ bhavataṃ samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ ajānataṃ apassataṃ vedayitaṃ taṇhāgatānaṃ paritassitavipphanditameva.**or they resort to equivocation on four grounds …*";
P_HTM[596]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā adhiccasamuppannikā adhiccasamuppannaṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti dvīhi vatthūhi, tadapi tesaṃ bhavataṃ samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ ajānataṃ apassataṃ vedayitaṃ taṇhāgatānaṃ paritassitavipphanditameva.**or they assert that the self and the cosmos arose by chance on two grounds …*";
P_HTM[597]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā pubbantakappikā pubbantānudiṭṭhino pubbantaṃ ārabbha anekavihitāni adhimuttipadāni abhivadanti aṭṭhārasahi vatthūhi, tadapi tesaṃ bhavataṃ samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ ajānataṃ apassataṃ vedayitaṃ taṇhāgatānaṃ paritassitavipphanditameva.**they theorize about the past on these eighteen grounds …*";
P_HTM[598]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā uddhamāghātanikā saññīvādā uddhamāghātanaṃ saññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti soḷasahi vatthūhi, tadapi tesaṃ bhavataṃ samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ ajānataṃ apassataṃ vedayitaṃ taṇhāgatānaṃ paritassitavipphanditameva.**or they assert that the self lives on after death in a percipient form on sixteen grounds …*";
P_HTM[599]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā uddhamāghātanikā asaññīvādā uddhamāghātanaṃ asaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti aṭṭhahi vatthūhi, tadapi tesaṃ bhavataṃ samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ ajānataṃ apassataṃ vedayitaṃ taṇhāgatānaṃ paritassitavipphanditameva.**or that the self lives on after death in a non-percipient form on eight grounds …*";
P_HTM[600]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā uddhamāghātanikā nevasaññīnāsaññīvādā uddhamāghātanaṃ nevasaññīnāsaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti aṭṭhahi vatthūhi, tadapi tesaṃ bhavataṃ samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ ajānataṃ apassataṃ vedayitaṃ taṇhāgatānaṃ paritassitavipphanditameva.**or that the self lives on after death in a neither percipient nor non-percipient form on eight grounds …*";
P_HTM[601]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā ucchedavādā sato sattassa ucchedaṃ vināsaṃ vibhavaṃ paññapenti sattahi vatthūhi, tadapi tesaṃ bhavataṃ samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ ajānataṃ apassataṃ vedayitaṃ taṇhāgatānaṃ paritassitavipphanditameva.**or they assert the annihilation of an existing being on seven grounds …*";
P_HTM[602]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā diṭṭhadhammanibbānavādā sato sattassa paramadiṭṭhadhammanibbānaṃ paññapenti pañcahi vatthūhi, tadapi tesaṃ bhavataṃ samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ ajānataṃ apassataṃ vedayitaṃ taṇhāgatānaṃ paritassitavipphanditameva.**or they assert the ultimate extinguishment of an existing being in the present life on five grounds …*";
P_HTM[603]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā aparantakappikā aparantānudiṭṭhino aparantaṃ ārabbha anekavihitāni adhimuttipadāni abhivadanti catucattārīsāya vatthūhi, tadapi tesaṃ bhavataṃ samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ ajānataṃ apassataṃ vedayitaṃ taṇhāgatānaṃ paritassitavipphanditameva.**they theorize about the future on these forty-four grounds …*";
P_HTM[604]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā pubbantakappikā ca aparantakappikā ca pubbantāparantakappikā ca pubbantāparantānudiṭṭhino pubbantāparantaṃ ārabbha anekavihitāni adhimuttipadāni abhivadanti dvāsaṭṭhiyā vatthūhi, tadapi tesaṃ bhavataṃ samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ ajānataṃ apassataṃ vedayitaṃ taṇhāgatānaṃ paritassitavipphanditameva.**When those ascetics and brahmins theorize about the past and the future on these sixty-two grounds, these things are only the feeling of those who do not know or see, the agitation and evasiveness of those under the sway of craving.*";
P_HTM[605]="*4.2. Phassapaccayāvāra**4.2. Conditioned by Contact*";
P_HTM[606]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā sassatavādā sassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti catūhi vatthūhi, tadapi phassapaccayā.**Now, these things are conditioned by contact. Namely, when those ascetics and brahmins assert that the self and the cosmos are eternal on four grounds …*";
P_HTM[607]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā ekaccasassatikā ekaccaasassatikā ekaccaṃ sassataṃ ekaccaṃ asassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti catūhi vatthūhi, tadapi phassapaccayā.**partially eternal on four grounds …*";
P_HTM[608]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā antānantikā antānantaṃ lokassa paññapenti catūhi vatthūhi, tadapi phassapaccayā.**finite or infinite on four grounds …*";
P_HTM[609]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā amarāvikkhepikā tattha tattha pañhaṃ puṭṭhā samānā vācāvikkhepaṃ āpajjanti amarāvikkhepaṃ catūhi vatthūhi, tadapi phassapaccayā.**or they resort to equivocation on four grounds …*";
P_HTM[610]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā adhiccasamuppannikā adhiccasamuppannaṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti dvīhi vatthūhi, tadapi phassapaccayā.**or they assert that the self and the cosmos arose by chance on two grounds …*";
P_HTM[611]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā pubbantakappikā pubbantānudiṭṭhino pubbantaṃ ārabbha anekavihitāni adhimuttipadāni abhivadanti aṭṭhārasahi vatthūhi, tadapi phassapaccayā.**they theorize about the past on these eighteen grounds …*";
P_HTM[612]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā uddhamāghātanikā saññīvādā uddhamāghātanaṃ saññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti soḷasahi vatthūhi, tadapi phassapaccayā.**or they assert that the self lives on after death in a percipient form on sixteen grounds …*";
P_HTM[613]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā uddhamāghātanikā asaññīvādā uddhamāghātanaṃ asaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti aṭṭhahi vatthūhi, tadapi phassapaccayā.**or that the self lives on after death in a non-percipient form on eight grounds …*";
P_HTM[614]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā uddhamāghātanikā nevasaññīnāsaññīvādā uddhamāghātanaṃ nevasaññīnāsaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti aṭṭhahi vatthūhi, tadapi phassapaccayā.**or that the self lives on after death in a neither percipient nor non-percipient form on eight grounds …*";
P_HTM[615]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā ucchedavādā sato sattassa ucchedaṃ vināsaṃ vibhavaṃ paññapenti sattahi vatthūhi, tadapi phassapaccayā.**or they assert the annihilation of an existing being on seven grounds …*";
P_HTM[616]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā diṭṭhadhammanibbānavādā sato sattassa paramadiṭṭhadhammanibbānaṃ paññapenti pañcahi vatthūhi, tadapi phassapaccayā.**or they assert the ultimate extinguishment of an existing being in the present life on five grounds …*";
P_HTM[617]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā aparantakappikā aparantānudiṭṭhino aparantaṃ ārabbha anekavihitāni adhimuttipadāni abhivadanti catucattārīsāya vatthūhi, tadapi phassapaccayā.**they theorize about the future on these forty-four grounds …*";
P_HTM[618]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā pubbantakappikā ca aparantakappikā ca pubbantāparantakappikā ca pubbantāparantānudiṭṭhino pubbantāparantaṃ ārabbha anekavihitāni adhimuttipadāni abhivadanti dvāsaṭṭhiyā vatthūhi, tadapi phassapaccayā.**When those ascetics and brahmins theorize about the past and the future on these sixty-two grounds, that too is conditioned by contact.*";
P_HTM[619]="*4.3. Netaṃṭhānaṃvijjativāra**4.3. Not Possible*";
P_HTM[620]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā sassatavādā sassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti catūhi vatthūhi, te vata aññatra phassā paṭisaṃvedissantīti netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.* **";
P_HTM[621]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā ekaccasassatikā ekaccaasassatikā ekaccaṃ sassataṃ ekaccaṃ asassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti catūhi vatthūhi, te vata aññatra phassā paṭisaṃvedissantīti netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.* **";
P_HTM[622]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā antānantikā antānantaṃ lokassa paññapenti catūhi vatthūhi, te vata aññatra phassā paṭisaṃvedissantīti netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.* **";
P_HTM[623]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā amarāvikkhepikā tattha tattha pañhaṃ puṭṭhā samānā vācāvikkhepaṃ āpajjanti amarāvikkhepaṃ catūhi vatthūhi, te vata aññatra phassā paṭisaṃvedissantīti netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.* **";
P_HTM[624]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā adhiccasamuppannikā adhiccasamuppannaṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti dvīhi vatthūhi, te vata aññatra phassā paṭisaṃvedissantīti netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.* **";
P_HTM[625]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā pubbantakappikā pubbantānudiṭṭhino pubbantaṃ ārabbha anekavihitāni adhimuttipadāni abhivadanti aṭṭhārasahi vatthūhi, te vata aññatra phassā paṭisaṃvedissantīti netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.* **";
P_HTM[626]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā uddhamāghātanikā saññīvādā uddhamāghātanaṃ saññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti soḷasahi vatthūhi, te vata aññatra phassā paṭisaṃvedissantīti netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.* **";
P_HTM[627]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā uddhamāghātanikā asaññīvādā, uddhamāghātanaṃ asaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti aṭṭhahi vatthūhi, te vata aññatra phassā paṭisaṃvedissantīti netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.* **";
P_HTM[628]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā uddhamāghātanikā nevasaññīnāsaññīvādā uddhamāghātanaṃ nevasaññīnāsaññiṃ attānaṃ paññapenti aṭṭhahi vatthūhi, te vata aññatra phassā paṭisaṃvedissantīti netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.* **";
P_HTM[629]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā ucchedavādā sato sattassa ucchedaṃ vināsaṃ vibhavaṃ paññapenti sattahi vatthūhi, te vata aññatra phassā paṭisaṃvedissantīti netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.* **";
P_HTM[630]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā diṭṭhadhammanibbānavādā sato sattassa paramadiṭṭhadhammanibbānaṃ paññapenti pañcahi vatthūhi, te vata aññatra phassā paṭisaṃvedissantīti netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.* **";
P_HTM[631]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā aparantakappikā aparantānudiṭṭhino aparantaṃ ārabbha anekavihitāni adhimuttipadāni abhivadanti catucattārīsāya vatthūhi, te vata aññatra phassā paṭisaṃvedissantīti netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.* **";
P_HTM[632]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā pubbantakappikā ca aparantakappikā ca pubbantāparantakappikā ca pubbantāparantānudiṭṭhino pubbantāparantaṃ ārabbha anekavihitāni adhimuttipadāni abhivadanti dvāsaṭṭhiyā vatthūhi, te vata aññatra phassā paṭisaṃvedissantīti netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**Now, when those ascetics and brahmins theorize about the past and the future on these sixty-two grounds, it is not possible that they should experience these things without contact.*";
P_HTM[633]="*4.4. Diṭṭhigatikādhiṭṭhānavaṭṭakathā**4.4. Dependent Origination*";
P_HTM[634]="*Tatra, bhikkhave, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā sassatavādā sassataṃ attānañca lokañca paññapenti catūhi vatthūhi, yepi te samaṇabrāhmaṇā ekaccasassatikā ekaccaasassatikā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[635]="*yepi te samaṇabrāhmaṇā antānantikā …* **";
P_HTM[636]="*yepi te samaṇabrāhmaṇā amarāvikkhepikā …* **";
P_HTM[637]="*yepi te samaṇabrāhmaṇā adhiccasamuppannikā …* **";
P_HTM[638]="*yepi te samaṇabrāhmaṇā pubbantakappikā …* **";
P_HTM[639]="*yepi te samaṇabrāhmaṇā uddhamāghātanikā saññīvādā …* **";
P_HTM[640]="*yepi te samaṇabrāhmaṇā uddhamāghātanikā asaññīvādā …* **";
P_HTM[641]="*yepi te samaṇabrāhmaṇā uddhamāghātanikā nevasaññīnāsaññīvādā …* **";
P_HTM[642]="*yepi te samaṇabrāhmaṇā ucchedavādā …* **";
P_HTM[643]="*yepi te samaṇabrāhmaṇā diṭṭhadhammanibbānavādā …* **";
P_HTM[644]="*yepi te samaṇabrāhmaṇā aparantakappikā …* **";
P_HTM[645]="*yepi te samaṇabrāhmaṇā pubbantakappikā ca aparantakappikā ca pubbantāparantakappikā ca pubbantāparantānudiṭṭhino pubbantāparantaṃ ārabbha anekavihitāni adhimuttipadāni abhivadanti dvāsaṭṭhiyā vatthūhi, sabbe te chahi phassāyatanehi phussa phussa paṭisaṃvedenti tesaṃ vedanāpaccayā taṇhā, taṇhāpaccayā upādānaṃ, upādānapaccayā bhavo, bhavapaccayā jāti, jātipaccayā jarāmaraṇaṃ sokaparidevadukkhadomanassupāyāsā sambhavanti.**Now, when those ascetics and brahmins theorize about the past and the future on these sixty-two grounds, all of them experience this by repeated contact through the six fields of contact. Their feeling is a condition for craving. Craving is a condition for grasping. Grasping is a condition for continued existence. Continued existence is a condition for rebirth. Rebirth is a condition for old age and death, sorrow, lamentation, pain, sadness, and distress to come to be.*";
P_HTM[646]="*5. Vivaṭṭakathādi**5. The End of the Round*";
P_HTM[647]="*Yato kho, bhikkhave, bhikkhu channaṃ phassāyatanānaṃ samudayañca atthaṅgamañca assādañca ādīnavañca nissaraṇañca yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ayaṃ imehi sabbeheva uttaritaraṃ pajānāti.**When a mendicant truly understands the six fields of contacts’ origin, ending, gratification, drawback, and escape, they understand what lies beyond all these things.*";
P_HTM[648]="*Ye hi keci, bhikkhave, samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā pubbantakappikā vā aparantakappikā vā pubbantāparantakappikā vā pubbantāparantānudiṭṭhino pubbantāparantaṃ ārabbha anekavihitāni adhimuttipadāni abhivadanti, sabbe te imeheva dvāsaṭṭhiyā vatthūhi antojālīkatā, ettha sitāva ummujjamānā ummujjanti, ettha pariyāpannā antojālīkatāva ummujjamānā ummujjanti.**All of these ascetics and brahmins who theorize about the past or the future are trapped in the net of these sixty-two grounds, so that wherever they emerge they are caught and trapped in this very net.*";
P_HTM[649]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, dakkho kevaṭṭo vā kevaṭṭantevāsī vā sukhumacchikena jālena parittaṃ udakadahaṃ otthareyya. Tassa evamassa: ‘ye kho keci imasmiṃ udakadahe oḷārikā pāṇā, sabbe te antojālīkatā. Ettha sitāva ummujjamānā ummujjanti; ettha pariyāpannā antojālīkatāva ummujjamānā ummujjantī’ti;**Suppose a deft fisherman or his apprentice were to cast a fine-meshed net over a small pond. They’d think: ‘Any sizable creatures in this pond will be trapped in the net. Wherever they emerge they are caught and trapped in this very net.’*";
P_HTM[650]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, ye hi keci samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā pubbantakappikā vā aparantakappikā vā pubbantāparantakappikā vā pubbantāparantānudiṭṭhino pubbantāparantaṃ ārabbha anekavihitāni adhimuttipadāni abhivadanti, sabbe te imeheva dvāsaṭṭhiyā vatthūhi antojālīkatā ettha sitāva ummujjamānā ummujjanti, ettha pariyāpannā antojālīkatāva ummujjamānā ummujjanti.**In the same way, all of these ascetics and brahmins who theorize about the past or the future are trapped in the net of these sixty-two grounds, so that wherever they emerge they are caught and trapped in this very net.*";
P_HTM[651]="*Ucchinnabhavanettiko, bhikkhave, tathāgatassa kāyo tiṭṭhati.**The Realized One’s body remains, but his attachment to rebirth has been cut off.*";
P_HTM[652]="*Yāvassa kāyo ṭhassati, tāva naṃ dakkhanti devamanussā.**As long as his body remains he will be seen by gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[653]="*Kāyassa bhedā uddhaṃ jīvitapariyādānā na naṃ dakkhanti devamanussā.**But when his body breaks up, after life has ended, gods and humans will see him no more.*";
P_HTM[654]="*Seyyathāpi, bhikkhave, ambapiṇḍiyā vaṇṭacchinnāya yāni kānici ambāni vaṇṭapaṭibandhāni, sabbāni tāni tadanvayāni bhavanti;**When the stalk of a bunch of mangoes is cut, all the mangoes attached to the stalk will follow along.*";
P_HTM[655]="*evameva kho, bhikkhave, ucchinnabhavanettiko tathāgatassa kāyo tiṭṭhati,**In the same way, the Realized One’s body remains, but his attachment to rebirth has been cut off.*";
P_HTM[656]="*yāvassa kāyo ṭhassati, tāva naṃ dakkhanti devamanussā,**As long as his body remains he will be seen by gods and humans.*";
P_HTM[657]="*kāyassa bhedā uddhaṃ jīvitapariyādānā na naṃ dakkhanti devamanussā”ti.**But when his body breaks up, after life has ended, gods and humans will see him no more.”*";
P_HTM[658]="*Evaṃ vutte, āyasmā ānando bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he had spoken, Venerable Ānanda said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[659]="*“acchariyaṃ, bhante, abbhutaṃ, bhante, ko nāmo ayaṃ, bhante, dhammapariyāyo”ti?**“It’s incredible, sir, it’s amazing! What is the name of this exposition of the teaching?”*";
P_HTM[660]="*“Tasmātiha tvaṃ, ānanda, imaṃ dhammapariyāyaṃ atthajālantipi naṃ dhārehi, dhammajālantipi naṃ dhārehi, brahmajālantipi naṃ dhārehi, diṭṭhijālantipi naṃ dhārehi, anuttaro saṅgāmavijayotipi naṃ dhārehī”ti.**“Well, then, Ānanda, you may remember this exposition of the teaching as ‘The Net of Meaning’, or else ‘The Net of the Teaching’, or else ‘The Prime Net’, or else ‘The Net of Views’, or else ‘The Supreme Victory in Battle’.”*";
P_HTM[661]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[662]="*Attamanā te bhikkhū bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the mendicants were happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[663]="*Imasmiñca pana veyyākaraṇasmiṃ bhaññamāne dasasahassī lokadhātu akampitthāti.**And while this discourse was being spoken, the galaxy shook.*";
P_HTM[664]="*Brahmajālasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ paṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[665]="*02. Sāmaññaphalasutta  - The Fruits of the Ascetic Life * **";
P_HTM[666]="*1. Rājāmaccakathā**1. A Discussion With the King’s Ministers*";
P_HTM[667]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[668]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā rājagahe viharati jīvakassa komārabhaccassa ambavane mahatā bhikkhusaṅghena saddhiṃ aḍḍhateḷasehi bhikkhusatehi.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Rājagaha in the Mango Grove of Jīvaka Komārabhacca, together with a large Saṅgha of 1,250 mendicants.*";
P_HTM[669]="*Tena kho pana samayena rājā māgadho ajātasattu vedehiputto tadahuposathe pannarase komudiyā cātumāsiniyā puṇṇāya puṇṇamāya rattiyā rājāmaccaparivuto uparipāsādavaragato nisinno hoti.**Now, at that time it was the sabbath—the Komudi full moon on the fifteenth day of the fourth month—and King Ajātasattu Vedehiputta of Magadha was sitting upstairs in the stilt longhouse surrounded by his ministers.*";
P_HTM[670]="*Atha kho rājā māgadho ajātasattu vedehiputto tadahuposathe udānaṃ udānesi:**Then Ajātasattu was inspired to exclaim,*";
P_HTM[671]="*“ramaṇīyā vata bho dosinā ratti, abhirūpā vata bho dosinā ratti, dassanīyā vata bho dosinā ratti, pāsādikā vata bho dosinā ratti, lakkhaññā vata bho dosinā ratti.**“Oh, sirs, this moonlit night is so very delightful, so beautiful, so glorious, so lovely, so striking.*";
P_HTM[672]="*Kaṃ nu khvajja samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā payirupāseyyāma, yaṃ no payirupāsato cittaṃ pasīdeyyā”ti?**Now, what ascetic or brahmin might I pay homage to today, paying homage to whom my mind might find peace?”*";
P_HTM[673]="*Evaṃ vutte, aññataro rājāmacco rājānaṃ māgadhaṃ ajātasattuṃ vedehiputtaṃ etadavoca:**When he had spoken, one of the king’s ministers said to him,*";
P_HTM[674]="*“ayaṃ, deva, pūraṇo kassapo saṅghī ceva gaṇī ca gaṇācariyo ca ñāto yasassī titthakaro sādhusammato bahujanassa rattaññū cirapabbajito addhagato vayoanuppatto.**“Sire, Pūraṇa Kassapa leads an order and a community, and teaches a community. He’s a well-known and famous religious founder, regarded as holy by many people. He is of long standing, long gone forth; he is advanced in years and has reached the final stage of life.*";
P_HTM[675]="*Taṃ devo pūraṇaṃ kassapaṃ payirupāsatu.**Let Your Majesty pay homage to him.*";
P_HTM[676]="*Appeva nāma devassa pūraṇaṃ kassapaṃ payirupāsato cittaṃ pasīdeyyā”ti.**Hopefully in so doing your mind will find peace.”*";
P_HTM[677]="*Evaṃ vutte, rājā māgadho ajātasattu vedehiputto tuṇhī ahosi.**But when he had spoken, the king remained silent.*";
P_HTM[678]="*Aññataropi kho rājāmacco rājānaṃ māgadhaṃ ajātasattuṃ vedehiputtaṃ etadavoca:**Another of the king’s ministers said to him,*";
P_HTM[679]="*“ayaṃ, deva, makkhali gosālo saṅghī ceva gaṇī ca gaṇācariyo ca ñāto yasassī titthakaro sādhusammato bahujanassa rattaññū cirapabbajito addhagato vayoanuppatto.**“Sire, Makkhali Gosāla leads an order and a community, and teaches a community. He’s a well-known and famous religious founder, regarded as holy by many people. He is of long standing, long gone forth; he is advanced in years and has reached the final stage of life.*";
P_HTM[680]="*Taṃ devo makkhaliṃ gosālaṃ payirupāsatu.**Let Your Majesty pay homage to him.*";
P_HTM[681]="*Appeva nāma devassa makkhaliṃ gosālaṃ payirupāsato cittaṃ pasīdeyyā”ti.**Hopefully in so doing your mind will find peace.”*";
P_HTM[682]="*Evaṃ vutte, rājā māgadho ajātasattu vedehiputto tuṇhī ahosi.**But when he had spoken, the king remained silent.*";
P_HTM[683]="*Aññataropi kho rājāmacco rājānaṃ māgadhaṃ ajātasattuṃ vedehiputtaṃ etadavoca:**Another of the king’s ministers said to him,*";
P_HTM[684]="*“ayaṃ, deva, ajito kesakambalo saṅghī ceva gaṇī ca gaṇācariyo ca ñāto yasassī titthakaro sādhusammato bahujanassa rattaññū cirapabbajito addhagato vayoanuppatto.**“Sire, Ajita Kesakambala leads an order and a community, and teaches a community. He’s a well-known and famous religious founder, regarded as holy by many people. He is of long standing, long gone forth; he is advanced in years and has reached the final stage of life.*";
P_HTM[685]="*Taṃ devo ajitaṃ kesakambalaṃ payirupāsatu.**Let Your Majesty pay homage to him.*";
P_HTM[686]="*Appeva nāma devassa ajitaṃ kesakambalaṃ payirupāsato cittaṃ pasīdeyyā”ti.**Hopefully in so doing your mind will find peace.”*";
P_HTM[687]="*Evaṃ vutte, rājā māgadho ajātasattu vedehiputto tuṇhī ahosi.**But when he had spoken, the king remained silent.*";
P_HTM[688]="*Aññataropi kho rājāmacco rājānaṃ māgadhaṃ ajātasattuṃ vedehiputtaṃ etadavoca:**Another of the king’s ministers said to him,*";
P_HTM[689]="*“ayaṃ, deva, pakudho kaccāyano saṅghī ceva gaṇī ca gaṇācariyo ca ñāto yasassī titthakaro sādhusammato bahujanassa rattaññū cirapabbajito addhagato vayoanuppatto.**“Sire, Pakudha Kaccāyana leads an order and a community, and teaches a community. He’s a well-known and famous religious founder, regarded as holy by many people. He is of long standing, long gone forth; he is advanced in years and has reached the final stage of life.*";
P_HTM[690]="*Taṃ devo pakudhaṃ kaccāyanaṃ payirupāsatu.**Let Your Majesty pay homage to him.*";
P_HTM[691]="*Appeva nāma devassa pakudhaṃ kaccāyanaṃ payirupāsato cittaṃ pasīdeyyā”ti.**Hopefully in so doing your mind will find peace.”*";
P_HTM[692]="*Evaṃ vutte, rājā māgadho ajātasattu vedehiputto tuṇhī ahosi.**But when he had spoken, the king remained silent.*";
P_HTM[693]="*Aññataropi kho rājāmacco rājānaṃ māgadhaṃ ajātasattuṃ vedehiputtaṃ etadavoca:**Another of the king’s ministers said to him,*";
P_HTM[694]="*“ayaṃ, deva, sañcayo belaṭṭhaputto saṃghī ceva gaṇī ca gaṇācariyo ca ñāto yasassī titthakaro sādhusammato bahujanassa rattaññū cirapabbajito addhagato vayoanuppatto.**“Sire, Sañjaya Belaṭṭhiputta leads an order and a community, and teaches a community. He’s a well-known and famous religious founder, regarded as holy by many people. He is of long standing, long gone forth; he is advanced in years and has reached the final stage of life.*";
P_HTM[695]="*Taṃ devo sañcayaṃ belaṭṭhaputtaṃ payirupāsatu.**Let Your Majesty pay homage to him.*";
P_HTM[696]="*Appeva nāma devassa sañcayaṃ belaṭṭhaputtaṃ payirupāsato cittaṃ pasīdeyyā”ti.**Hopefully in so doing your mind will find peace.”*";
P_HTM[697]="*Evaṃ vutte, rājā māgadho ajātasattu vedehiputto tuṇhī ahosi.**But when he had spoken, the king remained silent.*";
P_HTM[698]="*Aññataropi kho rājāmacco rājānaṃ māgadhaṃ ajātasattuṃ vedehiputtaṃ etadavoca:**Another of the king’s ministers said to him,*";
P_HTM[699]="*“ayaṃ, deva, nigaṇṭho nāṭaputto saṃghī ceva gaṇī ca gaṇācariyo ca ñāto yasassī titthakaro sādhusammato bahujanassa rattaññū cirapabbajito addhagato vayoanuppatto.**“Sire, Nigaṇṭha Nātaputta leads an order and a community, and teaches a community. He’s a well-known and famous religious founder, regarded as holy by many people. He is of long standing, long gone forth; he is advanced in years and has reached the final stage of life.*";
P_HTM[700]="*Taṃ devo nigaṇṭhaṃ nāṭaputtaṃ payirupāsatu.**Let Your Majesty pay homage to him.*";
P_HTM[701]="*Appeva nāma devassa nigaṇṭhaṃ nāṭaputtaṃ payirupāsato cittaṃ pasīdeyyā”ti.**Hopefully in so doing your mind will find peace.”*";
P_HTM[702]="*Evaṃ vutte, rājā māgadho ajātasattu vedehiputto tuṇhī ahosi.**But when he had spoken, the king remained silent.*";
P_HTM[703]="*2. Komārabhaccajīvakakathā**2. A Discussion With Jīvaka Komārabhacca*";
P_HTM[704]="*Tena kho pana samayena jīvako komārabhacco rañño māgadhassa ajātasattussa vedehiputtassa avidūre tuṇhībhūto nisinno hoti.**Now at that time Jīvaka Komārabhacca was sitting silently not far from the king.*";
P_HTM[705]="*Atha kho rājā māgadho ajātasattu vedehiputto jīvakaṃ komārabhaccaṃ etadavoca:**Then the king said to him,*";
P_HTM[706]="*“tvaṃ pana, samma jīvaka, kiṃ tuṇhī”ti?**“But my dear Jīvaka, why are you silent?”*";
P_HTM[707]="*“Ayaṃ, deva, bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho amhākaṃ ambavane viharati mahatā bhikkhusaṃghena saddhiṃ aḍḍhateḷasehi bhikkhusatehi.**“Sire, the Blessed One, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha is staying in my mango grove together with a large Saṅgha of 1,250 mendicants.*";
P_HTM[708]="*Taṃ kho pana bhagavantaṃ evaṃ kalyāṇo kittisaddo abbhuggato:**He has this good reputation:*";
P_HTM[709]="*‘itipi so bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā’ti.**‘That Blessed One is perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.’*";
P_HTM[710]="*Taṃ devo bhagavantaṃ payirupāsatu.**Let Your Majesty pay homage to him.*";
P_HTM[711]="*Appeva nāma devassa bhagavantaṃ payirupāsato cittaṃ pasīdeyyā”ti.**Hopefully in so doing your mind will find peace.”*";
P_HTM[712]="*“Tena hi, samma jīvaka, hatthiyānāni kappāpehī”ti.**“Well then, my dear Jīvaka, have the elephants readied.”*";
P_HTM[713]="*“Evaṃ, devā”ti kho jīvako komārabhacco rañño māgadhassa ajātasattussa vedehiputtassa paṭissuṇitvā pañcamattāni hatthinikāsatāni kappāpetvā rañño ca ārohaṇīyaṃ nāgaṃ, rañño māgadhassa ajātasattussa vedehiputtassa paṭivedesi:**“Yes, Your Majesty,” replied Jīvaka. He had around five hundred female elephants readied, in addition to the king’s bull elephant for riding. Then he informed the king,*";
P_HTM[714]="*“kappitāni kho te, deva, hatthiyānāni,**“The elephants are ready, sire.*";
P_HTM[715]="*yassadāni kālaṃ maññasī”ti.**Please go at your convenience.”*";
P_HTM[716]="*Atha kho rājā māgadho ajātasattu vedehiputto pañcasu hatthinikāsatesu paccekā itthiyo āropetvā ārohaṇīyaṃ nāgaṃ abhiruhitvā ukkāsu dhāriyamānāsu rājagahamhā niyyāsi mahaccarājānubhāvena, yena jīvakassa komārabhaccassa ambavanaṃ tena pāyāsi.**Then King Ajātasattu had women mounted on each of the five hundred female elephants, while he mounted his bull elephant. With attendants carrying torches, he set out in full royal pomp from Rājagaha to Jīvaka’s mango grove.*";
P_HTM[717]="*Atha kho rañño māgadhassa ajātasattussa vedehiputtassa avidūre ambavanassa ahudeva bhayaṃ, ahu chambhitattaṃ, ahu lomahaṃso.**But as he drew near the mango grove, the king became frightened, scared, his hair standing on end.*";
P_HTM[718]="*Atha kho rājā māgadho ajātasattu vedehiputto bhīto saṃviggo lomahaṭṭhajāto jīvakaṃ komārabhaccaṃ etadavoca:**He said to Jīvaka,*";
P_HTM[719]="*“kacci maṃ, samma jīvaka, na vañcesi?**“My dear Jīvaka, I hope you’re not deceiving me!*";
P_HTM[720]="*Kacci maṃ, samma jīvaka, na palambhesi?**I hope you’re not betraying me!*";
P_HTM[721]="*Kacci maṃ, samma jīvaka, na paccatthikānaṃ desi?**I hope you’re not turning me over to my enemies!*";
P_HTM[722]="*Kathañhi nāma tāva mahato bhikkhusaṅghassa aḍḍhateḷasānaṃ bhikkhusatānaṃ neva khipitasaddo bhavissati, na ukkāsitasaddo na nigghoso”ti.**For how on earth can there be no sound of coughing or clearing throats or any noise in such a large Saṅgha of 1,250 mendicants?”*";
P_HTM[723]="*“Mā bhāyi, mahārāja, mā bhāyi, mahārāja.**“Do not fear, great king, do not fear!*";
P_HTM[724]="*Na taṃ, deva, vañcemi;**I am not deceiving you,*";
P_HTM[725]="*na taṃ, deva, palambhāmi;**or betraying you,*";
P_HTM[726]="*na taṃ, deva, paccatthikānaṃ demi.**or turning you over to your enemies.*";
P_HTM[727]="*Abhikkama, mahārāja, abhikkama, mahārāja, ete maṇḍalamāḷe dīpā jhāyantī”ti.**Go forward, great king, go forward! Those are lamps shining in the pavilion.”*";
P_HTM[728]="*3. Sāmaññaphalapucchā**3. The Question About the Fruits of the Ascetic Life*";
P_HTM[729]="*Atha kho rājā māgadho ajātasattu vedehiputto yāvatikā nāgassa bhūmi nāgena gantvā, nāgā paccorohitvā, pattikova yena maṇḍalamāḷassa dvāraṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā jīvakaṃ komārabhaccaṃ etadavoca:**Then King Ajātasattu rode on the elephant as far as the terrain allowed, then descended and approached the pavilion door on foot, where he asked Jīvaka,*";
P_HTM[730]="*“kahaṃ pana, samma jīvaka, bhagavā”ti?**“But my dear Jīvaka, where is the Buddha?”*";
P_HTM[731]="*“Eso, mahārāja, bhagavā;**“That is the Buddha, great king, that is the Buddha!*";
P_HTM[732]="*eso, mahārāja, bhagavā majjhimaṃ thambhaṃ nissāya puratthābhimukho nisinno purakkhato bhikkhusaṃghassā”ti.**He’s sitting against the central column facing east, in front of the Saṅgha of mendicants.”*";
P_HTM[733]="*Atha kho rājā māgadho ajātasattu vedehiputto yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhāsi.**Then the king went up to the Buddha and stood to one side.*";
P_HTM[734]="*Ekamantaṃ ṭhito kho rājā māgadho ajātasattu vedehiputto tuṇhībhūtaṃ tuṇhībhūtaṃ bhikkhusaṃghaṃ anuviloketvā rahadamiva vippasannaṃ udānaṃ udānesi:**He looked around the Saṅgha of monks, who were so very silent, like a still, clear lake, and was inspired to exclaim,*";
P_HTM[735]="*“iminā me upasamena udayabhaddo kumāro samannāgato hotu, yenetarahi upasamena bhikkhusaṃgho samannāgato”ti.**“May my son, Prince Udāyibhadda, be blessed with such peace as the Saṅgha of mendicants now enjoys!”*";
P_HTM[736]="*“Agamā kho tvaṃ, mahārāja, yathāpeman”ti.**“Has your mind gone to one you love, great king?”*";
P_HTM[737]="*“Piyo me, bhante, udayabhaddo kumāro.**“I love my son, sir, Prince Udāyibhadda.*";
P_HTM[738]="*Iminā me, bhante, upasamena udayabhaddo kumāro samannāgato hotu yenetarahi upasamena bhikkhusaṃgho samannāgato”ti.**May he be blessed with such peace as the Saṅgha of mendicants now enjoys!”*";
P_HTM[739]="*Atha kho rājā māgadho ajātasattu vedehiputto bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā, bhikkhusaṃghassa añjaliṃ paṇāmetvā, ekamantaṃ nisīdi.**Then the king bowed to the Buddha, raised his joined palms toward the Saṅgha, and sat down to one side.*";
P_HTM[740]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho rājā māgadho ajātasattu vedehiputto bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**He said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[741]="*“puccheyyāmahaṃ, bhante, bhagavantaṃ kañcideva desaṃ;**“Sir, I’d like to ask you about a certain point, if you’d take the time to answer.”*";
P_HTM[742]="*sace me bhagavā okāsaṃ karoti pañhassa veyyākaraṇāyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[743]="*“Puccha, mahārāja, yadākaṅkhasī”ti.**“Ask what you wish, great king.”*";
P_HTM[744]="*“Yathā nu kho imāni, bhante, puthusippāyatanāni,**“Sir, there are many different professional fields.*";
P_HTM[745]="*seyyathidaṃ—hatthārohā assārohā rathikā dhanuggahā celakā calakā piṇḍadāyakā uggā rājaputtā pakkhandino mahānāgā sūrā cammayodhino dāsikaputtā**These include elephant riders, cavalry, charioteers, archers, bannermen, adjutants, food servers, warrior-chiefs, princes, chargers, great warriors, heroes, leather-clad soldiers, and sons of bondservants.*";
P_HTM[746]="*āḷārikā kappakā nhāpakā sūdā mālakārā rajakā pesakārā naḷakārā kumbhakārā gaṇakā muddikā, yāni vā panaññānipi evaṃgatāni puthusippāyatanāni, te diṭṭheva dhamme sandiṭṭhikaṃ sippaphalaṃ upajīvanti;**They also include bakers, barbers, bathroom attendants, cooks, garland-makers, dyers, weavers, basket-makers, potters, accountants, finger-talliers, or those following any similar professions. All these live off the fruits of their profession which are apparent in the present life.*";
P_HTM[747]="*te tena attānaṃ sukhenti pīṇenti, mātāpitaro sukhenti pīṇenti, puttadāraṃ sukhenti pīṇenti, mittāmacce sukhenti pīṇenti, samaṇabrāhmaṇesu uddhaggikaṃ dakkhiṇaṃ patiṭṭhapenti sovaggikaṃ sukhavipākaṃ saggasaṃvattanikaṃ.**With that they bring happiness and joy to themselves, their parents, their children and partners, and their friends and colleagues. And they establish an uplifting religious donation for ascetics and brahmins that’s conducive to heaven, ripens in happiness, and leads to heaven.*";
P_HTM[748]="*Sakkā nu kho, bhante, evameva diṭṭheva dhamme sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ paññapetun”ti?**Sir, can you point out a fruit of the ascetic life that’s likewise apparent in the present life?”*";
P_HTM[749]="*“Abhijānāsi no tvaṃ, mahārāja, imaṃ pañhaṃ aññe samaṇabrāhmaṇe pucchitā”ti?**“Great king, do you recall having asked this question of other ascetics and brahmins?”*";
P_HTM[750]="*“Abhijānāmahaṃ, bhante, imaṃ pañhaṃ aññe samaṇabrāhmaṇe pucchitā”ti.**“I do, sir.”*";
P_HTM[751]="*“Yathā kathaṃ pana te, mahārāja, byākariṃsu, sace te agaru bhāsassū”ti.**“If you wouldn’t mind, great king, tell me how they answered.”*";
P_HTM[752]="*“Na kho me, bhante, garu, yatthassa bhagavā nisinno, bhagavantarūpo vā”ti.**“It’s no trouble when someone such as the Blessed One is sitting here.”*";
P_HTM[753]="*“Tena hi, mahārāja, bhāsassū”ti.**“Well, speak then, great king.”*";
P_HTM[754]="*3.1. Pūraṇakassapavāda**3.1. The Doctrine of Pūraṇa Kassapa*";
P_HTM[755]="*“Ekamidāhaṃ, bhante, samayaṃ yena pūraṇo kassapo tenupasaṅkamiṃ; upasaṅkamitvā pūraṇena kassapena saddhiṃ sammodiṃ.**“One time, sir, I approached Pūraṇa Kassapa and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[756]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃ. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho ahaṃ, bhante, pūraṇaṃ kassapaṃ etadavocaṃ:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, I sat down to one side, and asked him the same question.*";
P_HTM[757]="*‘yathā nu kho imāni, bho kassapa, puthusippāyatanāni,* **";
P_HTM[758]="*seyyathidaṃ—hatthārohā assārohā rathikā dhanuggahā celakā calakā piṇḍadāyakā uggā rājaputtā pakkhandino mahānāgā sūrā cammayodhino dāsikaputtā āḷārikā kappakā nhāpakā sūdā mālakārā rajakā pesakārā naḷakārā kumbhakārā gaṇakā muddikā, yāni vā panaññānipi evaṅgatāni puthusippāyatanāni, te diṭṭheva dhamme sandiṭṭhikaṃ sippaphalaṃ upajīvanti;* **";
P_HTM[759]="*te tena attānaṃ sukhenti pīṇenti, mātāpitaro sukhenti pīṇenti, puttadāraṃ sukhenti pīṇenti, mittāmacce sukhenti pīṇenti, samaṇabrāhmaṇesu uddhaggikaṃ dakkhiṇaṃ patiṭṭhapenti sovaggikaṃ sukhavipākaṃ saggasaṃvattanikaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[760]="*Sakkā nu kho, bho kassapa, evameva diṭṭheva dhamme sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ paññapetun’ti?* **";
P_HTM[761]="*Evaṃ vutte, bhante, pūraṇo kassapo maṃ etadavoca:**He said to me:*";
P_HTM[762]="*‘karoto kho, mahārāja, kārayato, chindato chedāpayato, pacato pācāpayato socayato, socāpayato, kilamato kilamāpayato, phandato phandāpayato, pāṇamatipātāpayato, adinnaṃ ādiyato, sandhiṃ chindato, nillopaṃ harato, ekāgārikaṃ karoto, paripanthe tiṭṭhato, paradāraṃ gacchato, musā bhaṇato, karoto na karīyati pāpaṃ. Khurapariyantena cepi cakkena yo imissā pathaviyā pāṇe ekaṃ maṃsakhalaṃ ekaṃ maṃsapuñjaṃ kareyya, natthi tatonidānaṃ pāpaṃ, natthi pāpassa āgamo.**‘Great king, the one who acts does nothing wrong when they punish, mutilate, torture, aggrieve, oppress, intimidate, or when they encourage others to do the same. They do nothing wrong when they kill, steal, break into houses, plunder wealth, steal from isolated buildings, commit highway robbery, commit adultery, and lie. If you were to reduce all the living creatures of this earth to one heap and mass of flesh with a razor-edged chakram, no evil comes of that, and no outcome of evil.*";
P_HTM[763]="*Dakkhiṇañcepi gaṅgāya tīraṃ gaccheyya hananto ghātento chindanto chedāpento pacanto pācāpento, natthi tatonidānaṃ pāpaṃ, natthi pāpassa āgamo.**If you were to go along the south bank of the Ganges killing, mutilating, and torturing, and encouraging others to do the same, no evil comes of that, and no outcome of evil.*";
P_HTM[764]="*Uttarañcepi gaṅgāya tīraṃ gaccheyya dadanto dāpento yajanto yajāpento, natthi tatonidānaṃ puññaṃ, natthi puññassa āgamo.**If you were to go along the north bank of the Ganges giving and sacrificing and encouraging others to do the same, no merit comes of that, and no outcome of merit.*";
P_HTM[765]="*Dānena damena saṃyamena saccavajjena natthi puññaṃ, natthi puññassa āgamo’ti.**In giving, self-control, restraint, and truthfulness there is no merit or outcome of merit.’*";
P_HTM[766]="*Itthaṃ kho me, bhante, pūraṇo kassapo sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ puṭṭho samāno akiriyaṃ byākāsi.**And so, when I asked Pūraṇa Kassapa about the fruits of the ascetic life apparent in the present life, he answered with the doctrine of inaction.*";
P_HTM[767]="*Seyyathāpi, bhante, ambaṃ vā puṭṭho labujaṃ byākareyya, labujaṃ vā puṭṭho ambaṃ byākareyya;**It was like someone who, when asked about a mango, answered with a breadfruit, or when asked about a breadfruit, answered with a mango.*";
P_HTM[768]="*evameva kho me, bhante, pūraṇo kassapo sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ puṭṭho samāno akiriyaṃ byākāsi.* **";
P_HTM[769]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhante, etadahosi:**I thought:*";
P_HTM[770]="*‘kathañhi nāma mādiso samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā vijite vasantaṃ apasādetabbaṃ maññeyyā’ti.**‘How could one such as I presume to rebuke an ascetic or brahmin living in my realm?’*";
P_HTM[771]="*So kho ahaṃ, bhante, pūraṇassa kassapassa bhāsitaṃ neva abhinandiṃ nappaṭikkosiṃ.**So I neither approved nor dismissed that statement of Pūraṇa Kassapa.*";
P_HTM[772]="*Anabhinanditvā appaṭikkositvā anattamano, anattamanavācaṃ anicchāretvā, tameva vācaṃ anuggaṇhanto anikkujjanto uṭṭhāyāsanā pakkamiṃ.**I was displeased, but did not express my displeasure. Neither accepting what he said nor contradicting it, I got up from my seat and left.*";
P_HTM[773]="*3.2. Makkhaligosālavāda**3.2. The Doctrine of Makkhali Gosāla*";
P_HTM[774]="*Ekamidāhaṃ, bhante, samayaṃ yena makkhali gosālo tenupasaṅkamiṃ; upasaṅkamitvā makkhalinā gosālena saddhiṃ sammodiṃ.**One time, sir, I approached Makkhali Gosāla and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[775]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃ. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho ahaṃ, bhante, makkhaliṃ gosālaṃ etadavocaṃ:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, I sat down to one side, and asked him the same question.*";
P_HTM[776]="*‘yathā nu kho imāni, bho gosāla, puthusippāyatanāni … pe …* **";
P_HTM[777]="*sakkā nu kho, bho gosāla, evameva diṭṭheva dhamme sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ paññapetun’ti?* **";
P_HTM[778]="*Evaṃ vutte, bhante, makkhali gosālo maṃ etadavoca:**He said:*";
P_HTM[779]="*‘natthi, mahārāja, hetu natthi paccayo sattānaṃ saṃkilesāya, ahetū apaccayā sattā saṅkilissanti.**‘Great king, there is no cause or condition for the corruption of sentient beings. Sentient beings are corrupted without cause or condition.*";
P_HTM[780]="*Natthi hetu, natthi paccayo sattānaṃ visuddhiyā,**There’s no cause or condition for the purification of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[781]="*ahetū apaccayā sattā visujjhanti.**Sentient beings are purified without cause or condition.*";
P_HTM[782]="*Natthi attakāre, natthi parakāre, natthi purisakāre, natthi balaṃ, natthi vīriyaṃ, natthi purisathāmo, natthi purisaparakkamo.**One does not act of one’s own volition, one does not act of another’s volition, one does not act from a person’s volition. There is no power, no energy, no manly strength or vigor.*";
P_HTM[783]="*Sabbe sattā sabbe pāṇā sabbe bhūtā sabbe jīvā avasā abalā avīriyā niyatisaṅgatibhāvapariṇatā chasvevābhijātīsu sukhadukkhaṃ paṭisaṃvedenti.**All sentient beings, all living creatures, all beings, all souls lack control, power, and energy. Molded by destiny, circumstance, and nature, they experience pleasure and pain in the six classes of rebirth.*";
P_HTM[784]="*Cuddasa kho panimāni yonipamukhasatasahassāni saṭṭhi ca satāni cha ca satāni pañca ca kammuno satāni pañca ca kammāni tīṇi ca kammāni kamme ca aḍḍhakamme ca dvaṭṭhipaṭipadā dvaṭṭhantarakappā chaḷābhijātiyo aṭṭha purisabhūmiyo ekūnapaññāsa ājīvakasate ekūnapaññāsa paribbājakasate ekūnapaññāsa nāgāvāsasate vīse indriyasate tiṃse nirayasate chattiṃsa rajodhātuyo satta saññīgabbhā satta asaññīgabbhā satta nigaṇṭhigabbhā satta devā satta mānusā satta pisācā satta sarā satta pavuṭā satta pavuṭasatāni satta papātā satta papātasatāni satta supinā satta supinasatāni cullāsīti mahākappino satasahassāni, yāni bāle ca paṇḍite ca sandhāvitvā saṃsaritvā dukkhassantaṃ karissanti.**There are 1.4 million main wombs, and 6,000, and 600. There are 500 deeds, and five, and three. There are deeds and half-deeds. There are 62 paths, 62 sub-eons, six classes of rebirth, and eight stages in a person’s life. There are 4,900 Ājīvaka ascetics, 4,900 wanderers, and 4,900 naked ascetics. There are 2,000 faculties, 3,000 hells, and 36 realms of dust. There are seven percipient embryos, seven non-percipient embryos, and seven embryos without attachments. There are seven gods, seven humans, and seven goblins. There are seven lakes, seven winds, 700 winds, seven cliffs, and 700 cliffs. There are seven dreams and 700 dreams. There are 8.4 million great eons through which the foolish and the astute transmigrate before making an end of suffering.*";
P_HTM[785]="*Tattha natthi “imināhaṃ sīlena vā vatena vā tapena vā brahmacariyena vā aparipakkaṃ vā kammaṃ paripācessāmi, paripakkaṃ vā kammaṃ phussa phussa byantiṃ karissāmī”ti hevaṃ natthi.**And here there is no such thing as this: “By this precept or observance or mortification or spiritual life I shall force unripened deeds to bear their fruit, or eliminate old deeds by experiencing their results little by little,” for that cannot be.*";
P_HTM[786]="*Doṇamite sukhadukkhe pariyantakate saṃsāre, natthi hāyanavaḍḍhane, natthi ukkaṃsāvakaṃse.**Pleasure and pain are allotted. Transmigration lasts only for a limited period, so there’s no increase or decrease, no getting better or worse.*";
P_HTM[787]="*Seyyathāpi nāma suttaguḷe khitte nibbeṭhiyamānameva paleti;**It’s like how, when you toss a ball of string, it rolls away unraveling.*";
P_HTM[788]="*evameva bāle ca paṇḍite ca sandhāvitvā saṃsaritvā dukkhassantaṃ karissantī’ti.**In the same way, after transmigrating the foolish and the astute will make an end of suffering.’*";
P_HTM[789]="*Itthaṃ kho me, bhante, makkhali gosālo sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ puṭṭho samāno saṃsārasuddhiṃ byākāsi.**And so, when I asked Makkhali Gosāla about the fruits of the ascetic life apparent in the present life, he answered with the doctrine of purification through transmigration.*";
P_HTM[790]="*Seyyathāpi, bhante, ambaṃ vā puṭṭho labujaṃ byākareyya, labujaṃ vā puṭṭho ambaṃ byākareyya;**It was like someone who, when asked about a mango, answered with a breadfruit, or when asked about a breadfruit, answered with a mango.*";
P_HTM[791]="*evameva kho me, bhante, makkhali gosālo sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ puṭṭho samāno saṃsārasuddhiṃ byākāsi.* **";
P_HTM[792]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhante, etadahosi:**I thought:*";
P_HTM[793]="*‘kathañhi nāma mādiso samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā vijite vasantaṃ apasādetabbaṃ maññeyyā’ti.**‘How could one such as I presume to rebuke an ascetic or brahmin living in my realm?’*";
P_HTM[794]="*So kho ahaṃ, bhante, makkhalissa gosālassa bhāsitaṃ neva abhinandiṃ nappaṭikkosiṃ.**So I neither approved nor dismissed that statement of Makkhali Gosāla.*";
P_HTM[795]="*Anabhinanditvā appaṭikkositvā anattamano, anattamanavācaṃ anicchāretvā, tameva vācaṃ anuggaṇhanto anikkujjanto uṭṭhāyāsanā pakkamiṃ.**I was displeased, but did not express my displeasure. Neither accepting what he said nor contradicting it, I got up from my seat and left.*";
P_HTM[796]="*3.3. Ajitakesakambalavāda**3.3. The Doctrine of Ajita Kesakambala*";
P_HTM[797]="*Ekamidāhaṃ, bhante, samayaṃ yena ajito kesakambalo tenupasaṅkamiṃ; upasaṅkamitvā ajitena kesakambalena saddhiṃ sammodiṃ.**One time, sir, I approached Ajita Kesakambala and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[798]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃ. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho ahaṃ, bhante, ajitaṃ kesakambalaṃ etadavocaṃ:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, I sat down to one side, and asked him the same question.*";
P_HTM[799]="*‘yathā nu kho imāni, bho ajita, puthusippāyatanāni … pe …* **";
P_HTM[800]="*sakkā nu kho, bho ajita, evameva diṭṭheva dhamme sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ paññapetun’ti?* **";
P_HTM[801]="*Evaṃ vutte, bhante, ajito kesakambalo maṃ etadavoca:**He said:*";
P_HTM[802]="*‘natthi, mahārāja, dinnaṃ, natthi yiṭṭhaṃ, natthi hutaṃ, natthi sukatadukkaṭānaṃ kammānaṃ phalaṃ vipāko, natthi ayaṃ loko, natthi paro loko, natthi mātā, natthi pitā, natthi sattā opapātikā, natthi loke samaṇabrāhmaṇā sammaggatā sammāpaṭipannā, ye imañca lokaṃ parañca lokaṃ sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedenti.**‘Great king, there is no meaning in giving, sacrifice, or offerings. There’s no fruit or result of good and bad deeds. There’s no afterlife. There’s no obligation to mother and father. No beings are reborn spontaneously. And there’s no ascetic or brahmin who is well attained and practiced, and who describes the afterlife after realizing it with their own insight.*";
P_HTM[803]="*Cātumahābhūtiko ayaṃ puriso, yadā kālaṃ karoti, pathavī pathavikāyaṃ anupeti anupagacchati, āpo āpokāyaṃ anupeti anupagacchati, tejo tejokāyaṃ anupeti anupagacchati, vāyo vāyokāyaṃ anupeti anupagacchati, ākāsaṃ indriyāni saṅkamanti.**This person is made up of the four primary elements. When they die, the earth in their body merges and coalesces with the main mass of earth. The water in their body merges and coalesces with the main mass of water. The fire in their body merges and coalesces with the main mass of fire. The air in their body merges and coalesces with the main mass of air. The faculties are transferred to space.*";
P_HTM[804]="*Āsandipañcamā purisā mataṃ ādāya gacchanti.**Four men with a bier carry away the corpse.*";
P_HTM[805]="*Yāvāḷāhanā padāni paññāyanti.**Their footprints show the way to the cemetery.*";
P_HTM[806]="*Kāpotakāni aṭṭhīni bhavanti, bhassantā āhutiyo.**The bones become bleached. Offerings dedicated to the gods end in ashes.*";
P_HTM[807]="*Dattupaññattaṃ yadidaṃ dānaṃ.**Giving is a doctrine of morons.*";
P_HTM[808]="*Tesaṃ tucchaṃ musā vilāpo ye keci atthikavādaṃ vadanti.**When anyone affirms a positive teaching it’s just hollow, false nonsense.*";
P_HTM[809]="*Bāle ca paṇḍite ca kāyassa bhedā ucchijjanti vinassanti, na honti paraṃ maraṇā’ti.**Both the foolish and the astute are annihilated and destroyed when their body breaks up, and don’t exist after death.’*";
P_HTM[810]="*Itthaṃ kho me, bhante, ajito kesakambalo sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ puṭṭho samāno ucchedaṃ byākāsi.**And so, when I asked Ajita Kesakambala about the fruits of the ascetic life apparent in the present life, he answered with the doctrine of annihilationism.*";
P_HTM[811]="*Seyyathāpi, bhante, ambaṃ vā puṭṭho labujaṃ byākareyya, labujaṃ vā puṭṭho ambaṃ byākareyya;**It was like someone who, when asked about a mango, answered with a breadfruit, or when asked about a breadfruit, answered with a mango.*";
P_HTM[812]="*evameva kho me, bhante, ajito kesakambalo sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ puṭṭho samāno ucchedaṃ byākāsi.* **";
P_HTM[813]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhante, etadahosi:**I thought:*";
P_HTM[814]="*‘kathañhi nāma mādiso samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā vijite vasantaṃ apasādetabbaṃ maññeyyā’ti.**‘How could one such as I presume to rebuke an ascetic or brahmin living in my realm?’*";
P_HTM[815]="*So kho ahaṃ, bhante, ajitassa kesakambalassa bhāsitaṃ neva abhinandiṃ nappaṭikkosiṃ.**So I neither approved nor dismissed that statement of Ajita Kesakambala.*";
P_HTM[816]="*Anabhinanditvā appaṭikkositvā anattamano anattamanavācaṃ anicchāretvā tameva vācaṃ anuggaṇhanto anikkujjanto uṭṭhāyāsanā pakkamiṃ.**I was displeased, but did not express my displeasure. Neither accepting what he said nor contradicting it, I got up from my seat and left.*";
P_HTM[817]="*3.4. Pakudhakaccāyanavāda**3.4. The Doctrine of Pakudha Kaccāyana*";
P_HTM[818]="*Ekamidāhaṃ, bhante, samayaṃ yena pakudho kaccāyano tenupasaṅkamiṃ; upasaṅkamitvā pakudhena kaccāyanena saddhiṃ sammodiṃ.**One time, sir, I approached Pakudha Kaccāyana and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[819]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃ. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho ahaṃ, bhante, pakudhaṃ kaccāyanaṃ etadavocaṃ:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, I sat down to one side, and asked him the same question.*";
P_HTM[820]="*‘yathā nu kho imāni, bho kaccāyana, puthusippāyatanāni … pe …* **";
P_HTM[821]="*sakkā nu kho, bho kaccāyana, evameva diṭṭheva dhamme sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ paññapetun’ti?* **";
P_HTM[822]="*Evaṃ vutte, bhante, pakudho kaccāyano maṃ etadavoca:**He said:*";
P_HTM[823]="*‘sattime, mahārāja, kāyā akaṭā akaṭavidhā animmitā animmātā vañjhā kūṭaṭṭhā esikaṭṭhāyiṭṭhitā.**‘Great king, these seven substances are not made, not derived, not created, without a creator, barren, steady as a mountain peak, standing firm like a pillar.*";
P_HTM[824]="*Te na iñjanti, na vipariṇamanti, na aññamaññaṃ byābādhenti, nālaṃ aññamaññassa sukhāya vā dukkhāya vā sukhadukkhāya vā.**They don’t move or deteriorate or obstruct each other. They’re unable to cause pleasure, pain, or neutral feeling to each other.*";
P_HTM[825]="*Katame satta?**What seven?*";
P_HTM[826]="*Pathavikāyo, āpokāyo, tejokāyo, vāyokāyo, sukhe, dukkhe, jīve sattame—**The substances of earth, water, fire, air; pleasure, pain, and the soul is the seventh.*";
P_HTM[827]="*ime satta kāyā akaṭā akaṭavidhā animmitā animmātā vañjhā kūṭaṭṭhā esikaṭṭhāyiṭṭhitā.**These seven substances are not made, not derived, not created, without a creator, barren, steady as a mountain peak, standing firm like a pillar.*";
P_HTM[828]="*Te na iñjanti, na vipariṇamanti, na aññamaññaṃ byābādhenti, nālaṃ aññamaññassa sukhāya vā dukkhāya vā sukhadukkhāya vā.**They don’t move or deteriorate or obstruct each other. They’re unable to cause pleasure, pain, or neutral feeling to each other.*";
P_HTM[829]="*Tattha natthi hantā vā ghātetā vā, sotā vā sāvetā vā, viññātā vā viññāpetā vā.**And here there is no-one who kills or who makes others kill; no-one who learns or who educates others; no-one who understands or who helps others understand.*";
P_HTM[830]="*Yopi tiṇhena satthena sīsaṃ chindati, na koci kiñci jīvitā voropeti;**If you chop off someone’s head with a sharp sword, you don’t take anyone’s life.*";
P_HTM[831]="*sattannaṃ tveva kāyānamantarena satthaṃ vivaramanupatatī’ti.**The sword simply passes through the gap between the seven substances.’*";
P_HTM[832]="*Itthaṃ kho me, bhante, pakudho kaccāyano sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ puṭṭho samāno aññena aññaṃ byākāsi.**And so, when I asked Pakudha Kaccāyana about the fruits of the ascetic life apparent in the present life, he answered with something else entirely.*";
P_HTM[833]="*Seyyathāpi, bhante, ambaṃ vā puṭṭho labujaṃ byākareyya, labujaṃ vā puṭṭho ambaṃ byākareyya;**It was like someone who, when asked about a mango, answered with a breadfruit, or when asked about a breadfruit, answered with a mango.*";
P_HTM[834]="*evameva kho me, bhante, pakudho kaccāyano sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ puṭṭho samāno aññena aññaṃ byākāsi.* **";
P_HTM[835]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhante, etadahosi:**I thought:*";
P_HTM[836]="*‘kathañhi nāma mādiso samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā vijite vasantaṃ apasādetabbaṃ maññeyyā’ti.**‘How could one such as I presume to rebuke an ascetic or brahmin living in my realm?’*";
P_HTM[837]="*So kho ahaṃ, bhante, pakudhassa kaccāyanassa bhāsitaṃ neva abhinandiṃ nappaṭikkosiṃ,**So I neither approved nor dismissed that statement of Pakudha Kaccāyana.*";
P_HTM[838]="*anabhinanditvā appaṭikkositvā anattamano, anattamanavācaṃ anicchāretvā tameva vācaṃ anuggaṇhanto anikkujjanto uṭṭhāyāsanā pakkamiṃ.**I was displeased, but did not express my displeasure. Neither accepting what he said nor contradicting it, I got up from my seat and left.*";
P_HTM[839]="*3.5. Nigaṇṭhanāṭaputtavāda**3.5. The Doctrine of Nigaṇṭha Nātaputta*";
P_HTM[840]="*Ekamidāhaṃ, bhante, samayaṃ yena nigaṇṭho nāṭaputto tenupasaṅkamiṃ; upasaṅkamitvā nigaṇṭhena nāṭaputtena saddhiṃ sammodiṃ.**One time, sir, I approached Nigaṇṭha Nātaputta and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[841]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃ. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho ahaṃ, bhante, nigaṇṭhaṃ nāṭaputtaṃ etadavocaṃ:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, I sat down to one side, and asked him the same question.*";
P_HTM[842]="*‘yathā nu kho imāni, bho aggivessana, puthusippāyatanāni … pe …* **";
P_HTM[843]="*sakkā nu kho, bho aggivessana, evameva diṭṭheva dhamme sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ paññapetun’ti?* **";
P_HTM[844]="*Evaṃ vutte, bhante, nigaṇṭho nāṭaputto maṃ etadavoca:**He said:*";
P_HTM[845]="*‘idha, mahārāja, nigaṇṭho cātuyāmasaṃvarasaṃvuto hoti.**‘Great king, consider a Jain ascetic who is restrained in the fourfold restraint.*";
P_HTM[846]="*Kathañca, mahārāja, nigaṇṭho cātuyāmasaṃvarasaṃvuto hoti?**And how is a Jain ascetic restrained in the fourfold restraint?*";
P_HTM[847]="*Idha, mahārāja, nigaṇṭho sabbavārivārito ca hoti, sabbavāriyutto ca, sabbavāridhuto ca, sabbavāriphuṭo ca.**It’s when a Jain ascetic is obstructed by all water, devoted to all water, shaking off all water, pervaded by all water.*";
P_HTM[848]="*Evaṃ kho, mahārāja, nigaṇṭho cātuyāmasaṃvarasaṃvuto hoti.**That’s how a Jain ascetic is restrained in the fourfold restraint.*";
P_HTM[849]="*Yato kho, mahārāja, nigaṇṭho evaṃ cātuyāmasaṃvarasaṃvuto hoti;**When a Jain ascetic is restrained in the fourfold restraint,*";
P_HTM[850]="*ayaṃ vuccati, mahārāja, nigaṇṭho gatatto ca yatatto ca ṭhitatto cā’ti.**they’re called a knotless one who is self-realized, self-controlled, and steadfast.’*";
P_HTM[851]="*Itthaṃ kho me, bhante, nigaṇṭho nāṭaputto sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ puṭṭho samāno cātuyāmasaṃvaraṃ byākāsi.**And so, when I asked Nigaṇṭha Nāṭaputta about the fruits of the ascetic life apparent in the present life, he answered with the fourfold restraint.*";
P_HTM[852]="*Seyyathāpi, bhante, ambaṃ vā puṭṭho labujaṃ byākareyya, labujaṃ vā puṭṭho ambaṃ byākareyya;**It was like someone who, when asked about a mango, answered with a breadfruit, or when asked about a breadfruit, answered with a mango.*";
P_HTM[853]="*evameva kho me, bhante, nigaṇṭho nāṭaputto sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ puṭṭho samāno cātuyāmasaṃvaraṃ byākāsi.* **";
P_HTM[854]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhante, etadahosi:**I thought:*";
P_HTM[855]="*‘kathañhi nāma mādiso samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā vijite vasantaṃ apasādetabbaṃ maññeyyā’ti.**‘How could one such as I presume to rebuke an ascetic or brahmin living in my realm?’*";
P_HTM[856]="*So kho ahaṃ, bhante, nigaṇṭhassa nāṭaputtassa bhāsitaṃ neva abhinandiṃ nappaṭikkosiṃ.**So I neither approved nor dismissed that statement of Nigaṇṭha Nāṭaputta.*";
P_HTM[857]="*Anabhinanditvā appaṭikkositvā anattamano anattamanavācaṃ anicchāretvā tameva vācaṃ anuggaṇhanto anikkujjanto uṭṭhāyāsanā pakkamiṃ.**I was displeased, but did not express my displeasure. Neither accepting what he said nor contradicting it, I got up from my seat and left.*";
P_HTM[858]="*3.6. Sañcayabelaṭṭhaputtavāda**3.6. The Doctrine of Sañjaya Belaṭṭhiputta*";
P_HTM[859]="*Ekamidāhaṃ, bhante, samayaṃ yena sañcayo belaṭṭhaputto tenupasaṅkamiṃ; upasaṅkamitvā sañcayena belaṭṭhaputtena saddhiṃ sammodiṃ.**One time, sir, I approached Sañjaya Belaṭṭhiputta and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[860]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃ. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho ahaṃ, bhante, sañcayaṃ belaṭṭhaputtaṃ etadavocaṃ:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, I sat down to one side, and asked him the same question.*";
P_HTM[861]="*‘yathā nu kho imāni, bho sañcaya, puthusippāyatanāni … pe …* **";
P_HTM[862]="*sakkā nu kho, bho sañcaya, evameva diṭṭheva dhamme sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ paññapetun’ti?* **";
P_HTM[863]="*Evaṃ vutte, bhante, sañcayo belaṭṭhaputto maṃ etadavoca:**He said:*";
P_HTM[864]="*‘atthi paro lokoti iti ce maṃ pucchasi, atthi paro lokoti iti ce me assa, atthi paro lokoti iti te naṃ byākareyyaṃ.**‘Suppose you were to ask me whether there is another world. If I believed there was, I would say so.*";
P_HTM[865]="*Evantipi me no, tathātipi me no, aññathātipi me no, notipi me no, no notipi me no.**But I don’t say it’s like this. I don’t say it’s like that. I don’t say it’s otherwise. I don’t say it’s not so. And I don’t deny it’s not so.*";
P_HTM[866]="*Natthi paro loko … pe …**Suppose you were to ask me whether there is no other world …*";
P_HTM[867]="*atthi ca natthi ca paro loko … pe …**whether there both is and is not another world …*";
P_HTM[868]="*nevatthi na natthi paro loko … pe …**whether there neither is nor is not another world …*";
P_HTM[869]="*atthi sattā opapātikā … pe …**whether there are beings who are reborn spontaneously …*";
P_HTM[870]="*natthi sattā opapātikā … pe …**whether there are no beings who are reborn spontaneously …*";
P_HTM[871]="*atthi ca natthi ca sattā opapātikā … pe …**whether there both are and are not beings who are reborn spontaneously …*";
P_HTM[872]="*nevatthi na natthi sattā opapātikā … pe …**whether there neither are nor are not beings who are reborn spontaneously …*";
P_HTM[873]="*atthi sukatadukkaṭānaṃ kammānaṃ phalaṃ vipāko … pe …**whether there is fruit and result of good and bad deeds …*";
P_HTM[874]="*natthi sukatadukkaṭānaṃ kammānaṃ phalaṃ vipāko … pe …**whether there is no fruit and result of good and bad deeds …*";
P_HTM[875]="*atthi ca natthi ca sukatadukkaṭānaṃ kammānaṃ phalaṃ vipāko … pe …**whether there both is and is not fruit and result of good and bad deeds …*";
P_HTM[876]="*nevatthi na natthi sukatadukkaṭānaṃ kammānaṃ phalaṃ vipāko … pe …**whether there neither is nor is not fruit and result of good and bad deeds …*";
P_HTM[877]="*hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā … pe …**whether a Realized One exists after death …*";
P_HTM[878]="*na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā … pe …**whether a Realized One doesn’t exist after death …*";
P_HTM[879]="*hoti ca na ca hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā … pe …**whether a Realized One both exists and doesn’t exist after death …*";
P_HTM[880]="*neva hoti na na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇāti iti ce maṃ pucchasi, neva hoti na na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇāti iti ce me assa, neva hoti na na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇāti iti te naṃ byākareyyaṃ.**whether a Realized One neither exists nor doesn’t exist after death. If I believed there was, I would say so.*";
P_HTM[881]="*Evantipi me no, tathātipi me no, aññathātipi me no, notipi me no, no notipi me no’ti.**But I don’t say it’s like this. I don’t say it’s like that. I don’t say it’s otherwise. I don’t say it’s not so. And I don’t deny it’s not so.’*";
P_HTM[882]="*Itthaṃ kho me, bhante, sañcayo belaṭṭhaputto sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ puṭṭho samāno vikkhepaṃ byākāsi.**And so, when I asked Sañjaya Belaṭṭhiputta about the fruits of the ascetic life apparent in the present life, he answered with evasiveness.*";
P_HTM[883]="*Seyyathāpi, bhante, ambaṃ vā puṭṭho labujaṃ byākareyya, labujaṃ vā puṭṭho ambaṃ byākareyya;**It was like someone who, when asked about a mango, answered with a breadfruit, or when asked about a breadfruit, answered with a mango.*";
P_HTM[884]="*evameva kho me, bhante, sañcayo belaṭṭhaputto sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ puṭṭho samāno vikkhepaṃ byākāsi.* **";
P_HTM[885]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhante, etadahosi:**I thought:*";
P_HTM[886]="*‘ayañca imesaṃ samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ sabbabālo sabbamūḷho.**‘This is the most foolish and stupid of all these ascetics and brahmins!*";
P_HTM[887]="*Kathañhi nāma sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ puṭṭho samāno vikkhepaṃ byākarissatī’ti.**How on earth can he answer with evasiveness when asked about the fruits of the ascetic life apparent in the present life?’*";
P_HTM[888]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhante, etadahosi:**I thought:*";
P_HTM[889]="*‘kathañhi nāma mādiso samaṇaṃ vā brāhmaṇaṃ vā vijite vasantaṃ apasādetabbaṃ maññeyyā’ti.**‘How could one such as I presume to rebuke an ascetic or brahmin living in my realm?’*";
P_HTM[890]="*So kho ahaṃ, bhante, sañcayassa belaṭṭhaputtassa bhāsitaṃ neva abhinandiṃ nappaṭikkosiṃ.**So I neither approved nor dismissed that statement of Sañjaya Belaṭṭhiputta.*";
P_HTM[891]="*Anabhinanditvā appaṭikkositvā anattamano anattamanavācaṃ anicchāretvā tameva vācaṃ anuggaṇhanto anikkujjanto uṭṭhāyāsanā pakkamiṃ.**I was displeased, but did not express my displeasure. Neither accepting what he said nor contradicting it, I got up from my seat and left.*";
P_HTM[892]="*4. Sāmaññaphala**4. The Fruits of the Ascetic Life*";
P_HTM[893]="*4.1. Paṭhamasandiṭṭhikasāmaññaphala**4.1. The First Fruit of the Ascetic Life*";
P_HTM[894]="*Sohaṃ, bhante, bhagavantampi pucchāmi:**And so I ask the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[895]="*‘yathā nu kho imāni, bhante, puthusippāyatanāni**Sir, there are many different professional fields.*";
P_HTM[896]="*seyyathidaṃ—hatthārohā assārohā rathikā dhanuggahā celakā calakā piṇḍadāyakā uggā rājaputtā pakkhandino mahānāgā sūrā cammayodhino dāsikaputtā**These include elephant riders, cavalry, charioteers, archers, bannermen, adjutants, food servers, warrior-chiefs, princes, chargers, great warriors, heroes, leather-clad soldiers, and sons of bondservants.*";
P_HTM[897]="*āḷārikā kappakā nhāpakā sūdā mālakārā rajakā pesakārā naḷakārā kumbhakārā gaṇakā muddikā, yāni vā panaññānipi evaṅgatāni puthusippāyatanāni, te diṭṭheva dhamme sandiṭṭhikaṃ sippaphalaṃ upajīvanti,**They also include bakers, barbers, bathroom attendants, cooks, garland-makers, dyers, weavers, basket-makers, potters, accountants, finger-talliers, or those following any similar professions. All these live off the fruits of their profession which are apparent in the present life.*";
P_HTM[898]="*te tena attānaṃ sukhenti pīṇenti, mātāpitaro sukhenti pīṇenti, puttadāraṃ sukhenti pīṇenti, mittāmacce sukhenti pīṇenti, samaṇabrāhmaṇesu uddhaggikaṃ dakkhiṇaṃ patiṭṭhapenti sovaggikaṃ sukhavipākaṃ saggasaṃvattanikaṃ.**With that they bring happiness and joy to themselves, their parents, their children and partners, and their friends and colleagues. And they establish an uplifting religious donation for ascetics and brahmins that’s conducive to heaven, ripens in happiness, and leads to heaven.*";
P_HTM[899]="*Sakkā nu kho, bhante, evameva diṭṭheva dhamme sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ paññapetun’”ti?**Sir, can you point out a fruit of the ascetic life that’s likewise apparent in the present life?”*";
P_HTM[900]="*“Sakkā, mahārāja.**“I can, great king.*";
P_HTM[901]="*Tena hi, mahārāja, taññevettha paṭipucchissāmi. Yathā te khameyya, tathā naṃ byākareyyāsi.**Well then, I’ll ask you about this in return, and you can answer as you like.*";
P_HTM[902]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, mahārāja,**What do you think, great king?*";
P_HTM[903]="*idha te assa puriso dāso kammakāro pubbuṭṭhāyī pacchānipātī kiṃkārapaṭissāvī manāpacārī piyavādī mukhullokako.**Suppose you had a person who was a bondservant, a worker. They get up before you and go to bed after you, and are obliging, behaving nicely and speaking politely, and gazing up at your face.*";
P_HTM[904]="*Tassa evamassa:**They’d think:*";
P_HTM[905]="*‘acchariyaṃ, vata bho, abbhutaṃ, vata bho, puññānaṃ gati, puññānaṃ vipāko.**‘The outcome and result of good deeds is just so incredible, so amazing!*";
P_HTM[906]="*Ayañhi rājā māgadho ajātasattu vedehiputto manusso; ahampi manusso.**For this King Ajātasattu is a human being, and so am I.*";
P_HTM[907]="*Ayañhi rājā māgadho ajātasattu vedehiputto pañcahi kāmaguṇehi samappito samaṅgībhūto paricāreti, devo maññe.**Yet he amuses himself, supplied and provided with the five kinds of sensual stimulation as if he were a god.*";
P_HTM[908]="*Ahaṃ panamhissa dāso kammakāro pubbuṭṭhāyī pacchānipātī kiṃkārapaṭissāvī manāpacārī piyavādī mukhullokako.**Whereas I’m his bondservant, his worker. I get up before him and go to bed after him, and am obliging, behaving nicely and speaking politely, and gazing up at his face.*";
P_HTM[909]="*So vatassāhaṃ puññāni kareyyaṃ.**I should do good deeds.*";
P_HTM[910]="*Yannūnāhaṃ kesamassuṃ ohāretvā kāsāyāni vatthāni acchādetvā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajeyyan’ti.**Why don’t I shave off my hair and beard, dress in ocher robes, and go forth from the lay life to homelessness?’*";
P_HTM[911]="*So aparena samayena kesamassuṃ ohāretvā kāsāyāni vatthāni acchādetvā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajeyya.**After some time, that is what they do.*";
P_HTM[912]="*So evaṃ pabbajito samāno kāyena saṃvuto vihareyya, vācāya saṃvuto vihareyya, manasā saṃvuto vihareyya, ghāsacchādanaparamatāya santuṭṭho, abhirato paviveke.**Having gone forth they’d live restrained in body, speech, and mind, living content with nothing more than food and clothes, delighting in seclusion.*";
P_HTM[913]="*Tañce te purisā evamāroceyyuṃ:**And suppose your men were to report all this to you.*";
P_HTM[914]="*‘yagghe, deva, jāneyyāsi, yo te so puriso dāso kammakāro pubbuṭṭhāyī pacchānipātī kiṃkārapaṭissāvī manāpacārī piyavādī mukhullokako;* **";
P_HTM[915]="*so, deva, kesamassuṃ ohāretvā kāsāyāni vatthāni acchādetvā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajito.* **";
P_HTM[916]="*So evaṃ pabbajito samāno kāyena saṃvuto viharati, vācāya saṃvuto viharati, manasā saṃvuto viharati, ghāsacchādanaparamatāya santuṭṭho, abhirato paviveke’ti.* **";
P_HTM[917]="*Api nu tvaṃ evaṃ vadeyyāsi:**Would you say to them:*";
P_HTM[918]="*‘etu me, bho, so puriso, punadeva hotu dāso kammakāro pubbuṭṭhāyī pacchānipātī kiṃkārapaṭissāvī manāpacārī piyavādī mukhullokako’”ti?**‘Bring that person to me! Let them once more be my bondservant, my worker’?”*";
P_HTM[919]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante.**“No, sir.*";
P_HTM[920]="*Atha kho naṃ mayameva abhivādeyyāmapi, paccuṭṭheyyāmapi, āsanenapi nimanteyyāma, abhinimanteyyāmapi naṃ cīvarapiṇḍapātasenāsanagilānappaccayabhesajjaparikkhārehi, dhammikampissa rakkhāvaraṇaguttiṃ saṃvidaheyyāmā”ti.**Rather, I would bow to them, rise in their presence, and offer them a seat. I’d invite them to accept robes, alms-food, lodgings, and medicines and supplies for the sick. And I’d arrange for their lawful guarding and protection.”*";
P_HTM[921]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, mahārāja,**“What do you think, great king?*";
P_HTM[922]="*yadi evaṃ sante hoti vā sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ no vā”ti?**If this is so, is there a fruit of the ascetic life apparent in the present life or not?”*";
P_HTM[923]="*“Addhā kho, bhante, evaṃ sante hoti sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalan”ti.**“Clearly, sir, there is.”*";
P_HTM[924]="*“Idaṃ kho te, mahārāja, mayā paṭhamaṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ paññattan”ti.**“This is the first fruit of the ascetic life that’s apparent in the present life, which I point out to you.”*";
P_HTM[925]="*4.2. Dutiyasandiṭṭhikasāmaññaphala**4.2. The Second Fruit of the Ascetic Life*";
P_HTM[926]="*“Sakkā pana, bhante, aññampi evameva diṭṭheva dhamme sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ paññapetun”ti?**“But sir, can you point out another fruit of the ascetic life that’s likewise apparent in the present life?”*";
P_HTM[927]="*“Sakkā, mahārāja.**“I can, great king.*";
P_HTM[928]="*Tena hi, mahārāja, taññevettha paṭipucchissāmi. Yathā te khameyya, tathā naṃ byākareyyāsi.**Well then, I’ll ask you about this in return, and you can answer as you like.*";
P_HTM[929]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, mahārāja,**What do you think, great king?*";
P_HTM[930]="*idha te assa puriso kassako gahapatiko karakārako rāsivaḍḍhako.**Suppose you had a person who was a farmer, a householder, a hard worker, someone who builds up their capital.*";
P_HTM[931]="*Tassa evamassa:**They’d think:*";
P_HTM[932]="*‘acchariyaṃ vata bho, abbhutaṃ vata bho, puññānaṃ gati, puññānaṃ vipāko.**‘The outcome and result of good deeds is just so incredible, so amazing!*";
P_HTM[933]="*Ayañhi rājā māgadho ajātasattu vedehiputto manusso, ahampi manusso.**For this King Ajātasattu is a human being, and so am I.*";
P_HTM[934]="*Ayañhi rājā māgadho ajātasattu vedehiputto pañcahi kāmaguṇehi samappito samaṅgībhūto paricāreti, devo maññe.**Yet he amuses himself, supplied and provided with the five kinds of sensual stimulation as if he were a god.*";
P_HTM[935]="*Ahaṃ panamhissa kassako gahapatiko karakārako rāsivaḍḍhako.**Whereas I’m a farmer, a householder, a hard worker, someone who builds up their capital.*";
P_HTM[936]="*So vatassāhaṃ puññāni kareyyaṃ.**I should do good deeds.*";
P_HTM[937]="*Yannūnāhaṃ kesamassuṃ ohāretvā kāsāyāni vatthāni acchādetvā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajeyyan’ti.**Why don’t I shave off my hair and beard, dress in ocher robes, and go forth from the lay life to homelessness?’*";
P_HTM[938]="*So aparena samayena appaṃ vā bhogakkhandhaṃ pahāya mahantaṃ vā bhogakkhandhaṃ pahāya, appaṃ vā ñātiparivaṭṭaṃ pahāya mahantaṃ vā ñātiparivaṭṭaṃ pahāya kesamassuṃ ohāretvā kāsāyāni vatthāni acchādetvā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajeyya.**After some time they give up a large or small fortune, and a large or small family circle. They’d shave off hair and beard, dress in ocher robes, and go forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[939]="*So evaṃ pabbajito samāno kāyena saṃvuto vihareyya, vācāya saṃvuto vihareyya, manasā saṃvuto vihareyya, ghāsacchādanaparamatāya santuṭṭho, abhirato paviveke.**Having gone forth they’d live restrained in body, speech, and mind, living content with nothing more than food and clothes, delighting in seclusion.*";
P_HTM[940]="*Tañce te purisā evamāroceyyuṃ:**And suppose your men were to report all this to you.*";
P_HTM[941]="*‘yagghe, deva, jāneyyāsi, yo te so puriso kassako gahapatiko karakārako rāsivaḍḍhako;* **";
P_HTM[942]="*so deva kesamassuṃ ohāretvā kāsāyāni vatthāni acchādetvā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajito.* **";
P_HTM[943]="*So evaṃ pabbajito samāno kāyena saṃvuto viharati, vācāya saṃvuto viharati, manasā saṃvuto viharati, ghāsacchādanaparamatāya santuṭṭho, abhirato paviveke’ti.* **";
P_HTM[944]="*Api nu tvaṃ evaṃ vadeyyāsi:**Would you say to them:*";
P_HTM[945]="*‘etu me, bho, so puriso, punadeva hotu kassako gahapatiko karakārako rāsivaḍḍhako’”ti?**‘Bring that person to me! Let them once more be a farmer, a householder, a hard worker, someone who builds up their capital’?”*";
P_HTM[946]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante.**“No, sir.*";
P_HTM[947]="*Atha kho naṃ mayameva abhivādeyyāmapi, paccuṭṭheyyāmapi, āsanenapi nimanteyyāma, abhinimanteyyāmapi naṃ cīvarapiṇḍapātasenāsanagilānappaccayabhesajjaparikkhārehi, dhammikampissa rakkhāvaraṇaguttiṃ saṃvidaheyyāmā”ti.**Rather, I would bow to them, rise in their presence, and offer them a seat. I’d invite them to accept robes, alms-food, lodgings, and medicines and supplies for the sick. And I’d arrange for their lawful guarding and protection.”*";
P_HTM[948]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, mahārāja?**“What do you think, great king?*";
P_HTM[949]="*Yadi evaṃ sante hoti vā sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ no vā”ti?**If this is so, is there a fruit of the ascetic life apparent in the present life or not?”*";
P_HTM[950]="*“Addhā kho, bhante, evaṃ sante hoti sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalan”ti.**“Clearly, sir, there is.”*";
P_HTM[951]="*“Idaṃ kho te, mahārāja, mayā dutiyaṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ paññattan”ti.**“This is the second fruit of the ascetic life that’s apparent in the present life, which I point out to you.”*";
P_HTM[952]="*4.3. Paṇītatarasāmaññaphala**4.3. The Finer Fruits of the Ascetic Life*";
P_HTM[953]="*“Sakkā pana, bhante, aññampi diṭṭheva dhamme sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ paññapetuṃ imehi sandiṭṭhikehi sāmaññaphalehi abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañcā”ti?**“But sir, can you point out a fruit of the ascetic life that’s apparent in the present life which is better and finer than these?”*";
P_HTM[954]="*“Sakkā, mahārāja.**“I can, great king.*";
P_HTM[955]="*Tena hi, mahārāja, suṇohi, sādhukaṃ manasi karohi, bhāsissāmī”ti.**Well then, listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[956]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho rājā māgadho ajātasattu vedehiputto bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” replied the king.*";
P_HTM[957]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[958]="*“idha, mahārāja, tathāgato loke uppajjati arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā.**“Consider when a Realized One arises in the world, perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.*";
P_HTM[959]="*So imaṃ lokaṃ sadevakaṃ samārakaṃ sabrahmakaṃ sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiṃ pajaṃ sadevamanussaṃ sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedeti.**He has realized with his own insight this world—with its gods, Māras and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, gods and humans—and he makes it known to others.*";
P_HTM[960]="*So dhammaṃ deseti ādikalyāṇaṃ majjhekalyāṇaṃ pariyosānakalyāṇaṃ sātthaṃ sabyañjanaṃ, kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ pakāseti.**He teaches Dhamma that’s good in the beginning, good in the middle, and good in the end, meaningful and well-phrased. And he reveals a spiritual practice that’s entirely full and pure.*";
P_HTM[961]="*Taṃ dhammaṃ suṇāti gahapati vā gahapatiputto vā aññatarasmiṃ vā kule paccājāto.**A householder hears that teaching, or a householder’s child, or someone reborn in some clan.*";
P_HTM[962]="*So taṃ dhammaṃ sutvā tathāgate saddhaṃ paṭilabhati.**They gain faith in the Realized One,*";
P_HTM[963]="*So tena saddhāpaṭilābhena samannāgato iti paṭisañcikkhati:**and reflect:*";
P_HTM[964]="*‘sambādho gharāvāso rajopatho, abbhokāso pabbajjā.**‘Living in a house is cramped and dirty, but the life of one gone forth is wide open.*";
P_HTM[965]="*Nayidaṃ sukaraṃ agāraṃ ajjhāvasatā ekantaparipuṇṇaṃ ekantaparisuddhaṃ saṅkhalikhitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ carituṃ.**It’s not easy for someone living at home to lead the spiritual life utterly full and pure, like a polished shell.*";
P_HTM[966]="*Yannūnāhaṃ kesamassuṃ ohāretvā kāsāyāni vatthāni acchādetvā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajeyyan’ti.**Why don’t I shave off my hair and beard, dress in ocher robes, and go forth from the lay life to homelessness?’*";
P_HTM[967]="*So aparena samayena appaṃ vā bhogakkhandhaṃ pahāya mahantaṃ vā bhogakkhandhaṃ pahāya appaṃ vā ñātiparivaṭṭaṃ pahāya mahantaṃ vā ñātiparivaṭṭaṃ pahāya kesamassuṃ ohāretvā kāsāyāni vatthāni acchādetvā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajati.**After some time they give up a large or small fortune, and a large or small family circle. They shave off hair and beard, dress in ocher robes, and go forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[968]="*So evaṃ pabbajito samāno pātimokkhasaṃvarasaṃvuto viharati ācāragocarasampanno, aṇumattesu vajjesu bhayadassāvī, samādāya sikkhati sikkhāpadesu, kāyakammavacīkammena samannāgato kusalena, parisuddhājīvo sīlasampanno, indriyesu guttadvāro, satisampajaññena samannāgato, santuṭṭho.**Once they’ve gone forth, they live restrained in the monastic code, conducting themselves well and seeking alms in suitable places. Seeing danger in the slightest fault, they keep the rules they’ve undertaken. They act skillfully by body and speech. They’re purified in livelihood and accomplished in ethical conduct. They guard the sense doors, have mindfulness and situational awareness, and are content.*";
P_HTM[969]="*4.3.1. Sīla**4.3.1. Ethics*";
P_HTM[970]="*4.3.1.1. Cūḷasīla**4.3.1.1. The Shorter Section on Ethics*";
P_HTM[971]="*Kathañca, mahārāja, bhikkhu sīlasampanno hoti?**And how, great king, is a mendicant accomplished in ethics?*";
P_HTM[972]="*Idha, mahārāja, bhikkhu pāṇātipātaṃ pahāya pāṇātipātā paṭivirato hoti. Nihitadaṇḍo nihitasattho lajjī dayāpanno sabbapāṇabhūtahitānukampī viharati.**It’s when a mendicant gives up killing living creatures, renouncing the rod and the sword. They’re scrupulous and kind, living full of compassion for all living beings.*";
P_HTM[973]="*Idampissa hoti sīlasmiṃ.**This pertains to their ethics.*";
P_HTM[974]="*Adinnādānaṃ pahāya adinnādānā paṭivirato hoti dinnādāyī dinnapāṭikaṅkhī, athenena sucibhūtena attanā viharati.**They give up stealing. They take only what’s given, and expect only what’s given. They keep themselves clean by not thieving.*";
P_HTM[975]="*Idampissa hoti sīlasmiṃ.**This pertains to their ethics.*";
P_HTM[976]="*Abrahmacariyaṃ pahāya brahmacārī hoti ārācārī virato methunā gāmadhammā.**They give up unchastity. They are celibate, set apart, avoiding the common practice of sex.*";
P_HTM[977]="*Idampissa hoti sīlasmiṃ.**This pertains to their ethics.*";
P_HTM[978]="*Musāvādaṃ pahāya musāvādā paṭivirato hoti saccavādī saccasandho theto paccayiko avisaṃvādako lokassa.**They give up lying. They speak the truth and stick to the truth. They’re honest and trustworthy, and don’t trick the world with their words.*";
P_HTM[979]="*Idampissa hoti sīlasmiṃ.**This pertains to their ethics.*";
P_HTM[980]="*Pisuṇaṃ vācaṃ pahāya pisuṇāya vācāya paṭivirato hoti; ito sutvā na amutra akkhātā imesaṃ bhedāya; amutra vā sutvā na imesaṃ akkhātā, amūsaṃ bhedāya. Iti bhinnānaṃ vā sandhātā, sahitānaṃ vā anuppadātā, samaggārāmo samaggarato samagganandī samaggakaraṇiṃ vācaṃ bhāsitā hoti.**They give up divisive speech. They don’t repeat in one place what they heard in another so as to divide people against each other. Instead, they reconcile those who are divided, supporting unity, delighting in harmony, loving harmony, speaking words that promote harmony.*";
P_HTM[981]="*Idampissa hoti sīlasmiṃ.**This pertains to their ethics.*";
P_HTM[982]="*Pharusaṃ vācaṃ pahāya pharusāya vācāya paṭivirato hoti; yā sā vācā nelā kaṇṇasukhā pemanīyā hadayaṅgamā porī bahujanakantā bahujanamanāpā tathārūpiṃ vācaṃ bhāsitā hoti.**They give up harsh speech. They speak in a way that’s mellow, pleasing to the ear, lovely, going to the heart, polite, likable and agreeable to the people.*";
P_HTM[983]="*Idampissa hoti sīlasmiṃ.**This pertains to their ethics.*";
P_HTM[984]="*Samphappalāpaṃ pahāya samphappalāpā paṭivirato hoti kālavādī bhūtavādī atthavādī dhammavādī vinayavādī, nidhānavatiṃ vācaṃ bhāsitā hoti kālena sāpadesaṃ pariyantavatiṃ atthasaṃhitaṃ.**They give up talking nonsense. Their words are timely, true, and meaningful, in line with the teaching and training. They say things at the right time which are valuable, reasonable, succinct, and beneficial.*";
P_HTM[985]="*Idampissa hoti sīlasmiṃ.**This pertains to their ethics.*";
P_HTM[986]="*Bījagāmabhūtagāmasamārambhā paṭivirato hoti … pe …**They refrain from injuring plants and seeds.*";
P_HTM[987]="*ekabhattiko hoti rattūparato virato vikālabhojanā.**They eat in one part of the day, abstaining from eating at night and food at the wrong time.*";
P_HTM[988]="*Naccagītavāditavisūkadassanā paṭivirato hoti.**They avoid dancing, singing, music, and seeing shows.*";
P_HTM[989]="*Mālāgandhavilepanadhāraṇamaṇḍanavibhūsanaṭṭhānā paṭivirato hoti.**They refrain from beautifying and adorning themselves with garlands, fragrance, and makeup.*";
P_HTM[990]="*Uccāsayanamahāsayanā paṭivirato hoti.**They avoid high and luxurious beds.*";
P_HTM[991]="*Jātarūparajatapaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato hoti.**They avoid receiving gold and money,*";
P_HTM[992]="*Āmakadhaññapaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato hoti.**raw grains,*";
P_HTM[993]="*Āmakamaṃsapaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato hoti.**raw meat,*";
P_HTM[994]="*Itthikumārikapaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato hoti.**women and girls,*";
P_HTM[995]="*Dāsidāsapaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato hoti.**male and female bondservants,*";
P_HTM[996]="*Ajeḷakapaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato hoti.**goats and sheep,*";
P_HTM[997]="*Kukkuṭasūkarapaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato hoti.**chickens and pigs,*";
P_HTM[998]="*Hatthigavassavaḷavapaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato hoti.**elephants, cows, horses, and mares,*";
P_HTM[999]="*Khettavatthupaṭiggahaṇā paṭivirato hoti.**and fields and land.*";
P_HTM[1000]="*Dūteyyapahiṇagamanānuyogā paṭivirato hoti.**They refrain from running errands and messages;*";
P_HTM[1001]="*Kayavikkayā paṭivirato hoti.**buying and selling;*";
P_HTM[1002]="*Tulākūṭakaṃsakūṭamānakūṭā paṭivirato hoti.**falsifying weights, metals, or measures;*";
P_HTM[1003]="*Ukkoṭanavañcananikatisāciyogā paṭivirato hoti.**bribery, fraud, cheating, and duplicity;*";
P_HTM[1004]="*Chedanavadhabandhanaviparāmosaālopasahasākārā paṭivirato hoti.**mutilation, murder, abduction, banditry, plunder, and violence.*";
P_HTM[1005]="*Idampissa hoti sīlasmiṃ.**This pertains to their ethics.*";
P_HTM[1006]="*Cūḷasīlaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ.**The shorter section on ethics is finished.*";
P_HTM[1007]="*4.3.1.2. Majjhimasīla**4.3.1.2. The Middle Section on Ethics*";
P_HTM[1008]="*Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpaṃ bījagāmabhūtagāmasamārambhaṃ anuyuttā viharanti.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still engage in injuring plants and seeds.*";
P_HTM[1009]="*Seyyathidaṃ—mūlabījaṃ khandhabījaṃ phaḷubījaṃ aggabījaṃ bījabījameva pañcamaṃ, iti evarūpā bījagāmabhūtagāmasamārambhā paṭivirato hoti.**These include plants propagated from roots, stems, cuttings, or joints; and those from regular seeds as the fifth. They refrain from such injury to plants and seeds.*";
P_HTM[1010]="*Idampissa hoti sīlasmiṃ.**This pertains to their ethics.*";
P_HTM[1011]="*Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpaṃ sannidhikāraparibhogaṃ anuyuttā viharanti.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still engage in storing up goods for their own use.*";
P_HTM[1012]="*Seyyathidaṃ—annasannidhiṃ pānasannidhiṃ vatthasannidhiṃ yānasannidhiṃ sayanasannidhiṃ gandhasannidhiṃ āmisasannidhiṃ,**This includes such things as food, drink, clothes, vehicles, bedding, fragrance, and material possessions.*";
P_HTM[1013]="*iti vā iti evarūpā sannidhikāraparibhogā paṭivirato hoti.**They refrain from storing up such goods.*";
P_HTM[1014]="*Idampissa hoti sīlasmiṃ.**This pertains to their ethics.*";
P_HTM[1015]="*Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpaṃ visūkadassanaṃ anuyuttā viharanti.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still engage in seeing shows.*";
P_HTM[1016]="*Seyyathidaṃ—naccaṃ gītaṃ vāditaṃ pekkhaṃ akkhānaṃ pāṇissaraṃ vetāḷaṃ kumbhathūṇaṃ sobhanakaṃ caṇḍālaṃ vaṃsaṃ dhovanaṃ hatthiyuddhaṃ assayuddhaṃ mahiṃsayuddhaṃ usabhayuddhaṃ ajayuddhaṃ meṇḍayuddhaṃ kukkuṭayuddhaṃ vaṭṭakayuddhaṃ daṇḍayuddhaṃ muṭṭhiyuddhaṃ nibbuddhaṃ uyyodhikaṃ balaggaṃ senābyūhaṃ anīkadassanaṃ**This includes such things as dancing, singing, music, performances, and storytelling; clapping, gongs, and kettle-drums; art exhibitions and acrobatic displays; battles of elephants, horses, buffaloes, bulls, goats, rams, chickens, and quails; staff-fights, boxing, and wrestling; combat, roll calls of the armed forces, battle-formations, and regimental reviews.*";
P_HTM[1017]="*iti vā iti evarūpā visūkadassanā paṭivirato hoti.**They refrain from such shows.*";
P_HTM[1018]="*Idampissa hoti sīlasmiṃ.**This pertains to their ethics.*";
P_HTM[1019]="*Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpaṃ jūtappamādaṭṭhānānuyogaṃ anuyuttā viharanti.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still engage in gambling that causes negligence.*";
P_HTM[1020]="*Seyyathidaṃ—aṭṭhapadaṃ dasapadaṃ ākāsaṃ parihārapathaṃ santikaṃ khalikaṃ ghaṭikaṃ salākahatthaṃ akkhaṃ paṅgacīraṃ vaṅkakaṃ mokkhacikaṃ ciṅgulikaṃ pattāḷhakaṃ rathakaṃ dhanukaṃ akkharikaṃ manesikaṃ yathāvajjaṃ**This includes such things as checkers, draughts, checkers in the air, hopscotch, spillikins, board-games, tip-cat, drawing straws, dice, leaf-flutes, toy plows, somersaults, pinwheels, toy measures, toy carts, toy bows, guessing words from syllables, and guessing another’s thoughts.*";
P_HTM[1021]="*iti vā iti evarūpā jūtappamādaṭṭhānānuyogā paṭivirato hoti.**They refrain from such gambling.*";
P_HTM[1022]="*Idampissa hoti sīlasmiṃ.**This pertains to their ethics.*";
P_HTM[1023]="*Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpaṃ uccāsayanamahāsayanaṃ anuyuttā viharanti.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still make use of high and luxurious bedding.*";
P_HTM[1024]="*Seyyathidaṃ—āsandiṃ pallaṅkaṃ gonakaṃ cittakaṃ paṭikaṃ paṭalikaṃ tūlikaṃ vikatikaṃ uddalomiṃ ekantalomiṃ kaṭṭissaṃ koseyyaṃ kuttakaṃ hatthattharaṃ assattharaṃ rathattharaṃ ajinappaveṇiṃ kadalimigapavarapaccattharaṇaṃ sauttaracchadaṃ ubhatolohitakūpadhānaṃ**This includes such things as sofas, couches, woolen covers—shag-piled, colorful, white, embroidered with flowers, quilted, embroidered with animals, double-or single-fringed—and silk covers studded with gems, as well as silken sheets, woven carpets, rugs for elephants, horses, or chariots, antelope hide rugs, and spreads of fine deer hide, with a canopy above and red cushions at both ends.*";
P_HTM[1025]="*iti vā iti evarūpā uccāsayanamahāsayanā paṭivirato hoti.**They refrain from such bedding.*";
P_HTM[1026]="*Idampissa hoti sīlasmiṃ.**This pertains to their ethics.*";
P_HTM[1027]="*Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpaṃ maṇḍanavibhūsanaṭṭhānānuyogaṃ anuyuttā viharanti.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still engage in beautifying and adorning themselves with garlands, fragrance, and makeup.*";
P_HTM[1028]="*Seyyathidaṃ—ucchādanaṃ parimaddanaṃ nhāpanaṃ sambāhanaṃ ādāsaṃ añjanaṃ mālāgandhavilepanaṃ mukhacuṇṇaṃ mukhalepanaṃ hatthabandhaṃ sikhābandhaṃ daṇḍaṃ nāḷikaṃ asiṃ chattaṃ citrupāhanaṃ uṇhīsaṃ maṇiṃ vālabījaniṃ odātāni vatthāni dīghadasāni**This includes such things as applying beauty products by anointing, massaging, bathing, and rubbing; mirrors, ointments, garlands, fragrances, and makeup; face-powder, foundation, bracelets, headbands, fancy walking-sticks or containers, rapiers, parasols, fancy sandals, turbans, jewelry, chowries, and long-fringed white robes.*";
P_HTM[1029]="*iti vā iti evarūpā maṇḍanavibhūsanaṭṭhānānuyogā paṭivirato hoti.**They refrain from such beautification and adornment.*";
P_HTM[1030]="*Idampissa hoti sīlasmiṃ.**This pertains to their ethics.*";
P_HTM[1031]="*Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpaṃ tiracchānakathaṃ anuyuttā viharanti.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still engage in unworthy talk.*";
P_HTM[1032]="*Seyyathidaṃ—rājakathaṃ corakathaṃ mahāmattakathaṃ senākathaṃ bhayakathaṃ yuddhakathaṃ annakathaṃ pānakathaṃ vatthakathaṃ sayanakathaṃ mālākathaṃ gandhakathaṃ ñātikathaṃ yānakathaṃ gāmakathaṃ nigamakathaṃ nagarakathaṃ janapadakathaṃ itthikathaṃ sūrakathaṃ visikhākathaṃ kumbhaṭṭhānakathaṃ pubbapetakathaṃ nānattakathaṃ lokakkhāyikaṃ samuddakkhāyikaṃ itibhavābhavakathaṃ**This includes such topics as talk about kings, bandits, and ministers; talk about armies, threats, and wars; talk about food, drink, clothes, and beds; talk about garlands and fragrances; talk about family, vehicles, villages, towns, cities, and countries; talk about women and heroes; street talk and well talk; talk about the departed; motley talk; tales of land and sea; and talk about being reborn in this or that state of existence.*";
P_HTM[1033]="*iti vā iti evarūpāya tiracchānakathāya paṭivirato hoti.**They refrain from such unworthy talk.*";
P_HTM[1034]="*Idampissa hoti sīlasmiṃ.**This pertains to their ethics.*";
P_HTM[1035]="*Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpaṃ viggāhikakathaṃ anuyuttā viharanti.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still engage in arguments.*";
P_HTM[1036]="*Seyyathidaṃ—na tvaṃ imaṃ dhammavinayaṃ ājānāsi, ahaṃ imaṃ dhammavinayaṃ ājānāmi, kiṃ tvaṃ imaṃ dhammavinayaṃ ājānissasi, micchā paṭipanno tvamasi, ahamasmi sammā paṭipanno, sahitaṃ me, asahitaṃ te, pure vacanīyaṃ pacchā avaca, pacchā vacanīyaṃ pure avaca, adhiciṇṇaṃ te viparāvattaṃ, āropito te vādo, niggahito tvamasi, cara vādappamokkhāya, nibbeṭhehi vā sace pahosīti**They say such things as: ‘You don’t understand this teaching and training. I understand this teaching and training. What, you understand this teaching and training? You’re practicing wrong. I’m practicing right. I stay on topic, you don’t. You said last what you should have said first. You said first what you should have said last. What you’ve thought so much about has been disproved. Your doctrine is refuted. Go on, save your doctrine! You’re trapped; get yourself out of this—if you can!’*";
P_HTM[1037]="*iti vā iti evarūpāya viggāhikakathāya paṭivirato hoti.**They refrain from such argumentative talk.*";
P_HTM[1038]="*Idampissa hoti sīlasmiṃ.**This pertains to their ethics.*";
P_HTM[1039]="*Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpaṃ dūteyyapahiṇagamanānuyogaṃ anuyuttā viharanti.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still engage in running errands and messages.*";
P_HTM[1040]="*Seyyathidaṃ—raññaṃ, rājamahāmattānaṃ, khattiyānaṃ, brāhmaṇānaṃ, gahapatikānaṃ, kumārānaṃ—idha gaccha, amutrāgaccha, idaṃ hara, amutra idaṃ āharā’ti**This includes running errands for rulers, ministers, aristocrats, brahmins, householders, or princes who say: ‘Go here, go there. Take this, bring that from there.’*";
P_HTM[1041]="*iti vā iti evarūpā dūteyyapahiṇagamanānuyogā paṭivirato hoti.**They refrain from such errands.*";
P_HTM[1042]="*Idampissa hoti sīlasmiṃ.**This pertains to their ethics.*";
P_HTM[1043]="*Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te kuhakā ca honti lapakā ca nemittikā ca nippesikā ca lābhena lābhaṃ nijigīsitāro ca. Iti evarūpā kuhanalapanā paṭivirato hoti.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still engage in deceit, flattery, hinting, and belittling, and using material possessions to pursue other material possessions. They refrain from such deceit and flattery.*";
P_HTM[1044]="*Idampissa hoti sīlasmiṃ.**This pertains to their ethics.*";
P_HTM[1045]="*Majjhimasīlaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ.**The middle section on ethics is finished.*";
P_HTM[1046]="*4.3.1.3. Mahāsīla**4.3.1.3. The Long Section on Ethics*";
P_HTM[1047]="*Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpāya tiracchānavijjāya micchājīvena jīvitaṃ kappenti.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still earn a living by unworthy branches of knowledge, by wrong livelihood.*";
P_HTM[1048]="*Seyyathidaṃ—aṅgaṃ nimittaṃ uppātaṃ supinaṃ lakkhaṇaṃ mūsikacchinnaṃ aggihomaṃ dabbihomaṃ thusahomaṃ kaṇahomaṃ taṇḍulahomaṃ sappihomaṃ telahomaṃ mukhahomaṃ lohitahomaṃ aṅgavijjā vatthuvijjā khattavijjā sivavijjā bhūtavijjā bhūrivijjā ahivijjā visavijjā vicchikavijjā mūsikavijjā sakuṇavijjā vāyasavijjā pakkajjhānaṃ saraparittāṇaṃ migacakkaṃ**This includes such fields as limb-reading, omenology, divining celestial portents, interpreting dreams, divining bodily marks, divining holes in cloth gnawed by mice, fire offerings, ladle offerings, offerings of husks, rice powder, rice, ghee, or oil; offerings from the mouth, blood sacrifices, palmistry; geomancy for building sites, fields, and cemeteries; exorcisms, earth magic, snake charming, poisons; the crafts of the scorpion, the rat, the bird, and the crow; prophesying life span, chanting for protection, and animal cries.*";
P_HTM[1049]="*iti vā iti evarūpāya tiracchānavijjāya micchājīvā paṭivirato hoti.**They refrain from such unworthy branches of knowledge, such wrong livelihood.*";
P_HTM[1050]="*Idampissa hoti sīlasmiṃ.**This pertains to their ethics.*";
P_HTM[1051]="*Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpāya tiracchānavijjāya micchājīvena jīvitaṃ kappenti.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still earn a living by unworthy branches of knowledge, by wrong livelihood.*";
P_HTM[1052]="*Seyyathidaṃ—maṇilakkhaṇaṃ vatthalakkhaṇaṃ daṇḍalakkhaṇaṃ satthalakkhaṇaṃ asilakkhaṇaṃ usulakkhaṇaṃ dhanulakkhaṇaṃ āvudhalakkhaṇaṃ itthilakkhaṇaṃ purisalakkhaṇaṃ kumāralakkhaṇaṃ kumārilakkhaṇaṃ dāsalakkhaṇaṃ dāsilakkhaṇaṃ hatthilakkhaṇaṃ assalakkhaṇaṃ mahiṃsalakkhaṇaṃ usabhalakkhaṇaṃ golakkhaṇaṃ ajalakkhaṇaṃ meṇḍalakkhaṇaṃ kukkuṭalakkhaṇaṃ vaṭṭakalakkhaṇaṃ godhālakkhaṇaṃ kaṇṇikalakkhaṇaṃ kacchapalakkhaṇaṃ migalakkhaṇaṃ**This includes reading the marks of gems, cloth, clubs, swords, spears, arrows, weapons, women, men, boys, girls, male and female bondservants, elephants, horses, buffaloes, bulls, cows, goats, rams, chickens, quails, monitor lizards, rabbits, tortoises, or deer.*";
P_HTM[1053]="*iti vā iti evarūpāya tiracchānavijjāya micchājīvā paṭivirato hoti.**They refrain from such unworthy branches of knowledge, such wrong livelihood.*";
P_HTM[1054]="*Idampissa hoti sīlasmiṃ.**This pertains to their ethics.*";
P_HTM[1055]="*Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpāya tiracchānavijjāya micchājīvena jīvitaṃ kappenti.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still earn a living by unworthy branches of knowledge, by wrong livelihood.*";
P_HTM[1056]="*Seyyathidaṃ—raññaṃ niyyānaṃ bhavissati, raññaṃ aniyyānaṃ bhavissati, abbhantarānaṃ raññaṃ upayānaṃ bhavissati, bāhirānaṃ raññaṃ apayānaṃ bhavissati, bāhirānaṃ raññaṃ upayānaṃ bhavissati, abbhantarānaṃ raññaṃ apayānaṃ bhavissati, abbhantarānaṃ raññaṃ jayo bhavissati, bāhirānaṃ raññaṃ parājayo bhavissati, bāhirānaṃ raññaṃ jayo bhavissati, abbhantarānaṃ raññaṃ parājayo bhavissati, iti imassa jayo bhavissati, imassa parājayo bhavissati**This includes making predictions that the king will march forth or march back; or that our king will attack and the enemy king will retreat, or vice versa; or that our king will triumph and the enemy king will be defeated, or vice versa; and so there will be victory for one and defeat for the other.*";
P_HTM[1057]="*iti vā iti evarūpāya tiracchānavijjāya micchājīvā paṭivirato hoti.**They refrain from such unworthy branches of knowledge, such wrong livelihood.*";
P_HTM[1058]="*Idampissa hoti sīlasmiṃ.**This pertains to their ethics.*";
P_HTM[1059]="*Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpāya tiracchānavijjāya micchājīvena jīvitaṃ kappenti.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still earn a living by unworthy branches of knowledge, by wrong livelihood.*";
P_HTM[1060]="*Seyyathidaṃ—candaggāho bhavissati, sūriyaggāho bhavissati, nakkhattaggāho bhavissati, candimasūriyānaṃ pathagamanaṃ bhavissati, candimasūriyānaṃ uppathagamanaṃ bhavissati, nakkhattānaṃ pathagamanaṃ bhavissati, nakkhattānaṃ uppathagamanaṃ bhavissati, ukkāpāto bhavissati, disāḍāho bhavissati, bhūmicālo bhavissati, devadudrabhi bhavissati, candimasūriyanakkhattānaṃ uggamanaṃ ogamanaṃ saṅkilesaṃ vodānaṃ bhavissati, evaṃvipāko candaggāho bhavissati, evaṃvipāko sūriyaggāho bhavissati, evaṃvipāko nakkhattaggāho bhavissati, evaṃvipākaṃ candimasūriyānaṃ pathagamanaṃ bhavissati, evaṃvipākaṃ candimasūriyānaṃ uppathagamanaṃ bhavissati, evaṃvipākaṃ nakkhattānaṃ pathagamanaṃ bhavissati, evaṃvipākaṃ nakkhattānaṃ uppathagamanaṃ bhavissati, evaṃvipāko ukkāpāto bhavissati, evaṃvipāko disāḍāho bhavissati, evaṃvipāko bhūmicālo bhavissati, evaṃvipāko devadudrabhi bhavissati, evaṃvipākaṃ candimasūriyanakkhattānaṃ uggamanaṃ ogamanaṃ saṅkilesaṃ vodānaṃ bhavissati**This includes making predictions that there will be an eclipse of the moon, or sun, or stars; that the sun, moon, and stars will be in conjunction or in opposition; that there will be a meteor shower, a fiery sky, an earthquake, thunder; that there will be a rising, a setting, a darkening, a brightening of the moon, sun, and stars. And it also includes making predictions about the results of all such phenomena.*";
P_HTM[1061]="*iti vā iti evarūpāya tiracchānavijjāya micchājīvā paṭivirato hoti.**They refrain from such unworthy branches of knowledge, such wrong livelihood.*";
P_HTM[1062]="*Idampissa hoti sīlasmiṃ.**This pertains to their ethics.*";
P_HTM[1063]="*Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpāya tiracchānavijjāya micchājīvena jīvitaṃ kappenti.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still earn a living by unworthy branches of knowledge, by wrong livelihood.*";
P_HTM[1064]="*Seyyathidaṃ—suvuṭṭhikā bhavissati, dubbuṭṭhikā bhavissati, subhikkhaṃ bhavissati, dubbhikkhaṃ bhavissati, khemaṃ bhavissati, bhayaṃ bhavissati, rogo bhavissati, ārogyaṃ bhavissati, muddā, gaṇanā, saṅkhānaṃ, kāveyyaṃ, lokāyataṃ**This includes predicting whether there will be plenty of rain or drought; plenty to eat or famine; an abundant harvest or a bad harvest; security or peril; sickness or health. It also includes such occupations as computing, accounting, calculating, poetry, and cosmology.*";
P_HTM[1065]="*iti vā iti evarūpāya tiracchānavijjāya micchājīvā paṭivirato hoti.**They refrain from such unworthy branches of knowledge, such wrong livelihood.*";
P_HTM[1066]="*Idampissa hoti sīlasmiṃ.**This pertains to their ethics.*";
P_HTM[1067]="*Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpāya tiracchānavijjāya micchājīvena jīvitaṃ kappenti.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still earn a living by unworthy branches of knowledge, by wrong livelihood.*";
P_HTM[1068]="*Seyyathidaṃ—āvāhanaṃ vivāhanaṃ saṃvaraṇaṃ vivaraṇaṃ saṅkiraṇaṃ vikiraṇaṃ subhagakaraṇaṃ dubbhagakaraṇaṃ viruddhagabbhakaraṇaṃ jivhānibandhanaṃ hanusaṃhananaṃ hatthābhijappanaṃ hanujappanaṃ kaṇṇajappanaṃ ādāsapañhaṃ kumārikapañhaṃ devapañhaṃ ādiccupaṭṭhānaṃ mahatupaṭṭhānaṃ abbhujjalanaṃ sirivhāyanaṃ**This includes making arrangements for giving and taking in marriage; for engagement and divorce; and for scattering rice inwards or outwards at the wedding ceremony. It also includes casting spells for good or bad luck, curses to prevent conception, bind the tongue, or lock the jaws; charms for the hands and ears; questioning a mirror, a girl, or a god as an oracle; worshiping the sun, worshiping the Great One, breathing fire, and invoking Siri, the goddess of luck.*";
P_HTM[1069]="*iti vā iti evarūpāya tiracchānavijjāya micchājīvā paṭivirato hoti.**They refrain from such unworthy branches of knowledge, such wrong livelihood.*";
P_HTM[1070]="*Idampissa hoti sīlasmiṃ.**This pertains to their ethics.*";
P_HTM[1071]="*Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpāya tiracchānavijjāya micchājīvena jīvitaṃ kappenti.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still earn a living by unworthy branches of knowledge, by wrong livelihood.*";
P_HTM[1072]="*Seyyathidaṃ—santikammaṃ paṇidhikammaṃ bhūtakammaṃ bhūrikammaṃ vassakammaṃ vossakammaṃ vatthukammaṃ vatthuparikammaṃ ācamanaṃ nhāpanaṃ juhanaṃ vamanaṃ virecanaṃ uddhaṃvirecanaṃ adhovirecanaṃ sīsavirecanaṃ kaṇṇatelaṃ nettatappanaṃ natthukammaṃ añjanaṃ paccañjanaṃ sālākiyaṃ sallakattiyaṃ dārakatikicchā, mūlabhesajjānaṃ anuppadānaṃ, osadhīnaṃ paṭimokkho**This includes rites for propitiation, for granting wishes, for ghosts, for the earth, for rain, for property settlement, and for preparing and consecrating house sites, and rites involving rinsing and bathing, and oblations. It also includes administering emetics, purgatives, expectorants, and phlegmagogues; administering ear-oils, eye restoratives, nasal medicine, ointments, and counter-ointments; surgery with needle and scalpel, treating children, prescribing root medicines, and binding on herbs.*";
P_HTM[1073]="*iti vā iti evarūpāya tiracchānavijjāya micchājīvā paṭivirato hoti.**They refrain from such unworthy branches of knowledge, such wrong livelihood.*";
P_HTM[1074]="*Idampissa hoti sīlasmiṃ.**This pertains to their ethics.*";
P_HTM[1075]="*Sa kho so, mahārāja, bhikkhu evaṃ sīlasampanno na kutoci bhayaṃ samanupassati, yadidaṃ sīlasaṃvarato.**A mendicant thus accomplished in ethics sees no danger in any quarter in regards to their ethical restraint.*";
P_HTM[1076]="*Seyyathāpi, mahārāja, rājā khattiyo muddhābhisitto nihatapaccāmitto na kutoci bhayaṃ samanupassati, yadidaṃ paccatthikato;**It’s like a king who has defeated his enemies. He sees no danger from his foes in any quarter.*";
P_HTM[1077]="*evameva kho, mahārāja, bhikkhu evaṃ sīlasampanno na kutoci bhayaṃ samanupassati, yadidaṃ sīlasaṃvarato.**In the same way, a mendicant thus accomplished in ethics sees no danger in any quarter in regards to their ethical restraint.*";
P_HTM[1078]="*So iminā ariyena sīlakkhandhena samannāgato ajjhattaṃ anavajjasukhaṃ paṭisaṃvedeti.**When they have this entire spectrum of noble ethics, they experience a blameless happiness inside themselves.*";
P_HTM[1079]="*Evaṃ kho, mahārāja, bhikkhu sīlasampanno hoti.**That’s how a mendicant is accomplished in ethics.*";
P_HTM[1080]="*Mahāsīlaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ.**The longer section on ethics is finished.*";
P_HTM[1081]="*4.3.2. Samādhi**4.3.2. Immersion*";
P_HTM[1082]="*4.3.2.1. Indriyasaṃvara**4.3.2.1. Sense Restraint*";
P_HTM[1083]="*Kathañca, mahārāja, bhikkhu indriyesu guttadvāro hoti?**And how does a mendicant guard the sense doors?*";
P_HTM[1084]="*Idha, mahārāja, bhikkhu cakkhunā rūpaṃ disvā na nimittaggāhī hoti nānubyañjanaggāhī.**When a noble disciple sees a sight with their eyes, they don’t get caught up in the features and details.*";
P_HTM[1085]="*Yatvādhikaraṇamenaṃ cakkhundriyaṃ asaṃvutaṃ viharantaṃ abhijjhā domanassā pāpakā akusalā dhammā anvāssaveyyuṃ, tassa saṃvarāya paṭipajjati, rakkhati cakkhundriyaṃ, cakkhundriye saṃvaraṃ āpajjati.**If the faculty of sight were left unrestrained, bad unskillful qualities of desire and aversion would become overwhelming. For this reason, they practice restraint, protecting the faculty of sight, and achieving its restraint.*";
P_HTM[1086]="*Sotena saddaṃ sutvā … pe …**When they hear a sound with their ears …*";
P_HTM[1087]="*ghānena gandhaṃ ghāyitvā … pe …**When they smell an odor with their nose …*";
P_HTM[1088]="*jivhāya rasaṃ sāyitvā … pe …**When they taste a flavor with their tongue …*";
P_HTM[1089]="*kāyena phoṭṭhabbaṃ phusitvā … pe …**When they feel a touch with their body …*";
P_HTM[1090]="*manasā dhammaṃ viññāya na nimittaggāhī hoti nānubyañjanaggāhī.**When they know a thought with their mind, they don’t get caught up in the features and details.*";
P_HTM[1091]="*Yatvādhikaraṇamenaṃ manindriyaṃ asaṃvutaṃ viharantaṃ abhijjhā domanassā pāpakā akusalā dhammā anvāssaveyyuṃ, tassa saṃvarāya paṭipajjati, rakkhati manindriyaṃ, manindriye saṃvaraṃ āpajjati.**If the faculty of mind were left unrestrained, bad unskillful qualities of desire and aversion would become overwhelming. For this reason, they practice restraint, protecting the faculty of mind, and achieving its restraint.*";
P_HTM[1092]="*So iminā ariyena indriyasaṃvarena samannāgato ajjhattaṃ abyāsekasukhaṃ paṭisaṃvedeti.**When they have this noble sense restraint, they experience an unsullied bliss inside themselves.*";
P_HTM[1093]="*Evaṃ kho, mahārāja, bhikkhu indriyesu guttadvāro hoti.**That’s how a mendicant guards the sense doors.*";
P_HTM[1094]="*4.3.2.2. Satisampajañña**4.3.2.2. Mindfulness and Situational Awareness*";
P_HTM[1095]="*Kathañca, mahārāja, bhikkhu satisampajaññena samannāgato hoti?**And how does a mendicant have mindfulness and situational awareness?*";
P_HTM[1096]="*Idha, mahārāja, bhikkhu abhikkante paṭikkante sampajānakārī hoti, ālokite vilokite sampajānakārī hoti, samiñjite pasārite sampajānakārī hoti, saṅghāṭipattacīvaradhāraṇe sampajānakārī hoti, asite pīte khāyite sāyite sampajānakārī hoti, uccārapassāvakamme sampajānakārī hoti, gate ṭhite nisinne sutte jāgarite bhāsite tuṇhībhāve sampajānakārī hoti.**It’s when a mendicant acts with situational awareness when going out and coming back; when looking ahead and aside; when bending and extending the limbs; when bearing the outer robe, bowl and robes; when eating, drinking, chewing, and tasting; when urinating and defecating; when walking, standing, sitting, sleeping, waking, speaking, and keeping silent.*";
P_HTM[1097]="*Evaṃ kho, mahārāja, bhikkhu satisampajaññena samannāgato hoti.**That’s how a mendicant has mindfulness and situational awareness.*";
P_HTM[1098]="*4.3.2.3. Santosa**4.3.2.3. Contentment*";
P_HTM[1099]="*Kathañca, mahārāja, bhikkhu santuṭṭho hoti?**And how is a mendicant content?*";
P_HTM[1100]="*Idha, mahārāja, bhikkhu santuṭṭho hoti kāyaparihārikena cīvarena, kucchiparihārikena piṇḍapātena. So yena yeneva pakkamati, samādāyeva pakkamati.**It’s when a mendicant is content with robes to look after the body and alms-food to look after the belly. Wherever they go, they set out taking only these things.*";
P_HTM[1101]="*Seyyathāpi, mahārāja, pakkhī sakuṇo yena yeneva ḍeti, sapattabhārova ḍeti;**They’re like a bird: wherever it flies, wings are its only burden.*";
P_HTM[1102]="*evameva kho, mahārāja, bhikkhu santuṭṭho hoti kāyaparihārikena cīvarena kucchiparihārikena piṇḍapātena. So yena yeneva pakkamati, samādāyeva pakkamati.**In the same way, a mendicant is content with robes to look after the body and alms-food to look after the belly. Wherever they go, they set out taking only these things.*";
P_HTM[1103]="*Evaṃ kho, mahārāja, bhikkhu santuṭṭho hoti.**That’s how a mendicant is content.*";
P_HTM[1104]="*4.3.2.4. Nīvara­ṇap­pahāna**4.3.2.4. Giving Up the Hindrances*";
P_HTM[1105]="*So iminā ca ariyena sīlakkhandhena samannāgato, iminā ca ariyena indriyasaṃvarena samannāgato, iminā ca ariyena satisampajaññena samannāgato, imāya ca ariyāya santuṭṭhiyā samannāgato,**When they have this noble spectrum of ethics, this noble sense restraint, this noble mindfulness and situational awareness, and this noble contentment,*";
P_HTM[1106]="*vivittaṃ senāsanaṃ bhajati araññaṃ rukkhamūlaṃ pabbataṃ kandaraṃ giriguhaṃ susānaṃ vanapatthaṃ abbhokāsaṃ palālapuñjaṃ.**they frequent a secluded lodging—a wilderness, the root of a tree, a hill, a ravine, a mountain cave, a charnel ground, a forest, the open air, a heap of straw.*";
P_HTM[1107]="*So pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkanto nisīdati pallaṅkaṃ ābhujitvā ujuṃ kāyaṃ paṇidhāya parimukhaṃ satiṃ upaṭṭhapetvā.**After the meal, they return from alms-round, sit down cross-legged with their body straight, and establish mindfulness right there.*";
P_HTM[1108]="*So abhijjhaṃ loke pahāya vigatābhijjhena cetasā viharati, abhijjhāya cittaṃ parisodheti.**Giving up desire for the world, they meditate with a heart rid of desire, cleansing the mind of desire.*";
P_HTM[1109]="*Byāpādapadosaṃ pahāya abyāpannacitto viharati sabbapāṇabhūtahitānukampī, byāpādapadosā cittaṃ parisodheti.**Giving up ill will and malevolence, they meditate with a mind rid of ill will, full of compassion for all living beings, cleansing the mind of ill will.*";
P_HTM[1110]="*Thinamiddhaṃ pahāya vigatathinamiddho viharati ālokasaññī, sato sampajāno, thinamiddhā cittaṃ parisodheti.**Giving up dullness and drowsiness, they meditate with a mind rid of dullness and drowsiness, perceiving light, mindful and aware, cleansing the mind of dullness and drowsiness.*";
P_HTM[1111]="*Uddhaccakukkuccaṃ pahāya anuddhato viharati, ajjhattaṃ vūpasantacitto, uddhaccakukkuccā cittaṃ parisodheti.**Giving up restlessness and remorse, they meditate without restlessness, their mind peaceful inside, cleansing the mind of restlessness and remorse.*";
P_HTM[1112]="*Vicikicchaṃ pahāya tiṇṇavicikiccho viharati, akathaṅkathī kusalesu dhammesu, vicikicchāya cittaṃ parisodheti.**Giving up doubt, they meditate having gone beyond doubt, not undecided about skillful qualities, cleansing the mind of doubt.*";
P_HTM[1113]="*Seyyathāpi, mahārāja, puriso iṇaṃ ādāya kammante payojeyya.**Suppose a man who has gotten into debt were to apply himself to work,*";
P_HTM[1114]="*Tassa te kammantā samijjheyyuṃ.**and his efforts proved successful.*";
P_HTM[1115]="*So yāni ca porāṇāni iṇamūlāni, tāni ca byantiṃ kareyya, siyā cassa uttariṃ avasiṭṭhaṃ dārabharaṇāya.**He would pay off the original loan and have enough left over to support his partner.*";
P_HTM[1116]="*Tassa evamassa:**Thinking about this,*";
P_HTM[1117]="*‘ahaṃ kho pubbe iṇaṃ ādāya kammante payojesiṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1118]="*Tassa me te kammantā samijjhiṃsu.* **";
P_HTM[1119]="*Sohaṃ yāni ca porāṇāni iṇamūlāni, tāni ca byantiṃ akāsiṃ, atthi ca me uttariṃ avasiṭṭhaṃ dārabharaṇāyā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1120]="*So tatonidānaṃ labhetha pāmojjaṃ, adhigaccheyya somanassaṃ.**he’d be filled with joy and happiness.*";
P_HTM[1121]="*Seyyathāpi, mahārāja, puriso ābādhiko assa dukkhito bāḷhagilāno; bhattañcassa nacchādeyya, na cassa kāye balamattā.**Suppose there was a person who was sick, suffering, gravely ill. They’d lose their appetite and get physically weak.*";
P_HTM[1122]="*So aparena samayena tamhā ābādhā mucceyya; bhattaṃ cassa chādeyya, siyā cassa kāye balamattā.**But after some time they’d recover from that illness, and regain their appetite and their strength.*";
P_HTM[1123]="*Tassa evamassa:**Thinking about this,*";
P_HTM[1124]="*‘ahaṃ kho pubbe ābādhiko ahosiṃ dukkhito bāḷhagilāno;* **";
P_HTM[1125]="*bhattañca me nacchādesi, na ca me āsi kāye balamattā.* **";
P_HTM[1126]="*Somhi etarahi tamhā ābādhā mutto;* **";
P_HTM[1127]="*bhattañca me chādeti, atthi ca me kāye balamattā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1128]="*So tatonidānaṃ labhetha pāmojjaṃ, adhigaccheyya somanassaṃ.**they’d be filled with joy and happiness.*";
P_HTM[1129]="*Seyyathāpi, mahārāja, puriso bandhanāgāre baddho assa.**Suppose a person was imprisoned in a jail.*";
P_HTM[1130]="*So aparena samayena tamhā bandhanāgārā mucceyya sotthinā abbhayena, na cassa kiñci bhogānaṃ vayo.**But after some time they were released from jail, safe and sound, with no loss of wealth.*";
P_HTM[1131]="*Tassa evamassa:**Thinking about this,*";
P_HTM[1132]="*‘ahaṃ kho pubbe bandhanāgāre baddho ahosiṃ, somhi etarahi tamhā bandhanāgārā mutto sotthinā abbhayena.* **";
P_HTM[1133]="*Natthi ca me kiñci bhogānaṃ vayo’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1134]="*So tatonidānaṃ labhetha pāmojjaṃ, adhigaccheyya somanassaṃ.**they’d be filled with joy and happiness.*";
P_HTM[1135]="*Seyyathāpi, mahārāja, puriso dāso assa anattādhīno parādhīno na yenakāmaṅgamo.**Suppose a person was a bondservant. They belonged to someone else and were unable to go where they wish.*";
P_HTM[1136]="*So aparena samayena tamhā dāsabyā mucceyya attādhīno aparādhīno bhujisso yenakāmaṅgamo.**But after some time they’d be freed from servitude and become their own master, an emancipated individual able to go where they wish.*";
P_HTM[1137]="*Tassa evamassa:**Thinking about this,*";
P_HTM[1138]="*‘ahaṃ kho pubbe dāso ahosiṃ anattādhīno parādhīno na yenakāmaṅgamo.* **";
P_HTM[1139]="*Somhi etarahi tamhā dāsabyā mutto attādhīno aparādhīno bhujisso yenakāmaṅgamo’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1140]="*So tatonidānaṃ labhetha pāmojjaṃ, adhigaccheyya somanassaṃ.**they’d be filled with joy and happiness.*";
P_HTM[1141]="*Seyyathāpi, mahārāja, puriso sadhano sabhogo kantāraddhānamaggaṃ paṭipajjeyya dubbhikkhaṃ sappaṭibhayaṃ.**Suppose there was a person with wealth and property who was traveling along a desert road, which was perilous, with nothing to eat.*";
P_HTM[1142]="*So aparena samayena taṃ kantāraṃ nitthareyya sotthinā, gāmantaṃ anupāpuṇeyya khemaṃ appaṭibhayaṃ.**But after some time they crossed over the desert safely, reaching the neighborhood of a village, a sanctuary free of peril.*";
P_HTM[1143]="*Tassa evamassa:**Thinking about this,*";
P_HTM[1144]="*‘ahaṃ kho pubbe sadhano sabhogo kantāraddhānamaggaṃ paṭipajjiṃ dubbhikkhaṃ sappaṭibhayaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1145]="*Somhi etarahi taṃ kantāraṃ nitthiṇṇo sotthinā, gāmantaṃ anuppatto khemaṃ appaṭibhayan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1146]="*So tatonidānaṃ labhetha pāmojjaṃ, adhigaccheyya somanassaṃ.**they’d be filled with joy and happiness.*";
P_HTM[1147]="*Evameva kho, mahārāja, bhikkhu yathā iṇaṃ yathā rogaṃ yathā bandhanāgāraṃ yathā dāsabyaṃ yathā kantāraddhānamaggaṃ, evaṃ ime pañca nīvaraṇe appahīne attani samanupassati.**In the same way, as long as these five hindrances are not given up inside themselves, a mendicant regards them thus as a debt, a disease, a prison, slavery, and a desert crossing.*";
P_HTM[1148]="*Seyyathāpi, mahārāja, yathā āṇaṇyaṃ yathā ārogyaṃ yathā bandhanāmokkhaṃ yathā bhujissaṃ yathā khemantabhūmiṃ;**But when these five hindrances are given up inside themselves, a mendicant regards this as freedom from debt, good health, release from prison, emancipation, and sanctuary.*";
P_HTM[1149]="*evameva kho, mahārāja, bhikkhu ime pañca nīvaraṇe pahīne attani samanupassati.* **";
P_HTM[1150]="*Tassime pañca nīvaraṇe pahīne attani samanupassato pāmojjaṃ jāyati, pamuditassa pīti jāyati, pītimanassa kāyo passambhati, passaddhakāyo sukhaṃ vedeti, sukhino cittaṃ samādhiyati.**Seeing that the hindrances have been given up in them, joy springs up. Being joyful, rapture springs up. When the mind is full of rapture, the body becomes tranquil. When the body is tranquil, they feel bliss. And when blissful, the mind becomes immersed.*";
P_HTM[1151]="*4.3.2.5. Paṭhamajhāna**4.3.2.5. First Absorption*";
P_HTM[1152]="*So vivicceva kāmehi, vivicca akusalehi dhammehi savitakkaṃ savicāraṃ vivekajaṃ pītisukhaṃ paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, they enter and remain in the first absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of seclusion, while placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[1153]="*So imameva kāyaṃ vivekajena pītisukhena abhisandeti parisandeti paripūreti parippharati, nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa vivekajena pītisukhena apphuṭaṃ hoti.**They drench, steep, fill, and spread their body with rapture and bliss born of seclusion. There’s no part of the body that’s not spread with rapture and bliss born of seclusion.*";
P_HTM[1154]="*Seyyathāpi, mahārāja, dakkho nhāpako vā nhāpakantevāsī vā kaṃsathāle nhānīyacuṇṇāni ākiritvā udakena paripphosakaṃ paripphosakaṃ sanneyya, sāyaṃ nhānīyapiṇḍi snehānugatā snehaparetā santarabāhirā phuṭā snehena, na ca paggharaṇī;**It’s like when a deft bathroom attendant or their apprentice pours bath powder into a bronze dish, sprinkling it little by little with water. They knead it until the ball of bath powder is soaked and saturated with moisture, spread through inside and out; yet no moisture oozes out.*";
P_HTM[1155]="*evameva kho, mahārāja, bhikkhu imameva kāyaṃ vivekajena pītisukhena abhisandeti parisandeti paripūreti parippharati, nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa vivekajena pītisukhena apphuṭaṃ hoti.**In the same way, a mendicant drenches, steeps, fills, and spreads their body with rapture and bliss born of seclusion. There’s no part of the body that’s not spread with rapture and bliss born of seclusion.*";
P_HTM[1156]="*Idampi kho, mahārāja, sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ purimehi sandiṭṭhikehi sāmaññaphalehi abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca.**This, great king, is a fruit of the ascetic life that’s apparent in the present life which is better and finer than the former ones.*";
P_HTM[1157]="*4.3.2.6. Dutiyajhāna**4.3.2.6. Second Absorption*";
P_HTM[1158]="*Puna caparaṃ, mahārāja, bhikkhu vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā ajjhattaṃ sampasādanaṃ cetaso ekodibhāvaṃ avitakkaṃ avicāraṃ samādhijaṃ pītisukhaṃ dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, as the placing of the mind and keeping it connected are stilled, a mendicant enters and remains in the second absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of immersion, with internal clarity and confidence, and unified mind, without applying the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[1159]="*So imameva kāyaṃ samādhijena pītisukhena abhisandeti parisandeti paripūreti parippharati, nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa samādhijena pītisukhena apphuṭaṃ hoti.**In the same way, a mendicant drenches, steeps, fills, and spreads their body with rapture and bliss born of immersion. There’s no part of the body that’s not spread with rapture and bliss born of immersion.*";
P_HTM[1160]="*Seyyathāpi, mahārāja, udakarahado gambhīro ubbhidodako tassa nevassa puratthimāya disāya udakassa āyamukhaṃ, na dakkhiṇāya disāya udakassa āyamukhaṃ, na pacchimāya disāya udakassa āyamukhaṃ, na uttarāya disāya udakassa āyamukhaṃ, devo ca na kālena kālaṃ sammādhāraṃ anuppaveccheyya.**It’s like a deep lake fed by spring water. There’s no inlet to the east, west, north, or south, and no rainfall to replenish it from time to time.*";
P_HTM[1161]="*Atha kho tamhāva udakarahadā sītā vāridhārā ubbhijjitvā tameva udakarahadaṃ sītena vārinā abhisandeyya parisandeyya paripūreyya paripphareyya, nāssa kiñci sabbāvato udakarahadassa sītena vārinā apphuṭaṃ assa.**But the stream of cool water welling up in the lake drenches, steeps, fills, and spreads throughout the lake. There’s no part of the lake that’s not spread through with cool water.*";
P_HTM[1162]="*Evameva kho, mahārāja, bhikkhu imameva kāyaṃ samādhijena pītisukhena abhisandeti parisandeti paripūreti parippharati, nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa samādhijena pītisukhena apphuṭaṃ hoti.**In the same way, a mendicant drenches, steeps, fills, and spreads their body with rapture and bliss born of immersion. There’s no part of the body that’s not spread with rapture and bliss born of immersion.*";
P_HTM[1163]="*Idampi kho, mahārāja, sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ purimehi sandiṭṭhikehi sāmaññaphalehi abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca.**This too, great king, is a fruit of the ascetic life that’s apparent in the present life which is better and finer than the former ones.*";
P_HTM[1164]="*4.3.2.7. Tatiyajhāna**4.3.2.7. Third Absorption*";
P_HTM[1165]="*Puna caparaṃ, mahārāja, bhikkhu pītiyā ca virāgā upekkhako ca viharati sato sampajāno, sukhañca kāyena paṭisaṃvedeti, yaṃ taṃ ariyā ācikkhanti: ‘upekkhako satimā sukhavihārī’ti, tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, with the fading away of rapture, a mendicant enters and remains in the third absorption, where they meditate with equanimity, mindful and aware, personally experiencing the bliss of which the noble ones declare, ‘Equanimous and mindful, one meditates in bliss.’*";
P_HTM[1166]="*So imameva kāyaṃ nippītikena sukhena abhisandeti parisandeti paripūreti parippharati, nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa nippītikena sukhena apphuṭaṃ hoti.**They drench, steep, fill, and spread their body with bliss free of rapture. There’s no part of the body that’s not spread with bliss free of rapture.*";
P_HTM[1167]="*Seyyathāpi, mahārāja, uppaliniyaṃ vā paduminiyaṃ vā puṇḍarīkiniyaṃ vā appekaccāni uppalāni vā padumāni vā puṇḍarīkāni vā udake jātāni udake saṃvaḍḍhāni udakānuggatāni antonimuggaposīni, tāni yāva caggā yāva ca mūlā sītena vārinā abhisannāni parisannāni paripūrāni paripphuṭāni, nāssa kiñci sabbāvataṃ uppalānaṃ vā padumānaṃ vā puṇḍarīkānaṃ vā sītena vārinā apphuṭaṃ assa;**It’s like a pool with blue water lilies, or pink or white lotuses. Some of them sprout and grow in the water without rising above it, thriving underwater. From the tip to the root they’re drenched, steeped, filled, and soaked with cool water. There’s no part of them that’s not soaked with cool water.*";
P_HTM[1168]="*evameva kho, mahārāja, bhikkhu imameva kāyaṃ nippītikena sukhena abhisandeti parisandeti paripūreti parippharati, nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa nippītikena sukhena apphuṭaṃ hoti.**In the same way, a mendicant drenches, steeps, fills, and spreads their body with bliss free of rapture. There’s no part of the body that’s not spread with bliss free of rapture.*";
P_HTM[1169]="*Idampi kho, mahārāja, sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ purimehi sandiṭṭhikehi sāmaññaphalehi abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca.**This too, great king, is a fruit of the ascetic life that’s apparent in the present life which is better and finer than the former ones.*";
P_HTM[1170]="*4.3.2.8. Catutthajhāna**4.3.2.8. Fourth Absorption*";
P_HTM[1171]="*Puna caparaṃ, mahārāja, bhikkhu sukhassa ca pahānā dukkhassa ca pahānā, pubbeva somanassadomanassānaṃ atthaṅgamā adukkhamasukhaṃ upekkhāsatipārisuddhiṃ catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati, so imameva kāyaṃ parisuddhena cetasā pariyodātena pharitvā nisinno hoti, nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa parisuddhena cetasā pariyodātena apphuṭaṃ hoti.**Furthermore, giving up pleasure and pain, and ending former happiness and sadness, a mendicant enters and remains in the fourth absorption, without pleasure or pain, with pure equanimity and mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[1172]="*Seyyathāpi, mahārāja, puriso odātena vatthena sasīsaṃ pārupitvā nisinno assa, nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa odātena vatthena apphuṭaṃ assa;**It’s like someone sitting wrapped from head to foot with white cloth. There’s no part of the body that’s not spread over with white cloth.*";
P_HTM[1173]="*evameva kho, mahārāja, bhikkhu imameva kāyaṃ parisuddhena cetasā pariyodātena pharitvā nisinno hoti, nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa parisuddhena cetasā pariyodātena apphuṭaṃ hoti.**In the same way, they sit spreading their body through with pure bright mind. There’s no part of the body that’s not spread with pure bright mind.*";
P_HTM[1174]="*Idampi kho, mahārāja, sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ purimehi sandiṭṭhikehi sāmaññaphalehi abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca.**This too, great king, is a fruit of the ascetic life that’s apparent in the present life which is better and finer than the former ones.*";
P_HTM[1175]="*4.3.3. Aṭṭhañāṇa**4.3.3. The Eight Knowledges*";
P_HTM[1176]="*4.3.3.1. Vipassanāñāṇa**4.3.3.1. Knowledge and Vision*";
P_HTM[1177]="*So evaṃ samāhite citte parisuddhe pariyodāte anaṅgaṇe vigatūpakkilese mudubhūte kammaniye ṭhite āneñjappatte ñāṇadassanāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti.**When their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it and project it toward knowledge and vision.*";
P_HTM[1178]="*So evaṃ pajānāti:**They understand:*";
P_HTM[1179]="*‘ayaṃ kho me kāyo rūpī cātumahābhūtiko mātāpettikasambhavo odanakummāsūpacayo aniccucchādanaparimaddanabhedanaviddhaṃsanadhammo;**‘This body of mine is physical. It’s made up of the four primary elements, produced by mother and father, built up from rice and porridge, liable to impermanence, to wearing away and erosion, to breaking up and destruction.*";
P_HTM[1180]="*idañca pana me viññāṇaṃ ettha sitaṃ ettha paṭibaddhan’ti.**And this consciousness of mine is attached to it, tied to it.’*";
P_HTM[1181]="*Seyyathāpi, mahārāja, maṇi veḷuriyo subho jātimā aṭṭhaṃso suparikammakato accho vippasanno anāvilo sabbākārasampanno.**Suppose there was a beryl gem that was naturally beautiful, eight-faceted, well-worked, transparent, clear, and unclouded, endowed with all good qualities.*";
P_HTM[1182]="*Tatrāssa suttaṃ āvutaṃ nīlaṃ vā pītaṃ vā lohitaṃ vā odātaṃ vā paṇḍusuttaṃ vā.**And it was strung with a thread of blue, yellow, red, white, or golden brown.*";
P_HTM[1183]="*Tamenaṃ cakkhumā puriso hatthe karitvā paccavekkheyya:**And someone with good eyesight were to take it in their hand and check it:*";
P_HTM[1184]="*‘ayaṃ kho maṇi veḷuriyo subho jātimā aṭṭhaṃso suparikammakato accho vippasanno anāvilo sabbākārasampanno;**‘This beryl gem is naturally beautiful, eight-faceted, well-worked, transparent, clear, and unclouded, endowed with all good qualities.*";
P_HTM[1185]="*tatridaṃ suttaṃ āvutaṃ nīlaṃ vā pītaṃ vā lohitaṃ vā odātaṃ vā paṇḍusuttaṃ vā’ti.**And it’s strung with a thread of blue, yellow, red, white, or golden brown.’*";
P_HTM[1186]="*Evameva kho, mahārāja, bhikkhu evaṃ samāhite citte parisuddhe pariyodāte anaṅgaṇe vigatūpakkilese mudubhūte kammaniye ṭhite āneñjappatte ñāṇadassanāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti.**In the same way, when their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it and project it toward knowledge and vision.*";
P_HTM[1187]="*So evaṃ pajānāti:* **";
P_HTM[1188]="*‘ayaṃ kho me kāyo rūpī cātumahābhūtiko mātāpettikasambhavo odanakummāsūpacayo aniccucchādanaparimaddanabhedanaviddhaṃsanadhammo;* **";
P_HTM[1189]="*idañca pana me viññāṇaṃ ettha sitaṃ ettha paṭibaddhan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1190]="*Idampi kho, mahārāja, sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ purimehi sandiṭṭhikehi sāmaññaphalehi abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca.**This too, great king, is a fruit of the ascetic life that’s apparent in the present life which is better and finer than the former ones.*";
P_HTM[1191]="*4.3.3.2. ­Manoma­yiddhi­ñāṇa**4.3.3.2. Mind-Made Body*";
P_HTM[1192]="*So evaṃ samāhite citte parisuddhe pariyodāte anaṅgaṇe vigatūpakkilese mudubhūte kammaniye ṭhite āneñjappatte manomayaṃ kāyaṃ abhinimmānāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti.**When their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it and project it toward the creation of a mind-made body.*";
P_HTM[1193]="*So imamhā kāyā aññaṃ kāyaṃ abhinimmināti rūpiṃ manomayaṃ sabbaṅgapaccaṅgiṃ ahīnindriyaṃ.**From this body they create another body, physical, mind-made, complete in all its various parts, not deficient in any faculty.*";
P_HTM[1194]="*Seyyathāpi, mahārāja, puriso muñjamhā īsikaṃ pavāheyya.**Suppose a person was to draw a reed out from its sheath.*";
P_HTM[1195]="*Tassa evamassa:**They’d think:*";
P_HTM[1196]="*‘ayaṃ muñjo, ayaṃ īsikā, añño muñjo, aññā īsikā, muñjamhā tveva īsikā pavāḷhā’ti.**‘This is the reed, this is the sheath. The reed and the sheath are different things. The reed has been drawn out from the sheath.’*";
P_HTM[1197]="*Seyyathā vā pana, mahārāja, puriso asiṃ kosiyā pavāheyya.**Or suppose a person was to draw a sword out from its scabbard.*";
P_HTM[1198]="*Tassa evamassa:**They’d think:*";
P_HTM[1199]="*‘ayaṃ asi, ayaṃ kosi, añño asi, aññā kosi, kosiyā tveva asi pavāḷho’ti.**‘This is the sword, this is the scabbard. The sword and the scabbard are different things. The sword has been drawn out from the scabbard.’*";
P_HTM[1200]="*Seyyathā vā pana, mahārāja, puriso ahiṃ karaṇḍā uddhareyya.**Or suppose a person was to draw a snake out from its slough.*";
P_HTM[1201]="*Tassa evamassa:**They’d think:*";
P_HTM[1202]="*‘ayaṃ ahi, ayaṃ karaṇḍo. Añño ahi, añño karaṇḍo, karaṇḍā tveva ahi ubbhato’ti.**‘This is the snake, this is the slough. The snake and the slough are different things. The snake has been drawn out from the slough.’*";
P_HTM[1203]="*Evameva kho, mahārāja, bhikkhu evaṃ samāhite citte parisuddhe pariyodāte anaṅgaṇe vigatūpakkilese mudubhūte kammaniye ṭhite āneñjappatte manomayaṃ kāyaṃ abhinimmānāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti.**In the same way, when their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it and project it toward the creation of a mind-made body.*";
P_HTM[1204]="*So imamhā kāyā aññaṃ kāyaṃ abhinimmināti rūpiṃ manomayaṃ sabbaṅgapaccaṅgiṃ ahīnindriyaṃ.**From this body they create another body, physical, mind-made, complete in all its various parts, not deficient in any faculty.*";
P_HTM[1205]="*Idampi kho, mahārāja, sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ purimehi sandiṭṭhikehi sāmaññaphalehi abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca.**This too, great king, is a fruit of the ascetic life that’s apparent in the present life which is better and finer than the former ones.*";
P_HTM[1206]="*4.3.3.3. Iddhividhañāṇa**4.3.3.3. Psychic Powers*";
P_HTM[1207]="*So evaṃ samāhite citte parisuddhe pariyodāte anaṅgaṇe vigatūpakkilese mudubhūte kammaniye ṭhite āneñjappatte iddhividhāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti.**When their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it and project it toward psychic power.*";
P_HTM[1208]="*So anekavihitaṃ iddhividhaṃ paccanubhoti—ekopi hutvā bahudhā hoti, bahudhāpi hutvā eko hoti; āvibhāvaṃ tirobhāvaṃ tirokuṭṭaṃ tiropākāraṃ tiropabbataṃ asajjamāno gacchati seyyathāpi ākāse; pathaviyāpi ummujjanimujjaṃ karoti seyyathāpi udake; udakepi abhijjamāne gacchati seyyathāpi pathaviyā; ākāsepi pallaṅkena kamati seyyathāpi pakkhī sakuṇo; imepi candimasūriye evaṃmahiddhike evaṃmahānubhāve pāṇinā parāmasati parimajjati; yāva brahmalokāpi kāyena vasaṃ vatteti.**They wield the many kinds of psychic power: multiplying themselves and becoming one again; going unimpeded through a wall, a rampart, or a mountain as if through space; diving in and out of the earth as if it were water; walking on water as if it were earth; flying cross-legged through the sky like a bird; touching and stroking with the hand the sun and moon, so mighty and powerful; controlling the body as far as the Brahmā realm.*";
P_HTM[1209]="*Seyyathāpi, mahārāja, dakkho kumbhakāro vā kumbhakārantevāsī vā suparikammakatāya mattikāya yaṃ yadeva bhājanavikatiṃ ākaṅkheyya, taṃ tadeva kareyya abhinipphādeyya.**Suppose an expert potter or their apprentice had some well-prepared clay. They could produce any kind of pot that they like.*";
P_HTM[1210]="*Seyyathā vā pana, mahārāja, dakkho dantakāro vā dantakārantevāsī vā suparikammakatasmiṃ dantasmiṃ yaṃ yadeva dantavikatiṃ ākaṅkheyya, taṃ tadeva kareyya abhinipphādeyya.**Or suppose a deft ivory-carver or their apprentice had some well-prepared ivory. They could produce any kind of ivory item that they like.*";
P_HTM[1211]="*Seyyathā vā pana, mahārāja, dakkho suvaṇṇakāro vā suvaṇṇakārantevāsī vā suparikammakatasmiṃ suvaṇṇasmiṃ yaṃ yadeva suvaṇṇavikatiṃ ākaṅkheyya, taṃ tadeva kareyya abhinipphādeyya.**Or suppose a deft goldsmith or their apprentice had some well-prepared gold. They could produce any kind of gold item that they like.*";
P_HTM[1212]="*Evameva kho, mahārāja, bhikkhu evaṃ samāhite citte parisuddhe pariyodāte anaṅgaṇe vigatūpakkilese mudubhūte kammaniye ṭhite āneñjappatte iddhividhāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti.**In the same way, when their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it and project it toward psychic power.*";
P_HTM[1213]="*So anekavihitaṃ iddhividhaṃ paccanubhoti—ekopi hutvā bahudhā hoti, bahudhāpi hutvā eko hoti; āvibhāvaṃ tirobhāvaṃ tirokuṭṭaṃ tiropākāraṃ tiropabbataṃ asajjamāno gacchati seyyathāpi ākāse; pathaviyāpi ummujjanimujjaṃ karoti seyyathāpi udake; udakepi abhijjamāne gacchati seyyathāpi pathaviyā; ākāsepi pallaṅkena kamati seyyathāpi pakkhī sakuṇo; imepi candimasūriye evaṃmahiddhike evaṃmahānubhāve pāṇinā parāmasati parimajjati; yāva brahmalokāpi kāyena vasaṃ vatteti.* **";
P_HTM[1214]="*Idampi kho, mahārāja, sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ purimehi sandiṭṭhikehi sāmaññaphalehi abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca.**This too, great king, is a fruit of the ascetic life that’s apparent in the present life which is better and finer than the former ones.*";
P_HTM[1215]="*4.3.3.4. Dibbasotañāṇa**4.3.3.4. Clairaudience*";
P_HTM[1216]="*So evaṃ samāhite citte parisuddhe pariyodāte anaṅgaṇe vigatūpakkilese mudubhūte kammaniye ṭhite āneñjappatte dibbāya sotadhātuyā cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti.**When their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it and project it toward clairaudience.*";
P_HTM[1217]="*So dibbāya sotadhātuyā visuddhāya atikkantamānusikāya ubho sadde suṇāti dibbe ca mānuse ca ye dūre santike ca.**With clairaudience that is purified and superhuman, they hear both kinds of sounds, human and divine, whether near or far.*";
P_HTM[1218]="*Seyyathāpi, mahārāja, puriso addhānamaggappaṭipanno. So suṇeyya bherisaddampi mudiṅgasaddampi saṅkhapaṇavadindimasaddampi. Tassa evamassa: ‘bherisaddo’ itipi, ‘mudiṅgasaddo’ itipi, ‘saṅkhapaṇavadindimasaddo’ itipi.**Suppose there was a person traveling along the road. They’d hear the sound of drums, clay drums, horns, kettledrums, and tom-toms. They’d think: ‘That’s the sound of drums,’ and ‘that’s the sound of clay-drums,’ and ‘that’s the sound of horns, kettledrums, and tom-toms.’*";
P_HTM[1219]="*Evameva kho, mahārāja, bhikkhu evaṃ samāhite citte parisuddhe pariyodāte anaṅgaṇe vigatūpakkilese mudubhūte kammaniye ṭhite āneñjappatte dibbāya sotadhātuyā cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti.**In the same way, when their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it and project it toward clairaudience.*";
P_HTM[1220]="*So dibbāya sotadhātuyā visuddhāya atikkantamānusikāya ubho sadde suṇāti dibbe ca mānuse ca ye dūre santike ca.**With clairaudience that is purified and superhuman, they hear both kinds of sounds, human and divine, whether near or far.*";
P_HTM[1221]="*Idampi kho, mahārāja, sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ purimehi sandiṭṭhikehi sāmaññaphalehi abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca.**This too, great king, is a fruit of the ascetic life that’s apparent in the present life which is better and finer than the former ones.*";
P_HTM[1222]="*4.3.3.5. Cetopariyañāṇa**4.3.3.5. Comprehending the Minds of Others*";
P_HTM[1223]="*So evaṃ samāhite citte parisuddhe pariyodāte anaṅgaṇe vigatūpakkilese mudubhūte kammaniye ṭhite āneñjappatte cetopariyañāṇāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti.**When their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it and project it toward comprehending the minds of others.*";
P_HTM[1224]="*So parasattānaṃ parapuggalānaṃ cetasā ceto paricca pajānāti—sarāgaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘sarāgaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, vītarāgaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘vītarāgaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, sadosaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘sadosaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, vītadosaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘vītadosaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, samohaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘samohaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, vītamohaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘vītamohaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, saṅkhittaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘saṅkhittaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, vikkhittaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘vikkhittaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, mahaggataṃ vā cittaṃ ‘mahaggataṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, amahaggataṃ vā cittaṃ ‘amahaggataṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, sauttaraṃ vā cittaṃ ‘sauttaraṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, anuttaraṃ vā cittaṃ ‘anuttaraṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, samāhitaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘samāhitaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, asamāhitaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘asamāhitaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, vimuttaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘vimuttaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, avimuttaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘avimuttaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti.**They understand the minds of other beings and individuals, having comprehended them with their own mind. They understand mind with greed as ‘mind with greed’, and mind without greed as ‘mind without greed’. They understand mind with hate … mind without hate … mind with delusion … mind without delusion … constricted mind … scattered mind … expansive mind … unexpansive mind … mind that is not supreme … mind that is supreme … immersed mind … unimmersed mind … freed mind … They understand unfreed mind as ‘unfreed mind’.*";
P_HTM[1225]="*Seyyathāpi, mahārāja, itthī vā puriso vā daharo yuvā maṇḍanajātiko ādāse vā parisuddhe pariyodāte acche vā udakapatte sakaṃ mukhanimittaṃ paccavekkhamāno sakaṇikaṃ vā ‘sakaṇikan’ti jāneyya, akaṇikaṃ vā ‘akaṇikan’ti jāneyya;**Suppose there was a woman or man who was young, youthful, and fond of adornments, and they check their own reflection in a clean bright mirror or a clear bowl of water. If they had a spot they’d know ‘I have a spot,’ and if they had no spots they’d know ‘I have no spots.’*";
P_HTM[1226]="*evameva kho, mahārāja, bhikkhu evaṃ samāhite citte parisuddhe pariyodāte anaṅgaṇe vigatūpakkilese mudubhūte kammaniye ṭhite āneñjappatte cetopariyañāṇāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti.**In the same way, when their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it and project it toward comprehending the minds of others.*";
P_HTM[1227]="*So parasattānaṃ parapuggalānaṃ cetasā ceto paricca pajānāti—sarāgaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘sarāgaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, vītarāgaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘vītarāgaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, sadosaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘sadosaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, vītadosaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘vītadosaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, samohaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘samohaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, vītamohaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘vītamohaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, saṅkhittaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘saṅkhittaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, vikkhittaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘vikkhittaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, mahaggataṃ vā cittaṃ ‘mahaggataṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, amahaggataṃ vā cittaṃ ‘amahaggataṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, sauttaraṃ vā cittaṃ ‘sauttaraṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, anuttaraṃ vā cittaṃ ‘anuttaraṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, samāhitaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘samāhitaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, asamāhitaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘asamāhitaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, vimuttaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘vimuttaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, avimuttaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘avimuttaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti.**They understand the minds of other beings and individuals, having comprehended them with their own mind.*";
P_HTM[1228]="*Idampi kho, mahārāja, sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ purimehi sandiṭṭhikehi sāmaññaphalehi abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca.**This too, great king, is a fruit of the ascetic life that’s apparent in the present life which is better and finer than the former ones.*";
P_HTM[1229]="*4.3.3.6. Pubbe­nivāsā­nus­sati­ñāṇa**4.3.3.6. Recollection of Past Lives*";
P_HTM[1230]="*So evaṃ samāhite citte parisuddhe pariyodāte anaṅgaṇe vigatūpakkilese mudubhūte kammaniye ṭhite āneñjappatte pubbenivāsānussatiñāṇāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti.**When their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it and project it toward recollection of past lives.*";
P_HTM[1231]="*So anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati, seyyathidaṃ—ekampi jātiṃ dvepi jātiyo tissopi jātiyo catassopi jātiyo pañcapi jātiyo dasapi jātiyo vīsampi jātiyo tiṃsampi jātiyo cattālīsampi jātiyo paññāsampi jātiyo jātisatampi jātisahassampi jātisatasahassampi anekepi saṃvaṭṭakappe anekepi vivaṭṭakappe anekepi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭakappe, ‘amutrāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṅgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto, so tato cuto amutra udapādiṃ; tatrāpāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṅgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto, so tato cuto idhūpapanno’ti. Iti sākāraṃ sauddesaṃ anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati.**They recollect many kinds of past lives, that is, one, two, three, four, five, ten, twenty, thirty, forty, fifty, a hundred, a thousand, a hundred thousand rebirths; many eons of the world contracting, many eons of the world expanding, many eons of the world contracting and expanding. They remember: ‘There, I was named this, my clan was that, I looked like this, and that was my food. This was how I felt pleasure and pain, and that was how my life ended. When I passed away from that place I was reborn somewhere else. There, too, I was named this, my clan was that, I looked like this, and that was my food. This was how I felt pleasure and pain, and that was how my life ended. When I passed away from that place I was reborn here.’ And so they recollect their many kinds of past lives, with features and details.*";
P_HTM[1232]="*Seyyathāpi, mahārāja, puriso sakamhā gāmā aññaṃ gāmaṃ gaccheyya, tamhāpi gāmā aññaṃ gāmaṃ gaccheyya. So tamhā gāmā sakaṃyeva gāmaṃ paccāgaccheyya. Tassa evamassa: ‘ahaṃ kho sakamhā gāmā amuṃ gāmaṃ agacchiṃ, tatra evaṃ aṭṭhāsiṃ, evaṃ nisīdiṃ, evaṃ abhāsiṃ, evaṃ tuṇhī ahosiṃ, tamhāpi gāmā amuṃ gāmaṃ agacchiṃ, tatrāpi evaṃ aṭṭhāsiṃ, evaṃ nisīdiṃ, evaṃ abhāsiṃ, evaṃ tuṇhī ahosiṃ, somhi tamhā gāmā sakaṃyeva gāmaṃ paccāgato’ti.**Suppose a person was to leave their home village and go to another village. From that village they’d go to yet another village. And from that village they’d return to their home village. They’d think: ‘I went from my home village to another village. There I stood like this, sat like that, spoke like this, or kept silent like that. From that village I went to yet another village. There too I stood like this, sat like that, spoke like this, or kept silent like that. And from that village I returned to my home village.’*";
P_HTM[1233]="*Evameva kho, mahārāja, bhikkhu evaṃ samāhite citte parisuddhe pariyodāte anaṅgaṇe vigatūpakkilese mudubhūte kammaniye ṭhite āneñjappatte pubbenivāsānussatiñāṇāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti.**In the same way, when their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it and project it toward recollection of past lives.*";
P_HTM[1234]="*So anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati, seyyathidaṃ—ekampi jātiṃ dvepi jātiyo tissopi jātiyo catassopi jātiyo pañcapi jātiyo dasapi jātiyo vīsampi jātiyo tiṃsampi jātiyo cattālīsampi jātiyo paññāsampi jātiyo jātisatampi jātisahassampi jātisatasahassampi anekepi saṃvaṭṭakappe anekepi vivaṭṭakappe anekepi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭakappe, ‘amutrāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṃgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto, so tato cuto amutra udapādiṃ; tatrāpāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṃgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto, so tato cuto idhūpapanno’ti. Iti sākāraṃ sauddesaṃ anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati.* **";
P_HTM[1235]="*Idampi kho, mahārāja, sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ purimehi sandiṭṭhikehi sāmaññaphalehi abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca.**This too, great king, is a fruit of the ascetic life that’s apparent in the present life which is better and finer than the former ones.*";
P_HTM[1236]="*4.3.3.7. Dibba­cak­khu­ñāṇa**4.3.3.7. Clairvoyance*";
P_HTM[1237]="*So evaṃ samāhite citte parisuddhe pariyodāte anaṅgaṇe vigatūpakkilese mudubhūte kammaniye ṭhite āneñjappatte sattānaṃ cutūpapātañāṇāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti.**When their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it and project it toward knowledge of the death and rebirth of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[1238]="*So dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena satte passati cavamāne upapajjamāne hīne paṇīte suvaṇṇe dubbaṇṇe sugate duggate, yathākammūpage satte pajānāti: ‘ime vata bhonto sattā kāyaduccaritena samannāgatā vacīduccaritena samannāgatā manoduccaritena samannāgatā ariyānaṃ upavādakā micchādiṭṭhikā micchādiṭṭhikammasamādānā. Te kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapannā. Ime vā pana bhonto sattā kāyasucaritena samannāgatā vacīsucaritena samannāgatā manosucaritena samannāgatā ariyānaṃ anupavādakā sammādiṭṭhikā sammādiṭṭhikammasamādānā, te kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapannā’ti. Iti dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena satte passati cavamāne upapajjamāne hīne paṇīte suvaṇṇe dubbaṇṇe sugate duggate, yathākammūpage satte pajānāti.**With clairvoyance that is purified and superhuman, they see sentient beings passing away and being reborn—inferior and superior, beautiful and ugly, in a good place or a bad place. They understand how sentient beings are reborn according to their deeds: ‘These dear beings did bad things by way of body, speech, and mind. They spoke ill of the noble ones; they had wrong view; and they acted out of that wrong view. When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell. These dear beings, however, did good things by way of body, speech, and mind. They never spoke ill of the noble ones; they had right view; and they acted out of that right view. When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.’ And so, with clairvoyance that is purified and superhuman, they see sentient beings passing away and being reborn—inferior and superior, beautiful and ugly, in a good place or a bad place. They understand how sentient beings are reborn according to their deeds.*";
P_HTM[1239]="*Seyyathāpi, mahārāja, majjhe siṅghāṭake pāsādo. Tattha cakkhumā puriso ṭhito passeyya manusse gehaṃ pavisantepi nikkhamantepi rathikāyapi vīthiṃ sañcarante majjhe siṅghāṭake nisinnepi. Tassa evamassa: ‘ete manussā gehaṃ pavisanti, ete nikkhamanti, ete rathikāya vīthiṃ sañcaranti, ete majjhe siṅghāṭake nisinnā’ti.**Suppose there was a stilt longhouse at the central square. A person with good eyesight standing there might see people entering and leaving a house, walking along the streets and paths, and sitting at the central square. They’d think: ‘These are people entering and leaving a house, walking along the streets and paths, and sitting at the central square.’*";
P_HTM[1240]="*Evameva kho, mahārāja, bhikkhu evaṃ samāhite citte parisuddhe pariyodāte anaṅgaṇe vigatūpakkilese mudubhūte kammaniye ṭhite āneñjappatte sattānaṃ cutūpapātañāṇāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti.**In the same way, when their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend and project it toward knowledge of the death and rebirth of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[1241]="*So dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena satte passati cavamāne upapajjamāne hīne paṇīte suvaṇṇe dubbaṇṇe sugate duggate, yathākammūpage satte pajānāti: ‘ime vata bhonto sattā kāyaduccaritena samannāgatā vacīduccaritena samannāgatā manoduccaritena samannāgatā ariyānaṃ upavādakā micchādiṭṭhikā micchādiṭṭhikammasamādānā, te kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapannā. Ime vā pana bhonto sattā kāyasucaritena samannāgatā vacīsucaritena samannāgatā manosucaritena samannāgatā ariyānaṃ anupavādakā sammādiṭṭhikā sammādiṭṭhikammasamādānā. Te kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapannā’ti. Iti dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena satte passati cavamāne upapajjamāne hīne paṇīte suvaṇṇe dubbaṇṇe sugate duggate; yathākammūpage satte pajānāti.* **";
P_HTM[1242]="*Idampi kho, mahārāja, sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ purimehi sandiṭṭhikehi sāmaññaphalehi abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca.**This too, great king, is a fruit of the ascetic life that’s apparent in the present life which is better and finer than the former ones.*";
P_HTM[1243]="*4.3.3.8. Āsa­vak­kha­ya­ñāṇa**4.3.3.8. Ending of Defilements*";
P_HTM[1244]="*So evaṃ samāhite citte parisuddhe pariyodāte anaṅgaṇe vigatūpakkilese mudubhūte kammaniye ṭhite āneñjappatte āsavānaṃ khayañāṇāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti.**When their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it and project it toward knowledge of the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[1245]="*So idaṃ dukkhanti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ayaṃ dukkhasamudayoti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ayaṃ dukkhanirodhoti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadāti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**They truly understand: ‘This is suffering’ … ‘This is the origin of suffering’ … ‘This is the cessation of suffering’ … ‘This is the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering’.*";
P_HTM[1246]="*Ime āsavāti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ayaṃ āsavasamudayoti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ayaṃ āsavanirodhoti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ayaṃ āsavanirodhagāminī paṭipadāti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**They truly understand: ‘These are defilements’ … ‘This is the origin of defilements’ … ‘This is the cessation of defilements’ … ‘This is the practice that leads to the cessation of defilements’.*";
P_HTM[1247]="*Tassa evaṃ jānato evaṃ passato kāmāsavāpi cittaṃ vimuccati, bhavāsavāpi cittaṃ vimuccati, avijjāsavāpi cittaṃ vimuccati,**Knowing and seeing like this, their mind is freed from the defilements of sensuality, desire to be reborn, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[1248]="*vimuttasmiṃ ‘vimuttam’iti ñāṇaṃ hoti,**When they’re freed, they know they’re freed.*";
P_HTM[1249]="*‘khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānāti.**They understand: ‘Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.’*";
P_HTM[1250]="*Seyyathāpi, mahārāja, pabbatasaṅkhepe udakarahado accho vippasanno anāvilo. Tattha cakkhumā puriso tīre ṭhito passeyya sippisambukampi sakkharakathalampi macchagumbampi carantampi tiṭṭhantampi. Tassa evamassa: ‘ayaṃ kho udakarahado accho vippasanno anāvilo. Tatrime sippisambukāpi sakkharakathalāpi macchagumbāpi carantipi tiṭṭhantipī’ti.**Suppose that in a mountain glen there was a lake that was transparent, clear, and unclouded. A person with good eyesight standing on the bank would see the mussel shells, gravel and pebbles, and schools of fish swimming about or staying still. They’d think: ‘This lake is transparent, clear, and unclouded. And here are the mussel shells, gravel and pebbles, and schools of fish swimming about or staying still.’*";
P_HTM[1251]="*Evameva kho, mahārāja, bhikkhu evaṃ samāhite citte parisuddhe pariyodāte anaṅgaṇe vigatūpakkilese mudubhūte kammaniye ṭhite āneñjappatte āsavānaṃ khayañāṇāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti.**In the same way, when their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it and project it toward knowledge of the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[1252]="*‘So idaṃ dukkhan’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhasamudayo’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodho’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ‘ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.* **";
P_HTM[1253]="*‘Ime āsavā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ‘ayaṃ āsavasamudayo’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ‘ayaṃ āsavanirodho’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ‘ayaṃ āsavanirodhagāminī paṭipadā’ti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.* **";
P_HTM[1254]="*Tassa evaṃ jānato evaṃ passato kāmāsavāpi cittaṃ vimuccati, bhavāsavāpi cittaṃ vimuccati, avijjāsavāpi cittaṃ vimuccati,* **";
P_HTM[1255]="*vimuttasmiṃ ‘vimuttam’iti ñāṇaṃ hoti,* **";
P_HTM[1256]="*‘khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānāti.* **";
P_HTM[1257]="*Idaṃ kho, mahārāja, sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ purimehi sandiṭṭhikehi sāmaññaphalehi abhikkantatarañca paṇītatarañca.**This too, great king, is a fruit of the ascetic life that’s apparent in the present life which is better and finer than the former ones.*";
P_HTM[1258]="*Imasmā ca pana, mahārāja, sandiṭṭhikā sāmaññaphalā aññaṃ sandiṭṭhikaṃ sāmaññaphalaṃ uttaritaraṃ vā paṇītataraṃ vā natthī”ti.**And, great king, there is no other fruit of the ascetic life apparent in the present life which is better and finer than this.”*";
P_HTM[1259]="*5. Ajātasattuupāsakattapaṭivedanā**5. Ajātasattu Declares Himself a Lay Follower*";
P_HTM[1260]="*Evaṃ vutte, rājā māgadho ajātasattu vedehiputto bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When the Buddha had spoken, King Ajātasattu said to him,*";
P_HTM[1261]="*“abhikkantaṃ, bhante, abhikkantaṃ, bhante.**“Excellent, sir! Excellent!*";
P_HTM[1262]="*Seyyathāpi, bhante, nikkujjitaṃ vā ukkujjeyya, paṭicchannaṃ vā vivareyya, mūḷhassa vā maggaṃ ācikkheyya, andhakāre vā telapajjotaṃ dhāreyya: ‘cakkhumanto rūpāni dakkhantī’ti; evamevaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā anekapariyāyena dhammo pakāsito.**As if he were righting the overturned, or revealing the hidden, or pointing out the path to the lost, or lighting a lamp in the dark so people with good eyes can see what’s there, the Buddha has made the teaching clear in many ways.*";
P_HTM[1263]="*Esāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavantaṃ saraṇaṃ gacchāmi dhammañca bhikkhusaṅghañca.**I go for refuge to the Buddha, to the teaching, and to the mendicant Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[1264]="*Upāsakaṃ maṃ bhagavā dhāretu ajjatagge pāṇupetaṃ saraṇaṃ gataṃ.**From this day forth, may the Buddha remember me as a lay follower who has gone for refuge for life.*";
P_HTM[1265]="*Accayo maṃ, bhante, accagamā yathābālaṃ yathāmūḷhaṃ yathāakusalaṃ, yohaṃ pitaraṃ dhammikaṃ dhammarājānaṃ issariyakāraṇā jīvitā voropesiṃ.**I have made a mistake, sir. It was foolish, stupid, and unskillful of me to take the life of my father, a just and principled king, for the sake of authority.*";
P_HTM[1266]="*Tassa me, bhante bhagavā, accayaṃ accayato paṭiggaṇhātu āyatiṃ saṃvarāyā”ti.**Please, sir, accept my mistake for what it is, so I will restrain myself in future.”*";
P_HTM[1267]="*“Taggha tvaṃ, mahārāja, accayo accagamā yathābālaṃ yathāmūḷhaṃ yathāakusalaṃ, yaṃ tvaṃ pitaraṃ dhammikaṃ dhammarājānaṃ jīvitā voropesi.**“Indeed, great king, you made a mistake. It was foolish, stupid, and unskillful of you to take the life of your father, a just and principled king, for the sake of sovereignty.*";
P_HTM[1268]="*Yato ca kho tvaṃ, mahārāja, accayaṃ accayato disvā yathādhammaṃ paṭikarosi, taṃ te mayaṃ paṭiggaṇhāma.**But since you have recognized your mistake for what it is, and have dealt with it properly, I accept it.*";
P_HTM[1269]="*Vuddhihesā, mahārāja, ariyassa vinaye, yo accayaṃ accayato disvā yathādhammaṃ paṭikaroti, āyatiṃ saṃvaraṃ āpajjatī”ti.**For it is growth in the training of the noble one to recognize a mistake for what it is, deal with it properly, and commit to restraint in the future.”*";
P_HTM[1270]="*Evaṃ vutte, rājā māgadho ajātasattu vedehiputto bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When the Buddha had spoken, King Ajātasattu said to him,*";
P_HTM[1271]="*“handa ca dāni mayaṃ, bhante, gacchāma bahukiccā mayaṃ bahukaraṇīyā”ti.**“Well, now, sir, I must go. I have many duties, and much to do.”*";
P_HTM[1272]="*“Yassadāni tvaṃ, mahārāja, kālaṃ maññasī”ti.**“Please, great king, go at your convenience.”*";
P_HTM[1273]="*Atha kho rājā māgadho ajātasattu vedehiputto bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinanditvā anumoditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā pakkāmi.**Then the king, having approved and agreed with what the Buddha said, got up from his seat, bowed, and respectfully circled him, keeping him on his right, before leaving.*";
P_HTM[1274]="*Atha kho bhagavā acirapakkantassa rañño māgadhassa ajātasattussa vedehiputtassa bhikkhū āmantesi:**Soon after the king had left, the Buddha addressed the mendicants,*";
P_HTM[1275]="*“khatāyaṃ, bhikkhave, rājā.**“The king is broken, mendicants,*";
P_HTM[1276]="*Upahatāyaṃ, bhikkhave, rājā.**he is ruined.*";
P_HTM[1277]="*Sacāyaṃ, bhikkhave, rājā pitaraṃ dhammikaṃ dhammarājānaṃ jīvitā na voropessatha, imasmiññeva āsane virajaṃ vītamalaṃ dhammacakkhuṃ uppajjissathā”ti.**If he had not taken the life of his father, a just and principled king, the stainless, immaculate vision of the Dhamma would have arisen in him in that very seat.”*";
P_HTM[1278]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[1279]="*Attamanā te bhikkhū bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the mendicants were happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[1280]="*Sāmaññaphalasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ dutiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1281]="*03. Ambaṭṭhasutta  - With Ambaṭṭha * **";
P_HTM[1282]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[1283]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā kosalesu cārikaṃ caramāno mahatā bhikkhusaṅghena saddhiṃ pañcamattehi bhikkhusatehi yena icchānaṅgalaṃ nāma kosalānaṃ brāhmaṇagāmo tadavasari.**At one time the Buddha was wandering in the land of the Kosalans together with a large Saṅgha of around five hundred mendicants when he arrived at a village of the Kosalan brahmins named Icchānaṅgala.*";
P_HTM[1284]="*Tatra sudaṃ bhagavā icchānaṅgale viharati icchānaṅgalavanasaṇḍe.**He stayed in a forest near Icchānaṅgala.*";
P_HTM[1285]="*1. Pokkharasātivatthu**1. The Section on Pokkharasāti*";
P_HTM[1286]="*Tena kho pana samayena brāhmaṇo pokkharasāti ukkaṭṭhaṃ ajjhāvasati sattussadaṃ satiṇakaṭṭhodakaṃ sadhaññaṃ rājabhoggaṃ raññā pasenadinā kosalena dinnaṃ rājadāyaṃ brahmadeyyaṃ.**Now at that time the brahmin Pokkharasāti was living in Ukkaṭṭhā. It was a crown property given by King Pasenadi of Kosala, teeming with living creatures, full of hay, wood, water, and grain, a royal endowment of the highest quality.*";
P_HTM[1287]="*Assosi kho brāhmaṇo pokkharasāti:**Pokkharasāti heard:*";
P_HTM[1288]="*“samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo sakyaputto sakyakulā pabbajito kosalesu cārikaṃ caramāno mahatā bhikkhusaṃghena saddhiṃ pañcamattehi bhikkhusatehi icchānaṅgalaṃ anuppatto icchānaṅgale viharati icchānaṅgalavanasaṇḍe.**“It seems the ascetic Gotama—a Sakyan, gone forth from a Sakyan family—has arrived at Icchānaṅgala and is staying in a forest nearby.*";
P_HTM[1289]="*Taṃ kho pana bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ evaṃ kalyāṇo kittisaddo abbhuggato:**He has this good reputation:*";
P_HTM[1290]="*‘itipi so bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā’.**‘That Blessed One is perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.’*";
P_HTM[1291]="*So imaṃ lokaṃ sadevakaṃ samārakaṃ sabrahmakaṃ sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiṃ pajaṃ sadevamanussaṃ sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedeti.**He has realized with his own insight this world—with its gods, Māras and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, gods and humans—and he makes it known to others.*";
P_HTM[1292]="*So dhammaṃ deseti ādikalyāṇaṃ majjhekalyāṇaṃ pariyosānakalyāṇaṃ, sātthaṃ sabyañjanaṃ, kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ pakāseti.**He teaches Dhamma that’s good in the beginning, good in the middle, and good in the end, meaningful and well-phrased. And he reveals a spiritual practice that’s entirely full and pure.*";
P_HTM[1293]="*Sādhu kho pana tathārūpānaṃ arahataṃ dassanaṃ hotī”ti.**It’s good to see such perfected ones.”*";
P_HTM[1294]="*2. Ambaṭṭhamāṇava**2. The Brahmin Student Ambaṭṭha*";
P_HTM[1295]="*Tena kho pana samayena brāhmaṇassa pokkharasātissa ambaṭṭho nāma māṇavo antevāsī hoti ajjhāyako mantadharo tiṇṇaṃ vedānaṃ pāragū sanighaṇḍukeṭubhānaṃ sākkharappabhedānaṃ itihāsapañcamānaṃ padako veyyākaraṇo lokāyatamahāpurisalakkhaṇesu anavayo anuññātapaṭiññāto sake ācariyake tevijjake pāvacane:**Now at that time Pokkharasāti had a student named Ambaṭṭha. He was one who recited and remembered the hymns, and had mastered in the three Vedas, together with their vocabularies, ritual, phonology and etymology, and the testament as fifth. He knew philology and grammar, and was well versed in cosmology and the marks of a great man. He had been authorized as a master in his own teacher’s scriptural heritage of the three Vedas with the words:*";
P_HTM[1296]="*“yamahaṃ jānāmi taṃ tvaṃ jānāsi;**“What I know, you know.*";
P_HTM[1297]="*yaṃ tvaṃ jānāsi tamahaṃ jānāmī”ti.**And what you know, I know.”*";
P_HTM[1298]="*Atha kho brāhmaṇo pokkharasāti ambaṭṭhaṃ māṇavaṃ āmantesi:**Then Pokkharasāti addressed Ambaṭṭha,*";
P_HTM[1299]="*“ayaṃ, tāta ambaṭṭha, samaṇo gotamo sakyaputto sakyakulā pabbajito kosalesu cārikaṃ caramāno mahatā bhikkhusaṅghena saddhiṃ pañcamattehi bhikkhusatehi icchānaṅgalaṃ anuppatto icchānaṅgale viharati icchānaṅgalavanasaṇḍe.**“Dear Ambaṭṭha, the ascetic Gotama—a Sakyan, gone forth from a Sakyan family—has arrived at Icchānaṅgala and is staying in a forest nearby. …*";
P_HTM[1300]="*Taṃ kho pana bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ evaṃ kalyāṇo kittisaddo abbhuggato:* **";
P_HTM[1301]="*‘itipi so bhagavā, arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā.* **";
P_HTM[1302]="*So imaṃ lokaṃ sadevakaṃ samārakaṃ sabrahmakaṃ sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiṃ pajaṃ sadevamanussaṃ sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedeti.* **";
P_HTM[1303]="*So dhammaṃ deseti ādikalyāṇaṃ majjhekalyāṇaṃ pariyosānakalyāṇaṃ, sātthaṃ sabyañjanaṃ kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ pakāseti.* **";
P_HTM[1304]="*Sādhu kho pana tathārūpānaṃ arahataṃ dassanaṃ hotī’ti.**It’s good to see such perfected ones.*";
P_HTM[1305]="*Ehi tvaṃ, tāta ambaṭṭha, yena samaṇo gotamo tenupasaṅkama; upasaṅkamitvā samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ jānāhi, yadi vā taṃ bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ tathāsantaṃyeva saddo abbhuggato, yadi vā no tathā.**Please, dear Ambaṭṭha, go to the ascetic Gotama and find out whether or not he lives up to his reputation.*";
P_HTM[1306]="*Yadi vā so bhavaṃ gotamo tādiso, yadi vā na tādiso, tathā mayaṃ taṃ bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ vedissāmā”ti.**Through you I shall learn about Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[1307]="*“Yathā kathaṃ panāhaṃ, bho, taṃ bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ jānissāmi: ‘yadi vā taṃ bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ tathāsantaṃyeva saddo abbhuggato, yadi vā no tathā. Yadi vā so bhavaṃ gotamo tādiso, yadi vā na tādiso’”ti?**“But sir, how shall I find out whether or not the ascetic Gotama lives up to his reputation?”*";
P_HTM[1308]="*“Āgatāni kho, tāta ambaṭṭha, amhākaṃ mantesu dvattiṃsa mahāpurisalakkhaṇāni, yehi samannāgatassa mahāpurisassa dveyeva gatiyo bhavanti anaññā.**“Dear Ambaṭṭha, the thirty-two marks of a great man have been handed down in our hymns. A great man who possesses these has only two possible destinies, no other.*";
P_HTM[1309]="*Sace agāraṃ ajjhāvasati, rājā hoti cakkavattī dhammiko dhammarājā cāturanto vijitāvī janapadatthāvariyappatto sattaratanasamannāgato.**If he stays at home he becomes a king, a wheel-turning monarch, a just and principled king. His dominion extends to all four sides, he achieves stability in the country, and he possesses the seven treasures.*";
P_HTM[1310]="*Tassimāni satta ratanāni bhavanti.**He has the following seven treasures:*";
P_HTM[1311]="*Seyyathidaṃ—cakkaratanaṃ, hatthiratanaṃ, assaratanaṃ, maṇiratanaṃ, itthiratanaṃ, gahapatiratanaṃ, pariṇāyakaratanameva sattamaṃ.**the wheel, the elephant, the horse, the jewel, the woman, the treasurer, and the counselor as the seventh treasure.*";
P_HTM[1312]="*Parosahassaṃ kho panassa puttā bhavanti sūrā vīraṅgarūpā parasenappamaddanā.**He has over a thousand sons who are valiant and heroic, crushing the armies of his enemies.*";
P_HTM[1313]="*So imaṃ pathaviṃ sāgarapariyantaṃ adaṇḍena asatthena dhammena abhivijiya ajjhāvasati.**After conquering this land girt by sea, he reigns by principle, without rod or sword.*";
P_HTM[1314]="*Sace kho pana agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajati, arahaṃ hoti sammāsambuddho loke vivaṭṭacchado.**But if he goes forth from the lay life to homelessness, he becomes a perfected one, a fully awakened Buddha, who draws back the veil from the world.*";
P_HTM[1315]="*Ahaṃ kho pana, tāta ambaṭṭha, mantānaṃ dātā;**But, dear Ambaṭṭha, I am the one who gives the hymns,*";
P_HTM[1316]="*tvaṃ mantānaṃ paṭiggahetā”ti.**and you are the one who receives them.”*";
P_HTM[1317]="*“Evaṃ, bho”ti kho ambaṭṭho māṇavo brāhmaṇassa pokkharasātissa paṭissutvā uṭṭhāyāsanā brāhmaṇaṃ pokkharasātiṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā vaḷavārathamāruyha sambahulehi māṇavakehi saddhiṃ yena icchānaṅgalavanasaṇḍo tena pāyāsi.**“Yes, sir,” replied Ambaṭṭha. He got up from his seat, bowed, and respectfully circled Pokkharasāti, keeping him to his right. He mounted a mare-drawn chariot and, together with several students, set out for the forest near Icchānaṅgala.*";
P_HTM[1318]="*Yāvatikā yānassa bhūmi yānena gantvā yānā paccorohitvā pattikova ārāmaṃ pāvisi.**He went by carriage as far as the terrain allowed, then descended and entered the monastery on foot.*";
P_HTM[1319]="*Tena kho pana samayena sambahulā bhikkhū abbhokāse caṅkamanti.**At that time several mendicants were walking meditation in the open air.*";
P_HTM[1320]="*Atha kho ambaṭṭho māṇavo yena te bhikkhū tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā te bhikkhū etadavoca:**Then the student Ambaṭṭha went up to those mendicants and said,*";
P_HTM[1321]="*“kahaṃ nu kho, bho, etarahi so bhavaṃ gotamo viharati?**“Gentlemen, where is Master Gotama at present?*";
P_HTM[1322]="*Tañhi mayaṃ bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya idhūpasaṅkantā”ti.**For we have come here to see him.”*";
P_HTM[1323]="*Atha kho tesaṃ bhikkhūnaṃ etadahosi:**Then those mendicants thought,*";
P_HTM[1324]="*“ayaṃ kho ambaṭṭho māṇavo abhiññātakolañño ceva abhiññātassa ca brāhmaṇassa pokkharasātissa antevāsī.**“This Ambaṭṭha is from a well-known family, and he is the pupil of the well-known brahmin Pokkharasāti.*";
P_HTM[1325]="*Agaru kho pana bhagavato evarūpehi kulaputtehi saddhiṃ kathāsallāpo hotī”ti.**The Buddha won’t mind having a discussion together with such gentlemen.”*";
P_HTM[1326]="*Te ambaṭṭhaṃ māṇavaṃ etadavocuṃ:**They said to Ambaṭṭha,*";
P_HTM[1327]="*“eso, ambaṭṭha, vihāro saṃvutadvāro, tena appasaddo upasaṅkamitvā ataramāno āḷindaṃ pavisitvā ukkāsitvā aggaḷaṃ ākoṭehi, vivarissati te bhagavā dvāran”ti.**“Ambaṭṭha, that’s his dwelling, with the door closed. Approach it quietly, without hurrying; go onto the porch, clear your throat, and knock with the latch. The Buddha will open the door.”*";
P_HTM[1328]="*Atha kho ambaṭṭho māṇavo yena so vihāro saṃvutadvāro, tena appasaddo upasaṅkamitvā ataramāno āḷindaṃ pavisitvā ukkāsitvā aggaḷaṃ ākoṭesi. Vivari bhagavā dvāraṃ.**So he approached the Buddha’s dwelling and knocked, and the Buddha opened the door.*";
P_HTM[1329]="*Pāvisi ambaṭṭho māṇavo. Māṇavakāpi pavisitvā bhagavatā saddhiṃ sammodiṃsu, sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu.**Ambaṭṭha and the other students entered the dwelling. The other students exchanged greetings with the Buddha, and when the greetings and polite conversation were over, sat down to one side.*";
P_HTM[1330]="*Ambaṭṭho pana māṇavo caṅkamantopi nisinnena bhagavatā kañci kañci kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāreti, ṭhitopi nisinnena bhagavatā kañci kañci kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāreti.**But while the Buddha was sitting, Ambaṭṭha spoke some polite words or other while walking around or standing.*";
P_HTM[1331]="*Atha kho bhagavā ambaṭṭhaṃ māṇavaṃ etadavoca:**So the Buddha said to him,*";
P_HTM[1332]="*“evaṃ nu te, ambaṭṭha, brāhmaṇehi vuddhehi mahallakehi ācariyapācariyehi saddhiṃ kathāsallāpo hoti, yathayidaṃ caraṃ tiṭṭhaṃ nisinnena mayā kiñci kiñci kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretī”ti?**“Ambaṭṭha, is this how you hold a discussion with elderly and senior brahmins, the teachers of teachers: walking around or standing while I’m sitting, speaking some polite words or other?”*";
P_HTM[1333]="*2.1. Paṭhamaibbhavāda**2.1. The First Use of the Word “Riffraff”*";
P_HTM[1334]="*“No hidaṃ, bho gotama.**“No, Master Gotama.*";
P_HTM[1335]="*Gacchanto vā hi, bho gotama, gacchantena brāhmaṇo brāhmaṇena saddhiṃ sallapitumarahati, ṭhito vā hi, bho gotama, ṭhitena brāhmaṇo brāhmaṇena saddhiṃ sallapitumarahati, nisinno vā hi, bho gotama, nisinnena brāhmaṇo brāhmaṇena saddhiṃ sallapitumarahati, sayāno vā hi, bho gotama, sayānena brāhmaṇo brāhmaṇena saddhiṃ sallapitumarahati.**For it is proper for one brahmin to converse with another while both are walking, standing, sitting, or lying down.*";
P_HTM[1336]="*Ye ca kho te, bho gotama, muṇḍakā samaṇakā ibbhā kaṇhā bandhupādāpaccā, tehipi me saddhiṃ evaṃ kathāsallāpo hoti, yathariva bhotā gotamenā”ti.**But as to these shavelings, fake ascetics, riffraff, black spawn from the feet of our Kinsman, I converse with them as I do with Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[1337]="*“Atthikavato kho pana te, ambaṭṭha, idhāgamanaṃ ahosi, yāyeva kho panatthāya āgaccheyyātha, tameva atthaṃ sādhukaṃ manasi kareyyātha.**“But Ambaṭṭha, you must have come here for some purpose. You should focus on that.*";
P_HTM[1338]="*Avusitavāyeva kho pana, bho, ayaṃ ambaṭṭho māṇavo vusitamānī kimaññatra avusitattā”ti.**Though this Ambaṭṭha is unqualified, he thinks he’s qualified. What is that but lack of qualifications?”*";
P_HTM[1339]="*Atha kho ambaṭṭho māṇavo bhagavatā avusitavādena vuccamāno kupito anattamano bhagavantaṃyeva khuṃsento bhagavantaṃyeva vambhento bhagavantaṃyeva upavadamāno:**When he said this, Ambaṭṭha became angry and upset with the Buddha because of being described as unqualified. He even attacked and badmouthed the Buddha himself, saying,*";
P_HTM[1340]="*“samaṇo ca me bho gotamo pāpito bhavissatī”ti bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**“The ascetic Gotama will be worsted!” He said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[1341]="*“caṇḍā, bho gotama, sakyajāti;**“Master Gotama, the Sakyan clan are rude,*";
P_HTM[1342]="*pharusā, bho gotama, sakyajāti;**harsh,*";
P_HTM[1343]="*lahusā, bho gotama, sakyajāti;**touchy,*";
P_HTM[1344]="*bhassā, bho gotama, sakyajāti;**and argumentative.*";
P_HTM[1345]="*ibbhā santā ibbhā samānā na brāhmaṇe sakkaronti, na brāhmaṇe garuṃ karonti, na brāhmaṇe mānenti, na brāhmaṇe pūjenti, na brāhmaṇe apacāyanti.**Riffraff they are, and riffraff they remain! They don’t honor, respect, revere, worship, or venerate brahmins.*";
P_HTM[1346]="*Tayidaṃ, bho gotama, nacchannaṃ, tayidaṃ nappatirūpaṃ, yadime sakyā ibbhā santā ibbhā samānā na brāhmaṇe sakkaronti, na brāhmaṇe garuṃ karonti, na brāhmaṇe mānenti, na brāhmaṇe pūjenti, na brāhmaṇe apacāyantī”ti.**It is neither proper nor appropriate that the Sakyans—riffraff that they are—don’t honor, respect, revere, worship, or venerate brahmins.”*";
P_HTM[1347]="*Itiha ambaṭṭho māṇavo idaṃ paṭhamaṃ sakyesu ibbhavādaṃ nipātesi.**And that’s how Ambaṭṭha denigrated the Sakyans with the word “riffraff” for the first time.*";
P_HTM[1348]="*2.2. Dutiyaibbhavāda**2.2. The Second Use of the Word “Riffraff”*";
P_HTM[1349]="*“Kiṃ pana te, ambaṭṭha, sakyā aparaddhun”ti?**“But Ambaṭṭha, how have the Sakyans wronged you?”*";
P_HTM[1350]="*“Ekamidāhaṃ, bho gotama, samayaṃ ācariyassa brāhmaṇassa pokkharasātissa kenacideva karaṇīyena kapilavatthuṃ agamāsiṃ.**“This one time, Master Gotama, my teacher, the brahmin Pokkharasāti, went to Kapilavatthu on some business.*";
P_HTM[1351]="*Yena sakyānaṃ sandhāgāraṃ tenupasaṅkamiṃ.**He approached the Sakyans in their meeting hall.*";
P_HTM[1352]="*Tena kho pana samayena sambahulā sakyā ceva sakyakumārā ca sandhāgāre uccesu āsanesu nisinnā honti aññamaññaṃ aṅgulipatodakehi sañjagghantā saṅkīḷantā, aññadatthu mamaññeva maññe anujagghantā, na maṃ koci āsanenapi nimantesi.**Now at that time several Sakyans and Sakyan princes were sitting on high seats, poking each other with their fingers, giggling and playing together. In fact, they even presumed to giggle at me, and didn’t invite me to a seat.*";
P_HTM[1353]="*Tayidaṃ, bho gotama, nacchannaṃ, tayidaṃ nappatirūpaṃ, yadime sakyā ibbhā santā ibbhā samānā na brāhmaṇe sakkaronti, na brāhmaṇe garuṃ karonti, na brāhmaṇe mānenti, na brāhmaṇe pūjenti, na brāhmaṇe apacāyantī”ti.**It is neither proper nor appropriate that the Sakyans—riffraff that they are—don’t honor, respect, revere, worship, or venerate brahmins.”*";
P_HTM[1354]="*Itiha ambaṭṭho māṇavo idaṃ dutiyaṃ sakyesu ibbhavādaṃ nipātesi.**And that’s how Ambaṭṭha denigrated the Sakyans with the word “riffraff” for the second time.*";
P_HTM[1355]="*2.3. Tatiyaibbhavāda**2.3. The Third Use of the Word “Riffraff”*";
P_HTM[1356]="*“Laṭukikāpi kho, ambaṭṭha, sakuṇikā sake kulāvake kāmalāpinī hoti.**“Even a little quail, Ambaṭṭha, speaks as she likes in her own nest.*";
P_HTM[1357]="*Sakaṃ kho panetaṃ, ambaṭṭha, sakyānaṃ yadidaṃ kapilavatthuṃ, nārahatāyasmā ambaṭṭho imāya appamattāya abhisajjitun”ti.**Kapilavatthu is the Sakyans own place, Ambaṭṭha. It’s not worthy of the Venerable Ambaṭṭha to lose his temper over such a small thing.”*";
P_HTM[1358]="*“Cattārome, bho gotama, vaṇṇā—**“Master Gotama, there are these four castes:*";
P_HTM[1359]="*khattiyā brāhmaṇā vessā suddā.**aristocrats, brahmins, merchants, and workers.*";
P_HTM[1360]="*Imesañhi, bho gotama, catunnaṃ vaṇṇānaṃ tayo vaṇṇā—**Three of these castes—*";
P_HTM[1361]="*khattiyā ca vessā ca suddā ca—**aristocrats, merchants, and workers—*";
P_HTM[1362]="*aññadatthu brāhmaṇasseva paricārakā sampajjanti.**in fact succeed only in serving the brahmins.*";
P_HTM[1363]="*Tayidaṃ, bho gotama, nacchannaṃ, tayidaṃ nappatirūpaṃ, yadime sakyā ibbhā santā ibbhā samānā na brāhmaṇe sakkaronti, na brāhmaṇe garuṃ karonti, na brāhmaṇe mānenti, na brāhmaṇe pūjenti, na brāhmaṇe apacāyantī”ti.**It is neither proper nor appropriate that the Sakyans—riffraff that they are—don’t honor, respect, revere, worship, or venerate brahmins.”*";
P_HTM[1364]="*Itiha ambaṭṭho māṇavo idaṃ tatiyaṃ sakyesu ibbhavādaṃ nipātesi.**And that’s how Ambaṭṭha denigrated the Sakyans with the word “riffraff” for the third time.*";
P_HTM[1365]="*2.4. Dāsiputtavāda**2.4. The Word “Son of Bondservants” is Used*";
P_HTM[1366]="*Atha kho bhagavato etadahosi:**Then it occurred to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[1367]="*“atibāḷhaṃ kho ayaṃ ambaṭṭho māṇavo sakyesu ibbhavādena nimmādeti, yannūnāhaṃ gottaṃ puccheyyan”ti.**“This Ambaṭṭha puts the Sakyans down too much by calling them riffraff. Why don’t I ask him about his own clan?”*";
P_HTM[1368]="*Atha kho bhagavā ambaṭṭhaṃ māṇavaṃ etadavoca:**So the Buddha said to him,*";
P_HTM[1369]="*“kathaṃ gottosi, ambaṭṭhā”ti?**“What is your clan, Ambaṭṭha?”*";
P_HTM[1370]="*“Kaṇhāyanohamasmi, bho gotamā”ti.**“I am a Kaṇhāyana, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[1371]="*“Porāṇaṃ kho pana te, ambaṭṭha, mātāpettikaṃ nāmagottaṃ anussarato ayyaputtā sakyā bhavanti; dāsiputto tvamasi sakyānaṃ.**“But, recollecting the ancient name and clan of your mother and father, the Sakyans were the children of the masters, while you’re descended from the son of a female bondservant of the Sakyans.*";
P_HTM[1372]="*Sakyā kho pana, ambaṭṭha, rājānaṃ okkākaṃ pitāmahaṃ dahanti.**But the Sakyans claim King Okkāka as their grandfather.*";
P_HTM[1373]="*Bhūtapubbaṃ, ambaṭṭha, rājā okkāko yā sā mahesī piyā manāpā, tassā puttassa rajjaṃ pariṇāmetukāmo jeṭṭhakumāre raṭṭhasmā pabbājesi—**Once upon a time, King Okkāka, wishing to divert the royal succession to the son of his most beloved queen, banished the elder princes from the realm—*";
P_HTM[1374]="*okkāmukhaṃ karakaṇḍaṃ hatthinikaṃ sinisūraṃ.**Okkāmukha, Karakaṇḍa, Hatthinika, and Sinisūra.*";
P_HTM[1375]="*Te raṭṭhasmā pabbājitā himavantapasse pokkharaṇiyā tīre mahāsākasaṇḍo, tattha vāsaṃ kappesuṃ.**They made their home beside a lotus pond on the slopes of the Himalayas, where there was a large teak grove.*";
P_HTM[1376]="*Te jātisambhedabhayā sakāhi bhaginīhi saddhiṃ saṃvāsaṃ kappesuṃ.**For fear of diluting their lineage, they slept with their own sisters.*";
P_HTM[1377]="*Atha kho, ambaṭṭha, rājā okkāko amacce pārisajje āmantesi:**Then King Okkāka addressed his ministers and counselors,*";
P_HTM[1378]="*‘kahaṃ nu kho, bho, etarahi kumārā sammantī’ti?**‘Where, sirs, have the princes settled now?’*";
P_HTM[1379]="*‘Atthi, deva, himavantapasse pokkharaṇiyā tīre mahāsākasaṇḍo, tatthetarahi kumārā sammanti.**‘Sire, there is a lotus pond on the slopes of the Himalayas, by a large grove of sāka, the teak tree. They’ve settled there.*";
P_HTM[1380]="*Te jātisambhedabhayā sakāhi bhaginīhi saddhiṃ saṃvāsaṃ kappentī’ti.**For fear of diluting their lineage, they are sleeping with their own (saka) sisters.’*";
P_HTM[1381]="*Atha kho, ambaṭṭha, rājā okkāko udānaṃ udānesi:**Then, Ambaṭṭha, King Okkāka was inspired to exclaim:*";
P_HTM[1382]="*‘sakyā vata, bho, kumārā, paramasakyā vata, bho, kumārā’ti.**‘The princes are indeed Sakyans! The princes are indeed the best Sakyans!’*";
P_HTM[1383]="*Tadagge kho pana, ambaṭṭha, sakyā paññāyanti; so ca nesaṃ pubbapuriso.**From that day on the Sakyans were recognized, and he was their founder.*";
P_HTM[1384]="*Rañño kho pana, ambaṭṭha, okkākassa disā nāma dāsī ahosi.**Now, King Okkāka had a female bondservant named Disā.*";
P_HTM[1385]="*Sā kaṇhaṃ nāma janesi.**She gave birth to a black boy.*";
P_HTM[1386]="*Jāto kaṇho pabyāhāsi:**When he was born, Black Boy said:*";
P_HTM[1387]="*‘dhovatha maṃ, amma, nahāpetha maṃ amma, imasmā maṃ asucismā parimocetha, atthāya vo bhavissāmī’ti.**‘Wash me, mum, bathe me! Get this filth off of me! I will be useful for you!’*";
P_HTM[1388]="*Yathā kho pana, ambaṭṭha, etarahi manussā pisāce disvā ‘pisācā’ti sañjānanti;**Whereas these days when people see goblins they know them as goblins,*";
P_HTM[1389]="*evameva kho, ambaṭṭha, tena kho pana samayena manussā pisāce ‘kaṇhā’ti sañjānanti.**in those days they knew goblins as ‘blackboys’.*";
P_HTM[1390]="*Te evamāhaṃsu:**They said:*";
P_HTM[1391]="*‘ayaṃ jāto pabyāhāsi, kaṇho jāto, pisāco jāto’ti.**‘He spoke as soon as he was born—a blackboy is born! A goblin is born!’*";
P_HTM[1392]="*Tadagge kho pana, ambaṭṭha, kaṇhāyanā paññāyanti, so ca kaṇhāyanānaṃ pubbapuriso.**From that day on the Kaṇhāyanas were recognized, and he was their founder.*";
P_HTM[1393]="*Iti kho te, ambaṭṭha, porāṇaṃ mātāpettikaṃ nāmagottaṃ anussarato ayyaputtā sakyā bhavanti, dāsiputto tvamasi sakyānan”ti.**That’s how, recollecting the ancient name and clan of your mother and father, the Sakyans were the children of the masters, while you’re descended from the son of a female bondservant of the Sakyans.”*";
P_HTM[1394]="*Evaṃ vutte, te māṇavakā bhagavantaṃ etadavocuṃ:**When he said this, those students said to him,*";
P_HTM[1395]="*“mā bhavaṃ gotamo ambaṭṭhaṃ atibāḷhaṃ dāsiputtavādena nimmādesi.**“Master Gotama, please don’t put Ambaṭṭha down too much by calling him the son of a bondservant.*";
P_HTM[1396]="*Sujāto ca, bho gotama, ambaṭṭho māṇavo, kulaputto ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo, bahussuto ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo, kalyāṇavākkaraṇo ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo, paṇḍito ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo, pahoti ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo bhotā gotamena saddhiṃ asmiṃ vacane paṭimantetun”ti.**He’s well-born, a gentleman, learned, a good speaker, and astute. He’s capable of having a dialogue with Master Gotama about this.”*";
P_HTM[1397]="*Atha kho bhagavā te māṇavake etadavoca:**So the Buddha said to them,*";
P_HTM[1398]="*“sace kho tumhākaṃ māṇavakānaṃ evaṃ hoti:**“Well, students, if you think that*";
P_HTM[1399]="*‘dujjāto ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo, akulaputto ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo, appassuto ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo, akalyāṇavākkaraṇo ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo, duppañño ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo, na ca pahoti ambaṭṭho māṇavo samaṇena gotamena saddhiṃ asmiṃ vacane paṭimantetun’ti, tiṭṭhatu ambaṭṭho māṇavo, tumhe mayā saddhiṃ mantavho asmiṃ vacane.**Ambaṭṭha is ill-born, not a gentleman, uneducated, a poor speaker, witless, and not capable of having a dialogue with me about this, then leave him aside and you can have a dialogue with me.*";
P_HTM[1400]="*Sace pana tumhākaṃ māṇavakānaṃ evaṃ hoti:**But if you think that*";
P_HTM[1401]="*‘sujāto ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo, kulaputto ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo, bahussuto ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo, kalyāṇavākkaraṇo ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo, paṇḍito ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo, pahoti ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo samaṇena gotamena saddhiṃ asmiṃ vacane paṭimantetun’ti, tiṭṭhatha tumhe;**he’s well-born, a gentleman, learned, a good speaker, astute, and capable of having a dialogue with me about this, then you should stand aside and let him have a dialogue with me.”*";
P_HTM[1402]="*ambaṭṭho māṇavo mayā saddhiṃ paṭimantetū”ti.* **";
P_HTM[1403]="*“Sujāto ca, bho gotama, ambaṭṭho māṇavo, kulaputto ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo, bahussuto ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo, kalyāṇavākkaraṇo ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo, paṇḍito ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo, pahoti ca ambaṭṭho māṇavo bhotā gotamena saddhiṃ asmiṃ vacane paṭimantetuṃ, tuṇhī mayaṃ bhavissāma, ambaṭṭho māṇavo bhotā gotamena saddhiṃ asmiṃ vacane paṭimantetū”ti.**“He is capable of having a dialogue. We will be silent, and let Ambaṭṭha have a dialogue with Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[1404]="*Atha kho bhagavā ambaṭṭhaṃ māṇavaṃ etadavoca:**So the Buddha said to Ambaṭṭha,*";
P_HTM[1405]="*“ayaṃ kho pana te, ambaṭṭha, sahadhammiko pañho āgacchati, akāmā byākātabbo.**“Well, Ambaṭṭha, there’s a legitimate question that comes up. You won’t like it, but you ought to answer anyway.*";
P_HTM[1406]="*Sace tvaṃ na byākarissasi, aññena vā aññaṃ paṭicarissasi, tuṇhī vā bhavissasi, pakkamissasi vā ettheva te sattadhā muddhā phalissati.**If you don’t answer, but dodge the issue, remain silent, or simply leave, your head will explode into seven pieces right here.*";
P_HTM[1407]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, ambaṭṭha,**What do you think, Ambaṭṭha?*";
P_HTM[1408]="*kinti te sutaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ vuddhānaṃ mahallakānaṃ ācariyapācariyānaṃ bhāsamānānaṃ kutopabhutikā kaṇhāyanā, ko ca kaṇhāyanānaṃ pubbapuriso”ti?**According to what you have heard from elderly and senior brahmins, the teachers of teachers, what is the origin of the Kaṇhāyanas, and who is their founder?”*";
P_HTM[1409]="*Evaṃ vutte, ambaṭṭho māṇavo tuṇhī ahosi.**When he said this, Ambaṭṭha kept silent.*";
P_HTM[1410]="*Dutiyampi kho bhagavā ambaṭṭhaṃ māṇavaṃ etadavoca:**For a second time, the Buddha put the question,*";
P_HTM[1411]="*“taṃ kiṃ maññasi, ambaṭṭha, kinti te sutaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ vuddhānaṃ mahallakānaṃ ācariyapācariyānaṃ bhāsamānānaṃ kutopabhutikā kaṇhāyanā, ko ca kaṇhāyanānaṃ pubbapuriso”ti?* **";
P_HTM[1412]="*Dutiyampi kho ambaṭṭho māṇavo tuṇhī ahosi.**and for a second time Ambaṭṭha kept silent.*";
P_HTM[1413]="*Atha kho bhagavā ambaṭṭhaṃ māṇavaṃ etadavoca:**So the Buddha said to him,*";
P_HTM[1414]="*“byākarohi dāni, ambaṭṭha, na dāni, te tuṇhībhāvassa kālo.**“Answer now, Ambaṭṭha. Now is not the time for silence.*";
P_HTM[1415]="*Yo kho, ambaṭṭha, tathāgatena yāvatatiyakaṃ sahadhammikaṃ pañhaṃ puṭṭho na byākaroti, etthevassa sattadhā muddhā phalissatī”ti.**If someone fails to answer a legitimate question when asked three times by the Buddha, their head explodes into seven pieces there and then.”*";
P_HTM[1416]="*Tena kho pana samayena vajirapāṇī yakkho mahantaṃ ayokūṭaṃ ādāya ādittaṃ sampajjalitaṃ sajotibhūtaṃ ambaṭṭhassa māṇavassa upari vehāsaṃ ṭhito hoti:**Now at that time the spirit Vajirapāṇi, holding a massive iron spear, burning, blazing, and glowing, stood in the sky above Ambaṭṭha, thinking,*";
P_HTM[1417]="*“sacāyaṃ ambaṭṭho māṇavo bhagavatā yāvatatiyakaṃ sahadhammikaṃ pañhaṃ puṭṭho na byākarissati, etthevassa sattadhā muddhaṃ phālessāmī”ti.**“If this Ambaṭṭha doesn’t answer when asked a third time, I’ll blow his head into seven pieces there and then!”*";
P_HTM[1418]="*Taṃ kho pana vajirapāṇiṃ yakkhaṃ bhagavā ceva passati ambaṭṭho ca māṇavo.**And both the Buddha and Ambaṭṭha could see Vajirapāṇi.*";
P_HTM[1419]="*Atha kho ambaṭṭho māṇavo bhīto saṃviggo lomahaṭṭhajāto bhagavantaṃyeva tāṇaṃ gavesī bhagavantaṃyeva leṇaṃ gavesī bhagavantaṃyeva saraṇaṃ gavesī upanisīditvā bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Ambaṭṭha was terrified, shocked, and awestruck. Looking to the Buddha for shelter, protection, and refuge, he sat down close by the Buddha and said,*";
P_HTM[1420]="*“kimetaṃ bhavaṃ gotamo āha?**“What did you say?*";
P_HTM[1421]="*Punabhavaṃ gotamo bravitū”ti.**Please repeat the question.”*";
P_HTM[1422]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, ambaṭṭha,**“What do you think, Ambaṭṭha?*";
P_HTM[1423]="*kinti te sutaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ vuddhānaṃ mahallakānaṃ ācariyapācariyānaṃ bhāsamānānaṃ kutopabhutikā kaṇhāyanā, ko ca kaṇhāyanānaṃ pubbapuriso”ti?**According to what you have heard from elderly and senior brahmins, the teachers of teachers, what is the origin of the Kaṇhāyanas, and who is their founder?”*";
P_HTM[1424]="*“Evameva me, bho gotama, sutaṃ yatheva bhavaṃ gotamo āha.**“I have heard, Master Gotama, that it is just as you say.*";
P_HTM[1425]="*Tatopabhutikā kaṇhāyanā;**That’s the origin of the Kaṇhāyanas,*";
P_HTM[1426]="*so ca kaṇhāyanānaṃ pubbapuriso”ti.**and that’s who their founder is.”*";
P_HTM[1427]="*2.5. Ambaṭṭhavaṃsakathā**2.5. The Discussion of Ambaṭṭha’s Heritage*";
P_HTM[1428]="*Evaṃ vutte, te māṇavakā unnādino uccāsaddamahāsaddā ahesuṃ:**When he said this, those students made an uproar,*";
P_HTM[1429]="*“dujjāto kira, bho, ambaṭṭho māṇavo; akulaputto kira, bho, ambaṭṭho māṇavo; dāsiputto kira, bho, ambaṭṭho māṇavo sakyānaṃ. Ayyaputtā kira, bho, ambaṭṭhassa māṇavassa sakyā bhavanti.**“It turns out Ambaṭṭha is ill-born, not a gentleman, son of a Sakyan bondservant, and that the Sakyans are sons of his masters!*";
P_HTM[1430]="*Dhammavādiṃyeva kira mayaṃ samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ apasādetabbaṃ amaññimhā”ti.**And it seems that the ascetic Gotama spoke only the truth, though we presumed to rebuke him!”*";
P_HTM[1431]="*Atha kho bhagavato etadahosi:**Then it occurred to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[1432]="*“atibāḷhaṃ kho ime māṇavakā ambaṭṭhaṃ māṇavaṃ dāsiputtavādena nimmādenti, yannūnāhaṃ parimoceyyan”ti.**“These students put Ambaṭṭha down too much by calling him the son of a bondservant. Why don’t I get him out of this?”*";
P_HTM[1433]="*Atha kho bhagavā te māṇavake etadavoca:**So the Buddha said to the students,*";
P_HTM[1434]="*“mā kho tumhe, māṇavakā, ambaṭṭhaṃ māṇavaṃ atibāḷhaṃ dāsiputtavādena nimmādetha.**“Students, please don’t put Ambaṭṭha down too much by calling him the son of a bondservant.*";
P_HTM[1435]="*Uḷāro so kaṇho isi ahosi.**That Black Boy was an eminent sage.*";
P_HTM[1436]="*So dakkhiṇajanapadaṃ gantvā brahmamante adhīyitvā rājānaṃ okkākaṃ upasaṅkamitvā maddarūpiṃ dhītaraṃ yāci.**He went to a southern country and memorized the Prime Spell. Then he approached King Okkāka and asked for the hand of his daughter Maddarūpī.*";
P_HTM[1437]="*Tassa rājā okkāko:**The king said to him,*";
P_HTM[1438]="*‘ko nevaṃ re ayaṃ mayhaṃ dāsiputto samāno maddarūpiṃ dhītaraṃ yācatī’ti, kupito anattamano khurappaṃ sannayhi.**‘Who the hell is this son of a bondservant to ask for the hand of my daughter!’ Angry and upset he fastened a razor-tipped arrow.*";
P_HTM[1439]="*So taṃ khurappaṃ neva asakkhi muñcituṃ, no paṭisaṃharituṃ.**But he wasn’t able to either shoot it or to relax it.*";
P_HTM[1440]="*Atha kho, māṇavakā, amaccā pārisajjā kaṇhaṃ isiṃ upasaṅkamitvā etadavocuṃ:**Then the ministers and counselors approached the sage Black Boy and said:*";
P_HTM[1441]="*‘sotthi, bhaddante, hotu rañño;**‘Spare the king, sir,*";
P_HTM[1442]="*sotthi, bhaddante, hotu rañño’ti.**spare him!’*";
P_HTM[1443]="*‘Sotthi bhavissati rañño, api ca rājā yadi adho khurappaṃ muñcissati, yāvatā rañño vijitaṃ, ettāvatā pathavī undriyissatī’ti.**‘The king will be safe. But if he shoots the arrow downwards, there will be an earthquake across the entire realm.’*";
P_HTM[1444]="*‘Sotthi, bhaddante, hotu rañño, sotthi janapadassā’ti.**‘Spare the king, sir, and spare the country!’*";
P_HTM[1445]="*‘Sotthi bhavissati rañño, sotthi janapadassa, api ca rājā yadi uddhaṃ khurappaṃ muñcissati, yāvatā rañño vijitaṃ, ettāvatā satta vassāni devo na vassissatī’ti.**‘Both king and country will be safe. But if he shoots the arrow upwards, there will be no rain in the entire realm for seven years.’*";
P_HTM[1446]="*‘Sotthi, bhaddante, hotu rañño sotthi janapadassa devo ca vassatū’ti.**‘Spare the king, sir, spare the country, and let there be rain!’*";
P_HTM[1447]="*‘Sotthi bhavissati rañño sotthi janapadassa devo ca vassissati, api ca rājā jeṭṭhakumāre khurappaṃ patiṭṭhāpetu, sotthi kumāro pallomo bhavissatī’ti.**‘Both king and country will be safe, and the rain will fall. And if the king aims the arrow at the crown prince, he will be safe and untouched.’*";
P_HTM[1448]="*Atha kho, māṇavakā, amaccā okkākassa ārocesuṃ:**So the ministers said to Okkāka:*";
P_HTM[1449]="*‘okkāko jeṭṭhakumāre khurappaṃ patiṭṭhāpetu. Sotthi kumāro pallomo bhavissatī’ti.**‘Okkāka must aim the arrow at the crown prince. He will be safe and untouched.’*";
P_HTM[1450]="*Atha kho rājā okkāko jeṭṭhakumāre khurappaṃ patiṭṭhapesi, sotthi kumāro pallomo samabhavi.**So King Okkāka aimed the arrow at the crown prince. And he was safe and untouched.*";
P_HTM[1451]="*Atha kho tassa rājā okkāko bhīto saṃviggo lomahaṭṭhajāto brahmadaṇḍena tajjito maddarūpiṃ dhītaraṃ adāsi.**Then the king was terrified, shocked, and awestruck. Scared by the prime punishment, he gave the hand of his daughter Maddarūpī.*";
P_HTM[1452]="*Mā kho tumhe, māṇavakā, ambaṭṭhaṃ māṇavaṃ atibāḷhaṃ dāsiputtavādena nimmādetha, uḷāro so kaṇho isi ahosī”ti.**Students, please don’t put Ambaṭṭha down too much by calling him the son of a bondservant. That Black Boy was an eminent sage.”*";
P_HTM[1453]="*3. Khattiyaseṭṭhabhāva**3. The Supremacy of the Aristocrats*";
P_HTM[1454]="*Atha kho bhagavā ambaṭṭhaṃ māṇavaṃ āmantesi:**Then the Buddha addressed Ambaṭṭha,*";
P_HTM[1455]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, ambaṭṭha,**“What do you think, Ambaṭṭha?*";
P_HTM[1456]="*idha khattiyakumāro brāhmaṇakaññāya saddhiṃ saṃvāsaṃ kappeyya, tesaṃ saṃvāsamanvāya putto jāyetha.**Suppose an aristocrat boy was to sleep with a brahmin girl, and they had a son.*";
P_HTM[1457]="*Yo so khattiyakumārena brāhmaṇakaññāya putto uppanno, api nu so labhetha brāhmaṇesu āsanaṃ vā udakaṃ vā”ti?**Would he receive a seat and water from the brahmins?”*";
P_HTM[1458]="*“Labhetha, bho gotama”.**“He would, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[1459]="*“Api nu naṃ brāhmaṇā bhojeyyuṃ saddhe vā thālipāke vā yaññe vā pāhune vā”ti?**“And would the brahmins feed him at an offering of food for ancestors, an offering of a dish of milk-rice, a sacrifice, or a feast for guests?”*";
P_HTM[1460]="*“Bhojeyyuṃ, bho gotama”.**“They would.”*";
P_HTM[1461]="*“Api nu naṃ brāhmaṇā mante vāceyyuṃ vā no vā”ti?**“And would the brahmins teach him the hymns or not?”*";
P_HTM[1462]="*“Vāceyyuṃ, bho gotama”.**“They would.”*";
P_HTM[1463]="*“Api nussa itthīsu āvaṭaṃ vā assa anāvaṭaṃ vā”ti?**“And would he be kept from the women or not?”*";
P_HTM[1464]="*“Anāvaṭaṃ hissa, bho gotama”.**“He would not.”*";
P_HTM[1465]="*“Api nu naṃ khattiyā khattiyābhisekena abhisiñceyyun”ti?**“And would the aristocrats anoint him as king?”*";
P_HTM[1466]="*“No hidaṃ, bho gotama”.**“No, Master Gotama.*";
P_HTM[1467]="*“Taṃ kissa hetu”?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[1468]="*“Mātito hi, bho gotama, anupapanno”ti.**Because his maternity is unsuitable.”*";
P_HTM[1469]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, ambaṭṭha,**“What do you think, Ambaṭṭha?*";
P_HTM[1470]="*idha brāhmaṇakumāro khattiyakaññāya saddhiṃ saṃvāsaṃ kappeyya, tesaṃ saṃvāsamanvāya putto jāyetha.**Suppose a brahmin boy was to sleep with an aristocrat girl, and they had a son.*";
P_HTM[1471]="*Yo so brāhmaṇakumārena khattiyakaññāya putto uppanno, api nu so labhetha brāhmaṇesu āsanaṃ vā udakaṃ vā”ti?**Would he receive a seat and water from the brahmins?”*";
P_HTM[1472]="*“Labhetha, bho gotama”.**“He would, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[1473]="*“Api nu naṃ brāhmaṇā bhojeyyuṃ saddhe vā thālipāke vā yaññe vā pāhune vā”ti?**“And would the brahmins feed him at an offering of food for ancestors, an offering of a dish of milk-rice, a sacrifice, or a feast for guests?”*";
P_HTM[1474]="*“Bhojeyyuṃ, bho gotama”.**“They would.”*";
P_HTM[1475]="*“Api nu naṃ brāhmaṇā mante vāceyyuṃ vā no vā”ti?**“And would the brahmins teach him the hymns or not?”*";
P_HTM[1476]="*“Vāceyyuṃ, bho gotama”.**“They would.”*";
P_HTM[1477]="*“Api nussa itthīsu āvaṭaṃ vā assa anāvaṭaṃ vā”ti?**“And would he be kept from the women or not?”*";
P_HTM[1478]="*“Anāvaṭaṃ hissa, bho gotama”.**“He would not.”*";
P_HTM[1479]="*“Api nu naṃ khattiyā khattiyābhisekena abhisiñceyyun”ti?**“And would the aristocrats anoint him as king?”*";
P_HTM[1480]="*“No hidaṃ, bho gotama”.**“No, Master Gotama.*";
P_HTM[1481]="*“Taṃ kissa hetu”?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[1482]="*“Pitito hi, bho gotama, anupapanno”ti.**Because his paternity is unsuitable.”*";
P_HTM[1483]="*“Iti kho, ambaṭṭha, itthiyā vā itthiṃ karitvā purisena vā purisaṃ karitvā khattiyāva seṭṭhā, hīnā brāhmaṇā.**“And so, Ambaṭṭha, the aristocrats are superior and the brahmins inferior, whether comparing women with women or men with men.*";
P_HTM[1484]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, ambaṭṭha,**What do you think, Ambaṭṭha?*";
P_HTM[1485]="*idha brāhmaṇā brāhmaṇaṃ kismiñcideva pakaraṇe khuramuṇḍaṃ karitvā bhassapuṭena vadhitvā raṭṭhā vā nagarā vā pabbājeyyuṃ.**Suppose the brahmins for some reason were to shave a brahmin’s head, inflict him with a sack of ashes, and banish him from the nation or the city.*";
P_HTM[1486]="*Api nu so labhetha brāhmaṇesu āsanaṃ vā udakaṃ vā”ti?**Would he receive a seat and water from the brahmins?”*";
P_HTM[1487]="*“No hidaṃ, bho gotama”.**“No, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[1488]="*“Api nu naṃ brāhmaṇā bhojeyyuṃ saddhe vā thālipāke vā yaññe vā pāhune vā”ti?**“And would the brahmins feed him at an offering of food for ancestors, an offering of a dish of milk-rice, a sacrifice, or a feast for guests?”*";
P_HTM[1489]="*“No hidaṃ, bho gotama”.**“No, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[1490]="*“Api nu naṃ brāhmaṇā mante vāceyyuṃ vā no vā”ti?**“And would the brahmins teach him the hymns or not?”*";
P_HTM[1491]="*“No hidaṃ, bho gotama”.**“No, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[1492]="*“Api nussa itthīsu āvaṭaṃ vā assa anāvaṭaṃ vā”ti?**“And would he be kept from the women or not?”*";
P_HTM[1493]="*“Āvaṭaṃ hissa, bho gotama”.**“He would be.”*";
P_HTM[1494]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, ambaṭṭha,**“What do you think, Ambaṭṭha?*";
P_HTM[1495]="*idha khattiyā khattiyaṃ kismiñcideva pakaraṇe khuramuṇḍaṃ karitvā bhassapuṭena vadhitvā raṭṭhā vā nagarā vā pabbājeyyuṃ.**Suppose the aristocrats for some reason were to shave an aristocrat’s head, inflict him with a sack of ashes, and banish him from the nation or the city.*";
P_HTM[1496]="*Api nu so labhetha brāhmaṇesu āsanaṃ vā udakaṃ vā”ti?**Would he receive a seat and water from the brahmins?”*";
P_HTM[1497]="*“Labhetha, bho gotama”.**“He would, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[1498]="*“Api nu naṃ brāhmaṇā bhojeyyuṃ saddhe vā thālipāke vā yaññe vā pāhune vā”ti?**“And would the brahmins feed him at an offering of food for ancestors, an offering of a dish of milk-rice, a sacrifice, or a feast for guests?”*";
P_HTM[1499]="*“Bhojeyyuṃ, bho gotama”.**“They would.”*";
P_HTM[1500]="*“Api nu naṃ brāhmaṇā mante vāceyyuṃ vā no vā”ti?**“And would the brahmins teach him the hymns or not?”*";
P_HTM[1501]="*“Vāceyyuṃ, bho gotama”.**“They would.”*";
P_HTM[1502]="*“Api nussa itthīsu āvaṭaṃ vā assa anāvaṭaṃ vā”ti?**“And would he be kept from the women or not?”*";
P_HTM[1503]="*“Anāvaṭaṃ hissa, bho gotama”.**“He would not.”*";
P_HTM[1504]="*“Ettāvatā kho, ambaṭṭha, khattiyo paramanihīnataṃ patto hoti, yadeva naṃ khattiyā khuramuṇḍaṃ karitvā bhassapuṭena vadhitvā raṭṭhā vā nagarā vā pabbājenti.**“At this point, Ambaṭṭha, that aristocrat has reached rock bottom, with head shaven, inflicted with a sack of ashes, and banished from city or nation.*";
P_HTM[1505]="*Iti kho, ambaṭṭha, yadā khattiyo paramanihīnataṃ patto hoti, tadāpi khattiyāva seṭṭhā, hīnā brāhmaṇā.**Yet still the aristocrats are superior and the brahmins inferior.*";
P_HTM[1506]="*Brahmunā pesā, ambaṭṭha, sanaṅkumārena gāthā bhāsitā:**Brahmā Sanaṅkumāra also spoke this verse:*";
P_HTM[1507]="*‘Khattiyo seṭṭho janetasmiṃ,**‘The aristocrat is best of those people*";
P_HTM[1508]="*ye gottapaṭisārino;**who take clan as the standard.*";
P_HTM[1509]="*Vijjācaraṇasampanno,**But one accomplished in knowledge and conduct*";
P_HTM[1510]="*so seṭṭho devamānuse’ti.**is best of gods and humans.’*";
P_HTM[1511]="*Sā kho panesā, ambaṭṭha, brahmunā sanaṅkumārena gāthā sugītā no duggītā, subhāsitā no dubbhāsitā, atthasaṃhitā no anatthasaṃhitā, anumatā mayā.**That verse was well sung by Brahmā Sanaṅkumāra, not poorly sung; well spoken, not poorly spoken, beneficial, not harmful, and it was approved by me.*";
P_HTM[1512]="*Ahampi hi, ambaṭṭha, evaṃ vadāmi—**For I also say this:*";
P_HTM[1513]="*Khattiyo seṭṭho janetasmiṃ,**The aristocrat is best of those people*";
P_HTM[1514]="*ye gottapaṭisārino;**who take clan as the standard.*";
P_HTM[1515]="*Vijjācaraṇasampanno,**But one accomplished in knowledge and conduct*";
P_HTM[1516]="*so seṭṭho devamānuse”ti.**is best of gods and humans.”*";
P_HTM[1517]="*Bhāṇavāro paṭhamo.* **";
P_HTM[1518]="*4. Vijjācaraṇakathā**4. Knowledge and Conduct*";
P_HTM[1519]="*“Katamaṃ pana taṃ, bho gotama, caraṇaṃ, katamā ca pana sā vijjā”ti?**“But what, Master Gotama, is that conduct, and what is that knowledge?”*";
P_HTM[1520]="*“Na kho, ambaṭṭha, anuttarāya vijjācaraṇasampadāya jātivādo vā vuccati, gottavādo vā vuccati, mānavādo vā vuccati:**“Ambaṭṭha, in the supreme knowledge and conduct there is no discussion of ancestry or clan or pride—*";
P_HTM[1521]="*‘arahasi vā maṃ tvaṃ, na vā maṃ tvaṃ arahasī’ti.**‘You deserve me’ or ‘You don’t deserve me.’*";
P_HTM[1522]="*Yattha kho, ambaṭṭha, āvāho vā hoti, vivāho vā hoti, āvāhavivāho vā hoti, etthetaṃ vuccati jātivādo vā itipi gottavādo vā itipi mānavādo vā itipi:**Wherever there is giving and taking in marriage there is such discussion.*";
P_HTM[1523]="*‘arahasi vā maṃ tvaṃ, na vā maṃ tvaṃ arahasī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1524]="*Ye hi keci, ambaṭṭha, jātivādavinibaddhā vā gottavādavinibaddhā vā mānavādavinibaddhā vā āvāhavivāhavinibaddhā vā, ārakā te anuttarāya vijjācaraṇasampadāya.**Whoever is attached to questions of ancestry or clan or pride, or to giving and taking in marriage, is far from the supreme knowledge and conduct.*";
P_HTM[1525]="*Pahāya kho, ambaṭṭha, jātivādavinibaddhañca gottavādavinibaddhañca mānavādavinibaddhañca āvāhavivāhavinibaddhañca anuttarāya vijjācaraṇasampadāya sacchikiriyā hotī”ti.**The realization of supreme knowledge and conduct occurs when you’ve given up such things.”*";
P_HTM[1526]="*“Katamaṃ pana taṃ, bho gotama, caraṇaṃ, katamā ca sā vijjā”ti?**“But what, Master Gotama, is that conduct, and what is that knowledge?”*";
P_HTM[1527]="*“Idha, ambaṭṭha, tathāgato loke uppajjati arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā.**“Ambaṭṭha, it’s when a Realized One arises in the world, perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.*";
P_HTM[1528]="*So imaṃ lokaṃ sadevakaṃ samārakaṃ sabrahmakaṃ sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiṃ pajaṃ sadevamanussaṃ sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedeti.**He has realized with his own insight this world—with its gods, Māras and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, gods and humans—and he makes it known to others.*";
P_HTM[1529]="*So dhammaṃ deseti ādikalyāṇaṃ majjhekalyāṇaṃ pariyosānakalyāṇaṃ sātthaṃ sabyañjanaṃ kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ pakāseti.**He teaches Dhamma that’s good in the beginning, good in the middle, and good in the end, meaningful and well-phrased. And he reveals a spiritual practice that’s entirely full and pure.*";
P_HTM[1530]="*Taṃ dhammaṃ suṇāti gahapati vā gahapatiputto vā aññatarasmiṃ vā kule paccājāto.**A householder hears that teaching, or a householder’s child, or someone reborn in some clan.*";
P_HTM[1531]="*So taṃ dhammaṃ sutvā tathāgate saddhaṃ paṭilabhati.**They gain faith in the Realized One,*";
P_HTM[1532]="*So tena saddhāpaṭilābhena samannāgato iti paṭisañcikkhati … pe …**and reflect …*";
P_HTM[1533]="*So vivicceva kāmehi, vivicca akusalehi dhammehi, savitakkaṃ savicāraṃ vivekajaṃ pītisukhaṃ paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati … pe …**Quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, they enter and remain in the first absorption …*";
P_HTM[1534]="*idampissa hoti caraṇasmiṃ.**This pertains to their conduct.*";
P_HTM[1535]="*Puna caparaṃ, ambaṭṭha, bhikkhu vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā ajjhattaṃ sampasādanaṃ cetaso ekodibhāvaṃ avitakkaṃ avicāraṃ samādhijaṃ pītisukhaṃ dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati … pe …**Furthermore, as the placing of the mind and keeping it connected are stilled, a mendicant enters and remains in the second absorption …*";
P_HTM[1536]="*idampissa hoti caraṇasmiṃ.**This pertains to their conduct.*";
P_HTM[1537]="*Puna caparaṃ, ambaṭṭha, bhikkhu pītiyā ca virāgā upekkhako ca viharati sato ca sampajāno, sukhañca kāyena paṭisaṃvedeti, yaṃ taṃ ariyā ācikkhanti: ‘upekkhako satimā sukhavihārī’ti, tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati … pe …**Furthermore, with the fading away of rapture, they enter and remain in the third absorption …*";
P_HTM[1538]="*idampissa hoti caraṇasmiṃ.**This pertains to their conduct.*";
P_HTM[1539]="*Puna caparaṃ, ambaṭṭha, bhikkhu sukhassa ca pahānā dukkhassa ca pahānā, pubbeva somanassadomanassānaṃ atthaṅgamā adukkhamasukhaṃ upekkhāsatipārisuddhiṃ catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati … pe …**Furthermore, giving up pleasure and pain, and ending former happiness and sadness, they enter and remain in the fourth absorption …*";
P_HTM[1540]="*idampissa hoti caraṇasmiṃ.**This pertains to their conduct.*";
P_HTM[1541]="*Idaṃ kho taṃ, ambaṭṭha, caraṇaṃ.**This is that conduct.*";
P_HTM[1542]="*So evaṃ samāhite citte parisuddhe pariyodāte anaṅgaṇe vigatūpakkilese mudubhūte kammaniye ṭhite āneñjappatte ñāṇadassanāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti … pe …**When their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it and project it toward knowledge and vision.*";
P_HTM[1543]="*idampissa hoti vijjāya … pe …**This pertains to their knowledge. …*";
P_HTM[1544]="*nāparaṃ itthattāyāti pajānāti,**They understand: ‘There is no return to any state of existence.’*";
P_HTM[1545]="*idampissa hoti vijjāya.**This pertains to their knowledge.*";
P_HTM[1546]="*Ayaṃ kho sā, ambaṭṭha, vijjā.**This is that knowledge.*";
P_HTM[1547]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, ambaṭṭha, bhikkhu ‘vijjāsampanno’ itipi, ‘caraṇasampanno’ itipi, ‘vijjācaraṇasampanno’ itipi.**This mendicant is said to be ‘accomplished in knowledge’, and also ‘accomplished in conduct’, and also ‘accomplished in knowledge and conduct’.*";
P_HTM[1548]="*Imāya ca, ambaṭṭha, vijjāsampadāya caraṇasampadāya ca aññā vijjāsampadā ca caraṇasampadā ca uttaritarā vā paṇītatarā vā natthi.**And, Ambaṭṭha, there is no accomplishment in knowledge and conduct that is better or finer than this.*";
P_HTM[1549]="*5. Catuapāyamukha**5. Four Drains*";
P_HTM[1550]="*Imāya kho, ambaṭṭha, anuttarāya vijjācaraṇasampadāya cattāri apāyamukhāni bhavanti.**There are these four drains that affect this supreme knowledge and conduct.*";
P_HTM[1551]="*Katamāni cattāri?**What four?*";
P_HTM[1552]="*Idha, ambaṭṭha, ekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā imaññeva anuttaraṃ vijjācaraṇasampadaṃ anabhisambhuṇamāno khārividhamādāya araññāyatanaṃ ajjhogāhati:**Firstly, take some ascetic or brahmin who, not managing to obtain this supreme knowledge and conduct, plunges into a wilderness region carrying their stuff with a shoulder-pole, thinking*";
P_HTM[1553]="*‘pavattaphalabhojano bhavissāmī’ti.**they will get by eating fallen fruit.*";
P_HTM[1554]="*So aññadatthu vijjācaraṇasampannasseva paricārako sampajjati.**In fact they succeed only in serving someone accomplished in knowledge and conduct.*";
P_HTM[1555]="*Imāya kho, ambaṭṭha, anuttarāya vijjācaraṇasampadāya idaṃ paṭhamaṃ apāyamukhaṃ bhavati.**This is the first drain that affects this supreme knowledge and conduct.*";
P_HTM[1556]="*Puna caparaṃ, ambaṭṭha, idhekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā imañceva anuttaraṃ vijjācaraṇasampadaṃ anabhisambhuṇamāno pavattaphalabhojanatañca anabhisambhuṇamāno kudālapiṭakaṃ ādāya araññavanaṃ ajjhogāhati:**Furthermore, take some ascetic or brahmin who, not managing to obtain this supreme knowledge and conduct or to get by eating fallen fruit, plunges into a wilderness region carrying a spade and basket, thinking*";
P_HTM[1557]="*‘kandamūlaphalabhojano bhavissāmī’ti.**they will get by eating tubers and fruit.*";
P_HTM[1558]="*So aññadatthu vijjācaraṇasampannasseva paricārako sampajjati.**In fact they succeed only in serving someone accomplished in knowledge and conduct.*";
P_HTM[1559]="*Imāya kho, ambaṭṭha, anuttarāya vijjācaraṇasampadāya idaṃ dutiyaṃ apāyamukhaṃ bhavati.**This is the second drain that affects this supreme knowledge and conduct.*";
P_HTM[1560]="*Puna caparaṃ, ambaṭṭha, idhekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā imañceva anuttaraṃ vijjācaraṇasampadaṃ anabhisambhuṇamāno pavattaphalabhojanatañca anabhisambhuṇamāno kandamūlaphalabhojanatañca anabhisambhuṇamāno gāmasāmantaṃ vā nigamasāmantaṃ vā agyāgāraṃ karitvā aggiṃ paricaranto acchati.**Furthermore, take some ascetic or brahmin who, not managing to obtain this supreme knowledge and conduct, or to get by eating fallen fruit, or to get by eating tubers and fruit, sets up a fire chamber in the neighborhood of a village or town and dwells there serving the sacred flame.*";
P_HTM[1561]="*So aññadatthu vijjācaraṇasampannasseva paricārako sampajjati.**In fact they succeed only in serving someone accomplished in knowledge and conduct.*";
P_HTM[1562]="*Imāya kho, ambaṭṭha, anuttarāya vijjācaraṇasampadāya idaṃ tatiyaṃ apāyamukhaṃ bhavati.**This is the third drain that affects this supreme knowledge and conduct.*";
P_HTM[1563]="*Puna caparaṃ, ambaṭṭha, idhekacco samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā imaṃ ceva anuttaraṃ vijjācaraṇasampadaṃ anabhisambhuṇamāno pavattaphalabhojanatañca anabhisambhuṇamāno kandamūlaphalabhojanatañca anabhisambhuṇamāno aggipāricariyañca anabhisambhuṇamāno cātumahāpathe catudvāraṃ agāraṃ karitvā acchati:**Furthermore, take some ascetic or brahmin who, not managing to obtain this supreme knowledge and conduct, or to get by eating fallen fruit, or to get by eating tubers and fruit, or to serve the sacred flame, sets up a fire chamber in the central square and dwells there, thinking:*";
P_HTM[1564]="*‘yo imāhi catūhi disāhi āgamissati samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā, tamahaṃ yathāsatti yathābalaṃ paṭipūjessāmī’ti.**‘When an ascetic or brahmin comes from the four quarters, I will honor them as best I can.’*";
P_HTM[1565]="*So aññadatthu vijjācaraṇasampannasseva paricārako sampajjati.**In fact they succeed only in serving someone accomplished in knowledge and conduct.*";
P_HTM[1566]="*Imāya kho, ambaṭṭha, anuttarāya vijjācaraṇasampadāya idaṃ catutthaṃ apāyamukhaṃ bhavati.**This is the fourth drain that affects this supreme knowledge and conduct.*";
P_HTM[1567]="*Imāya kho, ambaṭṭha, anuttarāya vijjācaraṇasampadāya imāni cattāri apāyamukhāni bhavanti.**These are the four drains that affect this supreme knowledge and conduct.*";
P_HTM[1568]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, ambaṭṭha,**What do you think, Ambaṭṭha?*";
P_HTM[1569]="*api nu tvaṃ imāya anuttarāya vijjācaraṇasampadāya sandissasi sācariyako”ti?**Is this supreme knowledge and conduct seen in your own tradition?”*";
P_HTM[1570]="*“No hidaṃ, bho gotama.**“No, Master Gotama.*";
P_HTM[1571]="*Kocāhaṃ, bho gotama, sācariyako, kā ca anuttarā vijjācaraṇasampadā?**Who am I and my tradition compared with the supreme knowledge and conduct?*";
P_HTM[1572]="*Ārakāhaṃ, bho gotama, anuttarāya vijjācaraṇasampadāya sācariyako”ti.**We are far from that.”*";
P_HTM[1573]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, ambaṭṭha,**“What do you think, Ambaṭṭha?*";
P_HTM[1574]="*api nu tvaṃ imañceva anuttaraṃ vijjācaraṇasampadaṃ anabhisambhuṇamāno khārividhamādāya araññavanamajjhogāhasi sācariyako:**Since you’re not managing to obtain this supreme knowledge and conduct, have you with your tradition plunged into a wilderness region carrying your stuff with a shoulder-pole, thinking*";
P_HTM[1575]="*‘pavattaphalabhojano bhavissāmī’”ti?**you will get by eating fallen fruit?”*";
P_HTM[1576]="*“No hidaṃ, bho gotama”.**“No, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[1577]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, ambaṭṭha,**“What do you think, Ambaṭṭha?*";
P_HTM[1578]="*api nu tvaṃ imañceva anuttaraṃ vijjācaraṇasampadaṃ anabhisambhuṇamāno pavattaphalabhojanatañca anabhisambhuṇamāno kudālapiṭakaṃ ādāya araññavanamajjhogāhasi sācariyako:**Have you with your tradition … plunged into a wilderness region carrying a spade and basket, thinking*";
P_HTM[1579]="*‘kandamūlaphalabhojano bhavissāmī’”ti?**you will get by eating tubers and fruit?”*";
P_HTM[1580]="*“No hidaṃ, bho gotama”.**“No, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[1581]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, ambaṭṭha,**“What do you think, Ambaṭṭha?*";
P_HTM[1582]="*api nu tvaṃ imañceva anuttaraṃ vijjācaraṇasampadaṃ anabhisambhuṇamāno pavattaphalabhojanatañca anabhisambhuṇamāno kandamūlaphalabhojanatañca anabhisambhuṇamāno gāmasāmantaṃ vā nigamasāmantaṃ vā agyāgāraṃ karitvā aggiṃ paricaranto acchasi sācariyako”ti?**Have you with your tradition … set up a fire chamber in the neighborhood of a village or town and dwelt there serving the sacred flame?”*";
P_HTM[1583]="*“No hidaṃ, bho gotama”.**“No, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[1584]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, ambaṭṭha,**“What do you think, Ambaṭṭha?*";
P_HTM[1585]="*api nu tvaṃ imañceva anuttaraṃ vijjācaraṇasampadaṃ anabhisambhuṇamāno pavattaphalabhojanatañca anabhisambhuṇamāno kandamūlaphalabhojanatañca anabhisambhuṇamāno aggipāricariyañca anabhisambhuṇamāno cātumahāpathe catudvāraṃ agāraṃ karitvā acchasi sācariyako:**Have you with your tradition … set up a fire chamber in the central square and dwelt there, thinking:*";
P_HTM[1586]="*‘yo imāhi catūhi disāhi āgamissati samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā, taṃ mayaṃ yathāsatti yathābalaṃ paṭipūjessāmā’”ti?**‘When an ascetic or brahmin comes from the four quarters, I will honor them as best I can’?”*";
P_HTM[1587]="*“No hidaṃ, bho gotama”.**“No, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[1588]="*“Iti kho, ambaṭṭha, imāya ceva tvaṃ anuttarāya vijjācaraṇasampadāya parihīno sācariyako.**“So you with your tradition are not only inferior to the supreme knowledge and conduct,*";
P_HTM[1589]="*Ye cime anuttarāya vijjācaraṇasampadāya cattāri apāyamukhāni bhavanti, tato ca tvaṃ parihīno sācariyako.**you are even inferior to the four drains that affect the supreme knowledge and conduct.*";
P_HTM[1590]="*Bhāsitā kho pana te esā, ambaṭṭha, ācariyena brāhmaṇena pokkharasātinā vācā:**But you have been told this by your teacher, the brahmin Pokkharasāti:*";
P_HTM[1591]="*‘ke ca muṇḍakā samaṇakā ibbhā kaṇhā bandhupādāpaccā, kā ca tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ sākacchā’ti attanā āpāyikopi aparipūramāno.**‘Who are these shavelings, fake ascetics, riffraff, black spawn from the feet of our Kinsman compared with conversation with the brahmins of the three knowledges?” Yet he himself has not even fulfilled one of the drains!*";
P_HTM[1592]="*Passa, ambaṭṭha, yāva aparaddhañca te idaṃ ācariyassa brāhmaṇassa pokkharasātissa.**See, Ambaṭṭha, how your teacher Pokkharasāti has wronged you.*";
P_HTM[1593]="*6. Pubbakaisibhāvānuyoga**6. Being Like the Sages of the Past*";
P_HTM[1594]="*Brāhmaṇo kho pana, ambaṭṭha, pokkharasāti rañño pasenadissa kosalassa dattikaṃ bhuñjati.**But Pokkharasāti lives off an endowment provided by King Pasenadi of Kosala.*";
P_HTM[1595]="*Tassa rājā pasenadi kosalo sammukhībhāvampi na dadāti.**But the king won’t even grant him an audience face to face.*";
P_HTM[1596]="*Yadāpi tena manteti, tirodussantena manteti.**When he consults, he does so behind a curtain.*";
P_HTM[1597]="*Yassa kho pana, ambaṭṭha, dhammikaṃ payātaṃ bhikkhaṃ paṭiggaṇheyya, kathaṃ tassa rājā pasenadi kosalo sammukhībhāvampi na dadeyya.**Why wouldn’t the king grant a face to face audience with someone who’d receive his legitimate presentation of food?*";
P_HTM[1598]="*Passa, ambaṭṭha, yāva aparaddhañca te idaṃ ācariyassa brāhmaṇassa pokkharasātissa.**See, Ambaṭṭha, how your teacher Pokkharasāti has wronged you.*";
P_HTM[1599]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, ambaṭṭha,**What do you think, Ambaṭṭha?*";
P_HTM[1600]="*idha rājā pasenadi kosalo hatthigīvāya vā nisinno assapiṭṭhe vā nisinno rathūpatthare vā ṭhito uggehi vā rājaññehi vā kiñcideva mantanaṃ manteyya.**Suppose King Pasenadi was holding consultations with warrior-chiefs or chieftains while sitting on an elephant’s neck or on horseback, or while standing on the mat in a chariot.*";
P_HTM[1601]="*So tamhā padesā apakkamma ekamantaṃ tiṭṭheyya.**And suppose he’d get down from that place and stand aside.*";
P_HTM[1602]="*Atha āgaccheyya suddo vā suddadāso vā, tasmiṃ padese ṭhito tadeva mantanaṃ manteyya:**Then along would come a worker or their bondservant, who’d stand in the same place and continue the consultation:*";
P_HTM[1603]="*‘evampi rājā pasenadi kosalo āha, evampi rājā pasenadi kosalo āhā’ti.**‘This is what King Pasenadi says, and this too is what the king says.’*";
P_HTM[1604]="*Api nu so rājabhaṇitaṃ vā bhaṇati rājamantanaṃ vā manteti?**Though he spoke the king’s words and gave the king’s advice,*";
P_HTM[1605]="*Ettāvatā so assa rājā vā rājamatto vā”ti?**does that qualify him to be the king or the king’s minister?”*";
P_HTM[1606]="*“No hidaṃ, bho gotama”.**“No, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[1607]="*“Evameva kho tvaṃ, ambaṭṭha, ye te ahesuṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ pubbakā isayo mantānaṃ kattāro mantānaṃ pavattāro, yesamidaṃ etarahi brāhmaṇā porāṇaṃ mantapadaṃ gītaṃ pavuttaṃ samihitaṃ, tadanugāyanti tadanubhāsanti bhāsitamanubhāsanti vācitamanuvācenti, seyyathidaṃ—aṭṭhako vāmako vāmadevo vessāmitto yamataggi aṅgīraso bhāradvājo vāseṭṭho kassapo bhagu:**“In the same way, Ambaṭṭha, the brahmin seers of the past were Aṭṭhaka, Vāmaka, Vāmadeva, Vessāmitta, Yamadaggi, Aṅgīrasa, Bhāradvāja, Vāseṭṭha, Kassapa, and Bhagu. They were the authors and propagators of the hymns. Their hymnal was sung and propagated and compiled in ancient times; and these days, brahmins continue to sing and chant it, chanting what was chanted and teaching what was taught.*";
P_HTM[1608]="*‘tyāhaṃ mante adhiyāmi sācariyako’ti, tāvatā tvaṃ bhavissasi isi vā isitthāya vā paṭipannoti netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**You might imagine that, since you’ve learned their hymns by heart in your own tradition, that makes you a hermit or someone on the path to becoming a hermit. But that is not possible.*";
P_HTM[1609]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, ambaṭṭha,**What do you think, Ambaṭṭha?*";
P_HTM[1610]="*kinti te sutaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ vuddhānaṃ mahallakānaṃ ācariyapācariyānaṃ bhāsamānānaṃ—**According to what you have heard from elderly and senior brahmins, the teachers of teachers,*";
P_HTM[1611]="*ye te ahesuṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ pubbakā isayo mantānaṃ kattāro mantānaṃ pavattāro, yesamidaṃ etarahi brāhmaṇā porāṇaṃ mantapadaṃ gītaṃ pavuttaṃ samihitaṃ, tadanugāyanti tadanubhāsanti bhāsitamanubhāsanti vācitamanuvācenti, seyyathidaṃ—aṭṭhako vāmako vāmadevo vessāmitto yamataggi aṅgīraso bhāradvājo vāseṭṭho kassapo bhagu,**did those brahmin hermits of the past—*";
P_HTM[1612]="*evaṃ su te sunhātā suvilittā kappitakesamassū āmukkamaṇikuṇḍalābharaṇā odātavatthavasanā pañcahi kāmaguṇehi samappitā samaṅgībhūtā paricārenti, seyyathāpi tvaṃ etarahi sācariyako”ti?**nicely bathed and anointed, with hair and beard dressed, bedecked with jewels, earrings, and bracelets, dressed in white—amuse themselves, supplied and provided with the five kinds of sensual stimulation, like you do today in your tradition?”*";
P_HTM[1613]="*“No hidaṃ, bho gotama”.**“No, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[1614]="*“… pe …* **";
P_HTM[1615]="*Evaṃ su te sālīnaṃ odanaṃ sucimaṃsūpasecanaṃ vicitakāḷakaṃ anekasūpaṃ anekabyañjanaṃ paribhuñjanti, seyyathāpi tvaṃ etarahi sācariyako”ti?**“Did they eat boiled fine rice, garnished with clean meat, with the dark grains picked out, served with many soups and sauces, like you do today in your tradition?”*";
P_HTM[1616]="*“No hidaṃ, bho gotama”.**“No, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[1617]="*“… pe …* **";
P_HTM[1618]="*Evaṃ su te veṭhakanatapassāhi nārīhi paricārenti, seyyathāpi tvaṃ etarahi sācariyako”ti?**“Did they amuse themselves with girls wearing thongs that show off their curves, like you do today in your tradition?”*";
P_HTM[1619]="*“No hidaṃ, bho gotama”.**“No, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[1620]="*“… pe …* **";
P_HTM[1621]="*Evaṃ su te kuttavālehi vaḷavārathehi dīghāhi patodalaṭṭhīhi vāhane vitudentā vipariyāyanti, seyyathāpi tvaṃ etarahi sācariyako”ti?**“Did they drive about in chariots drawn by mares with plaited manes, whipping and lashing them onward with long goads, like you do today in your tradition?”*";
P_HTM[1622]="*“No hidaṃ, bho gotama”.**“No, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[1623]="*“… pe …* **";
P_HTM[1624]="*Evaṃ su te ukkiṇṇaparikhāsu okkhittapalighāsu nagarūpakārikāsu dīghāsivudhehi purisehi rakkhāpenti, seyyathāpi tvaṃ etarahi sācariyako”ti?**“Did they get men with long swords to guard them in fortresses with moats dug and barriers in place, like you do today in your tradition?”*";
P_HTM[1625]="*“No hidaṃ, bho gotama”.**“No, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[1626]="*“Iti kho, ambaṭṭha, neva tvaṃ isi na isitthāya paṭipanno sācariyako.**“So, Ambaṭṭha, in your own tradition you are neither hermit nor someone on the path to becoming a hermit.*";
P_HTM[1627]="*Yassa kho pana, ambaṭṭha, mayi kaṅkhā vā vimati vā so maṃ pañhena, ahaṃ veyyākaraṇena sodhissāmī”ti.**Whoever has any doubt or uncertainty about me, let them ask me and I will clear up their doubts with my answer.”*";
P_HTM[1628]="*7. Dvelakkhaṇādassana**7. Seeing the Two Marks*";
P_HTM[1629]="*Atha kho bhagavā vihārā nikkhamma caṅkamaṃ abbhuṭṭhāsi.**Then the Buddha came out of his dwelling and proceeded to begin walking meditation,*";
P_HTM[1630]="*Ambaṭṭhopi māṇavo vihārā nikkhamma caṅkamaṃ abbhuṭṭhāsi.**and Ambaṭṭha did likewise.*";
P_HTM[1631]="*Atha kho ambaṭṭho māṇavo bhagavantaṃ caṅkamantaṃ anucaṅkamamāno bhagavato kāye dvattiṃsamahāpurisalakkhaṇāni samannesi.**Then while walking beside the Buddha, Ambaṭṭha scrutinized his body for the thirty-two marks of a great man.*";
P_HTM[1632]="*Addasā kho ambaṭṭho māṇavo bhagavato kāye dvattiṃsamahāpurisalakkhaṇāni yebhuyyena ṭhapetvā dve.**He saw all of them except for two,*";
P_HTM[1633]="*Dvīsu mahāpurisalakkhaṇesu kaṅkhati vicikicchati nādhimuccati na sampasīdati—**which he had doubts about:*";
P_HTM[1634]="*kosohite ca vatthaguyhe pahūtajivhatāya ca.**whether the private parts are retracted, and the largeness of the tongue.*";
P_HTM[1635]="*Atha kho bhagavato etadahosi:**Then it occurred to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[1636]="*“passati kho me ayaṃ ambaṭṭho māṇavo dvattiṃsamahāpurisalakkhaṇāni yebhuyyena ṭhapetvā dve.**“This brahmin student Ambaṭṭha sees all the marks except for two,*";
P_HTM[1637]="*Dvīsu mahāpurisalakkhaṇesu kaṅkhati vicikicchati nādhimuccati na sampasīdati—**which he has doubts about:*";
P_HTM[1638]="*kosohite ca vatthaguyhe pahūtajivhatāya cā”ti.**whether the private parts are retracted, and the largeness of the tongue.”*";
P_HTM[1639]="*Atha kho bhagavā tathārūpaṃ iddhābhisaṅkhāraṃ abhisaṅkhāsi. Yathā addasa ambaṭṭho māṇavo bhagavato kosohitaṃ vatthaguyhaṃ.**Then the Buddha used his psychic power to will that Ambaṭṭha would see his retracted private parts.*";
P_HTM[1640]="*Atha kho bhagavā jivhaṃ ninnāmetvā ubhopi kaṇṇasotāni anumasi paṭimasi, ubhopi nāsikasotāni anumasi paṭimasi, kevalampi nalāṭamaṇḍalaṃ jivhāya chādesi.**And he stuck out his tongue and stroked back and forth on his ear holes and nostrils, and covered his entire forehead with his tongue.*";
P_HTM[1641]="*Atha kho ambaṭṭhassa māṇavassa etadahosi:**Then Ambaṭṭha thought,*";
P_HTM[1642]="*“samannāgato kho samaṇo gotamo dvattiṃsamahāpurisalakkhaṇehi paripuṇṇehi, no aparipuṇṇehī”ti.**“The ascetic Gotama possesses the thirty-two marks completely, lacking none.”*";
P_HTM[1643]="*Bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**He said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[1644]="*“handa ca dāni mayaṃ, bho gotama, gacchāma, bahukiccā mayaṃ bahukaraṇīyā”ti.**“Well, now, sir, I must go. I have many duties, and much to do.”*";
P_HTM[1645]="*“Yassadāni tvaṃ, ambaṭṭha, kālaṃ maññasī”ti.**“Please, Ambaṭṭha, go at your convenience.”*";
P_HTM[1646]="*Atha kho ambaṭṭho māṇavo vaḷavārathamāruyha pakkāmi.**Then Ambaṭṭha mounted his mare-drawn chariot and left.*";
P_HTM[1647]="*Tena kho pana samayena brāhmaṇo pokkharasāti ukkaṭṭhāya nikkhamitvā mahatā brāhmaṇagaṇena saddhiṃ sake ārāme nisinno hoti ambaṭṭhaṃyeva māṇavaṃ paṭimānento.**Now at that time the brahmin Pokkharasāti had come out from Ukkaṭṭhā together with a large group of brahmins and was sitting in his own park just waiting for Ambaṭṭha.*";
P_HTM[1648]="*Atha kho ambaṭṭho māṇavo yena sako ārāmo tena pāyāsi.**Then Ambaṭṭha entered the park.*";
P_HTM[1649]="*Yāvatikā yānassa bhūmi, yānena gantvā yānā paccorohitvā pattikova yena brāhmaṇo pokkharasāti tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā brāhmaṇaṃ pokkharasātiṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho ambaṭṭhaṃ māṇavaṃ brāhmaṇo pokkharasāti etadavoca:**He went by carriage as far as the terrain allowed, then descended and approached the brahmin Pokkharasāti on foot. He bowed and sat down to one side, and Pokkharasāti said to him:*";
P_HTM[1650]="*“kacci, tāta ambaṭṭha, addasa taṃ bhavantaṃ gotaman”ti?**“I hope, dear Ambaṭṭha, you saw the Master Gotama?”*";
P_HTM[1651]="*“Addasāma kho mayaṃ, bho, taṃ bhavantaṃ gotaman”ti.**“I saw him, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1652]="*“Kacci, tāta ambaṭṭha, taṃ bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ tathā santaṃyeva saddo abbhuggato no aññathā;**“Well, does he live up to his reputation or not?”*";
P_HTM[1653]="*kacci pana so bhavaṃ gotamo tādiso no aññādiso”ti?* **";
P_HTM[1654]="*“Tathā santaṃyeva, bho, taṃ bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ saddo abbhuggato no aññathā, tādisova so bhavaṃ gotamo no aññādiso.**“He does, sir.*";
P_HTM[1655]="*Samannāgato ca so bhavaṃ gotamo dvattiṃsamahāpurisalakkhaṇehi paripuṇṇehi no aparipuṇṇehī”ti.**Master Gotama possesses the thirty-two marks completely, lacking none.”*";
P_HTM[1656]="*“Ahu pana te, tāta ambaṭṭha, samaṇena gotamena saddhiṃ kocideva kathāsallāpo”ti?**“And did you have some discussion with him?”*";
P_HTM[1657]="*“Ahu kho me, bho, samaṇena gotamena saddhiṃ kocideva kathāsallāpo”ti.**“I did.”*";
P_HTM[1658]="*“Yathā kathaṃ pana te, tāta ambaṭṭha, ahu samaṇena gotamena saddhiṃ kocideva kathāsallāpo”ti?**“And what kind of discussion did you have with him?”*";
P_HTM[1659]="*Atha kho ambaṭṭho māṇavo yāvatako ahosi bhagavatā saddhiṃ kathāsallāpo, taṃ sabbaṃ brāhmaṇassa pokkharasātissa ārocesi.**Then Ambaṭṭha informed Pokkharasāti of all they had discussed.*";
P_HTM[1660]="*Evaṃ vutte, brāhmaṇo pokkharasāti ambaṭṭhaṃ māṇavaṃ etadavoca:**Then Pokkharasāti said to Ambaṭṭha,*";
P_HTM[1661]="*“aho vata re amhākaṃ, paṇḍitaka, aho vata re amhākaṃ, bahussutaka, aho vata re amhākaṃ, tevijjaka, evarūpena kira, bho, puriso atthacarakena kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjeyya.**“Oh, our bloody fake scholar, our fake learned man, who pretends to be proficient in the three Vedas! A man who behaves like this ought, when their body breaks up, after death, to be reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.*";
P_HTM[1662]="*Yadeva kho tvaṃ, ambaṭṭha, taṃ bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ evaṃ āsajja āsajja avacāsi, atha kho so bhavaṃ gotamo amhepi evaṃ upaneyya upaneyya avaca.**It’s only because you repeatedly attacked Master Gotama like that that he kept bringing up charges against us!”*";
P_HTM[1663]="*Aho vata re amhākaṃ, paṇḍitaka, aho vata re amhākaṃ, bahussutaka, aho vata re amhākaṃ, tevijjaka, evarūpena kira, bho, puriso atthacarakena kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapajjeyyā”ti, kupito anattamano ambaṭṭhaṃ māṇavaṃ padasāyeva pavattesi.**Angry and upset, he kicked Ambaṭṭha over,*";
P_HTM[1664]="*Icchati ca tāvadeva bhagavantaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamituṃ.**and wanted to go and see the Buddha right away.*";
P_HTM[1665]="*8. Pokkharasātibuddhūpasaṅkamana**8. Pokkharasāti Visits the Buddha*";
P_HTM[1666]="*Atha kho te brāhmaṇā brāhmaṇaṃ pokkharasātiṃ etadavocuṃ:**Then those brahmins said to Pokkharasāti,*";
P_HTM[1667]="*“ativikālo kho, bho, ajja samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamituṃ.**“It’s much too late to visit the ascetic Gotama today.*";
P_HTM[1668]="*Svedāni bhavaṃ pokkharasāti samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamissatī”ti.**You can visit him tomorrow.”*";
P_HTM[1669]="*Atha kho brāhmaṇo pokkharasāti sake nivesane paṇītaṃ khādanīyaṃ bhojanīyaṃ paṭiyādāpetvā yāne āropetvā ukkāsu dhāriyamānāsu ukkaṭṭhāya niyyāsi, yena icchānaṅgalavanasaṇḍo tena pāyāsi.**So Pokkharasāti had a variety of delicious foods prepared in his own home. Then he mounted a carriage and, with attendants carrying torches, set out from Ukkaṭṭhā for the forest near Icchānaṅgala.*";
P_HTM[1670]="*Yāvatikā yānassa bhūmi yānena gantvā, yānā paccorohitvā pattikova yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami. upasaṅkamitvā bhagavatā saddhiṃ sammodi, sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho brāhmaṇo pokkharasāti bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**He went by carriage as far as the terrain allowed, then descended and entered the monastery on foot. He went up to the Buddha and exchanged greetings with him. When the greetings and polite conversation were over, he sat down to one side and said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[1671]="*“āgamā nu khvidha, bho gotama, amhākaṃ antevāsī ambaṭṭho māṇavo”ti?**“Master Gotama, has my pupil, the student Ambaṭṭha, come here?”*";
P_HTM[1672]="*“Āgamā kho te, brāhmaṇa, antevāsī ambaṭṭho māṇavo”ti.**“Yes he has, brahmin.”*";
P_HTM[1673]="*“Ahu pana te, bho gotama, ambaṭṭhena māṇavena saddhiṃ kocideva kathāsallāpo”ti?**“And did you have some discussion with him?”*";
P_HTM[1674]="*“Ahu kho me, brāhmaṇa, ambaṭṭhena māṇavena saddhiṃ kocideva kathāsallāpo”ti.**“I did.”*";
P_HTM[1675]="*“Yathākathaṃ pana te, bho gotama, ahu ambaṭṭhena māṇavena saddhiṃ kocideva kathāsallāpo”ti?**“And what kind of discussion did you have with him?”*";
P_HTM[1676]="*Atha kho bhagavā yāvatako ahosi ambaṭṭhena māṇavena saddhiṃ kathāsallāpo, taṃ sabbaṃ brāhmaṇassa pokkharasātissa ārocesi.**Then the Buddha informed Pokkharasāti of all they had discussed.*";
P_HTM[1677]="*Evaṃ vutte, brāhmaṇo pokkharasāti bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Pokkharasāti said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[1678]="*“bālo, bho gotama, ambaṭṭho māṇavo, khamatu bhavaṃ gotamo ambaṭṭhassa māṇavassā”ti.**“Ambaṭṭha is a fool, Master Gotama. Please forgive him.”*";
P_HTM[1679]="*“Sukhī hotu, brāhmaṇa, ambaṭṭho māṇavo”ti.**“May the student Ambaṭṭha be happy, brahmin.”*";
P_HTM[1680]="*Atha kho brāhmaṇo pokkharasāti bhagavato kāye dvattiṃsamahāpurisalakkhaṇāni samannesi.**Then Pokkharasāti scrutinized the Buddha’s body for the thirty-two marks of a great man.*";
P_HTM[1681]="*Addasā kho brāhmaṇo pokkharasāti bhagavato kāye dvattiṃsamahāpurisalakkhaṇāni yebhuyyena ṭhapetvā dve.**He saw all of them except for two,*";
P_HTM[1682]="*Dvīsu mahāpurisalakkhaṇesu kaṅkhati vicikicchati nādhimuccati na sampasīdati—**which he had doubts about:*";
P_HTM[1683]="*kosohite ca vatthaguyhe pahūtajivhatāya ca.**whether the private parts are retracted, and the largeness of the tongue.*";
P_HTM[1684]="*Atha kho bhagavato etadahosi:**Then it occurred to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[1685]="*“passati kho me ayaṃ brāhmaṇo pokkharasāti dvattiṃsamahāpurisalakkhaṇāni yebhuyyena ṭhapetvā dve.**“Pokkharasāti sees all the marks except for two,*";
P_HTM[1686]="*Dvīsu mahāpurisalakkhaṇesu kaṅkhati vicikicchati nādhimuccati na sampasīdati—**which he has doubts about:*";
P_HTM[1687]="*kosohite ca vatthaguyhe pahūtajivhatāya cā”ti.**whether the private parts are retracted, and the largeness of the tongue.”*";
P_HTM[1688]="*Atha kho bhagavā tathārūpaṃ iddhābhisaṅkhāraṃ abhisaṅkhāsi yathā addasa brāhmaṇo pokkharasāti bhagavato kosohitaṃ vatthaguyhaṃ.**Then the Buddha used his psychic power to will that Brahmāyu would see his retracted private parts.*";
P_HTM[1689]="*Atha kho bhagavā jivhaṃ ninnāmetvā ubhopi kaṇṇasotāni anumasi paṭimasi, ubhopi nāsikasotāni anumasi paṭimasi, kevalampi nalāṭamaṇḍalaṃ jivhāya chādesi.**And he stuck out his tongue and stroked back and forth on his ear holes and nostrils, and covered his entire forehead with his tongue.*";
P_HTM[1690]="*Atha kho brāhmaṇassa pokkharasātissa etadahosi:**Pokkharasāti thought,*";
P_HTM[1691]="*“samannāgato kho samaṇo gotamo dvattiṃsamahāpurisalakkhaṇehi paripuṇṇehi no aparipuṇṇehī”ti.**“The ascetic Gotama possesses the thirty-two marks completely, lacking none.”*";
P_HTM[1692]="*Bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**He said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[1693]="*“adhivāsetu me bhavaṃ gotamo ajjatanāya bhattaṃ saddhiṃ bhikkhusaṅghenā”ti.**“Would Master Gotama together with the mendicant Saṅgha please accept today’s meal from me?”*";
P_HTM[1694]="*Adhivāsesi bhagavā tuṇhībhāvena.**The Buddha consented in silence.*";
P_HTM[1695]="*Atha kho brāhmaṇo pokkharasāti bhagavato adhivāsanaṃ viditvā bhagavato kālaṃ ārocesi:**Then, knowing that the Buddha had consented, Pokkharasāti announced the time to him,*";
P_HTM[1696]="*“kālo, bho gotama, niṭṭhitaṃ bhattan”ti.**“It’s time, Master Gotama, the meal is ready.”*";
P_HTM[1697]="*Atha kho bhagavā pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya saddhiṃ bhikkhusaṅghena yena brāhmaṇassa pokkharasātissa nivesanaṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdi.**Then the Buddha robed up in the morning and, taking his bowl and robe, went to the home of Pokkharasāti together with the mendicant Saṅgha, where he sat on the seat spread out.*";
P_HTM[1698]="*Atha kho brāhmaṇo pokkharasāti bhagavantaṃ paṇītena khādanīyena bhojanīyena sahatthā santappesi sampavāresi, māṇavakāpi bhikkhusaṅghaṃ.**Then Pokkharasāti served and satisfied the Buddha with his own hands with a variety of delicious foods, while his students served the Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[1699]="*Atha kho brāhmaṇo pokkharasāti bhagavantaṃ bhuttāviṃ onītapattapāṇiṃ aññataraṃ nīcaṃ āsanaṃ gahetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi.**When the Buddha had eaten and washed his hand and bowl, Pokkharasāti took a low seat and sat to one side.*";
P_HTM[1700]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinnassa kho brāhmaṇassa pokkharasātissa bhagavā anupubbiṃ kathaṃ kathesi,**Then the Buddha taught him step by step, with*";
P_HTM[1701]="*seyyathidaṃ—dānakathaṃ sīlakathaṃ saggakathaṃ;**a talk on giving, ethical conduct, and heaven.*";
P_HTM[1702]="*kāmānaṃ ādīnavaṃ okāraṃ saṅkilesaṃ, nekkhamme ānisaṃsaṃ pakāsesi.**He explained the drawbacks of sensual pleasures, so sordid and corrupt, and the benefit of renunciation.*";
P_HTM[1703]="*Yadā bhagavā aññāsi brāhmaṇaṃ pokkharasātiṃ kallacittaṃ muducittaṃ vinīvaraṇacittaṃ udaggacittaṃ pasannacittaṃ, atha yā buddhānaṃ sāmukkaṃsikā dhammadesanā, taṃ pakāsesi—**And when the Buddha knew that Pokkharasāti’s mind was ready, pliable, rid of hindrances, joyful, and confident he explained the special teaching of the Buddhas:*";
P_HTM[1704]="*dukkhaṃ samudayaṃ nirodhaṃ maggaṃ.**suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path.*";
P_HTM[1705]="*Seyyathāpi nāma suddhaṃ vatthaṃ apagatakāḷakaṃ sammadeva rajanaṃ paṭiggaṇheyya;**Just as a clean cloth rid of stains would properly absorb dye,*";
P_HTM[1706]="*evameva brāhmaṇassa pokkharasātissa tasmiññeva āsane virajaṃ vītamalaṃ dhammacakkhuṃ udapādi:**in that very seat the stainless, immaculate vision of the Dhamma arose in the brahmin Pokkharasāti:*";
P_HTM[1707]="*“yaṃ kiñci samudayadhammaṃ sabbaṃ taṃ nirodhadhamman”ti.**“Everything that has a beginning has an end.”*";
P_HTM[1708]="*9. Pokkharasātiupāsakattapaṭivedanā**9. Pokkharasāti Declares Himself a Lay Follower*";
P_HTM[1709]="*Atha kho brāhmaṇo pokkharasāti diṭṭhadhammo pattadhammo viditadhammo pariyogāḷhadhammo tiṇṇavicikiccho vigatakathaṃkatho vesārajjappatto aparappaccayo satthusāsane bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Pokkharasāti saw, attained, understood, and fathomed the Dhamma. He went beyond doubt, got rid of indecision, and became self-assured and independent of others regarding the Teacher’s instructions. He said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[1710]="*“abhikkantaṃ, bho gotama, abhikkantaṃ, bho gotama.**“Excellent, Master Gotama! Excellent!*";
P_HTM[1711]="*Seyyathāpi, bho gotama, nikkujjitaṃ vā ukkujjeyya, paṭicchannaṃ vā vivareyya, mūḷhassa vā maggaṃ ācikkheyya, andhakāre vā telapajjotaṃ dhāreyya: ‘cakkhumanto rūpāni dakkhantī’ti; evamevaṃ bhotā gotamena anekapariyāyena dhammo pakāsito.**As if he were righting the overturned, or revealing the hidden, or pointing out the path to the lost, or lighting a lamp in the dark so people with good eyes can see what’s there, just so has Master Gotama made the Teaching clear in many ways.*";
P_HTM[1712]="*Esāhaṃ, bho gotama, saputto sabhariyo sapariso sāmacco bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ saraṇaṃ gacchāmi dhammañca bhikkhusaṃghañca.**Together with my children, wives, retinue, and ministers, I go for refuge to Master Gotama, to the teaching, and to the mendicant Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[1713]="*Upāsakaṃ maṃ bhavaṃ gotamo dhāretu ajjatagge pāṇupetaṃ saraṇaṃ gataṃ.**From this day forth, may Master Gotama remember me as a lay follower who has gone for refuge for life.*";
P_HTM[1714]="*Yathā ca bhavaṃ gotamo ukkaṭṭhāya aññāni upāsakakulāni upasaṅkamati, evameva bhavaṃ gotamo pokkharasātikulaṃ upasaṅkamatu.**Just as Master Gotama visits other devoted families in Ukkaṭṭhā, may he visit mine.*";
P_HTM[1715]="*Tattha ye te māṇavakā vā māṇavikā vā bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ abhivādessanti vā paccuṭṭhissanti vā āsanaṃ vā udakaṃ vā dassanti cittaṃ vā pasādessanti, tesaṃ taṃ bhavissati dīgharattaṃ hitāya sukhāyā”ti.**The brahmin boys and girls there will bow to you, rise in your presence, give you a seat and water, and gain confidence in their hearts. That will be for their lasting welfare and happiness.”*";
P_HTM[1716]="*“Kalyāṇaṃ vuccati, brāhmaṇā”ti.**“That’s good of you to say, householder.”*";
P_HTM[1717]="*Ambaṭṭhasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ tatiyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1718]="*04. Soṇadaṇḍasutta  - With Soṇadaṇḍa * **";
P_HTM[1719]="*1. Campeyyakabrāhmaṇagahapatikā**1. The Brahmins and Householders of Campā*";
P_HTM[1720]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[1721]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā aṅgesu cārikaṃ caramāno mahatā bhikkhusaṅghena saddhiṃ pañcamattehi bhikkhusatehi yena campā tadavasari.**At one time the Buddha was wandering in the land of the Aṅgas together with a large Saṅgha of around five hundred mendicants when he arrived at Campā,*";
P_HTM[1722]="*Tatra sudaṃ bhagavā campāyaṃ viharati gaggarāya pokkharaṇiyā tīre.**where he stayed by the banks of the Gaggarā Lotus Pond.*";
P_HTM[1723]="*Tena kho pana samayena soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo campaṃ ajjhāvasati sattussadaṃ satiṇakaṭṭhodakaṃ sadhaññaṃ rājabhoggaṃ raññā māgadhena seniyena bimbisārena dinnaṃ rājadāyaṃ brahmadeyyaṃ.**Now at that time the brahmin Soṇadaṇḍa was living in Campā. It was a crown property given by King Seniya Bimbisāra of Magadha, teeming with living creatures, full of hay, wood, water, and grain, a royal endowment of the highest quality.*";
P_HTM[1724]="*Assosuṃ kho campeyyakā brāhmaṇagahapatikā:**The brahmins and householders of Campā heard:*";
P_HTM[1725]="*“samaṇo khalu bho gotamo sakyaputto sakyakulā pabbajito aṅgesu cārikaṃ caramāno mahatā bhikkhusaṃghena saddhiṃ pañcamattehi bhikkhusatehi campaṃ anuppatto campāyaṃ viharati gaggarāya pokkharaṇiyā tīre.**“It seems the ascetic Gotama—a Sakyan, gone forth from a Sakyan family—has arrived at Campā and is staying on the banks of the Gaggarā Lotus Pond.*";
P_HTM[1726]="*Taṃ kho pana bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ evaṃ kalyāṇo kittisaddo abbhuggato:**He has this good reputation:*";
P_HTM[1727]="*‘itipi so bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā’.**‘That Blessed One is perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.’*";
P_HTM[1728]="*So imaṃ lokaṃ sadevakaṃ samārakaṃ sabrahmakaṃ sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiṃ pajaṃ sadevamanussaṃ sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedeti.**He has realized with his own insight this world—with its gods, Māras and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, gods and humans—and he makes it known to others.*";
P_HTM[1729]="*So dhammaṃ deseti ādikalyāṇaṃ majjhekalyāṇaṃ pariyosānakalyāṇaṃ sātthaṃ sabyañjanaṃ kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ pakāseti.**He teaches Dhamma that’s good in the beginning, good in the middle, and good in the end, meaningful and well-phrased. And he reveals a spiritual practice that’s entirely full and pure.*";
P_HTM[1730]="*Sādhu kho pana tathārūpānaṃ arahataṃ dassanaṃ hotī”ti.**It’s good to see such perfected ones.”*";
P_HTM[1731]="*Atha kho campeyyakā brāhmaṇagahapatikā campāya nikkhamitvā saṅghasaṅghī gaṇībhūtā yena gaggarā pokkharaṇī tenupasaṅkamanti.**Then, having departed Campā, they formed into companies and headed to the Gaggarā Lotus Pond.*";
P_HTM[1732]="*Tena kho pana samayena soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo uparipāsāde divāseyyaṃ upagato hoti.**Now at that time the brahmin Soṇadaṇḍa had retired to the upper floor of his stilt longhouse for his midday nap.*";
P_HTM[1733]="*Addasā kho soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo campeyyake brāhmaṇagahapatike campāya nikkhamitvā saṅghasaṅghī gaṇībhūte yena gaggarā pokkharaṇī tenupasaṅkamante.**He saw the brahmins and householders heading for the lotus pond,*";
P_HTM[1734]="*Disvā khattaṃ āmantesi:**and addressed his steward,*";
P_HTM[1735]="*“kiṃ nu kho, bho khatte, campeyyakā brāhmaṇagahapatikā campāya nikkhamitvā saṅghasaṅghī gaṇībhūtā yena gaggarā pokkharaṇī tenupasaṅkamantī”ti?**“My steward, why are the brahmins and householders headed for the Gaggarā Lotus Pond?”*";
P_HTM[1736]="*“Atthi kho, bho, samaṇo gotamo sakyaputto sakyakulā pabbajito aṅgesu cārikaṃ caramāno mahatā bhikkhusaṃghena saddhiṃ pañcamattehi bhikkhusatehi campaṃ anuppatto campāyaṃ viharati gaggarāya pokkharaṇiyā tīre.**“The ascetic Gotama has arrived at Campā and is staying on the banks of the Gaggarā Lotus Pond.*";
P_HTM[1737]="*Taṃ kho pana bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ evaṃ kalyāṇo kittisaddo abbhuggato:**He has this good reputation:*";
P_HTM[1738]="*‘itipi so bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā’ti.**‘That Blessed One is perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.’*";
P_HTM[1739]="*Tamete bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamantī”ti.**They’re going to see that Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[1740]="*“Tena hi, bho khatte, yena campeyyakā brāhmaṇagahapatikā tenupasaṅkama, upasaṅkamitvā campeyyake brāhmaṇagahapatike evaṃ vadehi:**“Well then, go to the brahmins and householders and say to them:*";
P_HTM[1741]="*‘soṇadaṇḍo, bho, brāhmaṇo evamāha—**‘Sirs, the brahmin Soṇadaṇḍa asks*";
P_HTM[1742]="*āgamentu kira bhavanto, soṇadaṇḍopi brāhmaṇo samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamissatī’”ti.**you to wait, as he will also go to see the ascetic Gotama.’”*";
P_HTM[1743]="*“Evaṃ, bho”ti kho so khattā soṇadaṇḍassa brāhmaṇassa paṭissutvā yena campeyyakā brāhmaṇagahapatikā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā campeyyake brāhmaṇagahapatike etadavoca:**“Yes, sir,” replied the steward, and did as he was asked.*";
P_HTM[1744]="*“soṇadaṇḍo bho brāhmaṇo evamāha:* **";
P_HTM[1745]="*‘āgamentu kira bhavanto, soṇadaṇḍopi brāhmaṇo samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamissatī’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[1746]="*2. Soṇadaṇḍaguṇakathā**2. The Qualities of Soṇadaṇḍa*";
P_HTM[1747]="*Tena kho pana samayena nānāverajjakānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ pañcamattāni brāhmaṇasatāni campāyaṃ paṭivasanti kenacideva karaṇīyena.**Now at that time around five hundred brahmins from abroad were residing in Campā on some business.*";
P_HTM[1748]="*Assosuṃ kho te brāhmaṇā:**They heard that*";
P_HTM[1749]="*“soṇadaṇḍo kira brāhmaṇo samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamissatī”ti.**the brahmin Soṇadaṇḍa was going to see the ascetic Gotama.*";
P_HTM[1750]="*Atha kho te brāhmaṇā yena soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā soṇadaṇḍaṃ brāhmaṇaṃ etadavocuṃ:**They approached Soṇadaṇḍa and said to him,*";
P_HTM[1751]="*“saccaṃ kira bhavaṃ soṇadaṇḍo samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamissatī”ti?**“Is it really true that you are going to see the ascetic Gotama?”*";
P_HTM[1752]="*“Evaṃ kho me, bho, hoti:**“Yes, gentlemen, it is true.”*";
P_HTM[1753]="*‘ahampi samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamissāmī’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[1754]="*“Mā bhavaṃ soṇadaṇḍo samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkami.**“Please don’t, master Soṇadaṇḍa!*";
P_HTM[1755]="*Na arahati bhavaṃ soṇadaṇḍo samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamituṃ.**It’s not appropriate for you to go to see the ascetic Gotama.*";
P_HTM[1756]="*Sace bhavaṃ soṇadaṇḍo samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamissati, bhoto soṇadaṇḍassa yaso hāyissati, samaṇassa gotamassa yaso abhivaḍḍhissati.**For if you do so, your reputation will diminish and his will increase.*";
P_HTM[1757]="*Yampi bhoto soṇadaṇḍassa yaso hāyissati, samaṇassa gotamassa yaso abhivaḍḍhissati, imināpaṅgena na arahati bhavaṃ soṇadaṇḍo samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamituṃ;**For this reason it’s not appropriate for you to go to see the ascetic Gotama;*";
P_HTM[1758]="*samaṇo tveva gotamo arahati bhavantaṃ soṇadaṇḍaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamituṃ.**it’s appropriate that he comes to see you.*";
P_HTM[1759]="*Bhavañhi soṇadaṇḍo ubhato sujāto mātito ca pitito ca, saṃsuddhagahaṇiko yāva sattamā pitāmahayugā akkhitto anupakkuṭṭho jātivādena.**You are well born on both your mother’s and father’s side, of pure descent, irrefutable and impeccable in questions of ancestry back to the seventh paternal generation.*";
P_HTM[1760]="*Yampi bhavaṃ soṇadaṇḍo ubhato sujāto mātito ca pitito ca, saṃsuddhagahaṇiko yāva sattamā pitāmahayugā akkhitto anupakkuṭṭho jātivādena, imināpaṅgena na arahati bhavaṃ soṇadaṇḍo samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamituṃ;**For this reason it’s not appropriate for you to go to see the ascetic Gotama;*";
P_HTM[1761]="*samaṇo tveva gotamo arahati bhavantaṃ soṇadaṇḍaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamituṃ.**it’s appropriate that he comes to see you.*";
P_HTM[1762]="*Bhavañhi soṇadaṇḍo aḍḍho mahaddhano mahābhogo … pe …**You’re rich, affluent, and wealthy. …*";
P_HTM[1763]="*Bhavañhi soṇadaṇḍo ajjhāyako mantadharo tiṇṇaṃ vedānaṃ pāragū sanighaṇḍukeṭubhānaṃ sākkharappabhedānaṃ itihāsapañcamānaṃ padako veyyākaraṇo, lokāyatamahāpurisalakkhaṇesu anavayo … pe …**You recite and remember the hymns, and are have mastered the three Vedas, together with their vocabularies, ritual, phonology and etymology, and the testament as fifth. You know philology and grammar, and are well versed in cosmology and the marks of a great man. …*";
P_HTM[1764]="*Bhavañhi soṇadaṇḍo abhirūpo dassanīyo pāsādiko paramāya vaṇṇapokkharatāya samannāgato brahmavaṇṇī brahmavacchasī akhuddāvakāso dassanāya … pe …**You are attractive, good-looking, lovely, of surpassing beauty. You are magnificent, splendid, remarkable to behold. …*";
P_HTM[1765]="*Bhavañhi soṇadaṇḍo sīlavā vuddhasīlī vuddhasīlena samannāgato … pe …**You are ethical, mature in ethical conduct. …*";
P_HTM[1766]="*Bhavañhi soṇadaṇḍo kalyāṇavāco kalyāṇavākkaraṇo poriyā vācāya samannāgato vissaṭṭhāya anelagalāya atthassa viññāpaniyā … pe …**You’re a good speaker, with a polished, clear, and articulate voice that expresses the meaning. …*";
P_HTM[1767]="*Bhavañhi soṇadaṇḍo bahūnaṃ ācariyapācariyo tīṇi māṇavakasatāni mante vāceti. Bahū kho pana nānādisā nānājanapadā māṇavakā āgacchanti bhoto soṇadaṇḍassa santike mantatthikā mante adhiyitukāmā … pe …**You teach the teachers of many, and teach three hundred students to recite the hymns. Many students come from various districts and countries for the sake of the hymns, wishing to learn the hymns. …*";
P_HTM[1768]="*Bhavañhi soṇadaṇḍo jiṇṇo vuddho mahallako addhagato vayoanuppatto;**You’re old, elderly and senior, advanced in years, and have reached the final stage of life.*";
P_HTM[1769]="*samaṇo gotamo taruṇo ceva taruṇapabbajito ca … pe …**The ascetic Gotama is young, and has newly gone forth. …*";
P_HTM[1770]="*Bhavañhi soṇadaṇḍo rañño māgadhassa seniyassa bimbisārassa sakkato garukato mānito pūjito apacito … pe …**You’re honored, respected, revered, venerated, and esteemed by King Bimbisāra of Magadha …*";
P_HTM[1771]="*Bhavañhi soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇassa pokkharasātissa sakkato garukato mānito pūjito apacito … pe …**and the brahmin Pokkharasāti. …*";
P_HTM[1772]="*Bhavañhi soṇadaṇḍo campaṃ ajjhāvasati sattussadaṃ satiṇakaṭṭhodakaṃ sadhaññaṃ rājabhoggaṃ, raññā māgadhena seniyena bimbisārena dinnaṃ, rājadāyaṃ brahmadeyyaṃ.**You live in Campā, a crown property given by King Seniya Bimbisāra of Magadha, teeming with living creatures, full of hay, wood, water, and grain, a royal endowment of the highest quality.*";
P_HTM[1773]="*Yampi bhavaṃ soṇadaṇḍo campaṃ ajjhāvasati sattussadaṃ satiṇakaṭṭhodakaṃ sadhaññaṃ rājabhoggaṃ, raññā māgadhena seniyena bimbisārena dinnaṃ, rājadāyaṃ brahmadeyyaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1774]="*Imināpaṅgena na arahati bhavaṃ soṇadaṇḍo samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamituṃ;**For this reason, too, it’s not appropriate for you to go to see the ascetic Gotama;*";
P_HTM[1775]="*samaṇo tveva gotamo arahati bhavantaṃ soṇadaṇḍaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamitun”ti.**it’s appropriate that he comes to see you.*";
P_HTM[1776]="*3. Buddhaguṇakathā**3. The Qualities of the Buddha*";
P_HTM[1777]="*Evaṃ vutte, soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo te brāhmaṇe etadavoca:**When they had spoken, Soṇadaṇḍa said to those brahmins:*";
P_HTM[1778]="*“Tena hi, bho, mamapi suṇātha, yathā mayameva arahāma taṃ bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamituṃ;**“Well then, gentlemen, listen to why it’s appropriate for me to go to see the ascetic Gotama,*";
P_HTM[1779]="*na tveva arahati so bhavaṃ gotamo amhākaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamituṃ.**and it’s not appropriate for him to come to see me.*";
P_HTM[1780]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo ubhato sujāto mātito ca pitito ca, saṃsuddhagahaṇiko yāva sattamā pitāmahayugā, akkhitto anupakkuṭṭho jātivādena.**He is well born on both his mother’s and father’s side, of pure descent, irrefutable and impeccable in questions of ancestry back to the seventh paternal generation.*";
P_HTM[1781]="*Yampi, bho, samaṇo gotamo ubhato sujāto mātito ca pitito ca saṃsuddhagahaṇiko yāva sattamā pitāmahayugā, akkhitto anupakkuṭṭho jātivādena, imināpaṅgena na arahati so bhavaṃ gotamo amhākaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamituṃ;**For this reason it’s not appropriate for the ascetic Gotama to come to see me;*";
P_HTM[1782]="*atha kho mayameva arahāma taṃ bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamituṃ.**rather, it’s appropriate for me to go to see him.*";
P_HTM[1783]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo mahantaṃ ñātisaṅghaṃ ohāya pabbajito … pe …**When he went forth he abandoned a large family circle. …*";
P_HTM[1784]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo pahūtaṃ hiraññasuvaṇṇaṃ ohāya pabbajito bhūmigatañca vehāsaṭṭhaṃ ca … pe …**When he went forth he abandoned abundant gold coin and bullion stored in dungeons and towers. …*";
P_HTM[1785]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo daharova samāno yuvā susukāḷakeso bhadrena yobbanena samannāgato paṭhamena vayasā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajito … pe …**He went forth from the lay life to homelessness while still a youth, young, black-haired, blessed with youth, in the prime of life. …*";
P_HTM[1786]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo akāmakānaṃ mātāpitūnaṃ assumukhānaṃ rudantānaṃ kesamassuṃ ohāretvā kāsāyāni vatthāni acchādetvā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajito … pe …**Though his mother and father wished otherwise, weeping with tearful faces, he shaved off his hair and beard, dressed in ocher robes, and went forth from the lay life to homelessness. …*";
P_HTM[1787]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo abhirūpo dassanīyo pāsādiko paramāya vaṇṇapokkharatāya samannāgato, brahmavaṇṇī, brahmavacchasī, akhuddāvakāso dassanāya … pe …**He is attractive, good-looking, lovely, of surpassing beauty. He is magnificent, splendid, remarkable to behold. …*";
P_HTM[1788]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo sīlavā ariyasīlī kusalasīlī kusalasīlena samannāgato … pe …**He is ethical, possessing ethical conduct that is noble and skillful. …*";
P_HTM[1789]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo kalyāṇavāco kalyāṇavākkaraṇo poriyā vācāya samannāgato vissaṭṭhāya anelagalāya atthassa viññāpaniyā … pe …**He’s a good speaker, with a polished, clear, and articulate voice that expresses the meaning. …*";
P_HTM[1790]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo bahūnaṃ ācariyapācariyo … pe …**He’s a teacher of teachers. …*";
P_HTM[1791]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo khīṇakāmarāgo vigatacāpallo … pe …**He has ended sensual desire, and is rid of caprice. …*";
P_HTM[1792]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo kammavādī kiriyavādī apāpapurekkhāro brahmaññāya pajāya … pe …**He teaches the efficacy of deeds and action. He doesn’t wish any harm upon the community of brahmins. …*";
P_HTM[1793]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo uccā kulā pabbajito asambhinnakhattiyakulā … pe …**He went forth from an eminent family of unbroken aristocratic lineage. …*";
P_HTM[1794]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo aḍḍhā kulā pabbajito mahaddhanā mahābhogā … pe …**He went forth from a rich, affluent, and wealthy family. …*";
P_HTM[1795]="*Samaṇaṃ khalu, bho, gotamaṃ tiroraṭṭhā tirojanapadā pañhaṃ pucchituṃ āgacchanti … pe …**People come from distant lands and distant countries to question him. …*";
P_HTM[1796]="*Samaṇaṃ khalu, bho, gotamaṃ anekāni devatāsahassāni pāṇehi saraṇaṃ gatāni … pe …**Many thousands of deities have gone for refuge for life to him. …*";
P_HTM[1797]="*Samaṇaṃ khalu, bho, gotamaṃ evaṃ kalyāṇo kittisaddo abbhuggato:**He has this good reputation:*";
P_HTM[1798]="*‘itipi so bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā’ti … pe …**‘That Blessed One is perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.’ …*";
P_HTM[1799]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo dvattiṃsamahāpurisalakkhaṇehi samannāgato … pe …**He has the thirty-two marks of a great man. …*";
P_HTM[1800]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo ehisvāgatavādī sakhilo sammodako abbhākuṭiko uttānamukho pubbabhāsī … pe …**He is welcoming, congenial, polite, smiling, open, the first to speak. …*";
P_HTM[1801]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo catunnaṃ parisānaṃ sakkato garukato mānito pūjito apacito … pe …**He’s honored, respected, revered, venerated, and esteemed by the four assemblies. …*";
P_HTM[1802]="*Samaṇe khalu, bho, gotame bahū devā ca manussā ca abhippasannā … pe …**Many gods and humans are devoted to him. …*";
P_HTM[1803]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo yasmiṃ gāme vā nigame vā paṭivasati, na tasmiṃ gāme vā nigame vā amanussā manusse viheṭhenti … pe …**While he is residing in a village or town, non-human entities do not harass them. …*";
P_HTM[1804]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo saṅghī gaṇī gaṇācariyo puthutitthakarānaṃ aggamakkhāyati. Yathā kho pana, bho, etesaṃ samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ yathā vā tathā vā yaso samudāgacchati, na hevaṃ samaṇassa gotamassa yaso samudāgato.**He leads an order and a community, and teaches a community, and is said to be the best of the various religious founders. He didn’t come by his fame in the same ways as those other ascetics and brahmins.*";
P_HTM[1805]="*Atha kho anuttarāya vijjācaraṇasampadāya samaṇassa gotamassa yaso samudāgato … pe …**Rather, he came by his fame due to his supreme knowledge and conduct. …*";
P_HTM[1806]="*Samaṇaṃ khalu, bho, gotamaṃ rājā māgadho seniyo bimbisāro saputto sabhariyo sapariso sāmacco pāṇehi saraṇaṃ gato … pe …**King Seniya Bimbisāra of Magadha and his wives and children have gone for refuge for life to the ascetic Gotama. …*";
P_HTM[1807]="*Samaṇaṃ khalu, bho, gotamaṃ rājā pasenadi kosalo saputto sabhariyo sapariso sāmacco pāṇehi saraṇaṃ gato … pe …**King Pasenadi of Kosala and his wives and children have gone for refuge for life to the ascetic Gotama. …*";
P_HTM[1808]="*Samaṇaṃ khalu, bho, gotamaṃ brāhmaṇo pokkharasāti saputto sabhariyo sapariso sāmacco pāṇehi saraṇaṃ gato … pe …**The brahmin Pokkharasāti and his wives and children have gone for refuge for life to the ascetic Gotama. …*";
P_HTM[1809]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo rañño māgadhassa seniyassa bimbisārassa sakkato garukato mānito pūjito apacito … pe …**He’s honored, respected, revered, venerated, and esteemed by King Bimbisāra of Magadha …*";
P_HTM[1810]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo rañño pasenadissa kosalassa sakkato garukato mānito pūjito apacito … pe …**King Pasenadi of Kosala …*";
P_HTM[1811]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo brāhmaṇassa pokkharasātissa sakkato garukato mānito pūjito apacito … pe …**and the brahmin Pokkharasāti.*";
P_HTM[1812]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo campaṃ anuppatto, campāyaṃ viharati gaggarāya pokkharaṇiyā tīre.**The ascetic Gotama has arrived at Campā and is staying at the Gaggarā Lotus Pond.*";
P_HTM[1813]="*Ye kho pana, bho, keci samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā amhākaṃ gāmakhettaṃ āgacchanti atithī no te honti.**Any ascetic or brahmin who comes to stay in our village district is our guest,*";
P_HTM[1814]="*Atithī kho panamhehi sakkātabbā garukātabbā mānetabbā pūjetabbā apacetabbā.**and should be honored and respected as such.*";
P_HTM[1815]="*Yampi, bho, samaṇo gotamo campaṃ anuppatto campāyaṃ viharati gaggarāya pokkharaṇiyā tīre, atithimhākaṃ samaṇo gotamo;* **";
P_HTM[1816]="*atithi kho panamhehi sakkātabbo garukātabbo mānetabbo pūjetabbo apacetabbo.* **";
P_HTM[1817]="*Imināpaṅgena na arahati so bhavaṃ gotamo amhākaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamituṃ.**For this reason, too, it’s not appropriate for Master Gotama to come to see me;*";
P_HTM[1818]="*Atha kho mayameva arahāma taṃ bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamituṃ.**rather, it’s appropriate for me to go to see him.*";
P_HTM[1819]="*Ettake kho ahaṃ, bho, tassa bhoto gotamassa vaṇṇe pariyāpuṇāmi, no ca kho so bhavaṃ gotamo ettakavaṇṇo.**This is the extent of Master Gotama’s praise that I have learned. But his praises are not confined to this,*";
P_HTM[1820]="*Aparimāṇavaṇṇo hi so bhavaṃ gotamo”ti.**for the praise of Master Gotama is limitless.”*";
P_HTM[1821]="*Evaṃ vutte, te brāhmaṇā soṇadaṇḍaṃ brāhmaṇaṃ etadavocuṃ:**When he had spoken, those brahmins said to him,*";
P_HTM[1822]="*“yathā kho bhavaṃ soṇadaṇḍo samaṇassa gotamassa vaṇṇe bhāsati ito cepi so bhavaṃ gotamo yojanasate viharati, alameva saddhena kulaputtena dassanāya upasaṅkamituṃ api puṭosenā”ti.**“According to Soṇadaṇḍa’s praises, if Master Gotama were staying within a hundred leagues, it’d be worthwhile for a faithful gentleman to go to see him, even if they had to carry their own provisions in a shoulder bag.”*";
P_HTM[1823]="*“Tena hi, bho, sabbeva mayaṃ samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamissāmā”ti.**“Well then, gentlemen, let’s all go to see the ascetic Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[1824]="*4. Soṇadaṇḍaparivitakka**4. Soṇadaṇḍa’s Second Thoughts*";
P_HTM[1825]="*Atha kho soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo mahatā brāhmaṇagaṇena saddhiṃ yena gaggarā pokkharaṇī tenupasaṅkami.**Then Soṇadaṇḍa together with a large group of brahmins went to see the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[1826]="*Atha kho soṇadaṇḍassa brāhmaṇassa tirovanasaṇḍagatassa evaṃ cetaso parivitakko udapādi:**But as he reached the far side of the forest, this thought came to mind,*";
P_HTM[1827]="*“ahañceva kho pana samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ pañhaṃ puccheyyaṃ;**“Suppose I was to ask the ascetic Gotama a question.*";
P_HTM[1828]="*tatra ce maṃ samaṇo gotamo evaṃ vadeyya:**He might say to me:*";
P_HTM[1829]="*‘na kho esa, brāhmaṇa, pañho evaṃ pucchitabbo, evaṃ nāmesa, brāhmaṇa, pañho pucchitabbo’ti, tena maṃ ayaṃ parisā paribhaveyya:**‘Brahmin, you shouldn’t ask your question like that. This is how you should ask it.’ And the assembly might disparage me for that:*";
P_HTM[1830]="*‘bālo soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo abyatto, nāsakkhi samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ yoniso pañhaṃ pucchitun’ti.**‘Soṇadaṇḍa is foolish and incompetent. He’s not able to properly ask the ascetic Gotama a question.’*";
P_HTM[1831]="*Yaṃ kho panāyaṃ parisā paribhaveyya, yasopi tassa hāyetha.**And when you’re disparaged by the assembly, your reputation diminishes.*";
P_HTM[1832]="*Yassa kho pana yaso hāyetha, bhogāpi tassa hāyeyyuṃ.**When your reputation diminishes, your wealth also diminishes.*";
P_HTM[1833]="*Yasoladdhā kho panamhākaṃ bhogā.**But my wealth relies on my reputation.*";
P_HTM[1834]="*Mamañceva kho pana samaṇo gotamo pañhaṃ puccheyya, tassa cāhaṃ pañhassa veyyākaraṇena cittaṃ na ārādheyyaṃ;**Or if the ascetic Gotama asks me a question, I might not satisfy him with my answer.*";
P_HTM[1835]="*tatra ce maṃ samaṇo gotamo evaṃ vadeyya:**He might say to me:*";
P_HTM[1836]="*‘na kho esa, brāhmaṇa, pañho evaṃ byākātabbo, evaṃ nāmesa, brāhmaṇa, pañho byākātabbo’ti, tena maṃ ayaṃ parisā paribhaveyya:**‘Brahmin, you shouldn’t answer the question like that. This is how you should answer it.’ And the assembly might disparage me for that:*";
P_HTM[1837]="*‘bālo soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo abyatto, nāsakkhi samaṇassa gotamassa pañhassa veyyākaraṇena cittaṃ ārādhetun’ti.**‘Soṇadaṇḍa is foolish and incompetent. He’s not able to satisfy the ascetic Gotama’s mind with his answer.’*";
P_HTM[1838]="*Yaṃ kho panāyaṃ parisā paribhaveyya, yasopi tassa hāyetha.**And when you’re disparaged by the assembly, your reputation diminishes.*";
P_HTM[1839]="*Yassa kho pana yaso hāyetha, bhogāpi tassa hāyeyyuṃ.**When your reputation diminishes, your wealth also diminishes.*";
P_HTM[1840]="*Yasoladdhā kho panamhākaṃ bhogā.**But my wealth relies on my reputation.*";
P_HTM[1841]="*Ahañceva kho pana evaṃ samīpagato samāno adisvāva samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ nivatteyyaṃ, tena maṃ ayaṃ parisā paribhaveyya:**On the other hand, if I were to turn back after having come so far without having seen the ascetic Gotama, the assembly might disparage me for that:*";
P_HTM[1842]="*‘bālo soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo abyatto mānathaddho bhīto ca, no visahati samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamituṃ, kathañhi nāma evaṃ samīpagato samāno adisvā samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ nivattissatī’ti.**‘Soṇadaṇḍa is foolish and incompetent. He’s stuck-up and scared. He doesn’t dare to go and see the ascetic Gotama. For how on earth can he turn back after having come so far without having seen the ascetic Gotama!’*";
P_HTM[1843]="*Yaṃ kho panāyaṃ parisā paribhaveyya, yasopi tassa hāyetha.**And when you’re disparaged by the assembly, your reputation diminishes.*";
P_HTM[1844]="*Yassa kho pana yaso hāyetha, bhogāpi tassa hāyeyyuṃ,**When your reputation diminishes, your wealth also diminishes.*";
P_HTM[1845]="*yasoladdhā kho panamhākaṃ bhogā”ti.**But my wealth relies on my reputation.”*";
P_HTM[1846]="*Atha kho soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavatā saddhiṃ sammodi.**Then Soṇadaṇḍa went up to the Buddha, and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[1847]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi.**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, he sat down to one side.*";
P_HTM[1848]="*Campeyyakāpi kho brāhmaṇagahapatikā appekacce bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu; appekacce bhagavatā saddhiṃ sammodiṃsu; sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu; appekacce yena bhagavā tenañjaliṃ paṇāmetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu; appekacce nāmagottaṃ sāvetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu; appekacce tuṇhībhūtā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu.**Before sitting down to one side, some of the brahmins and householders of Campā bowed, some exchanged greetings and polite conversation, some held up their joined palms toward the Buddha, some announced their name and clan, while some kept silent.*";
P_HTM[1849]="*Tatrapi sudaṃ soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo etadeva bahulamanuvitakkento nisinno hoti:**But while sitting there, Soṇadaṇḍa continued to be plagued by many second thoughts. He thought,*";
P_HTM[1850]="*“ahañceva kho pana samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ pañhaṃ puccheyyaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[1851]="*tatra ce maṃ samaṇo gotamo evaṃ vadeyya:* **";
P_HTM[1852]="*‘na kho esa, brāhmaṇa, pañho evaṃ pucchitabbo, evaṃ nāmesa, brāhmaṇa, pañho pucchitabbo’ti, tena maṃ ayaṃ parisā paribhaveyya:* **";
P_HTM[1853]="*‘bālo soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo abyatto, nāsakkhi samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ yoniso pañhaṃ pucchitun’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1854]="*Yaṃ kho panāyaṃ parisā paribhaveyya, yasopi tassa hāyetha.* **";
P_HTM[1855]="*Yassa kho pana yaso hāyetha, bhogāpi tassa hāyeyyuṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1856]="*Yasoladdhā kho panamhākaṃ bhogā.* **";
P_HTM[1857]="*Mamañceva kho pana samaṇo gotamo pañhaṃ puccheyya, tassa cāhaṃ pañhassa veyyākaraṇena cittaṃ na ārādheyyaṃ;* **";
P_HTM[1858]="*tatra ce maṃ samaṇo gotamo evaṃ vadeyya:* **";
P_HTM[1859]="*‘na kho esa, brāhmaṇa, pañho evaṃ byākātabbo, evaṃ nāmesa, brāhmaṇa, pañho byākātabbo’ti, tena maṃ ayaṃ parisā paribhaveyya:* **";
P_HTM[1860]="*‘bālo soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo abyatto, nāsakkhi samaṇassa gotamassa pañhassa veyyākaraṇena cittaṃ ārādhetun’ti.* **";
P_HTM[1861]="*Yaṃ kho panāyaṃ parisā paribhaveyya, yasopi tassa hāyetha.* **";
P_HTM[1862]="*Yassa kho pana yaso hāyetha, bhogāpi tassa hāyeyyuṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1863]="*Yasoladdhā kho panamhākaṃ bhogā.* **";
P_HTM[1864]="*Aho vata maṃ samaṇo gotamo sake ācariyake tevijjake pañhaṃ puccheyya, addhā vatassāhaṃ cittaṃ ārādheyyaṃ pañhassa veyyākaraṇenā”ti.**“If only the ascetic Gotama would ask me about my own teacher’s scriptural heritage of the three Vedas! Then I could definitely satisfy his mind with my answer.”*";
P_HTM[1865]="*5. Brāhmaṇapaññatti**5. What Makes a Brahmin*";
P_HTM[1866]="*Atha kho bhagavato soṇadaṇḍassa brāhmaṇassa cetasā cetoparivitakkamaññāya etadahosi:**Then the Buddha, knowing what Soṇadaṇda was thinking, thought,*";
P_HTM[1867]="*“vihaññati kho ayaṃ soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo sakena cittena.**“This brahmin Soṇadaṇḍa is worried by his own thoughts.*";
P_HTM[1868]="*Yannūnāhaṃ soṇadaṇḍaṃ brāhmaṇaṃ sake ācariyake tevijjake pañhaṃ puccheyyan”ti.**Why don’t I ask him about his own teacher’s scriptural heritage of the three Vedas?”*";
P_HTM[1869]="*Atha kho bhagavā soṇadaṇḍaṃ brāhmaṇaṃ etadavoca:**So he said to Soṇadaṇḍa,*";
P_HTM[1870]="*“katihi pana, brāhmaṇa, aṅgehi samannāgataṃ brāhmaṇā brāhmaṇaṃ paññapenti;**“Brahmin, how many factors must a brahmin possess for the brahmins to describe him as a brahmin;*";
P_HTM[1871]="*‘brāhmaṇosmī’ti ca vadamāno sammā vadeyya, na ca pana musāvādaṃ āpajjeyyā”ti?**and so that when he says ‘I am a brahmin’ he speaks rightly, without falling into falsehood?”*";
P_HTM[1872]="*Atha kho soṇadaṇḍassa brāhmaṇassa etadahosi:**Then Soṇadaṇḍa thought,*";
P_HTM[1873]="*“yaṃ vata no ahosi icchitaṃ, yaṃ ākaṅkhitaṃ, yaṃ adhippetaṃ, yaṃ abhipatthitaṃ:**“The ascetic Gotama has asked me about exactly what I wanted, what I wished for, what I desired, what I yearned for; that is, my own scriptural heritage.*";
P_HTM[1874]="*‘aho vata maṃ samaṇo gotamo sake ācariyake tevijjake pañhaṃ puccheyya, addhā vatassāhaṃ cittaṃ ārādheyyaṃ pañhassa veyyākaraṇenā’ti, tatra maṃ samaṇo gotamo sake ācariyake tevijjake pañhaṃ pucchati.* **";
P_HTM[1875]="*Addhā vatassāhaṃ cittaṃ ārādhessāmi pañhassa veyyākaraṇenā”ti.**I can definitely satisfy his mind with my answer.”*";
P_HTM[1876]="*Atha kho soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo abbhunnāmetvā kāyaṃ anuviloketvā parisaṃ bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Soṇadaṇḍa straightened his back, looked around the assembly, and said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[1877]="*“pañcahi, bho gotama, aṅgehi samannāgataṃ brāhmaṇā brāhmaṇaṃ paññapenti;**“Master Gotama, a brahmin must possess five factors for the brahmins to describe him as a brahmin;*";
P_HTM[1878]="*‘brāhmaṇosmī’ti ca vadamāno sammā vadeyya, na ca pana musāvādaṃ āpajjeyya.**and so that when he says ‘I am a brahmin’ he speaks rightly, without falling into falsehood.*";
P_HTM[1879]="*Katamehi pañcahi?**What five?*";
P_HTM[1880]="*Idha, bho gotama, brāhmaṇo ubhato sujāto hoti mātito ca pitito ca, saṃsuddhagahaṇiko yāva sattamā pitāmahayugā akkhitto anupakkuṭṭho jātivādena;**It’s when a brahmin is well born on both his mother’s and father’s side, of pure descent, irrefutable and impeccable in questions of ancestry back to the seventh paternal generation.*";
P_HTM[1881]="*ajjhāyako hoti mantadharo tiṇṇaṃ vedānaṃ pāragū sanighaṇḍukeṭubhānaṃ sākkharappabhedānaṃ itihāsapañcamānaṃ padako veyyākaraṇo lokāyatamahāpurisalakkhaṇesu anavayo;**He recites and remembers the hymns, and have mastered the three Vedas, together with their vocabularies, ritual, phonology and etymology, and the testament as fifth. He knows philology and grammar, and is well versed in cosmology and the marks of a great man.*";
P_HTM[1882]="*abhirūpo hoti dassanīyo pāsādiko paramāya vaṇṇapokkharatāya samannāgato brahmavaṇṇī brahmavacchasī akhuddāvakāso dassanāya;**He is attractive, good-looking, lovely, of surpassing beauty. He is magnificent, splendid, remarkable to behold.*";
P_HTM[1883]="*sīlavā hoti vuddhasīlī vuddhasīlena samannāgato;**He is ethical, mature in ethical conduct.*";
P_HTM[1884]="*paṇḍito ca hoti medhāvī paṭhamo vā dutiyo vā sujaṃ paggaṇhantānaṃ.**He’s astute and clever, being the first or second to hold the sacrificial ladle.*";
P_HTM[1885]="*Imehi kho, bho gotama, pañcahi aṅgehi samannāgataṃ brāhmaṇā brāhmaṇaṃ paññapenti;**These are the five factors which a brahmin must possess for the brahmins to describe him as a brahmin;*";
P_HTM[1886]="*‘brāhmaṇosmī’ti ca vadamāno sammā vadeyya, na ca pana musāvādaṃ āpajjeyyā”ti.**and so that when he says ‘I am a brahmin’ he speaks rightly, without falling into falsehood.”*";
P_HTM[1887]="*“Imesaṃ pana, brāhmaṇa, pañcannaṃ aṅgānaṃ sakkā ekaṃ aṅgaṃ ṭhapayitvā catūhaṅgehi samannāgataṃ brāhmaṇā brāhmaṇaṃ paññapetuṃ;**“But brahmin, is it possible to set aside one of these five factors and still rightly describe someone as a brahmin?”*";
P_HTM[1888]="*‘brāhmaṇosmī’ti ca vadamāno sammā vadeyya, na ca pana musāvādaṃ āpajjeyyā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[1889]="*“Sakkā, bho gotama.**“It is possible, Master Gotama.*";
P_HTM[1890]="*Imesañhi, bho gotama, pañcannaṃ aṅgānaṃ vaṇṇaṃ ṭhapayāma.**We could leave appearance out of the five factors.*";
P_HTM[1891]="*Kiñhi vaṇṇo karissati?**For what does appearance matter?*";
P_HTM[1892]="*Yato kho, bho gotama, brāhmaṇo ubhato sujāto hoti mātito ca pitito ca saṃsuddhagahaṇiko yāva sattamā pitāmahayugā akkhitto anupakkuṭṭho jātivādena;* **";
P_HTM[1893]="*ajjhāyako ca hoti mantadharo ca tiṇṇaṃ vedānaṃ pāragū sanighaṇḍukeṭubhānaṃ sākkharappabhedānaṃ itihāsapañcamānaṃ padako veyyākaraṇo lokāyatamahāpurisalakkhaṇesu anavayo;* **";
P_HTM[1894]="*sīlavā ca hoti vuddhasīlī vuddhasīlena samannāgato;* **";
P_HTM[1895]="*paṇḍito ca hoti medhāvī paṭhamo vā dutiyo vā sujaṃ paggaṇhantānaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1896]="*Imehi kho, bho gotama, catūhaṅgehi samannāgataṃ brāhmaṇā brāhmaṇaṃ paññapenti;**A brahmin must possess the remaining four factors for the brahmins to rightly describe him as a brahmin.”*";
P_HTM[1897]="*‘brāhmaṇosmī’ti ca vadamāno sammā vadeyya, na ca pana musāvādaṃ āpajjeyyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[1898]="*“Imesaṃ pana, brāhmaṇa, catunnaṃ aṅgānaṃ sakkā ekaṃ aṅgaṃ ṭhapayitvā tīhaṅgehi samannāgataṃ brāhmaṇā brāhmaṇaṃ paññapetuṃ;**“But brahmin, is it possible to set aside one of these four factors and still rightly describe someone as a brahmin?”*";
P_HTM[1899]="*‘brāhmaṇosmī’ti ca vadamāno sammā vadeyya, na ca pana musāvādaṃ āpajjeyyā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[1900]="*“Sakkā, bho gotama.**“It is possible, Master Gotama.*";
P_HTM[1901]="*Imesañhi, bho gotama, catunnaṃ aṅgānaṃ mante ṭhapayāma.**We could leave the hymns out of the five factors.*";
P_HTM[1902]="*Kiñhi mantā karissanti?**For what do the hymns matter?*";
P_HTM[1903]="*Yato kho, bho gotama, brāhmaṇo ubhato sujāto hoti mātito ca pitito ca saṃsuddhagahaṇiko yāva sattamā pitāmahayugā akkhitto anupakkuṭṭho jātivādena;* **";
P_HTM[1904]="*sīlavā ca hoti vuddhasīlī vuddhasīlena samannāgato;* **";
P_HTM[1905]="*paṇḍito ca hoti medhāvī paṭhamo vā dutiyo vā sujaṃ paggaṇhantānaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[1906]="*Imehi kho, bho gotama, tīhaṅgehi samannāgataṃ brāhmaṇā brāhmaṇaṃ paññapenti;**A brahmin must possess the remaining three factors for the brahmins to rightly describe him as a brahmin.”*";
P_HTM[1907]="*‘brāhmaṇosmī’ti ca vadamāno sammā vadeyya, na ca pana musāvādaṃ āpajjeyyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[1908]="*“Imesaṃ pana, brāhmaṇa, tiṇṇaṃ aṅgānaṃ sakkā ekaṃ aṅgaṃ ṭhapayitvā dvīhaṅgehi samannāgataṃ brāhmaṇā brāhmaṇaṃ paññapetuṃ;**“But brahmin, is it possible to set aside one of these three factors and still rightly describe someone as a brahmin?”*";
P_HTM[1909]="*‘brāhmaṇosmī’ti ca vadamāno sammā vadeyya, na ca pana musāvādaṃ āpajjeyyā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[1910]="*“Sakkā, bho gotama.**“It is possible, Master Gotama.*";
P_HTM[1911]="*Imesañhi, bho gotama, tiṇṇaṃ aṅgānaṃ jātiṃ ṭhapayāma.**We could leave birth out of the five factors.*";
P_HTM[1912]="*Kiñhi jāti karissati?**For what does birth matter?*";
P_HTM[1913]="*Yato kho, bho gotama, brāhmaṇo sīlavā hoti vuddhasīlī vuddhasīlena samannāgato;**It’s when a brahmin is ethical, mature in ethical conduct;*";
P_HTM[1914]="*paṇḍito ca hoti medhāvī paṭhamo vā dutiyo vā sujaṃ paggaṇhantānaṃ.**and he’s astute and clever, being the first or second to hold the sacrificial ladle.*";
P_HTM[1915]="*Imehi kho, bho gotama, dvīhaṅgehi samannāgataṃ brāhmaṇā brāhmaṇaṃ paññapenti;**A brahmin must possess these two factors for the brahmins to rightly describe him as a brahmin.”*";
P_HTM[1916]="*‘brāhmaṇosmī’ti ca vadamāno sammā vadeyya, na ca pana musāvādaṃ āpajjeyyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[1917]="*Evaṃ vutte, te brāhmaṇā soṇadaṇḍaṃ brāhmaṇaṃ etadavocuṃ:**When he had spoken, those brahmins said to him,*";
P_HTM[1918]="*“mā bhavaṃ soṇadaṇḍo evaṃ avaca, mā bhavaṃ soṇadaṇḍo evaṃ avaca.**“Please don’t say that, Master Soṇadaṇda, please don’t say that!*";
P_HTM[1919]="*Apavadateva bhavaṃ soṇadaṇḍo vaṇṇaṃ, apavadati mante, apavadati jātiṃ, ekaṃsena bhavaṃ soṇadaṇḍo samaṇasseva gotamassa vādaṃ anupakkhandatī”ti.**You’re just condemning appearance, the hymns, and birth! You’re totally going over to the ascetic Gotama’s doctrine!”*";
P_HTM[1920]="*Atha kho bhagavā te brāhmaṇe etadavoca:**So the Buddha said to them,*";
P_HTM[1921]="*“sace kho tumhākaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ evaṃ hoti:**“Well, brahmins, if you think that*";
P_HTM[1922]="*‘appassuto ca soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo, akalyāṇavākkaraṇo ca soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo, duppañño ca soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo, na ca pahoti soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo samaṇena gotamena saddhiṃ asmiṃ vacane paṭimantetun’ti, tiṭṭhatu soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo, tumhe mayā saddhiṃ mantavho asmiṃ vacane.**Soṇadaṇḍa is uneducated, a poor speaker, witless, and not capable of having a dialogue with me about this, then leave him aside and you can have a dialogue with me.*";
P_HTM[1923]="*Sace pana tumhākaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ evaṃ hoti:**But if you think that*";
P_HTM[1924]="*‘bahussuto ca soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo, kalyāṇavākkaraṇo ca soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo, paṇḍito ca soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo, pahoti ca soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo samaṇena gotamena saddhiṃ asmiṃ vacane paṭimantetun’ti, tiṭṭhatha tumhe, soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo mayā saddhiṃ paṭimantetū”ti.**he’s learned, a good speaker, astute, and capable of having a dialogue with me about this, then you should stand aside and let him have a dialogue with me.”*";
P_HTM[1925]="*Evaṃ vutte, soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, Soṇadaṇḍa said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[1926]="*“tiṭṭhatu bhavaṃ gotamo, tuṇhī bhavaṃ gotamo hotu, ahameva tesaṃ sahadhammena paṭivacanaṃ karissāmī”ti.**“Let it be, Master Gotama, be silent. I myself will respond to them in a legitimate manner.”*";
P_HTM[1927]="*Atha kho soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo te brāhmaṇe etadavoca:**Then he said to those brahmins,*";
P_HTM[1928]="*“mā bhavanto evaṃ avacuttha, mā bhavanto evaṃ avacuttha:**“Don’t say this, gentlemen, don’t say this:*";
P_HTM[1929]="*‘apavadateva bhavaṃ soṇadaṇḍo vaṇṇaṃ, apavadati mante, apavadati jātiṃ, ekaṃsena bhavaṃ soṇadaṇḍo samaṇasseva gotamassa vādaṃ anupakkhandatī’ti.**‘You’re just condemning appearance, the hymns, and birth! You’re totally going over to the ascetic Gotama’s doctrine!’*";
P_HTM[1930]="*Nāhaṃ, bho, apavadāmi vaṇṇaṃ vā mante vā jātiṃ vā”ti.**I’m not condemning appearance, hymns, or birth.”*";
P_HTM[1931]="*Tena kho pana samayena soṇadaṇḍassa brāhmaṇassa bhāgineyyo aṅgako nāma māṇavako tassaṃ parisāyaṃ nisinno hoti.**Now at that time Soṇadaṇḍa’s nephew, the student Aṅgaka was sitting in that assembly.*";
P_HTM[1932]="*Atha kho soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo te brāhmaṇe etadavoca:**Then Soṇadaṇḍa said to those brahmins,*";
P_HTM[1933]="*“passanti no bhonto imaṃ aṅgakaṃ māṇavakaṃ amhākaṃ bhāgineyyan”ti?**“Gentlemen, do you see my nephew, the student Aṅgaka?”*";
P_HTM[1934]="*“Evaṃ, bho”.**“Yes, sir.”*";
P_HTM[1935]="*“Aṅgako kho, bho, māṇavako abhirūpo dassanīyo pāsādiko paramāya vaṇṇapokkharatāya samannāgato brahmavaṇṇī brahmavacchasī akhuddāvakāso dassanāya, nāssa imissaṃ parisāyaṃ samasamo atthi vaṇṇena ṭhapetvā samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ.**“Aṅgaka is attractive, good-looking, lovely, of surpassing beauty. He is magnificent, splendid, remarkable to behold. There’s no-one in this assembly so good-looking, apart from the ascetic Gotama.*";
P_HTM[1936]="*Aṅgako kho māṇavako ajjhāyako mantadharo, tiṇṇaṃ vedānaṃ pāragū sanighaṇḍukeṭubhānaṃ sākkharappabhedānaṃ itihāsapañcamānaṃ padako veyyākaraṇo lokāyatamahāpurisalakkhaṇesu anavayo.**Aṅgaka recites and remembers the hymns, and have mastered the three Vedas, together with their vocabularies, ritual, phonology and etymology, and the testament as fifth. He knows philology and grammar, and is well versed in cosmology and the marks of a great man.*";
P_HTM[1937]="*Ahamassa mante vācetā.**And I am the one who teaches him the hymns.*";
P_HTM[1938]="*Aṅgako kho māṇavako ubhato sujāto mātito ca pitito ca saṃsuddhagahaṇiko yāva sattamā pitāmahayugā akkhitto anupakkuṭṭho jātivādena.**Aṅgaka is well born on both his mother’s and father’s side, of pure descent, irrefutable and impeccable in questions of ancestry back to the seventh paternal generation.*";
P_HTM[1939]="*Ahamassa mātāpitaro jānāmi.**And I know his mother and father.*";
P_HTM[1940]="*Aṅgako kho māṇavako pāṇampi haneyya, adinnampi ādiyeyya, paradārampi gaccheyya, musāvādampi bhaṇeyya, majjampi piveyya, ettha dāni, bho, kiṃ vaṇṇo karissati, kiṃ mantā, kiṃ jāti?**But if Aṅgaka were to kill living creatures, steal, commit adultery, lie, and drink alcohol, then what’s the use of his appearance, his hymns, or his birth?*";
P_HTM[1941]="*Yato kho, bho, brāhmaṇo sīlavā ca hoti vuddhasīlī vuddhasīlena samannāgato,**It’s when a brahmin is ethical, mature in ethical conduct;*";
P_HTM[1942]="*paṇḍito ca hoti medhāvī paṭhamo vā dutiyo vā sujaṃ paggaṇhantānaṃ.**and he’s astute and clever, being the first or second to hold the sacrificial ladle.*";
P_HTM[1943]="*Imehi kho, bho, dvīhaṅgehi samannāgataṃ brāhmaṇā brāhmaṇaṃ paññapenti;**A brahmin must possess these two factors for the brahmins to rightly describe him as a brahmin.”*";
P_HTM[1944]="*‘brāhmaṇosmī’ti ca vadamāno sammā vadeyya, na ca pana musāvādaṃ āpajjeyyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[1945]="*6. Sīlapaññākathā**6. The Discussion of Ethics and Wisdom*";
P_HTM[1946]="*“Imesaṃ pana, brāhmaṇa, dvinnaṃ aṅgānaṃ sakkā ekaṃ aṅgaṃ ṭhapayitvā ekena aṅgena samannāgataṃ brāhmaṇā brāhmaṇaṃ paññapetuṃ;**“But brahmin, is it possible to set aside one of these two factors and still rightly describe someone as a brahmin?”*";
P_HTM[1947]="*‘brāhmaṇosmī’ti ca vadamāno sammā vadeyya, na ca pana musāvādaṃ āpajjeyyā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[1948]="*“No hidaṃ, bho gotama.**“No, Master Gotama.*";
P_HTM[1949]="*Sīlaparidhotā hi, bho gotama, paññā; paññāparidhotaṃ sīlaṃ.**For wisdom is cleansed by ethics, and ethics are cleansed by wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1950]="*Yattha sīlaṃ tattha paññā, yattha paññā tattha sīlaṃ.**Ethics and wisdom always go together.*";
P_HTM[1951]="*Sīlavato paññā, paññavato sīlaṃ.**An ethical person is wise, and a wise person ethical.*";
P_HTM[1952]="*Sīlapaññāṇañca pana lokasmiṃ aggamakkhāyati.**And ethics and wisdom are said to be the best things in the world.*";
P_HTM[1953]="*Seyyathāpi, bho gotama, hatthena vā hatthaṃ dhoveyya, pādena vā pādaṃ dhoveyya;**It’s just like when you clean one hand with the other, or clean one foot with the other.*";
P_HTM[1954]="*evameva kho, bho gotama, sīlaparidhotā paññā, paññāparidhotaṃ sīlaṃ.**In the same way, wisdom is cleansed by ethics, and ethics are cleansed by wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1955]="*Yattha sīlaṃ tattha paññā, yattha paññā tattha sīlaṃ.**Ethics and wisdom always go together.*";
P_HTM[1956]="*Sīlavato paññā, paññavato sīlaṃ.**An ethical person is wise, and a wise person ethical.*";
P_HTM[1957]="*Sīlapaññāṇañca pana lokasmiṃ aggamakkhāyatī”ti.**And ethics and wisdom are said to be the best things in the world.”*";
P_HTM[1958]="*“Evametaṃ, brāhmaṇa, evametaṃ, brāhmaṇa, sīlaparidhotā hi, brāhmaṇa, paññā, paññāparidhotaṃ sīlaṃ.**“That’s so true, brahmin, that’s so true! For wisdom is cleansed by ethics, and ethics are cleansed by wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1959]="*Yattha sīlaṃ tattha paññā, yattha paññā tattha sīlaṃ.**Ethics and wisdom always go together.*";
P_HTM[1960]="*Sīlavato paññā, paññavato sīlaṃ.**An ethical person is wise, and a wise person ethical.*";
P_HTM[1961]="*Sīlapaññāṇañca pana lokasmiṃ aggamakkhāyati.**And ethics and wisdom are said to be the best things in the world.*";
P_HTM[1962]="*Seyyathāpi, brāhmaṇa, hatthena vā hatthaṃ dhoveyya, pādena vā pādaṃ dhoveyya;**It’s just like when you clean one hand with the other, or clean one foot with the other.*";
P_HTM[1963]="*evameva kho, brāhmaṇa, sīlaparidhotā paññā, paññāparidhotaṃ sīlaṃ.**In the same way, wisdom is cleansed by ethics, and ethics are cleansed by wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1964]="*Yattha sīlaṃ tattha paññā, yattha paññā tattha sīlaṃ.**Ethics and wisdom always go together.*";
P_HTM[1965]="*Sīlavato paññā, paññavato sīlaṃ.**An ethical person is wise, and a wise person ethical.*";
P_HTM[1966]="*Sīlapaññāṇañca pana lokasmiṃ aggamakkhāyati.**And ethics and wisdom are said to be the best things in the world.*";
P_HTM[1967]="*Katamaṃ pana taṃ, brāhmaṇa, sīlaṃ?**But what, brahmin, is that ethical conduct?*";
P_HTM[1968]="*Katamā sā paññā”ti?**And what is that wisdom?”*";
P_HTM[1969]="*“Ettakaparamāva mayaṃ, bho gotama, etasmiṃ atthe.**“That’s all I know about this matter, Master Gotama.*";
P_HTM[1970]="*Sādhu vata bhavantaṃyeva gotamaṃ paṭibhātu etassa bhāsitassa attho”ti.**May Master Gotama himself please clarify the meaning of this.”*";
P_HTM[1971]="*“Tena hi, brāhmaṇa, suṇohi, sādhukaṃ manasikarohi, bhāsissāmī”ti.**“Well then, brahmin, listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[1972]="*“Evaṃ, bho”ti kho soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes sir,” Soṇadaṇḍa replied.*";
P_HTM[1973]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[1974]="*“idha, brāhmaṇa, tathāgato loke uppajjati arahaṃ sammāsambuddho … pe …**“It’s when a Realized One arises in the world, perfected, a fully awakened Buddha …*";
P_HTM[1975]="*Evaṃ kho, brāhmaṇa, bhikkhu sīlasampanno hoti.**That’s how a mendicant is accomplished in ethics.*";
P_HTM[1976]="*Idaṃ kho taṃ, brāhmaṇa, sīlaṃ … pe …**This, brahmin, is that ethical conduct. …*";
P_HTM[1977]="*paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati …**They enter and remain in the first absorption …*";
P_HTM[1978]="*dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ …**second absorption …*";
P_HTM[1979]="*tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ …**third absorption …*";
P_HTM[1980]="*catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati … pe …**fourth absorption …*";
P_HTM[1981]="*ñāṇadassanāya cittaṃ abhinīharati, abhininnāmeti … pe …**They extend and project the mind toward knowledge and vision …*";
P_HTM[1982]="*Idampissa hoti paññāya … pe …**This pertains to their wisdom. …*";
P_HTM[1983]="*nāparaṃ itthattāyāti pajānāti.**They understand: ‘… there is no return to any state of existence.’*";
P_HTM[1984]="*Idampissa hoti paññāya**This pertains to their wisdom.*";
P_HTM[1985]="*ayaṃ kho sā, brāhmaṇa, paññā”ti.**This, brahmin, is that wisdom.”*";
P_HTM[1986]="*7. Soṇadaṇḍaupāsakattapaṭivedanā**7. Soṇadaṇḍa Declares Himself a Lay Follower*";
P_HTM[1987]="*Evaṃ vutte, soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he had spoken, Soṇadaṇḍa said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[1988]="*“abhikkantaṃ, bho gotama, abhikkantaṃ, bho gotama.**“Excellent, Master Gotama! Excellent!*";
P_HTM[1989]="*Seyyathāpi, bho gotama, nikkujjitaṃ vā ukkujjeyya, paṭicchannaṃ vā vivareyya, mūḷhassa vā maggaṃ ācikkheyya, andhakāre vā telapajjotaṃ dhāreyya: ‘cakkhumanto rūpāni dakkhantī’ti; evamevaṃ bhotā gotamena anekapariyāyena dhammo pakāsito.**As if he were righting the overturned, or revealing the hidden, or pointing out the path to the lost, or lighting a lamp in the dark so people with good eyes can see what’s there, Master Gotama has made the Teaching clear in many ways.*";
P_HTM[1990]="*Esāhaṃ bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ saraṇaṃ gacchāmi, dhammañca, bhikkhusaṅghañca.**I go for refuge to Master Gotama, to the teaching, and to the mendicant Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[1991]="*Upāsakaṃ maṃ bhavaṃ gotamo dhāretu ajjatagge pāṇupetaṃ saraṇaṃ gataṃ.**From this day forth, may Master Gotama remember me as a lay follower who has gone for refuge for life.*";
P_HTM[1992]="*Adhivāsetu ca me bhavaṃ gotamo svātanāya bhattaṃ saddhiṃ bhikkhusaṅghenā”ti.**Would you and the Order of monks please accept a meal from me tomorrow?”*";
P_HTM[1993]="*Adhivāsesi bhagavā tuṇhībhāvena.**The Buddha consented in silence.*";
P_HTM[1994]="*Atha kho soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo bhagavato adhivāsanaṃ viditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā pakkāmi.**Then, knowing that the Buddha had consented, Soṇadaṇḍa got up from his seat, bowed, and respectfully circled the Buddha, keeping him on his right, before leaving.*";
P_HTM[1995]="*Atha kho soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo tassā rattiyā accayena sake nivesane paṇītaṃ khādanīyaṃ bhojanīyaṃ paṭiyādāpetvā bhagavato kālaṃ ārocāpesi:**And when the night had passed Soṇadaṇḍa had a variety of delicious foods prepared in his own home. Then he had the Buddha informed of the time, saying,*";
P_HTM[1996]="*“kālo, bho gotama, niṭṭhitaṃ bhattan”ti.**“It’s time, Master Gotama, the meal is ready.”*";
P_HTM[1997]="*Atha kho bhagavā pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya saddhiṃ bhikkhusaṅghena yena soṇadaṇḍassa brāhmaṇassa nivesanaṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdi.**Then the Buddha robed up in the morning and, taking his bowl and robe, went to the home of Soṇadaṇḍa together with the mendicant Saṅgha, where he sat on the seat spread out.*";
P_HTM[1998]="*Atha kho soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo buddhappamukhaṃ bhikkhusaṅghaṃ paṇītena khādanīyena bhojanīyena sahatthā santappesi sampavāresi.**Then Soṇadaṇḍa served and satisfied the mendicant Saṅgha headed by the Buddha with his own hands with a variety of delicious foods.*";
P_HTM[1999]="*Atha kho soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo bhagavantaṃ bhuttāviṃ onītapattapāṇiṃ aññataraṃ nīcaṃ āsanaṃ gahetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi.**When the Buddha had eaten and washed his hand and bowl, Soṇadaṇḍa took a low seat and sat to one side.*";
P_HTM[2000]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho soṇadaṇḍo brāhmaṇo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Seated to one side he said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[2001]="*“ahañceva kho pana, bho gotama, parisagato samāno āsanā vuṭṭhahitvā bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ abhivādeyyaṃ, tena maṃ sā parisā paribhaveyya.**“Master Gotama, if, when I have gone to an assembly, I rise from my seat and bow to the Buddha, that assembly might disparage me for that.*";
P_HTM[2002]="*Yaṃ kho pana sā parisā paribhaveyya, yasopi tassa hāyetha.**And when you’re disparaged by the assembly, your reputation diminishes.*";
P_HTM[2003]="*Yassa kho pana yaso hāyetha, bhogāpi tassa hāyeyyuṃ.**When your reputation diminishes, your wealth also diminishes.*";
P_HTM[2004]="*Yasoladdhā kho panamhākaṃ bhogā.**But my wealth relies on my reputation.*";
P_HTM[2005]="*Ahañceva kho pana, bho gotama, parisagato samāno añjaliṃ paggaṇheyyaṃ, āsanā me taṃ bhavaṃ gotamo paccuṭṭhānaṃ dhāretu.**If, when I have gone to an assembly, I raise my joined palms, please take it that I have risen from my seat.*";
P_HTM[2006]="*Ahañceva kho pana, bho gotama, parisagato samāno veṭhanaṃ omuñceyyaṃ, sirasā me taṃ bhavaṃ gotamo abhivādanaṃ dhāretu.**And if I undo my turban, please take it that I have bowed.*";
P_HTM[2007]="*Ahañceva kho pana, bho gotama, yānagato samāno yānā paccorohitvā bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ abhivādeyyaṃ, tena maṃ sā parisā paribhaveyya.**And Master Gotama, if, when I am in a carriage, I rise from my seat and bow to the Buddha, that assembly might disparage me for that.*";
P_HTM[2008]="*Yaṃ kho pana sā parisā paribhaveyya, yasopi tassa hāyetha, yassa kho pana yaso hāyetha, bhogāpi tassa hāyeyyuṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2009]="*Yasoladdhā kho panamhākaṃ bhogā.* **";
P_HTM[2010]="*Ahañceva kho pana, bho gotama, yānagato samāno patodalaṭṭhiṃ abbhunnāmeyyaṃ, yānā me taṃ bhavaṃ gotamo paccorohanaṃ dhāretu.**If, when I am in a carriage, I hold up my goad, please take it that I have got down from my carriage.*";
P_HTM[2011]="*Ahañceva kho pana, bho gotama, yānagato samāno chattaṃ apanāmeyyaṃ, sirasā me taṃ bhavaṃ gotamo abhivādanaṃ dhāretū”ti.**And if I lower my sunshade, please take it that I have bowed.”*";
P_HTM[2012]="*Atha kho bhagavā soṇadaṇḍaṃ brāhmaṇaṃ dhammiyā kathāya sandassetvā samādapetvā samuttejetvā sampahaṃsetvā uṭṭhāyāsanā pakkāmīti.**Then the Buddha educated, encouraged, fired up, and inspired the brahmin Soṇadaṇḍa with a Dhamma talk, after which he got up from his seat and left.*";
P_HTM[2013]="*Soṇadaṇḍasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ catutthaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2014]="*05. Kūṭadantasutta  - With Kūṭadanta * **";
P_HTM[2015]="*1. Khāṇumatakabrāhmaṇagahapatikā**1. The Brahmins and Householders of Khāṇumata*";
P_HTM[2016]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[2017]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā magadhesu cārikaṃ caramāno mahatā bhikkhusaṅghena saddhiṃ pañcamattehi bhikkhusatehi yena khāṇumataṃ nāma magadhānaṃ brāhmaṇagāmo tadavasari.**At one time the Buddha was wandering in the land of the Magadhans together with a large Saṅgha of around five hundred mendicants when he arrived at a village of the Magadhan brahmins named Khāṇumata.*";
P_HTM[2018]="*Tatra sudaṃ bhagavā khāṇumate viharati ambalaṭṭhikāyaṃ.**There he stayed nearby at Ambalaṭṭhikā.*";
P_HTM[2019]="*Tena kho pana samayena kūṭadanto brāhmaṇo khāṇumataṃ ajjhāvasati sattussadaṃ satiṇakaṭṭhodakaṃ sadhaññaṃ rājabhoggaṃ raññā māgadhena seniyena bimbisārena dinnaṃ rājadāyaṃ brahmadeyyaṃ.**Now at that time the brahmin Kūṭadanta was living in Khāṇumata. It was a crown property given by King Seniya Bimbisāra of Magadha, teeming with living creatures, full of hay, wood, water, and grain, a royal endowment of the highest quality.*";
P_HTM[2020]="*Tena kho pana samayena kūṭadantassa brāhmaṇassa mahāyañño upakkhaṭo hoti.**Now at that time Kūṭadanta had prepared a great sacrifice.*";
P_HTM[2021]="*Satta ca usabhasatāni satta ca vacchatarasatāni satta ca vacchatarīsatāni satta ca ajasatāni satta ca urabbhasatāni thūṇūpanītāni honti yaññatthāya.**Bulls, bullocks, heifers, goats and rams—seven hundred of each—had been led to the post for the sacrifice.*";
P_HTM[2022]="*Assosuṃ kho khāṇumatakā brāhmaṇagahapatikā:**The brahmins and householders of Khāṇumataka heard:*";
P_HTM[2023]="*“samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo sakyaputto sakyakulā pabbajito magadhesu cārikaṃ caramāno mahatā bhikkhusaṅghena saddhiṃ pañcamattehi bhikkhusatehi khāṇumataṃ anuppatto khāṇumate viharati ambalaṭṭhikāyaṃ.**“It seems the ascetic Gotama—a Sakyan, gone forth from a Sakyan family—has arrived at Khāṇumataka and is staying in a forest nearby.*";
P_HTM[2024]="*Taṃ kho pana bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ evaṃ kalyāṇo kittisaddo abbhuggato:**He has this good reputation:*";
P_HTM[2025]="*‘itipi so bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā’ti.**‘That Blessed One is perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.’*";
P_HTM[2026]="*So imaṃ lokaṃ sadevakaṃ samārakaṃ sabrahmakaṃ sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiṃ pajaṃ sadevamanussaṃ sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedeti.**He has realized with his own insight this world—with its gods, Māras and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, gods and humans—and he makes it known to others.*";
P_HTM[2027]="*So dhammaṃ deseti ādikalyāṇaṃ majjhekalyāṇaṃ pariyosānakalyāṇaṃ sātthaṃ sabyañjanaṃ kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ pakāseti.**He teaches Dhamma that’s good in the beginning, good in the middle, and good in the end, meaningful and well-phrased. And he reveals a spiritual practice that’s entirely full and pure.*";
P_HTM[2028]="*Sādhu kho pana tathārūpānaṃ arahataṃ dassanaṃ hotī”ti.**It’s good to see such perfected ones.”*";
P_HTM[2029]="*Atha kho khāṇumatakā brāhmaṇagahapatikā khāṇumatā nikkhamitvā saṅghasaṅghī gaṇībhūtā yena ambalaṭṭhikā tenupasaṅkamanti.**Then, having departed Khāṇumataka, they formed into companies and headed to Ambalaṭṭhikā.*";
P_HTM[2030]="*Tena kho pana samayena kūṭadanto brāhmaṇo uparipāsāde divāseyyaṃ upagato hoti.**Now at that time the brahmin Kūṭadanta had retired to the upper floor of his stilt longhouse for his midday nap.*";
P_HTM[2031]="*Addasā kho kūṭadanto brāhmaṇo khāṇumatake brāhmaṇagahapatike khāṇumatā nikkhamitvā saṅghasaṅghī gaṇībhūte yena ambalaṭṭhikā tenupasaṅkamante.**He saw the brahmins and householders heading for Ambalaṭṭhikā,*";
P_HTM[2032]="*Disvā khattaṃ āmantesi:**and addressed his steward,*";
P_HTM[2033]="*“kiṃ nu kho, bho khatte, khāṇumatakā brāhmaṇagahapatikā khāṇumatā nikkhamitvā saṅghasaṅghī gaṇībhūtā yena ambalaṭṭhikā tenupasaṅkamantī”ti?**“My steward, why are the brahmins and householders headed for Ambalaṭṭhikā?”*";
P_HTM[2034]="*“Atthi kho, bho, samaṇo gotamo sakyaputto sakyakulā pabbajito magadhesu cārikaṃ caramāno mahatā bhikkhusaṅghena saddhiṃ pañcamattehi bhikkhusatehi khāṇumataṃ anuppatto, khāṇumate viharati ambalaṭṭhikāyaṃ.**“The ascetic Gotama has arrived at Khāṇumataka and is staying at Ambalaṭṭhikā.*";
P_HTM[2035]="*Taṃ kho pana bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ evaṃ kalyāṇo kittisaddo abbhuggato:**He has this good reputation:*";
P_HTM[2036]="*‘itipi so bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā’ti.**‘That Blessed One is perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.’*";
P_HTM[2037]="*Tamete bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamantī”ti.**They’re going to see that Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[2038]="*Atha kho kūṭadantassa brāhmaṇassa etadahosi:**Then Kūṭadanta thought,*";
P_HTM[2039]="*“sutaṃ kho pana metaṃ:**“I’ve heard that*";
P_HTM[2040]="*‘samaṇo gotamo tividhaṃ yaññasampadaṃ soḷasaparikkhāraṃ jānātī’ti.**the ascetic Gotama knows how to accomplish the sacrifice with three modes and sixteen accessories.*";
P_HTM[2041]="*Na kho panāhaṃ jānāmi tividhaṃ yaññasampadaṃ soḷasaparikkhāraṃ.**I don’t know about that,*";
P_HTM[2042]="*Icchāmi cāhaṃ mahāyaññaṃ yajituṃ.**but I wish to perform a great sacrifice.*";
P_HTM[2043]="*Yannūnāhaṃ samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ upasaṅkamitvā tividhaṃ yaññasampadaṃ soḷasaparikkhāraṃ puccheyyan”ti.**Why don’t I ask him how to accomplish the sacrifice with three modes and sixteen accessories?”*";
P_HTM[2044]="*Atha kho kūṭadanto brāhmaṇo khattaṃ āmantesi:**Then Kūṭadanta addressed his steward,*";
P_HTM[2045]="*“tena hi, bho khatte, yena khāṇumatakā brāhmaṇagahapatikā tenupasaṅkama. upasaṅkamitvā khāṇumatake brāhmaṇagahapatike evaṃ vadehi:**“Well then, go to the brahmins and householders and say to them:*";
P_HTM[2046]="*‘kūṭadanto, bho, brāhmaṇo evamāha—**‘Sirs, the brahmin Kūṭadanta asks*";
P_HTM[2047]="*āgamentu kira bhavanto, kūṭadantopi brāhmaṇo samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamissatī’”ti.**you to wait, as he will also go to see the ascetic Gotama.’”*";
P_HTM[2048]="*“Evaṃ, bho”ti kho so khattā kūṭadantassa brāhmaṇassa paṭissutvā yena khāṇumatakā brāhmaṇagahapatikā tenupasaṅkami. upasaṅkamitvā khāṇumatake brāhmaṇagahapatike etadavoca:**“Yes, sir,” replied the steward, and did as he was asked.*";
P_HTM[2049]="*“kūṭadanto, bho, brāhmaṇo evamāha:* **";
P_HTM[2050]="*‘āgamentu kira bhonto, kūṭadantopi brāhmaṇo samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamissatī’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[2051]="*2. Kūṭadantaguṇakathā**2. The Qualities of Kūṭadanta*";
P_HTM[2052]="*Tena kho pana samayena anekāni brāhmaṇasatāni khāṇumate paṭivasanti:**Now at that time several hundred brahmins were residing in Khāṇumata*";
P_HTM[2053]="*“kūṭadantassa brāhmaṇassa mahāyaññaṃ anubhavissāmā”ti.**thinking to participate in Kūṭadanta’s sacrifice.*";
P_HTM[2054]="*Assosuṃ kho te brāhmaṇā:**They heard that*";
P_HTM[2055]="*“kūṭadanto kira brāhmaṇo samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamissatī”ti.**Kūṭadanta was going to see the ascetic Gotama.*";
P_HTM[2056]="*Atha kho te brāhmaṇā yena kūṭadanto brāhmaṇo tenupasaṅkamiṃsu. upasaṅkamitvā kūṭadantaṃ brāhmaṇaṃ etadavocuṃ:**They approached Kūṭadanta and said to him:*";
P_HTM[2057]="*“saccaṃ kira bhavaṃ kūṭadanto samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamissatī”ti?**“Is it really true that you are going to see the ascetic Gotama?”*";
P_HTM[2058]="*“Evaṃ kho me, bho, hoti:**“Yes, gentlemen, it is true.”*";
P_HTM[2059]="*‘ahampi samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamissāmī’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[2060]="*“Mā bhavaṃ kūṭadanto samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkami.**“Please don’t!*";
P_HTM[2061]="*Na arahati bhavaṃ kūṭadanto samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamituṃ.**It’s not appropriate for you to go to see the ascetic Gotama.*";
P_HTM[2062]="*Sace bhavaṃ kūṭadanto samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamissati, bhoto kūṭadantassa yaso hāyissati, samaṇassa gotamassa yaso abhivaḍḍhissati.**For if you do so, your reputation will diminish and his will increase.*";
P_HTM[2063]="*Yampi bhoto kūṭadantassa yaso hāyissati, samaṇassa gotamassa yaso abhivaḍḍhissati, imināpaṅgena na arahati bhavaṃ kūṭadanto samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamituṃ.**For this reason it’s not appropriate for you to go to see the ascetic Gotama;*";
P_HTM[2064]="*Samaṇo tveva gotamo arahati bhavantaṃ kūṭadantaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamituṃ.**it’s appropriate that he comes to see you.*";
P_HTM[2065]="*Bhavañhi kūṭadanto ubhato sujāto mātito ca pitito ca saṃsuddhagahaṇiko yāva sattamā pitāmahayugā akkhitto anupakkuṭṭho jātivādena.**You are well born on both your mother’s and father’s side, of pure descent, irrefutable and impeccable in questions of ancestry back to the seventh paternal generation.*";
P_HTM[2066]="*Yampi bhavaṃ kūṭadanto ubhato sujāto mātito ca pitito ca saṃsuddhagahaṇiko yāva sattamā pitāmahayugā akkhitto anupakkuṭṭho jātivādena, imināpaṅgena na arahati bhavaṃ kūṭadanto samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamituṃ.**For this reason it’s not appropriate for you to go to see the ascetic Gotama;*";
P_HTM[2067]="*Samaṇo tveva gotamo arahati bhavantaṃ kūṭadantaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamituṃ.**it’s appropriate that he comes to see you.*";
P_HTM[2068]="*Bhavañhi kūṭadanto aḍḍho mahaddhano mahābhogo pahūtavittūpakaraṇo pahūtajātarūparajato … pe …**You’re rich, affluent, and wealthy, with lots of property and assets, and lots of money and grain …*";
P_HTM[2069]="*Bhavañhi kūṭadanto ajjhāyako mantadharo tiṇṇaṃ vedānaṃ pāragū sanighaṇḍukeṭubhānaṃ sākkharappabhedānaṃ itihāsapañcamānaṃ padako veyyākaraṇo lokāyatamahāpurisalakkhaṇesu anavayo … pe …**You recite and remember the hymns, and have mastered the three Vedas, together with their vocabularies, ritual, phonology and etymology, and the testament as fifth. You know philology and grammar, and are well versed in cosmology and the marks of a great man. …*";
P_HTM[2070]="*Bhavañhi kūṭadanto abhirūpo dassanīyo pāsādiko paramāya vaṇṇapokkharatāya samannāgato brahmavaṇṇī brahmavacchasī akhuddāvakāso dassanāya … pe …**You are attractive, good-looking, lovely, of surpassing beauty. You are magnificent, splendid, remarkable to behold. …*";
P_HTM[2071]="*Bhavañhi kūṭadanto sīlavā vuddhasīlī vuddhasīlena samannāgato … pe …**You are ethical, mature in ethical conduct. …*";
P_HTM[2072]="*Bhavañhi kūṭadanto kalyāṇavāco kalyāṇavākkaraṇo poriyā vācāya samannāgato vissaṭṭhāya anelagalāya atthassa viññāpaniyā … pe …**You’re a good speaker, with a polished, clear, and articulate voice that expresses the meaning. …*";
P_HTM[2073]="*Bhavañhi kūṭadanto bahūnaṃ ācariyapācariyo tīṇi māṇavakasatāni mante vāceti, bahū kho pana nānādisā nānājanapadā māṇavakā āgacchanti bhoto kūṭadantassa santike mantatthikā mante adhiyitukāmā … pe …**You teach the teachers of many, and teach three hundred students to recite the hymns. Many students come from various districts and countries for the sake of the hymns, wishing to learn the hymns. …*";
P_HTM[2074]="*Bhavañhi kūṭadanto jiṇṇo vuddho mahallako addhagato vayoanuppatto.**You’re old, elderly and senior, advanced in years, and have reached the final stage of life.*";
P_HTM[2075]="*Samaṇo gotamo taruṇo ceva taruṇapabbajito ca … pe …**The ascetic Gotama is young, and has newly gone forth. …*";
P_HTM[2076]="*Bhavañhi kūṭadanto rañño māgadhassa seniyassa bimbisārassa sakkato garukato mānito pūjito apacito … pe …**You’re honored, respected, revered, venerated, and esteemed by King Bimbisāra of Magadha …*";
P_HTM[2077]="*Bhavañhi kūṭadanto brāhmaṇassa pokkharasātissa sakkato garukato mānito pūjito apacito … pe …**and the brahmin Pokkharasāti. …*";
P_HTM[2078]="*Bhavañhi kūṭadanto khāṇumataṃ ajjhāvasati sattussadaṃ satiṇakaṭṭhodakaṃ sadhaññaṃ rājabhoggaṃ raññā māgadhena seniyena bimbisārena dinnaṃ rājadāyaṃ brahmadeyyaṃ.**You live in Khāṇumata, a crown property given by King Seniya Bimbisāra of Magadha, teeming with living creatures, full of hay, wood, water, and grain, a royal endowment of the highest quality.*";
P_HTM[2079]="*Yampi bhavaṃ kūṭadanto khāṇumataṃ ajjhāvasati sattussadaṃ satiṇakaṭṭhodakaṃ sadhaññaṃ rājabhoggaṃ, raññā māgadhena seniyena bimbisārena dinnaṃ rājadāyaṃ brahmadeyyaṃ, imināpaṅgena na arahati bhavaṃ kūṭadanto samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamituṃ.**For this reason it’s not appropriate for you to go to see the ascetic Gotama;*";
P_HTM[2080]="*Samaṇo tveva gotamo arahati bhavantaṃ kūṭadantaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamitun”ti.**it’s appropriate that he comes to see you.”*";
P_HTM[2081]="*3. Buddhaguṇakathā**3. The Qualities of the Buddha*";
P_HTM[2082]="*Evaṃ vutte, kūṭadanto brāhmaṇo te brāhmaṇe etadavoca:**When they had spoken, Kūṭadanta said to those brahmins:*";
P_HTM[2083]="*“Tena hi, bho, mamapi suṇātha, yathā mayameva arahāma taṃ bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamituṃ,**“Well then, gentlemen, listen to why it’s appropriate for me to go to see the ascetic Gotama,*";
P_HTM[2084]="*na tveva arahati so bhavaṃ gotamo amhākaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamituṃ.**and it’s not appropriate for him to come to see me.*";
P_HTM[2085]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo ubhato sujāto mātito ca pitito ca saṃsuddhagahaṇiko yāva sattamā pitāmahayugā akkhitto anupakkuṭṭho jātivādena.**He is well born on both his mother’s and father’s side, of pure descent, irrefutable and impeccable in questions of ancestry back to the seventh paternal generation.*";
P_HTM[2086]="*Yampi, bho, samaṇo gotamo ubhato sujāto mātito ca pitito ca saṃsuddhagahaṇiko yāva sattamā pitāmahayugā akkhitto anupakkuṭṭho jātivādena, imināpaṅgena na arahati so bhavaṃ gotamo amhākaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamituṃ.**For this reason it’s not appropriate for the ascetic Gotama to come to see me;*";
P_HTM[2087]="*Atha kho mayameva arahāma taṃ bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamituṃ.**rather, it’s appropriate for me to go to see him.*";
P_HTM[2088]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo mahantaṃ ñātisaṅghaṃ ohāya pabbajito … pe …**When he went forth he abandoned a large family circle. …*";
P_HTM[2089]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo pahūtaṃ hiraññasuvaṇṇaṃ ohāya pabbajito bhūmigatañca vehāsaṭṭhaṃ ca … pe …**When he went forth he abandoned abundant gold coin and bullion stored in dungeons and towers. …*";
P_HTM[2090]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo daharova samāno yuvā susukāḷakeso bhadrena yobbanena samannāgato paṭhamena vayasā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajito … pe …**He went forth from the lay life to homelessness while still a youth, young, black-haired, blessed with youth, in the prime of life. …*";
P_HTM[2091]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo akāmakānaṃ mātāpitūnaṃ assumukhānaṃ rudantānaṃ kesamassuṃ ohāretvā kāsāyāni vatthāni acchādetvā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajito … pe …**Though his mother and father wished otherwise, weeping with tearful faces, he shaved off his hair and beard, dressed in ocher robes, and went forth from the lay life to homelessness. …*";
P_HTM[2092]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo abhirūpo dassanīyo pāsādiko paramāya vaṇṇapokkharatāya samannāgato brahmavaṇṇī brahmavacchasī akhuddāvakāso dassanāya … pe …**He is attractive, good-looking, lovely, of surpassing beauty. He is magnificent, splendid, remarkable to behold. …*";
P_HTM[2093]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo sīlavā ariyasīlī kusalasīlī kusalasīlena samannāgato … pe …**He is ethical, possessing ethical conduct that is noble and skillful. …*";
P_HTM[2094]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo kalyāṇavāco kalyāṇavākkaraṇo poriyā vācāya samannāgato vissaṭṭhāya anelagalāya atthassa viññāpaniyā … pe …**He’s a good speaker, with a polished, clear, and articulate voice that expresses the meaning. …*";
P_HTM[2095]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo bahūnaṃ ācariyapācariyo … pe …**He’s a teacher of teachers. …*";
P_HTM[2096]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo khīṇakāmarāgo vigatacāpallo … pe …**He has ended sensual desire, and is rid of caprice. …*";
P_HTM[2097]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo kammavādī kiriyavādī apāpapurekkhāro brahmaññāya pajāya … pe …**He teaches the efficacy of deeds and action. He doesn’t wish any harm upon the community of brahmins. …*";
P_HTM[2098]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo uccā kulā pabbajito asambhinnakhattiyakulā … pe …**He went forth from an eminent family of unbroken aristocratic lineage. …*";
P_HTM[2099]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo aḍḍhā kulā pabbajito mahaddhanā mahābhogā … pe …**He went forth from a rich, affluent, and wealthy family. …*";
P_HTM[2100]="*Samaṇaṃ khalu, bho, gotamaṃ tiroraṭṭhā tirojanapadā pañhaṃ pucchituṃ āgacchanti … pe …**People come from distant lands and distant countries to question him. …*";
P_HTM[2101]="*Samaṇaṃ khalu, bho, gotamaṃ anekāni devatāsahassāni pāṇehi saraṇaṃ gatāni … pe …**Many thousands of deities have gone for refuge for life to him. …*";
P_HTM[2102]="*Samaṇaṃ khalu, bho, gotamaṃ evaṃ kalyāṇo kittisaddo abbhuggato:**He has this good reputation:*";
P_HTM[2103]="*‘itipi so bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā’ti … pe …**‘That Blessed One is perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.’ …*";
P_HTM[2104]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo dvattiṃsamahāpurisalakkhaṇehi samannāgato … pe …**He has the thirty-two marks of a great man. …*";
P_HTM[2105]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo ehisvāgatavādī sakhilo sammodako abbhākuṭiko uttānamukho pubbabhāsī … pe …**He is welcoming, congenial, polite, smiling, open, the first to speak. …*";
P_HTM[2106]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo catunnaṃ parisānaṃ sakkato garukato mānito pūjito apacito … pe …**He’s honored, respected, revered, venerated, and esteemed by the four assemblies. …*";
P_HTM[2107]="*Samaṇe khalu, bho, gotame bahū devā ca manussā ca abhippasannā … pe …**Many gods and humans are devoted to him. …*";
P_HTM[2108]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo yasmiṃ gāme vā nigame vā paṭivasati na tasmiṃ gāme vā nigame vā amanussā manusse viheṭhenti … pe …**While he is residing in a village or town, non-human entities do not harass them. …*";
P_HTM[2109]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo saṅghī gaṇī gaṇācariyo puthutitthakarānaṃ aggamakkhāyati, yathā kho pana, bho, etesaṃ samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ yathā vā tathā vā yaso samudāgacchati, na hevaṃ samaṇassa gotamassa yaso samudāgato.**He leads an order and a community, and teaches a community, and is said to be the best of the various religious founders. He didn’t come by his fame in the same ways as those other ascetics and brahmins.*";
P_HTM[2110]="*Atha kho anuttarāya vijjācaraṇasampadāya samaṇassa gotamassa yaso samudāgato … pe …**Rather, he came by his fame due to his supreme knowledge and conduct. …*";
P_HTM[2111]="*Samaṇaṃ khalu, bho, gotamaṃ rājā māgadho seniyo bimbisāro saputto sabhariyo sapariso sāmacco pāṇehi saraṇaṃ gato … pe …**King Seniya Bimbisāra of Magadha and his wives and children have gone for refuge for life to the ascetic Gotama. …*";
P_HTM[2112]="*Samaṇaṃ khalu, bho, gotamaṃ rājā pasenadi kosalo saputto sabhariyo sapariso sāmacco pāṇehi saraṇaṃ gato … pe …**King Pasenadi of Kosala and his wives and children have gone for refuge for life to the ascetic Gotama. …*";
P_HTM[2113]="*Samaṇaṃ khalu, bho, gotamaṃ brāhmaṇo pokkharasāti saputto sabhariyo sapariso sāmacco pāṇehi saraṇaṃ gato … pe …**The brahmin Pokkharasāti and his wives and children have gone for refuge for life to the ascetic Gotama. …*";
P_HTM[2114]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo rañño māgadhassa seniyassa bimbisārassa sakkato garukato mānito pūjito apacito … pe …**He’s honored, respected, revered, venerated, and esteemed by King Bimbisāra of Magadha …*";
P_HTM[2115]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo rañño pasenadissa kosalassa sakkato garukato mānito pūjito apacito … pe …**King Pasenadi of Kosala …*";
P_HTM[2116]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo brāhmaṇassa pokkharasātissa sakkato garukato mānito pūjito apacito … pe …**and the brahmin Pokkharasāti.*";
P_HTM[2117]="*Samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo khāṇumataṃ anuppatto khāṇumate viharati ambalaṭṭhikāyaṃ.**The ascetic Gotama has arrived at Khāṇumata and is staying at Ambalaṭṭhikā.*";
P_HTM[2118]="*Ye kho pana, bho, keci samaṇā vā brāhmaṇā vā amhākaṃ gāmakhettaṃ āgacchanti, atithī no te honti.**Any ascetic or brahmin who comes to stay in our village district is our guest,*";
P_HTM[2119]="*Atithī kho panamhehi sakkātabbā garukātabbā mānetabbā pūjetabbā apacetabbā.**and should be honored and respected as such.*";
P_HTM[2120]="*Yampi, bho, samaṇo gotamo khāṇumataṃ anuppatto khāṇumate viharati ambalaṭṭhikāyaṃ, atithimhākaṃ samaṇo gotamo.* **";
P_HTM[2121]="*Atithi kho panamhehi sakkātabbo garukātabbo mānetabbo pūjetabbo apacetabbo.* **";
P_HTM[2122]="*Imināpaṅgena nārahati so bhavaṃ gotamo amhākaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamituṃ.**For this reason, too, it’s not appropriate for Master Gotama to come to see me,*";
P_HTM[2123]="*Atha kho mayameva arahāma taṃ bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamituṃ.**rather, it’s appropriate for me to go to see him.*";
P_HTM[2124]="*Ettake kho ahaṃ, bho, tassa bhoto gotamassa vaṇṇe pariyāpuṇāmi, no ca kho so bhavaṃ gotamo ettakavaṇṇo.**This is the extent of Master Gotama’s praise that I have learned. But his praises are not confined to this,*";
P_HTM[2125]="*Aparimāṇavaṇṇo hi so bhavaṃ gotamo”ti.**for the praise of Master Gotama is limitless.”*";
P_HTM[2126]="*Evaṃ vutte, te brāhmaṇā kūṭadantaṃ brāhmaṇaṃ etadavocuṃ:**When he had spoken, those brahmins said to him,*";
P_HTM[2127]="*“yathā kho bhavaṃ kūṭadanto samaṇassa gotamassa vaṇṇe bhāsati, ito cepi so bhavaṃ gotamo yojanasate viharati, alameva saddhena kulaputtena dassanāya upasaṅkamituṃ api puṭosenā”ti.**“According to Kūṭadanta’s praises, if Master Gotama were staying within a hundred leagues, it’d be worthwhile for a faithful gentleman to go to see him, even if they had to carry their own provisions in a shoulder bag.”*";
P_HTM[2128]="*“Tena hi, bho, sabbeva mayaṃ samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ dassanāya upasaṅkamissāmā”ti.**“Well then, gentlemen, let’s all go to see the ascetic Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[2129]="*4. Mahāvijitarājayaññakathā**4. The Story of King Mahāvijita’s Sacrifice*";
P_HTM[2130]="*Atha kho kūṭadanto brāhmaṇo mahatā brāhmaṇagaṇena saddhiṃ yena ambalaṭṭhikā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami, upasaṅkamitvā bhagavatā saddhiṃ sammodi.**Then Kūṭadanta together with a large group of brahmins went to see the Buddha and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[2131]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi.**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, he sat down to one side.*";
P_HTM[2132]="*Khāṇumatakāpi kho brāhmaṇagahapatikā appekacce bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu; appekacce bhagavatā saddhiṃ sammodiṃsu, sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu; appekacce yena bhagavā tenañjaliṃ paṇāmetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu; appekacce nāmagottaṃ sāvetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu; appekacce tuṇhībhūtā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu.**Before sitting down to one side, some of the brahmins and householders of Khāṇumataka bowed, some exchanged greetings and polite conversation, some held up their joined palms toward the Buddha, some announced their name and clan, while some kept silent.*";
P_HTM[2133]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho kūṭadanto brāhmaṇo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Kūṭadanta said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[2134]="*“sutaṃ metaṃ, bho gotama:**“Master Gotama, I’ve heard that*";
P_HTM[2135]="*‘samaṇo gotamo tividhaṃ yaññasampadaṃ soḷasaparikkhāraṃ jānātī’ti.**you know how to accomplish the sacrifice with three modes and sixteen accessories.*";
P_HTM[2136]="*Na kho panāhaṃ jānāmi tividhaṃ yaññasampadaṃ soḷasaparikkhāraṃ.**I don’t know about that,*";
P_HTM[2137]="*Icchāmi cāhaṃ mahāyaññaṃ yajituṃ.**but I wish to perform a great sacrifice.*";
P_HTM[2138]="*Sādhu me bhavaṃ gotamo tividhaṃ yaññasampadaṃ soḷasaparikkhāraṃ desetū”ti.**Please teach me how to accomplish the sacrifice with three modes and sixteen accessories.”*";
P_HTM[2139]="*“Tena hi, brāhmaṇa, suṇāhi sādhukaṃ manasikarohi, bhāsissāmī”ti.**“Well then, brahmin, listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[2140]="*“Evaṃ, bho”ti kho kūṭadanto brāhmaṇo bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes sir,” Kūṭadanta replied.*";
P_HTM[2141]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[2142]="*“bhūtapubbaṃ, brāhmaṇa, rājā mahāvijito nāma ahosi aḍḍho mahaddhano mahābhogo pahūtajātarūparajato pahūtavittūpakaraṇo pahūtadhanadhañño paripuṇṇakosakoṭṭhāgāro.**Once upon a time, brahmin, there was a king named Mahāvijita. He was rich, affluent, and wealthy, with lots of gold and silver, lots of property and assets, lots of money and grain, and a full treasury and storehouses.*";
P_HTM[2143]="*Atha kho, brāhmaṇa, rañño mahāvijitassa rahogatassa paṭisallīnassa evaṃ cetaso parivitakko udapādi:**Then as King Mahāvijita was in private retreat this thought came to his mind:*";
P_HTM[2144]="*‘adhigatā kho me vipulā mānusakā bhogā, mahantaṃ pathavimaṇḍalaṃ abhivijiya ajjhāvasāmi, yannūnāhaṃ mahāyaññaṃ yajeyyaṃ, yaṃ mama assa dīgharattaṃ hitāya sukhāyā’ti.**‘I have achieved human wealth, and reign after conquering this vast territory. Why don’t I hold a large sacrifice? That will be for my lasting welfare and happiness.’*";
P_HTM[2145]="*Atha kho, brāhmaṇa, rājā mahāvijito purohitaṃ brāhmaṇaṃ āmantetvā etadavoca:**Then he summoned the brahmin high priest and said to him:*";
P_HTM[2146]="*‘idha mayhaṃ, brāhmaṇa, rahogatassa paṭisallīnassa evaṃ cetaso parivitakko udapādi:**‘Just now, brahmin, as I was in private retreat this thought came to mind,*";
P_HTM[2147]="*“adhigatā kho me vipulā mānusakā bhogā, mahantaṃ pathavimaṇḍalaṃ abhivijiya ajjhāvasāmi. Yannūnāhaṃ mahāyaññaṃ yajeyyaṃ yaṃ mama assa dīgharattaṃ hitāya sukhāyā”ti.**“I have achieved human wealth, and reign after conquering this vast territory. Why don’t I perform a great sacrifice? That will be for my lasting welfare and happiness.”*";
P_HTM[2148]="*Icchāmahaṃ, brāhmaṇa, mahāyaññaṃ yajituṃ.**Brahmin, I wish to perform a great sacrifice.*";
P_HTM[2149]="*Anusāsatu maṃ bhavaṃ yaṃ mama assa dīgharattaṃ hitāya sukhāyā’ti.**Please instruct me. It will be for my lasting welfare and happiness.’*";
P_HTM[2150]="*Evaṃ vutte, brāhmaṇa, purohito brāhmaṇo rājānaṃ mahāvijitaṃ etadavoca:**When he had spoken, the brahmin high priest said to him:*";
P_HTM[2151]="*‘bhoto kho rañño janapado sakaṇṭako sauppīḷo, gāmaghātāpi dissanti, nigamaghātāpi dissanti, nagaraghātāpi dissanti, panthaduhanāpi dissanti.**‘Sir, the king’s realm is harried and oppressed. Bandits have been seen raiding villages, towns, and cities, and infesting the highways.*";
P_HTM[2152]="*Bhavaṃ kho pana rājā evaṃ sakaṇṭake janapade sauppīḷe balimuddhareyya, akiccakārī assa tena bhavaṃ rājā.**But if the king were to extract more taxes while his realm is thus harried and oppressed, he would not be doing his duty.*";
P_HTM[2153]="*Siyā kho pana bhoto rañño evamassa:**Now the king might think,*";
P_HTM[2154]="*“ahametaṃ dassukhīlaṃ vadhena vā bandhena vā jāniyā vā garahāya vā pabbājanāya vā samūhanissāmī”ti, na kho panetassa dassukhīlassa evaṃ sammā samugghāto hoti.**“I’ll eradicate this barbarian obstacle by execution or imprisonment or confiscation or condemnation or banishment!” But that’s not the right way to eradicate this barbarian obstacle.*";
P_HTM[2155]="*Ye te hatāvasesakā bhavissanti, te pacchā rañño janapadaṃ viheṭhessanti.**Those who remain after the killing will return to harass the king’s realm.*";
P_HTM[2156]="*Api ca kho idaṃ saṃvidhānaṃ āgamma evametassa dassukhīlassa sammā samugghāto hoti.**Rather, here is a plan, relying on which the barbarian obstacle will be properly uprooted.*";
P_HTM[2157]="*Tena hi bhavaṃ rājā ye bhoto rañño janapade ussahanti kasigorakkhe, tesaṃ bhavaṃ rājā bījabhattaṃ anuppadetu.**So let the king provide seed and fodder for those in the realm who work in farming and raising cattle.*";
P_HTM[2158]="*Ye bhoto rañño janapade ussahanti vāṇijjāya, tesaṃ bhavaṃ rājā pābhataṃ anuppadetu.**Let the king provide funding for those who work in trade.*";
P_HTM[2159]="*Ye bhoto rañño janapade ussahanti rājaporise, tesaṃ bhavaṃ rājā bhattavetanaṃ pakappetu.**Let the king guarantee food and wages for those in government service.*";
P_HTM[2160]="*Te ca manussā sakammapasutā rañño janapadaṃ na viheṭhessanti;**Then the people, occupied with their own work, will not harass the realm.*";
P_HTM[2161]="*mahā ca rañño rāsiko bhavissati.**The king’s revenues will be great.*";
P_HTM[2162]="*Khemaṭṭhitā janapadā akaṇṭakā anuppīḷā. Manussā mudā modamānā ure putte naccentā apārutagharā maññe viharissantī’ti.**When the country is secured as a sanctuary, free of being harried and oppressed, the happy people, with joy in their hearts, dancing with children at their breast, will dwell as if their houses were wide open.’*";
P_HTM[2163]="*‘Evaṃ, bho’ti kho, brāhmaṇa, rājā mahāvijito purohitassa brāhmaṇassa paṭissutvā ye rañño janapade ussahiṃsu kasigorakkhe, tesaṃ rājā mahāvijito bījabhattaṃ anuppadāsi.**The king agreed with the high priest’s advice and followed his recommendation.*";
P_HTM[2164]="*Ye ca rañño janapade ussahiṃsu vāṇijjāya, tesaṃ rājā mahāvijito pābhataṃ anuppadāsi.* **";
P_HTM[2165]="*Ye ca rañño janapade ussahiṃsu rājaporise, tesaṃ rājā mahāvijito bhattavetanaṃ pakappesi.* **";
P_HTM[2166]="*Te ca manussā sakammapasutā rañño janapadaṃ na viheṭhiṃsu, mahā ca rañño rāsiko ahosi.* **";
P_HTM[2167]="*Khemaṭṭhitā janapadā akaṇṭakā anuppīḷā manussā mudā modamānā ure putte naccentā apārutagharā maññe vihariṃsu.* **";
P_HTM[2168]="*Atha kho, brāhmaṇa, rājā mahāvijito purohitaṃ brāhmaṇaṃ āmantetvā etadavoca:**Then the king summoned the brahmin high priest and said to him:*";
P_HTM[2169]="*‘samūhato kho me bhoto dassukhīlo, bhoto saṃvidhānaṃ āgamma mahā ca me rāsiko.**‘I have eradicated the barbarian obstacle. And relying on your plan my revenue is now great.*";
P_HTM[2170]="*Khemaṭṭhitā janapadā akaṇṭakā anuppīḷā manussā mudā modamānā ure putte naccentā apārutagharā maññe viharanti.**Since the country is secured as a sanctuary, free of being harried and oppressed, the happy people, with joy in their hearts, dancing with children at their breast, dwell as if their houses were wide open.*";
P_HTM[2171]="*Icchāmahaṃ brāhmaṇa mahāyaññaṃ yajituṃ.**Brahmin, I wish to perform a great sacrifice.*";
P_HTM[2172]="*Anusāsatu maṃ bhavaṃ yaṃ mama assa dīgharattaṃ hitāya sukhāyā’ti.**Please instruct me. It will be for my lasting welfare and happiness.’*";
P_HTM[2173]="*4.1. Catuparikkhāra**4.1. The Four Accessories*";
P_HTM[2174]="*Tena hi bhavaṃ rājā ye bhoto rañño janapade khattiyā ānuyantā negamā ceva jānapadā ca te bhavaṃ rājā āmantayataṃ: ‘icchāmahaṃ, bho, mahāyaññaṃ yajituṃ, anujānantu me bhavanto yaṃ mama assa dīgharattaṃ hitāya sukhāyā’ti. Ye bhoto rañño janapade amaccā pārisajjā negamā ceva jānapadā ca … pe … brāhmaṇamahāsālā negamā ceva jānapadā ca … pe … gahapatinecayikā negamā ceva jānapadā ca, te bhavaṃ rājā āmantayataṃ:**‘In that case, let the king announce this throughout the realm to the aristocrat vassals, ministers and counselors, well-to-do brahmins, and well-off householders, both of town and country:*";
P_HTM[2175]="*‘icchāmahaṃ, bho, mahāyaññaṃ yajituṃ, anujānantu me bhavanto yaṃ mama assa dīgharattaṃ hitāya sukhāyā’ti.**“I wish to perform a great sacrifice. Please grant your approval, gentlemen; it will be for my lasting welfare and happiness.”*";
P_HTM[2176]="*‘Evaṃ, bho’ti kho, brāhmaṇa, rājā mahāvijito purohitassa brāhmaṇassa paṭissutvā ye rañño janapade khattiyā ānuyantā negamā ceva jānapadā ca, te rājā mahāvijito āmantesi:**The king agreed with the high priest’s advice and followed his recommendation.*";
P_HTM[2177]="*‘icchāmahaṃ, bho, mahāyaññaṃ yajituṃ, anujānantu me bhavanto yaṃ mama assa dīgharattaṃ hitāya sukhāyā’ti.**And all of the people who were thus informed responded by saying:*";
P_HTM[2178]="*‘Yajataṃ bhavaṃ rājā yaññaṃ, yaññakālo, mahārājā’ti.**‘May the king perform a sacrifice! It is time for a sacrifice, great king.’*";
P_HTM[2179]="*Ye rañño janapade amaccā pārisajjā negamā ceva jānapadā ca … pe … brāhmaṇamahāsālā negamā ceva jānapadā ca … pe … gahapatinecayikā negamā ceva jānapadā ca, te rājā mahāvijito āmantesi:* **";
P_HTM[2180]="*‘icchāmahaṃ, bho, mahāyaññaṃ yajituṃ. Anujānantu me bhavanto yaṃ mama assa dīgharattaṃ hitāya sukhāyā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2181]="*‘Yajataṃ bhavaṃ rājā yaññaṃ, yaññakālo, mahārājā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2182]="*Itime cattāro anumatipakkhā tasseva yaññassa parikkhārā bhavanti.**And so these four consenting factions became accessories to the sacrifice.*";
P_HTM[2183]="*4.2. Aṭṭhaparikkhāra**4.2. The Eight Accessories*";
P_HTM[2184]="*Rājā mahāvijito aṭṭhahaṅgehi samannāgato—**King Mahāvijita possessed eight factors.*";
P_HTM[2185]="*ubhato sujāto mātito ca pitito ca saṃsuddhagahaṇiko yāva sattamā pitāmahayugā akkhitto anupakkuṭṭho jātivādena;**He was well born on both his mother’s and father’s side, of pure descent, irrefutable and impeccable in questions of ancestry back to the seventh paternal generation.*";
P_HTM[2186]="*abhirūpo dassanīyo pāsādiko paramāya vaṇṇapokkharatāya samannāgato brahmavaṇṇī brahmavacchasī akhuddāvakāso dassanāya;**He was attractive, good-looking, lovely, of surpassing beauty. He was magnificent, splendid, remarkable to behold.*";
P_HTM[2187]="*aḍḍho mahaddhano mahābhogo pahūtajātarūparajato pahūtavittūpakaraṇo pahūtadhanadhañño paripuṇṇakosakoṭṭhāgāro;**He was rich, affluent, and wealthy, with lots of gold and silver, lots of property and assets, lots of money and grain, and a full treasury and storehouses.*";
P_HTM[2188]="*balavā caturaṅginiyā senāya samannāgato assavāya ovādapaṭikarāya sahati maññe paccatthike yasasā;**He was powerful, having an army of four divisions that was obedient and carried out instructions. He’d probably prevail over his enemies just with his reputation.*";
P_HTM[2189]="*saddho dāyako dānapati anāvaṭadvāro samaṇabrāhmaṇakapaṇaddhikavaṇibbakayācakānaṃ opānabhūto puññāni karoti;**He was faithful, generous, a donor, his door always open. He was a well-spring of support, making merit with ascetics and brahmins, for paupers, vagrants, travelers, and beggars.*";
P_HTM[2190]="*bahussuto tassa tassa sutajātassa, tassa tasseva kho pana bhāsitassa atthaṃ jānāti:**He was very learned in diverse fields of learning. He understood the meaning of diverse statements, saying:*";
P_HTM[2191]="*‘ayaṃ imassa bhāsitassa attho ayaṃ imassa bhāsitassa attho’ti;**‘This is what that statement means; that is what this statement means.’*";
P_HTM[2192]="*paṇḍito, viyatto, medhāvī, paṭibalo, atītānāgatapaccuppanne atthe cintetuṃ.**He was astute, competent, and intelligent, able to think issues through as they bear upon the past, future, and present.*";
P_HTM[2193]="*Rājā mahāvijito imehi aṭṭhahaṅgehi samannāgato.**These are the eight factors that King Mahāvijita possessed.*";
P_HTM[2194]="*Iti imānipi aṭṭhaṅgāni tasseva yaññassa parikkhārā bhavanti.**And so these eight factors also became accessories to the sacrifice.*";
P_HTM[2195]="*4.3. Catuparikkhāra**4.3. Four More Accessories*";
P_HTM[2196]="*Purohito brāhmaṇo catūhaṅgehi samannāgato,**And the brahmin high priest had four factors.*";
P_HTM[2197]="*ubhato sujāto mātito ca pitito ca saṃsuddhagahaṇiko yāva sattamā pitāmahayugā akkhitto anupakkuṭṭho jātivādena;**He was well born on both his mother’s and father’s side, of pure descent, irrefutable and impeccable in questions of ancestry back to the seventh paternal generation.*";
P_HTM[2198]="*ajjhāyako mantadharo tiṇṇaṃ vedānaṃ pāragū sanighaṇḍukeṭubhānaṃ sākkharappabhedānaṃ itihāsapañcamānaṃ padako veyyākaraṇo lokāyatamahāpurisalakkhaṇesu anavayo;**He recited and remembered the hymns, and had mastered the three Vedas, together with their vocabularies, ritual, phonology and etymology, and the testament as fifth. He knew philology and grammar, and was well versed in cosmology and the marks of a great man.*";
P_HTM[2199]="*sīlavā vuddhasīlī vuddhasīlena samannāgato;**He was ethical, mature in ethical conduct.*";
P_HTM[2200]="*paṇḍito viyatto medhāvī paṭhamo vā dutiyo vā sujaṃ paggaṇhantānaṃ.**He was astute and clever, being the first or second to hold the sacrificial ladle.*";
P_HTM[2201]="*Purohito brāhmaṇo imehi catūhaṅgehi samannāgato.**These are the four factors that the brahmin high priest possessed.*";
P_HTM[2202]="*Iti imānipi cattāri aṅgāni tasseva yaññassa parikkhārā bhavanti.**And so these four factors also became accessories to the sacrifice.*";
P_HTM[2203]="*4.4. Tissovidhā**4.4. The Three Modes*";
P_HTM[2204]="*Atha kho, brāhmaṇa, purohito brāhmaṇo rañño mahāvijitassa pubbeva yaññā tisso vidhā desesi.**Next, before the sacrifice, the brahmin high priest taught the three modes to the king.*";
P_HTM[2205]="*Siyā kho pana bhoto rañño mahāyaññaṃ yiṭṭhukāmassa kocideva vippaṭisāro:**‘Now, though the king wants to perform a great sacrifice, he might have certain regrets, thinking:*";
P_HTM[2206]="*‘“mahā vata me bhogakkhandho vigacchissatī”ti, so bhotā raññā vippaṭisāro na karaṇīyo.**“I shall lose a great fortune,” or*";
P_HTM[2207]="*Siyā kho pana bhoto rañño mahāyaññaṃ yajamānassa kocideva vippaṭisāro:* **";
P_HTM[2208]="*“mahā vata me bhogakkhandho vigacchatī”ti, so bhotā raññā vippaṭisāro na karaṇīyo.**“I am losing a great fortune,” or*";
P_HTM[2209]="*Siyā kho pana bhoto rañño mahāyaññaṃ yiṭṭhassa kocideva vippaṭisāro:* **";
P_HTM[2210]="*“mahā vata me bhogakkhandho vigato”ti, so bhotā raññā vippaṭisāro na karaṇīyo’ti.**“I have lost a great fortune.” But the king should not harbor such regrets.’*";
P_HTM[2211]="*Imā kho, brāhmaṇa, purohito brāhmaṇo rañño mahāvijitassa pubbeva yaññā tisso vidhā desesi.**These are the three modes that the brahmin high priest taught to the king before the sacrifice.*";
P_HTM[2212]="*4.5. Dasaākāra**4.5. The Ten Respects*";
P_HTM[2213]="*Atha kho, brāhmaṇa, purohito brāhmaṇo rañño mahāvijitassa pubbeva yaññā dasahākārehi paṭiggāhakesu vippaṭisāraṃ paṭivinesi.**Next, before the sacrifice, the brahmin high priest dispelled the king’s regret regarding the recipients in ten respects:*";
P_HTM[2214]="*‘Āgamissanti kho bhoto yaññaṃ pāṇātipātinopi pāṇātipātā paṭiviratāpi.**‘There will come to the sacrifice those who kill living creatures and those who refrain from killing living creatures.*";
P_HTM[2215]="*Ye tattha pāṇātipātino, tesaññeva tena.**As to those who kill living creatures, the outcome of that is theirs alone.*";
P_HTM[2216]="*Ye tattha pāṇātipātā paṭiviratā, te ārabbha yajataṃ bhavaṃ, sajjataṃ bhavaṃ, modataṃ bhavaṃ, cittameva bhavaṃ antaraṃ pasādetu.**But as to those who refrain from killing living creatures, it is for their sakes that the king should sacrifice, relinquish, rejoice, and gain confidence in his heart.*";
P_HTM[2217]="*Āgamissanti kho bhoto yaññaṃ adinnādāyinopi adinnādānā paṭiviratāpi … pe …**There will come to the sacrifice those who steal …*";
P_HTM[2218]="*kāmesu micchācārinopi kāmesumicchācārā paṭiviratāpi …**commit sexual misconduct …*";
P_HTM[2219]="*musāvādinopi musāvādā paṭiviratāpi …**lie …*";
P_HTM[2220]="*pisuṇavācinopi pisuṇāya vācāya paṭiviratāpi …**use divisive speech …*";
P_HTM[2221]="*pharusavācinopi pharusāya vācāya paṭiviratāpi …**use harsh speech …*";
P_HTM[2222]="*samphappalāpinopi samphappalāpā paṭiviratāpi …**talk nonsense …*";
P_HTM[2223]="*abhijjhālunopi anabhijjhālunopi …**are covetous …*";
P_HTM[2224]="*byāpannacittāpi abyāpannacittāpi …**have ill will …*";
P_HTM[2225]="*micchādiṭṭhikāpi sammādiṭṭhikāpi ….**have wrong view and those who have right view.*";
P_HTM[2226]="*Ye tattha micchādiṭṭhikā, tesaññeva tena.**As to those who have wrong view, the outcome of that is theirs alone.*";
P_HTM[2227]="*Ye tattha sammādiṭṭhikā, te ārabbha yajataṃ bhavaṃ, sajjataṃ bhavaṃ, modataṃ bhavaṃ, cittameva bhavaṃ antaraṃ pasādetū’ti.**But as to those who have right view, it is for their sakes that the king should sacrifice, relinquish, rejoice, and gain confidence in his heart.’*";
P_HTM[2228]="*Imehi kho, brāhmaṇa, purohito brāhmaṇo rañño mahāvijitassa pubbeva yaññā dasahākārehi paṭiggāhakesu vippaṭisāraṃ paṭivinesi.**These are the ten respects in which the high priest dispelled the king’s regret regarding the recipients before the sacrifice.*";
P_HTM[2229]="*4.6. Soḷasākāra**4.6. The Sixteen Respects*";
P_HTM[2230]="*Atha kho, brāhmaṇa, purohito brāhmaṇo rañño mahāvijitassa mahāyaññaṃ yajamānassa soḷasahākārehi cittaṃ sandassesi samādapesi samuttejesi sampahaṃsesi**Next, while the king was performing the great sacrifice, the brahmin high priest educated, encouraged, fired up, and inspired the king’s mind in sixteen respects:*";
P_HTM[2231]="*siyā kho pana bhoto rañño mahāyaññaṃ yajamānassa kocideva vattā:**‘Now, while the king is performing the great sacrifice, someone might say,*";
P_HTM[2232]="*‘rājā kho mahāvijito mahāyaññaṃ yajati, no ca kho tassa āmantitā khattiyā ānuyantā negamā ceva jānapadā ca;**“King Mahāvijita performs a great sacrifice, but he did not announce it to the aristocrat vassals of town and country.*";
P_HTM[2233]="*atha ca pana bhavaṃ rājā evarūpaṃ mahāyaññaṃ yajatī’ti.**That’s the kind of great sacrifice that this king performs.”*";
P_HTM[2234]="*Evampi bhoto rañño vattā dhammato natthi.**Those who speak against the king in this way have no legitimacy.*";
P_HTM[2235]="*Bhotā kho pana raññā āmantitā khattiyā ānuyantā negamā ceva jānapadā ca.**For the king did indeed announce it to the aristocrat vassals of town and country.*";
P_HTM[2236]="*Imināpetaṃ bhavaṃ rājā jānātu, yajataṃ bhavaṃ, sajjataṃ bhavaṃ, modataṃ bhavaṃ, cittameva bhavaṃ antaraṃ pasādetu. (1)**Let the king know this as a reason to sacrifice, relinquish, rejoice, and gain confidence in his heart.*";
P_HTM[2237]="*Siyā kho pana bhoto rañño mahāyaññaṃ yajamānassa kocideva vattā:**While the king is performing the great sacrifice, someone might say,*";
P_HTM[2238]="*‘rājā kho mahāvijito mahāyaññaṃ yajati, no ca kho tassa āmantitā amaccā pārisajjā negamā ceva jānapadā ca … pe … brāhmaṇamahāsālā negamā ceva jānapadā ca … pe … gahapatinecayikā negamā ceva jānapadā ca, atha ca pana bhavaṃ rājā evarūpaṃ mahāyaññaṃ yajatī’ti.**“King Mahāvijita performs a great sacrifice, but he did not announce it to the ministers and counselors, well-to-do brahmins, and well-off householders, both of town and country. That’s the kind of great sacrifice that this king performs.”*";
P_HTM[2239]="*Evampi bhoto rañño vattā dhammato natthi.**Those who speak against the king in this way have no legitimacy.*";
P_HTM[2240]="*Bhotā kho pana raññā āmantitā gahapatinecayikā negamā ceva jānapadā ca.**For the king did indeed announce it to all these people.*";
P_HTM[2241]="*Imināpetaṃ bhavaṃ rājā jānātu, yajataṃ bhavaṃ, sajjataṃ bhavaṃ, modataṃ bhavaṃ, cittameva bhavaṃ antaraṃ pasādetu. (2–4.)**Let the king know this too as a reason to sacrifice, relinquish, rejoice, and gain confidence in his heart.*";
P_HTM[2242]="*Siyā kho pana bhoto rañño mahāyaññaṃ yajamānassa kocideva vattā:**While the king is performing the great sacrifice, someone might say*";
P_HTM[2243]="*‘rājā kho mahāvijito mahāyaññaṃ yajati, no ca kho ubhato sujāto mātito ca pitito ca saṃsuddhagahaṇiko yāva sattamā pitāmahayugā akkhitto anupakkuṭṭho jātivādena, atha ca pana bhavaṃ rājā evarūpaṃ mahāyaññaṃ yajatī’ti.**that he does not possess the eight factors.*";
P_HTM[2244]="*Evampi bhoto rañño vattā dhammato natthi.* **";
P_HTM[2245]="*Bhavaṃ kho pana rājā ubhato sujāto mātito ca pitito ca saṃsuddhagahaṇiko yāva sattamā pitāmahayugā akkhitto anupakkuṭṭho jātivādena.* **";
P_HTM[2246]="*Imināpetaṃ bhavaṃ rājā jānātu, yajataṃ bhavaṃ, sajjataṃ bhavaṃ, modataṃ bhavaṃ, cittameva bhavaṃ antaraṃ pasādetu. (5)* **";
P_HTM[2247]="*Siyā kho pana bhoto rañño mahāyaññaṃ yajamānassa kocideva vattā:* **";
P_HTM[2248]="*‘rājā kho mahāvijito mahāyaññaṃ yajati no ca kho abhirūpo dassanīyo pāsādiko paramāya vaṇṇapokkharatāya samannāgato brahmavaṇṇī brahmavacchasī akhuddāvakāso dassanāya … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2249]="*no ca kho aḍḍho mahaddhano mahābhogo pahūtajātarūparajato pahūtavittūpakaraṇo pahūtadhanadhañño paripuṇṇakosakoṭṭhāgāro … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2250]="*no ca kho balavā caturaṅginiyā senāya samannāgato assavāya ovādapaṭikarāya sahati maññe paccatthike yasasā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2251]="*no ca kho saddho dāyako dānapati anāvaṭadvāro samaṇabrāhmaṇakapaṇaddhikavaṇibbakayācakānaṃ opānabhūto puññāni karoti … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2252]="*no ca kho bahussuto tassa tassa sutajātassa … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2253]="*no ca kho tassa tasseva kho pana bhāsitassa atthaṃ jānāti:* **";
P_HTM[2254]="*“ayaṃ imassa bhāsitassa attho, ayaṃ imassa bhāsitassa attho”ti … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2255]="*no ca kho paṇḍito viyatto medhāvī paṭibalo atītānāgatapaccuppanne atthe cintetuṃ, atha ca pana bhavaṃ rājā evarūpaṃ mahāyaññaṃ yajatī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2256]="*Evampi bhoto rañño vattā dhammato natthi.**Those who speak against the king in this way have no legitimacy.*";
P_HTM[2257]="*Bhavaṃ kho pana rājā paṇḍito viyatto medhāvī paṭibalo atītānāgatapaccuppanne atthe cintetuṃ.**For the king does indeed possess the eight factors.*";
P_HTM[2258]="*Imināpetaṃ bhavaṃ rājā jānātu, yajataṃ bhavaṃ, sajjataṃ bhavaṃ, modataṃ bhavaṃ, cittameva bhavaṃ antaraṃ pasādetu. (6–12.)**Let the king know this too as a reason to sacrifice, relinquish, rejoice, and gain confidence in his heart.*";
P_HTM[2259]="*Siyā kho pana bhoto rañño mahāyaññaṃ yajamānassa kocideva vattā:**While the king is performing the great sacrifice, someone might say*";
P_HTM[2260]="*‘rājā kho mahāvijito mahāyaññaṃ yajati.**that the high priest does not possess the four factors.*";
P_HTM[2261]="*No ca khvassa purohito brāhmaṇo ubhato sujāto mātito ca pitito ca saṃsuddhagahaṇiko yāva sattamā pitāmahayugā akkhitto anupakkuṭṭho jātivādena;* **";
P_HTM[2262]="*atha ca pana bhavaṃ rājā evarūpaṃ mahāyaññaṃ yajatī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2263]="*Evampi bhoto rañño vattā dhammato natthi.* **";
P_HTM[2264]="*Bhoto kho pana rañño purohito brāhmaṇo ubhato sujāto mātito ca pitito ca saṃsuddhagahaṇiko yāva sattamā pitāmahayugā akkhitto anupakkuṭṭho jātivādena.* **";
P_HTM[2265]="*Imināpetaṃ bhavaṃ rājā jānātu, yajataṃ bhavaṃ, sajjataṃ bhavaṃ, modataṃ bhavaṃ, cittameva bhavaṃ antaraṃ pasādetu. (13)* **";
P_HTM[2266]="*Siyā kho pana bhoto rañño mahāyaññaṃ yajamānassa kocideva vattā:* **";
P_HTM[2267]="*‘rājā kho mahāvijito mahāyaññaṃ yajati.* **";
P_HTM[2268]="*No ca khvassa purohito brāhmaṇo ajjhāyako mantadharo tiṇṇaṃ vedānaṃ pāragū sanighaṇḍukeṭubhānaṃ sākkharappabhedānaṃ itihāsapañcamānaṃ padako veyyākaraṇo lokāyatamahāpurisalakkhaṇesu anavayo … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2269]="*no ca khvassa purohito brāhmaṇo sīlavā vuddhasīlī vuddhasīlena samannāgato … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2270]="*no ca khvassa purohito brāhmaṇo paṇḍito viyatto medhāvī paṭhamo vā dutiyo vā sujaṃ paggaṇhantānaṃ, atha ca pana bhavaṃ rājā evarūpaṃ mahāyaññaṃ yajatī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2271]="*Evampi bhoto rañño vattā dhammato natthi.**Those who speak against the king in this way have no legitimacy.*";
P_HTM[2272]="*Bhoto kho pana rañño purohito brāhmaṇo paṇḍito viyatto medhāvī paṭhamo vā dutiyo vā sujaṃ paggaṇhantānaṃ.**For the high priest does indeed possess the four factors.*";
P_HTM[2273]="*Imināpetaṃ bhavaṃ rājā jānātu, yajataṃ bhavaṃ, sajjataṃ bhavaṃ, modataṃ bhavaṃ, cittameva bhavaṃ antaraṃ pasādetūti.**Let the king know this too as a reason to sacrifice, relinquish, rejoice, and gain confidence in his heart.’*";
P_HTM[2274]="*Imehi kho, brāhmaṇa, purohito brāhmaṇo rañño mahāvijitassa mahāyaññaṃ yajamānassa soḷasahi ākārehi cittaṃ sandassesi samādapesi samuttejesi sampahaṃsesi. (14–16.)**These are the sixteen respects in which the high priest educated, encouraged, fired up, and inspired the king’s mind while he was performing the sacrifice.*";
P_HTM[2275]="*Tasmiṃ kho, brāhmaṇa, yaññe neva gāvo haññiṃsu, na ajeḷakā haññiṃsu, na kukkuṭasūkarā haññiṃsu, na vividhā pāṇā saṅghātaṃ āpajjiṃsu, na rukkhā chijjiṃsu yūpatthāya, na dabbhā lūyiṃsu barihisatthāya.**And brahmin, in that sacrifice no cattle were killed, no goats were killed, and no chickens or pigs were killed. There was no slaughter of various kinds of creatures. No trees were felled for the sacrificial post. No grass was reaped to strew over the place of sacrifice.*";
P_HTM[2276]="*Yepissa ahesuṃ dāsāti vā pessāti vā kammakarāti vā, tepi na daṇḍatajjitā na bhayatajjitā na assumukhā rudamānā parikammāni akaṃsu.**No bondservants, employees, or workers did their jobs under threat of punishment and danger, weeping with tearful faces.*";
P_HTM[2277]="*Atha kho ye icchiṃsu, te akaṃsu, ye na icchiṃsu, na te akaṃsu;**Those who wished to work did so, while those who did not wish to did not.*";
P_HTM[2278]="*yaṃ icchiṃsu, taṃ akaṃsu, yaṃ na icchiṃsu, na taṃ akaṃsu.**They did the work they wanted to, and did not do what they didn’t want to.*";
P_HTM[2279]="*Sappitelanavanītadadhimadhuphāṇitena ceva so yañño niṭṭhānamagamāsi.**The sacrifice was completed with just ghee, oil, butter, curds, honey, and molasses.*";
P_HTM[2280]="*Atha kho, brāhmaṇa, khattiyā ānuyantā negamā ceva jānapadā ca, amaccā pārisajjā negamā ceva jānapadā ca, brāhmaṇamahāsālā negamā ceva jānapadā ca, gahapatinecayikā negamā ceva jānapadā ca pahūtaṃ sāpateyyaṃ ādāya rājānaṃ mahāvijitaṃ upasaṅkamitvā evamāhaṃsu:**Then the aristocrat vassals, ministers and counselors, well-to-do brahmins, and well-off householders of both town and country came to the king bringing abundant wealth and said,*";
P_HTM[2281]="*‘idaṃ, deva, pahūtaṃ sāpateyyaṃ devaññeva uddissābhataṃ, taṃ devo paṭiggaṇhātū’ti.**‘Sire, this abundant wealth is specially for you alone; may Your Highness accept it!’*";
P_HTM[2282]="*‘Alaṃ, bho, mamāpidaṃ pahūtaṃ sāpateyyaṃ dhammikena balinā abhisaṅkhataṃ;**‘There’s enough raised for me through regular taxes. Let this be for you; and here, take even more!’*";
P_HTM[2283]="*tañca vo hotu, ito ca bhiyyo harathā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2284]="*Te raññā paṭikkhittā ekamantaṃ apakkamma evaṃ samacintesuṃ:**When the king turned them down, they withdrew to one side to think up a plan,*";
P_HTM[2285]="*‘na kho etaṃ amhākaṃ patirūpaṃ, yaṃ mayaṃ imāni sāpateyyāni punadeva sakāni gharāni paṭihareyyāma.**‘It wouldn’t be proper for us to take this abundant wealth back to our own homes.*";
P_HTM[2286]="*Rājā kho mahāvijito mahāyaññaṃ yajati, handassa mayaṃ anuyāgino homā’ti.**King Mahāvijita is performing a great sacrifice. Let us make an offering as an auxiliary sacrifice.’*";
P_HTM[2287]="*Atha kho, brāhmaṇa, puratthimena yaññavāṭassa khattiyā ānuyantā negamā ceva jānapadā ca dānāni paṭṭhapesuṃ.**Then the aristocrat vassals of town and country set up gifts to the east of the sacrificial pit.*";
P_HTM[2288]="*Dakkhiṇena yaññavāṭassa amaccā pārisajjā negamā ceva jānapadā ca dānāni paṭṭhapesuṃ.**The ministers and counselors of town and country set up gifts to the south of the sacrificial pit.*";
P_HTM[2289]="*Pacchimena yaññavāṭassa brāhmaṇamahāsālā negamā ceva jānapadā ca dānāni paṭṭhapesuṃ.**The well-to-do brahmins of town and country set up gifts to the west of the sacrificial pit.*";
P_HTM[2290]="*Uttarena yaññavāṭassa gahapatinecayikā negamā ceva jānapadā ca dānāni paṭṭhapesuṃ.**The well-off householders of town and country set up gifts to the north of the sacrificial pit.*";
P_HTM[2291]="*Tesupi kho, brāhmaṇa, yaññesu neva gāvo haññiṃsu, na ajeḷakā haññiṃsu, na kukkuṭasūkarā haññiṃsu, na vividhā pāṇā saṅghātaṃ āpajjiṃsu, na rukkhā chijjiṃsu yūpatthāya, na dabbhā lūyiṃsu barihisatthāya.**And brahmin, in that sacrifice too no cattle were killed, no goats were killed, and no chickens or pigs were killed. There was no slaughter of various kinds of creatures. No trees were felled for the sacrificial post. No grass was reaped to strew over the place of sacrifice.*";
P_HTM[2292]="*Yepi nesaṃ ahesuṃ dāsāti vā pessāti vā kammakarāti vā, tepi na daṇḍatajjitā na bhayatajjitā na assumukhā rudamānā parikammāni akaṃsu.**No bondservants, employees, or workers did their jobs under threat of punishment and danger, weeping with tearful faces.*";
P_HTM[2293]="*Atha kho ye icchiṃsu, te akaṃsu, ye na icchiṃsu, na te akaṃsu;**Those who wished to work did so, while those who did not wish to did not.*";
P_HTM[2294]="*yaṃ icchiṃsu, taṃ akaṃsu, yaṃ na icchiṃsu na taṃ akaṃsu.**They did the work they wanted to, and did not do what they didn’t want to.*";
P_HTM[2295]="*Sappitelanavanītadadhimadhuphāṇitena ceva te yaññā niṭṭhānamagamaṃsu.**The sacrifice was completed with just ghee, oil, butter, curds, honey, and molasses.*";
P_HTM[2296]="*Iti cattāro ca anumatipakkhā, rājā mahāvijito aṭṭhahaṅgehi samannāgato, purohito brāhmaṇo catūhaṅgehi samannāgato;**And so there were four consenting factions, eight factors possessed by King Mahāvijita, four factors possessed by the high priest,*";
P_HTM[2297]="*tisso ca vidhā.**and three modes.*";
P_HTM[2298]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, brāhmaṇa, tividhā yaññasampadā soḷasaparikkhārā”ti.**Brahmin, this is called the sacrifice accomplished with three modes and sixteen accessories.”*";
P_HTM[2299]="*Evaṃ vutte, te brāhmaṇā unnādino uccāsaddamahāsaddā ahesuṃ:**When he said this, those brahmins made an uproar,*";
P_HTM[2300]="*“aho yañño, aho yaññasampadā”ti.**“Hooray for such sacrifice! Hooray for the accomplishment of such sacrifice!”*";
P_HTM[2301]="*Kūṭadanto pana brāhmaṇo tūṇhībhūtova nisinno hoti.**But the brahmin Kūṭadanta sat in silence.*";
P_HTM[2302]="*Atha kho te brāhmaṇā kūṭadantaṃ brāhmaṇaṃ etadavocuṃ:**So those brahmins said to him,*";
P_HTM[2303]="*“kasmā pana bhavaṃ kūṭadanto samaṇassa gotamassa subhāsitaṃ subhāsitato nābbhanumodatī”ti?**“How can you not applaud the ascetic Gotama’s fine words?”*";
P_HTM[2304]="*“Nāhaṃ, bho, samaṇassa gotamassa subhāsitaṃ subhāsitato nābbhanumodāmi.**“It’s not that I don’t applaud what he said.*";
P_HTM[2305]="*Muddhāpi tassa vipateyya, yo samaṇassa gotamassa subhāsitaṃ subhāsitato nābbhanumodeyya.**If anyone didn’t applaud such fine words, their head would explode!*";
P_HTM[2306]="*Api ca me, bho, evaṃ hoti—**But, gentlemen, it occurs to me that*";
P_HTM[2307]="*samaṇo gotamo na evamāha:**the ascetic Gotama does not say:*";
P_HTM[2308]="*‘evaṃ me sutan’ti vā ‘evaṃ arahati bhavitun’ti vā;**‘So I have heard’ or ‘It ought to be like this.’*";
P_HTM[2309]="*api ca samaṇo gotamo:**Rather, he just says:*";
P_HTM[2310]="*‘evaṃ tadā āsi, itthaṃ tadā āsi’ tveva bhāsati.**‘So it was then, this is how it was then.’*";
P_HTM[2311]="*Tassa mayhaṃ bho evaṃ hoti:**It occurs to me that*";
P_HTM[2312]="*‘addhā samaṇo gotamo tena samayena rājā vā ahosi mahāvijito yaññassāmi purohito vā brāhmaṇo tassa yaññassa yājetā’ti.**the ascetic Gotama at that time must have been King Mahāvijita, the owner of the sacrifice, or else the brahmin high priest who facilitated the sacrifice for him.*";
P_HTM[2313]="*Abhijānāti pana bhavaṃ gotamo evarūpaṃ yaññaṃ yajitvā vā yājetvā vā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjitā”ti?**Does Master Gotama recall having performed such a sacrifice, or having facilitated it, and then, when his body broke up, after death, being reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm?”*";
P_HTM[2314]="*“Abhijānāmahaṃ, brāhmaṇa, evarūpaṃ yaññaṃ yajitvā vā yājetvā vā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapajjitā, ahaṃ tena samayena purohito brāhmaṇo ahosiṃ tassa yaññassa yājetā”ti.**“I do recall that, brahmin. For at that time I was the brahmin high priest who facilitated the sacrifice.”*";
P_HTM[2315]="*5. Niccadānaanukulayañña**5. A Regular Gift as an Ongoing Family Sacrifice.*";
P_HTM[2316]="*“Atthi pana, bho gotama, añño yañño imāya tividhāya yaññasampadāya soḷasaparikkhārāya appaṭṭhataro ca appasamārambhataro ca mahapphalataro ca mahānisaṃsataro cā”ti?**“But Master Gotama, apart from that sacrifice accomplished with three modes and sixteen accessories, is there any other sacrifice that has fewer requirements and undertakings, yet is more fruitful and beneficial?”*";
P_HTM[2317]="*“Atthi kho, brāhmaṇa, añño yañño imāya tividhāya yaññasampadāya soḷasaparikkhārāya appaṭṭhataro ca appasamārambhataro ca mahapphalataro ca mahānisaṃsataro cā”ti.**“There is, brahmin.”*";
P_HTM[2318]="*“Katamo pana so, bho gotama, yañño imāya tividhāya yaññasampadāya soḷasaparikkhārāya appaṭṭhataro ca appasamārambhataro ca mahapphalataro ca mahānisaṃsataro cā”ti?**“But what is it?”*";
P_HTM[2319]="*“Yāni kho pana tāni, brāhmaṇa, niccadānāni anukulayaññāni sīlavante pabbajite uddissa diyyanti;**“The regular gifts as ongoing family sacrifice given specially to ethical renunciates;*";
P_HTM[2320]="*ayaṃ kho, brāhmaṇa, yañño imāya tividhāya yaññasampadāya soḷasaparikkhārāya appaṭṭhataro ca appasamārambhataro ca mahapphalataro ca mahānisaṃsataro cā”ti.**this sacrifice, brahmin, has fewer requirements and undertakings, yet is more fruitful and beneficial.”*";
P_HTM[2321]="*“Ko nu kho, bho gotama, hetu ko paccayo, yena taṃ niccadānaṃ anukulayaññaṃ imāya tividhāya yaññasampadāya soḷasaparikkhārāya appaṭṭhatarañca appasamārambhatarañca mahapphalatarañca mahānisaṃsatarañcā”ti?**“What is the cause, Master Gotama, what is the reason why those regular gifts as ongoing family sacrifice have fewer requirements and undertakings, yet are more fruitful and beneficial, compared with the sacrifice accomplished with three modes and sixteen accessories?”*";
P_HTM[2322]="*“Na kho, brāhmaṇa, evarūpaṃ yaññaṃ upasaṅkamanti arahanto vā arahattamaggaṃ vā samāpannā.**“Because neither perfected ones nor those who have entered the path to perfection will attend such a sacrifice.*";
P_HTM[2323]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[2324]="*Dissanti hettha, brāhmaṇa, daṇḍappahārāpi galaggahāpi, tasmā evarūpaṃ yaññaṃ na upasaṅkamanti arahanto vā arahattamaggaṃ vā samāpannā.**Because beatings and throttlings are seen there.*";
P_HTM[2325]="*Yāni kho pana tāni, brāhmaṇa, niccadānāni anukulayaññāni sīlavante pabbajite uddissa diyyanti;**But the regular gifts as ongoing family sacrifice given specially to ethical renunciates;*";
P_HTM[2326]="*evarūpaṃ kho, brāhmaṇa, yaññaṃ upasaṅkamanti arahanto vā arahattamaggaṃ vā samāpannā.**perfected ones and those who have entered the path to perfection will attend such a sacrifice.*";
P_HTM[2327]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[2328]="*Na hettha, brāhmaṇa, dissanti daṇḍappahārāpi galaggahāpi, tasmā evarūpaṃ yaññaṃ upasaṅkamanti arahanto vā arahattamaggaṃ vā samāpannā.**Because no beatings and throttlings are seen there.*";
P_HTM[2329]="*Ayaṃ kho, brāhmaṇa, hetu ayaṃ paccayo, yena taṃ niccadānaṃ anukulayaññaṃ imāya tividhāya yaññasampadāya soḷasaparikkhārāya appaṭṭhatarañca appasamārambhatarañca mahapphalatarañca mahānisaṃsatarañcā”ti.**This is the cause, brahmin, this is the reason why those regular gifts as ongoing family sacrifice have fewer requirements and undertakings, yet are more fruitful and beneficial, compared with the sacrifice accomplished with three modes and sixteen accessories.”*";
P_HTM[2330]="*“Atthi pana, bho gotama, añño yañño imāya ca tividhāya yaññasampadāya soḷasaparikkhārāya iminā ca niccadānena anukulayaññena appaṭṭhataro ca appasamārambhataro ca mahapphalataro ca mahānisaṃsataro cā”ti?**“But Master Gotama, apart from that sacrifice accomplished with three modes and sixteen accessories and those regular gifts as ongoing family sacrifice, is there any other sacrifice that has fewer requirements and undertakings, yet is more fruitful and beneficial?”*";
P_HTM[2331]="*“Atthi kho, brāhmaṇa, añño yañño imāya ca tividhāya yaññasampadāya soḷasaparikkhārāya iminā ca niccadānena anukulayaññena appaṭṭhataro ca appasamārambhataro ca mahapphalataro ca mahānisaṃsataro cā”ti.**“There is, brahmin.”*";
P_HTM[2332]="*“Katamo pana so, bho gotama, yañño imāya ca tividhāya yaññasampadāya soḷasaparikkhārāya iminā ca niccadānena anukulayaññena appaṭṭhataro ca appasamārambhataro ca mahapphalataro ca mahānisaṃsataro cā”ti?**“But what is it?”*";
P_HTM[2333]="*“Yo kho, brāhmaṇa, cātuddisaṃ saṅghaṃ uddissa vihāraṃ karoti, ayaṃ kho, brāhmaṇa, yañño imāya ca tividhāya yaññasampadāya soḷasaparikkhārāya iminā ca niccadānena anukulayaññena appaṭṭhataro ca appasamārambhataro ca mahapphalataro ca mahānisaṃsataro cā”ti.**“When someone gives a dwelling specially for the Saṅgha of the four quarters.”*";
P_HTM[2334]="*“Atthi pana, bho gotama, añño yañño imāya ca tividhāya yaññasampadāya soḷasaparikkhārāya iminā ca niccadānena anukulayaññena iminā ca vihāradānena appaṭṭhataro ca appasamārambhataro ca mahapphalataro ca mahānisaṃsataro cā”ti?**“But is there any other sacrifice that has fewer requirements and undertakings, yet is more fruitful and beneficial?”*";
P_HTM[2335]="*“Atthi kho, brāhmaṇa, añño yañño imāya ca tividhāya yaññasampadāya soḷasaparikkhārāya iminā ca niccadānena anukulayaññena iminā ca vihāradānena appaṭṭhataro ca appasamārambhataro ca mahapphalataro ca mahānisaṃsataro cā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[2336]="*“Katamo pana so, bho gotama, yañño imāya ca tividhāya yaññasampadāya soḷasaparikkhārāya iminā ca niccadānena anukulayaññena iminā ca vihāradānena appaṭṭhataro ca appasamārambhataro ca mahapphalataro ca mahānisaṃsataro cā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[2337]="*“Yo kho, brāhmaṇa, pasannacitto buddhaṃ saraṇaṃ gacchati, dhammaṃ saraṇaṃ gacchati, saṅghaṃ saraṇaṃ gacchati;**“When someone with confident heart goes for refuge to the Buddha, the teaching, and the Saṅgha.”*";
P_HTM[2338]="*ayaṃ kho, brāhmaṇa, yañño imāya ca tividhāya yaññasampadāya soḷasaparikkhārāya iminā ca niccadānena anukulayaññena iminā ca vihāradānena appaṭṭhataro ca appasamārambhataro ca mahapphalataro ca mahānisaṃsataro cā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[2339]="*“Atthi pana, bho gotama, añño yañño imāya ca tividhāya yaññasampadāya soḷasaparikkhārāya iminā ca niccadānena anukulayaññena iminā ca vihāradānena imehi ca saraṇagamanehi appaṭṭhataro ca appasamārambhataro ca mahapphalataro ca mahānisaṃsataro cā”ti?**“But is there any other sacrifice that has fewer requirements and undertakings, yet is more fruitful and beneficial?”*";
P_HTM[2340]="*“Atthi kho, brāhmaṇa, añño yañño imāya ca tividhāya yaññasampadāya soḷasaparikkhārāya iminā ca niccadānena anukulayaññena iminā ca vihāradānena imehi ca saraṇagamanehi appaṭṭhataro ca appasamārambhataro ca mahapphalataro ca mahānisaṃsataro cā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[2341]="*“Katamo pana so, bho gotama, yañño imāya ca tividhāya yaññasampadāya soḷasaparikkhārāya iminā ca niccadānena anukulayaññena iminā ca vihāradānena imehi ca saraṇagamanehi appaṭṭhataro ca appasamārambhataro ca mahapphalataro ca mahānisaṃsataro cā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[2342]="*“Yo kho, brāhmaṇa, pasannacitto sikkhāpadāni samādiyati—**“When someone with a confident heart undertakes the training rules*";
P_HTM[2343]="*pāṇātipātā veramaṇiṃ, adinnādānā veramaṇiṃ, kāmesumicchācārā veramaṇiṃ, musāvādā veramaṇiṃ, surāmerayamajjapamādaṭṭhānā veramaṇiṃ.**to refrain from killing living creatures, stealing, sexual misconduct, lying, and alcoholic drinks that cause negligence.”*";
P_HTM[2344]="*Ayaṃ kho, brāhmaṇa, yañño imāya ca tividhāya yaññasampadāya soḷasaparikkhārāya iminā ca niccadānena anukulayaññena iminā ca vihāradānena imehi ca saraṇagamanehi appaṭṭhataro ca appasamārambhataro ca mahapphalataro ca mahānisaṃsataro cā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[2345]="*“Atthi pana, bho gotama, añño yañño imāya ca tividhāya yaññasampadāya soḷasaparikkhārāya iminā ca niccadānena anukulayaññena iminā ca vihāradānena imehi ca saraṇagamanehi imehi ca sikkhāpadehi appaṭṭhataro ca appasamārambhataro ca mahapphalataro ca mahānisaṃsataro cā”ti?**“But is there any other sacrifice that has fewer requirements and undertakings, yet is more fruitful and beneficial?”*";
P_HTM[2346]="*“Atthi kho, brāhmaṇa, añño yañño imāya ca tividhāya yaññasampadāya soḷasaparikkhārāya iminā ca niccadānena anukulayaññena iminā ca vihāradānena imehi ca saraṇagamanehi imehi ca sikkhāpadehi appaṭṭhataro ca appasamārambhataro ca mahapphalataro ca mahānisaṃsataro cā”ti.**“There is, brahmin.*";
P_HTM[2347]="*“Katamo pana so, bho gotama, yañño imāya ca tividhāya yaññasampadāya soḷasaparikkhārāya iminā ca niccadānena anukulayaññena iminā ca vihāradānena imehi ca saraṇagamanehi imehi ca sikkhāpadehi appaṭṭhataro ca appasamārambhataro ca mahapphalataro ca mahānisaṃsataro cā”ti?* **";
P_HTM[2348]="*“Idha, brāhmaṇa, tathāgato loke uppajjati arahaṃ sammāsambuddho … pe …**It’s when a Realized One arises in the world, perfected, a fully awakened Buddha …*";
P_HTM[2349]="*Evaṃ kho, brāhmaṇa, bhikkhu sīlasampanno hoti … pe …**That’s how a mendicant is accomplished in ethics. …*";
P_HTM[2350]="*paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**They enter and remain in the first absorption …*";
P_HTM[2351]="*Ayaṃ kho, brāhmaṇa, yañño purimehi yaññehi appaṭṭhataro ca appasamārambhataro ca mahapphalataro ca mahānisaṃsataro ca … pe …**This sacrifice has fewer requirements and undertakings than the former, yet is more fruitful and beneficial. …*";
P_HTM[2352]="*Dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ …**They enter and remain in the second absorption …*";
P_HTM[2353]="*tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ …**third absorption …*";
P_HTM[2354]="*catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**fourth absorption.*";
P_HTM[2355]="*Ayampi kho, brāhmaṇa, yañño purimehi yaññehi appaṭṭhataro ca appasamārambhataro ca mahapphalataro ca mahānisaṃsataro cāti. … pe …**This sacrifice has fewer requirements and undertakings than the former, yet is more fruitful and beneficial. …*";
P_HTM[2356]="*Ñāṇadassanāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti …**They extend and project the mind toward knowledge and vision …*";
P_HTM[2357]="*ayampi kho, brāhmaṇa, yañño purimehi yaññehi appaṭṭhataro ca appasamārambhataro ca mahapphalataro ca mahānisaṃsataro ca … pe …**This sacrifice has fewer requirements and undertakings than the former, yet is more fruitful and beneficial.*";
P_HTM[2358]="*nāparaṃ itthattāyāti pajānāti.**They understand: ‘… there is no return to any state of existence.’*";
P_HTM[2359]="*Ayampi kho, brāhmaṇa, yañño purimehi yaññehi appaṭṭhataro ca appasamārambhataro ca mahapphalataro ca mahānisaṃsataro ca.**This sacrifice has fewer requirements and undertakings than the former, yet is more fruitful and beneficial.*";
P_HTM[2360]="*Imāya ca, brāhmaṇa, yaññasampadāya aññā yaññasampadā uttaritarā vā paṇītatarā vā natthī”ti.**And, brahmin, there is no other accomplishment of sacrifice which is better and finer than this.”*";
P_HTM[2361]="*6. Kūṭadantaupāsakattapaṭivedanā**6. Kūṭadanta Declares Himself a Lay Follower*";
P_HTM[2362]="*Evaṃ vutte, kūṭadanto brāhmaṇo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he had spoken, Kūṭadanta said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[2363]="*“abhikkantaṃ, bho gotama, abhikkantaṃ, bho gotama.**“Excellent, Master Gotama! Excellent!*";
P_HTM[2364]="*Seyyathāpi, bho gotama, nikkujjitaṃ vā ukkujjeyya, paṭicchannaṃ vā vivareyya, mūḷhassa vā maggaṃ ācikkheyya, andhakāre vā telapajjotaṃ dhāreyya: ‘cakkhumanto rūpāni dakkhantī’ti; evamevaṃ bhotā gotamena anekapariyāyena dhammo pakāsito.**As if he were righting the overturned, or revealing the hidden, or pointing out the path to the lost, or lighting a lamp in the dark so people with good eyes can see what’s there, Master Gotama has made the Teaching clear in many ways.*";
P_HTM[2365]="*Esāhaṃ bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ saraṇaṃ gacchāmi dhammañca bhikkhusaṅghañca.**I go for refuge to Master Gotama, to the teaching, and to the mendicant Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[2366]="*Upāsakaṃ maṃ bhavaṃ gotamo dhāretu ajjatagge pāṇupetaṃ saraṇaṃ gataṃ.**From this day forth, may Master Gotama remember me as a lay follower who has gone for refuge for life.*";
P_HTM[2367]="*Esāhaṃ, bho gotama, satta ca usabhasatāni satta ca vacchatarasatāni satta ca vacchatarīsatāni satta ca ajasatāni satta ca urabbhasatāni muñcāmi, jīvitaṃ demi, haritāni ceva tiṇāni khādantu, sītāni ca pānīyāni pivantu, sīto ca nesaṃ vāto upavāyatū”ti.**And these bulls, bullocks, heifers, goats, and rams—seven hundred of each—I release them, I grant them life! Let them eat green grass and drink cool water, and may a cool breeze blow upon them!”*";
P_HTM[2368]="*7. Sotāpattiphalasacchikiriyā**7. The Realization of the Fruit of Stream-Entry*";
P_HTM[2369]="*Atha kho bhagavā kūṭadantassa brāhmaṇassa anupubbiṃ kathaṃ kathesi,**Then the Buddha taught Kūṭadanta step by step, with*";
P_HTM[2370]="*seyyathidaṃ—dānakathaṃ sīlakathaṃ saggakathaṃ;**a talk on giving, ethical conduct, and heaven.*";
P_HTM[2371]="*kāmānaṃ ādīnavaṃ okāraṃ saṅkilesaṃ nekkhamme ānisaṃsaṃ pakāsesi.**He explained the drawbacks of sensual pleasures, so sordid and corrupt, and the benefit of renunciation.*";
P_HTM[2372]="*Yadā bhagavā aññāsi kūṭadantaṃ brāhmaṇaṃ kallacittaṃ muducittaṃ vinīvaraṇacittaṃ udaggacittaṃ pasannacittaṃ, atha yā buddhānaṃ sāmukkaṃsikā dhammadesanā, taṃ pakāsesi—**And when he knew that Kūṭadanta’s mind was ready, pliable, rid of hindrances, joyful, and confident he explained the special teaching of the Buddhas:*";
P_HTM[2373]="*dukkhaṃ samudayaṃ nirodhaṃ maggaṃ.**suffering, its origin, its cessation, and the path.*";
P_HTM[2374]="*Seyyathāpi nāma suddhaṃ vatthaṃ apagatakāḷakaṃ sammadeva rajanaṃ paṭiggaṇheyya;**Just as a clean cloth rid of stains would properly absorb dye,*";
P_HTM[2375]="*evameva kūṭadantassa brāhmaṇassa tasmiññeva āsane virajaṃ vītamalaṃ dhammacakkhuṃ udapādi:**in that very seat the stainless, immaculate vision of the Dhamma arose in the brahmin Kūṭadanta:*";
P_HTM[2376]="*“yaṃ kiñci samudayadhammaṃ sabbaṃ taṃ nirodhadhamman”ti.**“Everything that has a beginning has an end.”*";
P_HTM[2377]="*Atha kho kūṭadanto brāhmaṇo diṭṭhadhammo pattadhammo viditadhammo pariyogāḷhadhammo tiṇṇavicikiccho vigatakathaṅkatho vesārajjappatto aparappaccayo satthusāsane bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then Kūṭadanta saw, attained, understood, and fathomed the Dhamma. He went beyond doubt, got rid of indecision, and became self-assured and independent of others regarding the Teacher’s instructions. He said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[2378]="*“adhivāsetu me bhavaṃ gotamo svātanāya bhattaṃ saddhiṃ bhikkhusaṅghenā”ti.**“Would Master Gotama together with the mendicant Saṅgha please accept tomorrow’s meal from me?”*";
P_HTM[2379]="*Adhivāsesi bhagavā tuṇhībhāvena.**The Buddha consented in silence.*";
P_HTM[2380]="*Atha kho kūṭadanto brāhmaṇo bhagavato adhivāsanaṃ viditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā pakkāmi.**Then, knowing that the Buddha had consented, Kūṭadanta got up from his seat, bowed, and respectfully circled the Buddha, keeping him on his right, before leaving.*";
P_HTM[2381]="*Atha kho kūṭadanto brāhmaṇo tassā rattiyā accayena sake yaññavāṭe paṇītaṃ khādanīyaṃ bhojanīyaṃ paṭiyādāpetvā bhagavato kālaṃ ārocāpesi:**And when the night had passed Kūṭadanta had a variety of delicious foods prepared in his own home. Then he had the Buddha informed of the time, saying,*";
P_HTM[2382]="*“kālo, bho gotama; niṭṭhitaṃ bhattan”ti.**“It’s time, Master Gotama, the meal is ready.”*";
P_HTM[2383]="*Atha kho bhagavā pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya saddhiṃ bhikkhusaṅghena yena kūṭadantassa brāhmaṇassa yaññavāṭo tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdi.**Then the Buddha robed up in the morning and, taking his bowl and robe, went to the home of Kūṭadanta together with the mendicant Saṅgha, where he sat on the seat spread out.*";
P_HTM[2384]="*Atha kho kūṭadanto brāhmaṇo buddhappamukhaṃ bhikkhusaṅghaṃ paṇītena khādanīyena bhojanīyena sahatthā santappesi sampavāresi.**Then Kūṭadanta served and satisfied the mendicant Saṅgha headed by the Buddha with his own hands with a variety of delicious foods.*";
P_HTM[2385]="*Atha kho kūṭadanto brāhmaṇo bhagavantaṃ bhuttāviṃ onītapattapāṇiṃ aññataraṃ nīcaṃ āsanaṃ gahetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi.**When the Buddha had eaten and washed his hand and bowl, Kūṭadanta took a low seat and sat to one side.*";
P_HTM[2386]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho kūṭadantaṃ brāhmaṇaṃ bhagavā dhammiyā kathāya sandassetvā samādapetvā samuttejetvā sampahaṃsetvā uṭṭhāyāsanā pakkāmīti.**Then the Buddha educated, encouraged, fired up, and inspired him with a Dhamma talk, after which he got up from his seat and left.*";
P_HTM[2387]="*Kūṭadantasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ pañcamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2388]="*06. Mahālisutta  - With Mahāli * **";
P_HTM[2389]="*1. Brāhmaṇadūtavatthu**1. On the Brahmin Emissaries*";
P_HTM[2390]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[2391]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā vesāliyaṃ viharati mahāvane kūṭāgārasālāyaṃ.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Vesālī, at the Great Wood, in the hall with the peaked roof.*";
P_HTM[2392]="*Tena kho pana samayena sambahulā kosalakā ca brāhmaṇadūtā māgadhakā ca brāhmaṇadūtā vesāliyaṃ paṭivasanti kenacideva karaṇīyena.**Now at that time several brahmin emissaries from Kosala and Magadha were residing in Vesālī on some business.*";
P_HTM[2393]="*Assosuṃ kho te kosalakā ca brāhmaṇadūtā māgadhakā ca brāhmaṇadūtā:**They heard:*";
P_HTM[2394]="*“samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo sakyaputto sakyakulā pabbajito vesāliyaṃ viharati mahāvane kūṭāgārasālāyaṃ.**“It seems the ascetic Gotama—a Sakyan, gone forth from a Sakyan family—is staying near Vesālī, at the Great Wood, in the hall with the peaked roof.*";
P_HTM[2395]="*Taṃ kho pana bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ evaṃ kalyāṇo kittisaddo abbhuggato:**He has this good reputation:*";
P_HTM[2396]="*‘itipi so bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā’.**‘That Blessed One is perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.’*";
P_HTM[2397]="*So imaṃ lokaṃ sadevakaṃ samārakaṃ sabrahmakaṃ sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiṃ pajaṃ sadevamanussaṃ sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedeti.**He has realized with his own insight this world—with its gods, Māras and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, gods and humans—and he makes it known to others.*";
P_HTM[2398]="*So dhammaṃ deseti ādikalyāṇaṃ majjhekalyāṇaṃ pariyosānakalyāṇaṃ sātthaṃ sabyañjanaṃ kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ pakāseti.**He teaches Dhamma that’s good in the beginning, good in the middle, and good in the end, meaningful and well-phrased. And he reveals a spiritual practice that’s entirely full and pure.*";
P_HTM[2399]="*Sādhu kho pana tathārūpānaṃ arahataṃ dassanaṃ hotī”ti.**It’s good to see such perfected ones.”*";
P_HTM[2400]="*Atha kho te kosalakā ca brāhmaṇadūtā māgadhakā ca brāhmaṇadūtā yena mahāvanaṃ kūṭāgārasālā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu.**Then they went to the hall with the peaked roof in the Great Wood to see the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[2401]="*Tena kho pana samayena āyasmā nāgito bhagavato upaṭṭhāko hoti.**Now, at that time Venerable Nāgita was the Buddha’s attendant.*";
P_HTM[2402]="*Atha kho te kosalakā ca brāhmaṇadūtā māgadhakā ca brāhmaṇadūtā yenāyasmā nāgito tenupasaṅkamiṃsu. upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ nāgitaṃ etadavocuṃ:**The brahmin emissaries went up to him and said,*";
P_HTM[2403]="*“kahaṃ nu kho, bho nāgita, etarahi so bhavaṃ gotamo viharati?**“Master Nāgita, where is Master Gotama at present?*";
P_HTM[2404]="*Dassanakāmā hi mayaṃ taṃ bhavantaṃ gotaman”ti.**For we want to see him.”*";
P_HTM[2405]="*“Akālo kho, āvuso, bhagavantaṃ dassanāya, paṭisallīno bhagavā”ti.**“It’s the wrong time to see the Buddha; he is on retreat.”*";
P_HTM[2406]="*Atha kho te kosalakā ca brāhmaṇadūtā māgadhakā ca brāhmaṇadūtā tattheva ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu:**So the brahmin emissaries sat down to one side, thinking,*";
P_HTM[2407]="*“disvāva mayaṃ taṃ bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ gamissāmā”ti.**“We’ll go only after we’ve seen Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[2408]="*2. Oṭṭhaddhalicchavīvatthu**2. On Oṭṭhaddha the Licchavi*";
P_HTM[2409]="*Oṭṭhaddhopi licchavī mahatiyā licchavīparisāya saddhiṃ yena mahāvanaṃ kūṭāgārasālā yenāyasmā nāgito tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ nāgitaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhāsi. Ekamantaṃ ṭhito kho oṭṭhaddhopi licchavī āyasmantaṃ nāgitaṃ etadavoca:**Oṭṭhaddha the Licchavi together with a large assembly of Licchavis also approached Nāgita at the hall with the peaked roof. He bowed, stood to one side, and said to Nāgita,*";
P_HTM[2410]="*“kahaṃ nu kho, bhante nāgita, etarahi so bhagavā viharati arahaṃ sammāsambuddho,**“Master Nāgita, where is the Blessed One at present, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha?*";
P_HTM[2411]="*dassanakāmā hi mayaṃ taṃ bhagavantaṃ arahantaṃ sammāsambuddhan”ti.**For we want to see him.”*";
P_HTM[2412]="*“Akālo kho, mahāli, bhagavantaṃ dassanāya, paṭisallīno bhagavā”ti.**“It’s the wrong time to see the Buddha; he is on retreat.”*";
P_HTM[2413]="*Oṭṭhaddhopi licchavī tattheva ekamantaṃ nisīdi:**So Oṭṭhaddha also sat down to one side, thinking,*";
P_HTM[2414]="*“disvāva ahaṃ taṃ bhagavantaṃ gamissāmi arahantaṃ sammāsambuddhan”ti.**“I’ll go only after I’ve seen the Blessed One, the perfected one, the fully awakened Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[2415]="*Atha kho sīho samaṇuddeso yenāyasmā nāgito tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmantaṃ nāgitaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhāsi. Ekamantaṃ ṭhito kho sīho samaṇuddeso āyasmantaṃ nāgitaṃ etadavoca:**Then the novice Sīha approached Nāgita. He bowed, stood to one side, and said to Nāgita,*";
P_HTM[2416]="*“ete, bhante kassapa, sambahulā kosalakā ca brāhmaṇadūtā māgadhakā ca brāhmaṇadūtā idhūpasaṅkantā bhagavantaṃ dassanāya; oṭṭhaddhopi licchavī mahatiyā licchavīparisāya saddhiṃ idhūpasaṅkanto bhagavantaṃ dassanāya, sādhu, bhante kassapa, labhataṃ esā janatā bhagavantaṃ dassanāyā”ti.**“Sir, Kassapa, these several brahmin emissaries from Kosala and Magadha, and also Oṭṭhaddha the Licchavi together with a large assembly of Licchavis, have come here to see the Buddha. It’d be good if these people got to see the Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[2417]="*“Tena hi, sīha, tvaññeva bhagavato ārocehī”ti.**“Well then, Sīha, tell the Buddha yourself.”*";
P_HTM[2418]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho sīho samaṇuddeso āyasmato nāgitassa paṭissutvā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhāsi. Ekamantaṃ ṭhito kho sīho samaṇuddeso bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**“Yes, sir,” replied Sīha. He went to the Buddha, bowed, stood to one side, and told him of the people waiting to see him, adding:*";
P_HTM[2419]="*“ete, bhante, sambahulā kosalakā ca brāhmaṇadūtā māgadhakā ca brāhmaṇadūtā idhūpasaṅkantā bhagavantaṃ dassanāya, oṭṭhaddhopi licchavī mahatiyā licchavīparisāya saddhiṃ idhūpasaṅkanto bhagavantaṃ dassanāya.* **";
P_HTM[2420]="*Sādhu, bhante, labhataṃ esā janatā bhagavantaṃ dassanāyā”ti.**“Sir, it’d be good if these people got to see the Buddha.”*";
P_HTM[2421]="*“Tena hi, sīha, vihārapacchāyāyaṃ āsanaṃ paññapehī”ti.**“Well then, Sīha, spread out a seat in the shade of the dwelling.”*";
P_HTM[2422]="*“Evaṃ, bhante”ti kho sīho samaṇuddeso bhagavato paṭissutvā vihārapacchāyāyaṃ āsanaṃ paññapesi.**“Yes, sir,” replied Sīha, and he did so.*";
P_HTM[2423]="*Atha kho bhagavā vihārā nikkhamma vihārapacchāyāyaṃ paññatte āsane nisīdi.**Then the Buddha came out of his dwelling and sat in the shade of the dwelling on the seat spread out.*";
P_HTM[2424]="*Atha kho te kosalakā ca brāhmaṇadūtā māgadhakā ca brāhmaṇadūtā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavatā saddhiṃ sammodiṃsu.**Then the brahmin emissaries went up to the Buddha, and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[2425]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu.**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, they sat down to one side.*";
P_HTM[2426]="*Oṭṭhaddhopi licchavī mahatiyā licchavīparisāya saddhiṃ yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho oṭṭhaddho licchavī bhagavantaṃ etadavoca: “purimāni, bhante, divasāni purimatarāni sunakkhatto licchaviputto yenāhaṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā maṃ etadavoca:**Oṭṭhaddha the Licchavi together with a large assembly of Licchavis also went up to the Buddha, bowed, and sat down to one side. Oṭṭhaddha said to the Buddha, “Sir, a few days ago Sunakkhatta the Licchavi came to me and said:*";
P_HTM[2427]="*‘yadagge ahaṃ, mahāli, bhagavantaṃ upanissāya viharāmi, na ciraṃ tīṇi vassāni, dibbāni hi kho rūpāni passāmi piyarūpāni kāmūpasaṃhitāni rajanīyāni, no ca kho dibbāni saddāni suṇāmi piyarūpāni kāmūpasaṃhitāni rajanīyānī’ti.**‘Mahāli, soon I will have been living in dependence on the Buddha for three years. I see heavenly sights that are pleasant, sensual, and arousing, but I don’t hear heavenly sounds that are pleasant, sensual, and arousing.’*";
P_HTM[2428]="*Santāneva nu kho, bhante, sunakkhatto licchaviputto dibbāni saddāni nāssosi piyarūpāni kāmūpasaṃhitāni rajanīyāni, udāhu asantānī”ti?**The heavenly sounds that Sunakkhatta cannot hear: do such sounds really exist or not?”*";
P_HTM[2429]="*2.1. Ekaṃsabhāvitasamādhi**2.1. One-Sided Immersion*";
P_HTM[2430]="*“Santāneva kho, mahāli, sunakkhatto licchaviputto dibbāni saddāni nāssosi piyarūpāni kāmūpasaṃhitāni rajanīyāni, no asantānī”ti.**“Such sounds really do exist, but Sunakkhatta cannot hear them.”*";
P_HTM[2431]="*“Ko nu kho, bhante, hetu, ko paccayo, yena santāneva sunakkhatto licchaviputto dibbāni saddāni nāssosi piyarūpāni kāmūpasaṃhitāni rajanīyāni, no asantānī”ti?**“What is the cause, sir, what is the reason why Sunakkhatta cannot hear them, even though they really do exist?”*";
P_HTM[2432]="*“Idha, mahāli, bhikkhuno puratthimāya disāya ekaṃsabhāvito samādhi hoti dibbānaṃ rūpānaṃ dassanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ, no ca kho dibbānaṃ saddānaṃ savanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ.**“Mahāli, take a mendicant who has developed one-sided immersion to the eastern quarter so as to see heavenly sights but not to hear heavenly sounds.*";
P_HTM[2433]="*So puratthimāya disāya ekaṃsabhāvite samādhimhi dibbānaṃ rūpānaṃ dassanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ, no ca kho dibbānaṃ saddānaṃ savanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ.**When they have developed immersion for that purpose,*";
P_HTM[2434]="*Puratthimāya disāya dibbāni rūpāni passati piyarūpāni kāmūpasaṃhitāni rajanīyāni, no ca kho dibbāni saddāni suṇāti piyarūpāni kāmūpasaṃhitāni rajanīyāni.**they see heavenly sights but don’t hear heavenly sounds.*";
P_HTM[2435]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[2436]="*Evañhetaṃ, mahāli, hoti bhikkhuno puratthimāya disāya ekaṃsabhāvite samādhimhi dibbānaṃ rūpānaṃ dassanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ, no ca kho dibbānaṃ saddānaṃ savanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ.**Because that is how it is for a mendicant who develops immersion in that way.*";
P_HTM[2437]="*Puna caparaṃ, mahāli, bhikkhuno dakkhiṇāya disāya … pe …**Furthermore, take a mendicant who has developed one-sided immersion to the southern quarter …*";
P_HTM[2438]="*pacchimāya disāya …**western quarter …*";
P_HTM[2439]="*uttarāya disāya …**northern quarter …*";
P_HTM[2440]="*uddhamadho tiriyaṃ ekaṃsabhāvito samādhi hoti dibbānaṃ rūpānaṃ dassanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ, no ca kho dibbānaṃ saddānaṃ savanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ.**above, below, across …*";
P_HTM[2441]="*So uddhamadho tiriyaṃ ekaṃsabhāvite samādhimhi dibbānaṃ rūpānaṃ dassanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ, no ca kho dibbānaṃ saddānaṃ savanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2442]="*Uddhamadho tiriyaṃ dibbāni rūpāni passati piyarūpāni kāmūpasaṃhitāni rajanīyāni, no ca kho dibbāni saddāni suṇāti piyarūpāni kāmūpasaṃhitāni rajanīyāni.* **";
P_HTM[2443]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?* **";
P_HTM[2444]="*Evañhetaṃ, mahāli, hoti bhikkhuno uddhamadho tiriyaṃ ekaṃsabhāvite samādhimhi dibbānaṃ rūpānaṃ dassanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ, no ca kho dibbānaṃ saddānaṃ savanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ.**That is how it is for a mendicant who develops immersion in that way.*";
P_HTM[2445]="*Idha, mahāli, bhikkhuno puratthimāya disāya ekaṃsabhāvito samādhi hoti dibbānaṃ saddānaṃ savanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ, no ca kho dibbānaṃ rūpānaṃ dassanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ.**Take a mendicant who has developed one-sided immersion to the eastern quarter so as to hear heavenly sounds but not to see heavenly sights.*";
P_HTM[2446]="*So puratthimāya disāya ekaṃsabhāvite samādhimhi dibbānaṃ saddānaṃ savanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ, no ca kho dibbānaṃ rūpānaṃ dassanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ.**When they have developed immersion for that purpose,*";
P_HTM[2447]="*Puratthimāya disāya dibbāni saddāni suṇāti piyarūpāni kāmūpasaṃhitāni rajanīyāni, no ca kho dibbāni rūpāni passati piyarūpāni kāmūpasaṃhitāni rajanīyāni.**they hear heavenly sounds but don’t see heavenly sights.*";
P_HTM[2448]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[2449]="*Evañhetaṃ, mahāli, hoti bhikkhuno puratthimāya disāya ekaṃsabhāvite samādhimhi dibbānaṃ saddānaṃ savanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ, no ca kho dibbānaṃ rūpānaṃ dassanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ.**Because that is how it is for a mendicant who develops immersion in that way.*";
P_HTM[2450]="*Puna caparaṃ, mahāli, bhikkhuno dakkhiṇāya disāya … pe …**Furthermore, take a mendicant who has developed one-sided immersion to the southern quarter …*";
P_HTM[2451]="*pacchimāya disāya …**western quarter …*";
P_HTM[2452]="*uttarāya disāya …**northern quarter …*";
P_HTM[2453]="*uddhamadho tiriyaṃ ekaṃsabhāvito samādhi hoti dibbānaṃ saddānaṃ savanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ, no ca kho dibbānaṃ rūpānaṃ dassanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ.**above, below, across …*";
P_HTM[2454]="*So uddhamadho tiriyaṃ ekaṃsabhāvite samādhimhi dibbānaṃ saddānaṃ savanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ, no ca kho dibbānaṃ rūpānaṃ dassanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2455]="*Uddhamadho tiriyaṃ dibbāni saddāni suṇāti piyarūpāni kāmūpasaṃhitāni rajanīyāni, no ca kho dibbāni rūpāni passati piyarūpāni kāmūpasaṃhitāni rajanīyāni.* **";
P_HTM[2456]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?* **";
P_HTM[2457]="*Evañhetaṃ, mahāli, hoti bhikkhuno uddhamadho tiriyaṃ ekaṃsabhāvite samādhimhi dibbānaṃ saddānaṃ savanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ, no ca kho dibbānaṃ rūpānaṃ dassanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ.**That is how it is for a mendicant who develops immersion in that way.*";
P_HTM[2458]="*Idha, mahāli, bhikkhuno puratthimāya disāya ubhayaṃsabhāvito samādhi hoti dibbānañca rūpānaṃ dassanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ dibbānañca saddānaṃ savanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ.**Take a mendicant who has developed two-sided immersion to the eastern quarter so as to both hear heavenly sounds and see heavenly sights.*";
P_HTM[2459]="*So puratthimāya disāya ubhayaṃsabhāvite samādhimhi dibbānañca rūpānaṃ dassanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ, dibbānañca saddānaṃ savanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ.**When they have developed immersion for that purpose,*";
P_HTM[2460]="*Puratthimāya disāya dibbāni ca rūpāni passati piyarūpāni kāmūpasaṃhitāni rajanīyāni, dibbāni ca saddāni suṇāti piyarūpāni kāmūpasaṃhitāni rajanīyāni.**they both see heavenly sights and hear heavenly sounds.*";
P_HTM[2461]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[2462]="*Evañhetaṃ, mahāli, hoti bhikkhuno puratthimāya disāya ubhayaṃsabhāvite samādhimhi dibbānañca rūpānaṃ dassanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ dibbānañca saddānaṃ savanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ.**Because that is how it is for a mendicant who develops immersion in that way.*";
P_HTM[2463]="*Puna caparaṃ, mahāli, bhikkhuno dakkhiṇāya disāya … pe …**Furthermore, take a mendicant who has developed two-sided immersion to the southern quarter …*";
P_HTM[2464]="*pacchimāya disāya …**western quarter …*";
P_HTM[2465]="*uttarāya disāya …**northern quarter …*";
P_HTM[2466]="*uddhamadho tiriyaṃ ubhayaṃsabhāvito samādhi hoti dibbānañca rūpānaṃ dassanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ, dibbānañca saddānaṃ savanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ.**above, below, across …*";
P_HTM[2467]="*So uddhamadho tiriyaṃ ubhayaṃsabhāvite samādhimhi dibbānañca rūpānaṃ dassanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ dibbānañca saddānaṃ savanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2468]="*Uddhamadho tiriyaṃ dibbāni ca rūpāni passati piyarūpāni kāmūpasaṃhitāni rajanīyāni, dibbāni ca saddāni suṇāti piyarūpāni kāmūpasaṃhitāni rajanīyāni.* **";
P_HTM[2469]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?* **";
P_HTM[2470]="*Evañhetaṃ, mahāli, hoti bhikkhuno uddhamadho tiriyaṃ ubhayaṃsabhāvite samādhimhi dibbānañca rūpānaṃ dassanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ, dibbānañca saddānaṃ savanāya piyarūpānaṃ kāmūpasaṃhitānaṃ rajanīyānaṃ.**That is how it is for a mendicant who develops immersion in that way.*";
P_HTM[2471]="*Ayaṃ kho, mahāli, hetu ayaṃ paccayo, yena santāneva sunakkhatto licchaviputto dibbāni saddāni nāssosi piyarūpāni kāmūpasaṃhitāni rajanīyāni, no asantānī”ti.**This is the cause, Mahāli, this is the reason why Sunakkhatta cannot hear heavenly sounds that are pleasant, sensual, and arousing, even though they really do exist.”*";
P_HTM[2472]="*“Etāsaṃ nūna, bhante, samādhibhāvanānaṃ sacchikiriyāhetu bhikkhū bhagavati brahmacariyaṃ carantī”ti.**“Surely the mendicants must live the spiritual life under the Buddha for the sake of realizing such a development of immersion?”*";
P_HTM[2473]="*“Na kho, mahāli, etāsaṃ samādhibhāvanānaṃ sacchikiriyāhetu bhikkhū mayi brahmacariyaṃ caranti.**“No, Mahāli, the mendicants don’t live the spiritual life under me for the sake of realizing such a development of immersion.*";
P_HTM[2474]="*Atthi kho, mahāli, aññeva dhammā uttaritarā ca paṇītatarā ca, yesaṃ sacchikiriyāhetu bhikkhū mayi brahmacariyaṃ carantī”ti.**There are other things that are finer, for the sake of which the mendicants live the spiritual life under me.”*";
P_HTM[2475]="*2.2. Catuariyaphala**2.2. The Four Noble Fruits*";
P_HTM[2476]="*“Katame pana te, bhante, dhammā uttaritarā ca paṇītatarā ca, yesaṃ sacchikiriyāhetu bhikkhū bhagavati brahmacariyaṃ carantī”ti?**“But sir, what are those finer things?”*";
P_HTM[2477]="*“Idha, mahāli, bhikkhu tiṇṇaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā sotāpanno hoti avinipātadhammo niyato sambodhiparāyaṇo.**“Firstly, Mahāli, with the ending of three fetters a mendicant is a stream-enterer, not liable to be reborn in the underworld, bound for awakening.*";
P_HTM[2478]="*Ayampi kho, mahāli, dhammo uttaritaro ca paṇītataro ca, yassa sacchikiriyāhetu bhikkhū mayi brahmacariyaṃ caranti.**This is one of the finer things for the sake of which the mendicants live the spiritual life under me.*";
P_HTM[2479]="*Puna caparaṃ, mahāli, bhikkhu tiṇṇaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā rāgadosamohānaṃ tanuttā sakadāgāmī hoti, sakideva imaṃ lokaṃ āgantvā dukkhassantaṃ karoti.**Furthermore, a mendicant—with the ending of three fetters, and the weakening of greed, hate, and delusion—is a once-returner. They come back to this world once only, then make an end of suffering.*";
P_HTM[2480]="*Ayampi kho, mahāli, dhammo uttaritaro ca paṇītataro ca, yassa sacchikiriyāhetu bhikkhū mayi brahmacariyaṃ caranti.**This too is one of the finer things.*";
P_HTM[2481]="*Puna caparaṃ, mahāli, bhikkhu pañcannaṃ orambhāgiyānaṃ saṃyojanānaṃ parikkhayā opapātiko hoti, tattha parinibbāyī, anāvattidhammo tasmā lokā.**Furthermore, with the ending of the five lower fetters, a mendicant is reborn spontaneously and will become extinguished there, not liable to return from that world.*";
P_HTM[2482]="*Ayampi kho, mahāli, dhammo uttaritaro ca paṇītataro ca, yassa sacchikiriyāhetu bhikkhū mayi brahmacariyaṃ caranti.**This too is one of the finer things.*";
P_HTM[2483]="*Puna caparaṃ, mahāli, bhikkhu āsavānaṃ khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, a mendicant has realized the undefiled freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom in this very life, and lives having realized it with their own insight due to the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[2484]="*Ayampi kho, mahāli, dhammo uttaritaro ca paṇītataro ca, yassa sacchikiriyāhetu bhikkhū mayi brahmacariyaṃ caranti.**This too is one of the finer things.*";
P_HTM[2485]="*Ime kho te, mahāli, dhammā uttaritarā ca paṇītatarā ca, yesaṃ sacchikiriyāhetu bhikkhū mayi brahmacariyaṃ carantī”ti.**These are the finer things, for the sake of which the mendicants live the spiritual life under me.”*";
P_HTM[2486]="*2.3. Ariyaaṭṭhaṅgikamagga**2.3. The Noble Eightfold Path*";
P_HTM[2487]="*“Atthi pana, bhante, maggo atthi paṭipadā etesaṃ dhammānaṃ sacchikiriyāyā”ti?**“But, sir, is there a path and a practice for realizing these things?”*";
P_HTM[2488]="*“Atthi kho, mahāli, maggo atthi paṭipadā etesaṃ dhammānaṃ sacchikiriyāyā”ti.**“There is, Mahāli.”*";
P_HTM[2489]="*“Katamo pana, bhante, maggo katamā paṭipadā etesaṃ dhammānaṃ sacchikiriyāyā”ti?**“Well, what is it?”*";
P_HTM[2490]="*“Ayameva ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo.**“It is simply this noble eightfold path, that is:*";
P_HTM[2491]="*Seyyathidaṃ—sammādiṭṭhi sammāsaṅkappo sammāvācā sammākammanto sammāājīvo sammāvāyāmo sammāsati sammāsamādhi.**right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion.*";
P_HTM[2492]="*Ayaṃ kho, mahāli, maggo ayaṃ paṭipadā etesaṃ dhammānaṃ sacchikiriyāya.**This is the path and the practice for realizing these things.*";
P_HTM[2493]="*2.4. Dvepabbajitavatthu**2.4. On the Two Renunciates*";
P_HTM[2494]="*Ekamidāhaṃ, mahāli, samayaṃ kosambiyaṃ viharāmi ghositārāme.**This one time, Mahāli, I was staying near Kosambi, in Ghosita’s Monastery.*";
P_HTM[2495]="*Atha kho dve pabbajitā—**Then two renunciates—*";
P_HTM[2496]="*muṇḍiyo ca paribbājako jāliyo ca dārupattikantevāsī yenāhaṃ tenupasaṅkamiṃsu. upasaṅkamitvā mayā saddhiṃ sammodiṃsu.**the wanderer Muṇḍiya and Jāliya the pupil of Dārupattika—came and exchanged greetings with me.*";
P_HTM[2497]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhaṃsu. Ekamantaṃ ṭhitā kho te dve pabbajitā maṃ etadavocuṃ:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, they stood to one side and said to me:*";
P_HTM[2498]="*‘kiṃ nu kho, āvuso gotama, taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīraṃ, udāhu aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīran’ti?**‘Reverend Gotama, are the soul and the body the same thing, or they are different things?’*";
P_HTM[2499]="*‘Tena hāvuso, suṇātha sādhukaṃ manasi karotha bhāsissāmī’ti.**‘Well then, reverends, listen and pay close attention, I will speak.’*";
P_HTM[2500]="*‘Evamāvuso’ti kho te dve pabbajitā mama paccassosuṃ.**‘Yes, reverend,’ they replied.*";
P_HTM[2501]="*Ahaṃ etadavocaṃ:**I said this:*";
P_HTM[2502]="*‘idhāvuso tathāgato loke uppajjati arahaṃ sammāsambuddho … pe …**‘Take the case when a Realized One arises in the world, perfected, a fully awakened Buddha …*";
P_HTM[2503]="*Evaṃ kho, āvuso, bhikkhu sīlasampanno hoti.**That’s how a mendicant is accomplished in ethics. …*";
P_HTM[2504]="*… pe …* **";
P_HTM[2505]="*Paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**They enter and remain in the first absorption.*";
P_HTM[2506]="*Yo kho, āvuso, bhikkhu evaṃ jānāti evaṃ passati, kallaṃ nu kho tassetaṃ vacanāya:**When a mendicant knows and sees like this, would it be appropriate to say of them:*";
P_HTM[2507]="*‘taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīran’ti vā ‘aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīran’ti vāti?**“The soul and the body are the same thing” or “The soul and the body are different things”?’*";
P_HTM[2508]="*Yo so, āvuso, bhikkhu evaṃ jānāti evaṃ passati, kallaṃ tassetaṃ vacanāya:**‘It would, reverend.’*";
P_HTM[2509]="*‘taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīran’ti vā, ‘aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīran’ti vāti.* **";
P_HTM[2510]="*Ahaṃ kho panetaṃ, āvuso, evaṃ jānāmi evaṃ passāmi.**‘But reverends, I know and see like this.*";
P_HTM[2511]="*Atha ca panāhaṃ na vadāmi:**Nevertheless, I do not say:*";
P_HTM[2512]="*‘taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīran’ti vā ‘aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīran’ti vā … pe …**“The soul and the body are the same thing” or “The soul and the body are different things”. …*";
P_HTM[2513]="*dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ …**They enter and remain in the second absorption …*";
P_HTM[2514]="*tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ …**third absorption …*";
P_HTM[2515]="*catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**fourth absorption.*";
P_HTM[2516]="*Yo kho, āvuso, bhikkhu evaṃ jānāti evaṃ passati, kallaṃ nu kho tassetaṃ vacanāya:**When a mendicant knows and sees like this, would it be appropriate to say of them:*";
P_HTM[2517]="*‘taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīran’ti vā ‘aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīran’ti vāti?**“The soul and the body are the same thing” or “The soul and the body are different things”?’*";
P_HTM[2518]="*Yo so, āvuso, bhikkhu evaṃ jānāti evaṃ passati, kallaṃ tassetaṃ vacanāya:**‘It would, reverend.’*";
P_HTM[2519]="*‘taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīran’ti vā ‘aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīran’ti vāti.* **";
P_HTM[2520]="*Ahaṃ kho panetaṃ, āvuso, evaṃ jānāmi evaṃ passāmi.**‘But reverends, I know and see like this.*";
P_HTM[2521]="*Atha ca panāhaṃ na vadāmi:**Nevertheless, I do not say:*";
P_HTM[2522]="*‘taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīran’ti vā ‘aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīran’ti vā … pe …**“The soul and the body are the same thing” or “The soul and the body are different things”. …*";
P_HTM[2523]="*ñāṇadassanāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti …**They extend and project the mind toward knowledge and vision …*";
P_HTM[2524]="*yo kho, āvuso, bhikkhu evaṃ jānāti evaṃ passati, kallaṃ nu kho tassetaṃ vacanāya:**When a mendicant knows and sees like this, would it be appropriate to say of them:*";
P_HTM[2525]="*‘taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīran’ti vā ‘aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīran’ti vāti?**“The soul and the body are the same thing” or “The soul and the body are different things”?’*";
P_HTM[2526]="*… pe …* **";
P_HTM[2527]="*Yo so, āvuso, bhikkhu evaṃ jānāti evaṃ passati, kallaṃ tassetaṃ vacanāya:**‘It would, reverend.’*";
P_HTM[2528]="*‘taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīran’ti vā ‘aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīran’ti vāti.* **";
P_HTM[2529]="*Ahaṃ kho panetaṃ, āvuso, evaṃ jānāmi evaṃ passāmi.**‘But reverends, I know and see like this.*";
P_HTM[2530]="*Atha ca panāhaṃ na vadāmi:**Nevertheless, I do not say:*";
P_HTM[2531]="*‘taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīran’ti vā ‘aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīran’ti vā. … pe …**“The soul and the body are the same thing” or “The soul and the body are different things”. …*";
P_HTM[2532]="*Nāparaṃ itthattāyāti pajānāti.**They understand: “… there is no return to any state of existence.”*";
P_HTM[2533]="*Yo kho, āvuso, bhikkhu evaṃ jānāti evaṃ passati, kallaṃ nu kho tassetaṃ vacanāya:**When a mendicant knows and sees like this, would it be appropriate to say of them:*";
P_HTM[2534]="*‘taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīran’ti vā ‘aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīran’ti vāti?**“The soul and the body are the same thing” or “The soul and the body are different things”?’*";
P_HTM[2535]="*Yo so, āvuso, bhikkhu evaṃ jānāti evaṃ passati na kallaṃ tassetaṃ vacanāya:**‘It would not, reverend.’*";
P_HTM[2536]="*‘taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīran’ti vā ‘aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīran’ti vāti.* **";
P_HTM[2537]="*Ahaṃ kho panetaṃ, āvuso, evaṃ jānāmi evaṃ passāmi.**‘But reverends, I know and see like this.*";
P_HTM[2538]="*Atha ca panāhaṃ na vadāmi:**Nevertheless, I do not say:*";
P_HTM[2539]="*‘taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīran’ti vā ‘aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīran’ti vā”ti.**“The soul and the body are the same thing” or “The soul and the body are different things”.’”*";
P_HTM[2540]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2541]="*Attamano oṭṭhaddho licchavī bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandīti.**Satisfied, Oṭṭhaddha the Licchavi was happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2542]="*Mahālisuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ chaṭṭhaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2543]="*07. Jāliyasutta  - With Jāliya * **";
P_HTM[2544]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[2545]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā kosambiyaṃ viharati ghositārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Kosambi, in Ghosita’s Monastery.*";
P_HTM[2546]="*Tena kho pana samayena dve pabbajitā—**Now at that time two renunciates—*";
P_HTM[2547]="*muṇḍiyo ca paribbājako jāliyo ca dārupattikantevāsī yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavatā saddhiṃ sammodiṃsu.**the wanderer Muṇḍiya and Jāliya the pupil of Dārupattika—came to the Buddha and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[2548]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhaṃsu. Ekamantaṃ ṭhitā kho te dve pabbajitā bhagavantaṃ etadavocuṃ:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, they stood to one side and said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[2549]="*“kiṃ nu kho, āvuso gotama, taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīraṃ, udāhu aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīran”ti?**“Reverend Gotama, are the soul and the body the same thing, or they are different things?”*";
P_HTM[2550]="*“Tena hāvuso, suṇātha sādhukaṃ manasi karotha, bhāsissāmī”ti.**“Well then, reverends, listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[2551]="*“Evamāvuso”ti kho te dve pabbajitā bhagavato paccassosuṃ.**“Yes, reverend,” they replied.*";
P_HTM[2552]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[2553]="*“idhāvuso, tathāgato loke uppajjati arahaṃ, sammāsambuddho … pe …**“Take the case when a Realized One arises in the world, perfected, a fully awakened Buddha …*";
P_HTM[2554]="*Evaṃ kho, āvuso, bhikkhu sīlasampanno hoti.**That’s how a mendicant is accomplished in ethics. …*";
P_HTM[2555]="*… pe …* **";
P_HTM[2556]="*Paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**They enter and remain in the first absorption …*";
P_HTM[2557]="*Yo kho, āvuso, bhikkhu evaṃ jānāti evaṃ passati, kallaṃ nu kho tassetaṃ vacanāya:**When a mendicant knows and sees like this, would it be appropriate to say of them:*";
P_HTM[2558]="*‘taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīran’ti vā ‘aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīran’ti vāti.**‘The soul and the body are the same thing’ or ‘The soul and the body are different things’?”*";
P_HTM[2559]="*Yo so, āvuso, bhikkhu evaṃ jānāti evaṃ passati, kallaṃ tassetaṃ vacanāya:**“It would, reverend.”*";
P_HTM[2560]="*‘taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīran’ti vā ‘aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīran’ti vāti.* **";
P_HTM[2561]="*Ahaṃ kho panetaṃ, āvuso, evaṃ jānāmi evaṃ passāmi.**“But reverends, I know and see like this.*";
P_HTM[2562]="*Atha ca panāhaṃ na vadāmi:**Nevertheless, I do not say:*";
P_HTM[2563]="*‘taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīran’ti vā ‘aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīran’ti vā … pe …**‘The soul and the body are the same thing’ or ‘The soul and the body are different things’. …*";
P_HTM[2564]="*dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ …**They enter and remain in the second absorption …*";
P_HTM[2565]="*tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ …**third absorption …*";
P_HTM[2566]="*catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**fourth absorption.*";
P_HTM[2567]="*Yo kho, āvuso, bhikkhu evaṃ jānāti evaṃ passati, kallaṃ nu kho tassetaṃ vacanāya:**When a mendicant knows and sees like this, would it be appropriate to say of them:*";
P_HTM[2568]="*‘taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīran’ti vā ‘aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīran’ti vāti?**‘The soul and the body are the same thing’ or ‘The soul and the body are different things’?”*";
P_HTM[2569]="*Yo so, āvuso, bhikkhu evaṃ jānāti evaṃ passati kallaṃ, tassetaṃ vacanāya:**“It would, reverend.”*";
P_HTM[2570]="*‘taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīran’ti vā ‘aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīran’ti vāti.* **";
P_HTM[2571]="*Ahaṃ kho panetaṃ, āvuso, evaṃ jānāmi evaṃ passāmi.**“But reverends, I know and see like this.*";
P_HTM[2572]="*Atha ca panāhaṃ na vadāmi:**Nevertheless, I do not say:*";
P_HTM[2573]="*‘taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīran’ti vā ‘aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīran’ti vā … pe …**‘The soul and the body are the same thing’ or ‘The soul and the body are different things’. …*";
P_HTM[2574]="*ñāṇadassanāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti …**They extend and project the mind toward knowledge and vision …*";
P_HTM[2575]="*yo kho, āvuso, bhikkhu evaṃ jānāti evaṃ passati, kallaṃ nu kho tassetaṃ vacanāya:**When a mendicant knows and sees like this, would it be appropriate to say of them:*";
P_HTM[2576]="*‘taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīran’ti vā ‘aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīran’ti vāti.**‘The soul and the body are the same thing’ or ‘The soul and the body are different things’?”*";
P_HTM[2577]="*Yo so, āvuso, bhikkhu evaṃ jānāti evaṃ passati kallaṃ tassetaṃ vacanāya:**“It would, reverend.”*";
P_HTM[2578]="*‘taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīran’ti vā ‘aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīran’ti vāti.* **";
P_HTM[2579]="*Ahaṃ kho panetaṃ, āvuso, evaṃ jānāmi evaṃ passāmi.**“But reverends, I know and see like this.*";
P_HTM[2580]="*Atha ca panāhaṃ na vadāmi:**Nevertheless, I do not say:*";
P_HTM[2581]="*‘taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīran’ti vā ‘aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīran’ti vā … pe ….**‘The soul and the body are the same thing’ or ‘The soul and the body are different things’. …*";
P_HTM[2582]="*Nāparaṃ itthattāyāti pajānāti.**They understand: ‘… there is no return to any state of existence.’*";
P_HTM[2583]="*Yo kho, āvuso, bhikkhu evaṃ jānāti evaṃ passati, kallaṃ nu kho tassetaṃ vacanāya:**When a mendicant knows and sees like this, would it be appropriate to say of them:*";
P_HTM[2584]="*‘taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīran’ti vā ‘aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīran’ti vāti?**‘The soul and the body are the same thing’ or ‘The soul and the body are different things’?”*";
P_HTM[2585]="*Yo so, āvuso, bhikkhu evaṃ jānāti evaṃ passati, na kallaṃ tassetaṃ vacanāya:**“It would not, reverend.”*";
P_HTM[2586]="*‘taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīran’ti vā ‘aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīran’ti vāti.* **";
P_HTM[2587]="*Ahaṃ kho panetaṃ, āvuso, evaṃ jānāmi evaṃ passāmi.**“But reverends, I know and see like this.*";
P_HTM[2588]="*Atha ca panāhaṃ na vadāmi:**Nevertheless, I do not say:*";
P_HTM[2589]="*‘taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīran’ti vā ‘aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīran’ti vā”ti.**‘The soul and the body are the same thing’ or ‘The soul and the body are different things’.”*";
P_HTM[2590]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2591]="*Attamanā te dve pabbajitā bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandunti.**Satisfied, the two renunciates were happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[2592]="*Jāliyasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ sattamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2593]="*08. Mahāsīhanādasutta  - The Longer Discourse on the Lion’s Roar * **";
P_HTM[2594]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[2595]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā uruññāyaṃ viharati kaṇṇakatthale migadāye.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Ujuñña, in the deer park at Kaṇṇakatthala.*";
P_HTM[2596]="*Atha kho acelo kassapo yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavatā saddhiṃ sammodi.**Then the naked ascetic Kassapa went up to the Buddha and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[2597]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhāsi. Ekamantaṃ ṭhito kho acelo kassapo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, he stood to one side, and said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[2598]="*“sutaṃ metaṃ, bho gotama:**“Master Gotama, I have heard the following:*";
P_HTM[2599]="*‘samaṇo gotamo sabbaṃ tapaṃ garahati, sabbaṃ tapassiṃ lūkhājīviṃ ekaṃsena upakkosati upavadatī’ti.**‘The ascetic Gotama criticizes all forms of mortification. He categorically condemns and denounces those self-mortifiers who live rough.’*";
P_HTM[2600]="*Ye te, bho gotama, evamāhaṃsu: ‘samaṇo gotamo sabbaṃ tapaṃ garahati, sabbaṃ tapassiṃ lūkhājīviṃ ekaṃsena upakkosati upavadatī’ti, kacci te bhoto gotamassa vuttavādino, na ca bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ abhūtena abbhācikkhanti, dhammassa cānudhammaṃ byākaronti, na ca koci sahadhammiko vādānuvādo gārayhaṃ ṭhānaṃ āgacchati?**Do those who say this repeat what the Buddha has said, and not misrepresent him with an untruth? Is their explanation in line with the teaching? Are there any legitimate grounds for rebuke and criticism?*";
P_HTM[2601]="*Anabbhakkhātukāmā hi mayaṃ bhavantaṃ gotaman”ti.**For we don’t want to misrepresent Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[2602]="*“Ye te, kassapa, evamāhaṃsu: ‘samaṇo gotamo sabbaṃ tapaṃ garahati, sabbaṃ tapassiṃ lūkhājīviṃ ekaṃsena upakkosati upavadatī’ti, na me te vuttavādino, abbhācikkhanti ca pana maṃ te asatā abhūtena.**“Kassapa, those who say this do not repeat what I have said. They misrepresent me with what is false, baseless, and untrue.*";
P_HTM[2603]="*Idhāhaṃ, kassapa, ekaccaṃ tapassiṃ lūkhājīviṃ passāmi dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapannaṃ.**With clairvoyance that is purified and superhuman, I see some self-mortifier who lives rough reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell.*";
P_HTM[2604]="*Idha panāhaṃ, kassapa, ekaccaṃ tapassiṃ lūkhājīviṃ passāmi dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapannaṃ.**But I see another self-mortifier who lives rough reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[2605]="*Idhāhaṃ, kassapa, ekaccaṃ tapassiṃ appadukkhavihāriṃ passāmi dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapannaṃ.**I see some self-mortifier who takes it easy reborn in a place of loss.*";
P_HTM[2606]="*Idha panāhaṃ, kassapa, ekaccaṃ tapassiṃ appadukkhavihāriṃ passāmi dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapannaṃ.**But I see another self-mortifier who takes it easy reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.*";
P_HTM[2607]="*Yohaṃ, kassapa, imesaṃ tapassīnaṃ evaṃ āgatiñca gatiñca cutiñca upapattiñca yathābhūtaṃ pajānāmi, sohaṃ kiṃ sabbaṃ tapaṃ garahissāmi, sabbaṃ vā tapassiṃ lūkhājīviṃ ekaṃsena upakkosissāmi upavadissāmi?**Since I truly understand the coming and going, passing away and rebirth of these self-mortifiers in this way, how could I criticize all forms of mortification, or categorically condemn and denounce those self-mortifiers who live rough?*";
P_HTM[2608]="*Santi, kassapa, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā paṇḍitā nipuṇā kataparappavādā vālavedhirūpā. Te bhindantā maññe caranti paññāgatena diṭṭhigatāni.**There are some clever ascetics and brahmins who are subtle, accomplished in the doctrines of others, hair-splitters. You’d think they live to demolish convictions with their intellect.*";
P_HTM[2609]="*Tehipi me saddhiṃ ekaccesu ṭhānesu sameti, ekaccesu ṭhānesu na sameti.**They agree with me in some matters and disagree in others.*";
P_HTM[2610]="*Yaṃ te ekaccaṃ vadanti ‘sādhū’ti, mayampi taṃ ekaccaṃ vadema ‘sādhū’ti.**Some of the things that they applaud, I also applaud.*";
P_HTM[2611]="*Yaṃ te ekaccaṃ vadanti ‘na sādhū’ti, mayampi taṃ ekaccaṃ vadema ‘na sādhū’ti.**Some of the things that they don’t applaud, I also don’t applaud.*";
P_HTM[2612]="*Yaṃ te ekaccaṃ vadanti ‘sādhū’ti, mayaṃ taṃ ekaccaṃ vadema ‘na sādhū’ti.**But some of the things that they applaud, I don’t applaud.*";
P_HTM[2613]="*Yaṃ te ekaccaṃ vadanti ‘na sādhū’ti, mayaṃ taṃ ekaccaṃ vadema ‘sādhū’ti.**And some of the things that they don’t applaud, I do applaud.*";
P_HTM[2614]="*Yaṃ mayaṃ ekaccaṃ vadema ‘sādhū’ti, parepi taṃ ekaccaṃ vadanti ‘sādhū’ti.**Some of the things that I applaud, others also applaud.*";
P_HTM[2615]="*Yaṃ mayaṃ ekaccaṃ vadema ‘na sādhū’ti, parepi taṃ ekaccaṃ vadanti ‘na sādhū’ti.**Some of the things that I don’t applaud, they also don’t applaud.*";
P_HTM[2616]="*Yaṃ mayaṃ ekaccaṃ vadema ‘na sādhū’ti, pare taṃ ekaccaṃ vadanti ‘sādhū’ti.**But some of the things that I don’t applaud, others do applaud.*";
P_HTM[2617]="*Yaṃ mayaṃ ekaccaṃ vadema ‘sādhū’ti, pare taṃ ekaccaṃ vadanti ‘na sādhū’ti.**And some of the things that I do applaud, others don’t applaud.*";
P_HTM[2618]="*1. Samanuyuñjāpanakathā**1. Examination*";
P_HTM[2619]="*Tyāhaṃ upasaṅkamitvā evaṃ vadāmi:**I go up to them and say:*";
P_HTM[2620]="*‘yesu no, āvuso, ṭhānesu na sameti, tiṭṭhantu tāni ṭhānāni.**‘Let us leave aside those matters on which we disagree.*";
P_HTM[2621]="*Yesu ṭhānesu sameti, tattha viññū samanuyuñjantaṃ samanugāhantaṃ samanubhāsantaṃ satthārā vā satthāraṃ saṅghena vā saṅghaṃ:**But there are some matters on which we agree. Regarding these, sensible people, pursuing, pressing, and grilling, would compare teacher with teacher or community with community:*";
P_HTM[2622]="*“ye imesaṃ bhavataṃ dhammā akusalā akusalasaṅkhātā, sāvajjā sāvajjasaṅkhātā, asevitabbā asevitabbasaṅkhātā, na alamariyā na alamariyasaṅkhātā, kaṇhā kaṇhasaṅkhātā.**“There are things that are unskillful, blameworthy, not to be cultivated, unworthy of the noble ones, and dark—and are reckoned as such.*";
P_HTM[2623]="*Ko ime dhamme anavasesaṃ pahāya vattati, samaṇo vā gotamo, pare vā pana bhonto gaṇācariyā”ti?**Who behaves like they’ve totally given these things up: the ascetic Gotama, or the teachers of other communities?”’*";
P_HTM[2624]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, kassapa, vijjati, yaṃ viññū samanuyuñjantā samanugāhantā samanubhāsantā evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**It’s possible that they might say:*";
P_HTM[2625]="*‘ye imesaṃ bhavataṃ dhammā akusalā akusalasaṅkhātā, sāvajjā sāvajjasaṅkhātā, asevitabbā asevitabbasaṅkhātā, na alamariyā na alamariyasaṅkhātā, kaṇhā kaṇhasaṅkhātā.* **";
P_HTM[2626]="*Samaṇo gotamo ime dhamme anavasesaṃ pahāya vattati, yaṃ vā pana bhonto pare gaṇācariyā’ti.**‘The ascetic Gotama behaves like he’s totally given those unskillful things up, compared with the teachers of other communities.’*";
P_HTM[2627]="*Itiha, kassapa, viññū samanuyuñjantā samanugāhantā samanubhāsantā amheva tattha yebhuyyena pasaṃseyyuṃ.**And that’s how, when sensible people pursue the matter, they will mostly praise us.*";
P_HTM[2628]="*Aparampi no, kassapa, viññū samanuyuñjantaṃ samanugāhantaṃ samanubhāsantaṃ satthārā vā satthāraṃ saṅghena vā saṅghaṃ:**In addition, sensible people, engaging, pressing, and grilling, would compare teacher with teacher or community with community:*";
P_HTM[2629]="*‘ye imesaṃ bhavataṃ dhammā kusalā kusalasaṅkhātā, anavajjā anavajjasaṅkhātā, sevitabbā sevitabbasaṅkhātā, alamariyā alamariyasaṅkhātā, sukkā sukkasaṅkhātā.**‘There are things that are skillful, blameless, worth cultivating, worthy of the noble ones, and bright—and are reckoned as such.*";
P_HTM[2630]="*Ko ime dhamme anavasesaṃ samādāya vattati, samaṇo vā gotamo, pare vā pana bhonto gaṇācariyā’ti?**Who proceeds having totally undertaken these things: the ascetic Gotama, or the teachers of other communities?’*";
P_HTM[2631]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, kassapa, vijjati, yaṃ viññū samanuyuñjantā samanugāhantā samanubhāsantā evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**It’s possible that they might say:*";
P_HTM[2632]="*‘ye imesaṃ bhavataṃ dhammā kusalā kusalasaṅkhātā, anavajjā anavajjasaṅkhātā, sevitabbā sevitabbasaṅkhātā, alamariyā alamariyasaṅkhātā, sukkā sukkasaṅkhātā.* **";
P_HTM[2633]="*Samaṇo gotamo ime dhamme anavasesaṃ samādāya vattati, yaṃ vā pana bhonto pare gaṇācariyā’ti.**‘The ascetic Gotama proceeds having totally undertaken these things, compared with the teachers of other communities.’*";
P_HTM[2634]="*Itiha, kassapa, viññū samanuyuñjantā samanugāhantā samanubhāsantā amheva tattha yebhuyyena pasaṃseyyuṃ.**And that’s how, when sensible people pursue the matter, they will mostly praise us.*";
P_HTM[2635]="*Aparampi no, kassapa, viññū samanuyuñjantaṃ samanugāhantaṃ samanubhāsantaṃ satthārā vā satthāraṃ saṅghena vā saṅghaṃ:**In addition, sensible people, pursuing, pressing, and grilling, would compare teacher with teacher or community with community:*";
P_HTM[2636]="*‘ye imesaṃ bhavataṃ dhammā akusalā akusalasaṅkhātā, sāvajjā sāvajjasaṅkhātā, asevitabbā asevitabbasaṅkhātā, na alamariyā na alamariyasaṅkhātā, kaṇhā kaṇhasaṅkhātā.**‘There are things that are unskillful, blameworthy, not to be cultivated, unworthy of the noble ones, and dark—and are reckoned as such.*";
P_HTM[2637]="*Ko ime dhamme anavasesaṃ pahāya vattati, gotamasāvakasaṅgho vā, pare vā pana bhonto gaṇācariyasāvakasaṅghā’ti?**Who behaves like they’ve totally given these things up: the ascetic Gotama’s disciples, or the disciples of other teachers?’*";
P_HTM[2638]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, kassapa, vijjati, yaṃ viññū samanuyuñjantā samanugāhantā samanubhāsantā evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**It’s possible that they might say:*";
P_HTM[2639]="*‘ye imesaṃ bhavataṃ dhammā akusalā akusalasaṅkhātā, sāvajjā sāvajjasaṅkhātā, asevitabbā asevitabbasaṅkhātā, na alamariyā na alamariyasaṅkhātā, kaṇhā kaṇhasaṅkhātā.* **";
P_HTM[2640]="*Gotamasāvakasaṅgho ime dhamme anavasesaṃ pahāya vattati, yaṃ vā pana bhonto pare gaṇācariyasāvakasaṅghā’ti.**‘The ascetic Gotama’s disciples behave like they’ve totally given those unskillful things up, compared with the disciples of other teachers.’*";
P_HTM[2641]="*Itiha, kassapa, viññū samanuyuñjantā samanugāhantā samanubhāsantā amheva tattha yebhuyyena pasaṃseyyuṃ.**And that’s how, when sensible people pursue the matter, they will mostly praise us.*";
P_HTM[2642]="*Aparampi no, kassapa, viññū samanuyuñjantaṃ samanugāhantaṃ samanubhāsantaṃ satthārā vā satthāraṃ saṅghena vā saṅghaṃ.**In addition, sensible people, pursuing, pressing, and grilling, would compare teacher with teacher or community with community:*";
P_HTM[2643]="*‘Ye imesaṃ bhavataṃ dhammā kusalā kusalasaṅkhātā, anavajjā anavajjasaṅkhātā, sevitabbā sevitabbasaṅkhātā, alamariyā alamariyasaṅkhātā, sukkā sukkasaṅkhātā.**‘There are things that are skillful, blameless, worth cultivating, worthy of the noble ones, and bright—and are reckoned as such.*";
P_HTM[2644]="*Ko ime dhamme anavasesaṃ samādāya vattati, gotamasāvakasaṅgho vā, pare vā pana bhonto gaṇācariyasāvakasaṅghā’ti?**Who proceeds having totally undertaken these things: the ascetic Gotama’s disciples, or the disciples of other teachers?’*";
P_HTM[2645]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, kassapa, vijjati, yaṃ viññū samanuyuñjantā samanugāhantā samanubhāsantā evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**It’s possible that they might say:*";
P_HTM[2646]="*‘ye imesaṃ bhavataṃ dhammā kusalā kusalasaṅkhātā, anavajjā anavajjasaṅkhātā, sevitabbā sevitabbasaṅkhātā, alamariyā alamariyasaṅkhātā, sukkā sukkasaṅkhātā.* **";
P_HTM[2647]="*Gotamasāvakasaṅgho ime dhamme anavasesaṃ samādāya vattati, yaṃ vā pana bhonto pare gaṇācariyasāvakasaṅghā’ti.**‘The ascetic Gotama’s disciples proceed having totally undertaken those skillful things, compared with the disciples of other teachers.’*";
P_HTM[2648]="*Itiha, kassapa, viññū samanuyuñjantā samanugāhantā samanubhāsantā amheva tattha yebhuyyena pasaṃseyyuṃ.**And that’s how, when sensible people pursue the matter, they will mostly praise us.*";
P_HTM[2649]="*2. Ariyaaṭṭhaṅgikamagga**2. The Noble Eightfold Path*";
P_HTM[2650]="*Atthi, kassapa, maggo atthi paṭipadā, yathāpaṭipanno sāmaññeva ñassati sāmaṃ dakkhati:**There is, Kassapa, a path, there is a practice, practicing in accordance with which you will know and see for yourself:*";
P_HTM[2651]="*‘samaṇova gotamo kālavādī bhūtavādī atthavādī dhammavādī vinayavādī’ti.**‘Only the ascetic Gotama’s words are timely, true, and meaningful, in line with the teaching and training.’*";
P_HTM[2652]="*Katamo ca, kassapa, maggo, katamā ca paṭipadā, yathāpaṭipanno sāmaññeva ñassati sāmaṃ dakkhati:**And what is that path?*";
P_HTM[2653]="*‘samaṇova gotamo kālavādī bhūtavādī atthavādī dhammavādī vinayavādī’ti?* **";
P_HTM[2654]="*Ayameva ariyo aṭṭhaṅgiko maggo.**It is simply this noble eightfold path, that is:*";
P_HTM[2655]="*Seyyathidaṃ—sammādiṭṭhi sammāsaṅkappo sammāvācā sammākammanto sammāājīvo sammāvāyāmo sammāsati sammāsamādhi.**right view, right thought, right speech, right action, right livelihood, right effort, right mindfulness, and right immersion.*";
P_HTM[2656]="*Ayaṃ kho, kassapa, maggo, ayaṃ paṭipadā, yathāpaṭipanno sāmaññeva ñassati sāmaṃ dakkhati ‘samaṇova gotamo kālavādī bhūtavādī atthavādī dhammavādī vinayavādī’”ti.**This is the path, this is the practice, practicing in accordance with which you will know and see for yourself: ‘Only the ascetic Gotama’s words are timely, true, and meaningful, in line with the teaching and training.’”*";
P_HTM[2657]="*3. Tapopakkamakathā**3. Practicing Self-Mortification*";
P_HTM[2658]="*Evaṃ vutte, acelo kassapo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he had spoken, Kassapa said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[2659]="*“imepi kho, āvuso gotama, tapopakkamā etesaṃ samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ sāmaññasaṅkhātā ca brahmaññasaṅkhātā ca.**“Reverend Gotama, those ascetics and brahmins consider these practices of self-mortification to be what makes someone a true ascetic or brahmin.*";
P_HTM[2660]="*Acelako hoti, muttācāro, hatthāpalekhano, naehibhaddantiko, natiṭṭhabhaddantiko, nābhihaṭaṃ, na uddissakataṃ, na nimantanaṃ sādiyati.**They go naked, ignoring conventions. They lick their hands, and don’t come or wait when asked. They don’t consent to food brought to them, or food prepared on purpose for them, or an invitation for a meal.*";
P_HTM[2661]="*So na kumbhimukhā paṭiggaṇhāti, na kaḷopimukhā paṭiggaṇhāti, na eḷakamantaraṃ, na daṇḍamantaraṃ, na musalamantaraṃ, na dvinnaṃ bhuñjamānānaṃ, na gabbhiniyā, na pāyamānāya, na purisantaragatāya, na saṅkittīsu, na yattha sā upaṭṭhito hoti, na yattha makkhikā saṇḍasaṇḍacārinī, na macchaṃ, na maṃsaṃ, na suraṃ, na merayaṃ, na thusodakaṃ pivati.**They don’t receive anything from a pot or bowl; or from someone who keeps sheep, or who has a weapon or a shovel in their home; or where a couple is eating; or where there is a woman who is pregnant, breastfeeding, or who has a man in her home; or where there’s a dog waiting or flies buzzing. They accept no fish or meat or liquor or wine, and drink no beer.*";
P_HTM[2662]="*So ekāgāriko vā hoti ekālopiko, dvāgāriko vā hoti dvālopiko … sattāgāriko vā hoti sattālopiko;**They go to just one house for alms, taking just one mouthful, or two houses and two mouthfuls, up to seven houses and seven mouthfuls.*";
P_HTM[2663]="*ekissāpi dattiyā yāpeti, dvīhipi dattīhi yāpeti … sattahipi dattīhi yāpeti;**They feed on one saucer a day, two saucers a day, up to seven saucers a day.*";
P_HTM[2664]="*ekāhikampi āhāraṃ āhāreti, dvīhikampi āhāraṃ āhāreti … sattāhikampi āhāraṃ āhāreti. Iti evarūpaṃ addhamāsikampi pariyāyabhattabhojanānuyogamanuyutto viharati.**They eat once a day, once every second day, up to once a week, and so on, even up to once a fortnight. They live committed to the practice of eating food at set intervals.*";
P_HTM[2665]="*Imepi kho, āvuso gotama, tapopakkamā etesaṃ samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ sāmaññasaṅkhātā ca brahmaññasaṅkhātā ca.**Those ascetics and brahmins also consider these practices of self-mortification to be what makes someone a true ascetic or brahmin.*";
P_HTM[2666]="*Sākabhakkho vā hoti, sāmākabhakkho vā hoti, nīvārabhakkho vā hoti, daddulabhakkho vā hoti, haṭabhakkho vā hoti, kaṇabhakkho vā hoti, ācāmabhakkho vā hoti, piññākabhakkho vā hoti, tiṇabhakkho vā hoti, gomayabhakkho vā hoti, vanamūlaphalāhāro yāpeti pavattaphalabhojī.**They eat herbs, millet, wild rice, poor rice, water lettuce, rice bran, scum from boiling rice, sesame flour, grass, or cow dung. They survive on forest roots and fruits, or eating fallen fruit.*";
P_HTM[2667]="*Imepi kho, āvuso gotama, tapopakkamā etesaṃ samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ sāmaññasaṅkhātā ca brahmaññasaṅkhātā ca.**Those ascetics and brahmins also consider these practices of mortification to be what makes someone a true ascetic or brahmin.*";
P_HTM[2668]="*Sāṇānipi dhāreti, masāṇānipi dhāreti, chavadussānipi dhāreti, paṃsukūlānipi dhāreti, tirīṭānipi dhāreti, ajinampi dhāreti, ajinakkhipampi dhāreti, kusacīrampi dhāreti, vākacīrampi dhāreti, phalakacīrampi dhāreti, kesakambalampi dhāreti, vāḷakambalampi dhāreti, ulūkapakkhikampi dhāreti,**They wear robes of sunn hemp, mixed hemp, corpse-wrapping cloth, rags, lodh tree bark, antelope hide (whole or in strips), kusa grass, bark, wood-chips, human hair, horse-tail hair, or owls’ wings.*";
P_HTM[2669]="*kesamassulocakopi hoti kesamassulocanānuyogamanuyutto,**They tear out hair and beard, committed to this practice.*";
P_HTM[2670]="*ubbhaṭṭhakopi hoti āsanapaṭikkhitto,**They constantly stand, refusing seats.*";
P_HTM[2671]="*ukkuṭikopi hoti ukkuṭikappadhānamanuyutto,**They squat, committed to persisting in the squatting position.*";
P_HTM[2672]="*kaṇṭakāpassayikopi hoti kaṇṭakāpassaye seyyaṃ kappeti,**They lie on a mat of thorns, making a mat of thorns their bed.*";
P_HTM[2673]="*phalakaseyyampi kappeti, thaṇḍilaseyyampi kappeti,**They make their bed on a plank, or the bare ground.*";
P_HTM[2674]="*ekapassayikopi hoti**They lie only on one side.*";
P_HTM[2675]="*rajojalladharo,**They wear dust and dirt.*";
P_HTM[2676]="*abbhokāsikopi hoti**They stay in the open air.*";
P_HTM[2677]="*yathāsanthatiko,**They sleep wherever they lay their mat.*";
P_HTM[2678]="*vekaṭikopi hoti vikaṭabhojanānuyogamanuyutto,**They eat unnatural things, committed to the practice of eating unnatural foods.*";
P_HTM[2679]="*apānakopi hoti apānakattamanuyutto,**They don’t drink, committed to the practice of not drinking liquids.*";
P_HTM[2680]="*sāyatatiyakampi udakorohanānuyogamanuyutto viharatī”ti.**They’re committed to the practice of immersion in water three times a day, including the evening.”*";
P_HTM[2681]="*4. Tapopakkamaniratthakathā**4. The Uselessness of Self-Mortification*";
P_HTM[2682]="*“Acelako cepi, kassapa, hoti, muttācāro, hatthāpalekhano … pe … iti evarūpaṃ addhamāsikampi pariyāyabhattabhojanānuyogamanuyutto viharati.**“Kassapa, someone may practice all those forms of self-mortification,*";
P_HTM[2683]="*Tassa cāyaṃ sīlasampadā cittasampadā paññāsampadā abhāvitā hoti asacchikatā. Atha kho so ārakāva sāmaññā ārakāva brahmaññā.**but if they haven’t developed and realized any accomplishment in ethics, mind, and wisdom, they are far from being a true ascetic or brahmin.*";
P_HTM[2684]="*Yato kho, kassapa, bhikkhu averaṃ abyāpajjaṃ mettacittaṃ bhāveti, āsavānañca khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharati.**But take a mendicant who develops a heart of love, free of enmity and ill will. And they realize the undefiled freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom in this very life, and live having realized it with their own insight due to the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[2685]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, kassapa, bhikkhu samaṇo itipi brāhmaṇo itipi.**When they achieve this, they’re called a mendicant who is a ‘true ascetic’ and also ‘a true brahmin’.*";
P_HTM[2686]="*Sākabhakkho cepi, kassapa, hoti, sāmākabhakkho … pe … vanamūlaphalāhāro yāpeti pavattaphalabhojī.* **";
P_HTM[2687]="*Tassa cāyaṃ sīlasampadā cittasampadā paññāsampadā abhāvitā hoti asacchikatā.* **";
P_HTM[2688]="*Atha kho so ārakāva sāmaññā ārakāva brahmaññā.* **";
P_HTM[2689]="*Yato kho, kassapa, bhikkhu averaṃ abyāpajjaṃ mettacittaṃ bhāveti, āsavānañca khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharati.* **";
P_HTM[2690]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, kassapa, bhikkhu samaṇo itipi brāhmaṇo itipi.* **";
P_HTM[2691]="*Sāṇāni cepi, kassapa, dhāreti, masāṇānipi dhāreti … pe …* **";
P_HTM[2692]="*sāyatatiyakampi udakorohanānuyogamanuyutto viharati.* **";
P_HTM[2693]="*Tassa cāyaṃ sīlasampadā cittasampadā paññāsampadā abhāvitā hoti asacchikatā.* **";
P_HTM[2694]="*Atha kho so ārakāva sāmaññā ārakāva brahmaññā.* **";
P_HTM[2695]="*Yato kho, kassapa, bhikkhu averaṃ abyāpajjaṃ mettacittaṃ bhāveti, āsavānañca khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharati.* **";
P_HTM[2696]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, kassapa, bhikkhu samaṇo itipi brāhmaṇo itipī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[2697]="*Evaṃ vutte, acelo kassapo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he had spoken, Kassapa said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[2698]="*“dukkaraṃ, bho gotama, sāmaññaṃ dukkaraṃ brahmaññan”ti.**“It’s hard, Master Gotama, to be a true ascetic or a true brahmin.”*";
P_HTM[2699]="*“Pakati kho esā, kassapa, lokasmiṃ ‘dukkaraṃ sāmaññaṃ dukkaraṃ brahmaññan’ti.**“It’s typical, Kassapa, in this world to think that it’s hard to be a true ascetic or brahmin.*";
P_HTM[2700]="*Acelako cepi, kassapa, hoti, muttācāro, hatthāpalekhano … pe … iti evarūpaṃ addhamāsikampi pariyāyabhattabhojanānuyogamanuyutto viharati.**But someone might practice all those forms of self-mortification.*";
P_HTM[2701]="*Imāya ca, kassapa, mattāya iminā tapopakkamena sāmaññaṃ vā abhavissa brahmaññaṃ vā dukkaraṃ sudukkaraṃ, netaṃ abhavissa kallaṃ vacanāya:**And if it was only because of just that much, only because of that self-mortification that it was so very hard to be a true ascetic or brahmin, it wouldn’t be appropriate to say that*";
P_HTM[2702]="*‘dukkaraṃ sāmaññaṃ dukkaraṃ brahmaññan’ti.**it’s hard to be a true ascetic or brahmin.*";
P_HTM[2703]="*Sakkā ca panetaṃ abhavissa kātuṃ gahapatinā vā gahapatiputtena vā antamaso kumbhadāsiyāpi:**For it would be quite possible for a householder or a householder’s child—or even the bonded maid who carries the water-jar—*";
P_HTM[2704]="*‘handāhaṃ acelako homi, muttācāro, hatthāpalekhano … pe … iti evarūpaṃ addhamāsikampi pariyāyabhattabhojanānuyogamanuyutto viharāmī’ti.**to practice all those forms of self-mortification.*";
P_HTM[2705]="*Yasmā ca kho, kassapa, aññatreva imāya mattāya aññatra iminā tapopakkamena sāmaññaṃ vā hoti brahmaññaṃ vā dukkaraṃ sudukkaraṃ, tasmā etaṃ kallaṃ vacanāya:**It’s because there’s something other than just that much, something other than that self-mortification that it’s so very hard to be a true ascetic or brahmin. And that’s why it is appropriate to say that*";
P_HTM[2706]="*‘dukkaraṃ sāmaññaṃ dukkaraṃ brahmaññan’ti.**it’s hard to be a true ascetic or brahmin.*";
P_HTM[2707]="*Yato kho, kassapa, bhikkhu averaṃ abyāpajjaṃ mettacittaṃ bhāveti, āsavānañca khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharati.**Take a mendicant who develops a heart of love, free of enmity and ill will. And they realize the undefiled freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom in this very life, and live having realized it with their own insight due to the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[2708]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, kassapa, bhikkhu samaṇo itipi brāhmaṇo itipi.**When they achieve this, they’re called a mendicant who is a ‘true ascetic’ and also ‘a true brahmin’.*";
P_HTM[2709]="*Sākabhakkho cepi, kassapa, hoti, sāmākabhakkho … pe … vanamūlaphalāhāro yāpeti pavattaphalabhojī.* **";
P_HTM[2710]="*Imāya ca, kassapa, mattāya iminā tapopakkamena sāmaññaṃ vā abhavissa brahmaññaṃ vā dukkaraṃ sudukkaraṃ, netaṃ abhavissa kallaṃ vacanāya:* **";
P_HTM[2711]="*‘dukkaraṃ sāmaññaṃ dukkaraṃ brahmaññan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2712]="*Sakkā ca panetaṃ abhavissa kātuṃ gahapatinā vā gahapatiputtena vā antamaso kumbhadāsiyāpi:* **";
P_HTM[2713]="*‘handāhaṃ sākabhakkho vā homi, sāmākabhakkho vā … pe … vanamūlaphalāhāro yāpemi pavattaphalabhojī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2714]="*Yasmā ca kho, kassapa, aññatreva imāya mattāya aññatra iminā tapopakkamena sāmaññaṃ vā hoti brahmaññaṃ vā dukkaraṃ sudukkaraṃ, tasmā etaṃ kallaṃ vacanāya:* **";
P_HTM[2715]="*‘dukkaraṃ sāmaññaṃ dukkaraṃ brahmaññan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2716]="*Yato kho, kassapa, bhikkhu averaṃ abyāpajjaṃ mettacittaṃ bhāveti, āsavānañca khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharati.* **";
P_HTM[2717]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, kassapa, bhikkhu samaṇo itipi brāhmaṇo itipi.* **";
P_HTM[2718]="*Sāṇāni cepi, kassapa, dhāreti, masāṇānipi dhāreti … pe … sāyatatiyakampi udakorohanānuyogamanuyutto viharati.* **";
P_HTM[2719]="*Imāya ca, kassapa, mattāya iminā tapopakkamena sāmaññaṃ vā abhavissa brahmaññaṃ vā dukkaraṃ sudukkaraṃ, netaṃ abhavissa kallaṃ vacanāya:* **";
P_HTM[2720]="*‘dukkaraṃ sāmaññaṃ dukkaraṃ brahmaññan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2721]="*Sakkā ca panetaṃ abhavissa kātuṃ gahapatinā vā gahapatiputtena vā antamaso kumbhadāsiyāpi:* **";
P_HTM[2722]="*‘handāhaṃ sāṇānipi dhāremi, masāṇānipi dhāremi … pe … sāyatatiyakampi udakorohanānuyogamanuyutto viharāmī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2723]="*Yasmā ca kho, kassapa, aññatreva imāya mattāya aññatra iminā tapopakkamena sāmaññaṃ vā hoti brahmaññaṃ vā dukkaraṃ sudukkaraṃ, tasmā etaṃ kallaṃ vacanāya:* **";
P_HTM[2724]="*‘dukkaraṃ sāmaññaṃ dukkaraṃ brahmaññan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2725]="*Yato kho, kassapa, bhikkhu averaṃ abyāpajjaṃ mettacittaṃ bhāveti, āsavānañca khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharati.* **";
P_HTM[2726]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, kassapa, bhikkhu samaṇo itipi brāhmaṇo itipī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[2727]="*Evaṃ vutte, acelo kassapo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he had spoken, Kassapa said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[2728]="*“dujjāno, bho gotama, samaṇo, dujjāno brāhmaṇo”ti.**“It’s hard, Master Gotama, to know a true ascetic or a true brahmin.”*";
P_HTM[2729]="*“Pakati kho esā, kassapa, lokasmiṃ ‘dujjāno samaṇo dujjāno brāhmaṇo’ti.**“It’s typical in this world to think that it’s hard to know a true ascetic or brahmin.*";
P_HTM[2730]="*Acelako cepi, kassapa, hoti, muttācāro, hatthāpalekhano … pe … iti evarūpaṃ addhamāsikampi pariyāyabhattabhojanānuyogamanuyutto viharati.**But someone might practice all those forms of self-mortification.*";
P_HTM[2731]="*Imāya ca, kassapa, mattāya iminā tapopakkamena samaṇo vā abhavissa brāhmaṇo vā dujjāno sudujjāno, netaṃ abhavissa kallaṃ vacanāya:**And if it was only by just that much, only by that self-mortification that it was so very hard to know a true ascetic or brahmin, it wouldn’t be appropriate to say that*";
P_HTM[2732]="*‘dujjāno samaṇo dujjāno brāhmaṇo’ti.**it’s hard to know a true ascetic or brahmin.*";
P_HTM[2733]="*Sakkā ca paneso abhavissa ñātuṃ gahapatinā vā gahapatiputtena vā antamaso kumbhadāsiyāpi:**For it would be quite possible for a householder or a householder’s child—or even the bonded maid who carries the water-jar—*";
P_HTM[2734]="*‘ayaṃ acelako hoti, muttācāro, hatthāpalekhano … pe … iti evarūpaṃ addhamāsikampi pariyāyabhattabhojanānuyogamanuyutto viharatī’ti.**to know that someone is practicing all those forms of self-mortification.*";
P_HTM[2735]="*Yasmā ca kho, kassapa, aññatreva imāya mattāya aññatra iminā tapopakkamena samaṇo vā hoti brāhmaṇo vā dujjāno sudujjāno, tasmā etaṃ kallaṃ vacanāya:**It’s because there’s something other than just that much, something other than that self-mortification that it’s so very hard to know a true ascetic or brahmin. And that’s why it is appropriate to say that*";
P_HTM[2736]="*‘dujjāno samaṇo dujjāno brāhmaṇo’ti.**it’s hard to know a true ascetic or brahmin.*";
P_HTM[2737]="*Yato kho, kassapa, bhikkhu averaṃ abyāpajjaṃ mettacittaṃ bhāveti, āsavānañca khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharati.**Take a mendicant who develops a heart of love, free of enmity and ill will. And they realize the undefiled freedom of heart and freedom by wisdom in this very life, and live having realized it with their own insight due to the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[2738]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, kassapa, bhikkhu samaṇo itipi brāhmaṇo itipi.**When they achieve this, they’re called a mendicant who is a ‘true ascetic’ and also ‘a true brahmin’.”*";
P_HTM[2739]="*Sākabhakkho cepi, kassapa, hoti sāmākabhakkho … pe … vanamūlaphalāhāro yāpeti pavattaphalabhojī.* **";
P_HTM[2740]="*Imāya ca, kassapa, mattāya iminā tapopakkamena samaṇo vā abhavissa brāhmaṇo vā dujjāno sudujjāno, netaṃ abhavissa kallaṃ vacanāya:* **";
P_HTM[2741]="*‘dujjāno samaṇo dujjāno brāhmaṇo’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2742]="*Sakkā ca paneso abhavissa ñātuṃ gahapatinā vā gahapatiputtena vā antamaso kumbhadāsiyāpi:* **";
P_HTM[2743]="*‘ayaṃ sākabhakkho vā hoti sāmākabhakkho … pe … vanamūlaphalāhāro yāpeti pavattaphalabhojī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2744]="*Yasmā ca kho, kassapa, aññatreva imāya mattāya aññatra iminā tapopakkamena samaṇo vā hoti brāhmaṇo vā dujjāno sudujjāno, tasmā etaṃ kallaṃ vacanāya:* **";
P_HTM[2745]="*‘dujjāno samaṇo dujjāno brāhmaṇo’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2746]="*Yato kho, kassapa, bhikkhu averaṃ abyāpajjaṃ mettacittaṃ bhāveti, āsavānañca khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharati.* **";
P_HTM[2747]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, kassapa, bhikkhu samaṇo itipi brāhmaṇo itipi.* **";
P_HTM[2748]="*Sāṇāni cepi, kassapa, dhāreti, masāṇānipi dhāreti … pe … sāyatatiyakampi udakorohanānuyogamanuyutto viharati.* **";
P_HTM[2749]="*Imāya ca, kassapa, mattāya iminā tapopakkamena samaṇo vā abhavissa brāhmaṇo vā dujjāno sudujjāno, netaṃ abhavissa kallaṃ vacanāya:* **";
P_HTM[2750]="*‘dujjāno samaṇo dujjāno brāhmaṇo’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2751]="*Sakkā ca paneso abhavissa ñātuṃ gahapatinā vā gahapatiputtena vā antamaso kumbhadāsiyāpi:* **";
P_HTM[2752]="*‘ayaṃ sāṇānipi dhāreti, masāṇānipi dhāreti … pe … sāyatatiyakampi udakorohanānuyogamanuyutto viharatī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2753]="*Yasmā ca kho, kassapa, aññatreva imāya mattāya aññatra iminā tapopakkamena samaṇo vā hoti brāhmaṇo vā dujjāno sudujjāno, tasmā etaṃ kallaṃ vacanāya:* **";
P_HTM[2754]="*‘dujjāno samaṇo dujjāno brāhmaṇo’ti.* **";
P_HTM[2755]="*Yato kho, kassapa, bhikkhu averaṃ abyāpajjaṃ mettacittaṃ bhāveti, āsavānañca khayā anāsavaṃ cetovimuttiṃ paññāvimuttiṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharati.* **";
P_HTM[2756]="*Ayaṃ vuccati, kassapa, bhikkhu samaṇo itipi brāhmaṇo itipī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[2757]="*5. Sīlasamādhipaññāsampadā**5. The Accomplishment of Ethics, Immersion, and Wisdom*";
P_HTM[2758]="*Evaṃ vutte, acelo kassapo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he had spoken, Kassapa said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[2759]="*“katamā pana sā, bho gotama, sīlasampadā, katamā cittasampadā, katamā paññāsampadā”ti?**“But Master Gotama, what is that accomplishment in ethics, in mind, and in wisdom?”*";
P_HTM[2760]="*“Idha, kassapa, tathāgato loke uppajjati arahaṃ, sammāsambuddho … pe …**“It’s when a Realized One arises in the world, perfected, a fully awakened Buddha …*";
P_HTM[2761]="*bhayadassāvī samādāya sikkhati sikkhāpadesu, kāyakammavacīkammena samannāgato kusalena parisuddhājīvo sīlasampanno indriyesu guttadvāro satisampajaññena samannāgato santuṭṭho.**Seeing danger in the slightest fault, a mendicant keeps the rules they’ve undertaken. They act skillfully by body and speech. They’re purified in livelihood and accomplished in ethical conduct. They guard the sense doors, have mindfulness and situational awareness, and are content.*";
P_HTM[2762]="*Kathañca, kassapa, bhikkhu sīlasampanno hoti?**And how is a mendicant accomplished in ethics?*";
P_HTM[2763]="*Idha, kassapa, bhikkhu pāṇātipātaṃ pahāya pāṇātipātā paṭivirato hoti nihitadaṇḍo nihitasattho lajjī dayāpanno, sabbapāṇabhūtahitānukampī viharati.**It’s when a mendicant gives up killing living creatures. They renounce the rod and the sword. They’re scrupulous and kind, living full of compassion for all living beings.*";
P_HTM[2764]="*Idampissa hoti sīlasampadāya … pe …**This pertains to their accomplishment in ethics. …*";
P_HTM[2765]="*Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpāya tiracchānavijjāya micchājīvena jīvitaṃ kappenti.**There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still earn a living by unworthy branches of knowledge, by wrong livelihood. …*";
P_HTM[2766]="*Seyyathidaṃ—santikammaṃ paṇidhikammaṃ … pe … osadhīnaṃ patimokkho* **";
P_HTM[2767]="*iti vā iti evarūpāya tiracchānavijjāya micchājīvā paṭivirato hoti.**They refrain from such unworthy branches of knowledge, such wrong livelihood.*";
P_HTM[2768]="*Idampissa hoti sīlasampadāya.**This pertains to their accomplishment in ethics.*";
P_HTM[2769]="*Sa kho so, kassapa, bhikkhu evaṃ sīlasampanno na kutoci bhayaṃ samanupassati, yadidaṃ sīlasaṃvarato.**A mendicant thus accomplished in ethics sees no danger in any quarter in regards to their ethical restraint.*";
P_HTM[2770]="*Seyyathāpi, kassapa, rājā khattiyo muddhāvasitto nihatapaccāmitto na kutoci bhayaṃ samanupassati, yadidaṃ paccatthikato;**It’s like a king who has defeated his enemies. He sees no danger from his foes in any quarter.*";
P_HTM[2771]="*evameva kho, kassapa, bhikkhu evaṃ sīlasampanno na kutoci bhayaṃ samanupassati, yadidaṃ sīlasaṃvarato.**In the same way, a mendicant thus accomplished in ethics sees no danger in any quarter in regards to their ethical restraint.*";
P_HTM[2772]="*So iminā ariyena sīlakkhandhena samannāgato ajjhattaṃ anavajjasukhaṃ paṭisaṃvedeti.**When they have this entire spectrum of noble ethics, they experience a blameless happiness inside themselves.*";
P_HTM[2773]="*Evaṃ kho, kassapa, bhikkhu sīlasampanno hoti.**That’s how a mendicant is accomplished in ethics.*";
P_HTM[2774]="*Ayaṃ kho, kassapa, sīlasampadā … pe …**This, Kassapa, is that accomplishment in ethics. …*";
P_HTM[2775]="*paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**They enter and remain in the first absorption …*";
P_HTM[2776]="*Idampissa hoti cittasampadāya … pe …**This pertains to their accomplishment in mind. …*";
P_HTM[2777]="*dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ …**They enter and remain in the second absorption …*";
P_HTM[2778]="*tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ …**third absorption …*";
P_HTM[2779]="*catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**fourth absorption.*";
P_HTM[2780]="*Idampissa hoti cittasampadāya.**This pertains to their accomplishment in mind.*";
P_HTM[2781]="*Ayaṃ kho, kassapa, cittasampadā.**This, Kassapa, is that accomplishment in mind.*";
P_HTM[2782]="*So evaṃ samāhite citte … pe …**When their mind is immersed like this,*";
P_HTM[2783]="*ñāṇadassanāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti …**they extend and project it toward knowledge and vision …*";
P_HTM[2784]="*idampissa hoti paññāsampadāya … pe …**This pertains to their accomplishment in wisdom. …*";
P_HTM[2785]="*nāparaṃ itthattāyāti pajānāti.**They understand: ‘… there is no return to any state of existence.’*";
P_HTM[2786]="*Idampissa hoti paññāsampadāya.**This pertains to their accomplishment in wisdom.*";
P_HTM[2787]="*Ayaṃ kho, kassapa, paññāsampadā.**This, Kassapa, is that accomplishment in wisdom.*";
P_HTM[2788]="*Imāya ca, kassapa, sīlasampadāya cittasampadāya paññāsampadāya aññā sīlasampadā cittasampadā paññāsampadā uttaritarā vā paṇītatarā vā natthi.**And, Kassapa, there is no accomplishment in ethics, mind, and wisdom that is better or finer than this.*";
P_HTM[2789]="*6. Sīhanādakathā**6. The Lion’s Roar*";
P_HTM[2790]="*Santi, kassapa, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā sīlavādā.**There are, Kassapa, some ascetics and brahmins who teach ethics.*";
P_HTM[2791]="*Te anekapariyāyena sīlassa vaṇṇaṃ bhāsanti.**They praise ethical conduct in many ways.*";
P_HTM[2792]="*Yāvatā, kassapa, ariyaṃ paramaṃ sīlaṃ, nāhaṃ tattha attano samasamaṃ samanupassāmi, kuto bhiyyo.**But as far as the highest noble ethics goes, I don’t see anyone who’s my equal, still less my superior.*";
P_HTM[2793]="*Atha kho ahameva tattha bhiyyo, yadidaṃ adhisīlaṃ.**Rather, I am the one who is superior when it comes to the higher ethics.*";
P_HTM[2794]="*Santi, kassapa, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā tapojigucchāvādā.**There are, Kassapa, some ascetics and brahmins who teach mortification in disgust of sin.*";
P_HTM[2795]="*Te anekapariyāyena tapojigucchāya vaṇṇaṃ bhāsanti.**They praise mortification in disgust of sin in many ways.*";
P_HTM[2796]="*Yāvatā, kassapa, ariyā paramā tapojigucchā, nāhaṃ tattha attano samasamaṃ samanupassāmi, kuto bhiyyo.**But as far as the highest noble mortification in disgust of sin goes, I don’t see anyone who’s my equal, still less my superior.*";
P_HTM[2797]="*Atha kho ahameva tattha bhiyyo, yadidaṃ adhijegucchaṃ.**Rather, I am the one who is superior when it comes to the higher mortification in disgust of sin.*";
P_HTM[2798]="*Santi, kassapa, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā paññāvādā.**There are, Kassapa, some ascetics and brahmins who teach wisdom.*";
P_HTM[2799]="*Te anekapariyāyena paññāya vaṇṇaṃ bhāsanti.**They praise wisdom in many ways.*";
P_HTM[2800]="*Yāvatā, kassapa, ariyā paramā paññā, nāhaṃ tattha attano samasamaṃ samanupassāmi, kuto bhiyyo.**But as far as the highest noble wisdom goes, I don’t see anyone who’s my equal, still less my superior.*";
P_HTM[2801]="*Atha kho ahameva tattha bhiyyo, yadidaṃ adhipaññaṃ.**Rather, I am the one who is superior when it comes to the higher wisdom.*";
P_HTM[2802]="*Santi, kassapa, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā vimuttivādā.**There are, Kassapa, some ascetics and brahmins who teach freedom.*";
P_HTM[2803]="*Te anekapariyāyena vimuttiyā vaṇṇaṃ bhāsanti.**They praise freedom in many ways.*";
P_HTM[2804]="*Yāvatā, kassapa, ariyā paramā vimutti, nāhaṃ tattha attano samasamaṃ samanupassāmi, kuto bhiyyo.**But as far as the highest noble freedom goes, I don’t see anyone who’s my equal, still less my superior.*";
P_HTM[2805]="*Atha kho ahameva tattha bhiyyo, yadidaṃ adhivimutti.**Rather, I am the one who is superior when it comes to the higher freedom.*";
P_HTM[2806]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, kassapa, vijjati, yaṃ aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**It’s possible that wanderers who follow other paths might say:*";
P_HTM[2807]="*‘sīhanādaṃ kho samaṇo gotamo nadati, tañca kho suññāgāre nadati, no parisāsū’ti.**‘The ascetic Gotama only roars his lion’s roar in an empty hut, not in an assembly.’*";
P_HTM[2808]="*Te: ‘mā hevan’tissu vacanīyā.**They should be told, ‘Not so!’*";
P_HTM[2809]="*‘Sīhanādañca samaṇo gotamo nadati, parisāsu ca nadatī’ti evamassu, kassapa, vacanīyā.**What should be said is this: ‘The ascetic Gotama roars his lion’s roar, and he roars it in an assembly.’*";
P_HTM[2810]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, kassapa, vijjati, yaṃ aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**It’s possible that wanderers who follow other paths might say:*";
P_HTM[2811]="*‘sīhanādañca samaṇo gotamo nadati, parisāsu ca nadati, no ca kho visārado nadatī’ti.**‘The ascetic Gotama roars his lion’s roar, and he roars it in an assembly. But he doesn’t roar it boldly.’*";
P_HTM[2812]="*Te: ‘mā hevan’tissu vacanīyā.**They should be told, ‘Not so!’*";
P_HTM[2813]="*‘Sīhanādañca samaṇo gotamo nadati, parisāsu ca nadati, visārado ca nadatī’ti evamassu, kassapa, vacanīyā.**What should be said is this: ‘The ascetic Gotama roars his lion’s roar, he roars it in an assembly, and he roars it boldly.’*";
P_HTM[2814]="*Ṭhānaṃ kho panetaṃ, kassapa, vijjati, yaṃ aññatitthiyā paribbājakā evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**It’s possible that wanderers who follow other paths might say:*";
P_HTM[2815]="*‘sīhanādañca samaṇo gotamo nadati, parisāsu ca nadati, visārado ca nadati, no ca kho naṃ pañhaṃ pucchanti … pe …**‘The ascetic Gotama roars his lion’s roar, he roars it in an assembly, and he roars it boldly. But they don’t question him. …*";
P_HTM[2816]="*pañhañca naṃ pucchanti; no ca kho nesaṃ pañhaṃ puṭṭho byākaroti … pe …**Or he doesn’t answer their questions. …*";
P_HTM[2817]="*pañhañca nesaṃ puṭṭho byākaroti; no ca kho pañhassa veyyākaraṇena cittaṃ ārādheti … pe …**Or his answers are not satisfactory. …*";
P_HTM[2818]="*pañhassa ca veyyākaraṇena cittaṃ ārādheti; no ca kho sotabbaṃ maññanti … pe …**Or they don’t think him worth listening to. …*";
P_HTM[2819]="*sotabbañcassa maññanti; no ca kho sutvā pasīdanti … pe …**Or they’re not confident after listening. …*";
P_HTM[2820]="*sutvā cassa pasīdanti; no ca kho pasannākāraṃ karonti … pe …**Or they don’t show their confidence. …*";
P_HTM[2821]="*pasannākārañca karonti; no ca kho tathattāya paṭipajjanti … pe …**Or they don’t practice accordingly. …*";
P_HTM[2822]="*tathattāya ca paṭipajjanti; no ca kho paṭipannā ārādhentī’ti.**Or they don’t succeed in their practice.’*";
P_HTM[2823]="*Te: ‘mā hevan’tissu vacanīyā.**They should be told, ‘Not so!’*";
P_HTM[2824]="*‘Sīhanādañca samaṇo gotamo nadati, parisāsu ca nadati, visārado ca nadati, pañhañca naṃ pucchanti, pañhañca nesaṃ puṭṭho byākaroti, pañhassa ca veyyākaraṇena cittaṃ ārādheti, sotabbañcassa maññanti, sutvā cassa pasīdanti, pasannākārañca karonti, tathattāya ca paṭipajjanti, paṭipannā ca ārādhentī’ti evamassu, kassapa, vacanīyā.**What should be said is this: ‘The ascetic Gotama roars his lion’s roar; he roars it in an assembly; he roars it boldly; they question him; he answers their questions; his answers are satisfactory; they think him worth listening to; they’re confident after listening; they show their confidence; they practice accordingly; and they succeed in their practice.’*";
P_HTM[2825]="*7. Titthiyaparivāsakathā**7. The Probation For One Previously Ordained*";
P_HTM[2826]="*Ekamidāhaṃ, kassapa, samayaṃ rājagahe viharāmi gijjhakūṭe pabbate.**Kassapa, this one time I was staying near Rājagaha, on the Vulture’s Peak Mountain.*";
P_HTM[2827]="*Tatra maṃ aññataro tapabrahmacārī nigrodho nāma adhijegucche pañhaṃ apucchi.**There a certain practitioner of self-mortification named Nigrodha asked me about the higher mortification in disgust of sin.*";
P_HTM[2828]="*Tassāhaṃ adhijegucche pañhaṃ puṭṭho byākāsiṃ.**I answered his question.*";
P_HTM[2829]="*Byākate ca pana me attamano ahosi paraṃ viya mattāyā”ti.**He was extremely happy with my answer.”*";
P_HTM[2830]="*“Ko hi, bhante, bhagavato dhammaṃ sutvā na attamano assa paraṃ viya mattāya?**“Sir, who wouldn’t be extremely happy after hearing the Buddha’s teaching?*";
P_HTM[2831]="*Ahampi hi, bhante, bhagavato dhammaṃ sutvā attamano paraṃ viya mattāya.**For I too am extremely happy after hearing the Buddha’s teaching!*";
P_HTM[2832]="*Abhikkantaṃ, bhante, abhikkantaṃ, bhante.**Excellent, sir! Excellent!*";
P_HTM[2833]="*Seyyathāpi, bhante, nikkujjitaṃ vā ukkujjeyya, paṭicchannaṃ vā vivareyya, mūḷhassa vā maggaṃ ācikkheyya, andhakāre vā telapajjotaṃ dhāreyya: ‘cakkhumanto rūpāni dakkhantī’ti; evamevaṃ bhagavatā anekapariyāyena dhammo pakāsito.**As if he were righting the overturned, or revealing the hidden, or pointing out the path to the lost, or lighting a lamp in the dark so people with good eyes can see what’s there, so too the Buddha has made the teaching clear in many ways.*";
P_HTM[2834]="*Esāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavantaṃ saraṇaṃ gacchāmi, dhammañca bhikkhusaṅghañca.**I go for refuge to the Buddha, to the teaching, and to the mendicant Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[2835]="*Labheyyāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavato santike pabbajjaṃ, labheyyaṃ upasampadan”ti.**Sir, may I receive the going forth, the ordination in the Buddha’s presence?”*";
P_HTM[2836]="*“Yo kho, kassapa, aññatitthiyapubbo imasmiṃ dhammavinaye ākaṅkhati pabbajjaṃ, ākaṅkhati upasampadaṃ, so cattāro māse parivasati, catunnaṃ māsānaṃ accayena āraddhacittā bhikkhū pabbājenti, upasampādenti bhikkhubhāvāya.**“Kassapa, if someone formerly ordained in another sect wishes to take the going forth, the ordination in this teaching and training, they must spend four months on probation. When four months have passed, if the mendicants are satisfied, they’ll give the going forth, the ordination into monkhood.*";
P_HTM[2837]="*Api ca mettha puggalavemattatā viditā”ti.**However, I have recognized individual differences in this matter.”*";
P_HTM[2838]="*“Sace, bhante, aññatitthiyapubbā imasmiṃ dhammavinaye ākaṅkhanti pabbajjaṃ, ākaṅkhanti upasampadaṃ, cattāro māse parivasanti, catunnaṃ māsānaṃ accayena āraddhacittā bhikkhū pabbājenti, upasampādenti bhikkhubhāvāya. Ahaṃ cattāri vassāni parivasissāmi, catunnaṃ vassānaṃ accayena āraddhacittā bhikkhū pabbājentu, upasampādentu bhikkhubhāvāyā”ti.**“Sir, if four months probation are required in such a case, I’ll spend four years on probation. When four years have passed, if the mendicants are satisfied, let them give me the going forth, the ordination into monkhood.”*";
P_HTM[2839]="*Alattha kho acelo kassapo bhagavato santike pabbajjaṃ, alattha upasampadaṃ.**And the naked ascetic Kassapa received the going forth, the ordination in the Buddha’s presence.*";
P_HTM[2840]="*Acirūpasampanno kho panāyasmā kassapo eko vūpakaṭṭho appamatto ātāpī pahitatto viharanto na cirasseva—yassatthāya kulaputtā sammadeva agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajanti, tadanuttaraṃ—brahmacariyapariyosānaṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja vihāsi.**Not long after his ordination, Venerable Kassapa, living alone, withdrawn, diligent, keen, and resolute, soon realized the supreme end of the spiritual path in this very life. He lived having achieved with his own insight the goal for which gentlemen rightly go forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[2841]="*“Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā”ti abbhaññāsi.**He understood: “Rebirth is ended; the spiritual journey has been completed; what had to be done has been done; there is no return to any state of existence.”*";
P_HTM[2842]="*Aññataro kho panāyasmā kassapo arahataṃ ahosīti.**And Venerable Kassapa became one of the perfected.*";
P_HTM[2843]="*Mahāsīhanādasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ aṭṭhamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[2844]="*09. Poṭṭhapādasutta  - With Poṭṭhapāda * **";
P_HTM[2845]="*1. Poṭṭhapādaparibbājakavatthu**1. On the Wanderer Poṭṭhapāda*";
P_HTM[2846]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[2847]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery.*";
P_HTM[2848]="*Tena kho pana samayena poṭṭhapādo paribbājako samayappavādake tindukācīre ekasālake mallikāya ārāme paṭivasati mahatiyā paribbājakaparisāya saddhiṃ tiṃsamattehi paribbājakasatehi.**Now at that time the wanderer Poṭṭhapāda was residing together with three hundred wanderers in Mallikā’s single-halled monastery for group debates, set among the flaking pale-moon ebony trees.*";
P_HTM[2849]="*Atha kho bhagavā pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya sāvatthiṃ piṇḍāya pāvisi.**Then the Buddha robed up in the morning and, taking his bowl and robe, entered Sāvatthī for alms.*";
P_HTM[2850]="*Atha kho bhagavato etadahosi:**Then it occurred to him,*";
P_HTM[2851]="*“atippago kho tāva sāvatthiyaṃ piṇḍāya carituṃ.**“It’s too early to wander for alms in Sāvatthī.*";
P_HTM[2852]="*Yannūnāhaṃ yena samayappavādako tindukācīro ekasālako mallikāya ārāmo, yena poṭṭhapādo paribbājako tenupasaṅkameyyan”ti.**Why don’t I go to Mallikā’s monastery to visit the wanderer Poṭṭhapāda?”*";
P_HTM[2853]="*Atha kho bhagavā yena samayappavādako tindukācīro ekasālako mallikāya ārāmo tenupasaṅkami.**So that’s what he did.*";
P_HTM[2854]="*Tena kho pana samayena poṭṭhapādo paribbājako mahatiyā paribbājakaparisāya saddhiṃ nisinno hoti unnādiniyā uccāsaddamahāsaddāya anekavihitaṃ tiracchānakathaṃ kathentiyā.**Now at that time, Poṭṭhapāda was sitting together with a large assembly of wanderers making an uproar, a dreadful racket. They engaged in all kinds of unworthy talk, such as*";
P_HTM[2855]="*Seyyathidaṃ—rājakathaṃ corakathaṃ mahāmattakathaṃ senākathaṃ bhayakathaṃ yuddhakathaṃ annakathaṃ pānakathaṃ vatthakathaṃ sayanakathaṃ mālākathaṃ gandhakathaṃ ñātikathaṃ yānakathaṃ gāmakathaṃ nigamakathaṃ nagarakathaṃ janapadakathaṃ itthikathaṃ sūrakathaṃ visikhākathaṃ kumbhaṭṭhānakathaṃ pubbapetakathaṃ nānattakathaṃ lokakkhāyikaṃ samuddakkhāyikaṃ itibhavābhavakathaṃ iti vā.**talk about kings, bandits, and ministers; talk about armies, threats, and wars; talk about food, drink, clothes, and beds; talk about garlands and fragrances; talk about family, vehicles, villages, towns, cities, and countries; talk about women and heroes; street talk and well talk; talk about the departed; motley talk; tales of land and sea; and talk about being reborn in this or that state of existence.*";
P_HTM[2856]="*Addasā kho poṭṭhapādo paribbājako bhagavantaṃ dūratova āgacchantaṃ;**Poṭṭhapāda saw the Buddha coming off in the distance,*";
P_HTM[2857]="*disvāna sakaṃ parisaṃ saṇṭhapesi:**and hushed his own assembly,*";
P_HTM[2858]="*“appasaddā bhonto hontu, mā bhonto saddamakattha.**“Be quiet, good sirs, don’t make a sound.*";
P_HTM[2859]="*Ayaṃ samaṇo gotamo āgacchati.**Here comes the ascetic Gotama.*";
P_HTM[2860]="*Appasaddakāmo kho so āyasmā appasaddassa vaṇṇavādī.**The venerable likes quiet and praises quiet.*";
P_HTM[2861]="*Appeva nāma appasaddaṃ parisaṃ viditvā upasaṅkamitabbaṃ maññeyyā”ti.**Hopefully if he sees that our assembly is quiet he’ll see fit to approach.”*";
P_HTM[2862]="*Evaṃ vutte, te paribbājakā tuṇhī ahesuṃ.**Then those wanderers fell silent.*";
P_HTM[2863]="*Atha kho bhagavā yena poṭṭhapādo paribbājako tenupasaṅkami.**Then the Buddha approached Poṭṭhapāda,*";
P_HTM[2864]="*Atha kho poṭṭhapādo paribbājako bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**who said to him,*";
P_HTM[2865]="*“etu kho, bhante, bhagavā.**“Come, Blessed One!*";
P_HTM[2866]="*Svāgataṃ, bhante, bhagavato.**Welcome, Blessed One!*";
P_HTM[2867]="*Cirassaṃ kho, bhante, bhagavā imaṃ pariyāyamakāsi, yadidaṃ idhāgamanāya.**It’s been a long time since you took the opportunity to come here.*";
P_HTM[2868]="*Nisīdatu, bhante, bhagavā, idaṃ āsanaṃ paññattan”ti.**Please, sir, sit down, this seat is ready.”*";
P_HTM[2869]="*Nisīdi bhagavā paññatte āsane.**The Buddha sat on the seat spread out,*";
P_HTM[2870]="*Poṭṭhapādopi kho paribbājako aññataraṃ nīcaṃ āsanaṃ gahetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi.**while Poṭṭhapāda took a low seat and sat to one side.*";
P_HTM[2871]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho poṭṭhapādaṃ paribbājakaṃ bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said to him,*";
P_HTM[2872]="*“kāya nuttha, poṭṭhapāda, etarahi kathāya sannisinnā, kā ca pana vo antarākathā vippakatā”ti?**“Poṭṭhapāda, what were you sitting talking about just now? What conversation was unfinished?”*";
P_HTM[2873]="*1.1. Abhisaññānirodhakathā**1.1. On the Cessation of Perception*";
P_HTM[2874]="*Evaṃ vutte, poṭṭhapādo paribbājako bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, the wanderer Poṭṭhapāda said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[2875]="*“tiṭṭhatesā, bhante, kathā, yāya mayaṃ etarahi kathāya sannisinnā.**“Sir, leave aside what we were sitting talking about just now.*";
P_HTM[2876]="*Nesā, bhante, kathā bhagavato dullabhā bhavissati pacchāpi savanāya.**It won’t be hard for you to hear about that later.*";
P_HTM[2877]="*Purimāni, bhante, divasāni purimatarāni, nānātitthiyānaṃ samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ kotūhalasālāya sannisinnānaṃ sannipatitānaṃ abhisaññānirodhe kathā udapādi:**Sir, a few days ago several ascetics and brahmins who follow various other paths were sitting together at the debating hall, and this discussion came up among them:*";
P_HTM[2878]="*‘kathaṃ nu kho, bho, abhisaññānirodho hotī’ti?**‘How does the cessation of perception happen?’*";
P_HTM[2879]="*Tatrekacce evamāhaṃsu:**Some of them said:*";
P_HTM[2880]="*‘ahetū appaccayā purisassa saññā uppajjantipi nirujjhantipi.**‘A person’s perceptions arise and cease without cause or reason.*";
P_HTM[2881]="*Yasmiṃ samaye uppajjanti, saññī tasmiṃ samaye hoti.**When they arise, you become percipient.*";
P_HTM[2882]="*Yasmiṃ samaye nirujjhanti, asaññī tasmiṃ samaye hotī’ti.**When they cease, you become non-percipient.’*";
P_HTM[2883]="*Ittheke abhisaññānirodhaṃ paññapenti. (1)**That’s how some describe the cessation of perception.*";
P_HTM[2884]="*Tamañño evamāha:**But someone else says:*";
P_HTM[2885]="*‘na kho pana metaṃ, bho, evaṃ bhavissati.**‘That’s not how it is, gentlemen !*";
P_HTM[2886]="*Saññā hi, bho, purisassa attā.**Perception is a person’s self,*";
P_HTM[2887]="*Sā ca kho upetipi apetipi.* **";
P_HTM[2888]="*Yasmiṃ samaye upeti, saññī tasmiṃ samaye hoti.**When it enters, you become percipient.*";
P_HTM[2889]="*Yasmiṃ samaye apeti, asaññī tasmiṃ samaye hotī’ti.**When it departs, you become non-percipient.’*";
P_HTM[2890]="*Ittheke abhisaññānirodhaṃ paññapenti. (2)**That’s how some describe the cessation of perception.*";
P_HTM[2891]="*Tamañño evamāha:**But someone else says:*";
P_HTM[2892]="*‘na kho pana metaṃ, bho, evaṃ bhavissati.**‘That’s not how it is, gentlemen !*";
P_HTM[2893]="*Santi hi, bho, samaṇabrāhmaṇā mahiddhikā mahānubhāvā.**There are ascetics and brahmins of great power and might.*";
P_HTM[2894]="*Te imassa purisassa saññaṃ upakaḍḍhantipi apakaḍḍhantipi.**They insert and extract a person’s perception.*";
P_HTM[2895]="*Yasmiṃ samaye upakaḍḍhanti, saññī tasmiṃ samaye hoti.**When they insert it, you become percipient.*";
P_HTM[2896]="*Yasmiṃ samaye apakaḍḍhanti, asaññī tasmiṃ samaye hotī’ti.**When they extract it, you become non-percipient.’*";
P_HTM[2897]="*Ittheke abhisaññānirodhaṃ paññapenti. (3)**That’s how some describe the cessation of perception.*";
P_HTM[2898]="*Tamañño evamāha:**But someone else says:*";
P_HTM[2899]="*‘na kho pana metaṃ, bho, evaṃ bhavissati.**‘That’s not how it is, gentlemen !*";
P_HTM[2900]="*Santi hi, bho, devatā mahiddhikā mahānubhāvā.**There are deities of great power and might.*";
P_HTM[2901]="*Tā imassa purisassa saññaṃ upakaḍḍhantipi apakaḍḍhantipi.**They insert and extract a person’s perception.*";
P_HTM[2902]="*Yasmiṃ samaye upakaḍḍhanti, saññī tasmiṃ samaye hoti.**When they insert it, you become percipient.*";
P_HTM[2903]="*Yasmiṃ samaye apakaḍḍhanti, asaññī tasmiṃ samaye hotī’ti.**When they extract it, you become non-percipient.’*";
P_HTM[2904]="*Ittheke abhisaññānirodhaṃ paññapenti. (4)**That’s how some describe the cessation of perception.*";
P_HTM[2905]="*Tassa mayhaṃ, bhante, bhagavantaṃyeva ārabbha sati udapādi:**That reminded me of the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[2906]="*‘aho nūna bhagavā, aho nūna sugato, yo imesaṃ dhammānaṃ sukusalo’ti.**‘Surely it must be the Blessed One, the Holy One who is so skilled in such matters.’*";
P_HTM[2907]="*Bhagavā, bhante, kusalo, bhagavā pakataññū abhisaññānirodhassa.**The Buddha is skilled and well-versed in the cessation of perception.*";
P_HTM[2908]="*Kathaṃ nu kho, bhante, abhisaññānirodho hotī”ti?**How does the cessation of perception happen?”*";
P_HTM[2909]="*1.2. Sahetukasaññuppādanirodhakathā**1.2. Perception Arises With a Cause*";
P_HTM[2910]="*“Tatra, poṭṭhapāda, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā evamāhaṃsu:**“Regarding this, Poṭṭhapāda, those ascetics and brahmins who say that*";
P_HTM[2911]="*‘ahetū appaccayā purisassa saññā uppajjantipi nirujjhantipī’ti, āditova tesaṃ aparaddhaṃ.**a person’s perceptions arise and cease without cause or reason are wrong from the start.*";
P_HTM[2912]="*Taṃ kissa hetu?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[2913]="*Sahetū hi, poṭṭhapāda, sappaccayā purisassa saññā uppajjantipi nirujjhantipi.**Because a person’s perceptions arise and cease with cause and reason.*";
P_HTM[2914]="*Sikkhā ekā saññā uppajjati, sikkhā ekā saññā nirujjhati.**With training, certain perceptions arise and certain perceptions cease.*";
P_HTM[2915]="*Kā ca sikkhā”ti? Bhagavā avoca.**And what is that training?” said the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[2916]="*“Idha, poṭṭhapāda, tathāgato loke uppajjati arahaṃ, sammāsambuddho … pe …**“It’s when a Realized One arises in the world, perfected, a fully awakened Buddha …*";
P_HTM[2917]="*Evaṃ kho, poṭṭhapāda, bhikkhu sīlasampanno hoti … pe …**That’s how a mendicant is accomplished in ethics. …*";
P_HTM[2918]="*tassime pañcanīvaraṇe pahīne attani samanupassato pāmojjaṃ jāyati, pamuditassa pīti jāyati, pītimanassa kāyo passambhati, passaddhakāyo sukhaṃ vedeti, sukhino cittaṃ samādhiyati.**Seeing that the hindrances have been given up in them, joy springs up. Being joyful, rapture springs up. When the mind is full of rapture, the body becomes tranquil. When the body is tranquil, they feel bliss. And when blissful, the mind becomes immersed.*";
P_HTM[2919]="*So vivicceva kāmehi, vivicca akusalehi dhammehi, savitakkaṃ savicāraṃ vivekajaṃ pītisukhaṃ paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, they enter and remain in the first absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of seclusion, while placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[2920]="*Tassa yā purimā kāmasaññā, sā nirujjhati.**The sensual perception that they had previously ceases.*";
P_HTM[2921]="*Vivekajapītisukhasukhumasaccasaññā tasmiṃ samaye hoti, vivekajapītisukhasukhumasaccasaññīyeva tasmiṃ samaye hoti.**At that time they have a subtle and true perception of the rapture and bliss born of seclusion.*";
P_HTM[2922]="*Evampi sikkhā ekā saññā uppajjati, sikkhā ekā saññā nirujjhati.**That’s how, with training, certain perceptions arise and certain perceptions cease.*";
P_HTM[2923]="*Ayaṃ sikkhā”ti bhagavā avoca.**And this is that training,” said the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[2924]="*“Puna caparaṃ, poṭṭhapāda, bhikkhu vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā ajjhattaṃ sampasādanaṃ cetaso ekodibhāvaṃ avitakkaṃ avicāraṃ samādhijaṃ pītisukhaṃ dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**“Furthermore, as the placing of the mind and keeping it connected are stilled, a mendicant enters and remains in the second absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of immersion, with internal clarity and confidence, and unified mind, without placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[2925]="*Tassa yā purimā vivekajapītisukhasukhumasaccasaññā, sā nirujjhati.**The subtle and true perception of the rapture and bliss born of seclusion that they had previously ceases.*";
P_HTM[2926]="*Samādhijapītisukhasukhumasaccasaññā tasmiṃ samaye hoti, samādhijapītisukhasukhumasaccasaññīyeva tasmiṃ samaye hoti.**At that time they have a subtle and true perception of the rapture and bliss born of immersion.*";
P_HTM[2927]="*Evampi sikkhā ekā saññā uppajjati, sikkhā ekā saññā nirujjhati.**That’s how, with training, certain perceptions arise and certain perceptions cease.*";
P_HTM[2928]="*Ayampi sikkhā”ti bhagavā avoca.**And this is that training,” said the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[2929]="*“Puna caparaṃ, poṭṭhapāda, bhikkhu pītiyā ca virāgā upekkhako ca viharati sato ca sampajāno, sukhañca kāyena paṭisaṃvedeti, yaṃ taṃ ariyā ācikkhanti: ‘upekkhako satimā sukhavihārī’ti, tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**“Furthermore, with the fading away of rapture, a mendicant enters and remains in the third absorption, where they meditate with equanimity, mindful and aware, personally experiencing the bliss of which the noble ones declare, ‘Equanimous and mindful, one meditates in bliss.’*";
P_HTM[2930]="*Tassa yā purimā samādhijapītisukhasukhumasaccasaññā, sā nirujjhati.**The subtle and true perception of the rapture and bliss born of immersion that they had previously ceases.*";
P_HTM[2931]="*Upekkhāsukhasukhumasaccasaññā tasmiṃ samaye hoti, upekkhāsukhasukhumasaccasaññīyeva tasmiṃ samaye hoti.**At that time they have a subtle and true perception of equanimous bliss.*";
P_HTM[2932]="*Evampi sikkhā ekā saññā uppajjati, sikkhā ekā saññā nirujjhati.**That’s how, with training, certain perceptions arise and certain perceptions cease.*";
P_HTM[2933]="*Ayampi sikkhā”ti bhagavā avoca.**And this is that training,” said the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[2934]="*“Puna caparaṃ, poṭṭhapāda, bhikkhu sukhassa ca pahānā dukkhassa ca pahānā pubbeva somanassadomanassānaṃ atthaṅgamā adukkhamasukhaṃ upekkhāsatipārisuddhiṃ catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**“Furthermore, giving up pleasure and pain, and ending former happiness and sadness, a mendicant enters and remains in the fourth absorption, without pleasure or pain, with pure equanimity and mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[2935]="*Tassa yā purimā upekkhāsukhasukhumasaccasaññā, sā nirujjhati.**The subtle and true perception of equanimous bliss that they had previously ceases.*";
P_HTM[2936]="*Adukkhamasukhasukhumasaccasaññā tasmiṃ samaye hoti, adukkhamasukhasukhumasaccasaññīyeva tasmiṃ samaye hoti.**At that time they have a subtle and true perception of neutral feeling.*";
P_HTM[2937]="*Evampi sikkhā ekā saññā uppajjati, sikkhā ekā saññā nirujjhati.**That’s how, with training, certain perceptions arise and certain perceptions cease.*";
P_HTM[2938]="*Ayampi sikkhā”ti bhagavā avoca.**And this is that training,” said the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[2939]="*“Puna caparaṃ, poṭṭhapāda, bhikkhu sabbaso rūpasaññānaṃ samatikkamā paṭighasaññānaṃ atthaṅgamā nānattasaññānaṃ amanasikārā ‘ananto ākāso’ti ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**“Furthermore, a mendicant, going totally beyond perceptions of form, with the ending of perceptions of impingement, not focusing on perceptions of diversity, aware that ‘space is infinite’, enters and remains in the dimension of infinite space.*";
P_HTM[2940]="*Tassa yā purimā rūpasaññā, sā nirujjhati.**The perception of luminous form that they had previously ceases.*";
P_HTM[2941]="*Ākāsānañcāyatanasukhumasaccasaññā tasmiṃ samaye hoti, ākāsānañcāyatanasukhumasaccasaññīyeva tasmiṃ samaye hoti.**At that time they have a subtle and true perception of the dimension of infinite space.*";
P_HTM[2942]="*Evampi sikkhā ekā saññā uppajjati, sikkhā ekā saññā nirujjhati.**That’s how, with training, certain perceptions arise and certain perceptions cease.*";
P_HTM[2943]="*Ayampi sikkhā”ti bhagavā avoca.**And this is that training,” said the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[2944]="*“Puna caparaṃ, poṭṭhapāda, bhikkhu sabbaso ākāsānañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma ‘anantaṃ viññāṇan’ti viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**“Furthermore, a mendicant, going totally beyond the dimension of infinite space, aware that ‘consciousness is infinite’, enters and remains in the dimension of infinite consciousness.*";
P_HTM[2945]="*Tassa yā purimā ākāsānañcāyatanasukhumasaccasaññā, sā nirujjhati.**The subtle and true perception of the dimension of infinite space that they had previously ceases.*";
P_HTM[2946]="*Viññāṇañcāyatanasukhumasaccasaññā tasmiṃ samaye hoti, viññāṇañcāyatanasukhumasaccasaññīyeva tasmiṃ samaye hoti.**At that time they have a subtle and true perception of the dimension of infinite consciousness.*";
P_HTM[2947]="*Evampi sikkhā ekā saññā uppajjati, sikkhā ekā saññā nirujjhati.**That’s how, with training, certain perceptions arise and certain perceptions cease.*";
P_HTM[2948]="*Ayampi sikkhā”ti bhagavā avoca.**And this is that training,” said the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[2949]="*“Puna caparaṃ, poṭṭhapāda, bhikkhu sabbaso viññāṇañcāyatanaṃ samatikkamma ‘natthi kiñcī’ti ākiñcaññāyatanaṃ upasampajja viharati.**“Furthermore, a mendicant, going totally beyond the dimension of infinite consciousness, aware that ‘there is nothing at all’, enters and remains in the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[2950]="*Tassa yā purimā viññāṇañcāyatanasukhumasaccasaññā, sā nirujjhati.**The subtle and true perception of the dimension of infinite consciousness that they had previously ceases.*";
P_HTM[2951]="*Ākiñcaññāyatanasukhumasaccasaññā tasmiṃ samaye hoti, ākiñcaññāyatanasukhumasaccasaññīyeva tasmiṃ samaye hoti.**At that time they have a subtle and true perception of the dimension of nothingness.*";
P_HTM[2952]="*Evampi sikkhā ekā saññā uppajjati, sikkhā ekā saññā nirujjhati.**That’s how, with training, certain perceptions arise and certain perceptions cease.*";
P_HTM[2953]="*Ayampi sikkhā”ti bhagavā avoca.**And this is that training,” said the Buddha.*";
P_HTM[2954]="*“Yato kho, poṭṭhapāda, bhikkhu idha sakasaññī hoti, so tato amutra tato amutra anupubbena saññaggaṃ phusati.**“Poṭṭhapāda, from the time a mendicant here takes responsibility for their own perception, they proceed from one stage to the next, gradually reaching the peak of perception.*";
P_HTM[2955]="*Tassa saññagge ṭhitassa evaṃ hoti:**Standing on the peak of perception they think,*";
P_HTM[2956]="*‘cetayamānassa me pāpiyo, acetayamānassa me seyyo.**‘Intentionality is bad for me, it’s better to be free of it.*";
P_HTM[2957]="*Ahañceva kho pana ceteyyaṃ, abhisaṅkhareyyaṃ, imā ca me saññā nirujjheyyuṃ, aññā ca oḷārikā saññā uppajjeyyuṃ;**For if I were to intend and choose, these perceptions would cease in me, and other coarser perceptions would arise.*";
P_HTM[2958]="*yannūnāhaṃ na ceva ceteyyaṃ na ca abhisaṅkhareyyan’ti.**Why don’t I neither make a choice nor form an intention?’*";
P_HTM[2959]="*So na ceva ceteti, na ca abhisaṅkharoti.**They neither make a choice nor form an intention.*";
P_HTM[2960]="*Tassa acetayato anabhisaṅkharoto tā ceva saññā nirujjhanti, aññā ca oḷārikā saññā na uppajjanti.**Those perceptions cease in them, and other coarser perceptions don’t arise.*";
P_HTM[2961]="*So nirodhaṃ phusati.**They touch cessation.*";
P_HTM[2962]="*Evaṃ kho, poṭṭhapāda, anupubbābhisaññānirodhasampajānasamāpatti hoti.**And that, Poṭṭhapāda, is how the gradual cessation of perception is attained with awareness.*";
P_HTM[2963]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, poṭṭhapāda,**What do you think, Poṭṭhapāda?*";
P_HTM[2964]="*api nu te ito pubbe evarūpā anupubbābhisaññānirodhasampajānasamāpatti sutapubbā”ti?**Have you ever heard of this before?”*";
P_HTM[2965]="*“No hetaṃ, bhante.**“No, sir.*";
P_HTM[2966]="*Evaṃ kho ahaṃ, bhante, bhagavato bhāsitaṃ ājānāmi:**This is how I understand what the Buddha said:*";
P_HTM[2967]="*‘yato kho, poṭṭhapāda, bhikkhu idha sakasaññī hoti, so tato amutra tato amutra anupubbena saññaggaṃ phusati,**‘From the time a mendicant here takes responsibility for their own perception, they proceed from one stage to the next, gradually reaching the peak of perception.*";
P_HTM[2968]="*tassa saññagge ṭhitassa evaṃ hoti:**Standing on the peak of perception they think,*";
P_HTM[2969]="*“cetayamānassa me pāpiyo, acetayamānassa me seyyo.**“Intentionality is bad for me, it’s better to be free of it.*";
P_HTM[2970]="*Ahañceva kho pana ceteyyaṃ abhisaṅkhareyyaṃ, imā ca me saññā nirujjheyyuṃ, aññā ca oḷārikā saññā uppajjeyyuṃ;**For if I were to intend and choose, these perceptions would cease in me, and other coarser perceptions would arise.*";
P_HTM[2971]="*yannūnāhaṃ na ceva ceteyyaṃ, na ca abhisaṅkhareyyan”ti.**Why don’t I neither make a choice nor form an intention?”*";
P_HTM[2972]="*So na ceva ceteti, na cābhisaṅkharoti, tassa acetayato anabhisaṅkharoto tā ceva saññā nirujjhanti, aññā ca oḷārikā saññā na uppajjanti.**Those perceptions cease in them, and other coarser perceptions don’t arise.*";
P_HTM[2973]="*So nirodhaṃ phusati.**They touch cessation.*";
P_HTM[2974]="*Evaṃ kho, poṭṭhapāda, anupubbābhisaññānirodhasampajānasamāpatti hotī’”ti.**And that is how the gradual cessation of perception is attained with awareness.’”*";
P_HTM[2975]="*“Evaṃ, poṭṭhapādā”ti.**“That’s right, Poṭṭhapāda.”*";
P_HTM[2976]="*“Ekaññeva nu kho, bhante, bhagavā saññaggaṃ paññapeti, udāhu puthūpi saññagge paññapetī”ti?**“Does the Buddha describe just one peak of perception, or many?”*";
P_HTM[2977]="*“Ekampi kho ahaṃ, poṭṭhapāda, saññaggaṃ paññapemi, puthūpi saññagge paññapemī”ti.**“I describe the peak of perception as both one and many.”*";
P_HTM[2978]="*“Yathā kathaṃ pana, bhante, bhagavā ekampi saññaggaṃ paññapeti, puthūpi saññagge paññapetī”ti?**“But sir, how do you describe it as one peak and as many?”*";
P_HTM[2979]="*“Yathā yathā kho, poṭṭhapāda, nirodhaṃ phusati tathā tathāhaṃ saññaggaṃ paññapemi.**“I describe the peak of perception according to the specific manner in which one touches cessation.*";
P_HTM[2980]="*Evaṃ kho ahaṃ, poṭṭhapāda, ekampi saññaggaṃ paññapemi, puthūpi saññagge paññapemī”ti.**That’s how I describe the peak of perception as both one and many.”*";
P_HTM[2981]="*“Saññā nu kho, bhante, paṭhamaṃ uppajjati, pacchā ñāṇaṃ, udāhu ñāṇaṃ paṭhamaṃ uppajjati, pacchā saññā, udāhu saññā ca ñāṇañca apubbaṃ acarimaṃ uppajjantī”ti?**“But sir, does perception arise first and knowledge afterwards? Or does knowledge arise first and perception afterwards? Or do they both arise at the same time?”*";
P_HTM[2982]="*“Saññā kho, poṭṭhapāda, paṭhamaṃ uppajjati, pacchā ñāṇaṃ, saññuppādā ca pana ñāṇuppādo hoti.**“Perception arises first and knowledge afterwards. The arising of perception leads to the arising of knowledge.*";
P_HTM[2983]="*So evaṃ pajānāti:**They understand,*";
P_HTM[2984]="*‘idappaccayā kira me ñāṇaṃ udapādī’ti.**‘My knowledge arose from a specific condition.’*";
P_HTM[2985]="*Iminā kho etaṃ, poṭṭhapāda, pariyāyena veditabbaṃ—**That is a way to understand how*";
P_HTM[2986]="*yathā saññā paṭhamaṃ uppajjati, pacchā ñāṇaṃ, saññuppādā ca pana ñāṇuppādo hotī”ti.**perception arises first and knowledge afterwards; that the arising of perception leads to the arising of knowledge.”*";
P_HTM[2987]="*1.3. Saññāattakathā**1.3. Perception and the Self*";
P_HTM[2988]="*“Saññā nu kho, bhante, purisassa attā, udāhu aññā saññā añño attā”ti?**“Sir, is perception a person’s self, or are perception and self different things?”*";
P_HTM[2989]="*“Kaṃ pana tvaṃ, poṭṭhapāda, attānaṃ paccesī”ti?**“But Poṭṭhapāda, do you believe in a self?”*";
P_HTM[2990]="*“Oḷārikaṃ kho ahaṃ, bhante, attānaṃ paccemi rūpiṃ cātumahābhūtikaṃ kabaḷīkārāhārabhakkhan”ti.**“I believe in a substantial self, sir, which is physical, made up of the four primary elements, and consumes solid food.”*";
P_HTM[2991]="*“Oḷāriko ca hi te, poṭṭhapāda, attā abhavissa rūpī cātumahābhūtiko kabaḷīkārāhārabhakkho. Evaṃ santaṃ kho te, poṭṭhapāda, aññāva saññā bhavissati añño attā.**“Suppose there were such a substantial self, Poṭṭhapāda. In that case, perception would be one thing, the self another.*";
P_HTM[2992]="*Tadamināpetaṃ, poṭṭhapāda, pariyāyena veditabbaṃ yathā aññāva saññā bhavissati añño attā.**Here is another way to understand how perception and self are different things.*";
P_HTM[2993]="*Tiṭṭhateva sāyaṃ, poṭṭhapāda, oḷāriko attā rūpī cātumahābhūtiko kabaḷīkārāhārabhakkho, atha imassa purisassa aññā ca saññā uppajjanti, aññā ca saññā nirujjhanti.**So long as that substantial self remains, still some perceptions arise in a person and others cease.*";
P_HTM[2994]="*Iminā kho etaṃ, poṭṭhapāda, pariyāyena veditabbaṃ yathā aññāva saññā bhavissati añño attā”ti.**That is a way to understand how perception and self are different things.”*";
P_HTM[2995]="*“Manomayaṃ kho ahaṃ, bhante, attānaṃ paccemi sabbaṅgapaccaṅgiṃ ahīnindriyan”ti.**“Sir, I believe in a mind-made self which is complete in all its various parts, not deficient in any faculty.”*";
P_HTM[2996]="*“Manomayo ca hi te, poṭṭhapāda, attā abhavissa sabbaṅgapaccaṅgī ahīnindriyo, evaṃ santampi kho te, poṭṭhapāda, aññāva saññā bhavissati añño attā.**“Suppose there were such a mind-made self, Poṭṭhapāda. In that case, perception would be one thing, the self another.*";
P_HTM[2997]="*Tadamināpetaṃ, poṭṭhapāda, pariyāyena veditabbaṃ yathā aññāva saññā bhavissati añño attā.**Here is another way to understand how perception and self are different things.*";
P_HTM[2998]="*Tiṭṭhateva sāyaṃ, poṭṭhapāda, manomayo attā sabbaṅgapaccaṅgī ahīnindriyo, atha imassa purisassa aññā ca saññā uppajjanti, aññā ca saññā nirujjhanti.**So long as that mind-made self remains, still some perceptions arise in a person and others cease.*";
P_HTM[2999]="*Imināpi kho etaṃ, poṭṭhapāda, pariyāyena veditabbaṃ yathā aññāva saññā bhavissati añño attā”ti.**That too is a way to understand how perception and self are different things.”*";
P_HTM[3000]="*“Arūpiṃ kho ahaṃ, bhante, attānaṃ paccemi saññāmayan”ti.**“Sir, I believe in a non-physical self which is made of perception.”*";
P_HTM[3001]="*“Arūpī ca hi te, poṭṭhapāda, attā abhavissa saññāmayo, evaṃ santampi kho te, poṭṭhapāda, aññāva saññā bhavissati añño attā.**“Suppose there were such a non-physical self, Poṭṭhapāda. In that case, perception would be one thing, the self another.*";
P_HTM[3002]="*Tadamināpetaṃ, poṭṭhapāda, pariyāyena veditabbaṃ yathā aññāva saññā bhavissati añño attā.**Here is another way to understand how perception and self are different things.*";
P_HTM[3003]="*Tiṭṭhateva sāyaṃ, poṭṭhapāda, arūpī attā saññāmayo, atha imassa purisassa aññā ca saññā uppajjanti, aññā ca saññā nirujjhanti.**So long as that non-physical self remains, still some perceptions arise in a person and others cease.*";
P_HTM[3004]="*Imināpi kho etaṃ, poṭṭhapāda, pariyāyena veditabbaṃ yathā aññāva saññā bhavissati añño attā”ti.**That too is a way to understand how perception and self are different things.”*";
P_HTM[3005]="*“Sakkā panetaṃ, bhante, mayā ñātuṃ:**“But, sir, am I able to know whether*";
P_HTM[3006]="*‘saññā purisassa attā’ti vā ‘aññāva saññā añño attā’ti vā”ti?**perception is a person’s self, or whether perception and self are different things?”*";
P_HTM[3007]="*“Dujjānaṃ kho etaṃ, poṭṭhapāda, tayā aññadiṭṭhikena aññakhantikena aññarucikena aññatrāyogena aññatrācariyakena:**“It’s hard for you to understand this, since you have a different view, creed, preference, practice, and tradition.”*";
P_HTM[3008]="*‘saññā purisassa attā’ti vā, ‘aññāva saññā añño attāti’ vā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3009]="*“Sacetaṃ, bhante, mayā dujjānaṃ aññadiṭṭhikena aññakhantikena aññarucikena aññatrāyogena aññatrācariyakena:**“Well, if that’s the case, sir,*";
P_HTM[3010]="*‘saññā purisassa attā’ti vā, ‘aññāva saññā añño attā’ti vā;* **";
P_HTM[3011]="*kiṃ pana, bhante, ‘sassato loko, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’”ti?**then is this right: ‘The cosmos is eternal. This is the only truth, anything else is wrong’?”*";
P_HTM[3012]="*“Abyākataṃ kho etaṃ, poṭṭhapāda, mayā:**“This has not been declared by me, Poṭṭhapāda.”*";
P_HTM[3013]="*‘sassato loko, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3014]="*“Kiṃ pana, bhante, ‘asassato loko, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’”ti?**“Then is this right: ‘The cosmos is not eternal. This is the only truth, anything else is wrong’?”*";
P_HTM[3015]="*“Etampi kho, poṭṭhapāda, mayā abyākataṃ:**“This too has not been declared by me.”*";
P_HTM[3016]="*‘asassato loko, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3017]="*“Kiṃ pana, bhante, ‘antavā loko … pe …**“Then is this right: ‘The cosmos is finite …’ …*";
P_HTM[3018]="*‘anantavā loko …**‘The cosmos is infinite …’ …*";
P_HTM[3019]="*‘taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīraṃ …**‘The soul and the body are the same thing …’ …*";
P_HTM[3020]="*‘aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīraṃ …**‘The soul and the body are different things …’ …*";
P_HTM[3021]="*‘hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā …**‘A Realized One exists after death …’ …*";
P_HTM[3022]="*‘na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā …**‘A Realized One doesn’t exist after death …’ …*";
P_HTM[3023]="*‘hoti ca na ca hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā …**‘A Realized One both exists and doesn’t exist after death …’ …*";
P_HTM[3024]="*‘neva hoti na na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’”ti?**‘A Realized One neither exists nor doesn’t exist after death. This is the only truth, anything else is wrong’?”*";
P_HTM[3025]="*“Etampi kho, poṭṭhapāda, mayā abyākataṃ:**“This too has not been declared by me.”*";
P_HTM[3026]="*‘neva hoti na na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā, idameva saccaṃ moghamaññan’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3027]="*“Kasmā panetaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā abyākatan”ti?**“Why haven’t these things been declared by the Buddha?”*";
P_HTM[3028]="*“Na hetaṃ, poṭṭhapāda, atthasaṃhitaṃ na dhammasaṃhitaṃ nādibrahmacariyakaṃ, na nibbidāya na virāgāya na nirodhāya na upasamāya na abhiññāya na sambodhāya na nibbānāya saṃvattati,**“Because they’re not beneficial or relevant to the fundamentals of the spiritual life. They don’t lead to disillusionment, dispassion, cessation, peace, insight, awakening, and extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[3029]="*tasmā etaṃ mayā abyākatan”ti.**That’s why I haven’t declared them.”*";
P_HTM[3030]="*“Kiṃ pana, bhante, bhagavatā byākatan”ti?**“Then what has been declared by the Buddha?”*";
P_HTM[3031]="*“Idaṃ dukkhanti kho, poṭṭhapāda, mayā byākataṃ. Ayaṃ dukkhasamudayoti kho, poṭṭhapāda, mayā byākataṃ. Ayaṃ dukkhanirodhoti kho, poṭṭhapāda, mayā byākataṃ. Ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadāti kho, poṭṭhapāda, mayā byākatan”ti.**“I have declared this: ‘This is suffering’ … ‘This is the origin of suffering’ … ‘This is the cessation of suffering’ … ‘This is the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering’.”*";
P_HTM[3032]="*“Kasmā panetaṃ, bhante, bhagavatā byākatan”ti?**“Why have these things been declared by the Buddha?”*";
P_HTM[3033]="*“Etañhi, poṭṭhapāda, atthasaṃhitaṃ, etaṃ dhammasaṃhitaṃ, etaṃ ādibrahmacariyakaṃ, etaṃ nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya upasamāya abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattati;**“Because they are beneficial and relevant to the fundamentals of the spiritual life. They lead to disillusionment, dispassion, cessation, peace, insight, awakening, and extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[3034]="*tasmā etaṃ mayā byākatan”ti.**That’s why I have declared them.”*";
P_HTM[3035]="*“Evametaṃ, bhagavā, evametaṃ, sugata.**“That’s so true, Blessed One! That’s so true, Holy One!*";
P_HTM[3036]="*Yassadāni, bhante, bhagavā kālaṃ maññatī”ti.**Please, sir, go at your convenience.”*";
P_HTM[3037]="*Atha kho bhagavā uṭṭhāyāsanā pakkāmi.**Then the Buddha got up from his seat and left.*";
P_HTM[3038]="*Atha kho te paribbājakā acirapakkantassa bhagavato poṭṭhapādaṃ paribbājakaṃ samantato vācā sannitodakena sañjhabbharimakaṃsu:**Soon after the Buddha left, those wanderers gave Poṭṭhapāda a comprehensive tongue-lashing,*";
P_HTM[3039]="*“evameva panāyaṃ bhavaṃ poṭṭhapādo yaññadeva samaṇo gotamo bhāsati, taṃ tadevassa abbhanumodati:**“No matter what the ascetic Gotama says, Poṭṭhapāda agrees with him:*";
P_HTM[3040]="*‘evametaṃ, bhagavā, evametaṃ, sugatā’ti.**‘That’s so true, Blessed One! That’s so true, Holy One!’*";
P_HTM[3041]="*Na kho pana mayaṃ kiñci samaṇassa gotamassa ekaṃsikaṃ dhammaṃ desitaṃ ājānāma:**We understand that the ascetic Gotama didn’t make any definitive statement at all regarding whether the cosmos is eternal and so on.”*";
P_HTM[3042]="*‘sassato loko’ti vā, ‘asassato loko’ti vā, ‘antavā loko’ti vā, ‘anantavā loko’ti vā, ‘taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīran’ti vā, ‘aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīran’ti vā, ‘hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā’ti vā, ‘na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā’ti vā, ‘hoti ca na ca hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā’ti vā, ‘neva hoti na na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā’ti vā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3043]="*Evaṃ vutte, poṭṭhapādo paribbājako te paribbājake etadavoca:**When they said this, Poṭṭhapāda said to them,*";
P_HTM[3044]="*“ahampi kho, bho, na kiñci samaṇassa gotamassa ekaṃsikaṃ dhammaṃ desitaṃ ājānāmi:**“I too understand that the ascetic Gotama didn’t make any definitive statement at all regarding whether the cosmos is eternal and so on.*";
P_HTM[3045]="*‘sassato loko’ti vā, ‘asassato loko’ti vā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[3046]="*‘neva hoti na na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā’ti vā;* **";
P_HTM[3047]="*api ca samaṇo gotamo bhūtaṃ tacchaṃ tathaṃ paṭipadaṃ paññapeti dhammaṭṭhitataṃ dhammaniyāmataṃ.**Nevertheless, the practice that he describes is true, real, and accurate. It is the regularity of natural principles, the invariance of natural principles.*";
P_HTM[3048]="*Bhūtaṃ kho pana tacchaṃ tathaṃ paṭipadaṃ paññapentassa dhammaṭṭhitataṃ dhammaniyāmataṃ, kathañhi nāma mādiso viññū samaṇassa gotamassa subhāsitaṃ subhāsitato nābbhanumodeyyā”ti?**So how could a sensible person such as I not agree that what was well spoken by the ascetic Gotama was in fact well spoken?”*";
P_HTM[3049]="*2. Cittahatthisāriputtapoṭṭhapādavatthu**2. On Citta Hatthisāriputta*";
P_HTM[3050]="*Atha kho dvīhatīhassa accayena citto ca hatthisāriputto poṭṭhapādo ca paribbājako yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā citto hatthisāriputto bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi.**Then after two or three days had passed, Citta Hatthisāriputta and Poṭṭhapāda went to see the Buddha. Citta Hatthisāriputta bowed and sat down to one side.*";
P_HTM[3051]="*Poṭṭhapādo pana paribbājako bhagavatā saddhiṃ sammodi. Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi.**But the wanderer Poṭṭhapāda exchanged greetings with the Buddha, and when the greetings and polite conversation were over, he sat down to one side.*";
P_HTM[3052]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho poṭṭhapādo paribbājako bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Poṭṭhapāda told the Buddha what had happened after he left. The Buddha said:*";
P_HTM[3053]="*“tadā maṃ, bhante, te paribbājakā acirapakkantassa bhagavato samantato vācāsannitodakena sañjhabbharimakaṃsu:* **";
P_HTM[3054]="*‘evameva panāyaṃ bhavaṃ poṭṭhapādo yaññadeva samaṇo gotamo bhāsati, taṃ tadevassa abbhanumodati:* **";
P_HTM[3055]="*“evametaṃ, bhagavā, evametaṃ, sugatā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3056]="*Na kho pana mayaṃ kiñci samaṇassa gotamassa ekaṃsikaṃ dhammaṃ desitaṃ ājānāma:* **";
P_HTM[3057]="*“sassato loko”ti vā, “asassato loko”ti vā, “antavā loko”ti vā, “anantavā loko”ti vā, “taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīran”ti vā, “aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīran”ti vā, “hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā”ti vā, “na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā”ti vā, “hoti ca na ca hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā”ti vā, “neva hoti na na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā”ti vā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3058]="*Evaṃ vuttāhaṃ, bhante, te paribbājake etadavocaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[3059]="*‘ahampi kho, bho, na kiñci samaṇassa gotamassa ekaṃsikaṃ dhammaṃ desitaṃ ājānāmi:* **";
P_HTM[3060]="*“sassato loko”ti vā, “asassato loko”ti vā … pe …* **";
P_HTM[3061]="*“neva hoti na na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā”ti vā;* **";
P_HTM[3062]="*api ca samaṇo gotamo bhūtaṃ tacchaṃ tathaṃ paṭipadaṃ paññapeti dhammaṭṭhitataṃ dhammaniyāmataṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3063]="*Bhūtaṃ kho pana tacchaṃ tathaṃ paṭipadaṃ paññapentassa dhammaṭṭhitataṃ dhammaniyāmataṃ, kathañhi nāma mādiso viññū samaṇassa gotamassa subhāsitaṃ subhāsitato nābbhanumodeyyā’”ti?* **";
P_HTM[3064]="*“Sabbeva kho ete, poṭṭhapāda, paribbājakā andhā acakkhukā;**“All those wanderers, Poṭṭhapāda, are blind and sightless.*";
P_HTM[3065]="*tvaṃyeva nesaṃ eko cakkhumā.**You are the only one who sees.*";
P_HTM[3066]="*Ekaṃsikāpi hi kho, poṭṭhapāda, mayā dhammā desitā paññattā;**For I have taught and pointed out both things that are definitive*";
P_HTM[3067]="*anekaṃsikāpi hi kho, poṭṭhapāda, mayā dhammā desitā paññattā.**and things that are not definitive.*";
P_HTM[3068]="*Katame ca te, poṭṭhapāda, mayā anekaṃsikā dhammā desitā paññattā?**And what things have I taught and pointed out that are not definitive?*";
P_HTM[3069]="*‘Sassato loko’ti kho, poṭṭhapāda, mayā anekaṃsiko dhammo desito paññatto;**‘The cosmos is eternal’ …*";
P_HTM[3070]="*‘asassato loko’ti kho, poṭṭhapāda, mayā anekaṃsiko dhammo desito paññatto;**‘The cosmos is not eternal’ …*";
P_HTM[3071]="*‘antavā loko’ti kho, poṭṭhapāda … pe …**‘The cosmos is finite’ …*";
P_HTM[3072]="*‘anantavā loko’ti kho, poṭṭhapāda …**‘The cosmos is infinite’ …*";
P_HTM[3073]="*‘taṃ jīvaṃ taṃ sarīran’ti kho, poṭṭhapāda …**‘The soul is the same thing as the body’ …*";
P_HTM[3074]="*‘aññaṃ jīvaṃ aññaṃ sarīran’ti kho, poṭṭhapāda …**‘The soul and the body are different things’ …*";
P_HTM[3075]="*‘hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā’ti kho, poṭṭhapāda …**‘A Realized One exists after death’ …*";
P_HTM[3076]="*na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā’ti kho, poṭṭhapāda …**‘A Realized One doesn’t exist after death’ …*";
P_HTM[3077]="*‘hoti ca na ca hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā’ti kho, poṭṭhapāda …**‘A Realized One both exists and doesn’t exist after death’ …*";
P_HTM[3078]="*‘neva hoti na na hoti tathāgato paraṃ maraṇā’ti kho, poṭṭhapāda, mayā anekaṃsiko dhammo desito paññatto.**‘A Realized One neither exists nor doesn’t exist after death.’*";
P_HTM[3079]="*Kasmā ca te, poṭṭhapāda, mayā anekaṃsikā dhammā desitā paññattā?**And why haven’t I taught and pointed out such things that are not definitive?*";
P_HTM[3080]="*Na hete, poṭṭhapāda, atthasaṃhitā na dhammasaṃhitā na ādibrahmacariyakā na nibbidāya na virāgāya na nirodhāya na upasamāya na abhiññāya na sambodhāya na nibbānāya saṃvattanti.**Because those things aren’t beneficial or relevant to the fundamentals of the spiritual life. They don’t lead to disillusionment, dispassion, cessation, peace, insight, awakening, and extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[3081]="*Tasmā te mayā anekaṃsikā dhammā desitā paññattā.**That’s why I haven’t taught and pointed them out.*";
P_HTM[3082]="*2.1. Ekaṃsikadhammā**2.1. Things That Are Definitive*";
P_HTM[3083]="*Katame ca te, poṭṭhapāda, mayā ekaṃsikā dhammā desitā paññattā?**And what things have I taught and pointed out that are definitive?*";
P_HTM[3084]="*Idaṃ dukkhanti kho, poṭṭhapāda, mayā ekaṃsiko dhammo desito paññatto.**‘This is suffering’ … ‘This is the origin of suffering’ … ‘This is the cessation of suffering’ … ‘This is the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering’.”*";
P_HTM[3085]="*Ayaṃ dukkhasamudayoti kho, poṭṭhapāda, mayā ekaṃsiko dhammo desito paññatto.* **";
P_HTM[3086]="*Ayaṃ dukkhanirodhoti kho, poṭṭhapāda, mayā ekaṃsiko dhammo desito paññatto.* **";
P_HTM[3087]="*Ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadāti kho, poṭṭhapāda, mayā ekaṃsiko dhammo desito paññatto.* **";
P_HTM[3088]="*Kasmā ca te, poṭṭhapāda, mayā ekaṃsikā dhammā desitā paññattā?**And why have I taught and pointed out such things that are definitive?*";
P_HTM[3089]="*Ete hi, poṭṭhapāda, atthasaṃhitā, ete dhammasaṃhitā, ete ādibrahmacariyakā ete nibbidāya virāgāya nirodhāya upasamāya abhiññāya sambodhāya nibbānāya saṃvattanti.**Because they are beneficial and relevant to the fundamentals of the spiritual life. They lead to disillusionment, dispassion, cessation, peace, insight, awakening, and extinguishment.*";
P_HTM[3090]="*Tasmā te mayā ekaṃsikā dhammā desitā paññattā.**That’s why I have taught and pointed them out.*";
P_HTM[3091]="*Santi, poṭṭhapāda, eke samaṇabrāhmaṇā evaṃvādino evaṃdiṭṭhino:**There are some ascetics and brahmins who have this doctrine and view:*";
P_HTM[3092]="*‘ekantasukhī attā hoti arogo paraṃ maraṇā’ti.**‘The self is exclusively happy and is sound after death.’*";
P_HTM[3093]="*Tyāhaṃ upasaṅkamitvā evaṃ vadāmi:**I go up to them and say,*";
P_HTM[3094]="*‘saccaṃ kira tumhe āyasmanto evaṃvādino evaṃdiṭṭhino:**‘Is it really true that this is the venerables’ view?’*";
P_HTM[3095]="*“ekantasukhī attā hoti arogo paraṃ maraṇā”’ti?* **";
P_HTM[3096]="*Te ce me evaṃ puṭṭhā ‘āmā’ti paṭijānanti.**And they answer, ‘Yes’.*";
P_HTM[3097]="*Tyāhaṃ evaṃ vadāmi:**I say to them,*";
P_HTM[3098]="*‘api pana tumhe āyasmanto ekantasukhaṃ lokaṃ jānaṃ passaṃ viharathā’ti?**‘But do you meditate knowing and seeing an exclusively happy world?’*";
P_HTM[3099]="*Iti puṭṭhā ‘no’ti vadanti.**Asked this, they say, ‘No.’*";
P_HTM[3100]="*Tyāhaṃ evaṃ vadāmi:**I say to them,*";
P_HTM[3101]="*‘api pana tumhe āyasmanto ekaṃ vā rattiṃ ekaṃ vā divasaṃ upaḍḍhaṃ vā rattiṃ upaḍḍhaṃ vā divasaṃ ekantasukhiṃ attānaṃ sañjānāthā’ti?**‘But have you perceived an exclusively happy self for a single day or night, or even half a day or night?’*";
P_HTM[3102]="*Iti puṭṭhā ‘no’ti vadanti.**Asked this, they say, ‘No.’*";
P_HTM[3103]="*Tyāhaṃ evaṃ vadāmi:**I say to them,*";
P_HTM[3104]="*‘api pana tumhe āyasmanto jānātha:**‘But do you know*";
P_HTM[3105]="*“ayaṃ maggo ayaṃ paṭipadā ekantasukhassa lokassa sacchikiriyāyā”’ti?**a path and a practice to realize an exclusively happy world?’*";
P_HTM[3106]="*Iti puṭṭhā ‘no’ti vadanti.**Asked this, they say, ‘No.’*";
P_HTM[3107]="*Tyāhaṃ evaṃ vadāmi:**I say to them,*";
P_HTM[3108]="*‘api pana tumhe āyasmanto yā tā devatā ekantasukhaṃ lokaṃ upapannā, tāsaṃ bhāsamānānaṃ saddaṃ suṇātha:**‘But have you ever heard the voice of the deities reborn in an exclusively happy world saying,*";
P_HTM[3109]="*“suppaṭipannāttha, mārisā, ujuppaṭipannāttha, mārisā, ekantasukhassa lokassa sacchikiriyāya;**“Practice well, dear sirs, practice directly so as to realize an exclusively happy world.*";
P_HTM[3110]="*mayampi hi, mārisā, evaṃpaṭipannā ekantasukhaṃ lokaṃ upapannā”’ti?**For this is how we practiced, and we were reborn in an exclusively happy world”?’*";
P_HTM[3111]="*Iti puṭṭhā ‘no’ti vadanti.**Asked this, they say, ‘No.’*";
P_HTM[3112]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, poṭṭhapāda,**What do you think, Poṭṭhapāda?*";
P_HTM[3113]="*nanu evaṃ sante tesaṃ samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ appāṭihīrakataṃ bhāsitaṃ sampajjatī”ti?**This being so, doesn’t what they say turn out to have no demonstrable basis?”*";
P_HTM[3114]="*“Addhā kho, bhante, evaṃ sante tesaṃ samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ appāṭihīrakataṃ bhāsitaṃ sampajjatī”ti.**“Clearly that’s the case, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3115]="*“Seyyathāpi, poṭṭhapāda, puriso evaṃ vadeyya:**“Suppose, Poṭṭhapāda, a man were to say:*";
P_HTM[3116]="*‘ahaṃ yā imasmiṃ janapade janapadakalyāṇī, taṃ icchāmi taṃ kāmemī’ti.**‘Whoever the finest lady in the land is, it is her that I want, her that I desire!’*";
P_HTM[3117]="*Tamenaṃ evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**They’d say to him,*";
P_HTM[3118]="*‘ambho purisa, yaṃ tvaṃ janapadakalyāṇiṃ icchasi kāmesi, jānāsi taṃ janapadakalyāṇiṃ khattiyī vā brāhmaṇī vā vessī vā suddī vā’ti?**‘Mister, that finest lady in the land who you desire—do you know whether she’s an aristocrat, a brahmin, a merchant, or a worker?’*";
P_HTM[3119]="*Iti puṭṭho ‘no’ti vadeyya.**Asked this, he’d say, ‘No.’*";
P_HTM[3120]="*Tamenaṃ evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**They’d say to him,*";
P_HTM[3121]="*‘ambho purisa, yaṃ tvaṃ janapadakalyāṇiṃ icchasi kāmesi, jānāsi taṃ janapadakalyāṇiṃ evaṃnāmā evaṅgottāti vā, dīghā vā rassā vā majjhimā vā kāḷī vā sāmā vā maṅguracchavī vāti, amukasmiṃ gāme vā nigame vā nagare vā’ti?**‘Mister, that finest lady in the land who you desire—do you know her name or clan? Whether she’s tall or short or medium? Whether her skin is black, brown, or tawny? What village, town, or city she comes from?’*";
P_HTM[3122]="*Iti puṭṭho ‘no’ti vadeyya.**Asked this, he’d say, ‘No.’*";
P_HTM[3123]="*Tamenaṃ evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**They’d say to him,*";
P_HTM[3124]="*‘ambho purisa, yaṃ tvaṃ na jānāsi na passasi, taṃ tvaṃ icchasi kāmesī’ti?**‘Mister, do you desire someone who you’ve never even known or seen?’*";
P_HTM[3125]="*Iti puṭṭho ‘āmā’ti vadeyya.**Asked this, he’d say, ‘Yes.’*";
P_HTM[3126]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, poṭṭhapāda,**What do you think, Poṭṭhapāda?*";
P_HTM[3127]="*nanu evaṃ sante tassa purisassa appāṭihīrakataṃ bhāsitaṃ sampajjatī”ti?**This being so, doesn’t that man’s statement turn out to have no demonstrable basis?”*";
P_HTM[3128]="*“Addhā kho, bhante, evaṃ sante tassa purisassa appāṭihīrakataṃ bhāsitaṃ sampajjatī”ti.**“Clearly that’s the case, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3129]="*“Evameva kho, poṭṭhapāda, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā evaṃvādino evaṃdiṭṭhino:**“In the same way, the ascetics and brahmins who have those various doctrines and views …*";
P_HTM[3130]="*‘ekantasukhī attā hoti arogo paraṃ maraṇā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3131]="*Tyāhaṃ upasaṅkamitvā evaṃ vadāmi:* **";
P_HTM[3132]="*‘saccaṃ kira tumhe āyasmanto evaṃvādino evaṃdiṭṭhino:* **";
P_HTM[3133]="*“ekantasukhī attā hoti arogo paraṃ maraṇā”’ti?* **";
P_HTM[3134]="*Te ce me evaṃ puṭṭhā ‘āmā’ti paṭijānanti.* **";
P_HTM[3135]="*Tyāhaṃ evaṃ vadāmi:* **";
P_HTM[3136]="*‘api pana tumhe āyasmanto ekantasukhaṃ lokaṃ jānaṃ passaṃ viharathā’ti?* **";
P_HTM[3137]="*Iti puṭṭhā ‘no’ti vadanti.* **";
P_HTM[3138]="*Tyāhaṃ evaṃ vadāmi:* **";
P_HTM[3139]="*‘api pana tumhe āyasmanto ekaṃ vā rattiṃ ekaṃ vā divasaṃ upaḍḍhaṃ vā rattiṃ upaḍḍhaṃ vā divasaṃ ekantasukhiṃ attānaṃ sañjānāthā’ti?* **";
P_HTM[3140]="*Iti puṭṭhā ‘no’ti vadanti.* **";
P_HTM[3141]="*Tyāhaṃ evaṃ vadāmi:* **";
P_HTM[3142]="*‘api pana tumhe āyasmanto jānātha:* **";
P_HTM[3143]="*“ayaṃ maggo ayaṃ paṭipadā ekantasukhassa lokassa sacchikiriyāyā”’ti?* **";
P_HTM[3144]="*Iti puṭṭhā ‘no’ti vadanti.* **";
P_HTM[3145]="*Tyāhaṃ evaṃ vadāmi:* **";
P_HTM[3146]="*‘api pana tumhe āyasmanto yā tā devatā ekantasukhaṃ lokaṃ upapannā, tāsaṃ bhāsamānānaṃ saddaṃ suṇātha:* **";
P_HTM[3147]="*“suppaṭipannāttha, mārisā, ujuppaṭipannāttha, mārisā, ekantasukhassa lokassa sacchikiriyāya;* **";
P_HTM[3148]="*mayampi hi, mārisā, evaṃpaṭipannā ekantasukhaṃ lokaṃ upapannā”’ti?* **";
P_HTM[3149]="*Iti puṭṭhā ‘no’ti vadanti.* **";
P_HTM[3150]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, poṭṭhapāda, nanu evaṃ sante tesaṃ samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ appāṭihīrakataṃ bhāsitaṃ sampajjatī”ti?**Doesn’t what they say turn out to have no demonstrable basis?”*";
P_HTM[3151]="*“Addhā kho, bhante, evaṃ sante tesaṃ samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ appāṭihīrakataṃ bhāsitaṃ sampajjatī”ti.**“Clearly that’s the case, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3152]="*“Seyyathāpi, poṭṭhapāda, puriso cātumahāpathe nisseṇiṃ kareyya pāsādassa ārohaṇāya.**“Suppose a man was to build a ladder at the crossroads for climbing up to a stilt longhouse.*";
P_HTM[3153]="*Tamenaṃ evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**They’d say to him,*";
P_HTM[3154]="*‘ambho purisa, yassa tvaṃ pāsādassa ārohaṇāya nisseṇiṃ karosi, jānāsi taṃ pāsādaṃ puratthimāya vā disāya dakkhiṇāya vā disāya pacchimāya vā disāya uttarāya vā disāya ucco vā nīco vā majjhimo vā’ti?**‘Mister, that stilt longhouse that you’re building a ladder for—do you know whether it’s to the north, south, east, or west? Or whether it’s tall or short or medium?’*";
P_HTM[3155]="*Iti puṭṭho ‘no’ti vadeyya.**Asked this, he’d say, ‘No.’*";
P_HTM[3156]="*Tamenaṃ evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**They’d say to him,*";
P_HTM[3157]="*‘ambho purisa, yaṃ tvaṃ na jānāsi na passasi, tassa tvaṃ pāsādassa ārohaṇāya nisseṇiṃ karosī’ti?**‘Mister, are you building a ladder for a longhouse that you’ve never even known or seen?’*";
P_HTM[3158]="*Iti puṭṭho ‘āmā’ti vadeyya.**Asked this, he’d say, ‘Yes.’*";
P_HTM[3159]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, poṭṭhapāda,**What do you think, Poṭṭhapāda?*";
P_HTM[3160]="*nanu evaṃ sante tassa purisassa appāṭihīrakataṃ bhāsitaṃ sampajjatī”ti?**This being so, doesn’t that man’s statement turn out to have no demonstrable basis?”*";
P_HTM[3161]="*“Addhā kho, bhante, evaṃ sante tassa purisassa appāṭihīrakataṃ bhāsitaṃ sampajjatī”ti.**“Clearly that’s the case, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3162]="*“Evameva kho, poṭṭhapāda, ye te samaṇabrāhmaṇā evaṃvādino evaṃdiṭṭhino:**“In the same way, the ascetics and brahmins who have those various doctrines and views …*";
P_HTM[3163]="*‘ekantasukhī attā hoti arogo paraṃ maraṇā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3164]="*Tyāhaṃ upasaṅkamitvā evaṃ vadāmi:* **";
P_HTM[3165]="*‘saccaṃ kira tumhe āyasmanto evaṃvādino evaṃdiṭṭhino:* **";
P_HTM[3166]="*“ekantasukhī attā hoti arogo paraṃ maraṇā”’ti?* **";
P_HTM[3167]="*Te ce me evaṃ puṭṭhā ‘āmā’ti paṭijānanti.* **";
P_HTM[3168]="*Tyāhaṃ evaṃ vadāmi:* **";
P_HTM[3169]="*‘api pana tumhe āyasmanto ekantasukhaṃ lokaṃ jānaṃ passaṃ viharathā’ti?* **";
P_HTM[3170]="*Iti puṭṭhā ‘no’ti vadanti.* **";
P_HTM[3171]="*Tyāhaṃ evaṃ vadāmi:* **";
P_HTM[3172]="*‘api pana tumhe āyasmanto ekaṃ vā rattiṃ ekaṃ vā divasaṃ upaḍḍhaṃ vā rattiṃ upaḍḍhaṃ vā divasaṃ ekantasukhiṃ attānaṃ sañjānāthā’ti?* **";
P_HTM[3173]="*Iti puṭṭhā ‘no’ti vadanti.* **";
P_HTM[3174]="*Tyāhaṃ evaṃ vadāmi:* **";
P_HTM[3175]="*‘api pana tumhe āyasmanto jānātha ayaṃ maggo ayaṃ paṭipadā ekantasukhassa lokassa sacchikiriyāyā’ti?* **";
P_HTM[3176]="*Iti puṭṭhā ‘no’ti vadanti.* **";
P_HTM[3177]="*Tyāhaṃ evaṃ vadāmi:* **";
P_HTM[3178]="*‘api pana tumhe āyasmanto yā tā devatā ekantasukhaṃ lokaṃ upapannā tāsaṃ devatānaṃ bhāsamānānaṃ saddaṃ suṇātha:* **";
P_HTM[3179]="*“suppaṭipannāttha, mārisā, ujuppaṭipannāttha, mārisā, ekantasukhassa lokassa sacchikiriyāya;* **";
P_HTM[3180]="*mayampi hi, mārisā, evaṃ paṭipannā ekantasukhaṃ lokaṃ upapannā”’ti?* **";
P_HTM[3181]="*Iti puṭṭhā ‘no’ti vadanti.* **";
P_HTM[3182]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, poṭṭhapāda, nanu evaṃ sante tesaṃ samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ appāṭihīrakataṃ bhāsitaṃ sampajjatī”ti?**Doesn’t what they say turn out to have no demonstrable basis?”*";
P_HTM[3183]="*“Addhā kho, bhante, evaṃ sante tesaṃ samaṇabrāhmaṇānaṃ appāṭihīrakataṃ bhāsitaṃ sampajjatī”ti.**“Clearly that’s the case, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3184]="*2.2. Tayoattapaṭilābha**2.2. Three Kinds of Reincarnation*";
P_HTM[3185]="*“Tayo kho me, poṭṭhapāda, attapaṭilābhā—**“Poṭṭhapāda, there are these three kinds of reincarnation:*";
P_HTM[3186]="*oḷāriko attapaṭilābho, manomayo attapaṭilābho, arūpo attapaṭilābho.**a substantial reincarnation, a mind-made reincarnation, and a non-physical reincarnation.*";
P_HTM[3187]="*Katamo ca, poṭṭhapāda, oḷāriko attapaṭilābho?**And what is a substantial reincarnation?*";
P_HTM[3188]="*Rūpī cātumahābhūtiko kabaḷīkārāhārabhakkho, ayaṃ oḷāriko attapaṭilābho.**It is physical, made up of the four primary elements, and consumes solid food.*";
P_HTM[3189]="*Katamo manomayo attapaṭilābho?**What is a mind-made reincarnation?*";
P_HTM[3190]="*Rūpī manomayo sabbaṅgapaccaṅgī ahīnindriyo, ayaṃ manomayo attapaṭilābho.**It is physical, mind-made, complete in all its various parts, not deficient in any faculty.*";
P_HTM[3191]="*Katamo arūpo attapaṭilābho?**What is a non-physical reincarnation?*";
P_HTM[3192]="*Arūpī saññāmayo, ayaṃ arūpo attapaṭilābho.**It is non-physical, made of perception.*";
P_HTM[3193]="*Oḷārikassapi kho ahaṃ, poṭṭhapāda, attapaṭilābhassa pahānāya dhammaṃ desemi:**I teach the Dhamma for the giving up of these three kinds of reincarnation:*";
P_HTM[3194]="*‘yathāpaṭipannānaṃ vo saṅkilesikā dhammā pahīyissanti, vodāniyā dhammā abhivaḍḍhissanti, paññāpāripūriṃ vepullattañca diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharissathā’ti.**‘When you practice accordingly, corrupting qualities will be given up in you and cleansing qualities will grow. You’ll enter and remain in the fullness and abundance of wisdom, having realized it with your own insight in this very life.’*";
P_HTM[3195]="*Siyā kho pana te, poṭṭhapāda, evamassa:**Poṭṭhapāda, you might think:*";
P_HTM[3196]="*‘saṅkilesikā dhammā pahīyissanti, vodāniyā dhammā abhivaḍḍhissanti, paññāpāripūriṃ vepullattañca diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharissati, dukkho ca kho vihāro’ti.**‘Corrupting qualities will be given up and cleansing qualities will grow. One will enter and remain in the fullness and abundance of wisdom, having realized it with one’s own insight in this very life. But such a life is suffering.’*";
P_HTM[3197]="*Na kho panetaṃ, poṭṭhapāda, evaṃ daṭṭhabbaṃ.**But you should not see it like this.*";
P_HTM[3198]="*Saṅkilesikā ceva dhammā pahīyissanti, vodāniyā ca dhammā abhivaḍḍhissanti, paññāpāripūriṃ vepullattañca diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharissati, pāmujjañceva bhavissati pīti ca passaddhi ca sati ca sampajaññañca sukho ca vihāro.**Corrupting qualities will be given up and cleansing qualities will grow. One will enter and remain in the fullness and abundance of wisdom, having realized it with one’s own insight in this very life. And there will be only joy and happiness, tranquility, mindfulness and awareness. Such a life is blissful.*";
P_HTM[3199]="*Manomayassapi kho ahaṃ, poṭṭhapāda, attapaṭilābhassa pahānāya dhammaṃ desemi:* **";
P_HTM[3200]="*‘yathāpaṭipannānaṃ vo saṅkilesikā dhammā pahīyissanti, vodāniyā dhammā abhivaḍḍhissanti, paññāpāripūriṃ vepullattañca diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharissathā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3201]="*Siyā kho pana te, poṭṭhapāda, evamassa:* **";
P_HTM[3202]="*‘saṅkilesikā dhammā pahīyissanti, vodāniyā dhammā abhivaḍḍhissanti, paññāpāripūriṃ vepullattañca diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharissati, dukkho ca kho vihāro’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3203]="*Na kho panetaṃ, poṭṭhapāda, evaṃ daṭṭhabbaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3204]="*Saṅkilesikā ceva dhammā pahīyissanti, vodāniyā ca dhammā abhivaḍḍhissanti, paññāpāripūriṃ vepullattañca diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharissati, pāmujjañceva bhavissati pīti ca passaddhi ca sati ca sampajaññañca sukho ca vihāro.* **";
P_HTM[3205]="*Arūpassapi kho ahaṃ, poṭṭhapāda, attapaṭilābhassa pahānāya dhammaṃ desemi:* **";
P_HTM[3206]="*‘yathāpaṭipannānaṃ vo saṅkilesikā dhammā pahīyissanti, vodāniyā dhammā abhivaḍḍhissanti, paññāpāripūriṃ vepullattañca diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharissathā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3207]="*Siyā kho pana te, poṭṭhapāda, evamassa:* **";
P_HTM[3208]="*‘saṅkilesikā dhammā pahīyissanti, vodāniyā dhammā abhivaḍḍhissanti, paññāpāripūriṃ vepullattañca diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharissati, dukkho ca kho vihāro’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3209]="*Na kho panetaṃ, poṭṭhapāda, evaṃ daṭṭhabbaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3210]="*Saṅkilesikā ceva dhammā pahīyissanti, vodāniyā ca dhammā abhivaḍḍhissanti, paññāpāripūriṃ vepullattañca diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharissati, pāmujjañceva bhavissati pīti ca passaddhi ca sati ca sampajaññañca sukho ca vihāro.* **";
P_HTM[3211]="*Pare ce, poṭṭhapāda, amhe evaṃ puccheyyuṃ:**If others should ask us,*";
P_HTM[3212]="*‘katamo pana so, āvuso, oḷāriko attapaṭilābho, yassa tumhe pahānāya dhammaṃ desetha, yathāpaṭipannānaṃ vo saṅkilesikā dhammā pahīyissanti, vodāniyā dhammā abhivaḍḍhissanti, paññāpāripūriṃ vepullattañca diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharissathā’ti, tesaṃ mayaṃ evaṃ puṭṭhā evaṃ byākareyyāma:**‘But reverends, what is that substantial reincarnation?’ We’d answer like this,*";
P_HTM[3213]="*‘ayaṃ vā so, āvuso, oḷāriko attapaṭilābho, yassa mayaṃ pahānāya dhammaṃ desema, yathāpaṭipannānaṃ vo saṅkilesikā dhammā pahīyissanti, vodāniyā dhammā abhivaḍḍhissanti, paññāpāripūriṃ vepullattañca diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharissathā’ti.**‘This is that substantial reincarnation.’*";
P_HTM[3214]="*Pare ce, poṭṭhapāda, amhe evaṃ puccheyyuṃ:**If others should ask us,*";
P_HTM[3215]="*‘katamo pana so, āvuso, manomayo attapaṭilābho, yassa tumhe pahānāya dhammaṃ desetha, yathāpaṭipannānaṃ vo saṅkilesikā dhammā pahīyissanti, vodāniyā dhammā abhivaḍḍhissanti, paññāpāripūriṃ vepullattañca diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharissathā’ti?**‘But reverends, what is that mind-made reincarnation?’ We’d answer like this,*";
P_HTM[3216]="*Tesaṃ mayaṃ evaṃ puṭṭhā evaṃ byākareyyāma:* **";
P_HTM[3217]="*‘ayaṃ vā so, āvuso, manomayo attapaṭilābho yassa mayaṃ pahānāya dhammaṃ desema, yathāpaṭipannānaṃ vo saṅkilesikā dhammā pahīyissanti, vodāniyā dhammā abhivaḍḍhissanti, paññāpāripūriṃ vepullattañca diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharissathā’ti.**‘This is that mind-made reincarnation.’*";
P_HTM[3218]="*Pare ce, poṭṭhapāda, amhe evaṃ puccheyyuṃ:**If others should ask us,*";
P_HTM[3219]="*‘katamo pana so, āvuso, arūpo attapaṭilābho, yassa tumhe pahānāya dhammaṃ desetha, yathāpaṭipannānaṃ vo saṅkilesikā dhammā pahīyissanti, vodāniyā dhammā abhivaḍḍhissanti, paññāpāripūriṃ vepullattañca diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharissathā’ti?**‘But reverends, what is that non-physical reincarnation?’ We’d answer like this,*";
P_HTM[3220]="*Tesaṃ mayaṃ evaṃ puṭṭhā evaṃ byākareyyāma:* **";
P_HTM[3221]="*‘ayaṃ vā so, āvuso, arūpo attapaṭilābho yassa mayaṃ pahānāya dhammaṃ desema, yathāpaṭipannānaṃ vo saṅkilesikā dhammā pahīyissanti, vodāniyā dhammā abhivaḍḍhissanti, paññāpāripūriṃ vepullattañca diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharissathā’ti.**‘This is that non-physical reincarnation.’*";
P_HTM[3222]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, poṭṭhapāda,**What do you think, Poṭṭhapāda?*";
P_HTM[3223]="*nanu evaṃ sante sappāṭihīrakataṃ bhāsitaṃ sampajjatī”ti?**This being so, doesn’t that statement turn out to have a demonstrable basis?”*";
P_HTM[3224]="*“Addhā kho, bhante, evaṃ sante sappāṭihīrakataṃ bhāsitaṃ sampajjatī”ti.**“Clearly that’s the case, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3225]="*“Seyyathāpi, poṭṭhapāda, puriso nisseṇiṃ kareyya pāsādassa ārohaṇāya tasseva pāsādassa heṭṭhā.**“Suppose a man were to build a ladder for climbing up to a stilt longhouse right underneath that longhouse.*";
P_HTM[3226]="*Tamenaṃ evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**They’d say to him,*";
P_HTM[3227]="*‘ambho purisa, yassa tvaṃ pāsādassa ārohaṇāya nisseṇiṃ karosi, jānāsi taṃ pāsādaṃ, puratthimāya vā disāya dakkhiṇāya vā disāya pacchimāya vā disāya uttarāya vā disāya ucco vā nīco vā majjhimo vā’ti?**‘Mister, that stilt longhouse that you’re building a ladder for—do you know whether it’s to the north, south, east, or west? Or whether it’s tall or short or medium?’*";
P_HTM[3228]="*So evaṃ vadeyya:**He’d say,*";
P_HTM[3229]="*‘ayaṃ vā so, āvuso, pāsādo, yassāhaṃ ārohaṇāya nisseṇiṃ karomi, tasseva pāsādassa heṭṭhā’ti.**‘This is that stilt longhouse for which I’m building a ladder, right underneath it.’*";
P_HTM[3230]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, poṭṭhapāda,**What do you think, Poṭṭhapāda?*";
P_HTM[3231]="*nanu evaṃ sante tassa purisassa sappāṭihīrakataṃ bhāsitaṃ sampajjatī”ti?**This being so, doesn’t that man’s statement turn out to have a demonstrable basis?”*";
P_HTM[3232]="*“Addhā kho, bhante, evaṃ sante tassa purisassa sappāṭihīrakataṃ bhāsitaṃ sampajjatī”ti.**“Clearly that’s the case, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3233]="*“Evameva kho, poṭṭhapāda, pare ce amhe evaṃ puccheyyuṃ:* **";
P_HTM[3234]="*‘katamo pana so, āvuso, oḷāriko attapaṭilābho … pe …* **";
P_HTM[3235]="*katamo pana so, āvuso, manomayo attapaṭilābho … pe …* **";
P_HTM[3236]="*katamo pana so, āvuso, arūpo attapaṭilābho, yassa tumhe pahānāya dhammaṃ desetha, yathāpaṭipannānaṃ vo saṅkilesikā dhammā pahīyissanti, vodāniyā dhammā abhivaḍḍhissanti, paññāpāripūriṃ vepullattañca diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharissathā’ti?* **";
P_HTM[3237]="*Tesaṃ mayaṃ evaṃ puṭṭhā evaṃ byākareyyāma:* **";
P_HTM[3238]="*‘ayaṃ vā so, āvuso, arūpo attapaṭilābho, yassa mayaṃ pahānāya dhammaṃ desema, yathāpaṭipannānaṃ vo saṅkilesikā dhammā pahīyissanti, vodāniyā dhammā abhivaḍḍhissanti, paññāpāripūriṃ vepullattañca diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja viharissathā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3239]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, poṭṭhapāda, nanu evaṃ sante sappāṭihīrakataṃ bhāsitaṃ sampajjatī”ti?* **";
P_HTM[3240]="*“Addhā kho, bhante, evaṃ sante sappāṭihīrakataṃ bhāsitaṃ sampajjatī”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3241]="*Evaṃ vutte, citto hatthisāriputto bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When the Buddha had spoken, Citta Hatthisāriputta said,*";
P_HTM[3242]="*“yasmiṃ, bhante, samaye oḷāriko attapaṭilābho hoti, moghassa tasmiṃ samaye manomayo attapaṭilābho hoti, mogho arūpo attapaṭilābho hoti;**“Sir, while in a substantial reincarnation, are the mind-made and non-physical reincarnations fictitious,*";
P_HTM[3243]="*oḷāriko vāssa attapaṭilābho tasmiṃ samaye sacco hoti.**and only the substantial reincarnation real?*";
P_HTM[3244]="*Yasmiṃ, bhante, samaye manomayo attapaṭilābho hoti, moghassa tasmiṃ samaye oḷāriko attapaṭilābho hoti, mogho arūpo attapaṭilābho hoti;**While in a mind-made reincarnation, are the substantial and non-physical reincarnations fictitious,*";
P_HTM[3245]="*manomayo vāssa attapaṭilābho tasmiṃ samaye sacco hoti.**and only the mind-made reincarnation real?*";
P_HTM[3246]="*Yasmiṃ, bhante, samaye arūpo attapaṭilābho hoti, moghassa tasmiṃ samaye oḷāriko attapaṭilābho hoti, mogho manomayo attapaṭilābho hoti;**While in a non-physical reincarnation, are the substantial and mind-made reincarnations fictitious,*";
P_HTM[3247]="*arūpo vāssa attapaṭilābho tasmiṃ samaye sacco hotī”ti.**and only the non-physical reincarnation real?”*";
P_HTM[3248]="*“Yasmiṃ, citta, samaye oḷāriko attapaṭilābho hoti, neva tasmiṃ samaye manomayo attapaṭilābhoti saṅkhaṃ gacchati, na arūpo attapaṭilābhoti saṅkhaṃ gacchati;**“While in a substantial reincarnation, it’s not referred to as a mind-made or non-physical reincarnation,*";
P_HTM[3249]="*oḷāriko attapaṭilābhotveva tasmiṃ samaye saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**only as a substantial reincarnation.*";
P_HTM[3250]="*Yasmiṃ, citta, samaye manomayo attapaṭilābho hoti, neva tasmiṃ samaye oḷāriko attapaṭilābhoti saṅkhaṃ gacchati, na arūpo attapaṭilābhoti saṅkhaṃ gacchati;**While in a mind-made reincarnation, it’s not referred to as a substantial or non-physical reincarnation,*";
P_HTM[3251]="*manomayo attapaṭilābhotveva tasmiṃ samaye saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**only as a mind-made reincarnation.*";
P_HTM[3252]="*Yasmiṃ, citta, samaye arūpo attapaṭilābho hoti, neva tasmiṃ samaye oḷāriko attapaṭilābhoti saṅkhaṃ gacchati, na manomayo attapaṭilābhoti saṅkhaṃ gacchati;**While in a non-physical reincarnation, it’s not referred to as a substantial or mind-made reincarnation,*";
P_HTM[3253]="*arūpo attapaṭilābhotveva tasmiṃ samaye saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**only as a non-physical reincarnation.*";
P_HTM[3254]="*Sace taṃ, citta, evaṃ puccheyyuṃ:**Citta, suppose they were to ask you,*";
P_HTM[3255]="*‘ahosi tvaṃ atītamaddhānaṃ, na tvaṃ nāhosi;**‘Did you exist in the past?*";
P_HTM[3256]="*bhavissasi tvaṃ anāgatamaddhānaṃ, na tvaṃ na bhavissasi;**Will you exist in the future?*";
P_HTM[3257]="*atthi tvaṃ etarahi, na tvaṃ natthī’ti.**Do you exist now?’*";
P_HTM[3258]="*Evaṃ puṭṭho tvaṃ, citta, kinti byākareyyāsī”ti?**How would you answer?”*";
P_HTM[3259]="*“Sace maṃ, bhante, evaṃ puccheyyuṃ:**“Sir, if they were to ask me this,*";
P_HTM[3260]="*‘ahosi tvaṃ atītamaddhānaṃ, na tvaṃ na ahosi;* **";
P_HTM[3261]="*bhavissasi tvaṃ anāgatamaddhānaṃ, na tvaṃ na bhavissasi;* **";
P_HTM[3262]="*atthi tvaṃ etarahi, na tvaṃ natthī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3263]="*Evaṃ puṭṭho ahaṃ, bhante, evaṃ byākareyyaṃ:**I’d answer like this,*";
P_HTM[3264]="*‘ahosāhaṃ atītamaddhānaṃ, nāhaṃ na ahosiṃ;**‘I existed in the past.*";
P_HTM[3265]="*bhavissāmahaṃ anāgatamaddhānaṃ, nāhaṃ na bhavissāmi;**I will exist in the future.*";
P_HTM[3266]="*atthāhaṃ etarahi, nāhaṃ natthī’ti.**I exist now.’*";
P_HTM[3267]="*Evaṃ puṭṭho ahaṃ, bhante, evaṃ byākareyyan”ti.**That’s how I’d answer.”*";
P_HTM[3268]="*“Sace pana taṃ, citta, evaṃ puccheyyuṃ:**“But Citta, suppose they were to ask you,*";
P_HTM[3269]="*‘yo te ahosi atīto attapaṭilābho, sova te attapaṭilābho sacco, mogho anāgato, mogho paccuppanno?**‘Is the reincarnation you had in the past your only real one, and those of the future and present fictitious?*";
P_HTM[3270]="*Yo te bhavissati anāgato attapaṭilābho, sova te attapaṭilābho sacco, mogho atīto, mogho paccuppanno?**Is the reincarnation you will have in the future your only real one, and those of the past and present fictitious?*";
P_HTM[3271]="*Yo te etarahi paccuppanno attapaṭilābho, sova te attapaṭilābho sacco, mogho atīto, mogho anāgato’ti.**Is the reincarnation you have now your only real one, and those of the past and future fictitious?’*";
P_HTM[3272]="*Evaṃ puṭṭho tvaṃ, citta, kinti byākareyyāsī”ti?**How would you answer?”*";
P_HTM[3273]="*“Sace pana maṃ, bhante, evaṃ puccheyyuṃ:**“Sir, if they were to ask me this,*";
P_HTM[3274]="*‘yo te ahosi atīto attapaṭilābho, sova te attapaṭilābho sacco, mogho anāgato, mogho paccuppanno.* **";
P_HTM[3275]="*Yo te bhavissati anāgato attapaṭilābho, sova te attapaṭilābho sacco, mogho atīto, mogho paccuppanno.* **";
P_HTM[3276]="*Yo te etarahi paccuppanno attapaṭilābho, sova te attapaṭilābho sacco, mogho atīto, mogho anāgato’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3277]="*Evaṃ puṭṭho ahaṃ, bhante, evaṃ byākareyyaṃ:**I’d answer like this,*";
P_HTM[3278]="*‘yo me ahosi atīto attapaṭilābho, sova me attapaṭilābho tasmiṃ samaye sacco ahosi, mogho anāgato, mogho paccuppanno.**‘The reincarnation I had in the past was real at that time, and those of the future and present fictitious.*";
P_HTM[3279]="*Yo me bhavissati anāgato attapaṭilābho, sova me attapaṭilābho tasmiṃ samaye sacco bhavissati, mogho atīto, mogho paccuppanno.**The reincarnation I will have in the future will be real at the time, and those of the past and present fictitious.*";
P_HTM[3280]="*Yo me etarahi paccuppanno attapaṭilābho, sova me attapaṭilābho sacco, mogho atīto, mogho anāgato’ti.**The reincarnation I have now is real at this time, and those of the past and future fictitious.’*";
P_HTM[3281]="*Evaṃ puṭṭho ahaṃ, bhante, evaṃ byākareyyan”ti.**That’s how I’d answer.”*";
P_HTM[3282]="*“Evameva kho, citta, yasmiṃ samaye oḷāriko attapaṭilābho hoti, neva tasmiṃ samaye manomayo attapaṭilābhoti saṅkhaṃ gacchati, na arūpo attapaṭilābhoti saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**“In the same way, while in any one of the three reincarnations, it’s not referred to as the other two, only under its own name.*";
P_HTM[3283]="*Oḷāriko attapaṭilābhotveva tasmiṃ samaye saṅkhaṃ gacchati.* **";
P_HTM[3284]="*Yasmiṃ, citta, samaye manomayo attapaṭilābho hoti … pe …* **";
P_HTM[3285]="*yasmiṃ, citta, samaye arūpo attapaṭilābho hoti, neva tasmiṃ samaye oḷāriko attapaṭilābhoti saṅkhaṃ gacchati, na manomayo attapaṭilābhoti saṅkhaṃ gacchati;* **";
P_HTM[3286]="*arūpo attapaṭilābhotveva tasmiṃ samaye saṅkhaṃ gacchati.* **";
P_HTM[3287]="*Seyyathāpi, citta, gavā khīraṃ, khīramhā dadhi, dadhimhā navanītaṃ, navanītamhā sappi, sappimhā sappimaṇḍo.**From a cow comes milk, from milk comes curds, from curds come butter, from butter comes ghee, and from ghee comes cream of ghee. And the cream of ghee is said to be the best of these.*";
P_HTM[3288]="*Yasmiṃ samaye khīraṃ hoti, neva tasmiṃ samaye dadhīti saṅkhaṃ gacchati, na navanītanti saṅkhaṃ gacchati, na sappīti saṅkhaṃ gacchati, na sappimaṇḍoti saṅkhaṃ gacchati;**While it’s milk, it’s not referred to as curds, butter, ghee, or cream of ghee.*";
P_HTM[3289]="*khīrantveva tasmiṃ samaye saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**It’s only referred to as milk.*";
P_HTM[3290]="*Yasmiṃ samaye dadhi hoti … pe …**While it’s curd*";
P_HTM[3291]="*navanītaṃ hoti …**or butter*";
P_HTM[3292]="*sappi hoti …**or ghee*";
P_HTM[3293]="*sappimaṇḍo hoti, neva tasmiṃ samaye khīranti saṅkhaṃ gacchati, na dadhīti saṅkhaṃ gacchati, na navanītanti saṅkhaṃ gacchati, na sappīti saṅkhaṃ gacchati;**or cream of ghee, it’s not referred to as anything else,*";
P_HTM[3294]="*sappimaṇḍotveva tasmiṃ samaye saṅkhaṃ gacchati.**only under its own name.*";
P_HTM[3295]="*Evameva kho, citta, yasmiṃ samaye oḷāriko attapaṭilābho hoti … pe …**In the same way, while in any one of the three reincarnations, it’s not referred to as the other two, only under its own name.*";
P_HTM[3296]="*yasmiṃ, citta, samaye manomayo attapaṭilābho hoti … pe …* **";
P_HTM[3297]="*yasmiṃ, citta, samaye arūpo attapaṭilābho hoti, neva tasmiṃ samaye oḷāriko attapaṭilābhoti saṅkhaṃ gacchati, na manomayo attapaṭilābhoti saṅkhaṃ gacchati;* **";
P_HTM[3298]="*arūpo attapaṭilābhotveva tasmiṃ samaye saṅkhaṃ gacchati.* **";
P_HTM[3299]="*Imā kho, citta, lokasamaññā lokaniruttiyo lokavohārā lokapaññattiyo, yāhi tathāgato voharati aparāmasan”ti.**These are the world’s usages, terms, expressions, and descriptions, which the Realized One uses without misapprehending them.”*";
P_HTM[3300]="*Evaṃ vutte, poṭṭhapādo paribbājako bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he had spoken, the wanderer Poṭṭhapāda said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[3301]="*“abhikkantaṃ, bhante, abhikkantaṃ, bhante.**“Excellent, sir! Excellent!*";
P_HTM[3302]="*Seyyathāpi, bhante, nikkujjitaṃ vā ukkujjeyya, paṭicchannaṃ vā vivareyya, mūḷhassa vā maggaṃ ācikkheyya, andhakāre vā telapajjotaṃ dhāreyya: ‘cakkhumanto rūpāni dakkhantī’ti; evamevaṃ bhagavatā anekapariyāyena dhammo pakāsito.**As if he were righting the overturned, or revealing the hidden, or pointing out the path to the lost, or lighting a lamp in the dark so people with good eyes can see what’s there, so too the Buddha has made the teaching clear in many ways.*";
P_HTM[3303]="*Esāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavantaṃ saraṇaṃ gacchāmi dhammañca bhikkhusaṅghañca.**I go for refuge to the Buddha, to the teaching, and to the mendicant Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[3304]="*Upāsakaṃ maṃ bhagavā dhāretu ajjatagge pāṇupetaṃ saraṇaṃ gatan”ti.**From this day forth, may the Buddha remember me as a lay follower who has gone for refuge for life.”*";
P_HTM[3305]="*2.3. Cittahatthisāriputtaupasampadā**2.3. The Ordination of Citta Hatthisāriputta*";
P_HTM[3306]="*Citto pana hatthisāriputto bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**But Citta Hatthisāriputta said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[3307]="*“abhikkantaṃ, bhante, abhikkantaṃ, bhante.**“Excellent, sir! Excellent!*";
P_HTM[3308]="*Seyyathāpi, bhante, nikkujjitaṃ vā ukkujjeyya, paṭicchannaṃ vā vivareyya, mūḷhassa vā maggaṃ ācikkheyya, andhakāre vā telapajjotaṃ dhāreyya: ‘cakkhumanto rūpāni dakkhantī’ti; evamevaṃ bhagavatā anekapariyāyena dhammo pakāsito.**As if he were righting the overturned, or revealing the hidden, or pointing out the path to the lost, or lighting a lamp in the dark so people with good eyes can see what’s there, so too the Buddha has made the teaching clear in many ways.*";
P_HTM[3309]="*Esāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavantaṃ saraṇaṃ gacchāmi dhammañca bhikkhusaṅghañca.**I go for refuge to the Buddha, to the teaching, and to the mendicant Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[3310]="*Labheyyāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavato santike pabbajjaṃ, labheyyaṃ upasampadan”ti.**Sir, may I receive the going forth, the ordination in the Buddha’s presence?”*";
P_HTM[3311]="*Alattha kho citto hatthisāriputto bhagavato santike pabbajjaṃ, alattha upasampadaṃ.**And Citta Hatthisāriputta received the going forth, the ordination in the Buddha’s presence.*";
P_HTM[3312]="*Acirūpasampanno kho panāyasmā citto hatthisāriputto eko vūpakaṭṭho appamatto ātāpī pahitatto viharanto na cirasseva—yassatthāya kulaputtā sammadeva agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajanti, tadanuttaraṃ—brahmacariyapariyosānaṃ diṭṭheva dhamme sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā upasampajja vihāsi.**Not long after his ordination, Venerable Citta Hatthisāriputta, living alone, withdrawn, diligent, keen, and resolute, soon realized the supreme end of the spiritual path in this very life. He lived having achieved with his own insight the goal for which gentlemen rightly go forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[3313]="*“khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthAttāyā”ti abbhaññāsi.**He understood: “Rebirth is ended; the spiritual journey has been completed; what had to be done has been done; there is no return to any state of existence.”*";
P_HTM[3314]="*Aññataro kho panāyasmā citto hatthisāriputto arahataṃ ahosīti.**And Venerable Citta Hatthisāriputta became one of the perfected.*";
P_HTM[3315]="*Poṭṭhapādasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ navamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3316]="*10. Subhasutta  - With Subha * **";
P_HTM[3317]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[3318]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ āyasmā ānando sāvatthiyaṃ viharati jetavane anāthapiṇḍikassa ārāme aciraparinibbute bhagavati.**At one time Venerable Ānanda was staying near Sāvatthī in Jeta’s Grove, Anāthapiṇḍika’s monastery. It was not long after the Buddha had become fully extinguished.*";
P_HTM[3319]="*Tena kho pana samayena subho māṇavo todeyyaputto sāvatthiyaṃ paṭivasati kenacideva karaṇīyena.**Now at that time the brahmin student Subha, Todeyya’s son, was residing in Sāvatthī on some business.*";
P_HTM[3320]="*Atha kho subho māṇavo todeyyaputto aññataraṃ māṇavakaṃ āmantesi:**Then he addressed a certain student,*";
P_HTM[3321]="*“ehi tvaṃ, māṇavaka, yena samaṇo ānando tenupasaṅkama; upasaṅkamitvā mama vacanena samaṇaṃ ānandaṃ appābādhaṃ appātaṅkaṃ lahuṭṭhānaṃ balaṃ phāsuvihāraṃ puccha:**“Here, student, go to the ascetic Ānanda and in my name bow with your head to his feet. Ask him if he is healthy and well, nimble, strong, and living comfortably.*";
P_HTM[3322]="*‘subho māṇavo todeyyaputto bhavantaṃ ānandaṃ appābādhaṃ appātaṅkaṃ lahuṭṭhānaṃ balaṃ phāsuvihāraṃ pucchatī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3323]="*Evañca vadehi:**And then say:*";
P_HTM[3324]="*‘sādhu kira bhavaṃ ānando yena subhassa māṇavassa todeyyaputtassa nivesanaṃ tenupasaṅkamatu anukampaṃ upādāyā’”ti.**‘Sir, please visit the student Subha, Todeyya’s son, at his home out of compassion.’”*";
P_HTM[3325]="*“Evaṃ, bho”ti kho so māṇavako subhassa māṇavassa todeyyaputtassa paṭissutvā yenāyasmā ānando tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmatā ānandena saddhiṃ sammodi.**“Yes, sir,” replied the student, and did as he was asked.*";
P_HTM[3326]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho so māṇavako āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[3327]="*“subho māṇavo todeyyaputto bhavantaṃ ānandaṃ appābādhaṃ appātaṅkaṃ lahuṭṭhānaṃ balaṃ phāsuvihāraṃ pucchati;* **";
P_HTM[3328]="*evañca vadeti:* **";
P_HTM[3329]="*‘sādhu kira bhavaṃ ānando yena subhassa māṇavassa todeyyaputtassa nivesanaṃ tenupasaṅkamatu anukampaṃ upādāyā’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3330]="*Evaṃ vutte, āyasmā ānando taṃ māṇavakaṃ etadavoca:**When he had spoken, Venerable Ānanda said to him,*";
P_HTM[3331]="*“akālo kho, māṇavaka.**“It’s not the right time, student.*";
P_HTM[3332]="*Atthi me ajja bhesajjamattā pītā.**I’ve drunk sufficient refreshments for today.*";
P_HTM[3333]="*Appevanāma svepi upasaṅkameyyāma kālañca samayañca upādāyā”ti.**But hopefully tomorrow I’ll get a chance to visit him.”*";
P_HTM[3334]="*“Evaṃ, bho”ti kho so māṇavako āyasmato ānandassa paṭissutvā uṭṭhāyāsanā yena subho māṇavo todeyyaputto tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā subhaṃ māṇavaṃ todeyyaputtaṃ etadavoca:**“Yes, sir,” replied the student. He went back to Subha, and told him what had happened, adding,*";
P_HTM[3335]="*“avocumhā kho mayaṃ bhoto vacanena taṃ bhavantaṃ ānandaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[3336]="*‘subho māṇavo todeyyaputto bhavantaṃ ānandaṃ appābādhaṃ appātaṅkaṃ lahuṭṭhānaṃ balaṃ phāsuvihāraṃ pucchati, evañca vadeti:* **";
P_HTM[3337]="*“sādhu kira bhavaṃ ānando yena subhassa māṇavassa todeyyaputtassa nivesanaṃ tenupasaṅkamatu anukampaṃ upādāyā”’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3338]="*Evaṃ vutte, bho, samaṇo ānando maṃ etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[3339]="*‘akālo kho, māṇavaka.* **";
P_HTM[3340]="*Atthi me ajja bhesajjamattā pītā.* **";
P_HTM[3341]="*Appevanāma svepi upasaṅkameyyāma kālañca samayañca upādāyā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3342]="*Ettāvatāpi kho, bho, katameva etaṃ, yato kho so bhavaṃ ānando okāsamakāsi svātanāyapi upasaṅkamanāyā”ti.**“This much, sir, I managed to do. At least Master Ānanda will take the opportunity to visit tomorrow.”*";
P_HTM[3343]="*Atha kho āyasmā ānando tassā rattiyā accayena pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya cetakena bhikkhunā pacchāsamaṇena yena subhassa māṇavassa todeyyaputtassa nivesanaṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdi. Atha kho subho māṇavo todeyyaputto yenāyasmā ānando tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā āyasmatā ānandena saddhiṃ sammodi.**Then when the night had passed, Ānanda robed up in the morning and, taking his bowl and robe, went with Venerable Cetaka as his second monk to Subha’s home, where he sat on the seat spread out. Then Subha went up to Ānanda, and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[3344]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho subho māṇavo todeyyaputto āyasmantaṃ ānandaṃ etadavoca:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, he sat down to one side and said to Ānanda:*";
P_HTM[3345]="*“bhavañhi ānando tassa bhoto gotamassa dīgharattaṃ upaṭṭhāko santikāvacaro samīpacārī.**“Master Ānanda, you were Master Gotama’s attendant. You were close to him, living in his presence.*";
P_HTM[3346]="*Bhavametaṃ ānando jāneyya, yesaṃ so bhavaṃ gotamo dhammānaṃ vaṇṇavādī ahosi, yattha ca imaṃ janataṃ samādapesi nivesesi patiṭṭhāpesi.**You ought to know what things Master Gotama praised, and in which he encouraged, settled, and grounded all these people.*";
P_HTM[3347]="*Katamesānaṃ kho, bho ānanda, dhammānaṃ so bhavaṃ gotamo vaṇṇavādī ahosi; kattha ca imaṃ janataṃ samādapesi nivesesi patiṭṭhāpesī”ti?**What were those things?”*";
P_HTM[3348]="*“Tiṇṇaṃ kho, māṇava, khandhānaṃ so bhagavā vaṇṇavādī ahosi; ettha ca imaṃ janataṃ samādapesi nivesesi patiṭṭhāpesi.**“Student, the Buddha praised three sets of things, and that’s what he encouraged, settled, and grounded all these people in.*";
P_HTM[3349]="*Katamesaṃ tiṇṇaṃ?**What three?*";
P_HTM[3350]="*Ariyassa sīlakkhandhassa, ariyassa samādhikkhandhassa, ariyassa paññākkhandhassa.**The entire spectrum of noble ethics, immersion, and wisdom.*";
P_HTM[3351]="*Imesaṃ kho, māṇava, tiṇṇaṃ khandhānaṃ so bhagavā vaṇṇavādī ahosi; ettha ca imaṃ janataṃ samādapesi nivesesi patiṭṭhāpesī”ti.**These are the three sets of things that the Buddha praised.”*";
P_HTM[3352]="*1. Sīlakkhandha**1. The Entire Spectrum of Ethics*";
P_HTM[3353]="*“Katamo pana so, bho ānanda, ariyo sīlakkhandho, yassa so bhavaṃ gotamo vaṇṇavādī ahosi, yattha ca imaṃ janataṃ samādapesi nivesesi patiṭṭhāpesī”ti?**“But what was that noble spectrum of ethics that the Buddha praised?”*";
P_HTM[3354]="*“Idha, māṇava, tathāgato loke uppajjati arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā.**“Student, it’s when a Realized One arises in the world, perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.*";
P_HTM[3355]="*So imaṃ lokaṃ sadevakaṃ samārakaṃ sabrahmakaṃ sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiṃ pajaṃ sadevamanussaṃ sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedeti.**He has realized with his own insight this world—with its gods, Māras and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, gods and humans—and he makes it known to others.*";
P_HTM[3356]="*So dhammaṃ deseti ādikalyāṇaṃ majjhekalyāṇaṃ pariyosānakalyāṇaṃ sātthaṃ sabyañjanaṃ kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ pakāseti.**He teaches Dhamma that’s good in the beginning, good in the middle, and good in the end, meaningful and well-phrased. And he reveals a spiritual practice that’s entirely full and pure.*";
P_HTM[3357]="*Taṃ dhammaṃ suṇāti gahapati vā gahapatiputto vā aññatarasmiṃ vā kule paccājāto.**A householder hears that teaching, or a householder’s child, or someone reborn in some clan.*";
P_HTM[3358]="*So taṃ dhammaṃ sutvā tathāgate saddhaṃ paṭilabhati.**They gain faith in the Realized One,*";
P_HTM[3359]="*So tena saddhāpaṭilābhena samannāgato iti paṭisañcikkhati:**and reflect:*";
P_HTM[3360]="*‘sambādho gharāvāso rajopatho, abbhokāso pabbajjā,**‘Living in a house is cramped and dirty, but the life of one gone forth is wide open.*";
P_HTM[3361]="*nayidaṃ sukaraṃ agāraṃ ajjhāvasatā ekantaparipuṇṇaṃ ekantaparisuddhaṃ saṅkhalikhitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ carituṃ.**It’s not easy for someone living at home to lead the spiritual life utterly full and pure, like a polished shell.*";
P_HTM[3362]="*Yannūnāhaṃ kesamassuṃ ohāretvā kāsāyāni vatthāni acchādetvā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajeyyan’ti.**Why don’t I shave off my hair and beard, dress in ocher robes, and go forth from the lay life to homelessness?’*";
P_HTM[3363]="*So aparena samayena appaṃ vā bhogakkhandhaṃ pahāya mahantaṃ vā bhogakkhandhaṃ pahāya appaṃ vā ñātiparivaṭṭaṃ pahāya mahantaṃ vā ñātiparivaṭṭaṃ pahāya kesamassuṃ ohāretvā kāsāyāni vatthāni acchādetvā agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajati.**After some time they give up a large or small fortune, and a large or small family circle. They shave off hair and beard, dress in ocher robes, and go forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[3364]="*So evaṃ pabbajito samāno pātimokkhasaṃvarasaṃvuto viharati, ācāragocarasampanno, anumattesu vajjesu bhayadassāvī, samādāya sikkhati sikkhāpadesu, kāyakammavacīkammena samannāgato kusalena, parisuddhājīvo, sīlasampanno, indriyesu guttadvāro, satisampajaññena samannāgato, santuṭṭho.**Once they’ve gone forth, they live restrained in the monastic code, conducting themselves well and seeking alms in suitable places. Seeing danger in the slightest fault, they keep the rules they’ve undertaken. They act skillfully by body and speech. They’re purified in livelihood and accomplished in ethical conduct. They guard the sense doors, have mindfulness and situational awareness, and are content.*";
P_HTM[3365]="*Kathañca, māṇava, bhikkhu sīlasampanno hoti?**And how is a mendicant accomplished in ethics?*";
P_HTM[3366]="*Idha, māṇava, bhikkhu pāṇātipātaṃ pahāya pāṇātipātā paṭivirato hoti, nihitadaṇḍo nihitasattho lajjī dayāpanno, sabbapāṇabhūtahitānukampī viharati.**It’s when a mendicant gives up killing living creatures. They renounce the rod and the sword. They’re scrupulous and kind, living full of compassion for all living beings. …*";
P_HTM[3367]="*Yampi, māṇava, bhikkhu pāṇātipātaṃ pahāya pāṇātipātā paṭivirato hoti, nihitadaṇḍo nihitasattho lajjī dayāpanno, sabbapāṇabhūtahitānukampī viharati;* **";
P_HTM[3368]="*idampissa hoti sīlasmiṃ.**This pertains to their ethics.*";
P_HTM[3369]="*Yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpāya tiracchānavijjāya micchājīvena jīvitaṃ kappenti,**There are some ascetics and brahmins who, while enjoying food given in faith, still earn a living by unworthy branches of knowledge, by wrong livelihood.*";
P_HTM[3370]="*seyyathidaṃ—santikammaṃ paṇidhikammaṃ bhūtakammaṃ bhūrikammaṃ vassakammaṃ vossakammaṃ vatthukammaṃ vatthuparikammaṃ ācamanaṃ nhāpanaṃ juhanaṃ vamanaṃ virecanaṃ uddhaṃvirecanaṃ adhovirecanaṃ sīsavirecanaṃ kaṇṇatelaṃ nettatappanaṃ natthukammaṃ añjanaṃ paccañjanaṃ sālākiyaṃ sallakattiyaṃ dārakatikicchā mūlabhesajjānaṃ anuppadānaṃ osadhīnaṃ paṭimokkho**This includes rites for propitiation, for granting wishes, for ghosts, for the earth, for rain, for property settlement, and for preparing and consecrating house sites, and rites involving rinsing and bathing, and oblations. It also includes administering emetics, purgatives, expectorants, and phlegmagogues; administering ear-oils, eye restoratives, nasal medicine, ointments, and counter-ointments; surgery with needle and scalpel, treating children, prescribing root medicines, and binding on herbs.*";
P_HTM[3371]="*iti vā iti evarūpāya tiracchānavijjāya micchājīvā paṭivirato hoti.**They refrain from such unworthy branches of knowledge, such wrong livelihood. …*";
P_HTM[3372]="*Yampi, māṇava, bhikkhu yathā vā paneke bhonto samaṇabrāhmaṇā saddhādeyyāni bhojanāni bhuñjitvā te evarūpāya tiracchānavijjāya micchājīvena jīvitaṃ kappenti,* **";
P_HTM[3373]="*seyyathidaṃ—santikammaṃ paṇidhikammaṃ … pe … osadhīnaṃ paṭimokkho* **";
P_HTM[3374]="*iti vā iti evarūpāya tiracchānavijjāya micchājīvā paṭivirato hoti.* **";
P_HTM[3375]="*Idampissa hoti sīlasmiṃ.**This pertains to their ethics.*";
P_HTM[3376]="*Sa kho so, māṇava, bhikkhu evaṃ sīlasampanno na kutoci bhayaṃ samanupassati, yadidaṃ sīlasaṃvarato.**A mendicant thus accomplished in ethics sees no danger in any quarter in regards to their ethical restraint.*";
P_HTM[3377]="*Seyyathāpi, māṇava, rājā khattiyo muddhāvasitto nihatapaccāmitto na kutoci bhayaṃ samanupassati, yadidaṃ paccatthikato;**It’s like a king who has defeated his enemies. He sees no danger from his foes in any quarter.*";
P_HTM[3378]="*evameva kho, māṇava, bhikkhu evaṃ sīlasampanno na kutoci bhayaṃ samanupassati, yadidaṃ sīlasaṃvarato.**A mendicant thus accomplished in ethics sees no danger in any quarter in regards to their ethical restraint.*";
P_HTM[3379]="*So iminā ariyena sīlakkhandhena samannāgato ajjhattaṃ anavajjasukhaṃ paṭisaṃvedeti.**When they have this entire spectrum of noble ethics, they experience a blameless happiness inside themselves.*";
P_HTM[3380]="*Evaṃ kho, māṇava, bhikkhu sīlasampanno hoti.**That’s how a mendicant is accomplished in ethics.*";
P_HTM[3381]="*Ayaṃ kho so, māṇava, ariyo sīlakkhandho yassa so bhagavā vaṇṇavādī ahosi, yattha ca imaṃ janataṃ samādapesi nivesesi patiṭṭhāpesi.**This is that noble spectrum of ethics that the Buddha praised.*";
P_HTM[3382]="*Atthi cevettha uttarikaraṇīyan”ti.**But there is still more to be done.”*";
P_HTM[3383]="*“Acchariyaṃ, bho ānanda, abbhutaṃ, bho ānanda.**“It’s incredible, Master Ānanda, it’s amazing,*";
P_HTM[3384]="*So cāyaṃ, bho ānanda, ariyo sīlakkhandho paripuṇṇo, no aparipuṇṇo.**This noble spectrum of ethics is complete, not lacking anything!*";
P_HTM[3385]="*Evaṃ paripuṇṇañcāhaṃ, bho ānanda, ariyaṃ sīlakkhandhaṃ ito bahiddhā aññesu samaṇabrāhmaṇesu na samanupassāmi.**Such a complete spectrum of ethics cannot be seen among the other ascetics and brahmins.*";
P_HTM[3386]="*Evaṃ paripuṇṇañca, bho ānanda, ariyaṃ sīlakkhandhaṃ ito bahiddhā aññe samaṇabrāhmaṇā attani samanupasseyyuṃ, te tāvatakeneva attamanā assu:**Were other ascetics and brahmins to see such a complete spectrum of noble ethics in themselves, they’d be delighted with just that much:*";
P_HTM[3387]="*‘alamettāvatā, katamettāvatā, anuppatto no sāmaññattho, natthi no kiñci uttarikaraṇīyan’ti.**‘At this point it’s enough; at this point our work is done. We’ve reached the goal of our ascetic life. There is nothing more to be done.’*";
P_HTM[3388]="*Atha ca pana bhavaṃ ānando evamāha:**And yet you say:*";
P_HTM[3389]="*‘atthi cevettha uttarikaraṇīyan’”ti.**‘But there is still more to be done.’*";
P_HTM[3390]="*2. Samādhikkhandha**2. The Spectrum of Immersion*";
P_HTM[3391]="*“Katamo pana so, bho ānanda, ariyo samādhikkhandho, yassa so bhavaṃ gotamo vaṇṇavādī ahosi, yattha ca imaṃ janataṃ samādapesi nivesesi patiṭṭhāpesī”ti?**But what, Master Ānanda, was that noble spectrum of immersion that the Buddha praised?”*";
P_HTM[3392]="*“Kathañca, māṇava, bhikkhu indriyesu guttadvāro hoti?**“And how, student, does a mendicant guard the sense doors?*";
P_HTM[3393]="*Idha, māṇava, bhikkhu cakkhunā rūpaṃ disvā na nimittaggāhī hoti nānubyañjanaggāhī;**When a mendicant sees a sight with their eyes, they don’t get caught up in the features and details.*";
P_HTM[3394]="*yatvādhikaraṇamenaṃ cakkhundriyaṃ asaṃvutaṃ viharantaṃ abhijjhādomanassā pāpakā akusalā dhammā anvāssaveyyuṃ; tassa saṃvarāya paṭipajjati, rakkhati cakkhundriyaṃ, cakkhundriye saṃvaraṃ āpajjati.**If the faculty of sight were left unrestrained, bad unskillful qualities of desire and aversion would become overwhelming. For this reason, they practice restraint, protecting the faculty of sight, and achieving its restraint.*";
P_HTM[3395]="*Sotena saddaṃ sutvā … pe …**When they hear a sound with their ears …*";
P_HTM[3396]="*ghānena gandhaṃ ghāyitvā …**When they smell an odor with their nose …*";
P_HTM[3397]="*jivhāya rasaṃ sāyitvā …**When they taste a flavor with their tongue …*";
P_HTM[3398]="*kāyena phoṭṭhabbaṃ phusitvā …**When they feel a touch with their body …*";
P_HTM[3399]="*manasā dhammaṃ viññāya na nimittaggāhī hoti nānubyañjanaggāhī;**When they know a thought with their mind, they don’t get caught up in the features and details.*";
P_HTM[3400]="*yatvādhikaraṇamenaṃ manindriyaṃ asaṃvutaṃ viharantaṃ abhijjhādomanassā pāpakā akusalā dhammā anvāssaveyyuṃ; tassa saṃvarāya paṭipajjati, rakkhati manindriyaṃ, manindriye saṃvaraṃ āpajjati.**If the faculty of mind were left unrestrained, bad unskillful qualities of desire and aversion would become overwhelming. For this reason, they practice restraint, protecting the faculty of mind, and achieving its restraint.*";
P_HTM[3401]="*So iminā ariyena indriyasaṃvarena samannāgato ajjhattaṃ abyāsekasukhaṃ paṭisaṃvedeti.**When they have this noble sense restraint, they experience an unsullied bliss inside themselves.*";
P_HTM[3402]="*Evaṃ kho, māṇava, bhikkhu indriyesu guttadvāro hoti.**That’s how a mendicant guards the sense doors.*";
P_HTM[3403]="*Kathañca, māṇava, bhikkhu satisampajaññena samannāgato hoti?**And how does a mendicant have mindfulness and situational awareness?*";
P_HTM[3404]="*Idha, māṇava, bhikkhu abhikkante paṭikkante sampajānakārī hoti, ālokite vilokite sampajānakārī hoti, samiñjite pasārite sampajānakārī hoti, saṅghāṭipattacīvaradhāraṇe sampajānakārī hoti, asite pīte khāyite sāyite sampajānakārī hoti, uccārapassāvakamme sampajānakārī hoti, gate ṭhite nisinne sutte jāgarite bhāsite tuṇhībhāve sampajānakārī hoti.**It’s when a mendicant acts with situational awareness when going out and coming back; when looking ahead and aside; when bending and extending the limbs; when bearing the outer robe, bowl and robes; when eating, drinking, chewing, and tasting; when urinating and defecating; when walking, standing, sitting, sleeping, waking, speaking, and keeping silent.*";
P_HTM[3405]="*Evaṃ kho, māṇava, bhikkhu satisampajaññena samannāgato hoti.**That’s how a mendicant has mindfulness and situational awareness.*";
P_HTM[3406]="*Kathañca, māṇava, bhikkhu santuṭṭho hoti?**And how is a mendicant content?*";
P_HTM[3407]="*Idha, māṇava, bhikkhu santuṭṭho hoti kāyaparihārikena cīvarena kucchiparihārikena piṇḍapātena. So yena yeneva pakkamati, samādāyeva pakkamati.**It’s when a mendicant is content with robes to look after the body and alms-food to look after the belly. Wherever they go, they set out taking only these things.*";
P_HTM[3408]="*Seyyathāpi, māṇava, pakkhī sakuṇo yena yeneva ḍeti, sapattabhārova ḍeti;**They’re like a bird: wherever it flies, wings are its only burden.*";
P_HTM[3409]="*evameva kho, māṇava, bhikkhu santuṭṭho hoti kāyaparihārikena cīvarena kucchiparihārikena piṇḍapātena. So yena yeneva pakkamati, samādāyeva pakkamati.**In the same way, a mendicant is content with robes to look after the body and alms-food to look after the belly. Wherever they go, they set out taking only these things.*";
P_HTM[3410]="*Evaṃ kho, māṇava, bhikkhu santuṭṭho hoti.**That’s how a mendicant is content.*";
P_HTM[3411]="*So iminā ca ariyena sīlakkhandhena samannāgato, iminā ca ariyena indriyasaṃvarena samannāgato, iminā ca ariyena satisampajaññena samannāgato, imāya ca ariyāya santuṭṭhiyā samannāgato**When they have this noble spectrum of ethics, this noble sense restraint, this noble mindfulness and situational awareness, and this noble contentment,*";
P_HTM[3412]="*vivittaṃ senāsanaṃ bhajati araññaṃ rukkhamūlaṃ pabbataṃ kandaraṃ giriguhaṃ susānaṃ vanapatthaṃ abbhokāsaṃ palālapuñjaṃ.**they frequent a secluded lodging—a wilderness, the root of a tree, a hill, a ravine, a mountain cave, a charnel ground, a forest, the open air, a heap of straw.*";
P_HTM[3413]="*So pacchābhattaṃ piṇḍapātapaṭikkanto nisīdati pallaṅkaṃ ābhujitvā, ujuṃ kāyaṃ paṇidhāya, parimukhaṃ satiṃ upaṭṭhapetvā.**After the meal, they return from alms-round, sit down cross-legged with their body straight, and establish mindfulness right there.*";
P_HTM[3414]="*So abhijjhaṃ loke pahāya vigatābhijjhena cetasā viharati abhijjhāya cittaṃ parisodheti.**Giving up desire for the world, they meditate with a heart rid of desire, cleansing the mind of desire.*";
P_HTM[3415]="*Byāpādapadosaṃ pahāya abyāpannacitto viharati sabbapāṇabhūtahitānukampī byāpādapadosā cittaṃ parisodheti.**Giving up ill will and malevolence, they meditate with a mind rid of ill will, full of compassion for all living beings, cleansing the mind of ill will.*";
P_HTM[3416]="*Thinamiddhaṃ pahāya vigatathinamiddho viharati ālokasaññī sato sampajāno, thinamiddhā cittaṃ parisodheti.**Giving up dullness and drowsiness, they meditate with a mind rid of dullness and drowsiness, perceiving light, mindful and aware, cleansing the mind of dullness and drowsiness.*";
P_HTM[3417]="*Uddhaccakukkuccaṃ pahāya anuddhato viharati ajjhattaṃ vūpasantacitto uddhaccakukkuccā cittaṃ parisodheti.**Giving up restlessness and remorse, they meditate without restlessness, their mind peaceful inside, cleansing the mind of restlessness and remorse.*";
P_HTM[3418]="*Vicikicchaṃ pahāya tiṇṇavicikiccho viharati akathaṅkathī kusalesu dhammesu, vicikicchāya cittaṃ parisodheti.**Giving up doubt, they meditate having gone beyond doubt, not undecided about skillful qualities, cleansing the mind of doubt.*";
P_HTM[3419]="*Seyyathāpi, māṇava, puriso iṇaṃ ādāya kammante payojeyya.**Suppose a man who has gotten into debt were to apply himself to work,*";
P_HTM[3420]="*Tassa te kammantā samijjheyyuṃ.**and his efforts proved successful.*";
P_HTM[3421]="*So yāni ca porāṇāni iṇamūlāni tāni ca byantiṃ kareyya, siyā cassa uttariṃ avasiṭṭhaṃ dārabharaṇāya.**He would pay off the original loan and have enough left over to support his partner.*";
P_HTM[3422]="*Tassa evamassa:**Thinking about this,*";
P_HTM[3423]="*‘ahaṃ kho pubbe iṇaṃ ādāya kammante payojesiṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3424]="*Tassa me te kammantā samijjhiṃsu.* **";
P_HTM[3425]="*Sohaṃ yāni ca porāṇāni iṇamūlāni tāni ca byantiṃ akāsiṃ, atthi ca me uttariṃ avasiṭṭhaṃ dārabharaṇāyā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3426]="*So tatonidānaṃ labhetha pāmojjaṃ, adhigaccheyya somanassaṃ.**he’d be filled with joy and happiness.*";
P_HTM[3427]="*Seyyathāpi, māṇava, puriso ābādhiko assa dukkhito bāḷhagilāno; bhattañcassa nacchādeyya, na cassa kāye balamattā.**Suppose there was a person who was sick, suffering, gravely ill. They’d lose their appetite and get physically weak.*";
P_HTM[3428]="*So aparena samayena tamhā ābādhā mucceyya, bhattañcassa chādeyya, siyā cassa kāye balamattā.**But after some time they’d recover from that illness, and regain their appetite and their strength.*";
P_HTM[3429]="*Tassa evamassa:**Thinking about this,*";
P_HTM[3430]="*‘ahaṃ kho pubbe ābādhiko ahosiṃ dukkhito bāḷhagilāno, bhattañca me nacchādesi, na ca me āsi kāye balamattā.* **";
P_HTM[3431]="*Somhi etarahi tamhā ābādhā mutto bhattañca me chādeti, atthi ca me kāye balamattā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3432]="*So tatonidānaṃ labhetha pāmojjaṃ, adhigaccheyya somanassaṃ.**they’d be filled with joy and happiness.*";
P_HTM[3433]="*Seyyathāpi, māṇava, puriso bandhanāgāre baddho assa.**Suppose a person was imprisoned in a jail.*";
P_HTM[3434]="*So aparena samayena tamhā bandhanāgārā mucceyya sotthinā abbhayena, na cassa kiñci bhogānaṃ vayo.**But after some time they were released from jail, safe and sound, with no loss of wealth.*";
P_HTM[3435]="*Tassa evamassa:**Thinking about this,*";
P_HTM[3436]="*‘ahaṃ kho pubbe bandhanāgāre baddho ahosiṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3437]="*Somhi etarahi tamhā bandhanāgārā mutto sotthinā abbhayena, natthi ca me kiñci bhogānaṃ vayo’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3438]="*So tatonidānaṃ labhetha pāmojjaṃ, adhigaccheyya somanassaṃ.**they’d be filled with joy and happiness.*";
P_HTM[3439]="*Seyyathāpi, māṇava, puriso dāso assa anattādhīno parādhīno na yenakāmaṅgamo.**Suppose a person was a bondservant. They belonged to someone else and were unable to go where they wish.*";
P_HTM[3440]="*So aparena samayena tamhā dāsabyā mucceyya, attādhīno aparādhīno bhujisso yenakāmaṅgamo.**But after some time they’d be freed from servitude and become their own master, an emancipated individual able to go where they wish.*";
P_HTM[3441]="*Tassa evamassa:**Thinking about this,*";
P_HTM[3442]="*‘ahaṃ kho pubbe dāso ahosiṃ anattādhīno parādhīno na yenakāmaṅgamo.* **";
P_HTM[3443]="*Somhi etarahi tamhā dāsabyā mutto attādhīno aparādhīno bhujisso yenakāmaṅgamo’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3444]="*So tatonidānaṃ labhetha pāmojjaṃ, adhigaccheyya somanassaṃ.**they’d be filled with joy and happiness.*";
P_HTM[3445]="*Seyyathāpi, māṇava, puriso sadhano sabhogo kantāraddhānamaggaṃ paṭipajjeyya dubbhikkhaṃ sappaṭibhayaṃ.**Suppose there was a person with wealth and property who was traveling along a desert road, which was perilous, with nothing to eat.*";
P_HTM[3446]="*So aparena samayena taṃ kantāraṃ nitthareyya, sotthinā gāmantaṃ anupāpuṇeyya khemaṃ appaṭibhayaṃ.**But after some time they crossed over the desert safely, reaching the neighborhood of a village, a sanctuary free of peril.*";
P_HTM[3447]="*Tassa evamassa:**Thinking about this,*";
P_HTM[3448]="*‘ahaṃ kho pubbe sadhano sabhogo kantāraddhānamaggaṃ paṭipajjiṃ dubbhikkhaṃ sappaṭibhayaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3449]="*Somhi etarahi taṃ kantāraṃ nitthiṇṇo, sotthinā gāmantaṃ anuppatto khemaṃ appaṭibhayan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3450]="*So tatonidānaṃ labhetha pāmojjaṃ, adhigaccheyya somanassaṃ.**they’d be filled with joy and happiness.*";
P_HTM[3451]="*Evameva kho, māṇava, bhikkhu yathā iṇaṃ yathā rogaṃ yathā bandhanāgāraṃ yathā dāsabyaṃ yathā kantāraddhānamaggaṃ, evaṃ ime pañca nīvaraṇe appahīne attani samanupassati.**In the same way, as long as these five hindrances are not given up inside themselves, a mendicant regards them as a debt, a disease, a prison, slavery, and a desert crossing.*";
P_HTM[3452]="*Seyyathāpi, māṇava, yathā āṇaṇyaṃ yathā ārogyaṃ yathā bandhanāmokkhaṃ yathā bhujissaṃ yathā khemantabhūmiṃ.**But when these five hindrances are given up inside themselves, a mendicant regards this as freedom from debt, good health, release from prison, emancipation, and sanctuary.*";
P_HTM[3453]="*Evameva kho bhikkhu ime pañca nīvaraṇe pahīne attani samanupassati.* **";
P_HTM[3454]="*Tassime pañca nīvaraṇe pahīne attani samanupassato pāmojjaṃ jāyati, pamuditassa pīti jāyati, pītimanassa kāyo passambhati, passaddhakāyo sukhaṃ vedeti, sukhino cittaṃ samādhiyati.**Seeing that the hindrances have been given up in them, joy springs up. Being joyful, rapture springs up. When the mind is full of rapture, the body becomes tranquil. When the body is tranquil, they feel bliss. And when blissful, the mind becomes immersed.*";
P_HTM[3455]="*So vivicceva kāmehi vivicca akusalehi dhammehi savitakkaṃ savicāraṃ vivekajaṃ pītisukhaṃ paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Quite secluded from sensual pleasures, secluded from unskillful qualities, they enter and remain in the first absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of seclusion, while placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[3456]="*So imameva kāyaṃ vivekajena pītisukhena abhisandeti parisandeti paripūreti parippharati, nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa vivekajena pītisukhena apphuṭaṃ hoti.**They drench, steep, fill, and spread their body with rapture and bliss born of seclusion. There’s no part of the body that’s not spread with rapture and bliss born of seclusion.*";
P_HTM[3457]="*Seyyathāpi, māṇava, dakkho nhāpako vā nhāpakantevāsī vā kaṃsathāle nhānīyacuṇṇāni ākiritvā udakena paripphosakaṃ paripphosakaṃ sanneyya. Sāyaṃ nhānīyapiṇḍi snehānugatā snehaparetā santarabāhirā phuṭā snehena, na ca paggharaṇī.**It’s like when a deft bathroom attendant or their apprentice pours bath powder into a bronze dish, sprinkling it little by little with water. They knead it until the ball of bath powder is soaked and saturated with moisture, spread through inside and out; yet no moisture oozes out.*";
P_HTM[3458]="*Evameva kho, māṇava, bhikkhu imameva kāyaṃ vivekajena pītisukhena abhisandeti parisandeti paripūreti parippharati, nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa vivekajena pītisukhena apphuṭaṃ hoti.**In the same way, a mendicant drenches, steeps, fills, and spreads their body with rapture and bliss born of seclusion. There’s no part of the body that’s not spread with rapture and bliss born of seclusion.*";
P_HTM[3459]="*Yampi, māṇava, bhikkhu vivicceva kāmehi vivicca akusalehi dhammehi savitakkaṃ savicāraṃ vivekajaṃ pītisukhaṃ paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.* **";
P_HTM[3460]="*So imameva kāyaṃ vivekajena pītisukhena abhisandeti parisandeti paripūreti parippharati, nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa vivekajena pītisukhena apphuṭaṃ hoti.* **";
P_HTM[3461]="*Idampissa hoti samādhismiṃ.**This pertains to their immersion.*";
P_HTM[3462]="*Puna caparaṃ, māṇava, bhikkhu vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā ajjhattaṃ sampasādanaṃ cetaso ekodibhāvaṃ avitakkaṃ avicāraṃ samādhijaṃ pītisukhaṃ dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, as the placing of the mind and keeping it connected are stilled, a mendicant enters and remains in the second absorption, which has the rapture and bliss born of immersion, with internal clarity and confidence, and unified mind, without placing the mind and keeping it connected.*";
P_HTM[3463]="*So imameva kāyaṃ samādhijena pītisukhena abhisandeti parisandeti paripūreti parippharati, nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa samādhijena pītisukhena apphuṭaṃ hoti.**They drench, steep, fill, and spread their body with rapture and bliss born of immersion. There’s no part of the body that’s not spread with rapture and bliss born of immersion.*";
P_HTM[3464]="*Seyyathāpi, māṇava, udakarahado gambhīro ubbhidodako. Tassa nevassa puratthimāya disāya udakassa āyamukhaṃ, na dakkhiṇāya disāya udakassa āyamukhaṃ, na pacchimāya disāya udakassa āyamukhaṃ, na uttarāya disāya udakassa āyamukhaṃ, devo ca na kālena kālaṃ sammā dhāraṃ anupaveccheyya. Atha kho tamhāva udakarahadā sītā vāridhārā ubbhijjitvā tameva udakarahadaṃ sītena vārinā abhisandeyya parisandeyya paripūreyya paripphareyya, nāssa kiñci sabbāvato udakarahadassa sītena vārinā apphuṭaṃ assa.**It’s like a deep lake fed by spring water. There’s no inlet to the east, west, north, or south, and no rainfall to replenish it from time to time. But the stream of cool water welling up in the lake drenches, steeps, fills, and spreads throughout the lake. There’s no part of the lake that’s not spread through with cool water.*";
P_HTM[3465]="*Evameva kho, māṇava, bhikkhu … pe …**In the same way, a mendicant drenches, steeps, fills, and spreads their body with rapture and bliss born of immersion. There’s no part of the body that’s not spread with rapture and bliss born of immersion.*";
P_HTM[3466]="*yampi, māṇava, bhikkhu vitakkavicārānaṃ vūpasamā … pe … dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.* **";
P_HTM[3467]="*So imameva kāyaṃ samādhijena pītisukhena abhisandeti parisandeti paripūreti parippharati, nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa samādhijena pītisukhena apphuṭaṃ hoti.* **";
P_HTM[3468]="*Idampissa hoti samādhismiṃ.**This pertains to their immersion.*";
P_HTM[3469]="*Puna caparaṃ, māṇava, bhikkhu pītiyā ca virāgā upekkhako ca viharati sato sampajāno, sukhañca kāyena paṭisaṃvedeti, yaṃ taṃ ariyā ācikkhanti: ‘upekkhako satimā sukhavihārī’ti, tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, with the fading away of rapture, a mendicant enters and remains in the third absorption, where they meditate with equanimity, mindful and aware, personally experiencing the bliss of which the noble ones declare, ‘Equanimous and mindful, one meditates in bliss.’*";
P_HTM[3470]="*So imameva kāyaṃ nippītikena sukhena abhisandeti parisandeti paripūreti parippharati, nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa nippītikena sukhena apphuṭaṃ hoti.**They drench, steep, fill, and spread their body with bliss free of rapture. There’s no part of the body that’s not spread with bliss free of rapture.*";
P_HTM[3471]="*Seyyathāpi, māṇava, uppaliniyaṃ vā paduminiyaṃ vā puṇḍarīkiniyaṃ vā appekaccāni uppalāni vā padumāni vā puṇḍarīkāni vā udake jātāni udake saṃvaḍḍhāni udakānuggatāni antonimuggaposīni, tāni yāva caggā yāva ca mūlā sītena vārinā abhisannāni parisannāni paripūrāni paripphuṭāni, nāssa kiñci sabbāvataṃ uppalānaṃ vā padumānaṃ vā puṇḍarīkānaṃ vā sītena vārinā apphuṭaṃ assa.**It’s like a pool with blue water lilies, or pink or white lotuses. Some of them sprout and grow in the water without rising above it, thriving underwater. From the tip to the root they’re drenched, steeped, filled, and soaked with cool water. There’s no part of them that’s not soaked with cool water.*";
P_HTM[3472]="*Evameva kho, māṇava, bhikkhu … pe …**In the same way, a mendicant drenches, steeps, fills, and spreads their body with bliss free of rapture. There’s no part of the body that’s not spread with bliss free of rapture.*";
P_HTM[3473]="*yampi, māṇava, bhikkhu pītiyā ca virāgā … pe … tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.* **";
P_HTM[3474]="*So imameva kāyaṃ nippītikena sukhena abhisandeti parisandeti paripūreti parippharati, nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa nippītikena sukhena apphuṭaṃ hoti.* **";
P_HTM[3475]="*Idampissa hoti samādhismiṃ.**This pertains to their immersion.*";
P_HTM[3476]="*Puna caparaṃ, māṇava, bhikkhu sukhassa ca pahānā dukkhassa ca pahānā pubbeva somanassadomanassānaṃ atthaṅgamā adukkhamasukhaṃ upekkhāsatipārisuddhiṃ catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**Furthermore, giving up pleasure and pain, and ending former happiness and sadness, a mendicant enters and remains in the fourth absorption, without pleasure or pain, with pure equanimity and mindfulness.*";
P_HTM[3477]="*So imameva kāyaṃ parisuddhena cetasā pariyodātena pharitvā nisinno hoti;**They sit spreading their body through with pure bright mind.*";
P_HTM[3478]="*nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa parisuddhena cetasā pariyodātena apphuṭaṃ hoti.**There’s no part of the body that’s not spread with pure bright mind.*";
P_HTM[3479]="*Seyyathāpi, māṇava, puriso odātena vatthena sasīsaṃ pārupitvā nisinno assa, nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa odātena vatthena apphuṭaṃ assa.**It’s like someone sitting wrapped from head to foot with white cloth. There’s no part of the body that’s not spread over with white cloth.*";
P_HTM[3480]="*Evameva kho, māṇava, bhikkhu … pe …**In the same way, a mendicant sits spreading their body through with pure bright mind. There's no part of their body that's not spread with pure bright mind.*";
P_HTM[3481]="*yampi, māṇava, bhikkhu sukhassa ca pahānā dukkhassa ca pahānā pubbeva somanassadomanassānaṃ atthaṅgamā adukkhamasukhaṃ upekkhāsatipārisuddhiṃ catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.* **";
P_HTM[3482]="*So imameva kāyaṃ parisuddhena cetasā pariyodātena pharitvā nisinno hoti; nāssa kiñci sabbāvato kāyassa parisuddhena cetasā pariyodātena apphuṭaṃ hoti.* **";
P_HTM[3483]="*Idampissa hoti samādhismiṃ.**This pertains to their immersion.*";
P_HTM[3484]="*Ayaṃ kho so, māṇava, ariyo samādhikkhandho yassa so bhagavā vaṇṇavādī ahosi, yattha ca imaṃ janataṃ samādapesi nivesesi patiṭṭhāpesi.**This is that noble spectrum of immersion that the Buddha praised.*";
P_HTM[3485]="*Atthi cevettha uttarikaraṇīyan”ti.**But there is still more to be done.”*";
P_HTM[3486]="*“Acchariyaṃ, bho ānanda, abbhutaṃ, bho ānanda.**“It’s incredible, Master Ānanda, it’s amazing!*";
P_HTM[3487]="*So cāyaṃ, bho ānanda, ariyo samādhikkhandho paripuṇṇo, no aparipuṇṇo.**This noble spectrum of immersion is complete, not lacking anything!*";
P_HTM[3488]="*Evaṃ paripuṇṇañcāhaṃ, bho ānanda, ariyaṃ samādhikkhandhaṃ ito bahiddhā aññesu samaṇabrāhmaṇesu na samanupassāmi.**Such a complete spectrum of immersion cannot be seen among the other ascetics and brahmins.*";
P_HTM[3489]="*Evaṃ paripuṇṇañca, bho ānanda, ariyaṃ samādhikkhandhaṃ ito bahiddhā aññe samaṇabrāhmaṇā attani samanupasseyyuṃ, te tāvatakeneva attamanā assu:**Were other ascetics and brahmins to see such a complete spectrum of noble immersion in themselves, they’d be delighted with just that much:*";
P_HTM[3490]="*‘alamettāvatā, katamettāvatā, anuppatto no sāmaññattho, natthi no kiñci uttarikaraṇīyan’ti.**‘At this point it’s enough; at this point our work is done. We’ve reached the goal of our ascetic life. There is nothing more to be done.’*";
P_HTM[3491]="*Atha ca pana bhavaṃ ānando evamāha:**And yet you say:*";
P_HTM[3492]="*‘atthi cevettha uttarikaraṇīyan’ti.**‘But there is still more to be done.’*";
P_HTM[3493]="*3. Paññākkhandha**3. The Spectrum of Wisdom*";
P_HTM[3494]="*Katamo pana so, bho ānanda, ariyo paññākkhandho, yassa bho bhavaṃ gotamo vaṇṇavādī ahosi, yattha ca imaṃ janataṃ samādapesi nivesesi patiṭṭhāpesī”ti?**But what, Master Ānanda, was that noble spectrum of wisdom that the Buddha praised?”*";
P_HTM[3495]="*“So evaṃ samāhite citte parisuddhe pariyodāte anaṅgaṇe vigatūpakkilese mudubhūte kammaniye ṭhite āneñjappatte ñāṇadassanāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti.**“When their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it and project it toward knowledge and vision.*";
P_HTM[3496]="*So evaṃ pajānāti:**They understand:*";
P_HTM[3497]="*‘ayaṃ kho me kāyo rūpī cātumahābhūtiko mātāpettikasambhavo odanakummāsūpacayo aniccucchādanaparimaddanabhedanaviddhaṃsanadhammo; idañca pana me viññāṇaṃ ettha sitaṃ ettha paṭibaddhan’ti.**‘This body of mine is physical. It’s made up of the four primary elements, produced by mother and father, built up from rice and porridge, liable to impermanence, to wearing away and erosion, to breaking up and destruction. And this consciousness of mine is attached to it, tied to it.’*";
P_HTM[3498]="*Seyyathāpi, māṇava, maṇi veḷuriyo subho jātimā aṭṭhaṃso suparikammakato accho vippasanno anāvilo sabbākārasampanno. Tatrāssa suttaṃ āvutaṃ nīlaṃ vā pītaṃ vā lohitaṃ vā odātaṃ vā paṇḍusuttaṃ vā.**Suppose there was a beryl gem that was naturally beautiful, eight-faceted, well-worked, transparent, clear, and unclouded, endowed with all good qualities. And it was strung with a thread of blue, yellow, red, white, or golden brown.*";
P_HTM[3499]="*Tamenaṃ cakkhumā puriso hatthe karitvā paccavekkheyya: ‘ayaṃ kho maṇi veḷuriyo subho jātimā aṭṭhaṃso suparikammakato accho vippasanno anāvilo sabbākārasampanno. Tatridaṃ suttaṃ āvutaṃ nīlaṃ vā pītaṃ vā lohitaṃ vā odātaṃ vā paṇḍusuttaṃ vā’ti.**And someone with good eyesight were to take it in their hand and examine it: ‘This beryl gem is naturally beautiful, eight-faceted, well-worked, transparent, clear, and unclouded, endowed with all good qualities. And it’s strung with a thread of blue, yellow, red, white, or golden brown.’*";
P_HTM[3500]="*Evameva kho, māṇava, bhikkhu evaṃ samāhite citte parisuddhe pariyodāte anaṅgaṇe vigatūpakkilese mudubhūte kammaniye ṭhite āneñjappatte ñāṇadassanāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti.**In the same way, when their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it and project it toward knowledge and vision.*";
P_HTM[3501]="*So evaṃ pajānāti:* **";
P_HTM[3502]="*‘ayaṃ kho me kāyo rūpī cātumahābhūtiko mātāpettikasambhavo odanakummāsūpacayo aniccucchādanaparimaddanabhedanaviddhaṃsanadhammo. Idañca pana me viññāṇaṃ ettha sitaṃ ettha paṭibaddhan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3503]="*Yampi, māṇava, bhikkhu evaṃ samāhite citte … pe …* **";
P_HTM[3504]="*āneñjappatte ñāṇadassanāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti.* **";
P_HTM[3505]="*So evaṃ pajānāti … pe …* **";
P_HTM[3506]="*ettha paṭibaddhanti.* **";
P_HTM[3507]="*Idampissa hoti paññāya.**This pertains to their wisdom.*";
P_HTM[3508]="*So evaṃ samāhite citte parisuddhe pariyodāte anaṅgaṇe vigatūpakkilese mudubhūte kammaniye ṭhite āneñjappatte manomayaṃ kāyaṃ abhinimmānāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti.**When their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it and project it toward the creation of a mind-made body.*";
P_HTM[3509]="*So imamhā kāyā aññaṃ kāyaṃ abhinimmināti rūpiṃ manomayaṃ sabbaṅgapaccaṅgiṃ ahīnindriyaṃ.**From this body they create another body, physical, mind-made, complete in all its various parts, not deficient in any faculty.*";
P_HTM[3510]="*Seyyathāpi, māṇava, puriso muñjamhā īsikaṃ pavāheyya.**Suppose a person was to draw a reed out from its sheath.*";
P_HTM[3511]="*Tassa evamassa:**They’d think:*";
P_HTM[3512]="*‘ayaṃ muñjo ayaṃ īsikā; añño muñjo aññā īsikā; muñjamhā tveva īsikā pavāḷhā’ti.**‘This is the reed, this is the sheath. The reed and the sheath are different things. The reed has been drawn out from the sheath.’*";
P_HTM[3513]="*Seyyathā vā pana, māṇava, puriso asiṃ kosiyā pavāheyya.**Or suppose a person was to draw a sword out from its scabbard.*";
P_HTM[3514]="*Tassa evamassa:**They’d think:*";
P_HTM[3515]="*‘ayaṃ asi, ayaṃ kosi; añño asi, aññā kosi; kosiyā tveva asi pavāḷho’ti.**‘This is the sword, this is the scabbard. The sword and the scabbard are different things. The sword has been drawn out from the scabbard.’*";
P_HTM[3516]="*Seyyathā vā pana, māṇava, puriso ahiṃ karaṇḍā uddhareyya.**Or suppose a person was to draw a snake out from its slough.*";
P_HTM[3517]="*Tassa evamassa:**They’d think:*";
P_HTM[3518]="*‘ayaṃ ahi, ayaṃ karaṇḍo; añño ahi, añño karaṇḍo; karaṇḍā tveva ahi ubbhato’ti.**‘This is the snake, this is the slough. The snake and the slough are different things. The snake has been drawn out from the slough.’*";
P_HTM[3519]="*Evameva kho, māṇava, bhikkhu … pe …**In the same way, when their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it and project it toward the creation of a mind-made body.*";
P_HTM[3520]="*yampi, māṇava, bhikkhu evaṃ samāhite citte parisuddhe pariyodāte anaṅgaṇe vigatūpakkilese mudubhūte kammaniye ṭhite āneñjappatte manomayaṃ kāyaṃ abhinimmānāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti … pe ….* **";
P_HTM[3521]="*Idampissa hoti paññāya.**This pertains to their wisdom.*";
P_HTM[3522]="*So evaṃ samāhite citte parisuddhe pariyodāte anaṅgaṇe vigatūpakkilese mudubhūte kammaniye ṭhite āneñjappatte iddhividhāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti.**When their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it and project it toward psychic power.*";
P_HTM[3523]="*So anekavihitaṃ iddhividhaṃ paccanubhoti—ekopi hutvā bahudhā hoti, bahudhāpi hutvā eko hoti; āvibhāvaṃ tirobhāvaṃ tirokuṭṭaṃ tiropākāraṃ tiropabbataṃ asajjamāno gacchati seyyathāpi ākāse; pathaviyāpi ummujjanimujjaṃ karoti seyyathāpi udake; udakepi abhijjamāne gacchati seyyathāpi pathaviyaṃ; ākāsepi pallaṅkena kamati seyyathāpi pakkhī sakuṇo; imepi candimasūriye evaṃ mahiddhike evaṃ mahānubhāve pāṇinā parāmasati parimajjati; yāva brahmalokāpi kāyena vasaṃ vatteti.**They wield the many kinds of psychic power: multiplying themselves and becoming one again; going unimpeded through a wall, a rampart, or a mountain as if through space; diving in and out of the earth as if it were water; walking on water as if it were earth; flying cross-legged through the sky like a bird; touching and stroking with the hand the sun and moon, so mighty and powerful; controlling the body as far as the Brahmā realm.*";
P_HTM[3524]="*Seyyathāpi, māṇava, dakkho kumbhakāro vā kumbhakārantevāsī vā suparikammakatāya mattikāya yaññadeva bhājanavikatiṃ ākaṅkheyya, taṃ tadeva kareyya abhinipphādeyya.**Suppose an expert potter or their apprentice had some well-prepared clay. They could produce any kind of pot that they like.*";
P_HTM[3525]="*Seyyathā vā pana, māṇava, dakkho dantakāro vā dantakārantevāsī vā suparikammakatasmiṃ dantasmiṃ yaññadeva dantavikatiṃ ākaṅkheyya, taṃ tadeva kareyya abhinipphādeyya.**Or suppose an expert ivory-carver or their apprentice had some well-prepared ivory. They could produce any kind of ivory item that they like.*";
P_HTM[3526]="*Seyyathā vā pana, māṇava, dakkho suvaṇṇakāro vā suvaṇṇakārantevāsī vā suparikammakatasmiṃ suvaṇṇasmiṃ yaññadeva suvaṇṇavikatiṃ ākaṅkheyya, taṃ tadeva kareyya abhinipphādeyya.**Or suppose an expert goldsmith or their apprentice had some well-prepared gold. They could produce any kind of gold item that they like.*";
P_HTM[3527]="*Evameva kho, māṇava, bhikkhu … pe … yampi māṇava bhikkhu evaṃ samāhite citte parisuddhe pariyodāte anaṅgaṇe vigatūpakkilese mudubhūte kammaniye ṭhite āneñjappatte iddhividhāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti.**In the same way, when their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it and project it toward psychic power.*";
P_HTM[3528]="*So anekavihitaṃ iddhividhaṃ paccanubhoti—ekopi hutvā bahudhā hoti … pe … yāva brahmalokāpi kāyena vasaṃ vatteti.* **";
P_HTM[3529]="*Idampissa hoti paññāya.**This pertains to their wisdom.*";
P_HTM[3530]="*So evaṃ samāhite citte … pe … āneñjappatte dibbāya sotadhātuyā cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti**When their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it and project it toward clairaudience.*";
P_HTM[3531]="*So dibbāya sotadhātuyā visuddhāya atikkantamānusikāya ubho sadde suṇāti dibbe ca mānuse ca ye dūre santike ca.**With clairaudience that is purified and superhuman, they hear both kinds of sounds, human and divine, whether near or far.*";
P_HTM[3532]="*Seyyathāpi, māṇava, puriso addhānamaggappaṭipanno. So suṇeyya bherisaddampi mudiṅgasaddampi saṅkhapaṇavadindimasaddampi. Tassa evamassa—bherisaddo itipi mudiṅgasaddo itipi saṅkhapaṇavadindimasaddo itipi.**Suppose there was a person traveling along the road. They’d hear the sound of drums, clay drums, horns, kettledrums, and tom-toms. They’d think: ‘That’s the sound of drums,’ and ‘that’s the sound of clay-drums,’ and ‘that’s the sound of horns, kettledrums, and tom-toms.’*";
P_HTM[3533]="*Evameva kho, māṇava, bhikkhu … pe …**In the same way, when their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it and project it toward clairaudience.*";
P_HTM[3534]="*yampi, māṇava, bhikkhu evaṃ samāhite citte … pe … āneñjappatte dibbāya sotadhātuyā cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti.* **";
P_HTM[3535]="*So dibbāya sotadhātuyā visuddhāya atikkantamānusikāya ubho sadde suṇāti dibbe ca mānuse ca ye dūre santike ca.* **";
P_HTM[3536]="*Idampissa hoti paññāya.**This pertains to their wisdom.*";
P_HTM[3537]="*So evaṃ samāhite citte parisuddhe pariyodāte anaṅgaṇe vigatūpakkilese mudubhūte kammaniye ṭhite āneñjappatte cetopariyañāṇāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti.**When their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it and project it toward comprehending the minds of others.*";
P_HTM[3538]="*So parasattānaṃ parapuggalānaṃ cetasā ceto paricca pajānāti, sarāgaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘sarāgaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, vītarāgaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘vītarāgaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, sadosaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘sadosaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, vītadosaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘vītadosaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, samohaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘samohaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, vītamohaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘vītamohaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, saṅkhittaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘saṅkhittaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, vikkhittaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘vikkhittaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, mahaggataṃ vā cittaṃ ‘mahaggataṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, amahaggataṃ vā cittaṃ ‘amahaggataṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, sauttaraṃ vā cittaṃ ‘sauttaraṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, anuttaraṃ vā cittaṃ ‘anuttaraṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, samāhitaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘samāhitaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, asamāhitaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘asamāhitaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, vimuttaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘vimuttaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti, avimuttaṃ vā cittaṃ ‘avimuttaṃ cittan’ti pajānāti.**They understand mind with greed as ‘mind with greed’, and mind without greed as ‘mind without greed’. They understand mind with hate … mind without hate … mind with delusion … mind without delusion … constricted mind … scattered mind … expansive mind … unexpansive mind … mind that is not supreme … mind that is supreme … immersed mind … unimmersed mind … freed mind … They understand unfreed mind as ‘unfreed mind’.*";
P_HTM[3539]="*Seyyathāpi, māṇava, itthī vā puriso vā daharo yuvā maṇḍanajātiko ādāse vā parisuddhe pariyodāte acche vā udakapatte sakaṃ mukhanimittaṃ paccavekkhamāno sakaṇikaṃ vā sakaṇikanti jāneyya, akaṇikaṃ vā akaṇikanti jāneyya.**Suppose there was a woman or man who was young, youthful, and fond of adornments, and they check their own reflection in a clean bright mirror or a clear bowl of water. If they had a spot they’d know ‘I have a spot,’ and if they had no spots they’d know ‘I have no spots.’*";
P_HTM[3540]="*Evameva kho, māṇava, bhikkhu … pe …**In the same way, when their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it and project it toward comprehending the minds of others.*";
P_HTM[3541]="*yampi, māṇava, bhikkhu evaṃ samāhite … pe … āneñjappatte cetopariyañāṇāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti.* **";
P_HTM[3542]="*So parasattānaṃ parapuggalānaṃ cetasā ceto paricca pajānāti, sarāgaṃ vā cittaṃ sarāgaṃ cittanti pajānāti … pe … avimuttaṃ vā cittaṃ avimuttaṃ cittanti pajānāti.* **";
P_HTM[3543]="*Idampissa hoti paññāya.**This pertains to their wisdom.*";
P_HTM[3544]="*So evaṃ samāhite citte … pe … āneñjappatte pubbenivāsānussatiñāṇāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti**When their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it and project it toward recollection of past lives.*";
P_HTM[3545]="*So anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati. Seyyathidaṃ—ekampi jātiṃ dvepi jātiyo tissopi jātiyo catassopi jātiyo pañcapi jātiyo dasapi jātiyo vīsampi jātiyo tiṃsampi jātiyo cattālīsampi jātiyo paññāsampi jātiyo jātisatampi jātisahassampi jātisatasahassampi anekepi saṃvaṭṭakappe anekepi vivaṭṭakappe anekepi saṃvaṭṭavivaṭṭakappe: ‘amutrāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṅgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto. So tato cuto amutra udapādiṃ; tatrāpāsiṃ evaṃnāmo evaṅgotto evaṃvaṇṇo evamāhāro evaṃsukhadukkhappaṭisaṃvedī evamāyupariyanto; so tato cuto idhūpapanno’ti. Iti sākāraṃ sauddesaṃ anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati.**They recollect many kinds of past lives, that is, one, two, three, four, five, ten, twenty, thirty, forty, fifty, a hundred, a thousand, a hundred thousand rebirths; many eons of the world contracting, many eons of the world expanding, many eons of the world contracting and expanding. They remember: ‘There, I was named this, my clan was that, I looked like this, and that was my food. This was how I felt pleasure and pain, and that was how my life ended. When I passed away from that place I was reborn somewhere else. Passing away from there, I was reborn elsewhere, and there I had such a name, such a family, such appearance, such food, such experience of happiness and suffering, and such a life-span. Passing away from there, I was reborn here.’ And so they recollect their many kinds of past lives, with features and details.*";
P_HTM[3546]="*Seyyathāpi, māṇava, puriso sakamhā gāmā aññaṃ gāmaṃ gaccheyya; tamhāpi gāmā aññaṃ gāmaṃ gaccheyya; so tamhā gāmā sakaṃyeva gāmaṃ paccāgaccheyya. Tassa evamassa: ‘ahaṃ kho sakamhā gāmā amuṃ gāmaṃ agacchiṃ, tatra evaṃ aṭṭhāsiṃ evaṃ nisīdiṃ evaṃ abhāsiṃ evaṃ tuṇhī ahosiṃ. So tamhāpi gāmā amuṃ gāmaṃ gacchiṃ, tatrāpi evaṃ aṭṭhāsiṃ evaṃ nisīdiṃ evaṃ abhāsiṃ evaṃ tuṇhī ahosiṃ. Somhi tamhā gāmā sakaṃyeva gāmaṃ paccāgato’ti.**Suppose a person was to leave their home village and go to another village. From that village they’d go to yet another village. And from that village they’d return to their home village. They’d think: ‘I went from my home village to another village. There I stood like this, sat like that, spoke like this, or kept silent like that. From that village I went to yet another village. There too I stood like this, sat like that, spoke like this, or kept silent like that. And from that village I returned to my home village.’*";
P_HTM[3547]="*Evameva kho, māṇava, bhikkhu … pe … yampi, māṇava, bhikkhu evaṃ samāhite citte … pe … āneñjappatte pubbenivāsānussatiñāṇāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti.**In the same way, when their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it and project it toward recollection of past lives.*";
P_HTM[3548]="*So anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati. Seyyathidaṃ—ekampi jātiṃ … pe … iti sākāraṃ sauddesaṃ anekavihitaṃ pubbenivāsaṃ anussarati.* **";
P_HTM[3549]="*Idampissa hoti paññāya.**This pertains to their wisdom.*";
P_HTM[3550]="*So evaṃ samāhite citte … pe … āneñjappatte sattānaṃ cutūpapātañāṇāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti.**When their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it and project it toward knowledge of the death and rebirth of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[3551]="*So dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena satte passati cavamāne upapajjamāne hīne paṇīte suvaṇṇe dubbaṇṇe sugate duggate, yathākammūpage satte pajānāti: ‘ime vata bhonto sattā kāyaduccaritena samannāgatā vacīduccaritena samannāgatā manoduccaritena samannāgatā ariyānaṃ upavādakā micchādiṭṭhikā micchādiṭṭhikammasamādānā. Te kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apāyaṃ duggatiṃ vinipātaṃ nirayaṃ upapannā. Ime vā pana bhonto sattā kāyasucaritena samannāgatā vacīsucaritena samannāgatā manosucaritena samannāgatā ariyānaṃ anupavādakā sammādiṭṭhikā sammādiṭṭhikammasamādānā. Te kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā sugatiṃ saggaṃ lokaṃ upapannā’ti. Iti dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena satte passati cavamāne upapajjamāne hīne paṇīte suvaṇṇe dubbaṇṇe sugate duggate, yathākammūpage satte pajānāti.**With clairvoyance that is purified and superhuman, they see sentient beings passing away and being reborn—inferior and superior, beautiful and ugly, in a good place or a bad place. They understand how sentient beings are reborn according to their deeds. ‘These dear beings did bad things by way of body, speech, and mind. They spoke ill of the noble ones; they had wrong view; and they chose to act out of that wrong view. When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a place of loss, a bad place, the underworld, hell. These dear beings, however, did good things by way of body, speech, and mind. They never spoke ill of the noble ones; they had right view; and they chose to act out of that right view. When their body breaks up, after death, they’re reborn in a good place, a heavenly realm.’ And so, with clairvoyance that is purified and superhuman, they see sentient beings passing away and being reborn—inferior and superior, beautiful and ugly, in a good place or a bad place. They understand how sentient beings are reborn according to their deeds.*";
P_HTM[3552]="*Seyyathāpi, māṇava, majjhesiṅghāṭake pāsādo, tattha cakkhumā puriso ṭhito passeyya manusse gehaṃ pavisantepi nikkhamantepi rathikāyapi vīthiṃ sañcarante majjhesiṅghāṭake nisinnepi. Tassa evamassa: ‘ete manussā gehaṃ pavisanti, ete nikkhamanti, ete rathikāya vīthiṃ sañcaranti, ete majjhesiṅghāṭake nisinnā’ti.**Suppose there was a stilt longhouse at the central square. A person with good eyesight standing there might see people entering and leaving a house, walking along the streets and paths, and sitting at the central square. They’d think: ‘These are people entering and leaving a house, walking along the streets and paths, and sitting at the central square.’*";
P_HTM[3553]="*Evameva kho, māṇava, bhikkhu … pe …**In the same way, when their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend and project it toward knowledge of the death and rebirth of sentient beings.*";
P_HTM[3554]="*yampi, māṇava, bhikkhu evaṃ samāhite citte … pe … āneñjappatte sattānaṃ cutūpapātañāṇāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti.* **";
P_HTM[3555]="*So dibbena cakkhunā visuddhena atikkantamānusakena satte passati cavamāne upapajjamāne hīne paṇīte suvaṇṇe dubbaṇṇe sugate duggate, yathākammūpage satte pajānāti.* **";
P_HTM[3556]="*Idampissa hoti paññāya.**This pertains to their wisdom.*";
P_HTM[3557]="*So evaṃ samāhite citte parisuddhe pariyodāte anaṅgaṇe vigatūpakkilese mudubhūte kammaniye ṭhite āneñjappatte āsavānaṃ khayañāṇāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti.**When their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it and project it toward knowledge of the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[3558]="*So idaṃ dukkhanti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ayaṃ dukkhasamudayoti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ayaṃ dukkhanirodhoti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ayaṃ dukkhanirodhagāminī paṭipadāti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti;**They truly understand: ‘This is suffering’ … ‘This is the origin of suffering’ … ‘This is the cessation of suffering’ … ‘This is the practice that leads to the cessation of suffering’.*";
P_HTM[3559]="*ime āsavāti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ayaṃ āsavasamudayoti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ayaṃ āsavanirodhoti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti, ayaṃ āsavanirodhagāminī paṭipadāti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.**They truly understand: ‘These are defilements’ … ‘This is the origin of defilements’ … ‘This is the cessation of defilements’ … ‘This is the practice that leads to the cessation of defilements’.*";
P_HTM[3560]="*Tassa evaṃ jānato evaṃ passato kāmāsavāpi cittaṃ vimuccati, bhavāsavāpi cittaṃ vimuccati, avijjāsavāpi cittaṃ vimuccati,**Knowing and seeing like this, their mind is freed from the defilements of sensuality, desire to be reborn, and ignorance.*";
P_HTM[3561]="*vimuttasmiṃ vimuttamiti ñāṇaṃ hoti.**When they’re freed, they know they’re freed.*";
P_HTM[3562]="*‘Khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānāti.**They understand: ‘Rebirth is ended, the spiritual journey has been completed, what had to be done has been done, there is no return to any state of existence.’*";
P_HTM[3563]="*Seyyathāpi, māṇava, pabbatasaṅkhepe udakarahado accho vippasanno anāvilo. Tattha cakkhumā puriso tīre ṭhito passeyya sippisambukampi sakkharakathalampi macchagumbampi carantampi tiṭṭhantampi. Tassa evamassa: ‘ayaṃ kho udakarahado accho vippasanno anāvilo. Tatrime sippisambukāpi sakkharakathalāpi macchagumbāpi carantipi tiṭṭhantipī’ti.**Suppose that in a mountain glen there was a lake that was transparent, clear, and unclouded. A person with good eyesight standing on the bank would see the mussel shells, gravel and pebbles, and schools of fish swimming about or staying still. They’d think: ‘This lake is transparent, clear, and unclouded. And here are the mussel shells, gravel and pebbles, and schools of fish swimming about or staying still.’*";
P_HTM[3564]="*Evameva kho, māṇava, bhikkhu … pe …**In the same way, when their mind has become immersed in samādhi like this—purified, bright, flawless, rid of corruptions, pliable, workable, steady, and imperturbable—they extend it and project it toward knowledge of the ending of defilements.*";
P_HTM[3565]="*yampi, māṇava, bhikkhu evaṃ samāhite citte … pe … āneñjappatte āsavānaṃ khayañāṇāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti.* **";
P_HTM[3566]="*So idaṃ dukkhanti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti … pe …* **";
P_HTM[3567]="*āsavanirodhagāminī paṭipadāti yathābhūtaṃ pajānāti.* **";
P_HTM[3568]="*Tassa evaṃ jānato evaṃ passato kāmāsavāpi cittaṃ vimuccati, bhavāsavāpi cittaṃ vimuccati, avijjāsavāpi cittaṃ vimuccati, vimuttasmiṃ vimuttamiti ñāṇaṃ hoti, ‘khīṇā jāti, vusitaṃ brahmacariyaṃ, kataṃ karaṇīyaṃ, nāparaṃ itthattāyā’ti pajānāti.* **";
P_HTM[3569]="*Idampissa hoti paññāya.**This pertains to their wisdom.*";
P_HTM[3570]="*Ayaṃ kho so, māṇava, ariyo paññākkhandho yassa so bhagavā vaṇṇavādī ahosi, yattha ca imaṃ janataṃ samādapesi nivesesi patiṭṭhāpesi.**This is that noble spectrum of wisdom that the Buddha praised.*";
P_HTM[3571]="*Natthi cevettha uttarikaraṇīyan”ti.**And there is nothing more to be done.”*";
P_HTM[3572]="*“Acchariyaṃ, bho ānanda, abbhutaṃ, bho ānanda.**“It’s incredible, Master Ānanda, it’s amazing!*";
P_HTM[3573]="*So cāyaṃ, bho ānanda, ariyo paññākkhandho paripuṇṇo, no aparipuṇṇo.**This noble spectrum of wisdom is complete, not lacking anything!*";
P_HTM[3574]="*Evaṃ paripuṇṇañcāhaṃ, bho ānanda, ariyaṃ paññākkhandhaṃ ito bahiddhā aññesu samaṇabrāhmaṇesu na samanupassāmi.**Such a complete spectrum of wisdom cannot be seen among the other ascetics and brahmins.*";
P_HTM[3575]="*Natthi cevettha uttarikaraṇīyaṃ.**And there is nothing more to be done.*";
P_HTM[3576]="*Abhikkantaṃ, bho ānanda, abhikkantaṃ, bho ānanda.**Excellent, Master Ānanda! Excellent!*";
P_HTM[3577]="*Seyyathāpi, bho ānanda, nikkujjitaṃ vā ukkujjeyya, paṭicchannaṃ vā vivareyya, mūḷhassa vā maggaṃ ācikkheyya, andhakāre vā telapajjotaṃ dhāreyya: ‘cakkhumanto rūpāni dakkhantī’ti; evamevaṃ bhotā ānandena anekapariyāyena dhammo pakāsito.**As if he were righting the overturned, or revealing the hidden, or pointing out the path to the lost, or lighting a lamp in the dark so people with good eyes can see what’s there, Master Ānanda has made the teaching clear in many ways.*";
P_HTM[3578]="*Esāhaṃ, bho ānanda, taṃ bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ saraṇaṃ gacchāmi dhammañca bhikkhusaṃghañca.**I go for refuge to Master Gotama, to the teaching, and to the mendicant Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[3579]="*Upāsakaṃ maṃ bhavaṃ ānando dhāretu ajjatagge pāṇupetaṃ saraṇaṃ gatan”ti.**From this day forth, may Master Ānanda remember me as a lay follower who has gone for refuge for life.”*";
P_HTM[3580]="*Subhasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ dasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3581]="*11. Kevaṭṭasutta  - With Kevaddha * **";
P_HTM[3582]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[3583]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā nāḷandāyaṃ viharati pāvārikambavane.**At one time the Buddha was staying near Nālandā in Pāvārika’s mango grove.*";
P_HTM[3584]="*Atha kho kevaṭṭo gahapatiputto yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho kevaṭṭo gahapatiputto bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**Then the householder Kevaddha went up to the Buddha, bowed, sat down to one side, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[3585]="*“ayaṃ, bhante, nāḷandā iddhā ceva phītā ca bahujanā ākiṇṇamanussā bhagavati abhippasannā.**“Sir, this Nāḷandā is successful and prosperous and full of people.*";
P_HTM[3586]="*Sādhu, bhante, bhagavā ekaṃ bhikkhuṃ samādisatu, yo uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ karissati;**Sir, please direct a mendicant to perform a demonstration of superhuman psychic power.*";
P_HTM[3587]="*evāyaṃ nāḷandā bhiyyoso mattāya bhagavati abhippasīdissatī”ti.**Then Nāḷandā will become even more devoted to the Buddha!”*";
P_HTM[3588]="*Evaṃ vutte, bhagavā kevaṭṭaṃ gahapatiputtaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, The Buddha said,*";
P_HTM[3589]="*“na kho ahaṃ, kevaṭṭa, bhikkhūnaṃ evaṃ dhammaṃ desemi:**“Kevaddha, I do not teach the mendicants like this:*";
P_HTM[3590]="*‘etha tumhe, bhikkhave, gihīnaṃ odātavasanānaṃ uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ karothā’”ti.**‘Come now, mendicants, perform a demonstration of superhuman psychic power for the white-clothed laypeople.’”*";
P_HTM[3591]="*Dutiyampi kho kevaṭṭo gahapatiputto bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**For a second time, Kevaddha made the same request,*";
P_HTM[3592]="*“nāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavantaṃ dhaṃsemi;* **";
P_HTM[3593]="*api ca evaṃ vadāmi:* **";
P_HTM[3594]="*‘ayaṃ, bhante, nāḷandā iddhā ceva phītā ca bahujanā ākiṇṇamanussā bhagavati abhippasannā.* **";
P_HTM[3595]="*Sādhu, bhante, bhagavā ekaṃ bhikkhuṃ samādisatu, yo uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ karissati;* **";
P_HTM[3596]="*evāyaṃ nāḷandā bhiyyoso mattāya bhagavati abhippasīdissatī’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3597]="*Dutiyampi kho bhagavā kevaṭṭaṃ gahapatiputtaṃ etadavoca:**and the Buddha gave the same answer.*";
P_HTM[3598]="*“na kho ahaṃ, kevaṭṭa, bhikkhūnaṃ evaṃ dhammaṃ desemi:* **";
P_HTM[3599]="*‘etha tumhe, bhikkhave, gihīnaṃ odātavasanānaṃ uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ karothā’”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3600]="*Tatiyampi kho kevaṭṭo gahapatiputto bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**For a third time, Kevaddha made the same request,*";
P_HTM[3601]="*“nāhaṃ, bhante, bhagavantaṃ dhaṃsemi;* **";
P_HTM[3602]="*api ca evaṃ vadāmi:* **";
P_HTM[3603]="*‘ayaṃ, bhante, nāḷandā iddhā ceva phītā ca bahujanā ākiṇṇamanussā bhagavati abhippasannā.* **";
P_HTM[3604]="*Sādhu, bhante, bhagavā ekaṃ bhikkhuṃ samādisatu, yo uttari manussadhammā iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ karissati.* **";
P_HTM[3605]="*Evāyaṃ nāḷandā bhiyyoso mattāya bhagavati abhippasīdissatī’”ti.**and the Buddha said the following.*";
P_HTM[3606]="*1. Iddhipāṭihāriya**1. The Demonstration of Psychic Power*";
P_HTM[3607]="*“Tīṇi kho imāni, kevaṭṭa, pāṭihāriyāni mayā sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā paveditāni.**“Kevaddha, there are three kinds of demonstration, which I declare having realized them with my own insight.*";
P_HTM[3608]="*Katamāni tīṇi?**What three?*";
P_HTM[3609]="*Iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ, ādesanāpāṭihāriyaṃ, anusāsanīpāṭihāriyaṃ.**The demonstration of psychic power, the demonstration of revealing, and the demonstration of instruction.*";
P_HTM[3610]="*Katamañca, kevaṭṭa, iddhipāṭihāriyaṃ?**And what is the demonstration of psychic power?*";
P_HTM[3611]="*Idha, kevaṭṭa, bhikkhu anekavihitaṃ iddhividhaṃ paccanubhoti—ekopi hutvā bahudhā hoti, bahudhāpi hutvā eko hoti; āvibhāvaṃ tirobhāvaṃ tirokuṭṭaṃ tiropākāraṃ tiropabbataṃ asajjamāno gacchati seyyathāpi ākāse; pathaviyāpi ummujjanimujjaṃ karoti seyyathāpi udake; udakepi abhijjamāne gacchati seyyathāpi pathaviyaṃ; ākāsepi pallaṅkena kamati seyyathāpi pakkhī sakuṇo; imepi candimasūriye evaṃ mahiddhike evaṃ mahānubhāve pāṇinā parāmasati parimajjati; yāva brahmalokāpi kāyena vasaṃ vatteti.**It’s a mendicant who wields the many kinds of psychic power: multiplying themselves and becoming one again; going unimpeded through a wall, a rampart, or a mountain as if through space; diving in and out of the earth as if it were water; walking on water as if it were earth; flying cross-legged through the sky like a bird; touching and stroking with the hand the sun and moon, so mighty and powerful; controlling the body as far as the Brahmā realm.*";
P_HTM[3612]="*Tamenaṃ aññataro saddho pasanno passati taṃ bhikkhuṃ anekavihitaṃ iddhividhaṃ paccanubhontaṃ—ekopi hutvā bahudhā hontaṃ, bahudhāpi hutvā eko hontaṃ; āvibhāvaṃ tirobhāvaṃ; tirokuṭṭaṃ tiropākāraṃ tiropabbataṃ asajjamānaṃ gacchantaṃ seyyathāpi ākāse; pathaviyāpi ummujjanimujjaṃ karontaṃ seyyathāpi udake; udakepi abhijjamāne gacchantaṃ seyyathāpi pathaviyaṃ; ākāsepi pallaṅkena kamantaṃ seyyathāpi pakkhī sakuṇo; imepi candimasūriye evaṃ mahiddhike evaṃ mahānubhāve pāṇinā parāmasantaṃ parimajjantaṃ yāva brahmalokāpi kāyena vasaṃ vattentaṃ.**Then someone with faith and confidence sees that mendicant performing those superhuman feats.*";
P_HTM[3613]="*Tamenaṃ so saddho pasanno aññatarassa assaddhassa appasannassa āroceti:**They tell someone else who lacks faith and confidence:*";
P_HTM[3614]="*‘acchariyaṃ vata bho, abbhutaṃ vata bho, samaṇassa mahiddhikatā mahānubhāvatā.**‘It’s incredible, it’s amazing! The ascetic has such psychic power and might!*";
P_HTM[3615]="*Amāhaṃ bhikkhuṃ addasaṃ anekavihitaṃ iddhividhaṃ paccanubhontaṃ—ekopi hutvā bahudhā hontaṃ, bahudhāpi hutvā eko hontaṃ … pe … yāva brahmalokāpi kāyena vasaṃ vattentan’ti.**I saw him myself, performing all these superhuman feats!’*";
P_HTM[3616]="*Tamenaṃ so assaddho appasanno taṃ saddhaṃ pasannaṃ evaṃ vadeyya:**But the one lacking faith and confidence would say to them:*";
P_HTM[3617]="*‘atthi kho, bho, gandhārī nāma vijjā.**‘There’s a spell named Gandhārī.*";
P_HTM[3618]="*Tāya so bhikkhu anekavihitaṃ iddhividhaṃ paccanubhoti—ekopi hutvā bahudhā hoti, bahudhāpi hutvā eko hoti … pe … yāva brahmalokāpi kāyena vasaṃ vattetī’ti.**Using that a mendicant can perform such superhuman feats.’*";
P_HTM[3619]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, kevaṭṭa,**What do you think, Kevaddha?*";
P_HTM[3620]="*api nu so assaddho appasanno taṃ saddhaṃ pasannaṃ evaṃ vadeyyā”ti?**Wouldn’t someone lacking faith speak like that?”*";
P_HTM[3621]="*“Vadeyya, bhante”ti.**“They would, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3622]="*“Imaṃ kho ahaṃ, kevaṭṭa, iddhipāṭihāriye ādīnavaṃ sampassamāno iddhipāṭihāriyena aṭṭīyāmi harāyāmi jigucchāmi.**“Seeing this drawback in psychic power, I’m horrified, repelled, and disgusted by demonstrations of psychic power.*";
P_HTM[3623]="*2. Ādesanāpāṭihāriya**2. The Demonstration of Revealing*";
P_HTM[3624]="*Katamañca, kevaṭṭa, ādesanāpāṭihāriyaṃ?**And what is the demonstration of revealing?*";
P_HTM[3625]="*Idha, kevaṭṭa, bhikkhu parasattānaṃ parapuggalānaṃ cittampi ādisati, cetasikampi ādisati, vitakkitampi ādisati, vicāritampi ādisati:**In one case, someone reveals the mind, mentality, thoughts, and reflections of other beings and individuals:*";
P_HTM[3626]="*‘evampi te mano, itthampi te mano, itipi te cittan’ti.**‘This is what you’re thinking, such is your thought, and thus is your state of mind.’*";
P_HTM[3627]="*Tamenaṃ aññataro saddho pasanno passati taṃ bhikkhuṃ parasattānaṃ parapuggalānaṃ cittampi ādisantaṃ, cetasikampi ādisantaṃ, vitakkitampi ādisantaṃ, vicāritampi ādisantaṃ:**Then someone with faith and confidence sees that mendicant revealing another person’s thoughts.*";
P_HTM[3628]="*‘evampi te mano, itthampi te mano, itipi te cittan’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3629]="*Tamenaṃ so saddho pasanno aññatarassa assaddhassa appasannassa āroceti:**They tell someone else who lacks faith and confidence:*";
P_HTM[3630]="*‘acchariyaṃ vata bho, abbhutaṃ vata bho, samaṇassa mahiddhikatā mahānubhāvatā.**‘It’s incredible, it’s amazing! The ascetic has such psychic power and might!*";
P_HTM[3631]="*Amāhaṃ bhikkhuṃ addasaṃ parasattānaṃ parapuggalānaṃ cittampi ādisantaṃ, cetasikampi ādisantaṃ, vitakkitampi ādisantaṃ, vicāritampi ādisantaṃ:**I saw him myself, revealing the thoughts of another person!’*";
P_HTM[3632]="*“evampi te mano, itthampi te mano, itipi te cittan”’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3633]="*Tamenaṃ so assaddho appasanno taṃ saddhaṃ pasannaṃ evaṃ vadeyya:**But the one lacking faith and confidence would say to them:*";
P_HTM[3634]="*‘atthi kho, bho, maṇikā nāma vijjā;**‘There’s a spell named Māṇikā.*";
P_HTM[3635]="*tāya so bhikkhu parasattānaṃ parapuggalānaṃ cittampi ādisati, cetasikampi ādisati, vitakkitampi ādisati, vicāritampi ādisati:**Using that a mendicant can reveal another person’s thoughts.’*";
P_HTM[3636]="*“evampi te mano, itthampi te mano, itipi te cittan”’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3637]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, kevaṭṭa,**What do you think, Kevaddha?*";
P_HTM[3638]="*api nu so assaddho appasanno taṃ saddhaṃ pasannaṃ evaṃ vadeyyā”ti?**Wouldn’t someone lacking faith speak like that?”*";
P_HTM[3639]="*“Vadeyya, bhante”ti.**“They would, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3640]="*“Imaṃ kho ahaṃ, kevaṭṭa, ādesanāpāṭihāriye ādīnavaṃ sampassamāno ādesanāpāṭihāriyena aṭṭīyāmi harāyāmi jigucchāmi.**“Seeing this drawback in psychic power, I’m horrified, repelled, and disgusted by demonstrations of psychic power.*";
P_HTM[3641]="*3. Anusāsanīpāṭihāriya**3. The Demonstration of Instruction*";
P_HTM[3642]="*Katamañca, kevaṭṭa, anusāsanīpāṭihāriyaṃ?**And what is the demonstration of instruction?*";
P_HTM[3643]="*Idha, kevaṭṭa, bhikkhu evamanusāsati:**It’s when a mendicant instructs others like this:*";
P_HTM[3644]="*‘evaṃ vitakketha, mā evaṃ vitakkayittha, evaṃ manasikarotha, mā evaṃ manasākattha, idaṃ pajahatha, idaṃ upasampajja viharathā’ti.**‘Think like this, not like that. Focus your mind like this, not like that. Give up this, and live having achieved that.’*";
P_HTM[3645]="*Idaṃ vuccati, kevaṭṭa, anusāsanīpāṭihāriyaṃ.**This is called the demonstration of instruction.*";
P_HTM[3646]="*Puna caparaṃ, kevaṭṭa, idha tathāgato loke uppajjati arahaṃ sammāsambuddho … pe …**Furthermore, a Realized One arises in the world …*";
P_HTM[3647]="*Evaṃ kho, kevaṭṭa, bhikkhu sīlasampanno hoti … pe …**That’s how a mendicant is accomplished in ethics. …*";
P_HTM[3648]="*paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**They enter and remain in the first absorption …*";
P_HTM[3649]="*Idampi vuccati, kevaṭṭa, anusāsanīpāṭihāriyaṃ … pe …**This is called the demonstration of instruction.*";
P_HTM[3650]="*dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ … pe …**They enter and remain in the second absorption …*";
P_HTM[3651]="*tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ … pe …**third absorption …*";
P_HTM[3652]="*catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**fourth absorption.*";
P_HTM[3653]="*Idampi vuccati, kevaṭṭa, anusāsanīpāṭihāriyaṃ … pe …**This too is called the demonstration of instruction.*";
P_HTM[3654]="*ñāṇadassanāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti … pe …**They extend and project the mind toward knowledge and vision …*";
P_HTM[3655]="*idampi vuccati, kevaṭṭa, anusāsanīpāṭihāriyaṃ … pe …**This too is called the demonstration of instruction.*";
P_HTM[3656]="*nāparaṃ itthattāyāti pajānāti … pe …**They understand: ‘… there is no return to any state of existence.’*";
P_HTM[3657]="*idampi vuccati, kevaṭṭa, anusāsanīpāṭihāriyaṃ.**This too is called the demonstration of instruction.*";
P_HTM[3658]="*Imāni kho, kevaṭṭa, tīṇi pāṭihāriyāni mayā sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā paveditāni.**These, Kevaddha, are the three kinds of demonstration, which I declare having realized them with my own insight.*";
P_HTM[3659]="*4. Bhūtanirodhesakabhikkhuvatthu**4. On the Mendicant In Search of the Cessation of Being*";
P_HTM[3660]="*Bhūtapubbaṃ, kevaṭṭa, imasmiññeva bhikkhusaṅghe aññatarassa bhikkhuno evaṃ cetaso parivitakko udapādi:**Once it so happened, Kevaddha, that a mendicant in this very Saṅgha had the following thought,*";
P_HTM[3661]="*‘kattha nu kho ime cattāro mahābhūtā aparisesā nirujjhanti, seyyathidaṃ—pathavīdhātu āpodhātu tejodhātu vāyodhātū’ti?**‘Where do these four primary elements cease without anything left over, namely, the elements of earth, water, fire, and air?’*";
P_HTM[3662]="*Atha kho so, kevaṭṭa, bhikkhu tathārūpaṃ samādhiṃ samāpajji, yathāsamāhite citte devayāniyo maggo pāturahosi.**Then that mendicant attained a state of immersion such that a path to the gods appeared.*";
P_HTM[3663]="*Atha kho so, kevaṭṭa, bhikkhu yena cātumahārājikā devā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā cātumahārājike deve etadavoca:**Then he approached the Gods of the Four Great Kings and said,*";
P_HTM[3664]="*‘kattha nu kho, āvuso, ime cattāro mahābhūtā aparisesā nirujjhanti, seyyathidaṃ—pathavīdhātu āpodhātu tejodhātu vāyodhātū’ti?**‘Reverends, where do these four primary elements cease without anything left over, namely, the elements of earth, water, fire, and air?’*";
P_HTM[3665]="*Evaṃ vutte, kevaṭṭa, cātumahārājikā devā taṃ bhikkhuṃ etadavocuṃ:**When he said this, those gods said to him,*";
P_HTM[3666]="*‘mayampi kho, bhikkhu, na jānāma:**‘Mendicant, we too do not know this.*";
P_HTM[3667]="*“yatthime cattāro mahābhūtā aparisesā nirujjhanti, seyyathidaṃ—pathavīdhātu āpodhātu tejodhātu vāyodhātū”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3668]="*Atthi kho, bhikkhu, cattāro mahārājāno amhehi abhikkantatarā ca paṇītatarā ca.**But the Four Great Kings are our superiors.*";
P_HTM[3669]="*Te kho etaṃ jāneyyuṃ:**They might know.’*";
P_HTM[3670]="*“yatthime cattāro mahābhūtā aparisesā nirujjhanti, seyyathidaṃ—pathavīdhātu āpodhātu tejodhātu vāyodhātū”’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3671]="*Atha kho so, kevaṭṭa, bhikkhu yena cattāro mahārājāno tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā cattāro mahārāje etadavoca:**Then he approached the Four Great Kings and asked the same question.*";
P_HTM[3672]="*‘kattha nu kho, āvuso, ime cattāro mahābhūtā aparisesā nirujjhanti, seyyathidaṃ—pathavīdhātu āpodhātu tejodhātu vāyodhātū’ti?* **";
P_HTM[3673]="*Evaṃ vutte, kevaṭṭa, cattāro mahārājāno taṃ bhikkhuṃ etadavocuṃ:**But they also said to him,*";
P_HTM[3674]="*‘mayampi kho, bhikkhu, na jānāma:**‘Mendicant, we too do not know this.*";
P_HTM[3675]="*“yatthime cattāro mahābhūtā aparisesā nirujjhanti, seyyathidaṃ—pathavīdhātu, āpodhātu tejodhātu vāyodhātū”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3676]="*Atthi kho, bhikkhu, tāvatiṃsā nāma devā amhehi abhikkantatarā ca paṇītatarā ca.**But the gods of the Thirty-Three …*";
P_HTM[3677]="*Te kho etaṃ jāneyyuṃ:* **";
P_HTM[3678]="*“yatthime cattāro mahābhūtā aparisesā nirujjhanti, seyyathidaṃ—pathavīdhātu āpodhātu tejodhātu vāyodhātū”’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3679]="*Atha kho so, kevaṭṭa, bhikkhu yena tāvatiṃsā devā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā tāvatiṃse deve etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[3680]="*‘kattha nu kho, āvuso, ime cattāro mahābhūtā aparisesā nirujjhanti, seyyathidaṃ—pathavīdhātu āpodhātu tejodhātu vāyodhātū’ti?* **";
P_HTM[3681]="*Evaṃ vutte, kevaṭṭa, tāvatiṃsā devā taṃ bhikkhuṃ etadavocuṃ:* **";
P_HTM[3682]="*‘mayampi kho, bhikkhu, na jānāma:* **";
P_HTM[3683]="*“yatthime cattāro mahābhūtā aparisesā nirujjhanti, seyyathidaṃ—pathavīdhātu āpodhātu tejodhātu vāyodhātū”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3684]="*Atthi kho, bhikkhu, sakko nāma devānamindo amhehi abhikkantataro ca paṇītataro ca.**Sakka, lord of gods …*";
P_HTM[3685]="*So kho etaṃ jāneyya:* **";
P_HTM[3686]="*“yatthime cattāro mahābhūtā aparisesā nirujjhanti, seyyathidaṃ—pathavīdhātu āpodhātu tejodhātu vāyodhātū”’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3687]="*Atha kho so, kevaṭṭa, bhikkhu yena sakko devānamindo tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā sakkaṃ devānamindaṃ etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[3688]="*‘kattha nu kho, āvuso, ime cattāro mahābhūtā aparisesā nirujjhanti, seyyathidaṃ—pathavīdhātu āpodhātu tejodhātu vāyodhātū’ti?* **";
P_HTM[3689]="*Evaṃ vutte, kevaṭṭa, sakko devānamindo taṃ bhikkhuṃ etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[3690]="*‘ahampi kho, bhikkhu, na jānāmi:* **";
P_HTM[3691]="*“yatthime cattāro mahābhūtā aparisesā nirujjhanti, seyyathidaṃ—pathavīdhātu āpodhātu tejodhātu vāyodhātū”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3692]="*Atthi kho, bhikkhu, yāmā nāma devā … pe …**the gods of Yāmā …*";
P_HTM[3693]="*suyāmo nāma devaputto …**the god named Suyāma …*";
P_HTM[3694]="*tusitā nāma devā …**the Joyful gods …*";
P_HTM[3695]="*santussito nāma devaputto …**the god named Santussita …*";
P_HTM[3696]="*nimmānaratī nāma devā …**the gods who delight in creation …*";
P_HTM[3697]="*sunimmito nāma devaputto …**the god named Sunimmita …*";
P_HTM[3698]="*paranimmitavasavattī nāma devā …**the gods who control the creation of others …*";
P_HTM[3699]="*vasavattī nāma devaputto amhehi abhikkantataro ca paṇītataro ca.**the god named Vasavattī …*";
P_HTM[3700]="*So kho etaṃ jāneyya:* **";
P_HTM[3701]="*“yatthime cattāro mahābhūtā aparisesā nirujjhanti, seyyathidaṃ—pathavīdhātu āpodhātu tejodhātu vāyodhātū”’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3702]="*Atha kho so, kevaṭṭa, bhikkhu yena vasavattī devaputto tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā vasavattiṃ devaputtaṃ etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[3703]="*‘kattha nu kho, āvuso, ime cattāro mahābhūtā aparisesā nirujjhanti, seyyathidaṃ—pathavīdhātu āpodhātu tejodhātu vāyodhātū’ti?* **";
P_HTM[3704]="*Evaṃ vutte, kevaṭṭa, vasavattī devaputto taṃ bhikkhuṃ etadavoca:* **";
P_HTM[3705]="*‘ahampi kho, bhikkhu, na jānāmi:* **";
P_HTM[3706]="*“yatthime cattāro mahābhūtā aparisesā nirujjhanti, seyyathidaṃ—pathavīdhātu āpodhātu tejodhātu vāyodhātū”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3707]="*Atthi kho, bhikkhu, brahmakāyikā nāma devā amhehi abhikkantatarā ca paṇītatarā ca.**the gods of Brahmā’s Host.*";
P_HTM[3708]="*Te kho etaṃ jāneyyuṃ:**They might know.’*";
P_HTM[3709]="*“yatthime cattāro mahābhūtā aparisesā nirujjhanti, seyyathidaṃ—pathavīdhātu āpodhātu tejodhātu vāyodhātū”’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3710]="*Atha kho so, kevaṭṭa, bhikkhu tathārūpaṃ samādhiṃ samāpajji, yathāsamāhite citte brahmayāniyo maggo pāturahosi.**Then that mendicant attained a state of immersion such that a path to Brahmā appeared.*";
P_HTM[3711]="*Atha kho so, kevaṭṭa, bhikkhu yena brahmakāyikā devā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā brahmakāyike deve etadavoca:**Then he approached those gods and said,*";
P_HTM[3712]="*‘kattha nu kho, āvuso, ime cattāro mahābhūtā aparisesā nirujjhanti, seyyathidaṃ—pathavīdhātu āpodhātu tejodhātu vāyodhātū’ti?**‘Reverends, where do these four primary elements cease without anything left over, namely, the elements of earth, water, fire, and air?’*";
P_HTM[3713]="*Evaṃ vutte, kevaṭṭa, brahmakāyikā devā taṃ bhikkhuṃ etadavocuṃ:**But they also said to him,*";
P_HTM[3714]="*‘mayampi kho, bhikkhu, na jānāma:**‘Mendicant, we too do not know this.*";
P_HTM[3715]="*“yatthime cattāro mahābhūtā aparisesā nirujjhanti, seyyathidaṃ—pathavīdhātu āpodhātu tejodhātu vāyodhātū”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3716]="*Atthi kho, bhikkhu, brahmā mahābrahmā abhibhū anabhibhūto aññadatthudaso vasavattī issaro kattā nimmātā seṭṭho sajitā vasī pitā bhūtabhabyānaṃ amhehi abhikkantataro ca paṇītataro ca.**But there is Brahmā, the Great Brahmā, the Undefeated, the Champion, the Universal Seer, the Wielder of Power, the Lord God, the Maker, the Author, the Best, the Begetter, the Controller, the Father of those who have been born and those yet to be born. He is our superior.*";
P_HTM[3717]="*So kho etaṃ jāneyya:**He might know.’*";
P_HTM[3718]="*“yatthime cattāro mahābhūtā aparisesā nirujjhanti, seyyathidaṃ—pathavīdhātu āpodhātu tejodhātu vāyodhātū”’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3719]="*‘Kahaṃ panāvuso, etarahi so mahābrahmā’ti?**‘But reverends, where is that Brahmā now?’*";
P_HTM[3720]="*‘Mayampi kho, bhikkhu, na jānāma, yattha vā brahmā yena vā brahmā yahiṃ vā brahmā;**‘We also don’t know where he is or what way he lies.*";
P_HTM[3721]="*api ca, bhikkhu, yathā nimittā dissanti, āloko sañjāyati, obhāso pātubhavati, brahmā pātubhavissati, brahmuno hetaṃ pubbanimittaṃ pātubhāvāya, yadidaṃ āloko sañjāyati, obhāso pātubhavatī’ti.**But by the signs that are seen—light arising and radiance appearing—we know that Brahmā will appear. For this is the precursor for the appearance of Brahmā, namely light arising and radiance appearing.’*";
P_HTM[3722]="*Atha kho so, kevaṭṭa, mahābrahmā nacirasseva pāturahosi.**Not long afterwards, the Great Brahmā appeared.*";
P_HTM[3723]="*Atha kho so, kevaṭṭa, bhikkhu yena so mahābrahmā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā taṃ mahābrahmānaṃ etadavoca:**Then that mendicant approached the Great Brahmā and said to him,*";
P_HTM[3724]="*‘kattha nu kho, āvuso, ime cattāro mahābhūtā aparisesā nirujjhanti, seyyathidaṃ—pathavīdhātu āpodhātu tejodhātu vāyodhātū’ti?**‘Reverend, where do these four primary elements cease without anything left over, namely, the elements of earth, water, fire, and air?’*";
P_HTM[3725]="*Evaṃ vutte, kevaṭṭa, so mahābrahmā taṃ bhikkhuṃ etadavoca:**The Great Brahmā said to him,*";
P_HTM[3726]="*‘ahamasmi, bhikkhu, brahmā mahābrahmā abhibhū anabhibhūto aññadatthudaso vasavattī issaro kattā nimmātā seṭṭho sajitā vasī pitā bhūtabhabyānan’ti.**‘I am Brahmā, the Great Brahmā, the Undefeated, the Champion, the Universal Seer, the Wielder of Power, the Lord God, the Maker, the Author, the Best, the Begetter, the Controller, the Father of those who have been born and those yet to be born.’*";
P_HTM[3727]="*Dutiyampi kho so, kevaṭṭa, bhikkhu taṃ mahābrahmānaṃ etadavoca:**For a second time, that mendicant said to the Great Brahmā,*";
P_HTM[3728]="*‘na khohaṃ taṃ, āvuso, evaṃ pucchāmi:**‘Reverend, I am not asking you whether you are*";
P_HTM[3729]="*“tvamasi brahmā mahābrahmā abhibhū anabhibhūto aññadatthudaso vasavattī issaro kattā nimmātā seṭṭho sajitā vasī pitā bhūtabhabyānan”ti.**Brahmā, the Great Brahmā, the Undefeated, the Champion, the Universal Seer, the Wielder of Power, the Lord God, the Maker, the Author, the Best, the Begetter, the Controller, the Father of those who have been born and those yet to be born.*";
P_HTM[3730]="*Evañca kho ahaṃ taṃ, āvuso, pucchāmi:**I am asking*";
P_HTM[3731]="*“kattha nu kho, āvuso, ime cattāro mahābhūtā aparisesā nirujjhanti, seyyathidaṃ—pathavīdhātu āpodhātu tejodhātu vāyodhātū”’ti?**where these four primary elements cease without anything left over.’*";
P_HTM[3732]="*Dutiyampi kho so, kevaṭṭa, mahābrahmā taṃ bhikkhuṃ etadavoca:**For a second time, the Great Brahmā said to him,*";
P_HTM[3733]="*‘ahamasmi, bhikkhu, brahmā mahābrahmā abhibhū anabhibhūto aññadatthudaso vasavattī issaro kattā nimmātā seṭṭho sajitā vasī pitā bhūtabhabyānan’ti.**‘I am Brahmā, the Great Brahmā, the Undefeated, the Champion, the Universal Seer, the Wielder of Power, the Lord God, the Maker, the Author, the Best, the Begetter, the Controller, the Father of those who have been born and those yet to be born.’*";
P_HTM[3734]="*Tatiyampi kho so, kevaṭṭa, bhikkhu taṃ mahābrahmānaṃ etadavoca:**For a third time, that mendicant said to the Great Brahmā,*";
P_HTM[3735]="*‘na khohaṃ taṃ, āvuso, evaṃ pucchāmi:**‘Reverend, I am not asking you whether you are*";
P_HTM[3736]="*“tvamasi brahmā mahābrahmā abhibhū anabhibhūto aññadatthudaso vasavattī issaro kattā nimmātā seṭṭho sajitā vasī pitā bhūtabhabyānan”ti.**Brahmā, the Great Brahmā, the Undefeated, the Champion, the Universal Seer, the Wielder of Power, the Lord God, the Maker, the Author, the Best, the Begetter, the Controller, the Father of those who have been born and those yet to be born.*";
P_HTM[3737]="*Evañca kho ahaṃ taṃ, āvuso, pucchāmi:**I am asking*";
P_HTM[3738]="*“kattha nu kho, āvuso, ime cattāro mahābhūtā aparisesā nirujjhanti, seyyathidaṃ—pathavīdhātu āpodhātu tejodhātu vāyodhātū”’ti?**where these four primary elements cease without anything left over.’*";
P_HTM[3739]="*Atha kho so, kevaṭṭa, mahābrahmā taṃ bhikkhuṃ bāhāyaṃ gahetvā ekamantaṃ apanetvā taṃ bhikkhuṃ etadavoca:**Then the Great Brahmā took that mendicant by the arm, led him off to one side, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[3740]="*‘ime kho maṃ, bhikkhu, brahmakāyikā devā evaṃ jānanti, “natthi kiñci brahmuno aññātaṃ, natthi kiñci brahmuno adiṭṭhaṃ, natthi kiñci brahmuno aviditaṃ, natthi kiñci brahmuno asacchikatan”ti.**‘Mendicant, these gods think that there is nothing at all that I don’t know and see and understand and realize.*";
P_HTM[3741]="*Tasmāhaṃ tesaṃ sammukhā na byākāsiṃ.**That’s why I didn’t answer in front of them.*";
P_HTM[3742]="*Ahampi kho, bhikkhu, na jānāmi yatthime cattāro mahābhūtā aparisesā nirujjhanti, seyyathidaṃ—pathavīdhātu āpodhātu tejodhātu vāyodhātūti.**But I too do not know where these four primary elements cease with nothing left over.*";
P_HTM[3743]="*Tasmātiha, bhikkhu, tuyhevetaṃ dukkaṭaṃ, tuyhevetaṃ aparaddhaṃ, yaṃ tvaṃ taṃ bhagavantaṃ atidhāvitvā bahiddhā pariyeṭṭhiṃ āpajjasi imassa pañhassa veyyākaraṇāya.**Therefore, mendicant, the misdeed is yours alone, the mistake is yours alone, in that you passed over the Buddha and searched elsewhere for an answer to this question.*";
P_HTM[3744]="*Gaccha tvaṃ, bhikkhu, tameva bhagavantaṃ upasaṅkamitvā imaṃ pañhaṃ puccha, yathā ca te bhagavā byākaroti, tathā naṃ dhāreyyāsī’ti.**Mendicant, go to the Buddha and ask him this question. You should remember it in line with his answer.’*";
P_HTM[3745]="*Atha kho so, kevaṭṭa, bhikkhu—seyyathāpi nāma balavā puriso samiñjitaṃ vā bāhaṃ pasāreyya, pasāritaṃ vā bāhaṃ samiñjeyya; evameva brahmaloke antarahito mama purato pāturahosi.**Then that mendicant, as easily as a strong person would extend or contract their arm, vanished from the Brahmā realm and reappeared in front of me.*";
P_HTM[3746]="*Atha kho so, kevaṭṭa, bhikkhu maṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi, ekamantaṃ nisinno kho, kevaṭṭa, so bhikkhu maṃ etadavoca:**Then he bowed, sat down to one side, and said to me,*";
P_HTM[3747]="*‘kattha nu kho, bhante, ime cattāro mahābhūtā aparisesā nirujjhanti, seyyathidaṃ—pathavīdhātu āpodhātu tejodhātu vāyodhātū’ti?**‘Sir, where do these four primary elements cease without anything left over, namely, the elements of earth, water, fire, and air?’*";
P_HTM[3748]="*4.1. Tīradassisakuṇupamā**4.1. The Simile of the Land-Spotting Bird*";
P_HTM[3749]="*Evaṃ vutte, ahaṃ, kevaṭṭa, taṃ bhikkhuṃ etadavocaṃ—**When he said this, I said to him:*";
P_HTM[3750]="*bhūtapubbaṃ, bhikkhu, sāmuddikā vāṇijā tīradassiṃ sakuṇaṃ gahetvā nāvāya samuddaṃ ajjhogāhanti.**‘Once upon a time, mendicant, some sea-merchants set sail for the ocean deeps, taking with them a land-spotting bird.*";
P_HTM[3751]="*Te atīradakkhiniyā nāvāya tīradassiṃ sakuṇaṃ muñcanti.**When their ship was out of sight of land, they released the bird.*";
P_HTM[3752]="*So gacchateva puratthimaṃ disaṃ, gacchati dakkhiṇaṃ disaṃ, gacchati pacchimaṃ disaṃ, gacchati uttaraṃ disaṃ, gacchati uddhaṃ disaṃ, gacchati anudisaṃ.**It flew right away to the east, the west, the north, the south, upwards, and in-between.*";
P_HTM[3753]="*Sace so samantā tīraṃ passati, tathāgatakova hoti.**If it saw land on any side, it went there and stayed.*";
P_HTM[3754]="*Sace pana so samantā tīraṃ na passati, tameva nāvaṃ paccāgacchati.**But if it saw no land on any side it returned to the ship.*";
P_HTM[3755]="*Evameva kho tvaṃ, bhikkhu, yato yāva brahmalokā pariyesamāno imassa pañhassa veyyākaraṇaṃ nājjhagā, atha mamaññeva santike paccāgato.**In the same way, after failing to get an answer to this question even after searching as far as the Brahmā realm, you’ve returned to me.*";
P_HTM[3756]="*Na kho eso, bhikkhu, pañho evaṃ pucchitabbo:**Mendicant, this is not how the question should be asked:*";
P_HTM[3757]="*‘kattha nu kho, bhante, ime cattāro mahābhūtā aparisesā nirujjhanti, seyyathidaṃ—pathavīdhātu āpodhātu tejodhātu vāyodhātū’ti?**“Sir, where do these four primary elements cease without anything left over, namely, the elements of earth, water, fire, and air?”*";
P_HTM[3758]="*Evañca kho eso, bhikkhu, pañho pucchitabbo:**This is how the question should be asked:*";
P_HTM[3759]="*‘Kattha āpo ca pathavī,**“Where do water and earth,*";
P_HTM[3760]="*tejo vāyo na gādhati;**fire and air find no footing;*";
P_HTM[3761]="*Kattha dīghañca rassañca,**where do long and short,*";
P_HTM[3762]="*aṇuṃ thūlaṃ subhāsubhaṃ;**fine and coarse, beautiful and ugly;*";
P_HTM[3763]="*Kattha nāmañca rūpañca,**where do name and form*";
P_HTM[3764]="*asesaṃ uparujjhatī’ti.**cease with nothing left over?”*";
P_HTM[3765]="*Tatra veyyākaraṇaṃ bhavati:**And the answer to that is:*";
P_HTM[3766]="*‘Viññāṇaṃ anidassanaṃ,**“Consciousness that’s invisible,*";
P_HTM[3767]="*anantaṃ sabbatopabhaṃ;**infinite, radiant all round.*";
P_HTM[3768]="*Ettha āpo ca pathavī,**Here’s where water and earth,*";
P_HTM[3769]="*tejo vāyo na gādhati.**fire and air find no footing;*";
P_HTM[3770]="*Ettha dīghañca rassañca,**here’s where long and short,*";
P_HTM[3771]="*aṇuṃ thūlaṃ subhāsubhaṃ;**fine and coarse, beautiful and ugly;*";
P_HTM[3772]="*Ettha nāmañca rūpañca,**here’s where name and form*";
P_HTM[3773]="*asesaṃ uparujjhati;**cease with nothing left over—*";
P_HTM[3774]="*Viññāṇassa nirodhena,**with the cessation of consciousness,*";
P_HTM[3775]="*etthetaṃ uparujjhatī’”ti.**that’s where this ceases.”’”*";
P_HTM[3776]="*Idamavoca bhagavā.**That is what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[3777]="*Attamano kevaṭṭo gahapatiputto bhagavato bhāsitaṃ abhinandīti.**Satisfied, the householder Kevaddha was happy with what the Buddha said.*";
P_HTM[3778]="*Kevaṭṭasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ ekādasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3779]="*12. Lohiccasutta  - With Lohicca * **";
P_HTM[3780]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[3781]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā kosalesu cārikaṃ caramāno mahatā bhikkhusaṅghena saddhiṃ pañcamattehi bhikkhusatehi yena sālavatikā tadavasari.**At one time the Buddha was wandering in the land of the Kosalans together with a large Saṅgha of five hundred mendicants when he arrived at Sālavatikā.*";
P_HTM[3782]="*Tena kho pana samayena lohicco brāhmaṇo sālavatikaṃ ajjhāvasati sattussadaṃ satiṇakaṭṭhodakaṃ sadhaññaṃ rājabhoggaṃ raññā pasenadinā kosalena dinnaṃ rājadāyaṃ brahmadeyyaṃ.**Now at that time the brahmin Lohicca was living in Sālavatikā. It was a crown property given by King Pasenadi of Kosala, teeming with living creatures, full of hay, wood, water, and grain, a royal endowment of the highest quality.*";
P_HTM[3783]="*Tena kho pana samayena lohiccassa brāhmaṇassa evarūpaṃ pāpakaṃ diṭṭhigataṃ uppannaṃ hoti:**Now at that time Lohicca had the following harmful misconception:*";
P_HTM[3784]="*“idha samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā kusalaṃ dhammaṃ adhigaccheyya, kusalaṃ dhammaṃ adhigantvā na parassa āroceyya, kiñhi paro parassa karissati.**“Should an ascetic or brahmin achieve some skillful quality, they ought not inform anyone else. For what can one person do for another?*";
P_HTM[3785]="*Seyyathāpi nāma purāṇaṃ bandhanaṃ chinditvā aññaṃ navaṃ bandhanaṃ kareyya;**Suppose someone cut off an old bond, only to create another new bond.*";
P_HTM[3786]="*evaṃ sampadamidaṃ pāpakaṃ lobhadhammaṃ vadāmi, kiñhi paro parassa karissatī”ti.**That’s the consequence of such a wicked, greedy deed, I say. For what can one person do for another?”*";
P_HTM[3787]="*Assosi kho lohicco brāhmaṇo:**Lohicca heard:*";
P_HTM[3788]="*“samaṇo khalu, bho, gotamo sakyaputto sakyakulā pabbajito kosalesu cārikaṃ caramāno mahatā bhikkhusaṅghena saddhiṃ pañcamattehi bhikkhusatehi sālavatikaṃ anuppatto.**“It seems the ascetic Gotama—a Sakyan, gone forth from a Sakyan family—has arrived at Sālavatikā, together with a large Saṅgha of five hundred mendicants.*";
P_HTM[3789]="*Taṃ kho pana bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ evaṃ kalyāṇo kittisaddo abbhuggato:**He has this good reputation:*";
P_HTM[3790]="*‘itipi so bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā’.**‘That Blessed One is perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.’*";
P_HTM[3791]="*So imaṃ lokaṃ sadevakaṃ samārakaṃ sabrahmakaṃ sassamaṇabrāhmaṇiṃ pajaṃ sadevamanussaṃ sayaṃ abhiññā sacchikatvā pavedeti.**He has realized with his own insight this world—with its gods, Māras and Brahmās, this population with its ascetics and brahmins, gods and humans—and he makes it known to others.*";
P_HTM[3792]="*So dhammaṃ deseti ādikalyāṇaṃ majjhekalyāṇaṃ pariyosānakalyāṇaṃ sātthaṃ sabyañjanaṃ kevalaparipuṇṇaṃ parisuddhaṃ brahmacariyaṃ pakāseti.**He teaches Dhamma that’s good in the beginning, good in the middle, and good in the end, meaningful and well-phrased. And he reveals a spiritual practice that’s entirely full and pure.*";
P_HTM[3793]="*Sādhu kho pana tathārūpānaṃ arahataṃ dassanaṃ hotī”ti.**It’s good to see such perfected ones.”*";
P_HTM[3794]="*Atha kho lohicco brāhmaṇo rosikaṃ nhāpitaṃ āmantesi:**Then Lohicca addressed his barber Rosika,*";
P_HTM[3795]="*“ehi tvaṃ, samma rosike, yena samaṇo gotamo tenupasaṅkama; upasaṅkamitvā mama vacanena samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ appābādhaṃ appātaṅkaṃ lahuṭṭhānaṃ balaṃ phāsuvihāraṃ puccha:**“Here, dear Rosika, go to the ascetic Gotama and in my name bow with your head to his feet. Ask him if he is healthy and well, nimble, strong, and living comfortably.*";
P_HTM[3796]="*‘lohicco, bho gotama, brāhmaṇo bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ appābādhaṃ appātaṅkaṃ lahuṭṭhānaṃ balaṃ phāsuvihāraṃ pucchatī’ti;* **";
P_HTM[3797]="*evañca vadehi—**And then ask him whether he,*";
P_HTM[3798]="*adhivāsetu kira bhavaṃ gotamo lohiccassa brāhmaṇassa svātanāya bhattaṃ saddhiṃ bhikkhusaṃghenā”ti.**together with the mendicant Saṅgha, might accept tomorrow’s meal from the brahmin Lohicca.”*";
P_HTM[3799]="*“Evaṃ, bho”ti kho rosikā nhāpito lohiccassa brāhmaṇassa paṭissutvā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho rosikā nhāpito bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**“Yes, sir,” Rosika replied. He did as he was asked, and*";
P_HTM[3800]="*“lohicco, bhante, brāhmaṇo bhagavantaṃ appābādhaṃ appātaṅkaṃ lahuṭṭhānaṃ balaṃ phāsuvihāraṃ pucchati;* **";
P_HTM[3801]="*evañca vadeti—* **";
P_HTM[3802]="*adhivāsetu kira, bhante, bhagavā lohiccassa brāhmaṇassa svātanāya bhattaṃ saddhiṃ bhikkhusaṃghenā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3803]="*Adhivāsesi bhagavā tuṇhībhāvena.**the Buddha consented in silence.*";
P_HTM[3804]="*Atha kho rosikā nhāpito bhagavato adhivāsanaṃ viditvā uṭṭhāyāsanā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā padakkhiṇaṃ katvā yena lohicco brāhmaṇo tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā lohiccaṃ brāhmaṇaṃ etadavoca:**Then, knowing that the Buddha had consented, Rosika got up from his seat, went to Lohicca, and said to him,*";
P_HTM[3805]="*“avocumhā kho mayaṃ bhoto vacanena taṃ bhagavantaṃ:**“I gave the Buddha your message,*";
P_HTM[3806]="*‘lohicco, bhante, brāhmaṇo bhagavantaṃ appābādhaṃ appātaṅkaṃ lahuṭṭhānaṃ balaṃ phāsuvihāraṃ pucchati;* **";
P_HTM[3807]="*evañca vadeti—* **";
P_HTM[3808]="*adhivāsetu kira, bhante, bhagavā lohiccassa brāhmaṇassa svātanāya bhattaṃ saddhiṃ bhikkhusaṃghenā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3809]="*Adhivutthañca pana tena bhagavatā”ti.**and he accepted.”*";
P_HTM[3810]="*Atha kho lohicco brāhmaṇo tassā rattiyā accayena sake nivesane paṇītaṃ khādanīyaṃ bhojanīyaṃ paṭiyādāpetvā rosikaṃ nhāpitaṃ āmantesi:**And when the night had passed Lohicca had a variety of delicious foods prepared in his own home. Then he had the Buddha informed of the time, saying,*";
P_HTM[3811]="*“ehi tvaṃ, samma rosike, yena samaṇo gotamo tenupasaṅkama; upasaṅkamitvā samaṇassa gotamassa kālaṃ ārocehi—**“Here, dear Rosika, go to the ascetic Gotama and announce the time, saying:*";
P_HTM[3812]="*kālo, bho gotama, niṭṭhitaṃ bhattan”ti.**‘It’s time, Master Gotama, the meal is ready.’”*";
P_HTM[3813]="*“Evaṃ, bho”ti kho rosikā nhāpito lohiccassa brāhmaṇassa paṭissutvā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavantaṃ abhivādetvā ekamantaṃ aṭṭhāsi.**“Yes, sir,” Rosika replied. He did as he was asked.*";
P_HTM[3814]="*Ekamantaṃ ṭhito kho rosikā nhāpito bhagavato kālaṃ ārocesi:* **";
P_HTM[3815]="*“kālo, bhante, niṭṭhitaṃ bhattan”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3816]="*Atha kho bhagavā pubbaṇhasamayaṃ nivāsetvā pattacīvaramādāya saddhiṃ bhikkhusaṅghena yena sālavatikā tenupasaṅkami.**Then the Buddha robed up in the morning and, taking his bowl and robe, went to Sālavatikā together with the Saṅgha of mendicants.*";
P_HTM[3817]="*Tena kho pana samayena rosikā nhāpito bhagavantaṃ piṭṭhito piṭṭhito anubandho hoti.**Now, Rosika was following behind the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[3818]="*Atha kho rosikā nhāpito bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**and told him of Lohicca’s views, adding,*";
P_HTM[3819]="*“lohiccassa, bhante, brāhmaṇassa evarūpaṃ pāpakaṃ diṭṭhigataṃ uppannaṃ:* **";
P_HTM[3820]="*‘idha samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā kusalaṃ dhammaṃ adhigaccheyya, kusalaṃ dhammaṃ adhigantvā na parassa āroceyya—* **";
P_HTM[3821]="*kiñhi paro parassa karissati.* **";
P_HTM[3822]="*Seyyathāpi nāma purāṇaṃ bandhanaṃ chinditvā aññaṃ navaṃ bandhanaṃ kareyya;* **";
P_HTM[3823]="*evaṃ sampadamidaṃ pāpakaṃ lobhadhammaṃ vadāmi—* **";
P_HTM[3824]="*kiñhi paro parassa karissatī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3825]="*Sādhu, bhante, bhagavā lohiccaṃ brāhmaṇaṃ etasmā pāpakā diṭṭhigatā vivecetū”ti.**“Sir, please dissuade him from that harmful misconception.”*";
P_HTM[3826]="*“Appeva nāma siyā, rosike, appeva nāma siyā, rosike”ti.**“Hopefully that’ll happen, Rosika, hopefully that’ll happen.”*";
P_HTM[3827]="*Atha kho bhagavā yena lohiccassa brāhmaṇassa nivesanaṃ tenupasaṅkami; upasaṅkamitvā paññatte āsane nisīdi.**Then the Buddha approached Lohicca’s home, where he sat on the seat spread out.*";
P_HTM[3828]="*Atha kho lohicco brāhmaṇo buddhappamukhaṃ bhikkhusaṅghaṃ paṇītena khādanīyena bhojanīyena sahatthā santappesi sampavāresi.**Then Lohicca served and satisfied the mendicant Saṅgha headed by the Buddha with his own hands with a variety of delicious foods.*";
P_HTM[3829]="*1. Lohiccabrāhmaṇānuyoga**1. Questioning Lohicca*";
P_HTM[3830]="*Atha kho lohicco brāhmaṇo bhagavantaṃ bhuttāviṃ onītapattapāṇiṃ aññataraṃ nīcaṃ āsanaṃ gahetvā ekamantaṃ nisīdi.**When the Buddha had eaten and washed his hand and bowl, Lohicca took a low seat and sat to one side.*";
P_HTM[3831]="*Ekamantaṃ nisinnaṃ kho lohiccaṃ brāhmaṇaṃ bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said to him,*";
P_HTM[3832]="*“saccaṃ kira te, lohicca, evarūpaṃ pāpakaṃ diṭṭhigataṃ uppannaṃ:**“Is it really true, Lohicca, that you have such a harmful misconception:*";
P_HTM[3833]="*‘idha samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā kusalaṃ dhammaṃ adhigaccheyya, kusalaṃ dhammaṃ adhigantvā na parassa āroceyya, kiñhi paro parassa karissati.**‘Should an ascetic or brahmin achieve some skillful quality, they ought not inform anyone else. For what can one person do for another?*";
P_HTM[3834]="*Seyyathāpi nāma purāṇaṃ bandhanaṃ chinditvā aññaṃ navaṃ bandhanaṃ kareyya;**Suppose someone cut off an old bond, only to create another new bond.*";
P_HTM[3835]="*evaṃ sampadamidaṃ pāpakaṃ lobhadhammaṃ vadāmi, kiñhi paro parassa karissatī’”ti?**That’s the consequence of such a wicked, greedy deed, I say. For what can one person do for another?’”*";
P_HTM[3836]="*“Evaṃ, bho gotama”.**“Yes, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[3837]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, lohicca,**“What do you think, Lohicca?*";
P_HTM[3838]="*nanu tvaṃ sālavatikaṃ ajjhāvasasī”ti?**Do you reside in Sālavatikā?”*";
P_HTM[3839]="*“Evaṃ, bho gotama”.**“Yes, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[3840]="*“Yo nu kho, lohicca, evaṃ vadeyya:**“Lohicca, suppose someone were to say:*";
P_HTM[3841]="*‘lohicco brāhmaṇo sālavatikaṃ ajjhāvasati.**‘The brahmin Lohicca reigns over Sālavatikā.*";
P_HTM[3842]="*Yā sālavatikāya samudayasañjāti lohiccova taṃ brāhmaṇo ekako paribhuñjeyya, na aññesaṃ dadeyyā’ti.**He alone should enjoy the revenues produced in Sālavatikā and not share them with anyone else.’*";
P_HTM[3843]="*Evaṃ vādī so ye taṃ upajīvanti, tesaṃ antarāyakaro vā hoti, no vā”ti?**Would the person who spoke like that make it difficult for those whose living depends on you or not?”*";
P_HTM[3844]="*“Antarāyakaro, bho gotama”.**“They would, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[3845]="*“Antarāyakaro samāno hitānukampī vā tesaṃ hoti ahitānukampī vā”ti?**“But is someone who creates difficulties for others acting kindly or unkindly?”*";
P_HTM[3846]="*“Ahitānukampī, bho gotama”.**“Unkindly, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3847]="*“Ahitānukampissa mettaṃ vā tesu cittaṃ paccupaṭṭhitaṃ hoti sapattakaṃ vā”ti?**“But does an unkind person have love in their heart or hostility?”*";
P_HTM[3848]="*“Sapattakaṃ, bho gotama”.**“Hostility, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3849]="*“Sapattake citte paccupaṭṭhite micchādiṭṭhi vā hoti sammādiṭṭhi vā”ti?**“And when the heart is full of hostility, is there right view or wrong view?”*";
P_HTM[3850]="*“Micchādiṭṭhi, bho gotama”.**“Wrong view, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[3851]="*“Micchādiṭṭhissa kho ahaṃ, lohicca, dvinnaṃ gatīnaṃ aññataraṃ gatiṃ vadāmi—**“An individual with wrong view is reborn in one of two places, I say:*";
P_HTM[3852]="*nirayaṃ vā tiracchānayoniṃ vā.**hell or the animal realm.*";
P_HTM[3853]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, lohicca,**What do you think, Lohicca?*";
P_HTM[3854]="*nanu rājā pasenadi kosalo kāsikosalaṃ ajjhāvasatī”ti?**Does King Pasenadi reign over Kāsī and Kosala?”*";
P_HTM[3855]="*“Evaṃ, bho gotama”.**“Yes, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[3856]="*“Yo nu kho, lohicca, evaṃ vadeyya:**“Lohicca, suppose someone were to say:*";
P_HTM[3857]="*‘rājā pasenadi kosalo kāsikosalaṃ ajjhāvasati;**‘King Pasenadi reigns over Kāsī and Kosala.*";
P_HTM[3858]="*yā kāsikosale samudayasañjāti, rājāva taṃ pasenadi kosalo ekako paribhuñjeyya, na aññesaṃ dadeyyā’ti.**He alone should enjoy the revenues produced in Kāsī and Kosala and not share them with anyone else.’*";
P_HTM[3859]="*Evaṃ vādī so ye rājānaṃ pasenadiṃ kosalaṃ upajīvanti tumhe ceva aññe ca, tesaṃ antarāyakaro vā hoti, no vā”ti?**Would the person who spoke like that make it difficult for yourself and others whose living depends on King Pasenadi or not?”*";
P_HTM[3860]="*“Antarāyakaro, bho gotama”.**“They would, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[3861]="*“Antarāyakaro samāno hitānukampī vā tesaṃ hoti ahitānukampī vā”ti?**“But is someone who creates difficulties for others acting kindly or unkindly?”*";
P_HTM[3862]="*“Ahitānukampī, bho gotama”.**“Unkindly, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3863]="*“Ahitānukampissa mettaṃ vā tesu cittaṃ paccupaṭṭhitaṃ hoti sapattakaṃ vā”ti?**“But does an unkind person have love in their heart or hostility?”*";
P_HTM[3864]="*“Sapattakaṃ, bho gotama”.**“Hostility, sir.”*";
P_HTM[3865]="*“Sapattake citte paccupaṭṭhite micchādiṭṭhi vā hoti sammādiṭṭhi vā”ti?**“And when the heart is full of hostility, is there right view or wrong view?”*";
P_HTM[3866]="*“Micchādiṭṭhi, bho gotama”.**“Wrong view, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[3867]="*“Micchādiṭṭhissa kho ahaṃ, lohicca, dvinnaṃ gatīnaṃ aññataraṃ gatiṃ vadāmi—**“An individual with wrong view is reborn in one of two places, I say:*";
P_HTM[3868]="*nirayaṃ vā tiracchānayoniṃ vā.**hell or the animal realm.*";
P_HTM[3869]="*Iti kira, lohicca, yo evaṃ vadeyya:**So it seems, Lohicca, that should someone say such a thing either of Lohicca or of King Pasenadi,*";
P_HTM[3870]="*‘lohicco brāhmaṇo sālavatikaṃ ajjhāvasati;* **";
P_HTM[3871]="*yā sālavatikāya samudayasañjāti, lohiccova taṃ brāhmaṇo ekako paribhuñjeyya, na aññesaṃ dadeyyā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3872]="*Evaṃvādī so ye taṃ upajīvanti, tesaṃ antarāyakaro hoti.* **";
P_HTM[3873]="*Antarāyakaro samāno ahitānukampī hoti, ahitānukampissa sapattakaṃ cittaṃ paccupaṭṭhitaṃ hoti, sapattake citte paccupaṭṭhite micchādiṭṭhi hoti.**that is wrong view.*";
P_HTM[3874]="*Evameva kho, lohicca, yo evaṃ vadeyya:**In the same way, suppose someone were to say:*";
P_HTM[3875]="*‘idha samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā kusalaṃ dhammaṃ adhigaccheyya, kusalaṃ dhammaṃ adhigantvā na parassa āroceyya, kiñhi paro parassa karissati.**‘Should an ascetic or brahmin achieve some skillful quality, they ought not inform anyone else. For what can one person do for another?*";
P_HTM[3876]="*Seyyathāpi nāma purāṇaṃ bandhanaṃ chinditvā aññaṃ navaṃ bandhanaṃ kareyya … pe …**Suppose someone cut off an old bond, only to create another new bond.*";
P_HTM[3877]="*karissatī’ti.**That’s the consequence of such a wicked, greedy deed, I say. For what can one person do for another?’*";
P_HTM[3878]="*Evaṃvādī so ye te kulaputtā tathāgatappaveditaṃ dhammavinayaṃ āgamma evarūpaṃ uḷāraṃ visesaṃ adhigacchanti, sotāpattiphalampi sacchikaronti, sakadāgāmiphalampi sacchikaronti, anāgāmiphalampi sacchikaronti, arahattampi sacchikaronti, ye cime dibbā gabbhā paripācenti dibbānaṃ bhavānaṃ abhinibbattiyā, tesaṃ antarāyakaro hoti, antarāyakaro samāno ahitānukampī hoti, ahitānukampissa sapattakaṃ cittaṃ paccupaṭṭhitaṃ hoti, sapattake citte paccupaṭṭhite micchādiṭṭhi hoti.**Now, there are gentlemen who, relying on the teaching and training proclaimed by the Realized One, achieve a high distinction such as the following: they realize the fruit of stream-entry, the fruit of once-return, the fruit of non-return, or the fruit of perfection. And in addition, there are those who ripen the seeds for rebirth in a heavenly state. The person who spoke like that makes it difficult for them. They’re acting unkindly, their heart is full of hostility, and they have wrong view.*";
P_HTM[3879]="*Micchādiṭṭhissa kho ahaṃ, lohicca, dvinnaṃ gatīnaṃ aññataraṃ gatiṃ vadāmi—**An individual with wrong view is reborn in one of two places, I say:*";
P_HTM[3880]="*nirayaṃ vā tiracchānayoniṃ vā.**hell or the animal realm.*";
P_HTM[3881]="*Iti kira, lohicca, yo evaṃ vadeyya:* **";
P_HTM[3882]="*‘rājā pasenadi kosalo kāsikosalaṃ ajjhāvasati;* **";
P_HTM[3883]="*yā kāsikosale samudayasañjāti, rājāva taṃ pasenadi kosalo ekako paribhuñjeyya, na aññesaṃ dadeyyā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3884]="*Evaṃvādī so ye rājānaṃ pasenadiṃ kosalaṃ upajīvanti tumhe ceva aññe ca, tesaṃ antarāyakaro hoti.* **";
P_HTM[3885]="*Antarāyakaro samāno ahitānukampī hoti, ahitānukampissa sapattakaṃ cittaṃ paccupaṭṭhitaṃ hoti, sapattake citte paccupaṭṭhite micchādiṭṭhi hoti.* **";
P_HTM[3886]="*Evameva kho, lohicca, yo evaṃ vadeyya:* **";
P_HTM[3887]="*‘idha samaṇo vā brāhmaṇo vā kusalaṃ dhammaṃ adhigaccheyya, kusalaṃ dhammaṃ adhigantvā na parassa āroceyya, kiñhi paro parassa karissati.* **";
P_HTM[3888]="*Seyyathāpi nāma … pe …* **";
P_HTM[3889]="*kiñhi paro parassa karissatī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3890]="*Evaṃvādī so ye te kulaputtā tathāgatappaveditaṃ dhammavinayaṃ āgamma evarūpaṃ uḷāraṃ visesaṃ adhigacchanti, sotāpattiphalampi sacchikaronti, sakadāgāmiphalampi sacchikaronti, anāgāmiphalampi sacchikaronti, arahattampi sacchikaronti.* **";
P_HTM[3891]="*Ye cime dibbā gabbhā paripācenti dibbānaṃ bhavānaṃ abhinibbattiyā, tesaṃ antarāyakaro hoti,* **";
P_HTM[3892]="*antarāyakaro samāno ahitānukampī hoti, ahitānukampissa sapattakaṃ cittaṃ paccupaṭṭhitaṃ hoti, sapattake citte paccupaṭṭhite micchādiṭṭhi hoti.* **";
P_HTM[3893]="*Micchādiṭṭhissa kho ahaṃ, lohicca, dvinnaṃ gatīnaṃ aññataraṃ gatiṃ vadāmi—* **";
P_HTM[3894]="*nirayaṃ vā tiracchānayoniṃ vā.* **";
P_HTM[3895]="*2. Tayocodanārahā**2. Three Teachers Who Deserve to Be Reprimanded*";
P_HTM[3896]="*Tayo khome, lohicca, satthāro, ye loke codanārahā;**Lohicca, there are three kinds of teachers in the world who deserve to be reprimanded.*";
P_HTM[3897]="*yo ca panevarūpe satthāro codeti, sā codanā bhūtā tacchā dhammikā anavajjā.**When someone reprimands such teachers, the reprimand is true, substantive, legitimate, and blameless.*";
P_HTM[3898]="*Katame tayo?**What three?*";
P_HTM[3899]="*Idha, lohicca, ekacco satthā yassatthāya agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajito hoti, svāssa sāmaññattho ananuppatto hoti.**Firstly, take a teacher who has not reached the goal of the ascetic life for which they went forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[3900]="*So taṃ sāmaññatthaṃ ananupāpuṇitvā sāvakānaṃ dhammaṃ deseti:**They teach their disciples:*";
P_HTM[3901]="*‘idaṃ vo hitāya idaṃ vo sukhāyā’ti.**‘This is for your welfare. This is for your happiness.’*";
P_HTM[3902]="*Tassa sāvakā na sussūsanti, na sotaṃ odahanti, na aññā cittaṃ upaṭṭhapenti, vokkamma ca satthusāsanā vattanti.**But their disciples don’t want to listen. They don’t pay attention or apply their minds to understand. They proceed having turned away from the teacher’s instruction.*";
P_HTM[3903]="*So evamassa codetabbo:**That teacher deserves to be reprimanded:*";
P_HTM[3904]="*‘āyasmā kho yassatthāya agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajito, so te sāmaññattho ananuppatto, taṃ tvaṃ sāmaññatthaṃ ananupāpuṇitvā sāvakānaṃ dhammaṃ desesi:**‘Venerable, you haven’t reached the goal of the ascetic life; and when you teach disciples*";
P_HTM[3905]="*“idaṃ vo hitāya idaṃ vo sukhāyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3906]="*Tassa te sāvakā na sussūsanti, na sotaṃ odahanti, na aññā cittaṃ upaṭṭhapenti, vokkamma ca satthusāsanā vattanti.**they proceed having turned away from the teacher’s instruction.*";
P_HTM[3907]="*Seyyathāpi nāma osakkantiyā vā ussakkeyya, parammukhiṃ vā āliṅgeyya;**It’s like a man who makes advances on a woman though she pulls away, or embraces her though she turns her back.*";
P_HTM[3908]="*evaṃ sampadamidaṃ pāpakaṃ lobhadhammaṃ vadāmi—**That’s the consequence of such a wicked, greedy deed, I say. For what can one do for another?’*";
P_HTM[3909]="*kiñhi paro parassa karissatī’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3910]="*Ayaṃ kho, lohicca, paṭhamo satthā, yo loke codanāraho;**This is the first kind of teacher who deserves to be reprimanded.*";
P_HTM[3911]="*yo ca panevarūpaṃ satthāraṃ codeti, sā codanā bhūtā tacchā dhammikā anavajjā.* **";
P_HTM[3912]="*Puna caparaṃ, lohicca, idhekacco satthā yassatthāya agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajito hoti, svāssa sāmaññattho ananuppatto hoti.**Furthermore, take a teacher who has not reached the goal of the ascetic life for which they went forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[3913]="*So taṃ sāmaññatthaṃ ananupāpuṇitvā sāvakānaṃ dhammaṃ deseti:**They teach their disciples:*";
P_HTM[3914]="*‘idaṃ vo hitāya, idaṃ vo sukhāyā’ti.**‘This is for your welfare. This is for your happiness.’*";
P_HTM[3915]="*Tassa sāvakā sussūsanti, sotaṃ odahanti, aññā cittaṃ upaṭṭhapenti, na ca vokkamma satthusāsanā vattanti.**Their disciples do want to listen. They pay attention and apply their minds to understand. They don’t proceed having turned away from the teacher’s instruction.*";
P_HTM[3916]="*So evamassa codetabbo:**That teacher deserves to be reprimanded:*";
P_HTM[3917]="*‘āyasmā kho yassatthāya agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajito, so te sāmaññattho ananuppatto. Taṃ tvaṃ sāmaññatthaṃ ananupāpuṇitvā sāvakānaṃ dhammaṃ desesi:**‘Venerable, you haven’t reached the goal of the ascetic life; and when you teach disciples*";
P_HTM[3918]="*“idaṃ vo hitāya, idaṃ vo sukhāyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3919]="*Tassa te sāvakā sussūsanti, sotaṃ odahanti, aññā cittaṃ upaṭṭhapenti, na ca vokkamma satthusāsanā vattanti.**they don’t proceed having turned away from the teacher’s instruction.*";
P_HTM[3920]="*Seyyathāpi nāma sakaṃ khettaṃ ohāya paraṃ khettaṃ niddāyitabbaṃ maññeyya, evaṃ sampadamidaṃ pāpakaṃ lobhadhammaṃ vadāmi—kiñhi paro parassa karissatī’ti.**It’s like someone who abandons their own field and presumes to weed someone else’s field. That’s the consequence of such a wicked, greedy deed, I say. For what can one do for another?’*";
P_HTM[3921]="*Ayaṃ kho, lohicca, dutiyo satthā, yo, loke codanāraho;**This is the second kind of teacher who deserves to be reprimanded.*";
P_HTM[3922]="*yo ca panevarūpaṃ satthāraṃ codeti, sā codanā bhūtā tacchā dhammikā anavajjā.* **";
P_HTM[3923]="*Puna caparaṃ, lohicca, idhekacco satthā yassatthāya agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajito hoti, svāssa sāmaññattho anuppatto hoti.**Furthermore, take a teacher who has reached the goal of the ascetic life for which they went forth from the lay life to homelessness.*";
P_HTM[3924]="*So taṃ sāmaññatthaṃ anupāpuṇitvā sāvakānaṃ dhammaṃ deseti:**They teach their disciples:*";
P_HTM[3925]="*‘idaṃ vo hitāya, idaṃ vo sukhāyā’ti.**‘This is for your welfare. This is for your happiness.’*";
P_HTM[3926]="*Tassa sāvakā na sussūsanti, na sotaṃ odahanti, na aññā cittaṃ upaṭṭhapenti, vokkamma ca satthusāsanā vattanti.**But their disciples don’t want to listen. They don’t pay attention or apply their minds to understand. They proceed having turned away from the teacher’s instruction.*";
P_HTM[3927]="*So evamassa codetabbo:**That teacher deserves to be reprimanded:*";
P_HTM[3928]="*‘āyasmā kho yassatthāya agārasmā anagāriyaṃ pabbajito, so te sāmaññattho anuppatto.**‘Venerable, you have reached the goal of the ascetic life; yet when you teach disciples*";
P_HTM[3929]="*Taṃ tvaṃ sāmaññatthaṃ anupāpuṇitvā sāvakānaṃ dhammaṃ desesi:* **";
P_HTM[3930]="*“idaṃ vo hitāya, idaṃ vo sukhāyā”ti.* **";
P_HTM[3931]="*Tassa te sāvakā na sussūsanti, na sotaṃ odahanti, na aññā cittaṃ upaṭṭhapenti, vokkamma ca satthusāsanā vattanti.**they proceed having turned away from the teacher’s instruction.*";
P_HTM[3932]="*Seyyathāpi nāma purāṇaṃ bandhanaṃ chinditvā aññaṃ navaṃ bandhanaṃ kareyya;**Suppose someone cut off an old bond, only to create another new bond.*";
P_HTM[3933]="*evaṃ sampadamidaṃ pāpakaṃ lobhadhammaṃ vadāmi, kiñhi paro parassa karissatī’ti.**That’s the consequence of such a wicked, greedy deed, I say. For what can one person do for another?’*";
P_HTM[3934]="*Ayaṃ kho, lohicca, tatiyo satthā, yo loke codanāraho;**This is the third kind of teacher who deserves to be reprimanded.*";
P_HTM[3935]="*yo ca panevarūpaṃ satthāraṃ codeti, sā codanā bhūtā tacchā dhammikā anavajjā.* **";
P_HTM[3936]="*Ime kho, lohicca, tayo satthāro, ye loke codanārahā,**These are the three kinds of teachers in the world who deserve to be reprimanded.*";
P_HTM[3937]="*yo ca panevarūpe satthāro codeti, sā codanā bhūtā tacchā dhammikā anavajjā”ti.**When someone reprimands such teachers, the reprimand is true, substantive, legitimate, and blameless.”*";
P_HTM[3938]="*3. Nacodanārahasatthu**3. A Teacher Who Does Not Deserve to Be Reprimanded*";
P_HTM[3939]="*Evaṃ vutte, lohicco brāhmaṇo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he had spoken, Lohicca said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[3940]="*“atthi pana, bho gotama, koci satthā, yo loke nacodanāraho”ti?**“But Master Gotama, is there a teacher in the world who does not deserve to be reprimanded?”*";
P_HTM[3941]="*“Atthi kho, lohicca, satthā, yo loke nacodanāraho”ti.**“There is, Lohicca.”*";
P_HTM[3942]="*“Katamo pana so, bho gotama, satthā, yo loke nacodanāraho”ti?**“But who is that teacher?”*";
P_HTM[3943]="*“Idha, lohicca, tathāgato loke uppajjati arahaṃ, sammāsambuddho … pe …**“It’s when a Realized One arises in the world, perfected, a fully awakened Buddha …*";
P_HTM[3944]="*Evaṃ kho, lohicca, bhikkhu sīlasampanno hoti … pe …**That’s how a mendicant is accomplished in ethics. …*";
P_HTM[3945]="*paṭhamaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati …**They enter and remain in the first absorption …*";
P_HTM[3946]="*yasmiṃ kho, lohicca, satthari sāvako evarūpaṃ uḷāraṃ visesaṃ adhigacchati, ayampi kho, lohicca, satthā, yo loke nacodanāraho.**A teacher under whom a disciple achieves such a high distinction is one who does not deserve to be reprimanded.*";
P_HTM[3947]="*Yo ca panevarūpaṃ satthāraṃ codeti, sā codanā abhūtā atacchā adhammikā sāvajjā.**When someone reprimands such a teacher, the reprimand is false, baseless, illegitimate, and blameworthy.*";
P_HTM[3948]="*… pe …* **";
P_HTM[3949]="*Dutiyaṃ jhānaṃ … pe …**They enter and remain in the second absorption …*";
P_HTM[3950]="*tatiyaṃ jhānaṃ … pe …**third absorption …*";
P_HTM[3951]="*catutthaṃ jhānaṃ upasampajja viharati.**fourth absorption.*";
P_HTM[3952]="*Yasmiṃ kho, lohicca, satthari sāvako evarūpaṃ uḷāraṃ visesaṃ adhigacchati, ayampi kho, lohicca, satthā, yo loke nacodanāraho, yo ca panevarūpaṃ satthāraṃ codeti, sā codanā abhūtā atacchā adhammikā sāvajjā.**A teacher under whom a disciple achieves such a high distinction is one who does not deserve to be reprimanded. …*";
P_HTM[3953]="*… pe …* **";
P_HTM[3954]="*Ñāṇadassanāya cittaṃ abhinīharati abhininnāmeti …**They extend and project the mind toward knowledge and vision …*";
P_HTM[3955]="*yasmiṃ kho, lohicca, satthari sāvako evarūpaṃ uḷāraṃ visesaṃ adhigacchati, ayampi kho, lohicca, satthā, yo loke nacodanāraho, yo ca panevarūpaṃ satthāraṃ codeti, sā codanā abhūtā atacchā adhammikā sāvajjā.**A teacher under whom a disciple achieves such a high distinction is one who does not deserve to be reprimanded. …*";
P_HTM[3956]="*… pe …* **";
P_HTM[3957]="*Nāparaṃ itthattāyāti pajānāti.**They understand: ‘… there is no return to any state of existence.’*";
P_HTM[3958]="*Yasmiṃ kho, lohicca, satthari sāvako evarūpaṃ uḷāraṃ visesaṃ adhigacchati, ayampi kho, lohicca, satthā, yo loke nacodanāraho, yo ca panevarūpaṃ satthāraṃ codeti, sā codanā abhūtā atacchā adhammikā sāvajjā”ti.**A teacher under whom a disciple achieves such a high distinction is one who does not deserve to be reprimanded. When someone reprimands such a teacher, the reprimand is false, baseless, illegitimate, and blameworthy.”*";
P_HTM[3959]="*Evaṃ vutte, lohicco brāhmaṇo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he had spoken, Lohicca said to the Buddha:*";
P_HTM[3960]="*“seyyathāpi, bho gotama, puriso purisaṃ narakapapātaṃ patantaṃ kesesu gahetvā uddharitvā thale patiṭṭhapeyya;**“Suppose, Master Gotama, a person was on the verge of falling off a cliff, and another person were to grab them by the hair, pull them up, and place them on firm ground.*";
P_HTM[3961]="*evamevāhaṃ bhotā gotamena narakapapātaṃ papatanto uddharitvā thale patiṭṭhāpito.**In the same way, when I was falling off a cliff Master Gotama pulled me up and placed me on safe ground.*";
P_HTM[3962]="*Abhikkantaṃ, bho gotama, abhikkantaṃ, bho gotama.**Excellent, Master Gotama! Excellent!*";
P_HTM[3963]="*Seyyathāpi, bho gotama, nikkujjitaṃ vā ukkujjeyya, paṭicchannaṃ vā vivareyya, mūḷhassa vā maggaṃ ācikkheyya, andhakāre vā telapajjotaṃ dhāreyya: ‘cakkhumanto rūpāni dakkhantī’ti; evamevaṃ bhotā gotamena anekapariyāyena dhammo pakāsito.**As if he were righting the overturned, or revealing the hidden, or pointing out the path to the lost, or lighting a lamp in the dark so people with good eyes can see what’s there, Master Gotama has made the Teaching clear in many ways.*";
P_HTM[3964]="*Esāhaṃ bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ saraṇaṃ gacchāmi dhammañca bhikkhusaṅghañca.**I go for refuge to Master Gotama, to the teaching, and to the mendicant Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[3965]="*Upāsakaṃ maṃ bhavaṃ gotamo dhāretu ajjatagge pāṇupetaṃ saraṇaṃ gatan”ti.**From this day forth, may Master Gotama remember me as a lay follower who has gone for refuge for life.”*";
P_HTM[3966]="*Lohiccasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ dvādasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[3967]="*13. Tevijjasutta  - The Three Knowledges * **";
P_HTM[3968]="*Evaṃ me sutaṃ—**So I have heard.*";
P_HTM[3969]="*ekaṃ samayaṃ bhagavā kosalesu cārikaṃ caramāno mahatā bhikkhusaṅghena saddhiṃ pañcamattehi bhikkhusatehi yena manasākaṭaṃ nāma kosalānaṃ brāhmaṇagāmo tadavasari.**At one time the Buddha was wandering in the land of the Kosalans together with a large Saṅgha of five hundred mendicants when he arrived at a village of the Kosalan brahmins named Manasākaṭa.*";
P_HTM[3970]="*Tatra sudaṃ bhagavā manasākaṭe viharati uttarena manasākaṭassa aciravatiyā nadiyā tīre ambavane.**He stayed in a mango grove on a bank of the river Aciravatī to the north of Manasākaṭa.*";
P_HTM[3971]="*Tena kho pana samayena sambahulā abhiññātā abhiññātā brāhmaṇamahāsālā manasākaṭe paṭivasanti, seyyathidaṃ—**Now at that time several very well-known well-to-do brahmins were residing in Manasākaṭa. They included*";
P_HTM[3972]="*caṅkī brāhmaṇo tārukkho brāhmaṇo pokkharasāti brāhmaṇo jāṇusoṇi brāhmaṇo todeyyo brāhmaṇo aññe ca abhiññātā abhiññātā brāhmaṇamahāsālā.**the brahmins Caṅkī, Tārukkha, Pokkharasāti, Jāṇussoṇi, Todeyya, and others.*";
P_HTM[3973]="*Atha kho vāseṭṭhabhāradvājānaṃ māṇavānaṃ jaṅghavihāraṃ anucaṅkamantānaṃ anuvicarantānaṃ maggāmagge kathā udapādi.**Then as the students Vāseṭṭha and Bhāradvāja were going for a walk they began a discussion regarding the variety of paths.*";
P_HTM[3974]="*Atha kho vāseṭṭho māṇavo evamāha:**Vāseṭṭha said this:*";
P_HTM[3975]="*“ayameva ujumaggo, ayamañjasāyano niyyāniko niyyāti takkarassa brahmasahabyatāya, yvāyaṃ akkhāto brāhmaṇena pokkharasātinā”ti.**“This is the only straight path, the direct route that leads someone who practices it to the company of Brahmā; namely, that explained by the brahmin Pokkharasāti.”*";
P_HTM[3976]="*Bhāradvājopi māṇavo evamāha:**Bhāradvāja said this:*";
P_HTM[3977]="*“ayameva ujumaggo, ayamañjasāyano niyyāniko, niyyāti takkarassa brahmasahabyatāya, yvāyaṃ akkhāto brāhmaṇena tārukkhenā”ti.**“This is the only straight path, the direct route that leads someone who practices it to the company of Brahmā; namely, that explained by the brahmin Tārukkha.”*";
P_HTM[3978]="*Neva kho asakkhi vāseṭṭho māṇavo bhāradvājaṃ māṇavaṃ saññāpetuṃ, na pana asakkhi bhāradvājo māṇavo vāseṭṭhaṃ māṇavaṃ saññāpetuṃ.**But neither was able to persuade the other.*";
P_HTM[3979]="*Atha kho vāseṭṭho māṇavo bhāradvājaṃ māṇavaṃ āmantesi:**So Vāseṭṭha said to Bhāradvāja,*";
P_HTM[3980]="*“ayaṃ kho, bhāradvāja, samaṇo gotamo sakyaputto sakyakulā pabbajito manasākaṭe viharati uttarena manasākaṭassa aciravatiyā nadiyā tīre ambavane.**“Bhāradvāja, the ascetic Gotama—a Sakyan, gone forth from a Sakyan family—is staying in a mango grove on a bank of the river Aciravatī to the north of Manasākaṭa.*";
P_HTM[3981]="*Taṃ kho pana bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ evaṃ kalyāṇo kittisaddo abbhuggato:**He has this good reputation:*";
P_HTM[3982]="*‘itipi so bhagavā arahaṃ sammāsambuddho vijjācaraṇasampanno sugato lokavidū anuttaro purisadammasārathi satthā devamanussānaṃ buddho bhagavā’ti.**‘That Blessed One is perfected, a fully awakened Buddha, accomplished in knowledge and conduct, holy, knower of the world, supreme guide for those who wish to train, teacher of gods and humans, awakened, blessed.’*";
P_HTM[3983]="*Āyāma, bho bhāradvāja, yena samaṇo gotamo tenupasaṅkamissāma; upasaṅkamitvā etamatthaṃ samaṇaṃ gotamaṃ pucchissāma.**Come, let’s go to see him and ask him about this matter.*";
P_HTM[3984]="*Yathā no samaṇo gotamo byākarissati, tathā naṃ dhāressāmā”ti.**As he answers, so we’ll remember it.”*";
P_HTM[3985]="*“Evaṃ, bho”ti kho bhāradvājo māṇavo vāseṭṭhassa māṇavassa paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” replied Bhāradvāja.*";
P_HTM[3986]="*1. Maggāmaggakathā**1. The Variety of Paths*";
P_HTM[3987]="*Atha kho vāseṭṭhabhāradvājā māṇavā yena bhagavā tenupasaṅkamiṃsu; upasaṅkamitvā bhagavatā saddhiṃ sammodiṃsu.**So they went to the Buddha, and exchanged greetings with him.*";
P_HTM[3988]="*Sammodanīyaṃ kathaṃ sāraṇīyaṃ vītisāretvā ekamantaṃ nisīdiṃsu. Ekamantaṃ nisinno kho vāseṭṭho māṇavo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When the greetings and polite conversation were over, they sat down to one side and Vāseṭṭha told him of their conversation, adding:*";
P_HTM[3989]="*“idha, bho gotama, amhākaṃ jaṅghavihāraṃ anucaṅkamantānaṃ anuvicarantānaṃ maggāmagge kathā udapādi.* **";
P_HTM[3990]="*Ahaṃ evaṃ vadāmi:* **";
P_HTM[3991]="*‘ayameva ujumaggo, ayamañjasāyano niyyāniko niyyāti takkarassa brahmasahabyatāya, yvāyaṃ akkhāto brāhmaṇena pokkharasātinā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3992]="*Bhāradvājo māṇavo evamāha:* **";
P_HTM[3993]="*‘ayameva ujumaggo ayamañjasāyano niyyāniko niyyāti takkarassa brahmasahabyatāya, yvāyaṃ akkhāto brāhmaṇena tārukkhenā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[3994]="*Ettha, bho gotama, attheva viggaho, atthi vivādo, atthi nānāvādo”ti.**“In this matter we have a dispute, a disagreement, a difference of opinion.”*";
P_HTM[3995]="*“Iti kira, vāseṭṭha, tvaṃ evaṃ vadesi:**“So, Vāseṭṭha, it seems that you say that*";
P_HTM[3996]="*‘ayameva ujumaggo, ayamañjasāyano niyyāniko niyyāti takkarassa brahmasahabyatāya, yvāyaṃ akkhāto brāhmaṇena pokkharasātinā’ti.**the straight path is that explained by Pokkharasāti,*";
P_HTM[3997]="*Bhāradvājo māṇavo evamāha:**while Bhāradvāja says that*";
P_HTM[3998]="*‘ayameva ujumaggo ayamañjasāyano niyyāniko niyyāti takkarassa brahmasahabyatāya, yvāyaṃ akkhāto brāhmaṇena tārukkhenā’ti.**the straight path is that explained by Tārukkha.*";
P_HTM[3999]="*Atha kismiṃ pana vo, vāseṭṭha, viggaho, kismiṃ vivādo, kismiṃ nānāvādo”ti?**But what exactly is your disagreement about?”*";
P_HTM[4000]="*“Maggāmagge, bho gotama.**“About the variety of paths, Master Gotama.*";
P_HTM[4001]="*Kiñcāpi, bho gotama, brāhmaṇā nānāmagge paññāpenti, addhariyā brāhmaṇā tittiriyā brāhmaṇā chandokā brāhmaṇā bavhārijjhā brāhmaṇā, atha kho sabbāni tāni niyyānikā niyyanti takkarassa brahmasahabyatāya.**Even though brahmins describe different paths—the Addhariya brahmins, the Tittiriya brahmins, the Chandoka brahmins, and the Bavhadija brahmins—all of them lead someone who practices them to the company of Brahmā.*";
P_HTM[4002]="*Seyyathāpi, bho gotama, gāmassa vā nigamassa vā avidūre bahūni cepi nānāmaggāni bhavanti, atha kho sabbāni tāni gāmasamosaraṇāni bhavanti;**It’s like a village or town that has many different roads nearby, yet all of them meet at that village.*";
P_HTM[4003]="*evameva kho, bho gotama, kiñcāpi brāhmaṇā nānāmagge paññāpenti, addhariyā brāhmaṇā tittiriyā brāhmaṇā chandokā brāhmaṇā bavhārijjhā brāhmaṇā, atha kho sabbāni tāni niyyānikā niyyanti takkarassa brahmasahabyatāyā”ti.**In the same way, even though brahmins describe different paths—the Addhariya brahmins, the Tittiriya brahmins, the Chandoka brahmins, and the Bavhadija brahmins—all of them lead someone who practices them to the company of Brahmā.”*";
P_HTM[4004]="*2. Vāseṭṭhamāṇavānuyoga**2. Questioning Vāseṭṭha*";
P_HTM[4005]="*“Niyyantīti, vāseṭṭha vadesi”?**“Do you say, ‘they lead someone’, Vāseṭṭha?”*";
P_HTM[4006]="*“Niyyantīti, bho gotama, vadāmi”.**“I do, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[4007]="*“Niyyantīti, vāseṭṭha, vadesi”?**“Do you say, ‘they lead someone’, Vāseṭṭha?”*";
P_HTM[4008]="*“Niyyantīti, bho gotama, vadāmi”.**“I do, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[4009]="*“Niyyantīti, vāseṭṭha, vadesi”?**“Do you say, ‘they lead someone’, Vāseṭṭha?”*";
P_HTM[4010]="*“Niyyantīti, bho gotama, vadāmi”.**“I do, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[4011]="*“Kiṃ pana, vāseṭṭha, atthi koci tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ ekabrāhmaṇopi, yena brahmā sakkhidiṭṭho”ti?**“Well, of the brahmins who are proficient in the three Vedas, Vāseṭṭha, is there even a single one who has seen Brahmā with their own eyes?”*";
P_HTM[4012]="*“No hidaṃ, bho gotama”.**“No, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[4013]="*“Kiṃ pana, vāseṭṭha, atthi koci tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ ekācariyopi, yena brahmā sakkhidiṭṭho”ti?**“Well, has even a single one of their teachers seen Brahmā with their own eyes?”*";
P_HTM[4014]="*“No hidaṃ, bho gotama”.**“No, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[4015]="*“Kiṃ pana, vāseṭṭha, atthi koci tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ ekācariyapācariyopi, yena brahmā sakkhidiṭṭho”ti?**“Well, has even a single one of their teachers’ teachers seen Brahmā with their own eyes?”*";
P_HTM[4016]="*“No hidaṃ, bho gotama”.**“No, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[4017]="*“Kiṃ pana, vāseṭṭha, atthi koci tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ yāva sattamā ācariyāmahayugā yena brahmā sakkhidiṭṭho”ti?**“Well, has anyone back to the seventh generation of teachers seen Brahmā with their own eyes?”*";
P_HTM[4018]="*“No hidaṃ, bho gotama”.**“No, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[4019]="*“Kiṃ pana, vāseṭṭha, yepi tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ pubbakā isayo mantānaṃ kattāro mantānaṃ pavattāro, yesamidaṃ etarahi tevijjā brāhmaṇā porāṇaṃ mantapadaṃ gītaṃ pavuttaṃ samihitaṃ, tadanugāyanti, tadanubhāsanti, bhāsitamanubhāsanti, vācitamanuvācenti, seyyathidaṃ—aṭṭhako vāmako vāmadevo vessāmitto yamataggi aṅgīraso bhāradvājo vāseṭṭho kassapo bhagu.**“Well, what of the ancient hermits of the brahmins, namely Aṭṭhaka, Vāmaka, Vāmadeva, Vessāmitta, Yamadaggi, Aṅgīrasa, Bhāradvāja, Vāseṭṭha, Kassapa, and Bhagu? They were the authors and propagators of the hymns. Their hymnal was sung and propagated and compiled in ancient times; and these days, brahmins continue to sing and chant it, chanting what was chanted and teaching what was taught.*";
P_HTM[4020]="*Tepi evamāhaṃsu:**Did they say:*";
P_HTM[4021]="*‘mayametaṃ jānāma, mayametaṃ passāma, yattha vā brahmā, yena vā brahmā, yahiṃ vā brahmā’”ti?**‘We know and see where Brahmā is or what way he lies’?”*";
P_HTM[4022]="*“No hidaṃ, bho gotama”.**“No, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[4023]="*“Iti kira, vāseṭṭha, natthi koci tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ ekabrāhmaṇopi, yena brahmā sakkhidiṭṭho.**“So it seems that none of the brahmins have seen Brahmā with their own eyes,*";
P_HTM[4024]="*Natthi koci tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ ekācariyopi, yena brahmā sakkhidiṭṭho.* **";
P_HTM[4025]="*Natthi koci tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ ekācariyapācariyopi, yena brahmā sakkhidiṭṭho.* **";
P_HTM[4026]="*Natthi koci tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ yāva sattamā ācariyāmahayugā yena brahmā sakkhidiṭṭho.* **";
P_HTM[4027]="*Yepi kira tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ pubbakā isayo mantānaṃ kattāro mantānaṃ pavattāro, yesamidaṃ etarahi tevijjā brāhmaṇā porāṇaṃ mantapadaṃ gītaṃ pavuttaṃ samihitaṃ, tadanugāyanti, tadanubhāsanti, bhāsitamanubhāsanti, vācitamanuvācenti, seyyathidaṃ—aṭṭhako vāmako vāmadevo vessāmitto yamataggi aṅgīraso bhāradvājo vāseṭṭho kassapo bhagu, tepi na evamāhaṃsu:**and not even the ancient hermits*";
P_HTM[4028]="*‘mayametaṃ jānāma, mayametaṃ passāma, yattha vā brahmā, yena vā brahmā, yahiṃ vā brahmā’ti.**claimed to know where he is.*";
P_HTM[4029]="*Teva tevijjā brāhmaṇā evamāhaṃsu:**Yet the brahmins proficient in the three Vedas say:*";
P_HTM[4030]="*‘yaṃ na jānāma, yaṃ na passāma, tassa sahabyatāya maggaṃ desema.**‘We teach the path to the company of that which we neither know nor see.*";
P_HTM[4031]="*Ayameva ujumaggo ayamañjasāyano niyyāniko, niyyāti takkarassa brahmasahabyatāyā’ti.**This is the only straight path, the direct route that leads someone who practices it to the company of Brahmā.’*";
P_HTM[4032]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, vāseṭṭha,**What do you think, Vāseṭṭha?*";
P_HTM[4033]="*nanu evaṃ sante tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ appāṭihīrakataṃ bhāsitaṃ sampajjatī”ti?**This being so, doesn’t their statement turn out to have no demonstrable basis?”*";
P_HTM[4034]="*“Addhā kho, bho gotama, evaṃ sante tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ appāṭihīrakataṃ bhāsitaṃ sampajjatī”ti.**“Clearly that’s the case, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[4035]="*“Sādhu, vāseṭṭha, te vata, vāseṭṭha, tevijjā brāhmaṇā yaṃ na jānanti, yaṃ na passanti, tassa sahabyatāya maggaṃ desessanti. ‘Ayameva ujumaggo, ayamañjasāyano niyyāniko, niyyāti takkarassa brahmasahabyatāyā’ti, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**“Good, Vāseṭṭha. For it is impossible that they should teach the path to that which they neither know nor see.*";
P_HTM[4036]="*Seyyathāpi, vāseṭṭha, andhaveṇi paramparasaṃsattā purimopi na passati, majjhimopi na passati, pacchimopi na passati;**Suppose there was a queue of blind men, each holding the one in front: the first one does not see, the middle one does not see, and the last one does not see.*";
P_HTM[4037]="*evameva kho, vāseṭṭha, andhaveṇūpamaṃ maññe tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ bhāsitaṃ, purimopi na passati, majjhimopi na passati, pacchimopi na passati.**In the same way, it seems to me that the brahmins’ statement turns out to be comparable to a queue of blind men: the first one does not see, the middle one does not see, and the last one does not see.*";
P_HTM[4038]="*Tesamidaṃ tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ bhāsitaṃ hassakaññeva sampajjati, nāmakaññeva sampajjati, rittakaññeva sampajjati, tucchakaññeva sampajjati.**Their statement turns out to be a joke—mere words, void and hollow.*";
P_HTM[4039]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, vāseṭṭha,**What do you think, Vāseṭṭha?*";
P_HTM[4040]="*passanti tevijjā brāhmaṇā candimasūriye, aññe cāpi bahujanā, yato ca candimasūriyā uggacchanti, yattha ca ogacchanti, āyācanti thomayanti pañjalikā namassamānā anuparivattantī”ti?**Do the brahmins proficient in the three Vedas see the sun and moon just as other folk do? And do they pray to them and beseech them, following their course from where they rise to where they set with joined palms held in worship?”*";
P_HTM[4041]="*“Evaṃ, bho gotama, passanti tevijjā brāhmaṇā candimasūriye, aññe cāpi bahujanā, yato ca candimasūriyā uggacchanti, yattha ca ogacchanti, āyācanti thomayanti pañjalikā namassamānā anuparivattantī”ti.**“Yes, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[4042]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, vāseṭṭha,**“What do you think, Vāseṭṭha?*";
P_HTM[4043]="*yaṃ passanti tevijjā brāhmaṇā candimasūriye, aññe cāpi bahujanā, yato ca candimasūriyā uggacchanti, yattha ca ogacchanti, āyācanti thomayanti pañjalikā namassamānā anuparivattanti, pahonti tevijjā brāhmaṇā candimasūriyānaṃ sahabyatāya maggaṃ desetuṃ:**Though this is so, are the brahmins proficient in the three Vedas able to teach the path to the company of the sun and moon, saying:*";
P_HTM[4044]="*‘ayameva ujumaggo, ayamañjasāyano niyyāniko, niyyāti takkarassa candimasūriyānaṃ sahabyatāyā’”ti?**‘This is the only straight path, the direct route that leads someone who practices it to the company of the sun and moon’?”*";
P_HTM[4045]="*“No hidaṃ, bho gotama”.**“No, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[4046]="*“Iti kira, vāseṭṭha, yaṃ passanti tevijjā brāhmaṇā candimasūriye, aññe cāpi bahujanā, yato ca candimasūriyā uggacchanti, yattha ca ogacchanti, āyācanti thomayanti pañjalikā namassamānā anuparivattanti, tesampi nappahonti candimasūriyānaṃ sahabyatāya maggaṃ desetuṃ:**“So it seems that even though the brahmins proficient in the three Vedas see the sun and moon, they are not able to teach the path to the company of the sun and moon.*";
P_HTM[4047]="*‘ayameva ujumaggo, ayamañjasāyano niyyāniko, niyyāti takkarassa candimasūriyānaṃ sahabyatāyā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[4048]="*Iti pana na kira tevijjehi brāhmaṇehi brahmā sakkhidiṭṭho.**But it seems that even though they have not seen Brahmā with their own eyes,*";
P_HTM[4049]="*Napi kira tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ ācariyehi brahmā sakkhidiṭṭho.* **";
P_HTM[4050]="*Napi kira tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ ācariyapācariyehi brahmā sakkhidiṭṭho.* **";
P_HTM[4051]="*Napi kira tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ yāva sattamā ācariyāmahayugehi brahmā sakkhidiṭṭho.* **";
P_HTM[4052]="*Yepi kira tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ pubbakā isayo mantānaṃ kattāro mantānaṃ pavattāro, yesamidaṃ etarahi tevijjā brāhmaṇā porāṇaṃ mantapadaṃ gītaṃ pavuttaṃ samihitaṃ, tadanugāyanti, tadanubhāsanti, bhāsitamanubhāsanti, vācitamanuvācenti, seyyathidaṃ—aṭṭhako vāmako vāmadevo vessāmitto yamataggi aṅgīraso bhāradvājo vāseṭṭho kassapo bhagu, tepi na evamāhaṃsu:* **";
P_HTM[4053]="*‘mayametaṃ jānāma, mayametaṃ passāma, yattha vā brahmā, yena vā brahmā, yahiṃ vā brahmā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[4054]="*Teva tevijjā brāhmaṇā evamāhaṃsu:**they still claim*";
P_HTM[4055]="*‘yaṃ na jānāma, yaṃ na passāma, tassa sahabyatāya maggaṃ desema—ayameva ujumaggo ayamañjasāyano niyyāniko niyyāti takkarassa brahmasahabyatāyā’ti.**to teach the path to the company of that which they neither know nor see.*";
P_HTM[4056]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, vāseṭṭha,**What do you think, Vāseṭṭha?*";
P_HTM[4057]="*nanu evaṃ sante tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ appāṭihīrakataṃ bhāsitaṃ sampajjatī”ti?**This being so, doesn’t their statement turn out to have no demonstrable basis?”*";
P_HTM[4058]="*“Addhā kho, bho gotama, evaṃ sante tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ appāṭihīrakataṃ bhāsitaṃ sampajjatī”ti.**“Clearly that’s the case, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[4059]="*“Sādhu, vāseṭṭha, te vata, vāseṭṭha, tevijjā brāhmaṇā yaṃ na jānanti, yaṃ na passanti, tassa sahabyatāya maggaṃ desessanti: ‘ayameva ujumaggo, ayamañjasāyano niyyāniko, niyyāti takkarassa brahmasahabyatāyā’ti, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**“Good, Vāseṭṭha. For it is impossible that they should teach the path to that which they neither know nor see.*";
P_HTM[4060]="*2.1. Janapadakalyāṇīupamā**2.1. The Simile of the Finest Lady in the Land*";
P_HTM[4061]="*Seyyathāpi, vāseṭṭha, puriso evaṃ vadeyya:**Suppose a man were to say,*";
P_HTM[4062]="*‘ahaṃ yā imasmiṃ janapade janapadakalyāṇī, taṃ icchāmi, taṃ kāmemī’ti.**‘Whoever the finest lady in the land is, it is her that I want, her that I desire!’*";
P_HTM[4063]="*Tamenaṃ evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**They’d say to him,*";
P_HTM[4064]="*‘ambho purisa, yaṃ tvaṃ janapadakalyāṇiṃ icchasi kāmesi, jānāsi taṃ janapadakalyāṇiṃ—**‘Mister, that finest lady in the land who you desire—do you know whether*";
P_HTM[4065]="*khattiyī vā brāhmaṇī vā vessī vā suddī vā’ti?**she’s an aristocrat, a brahmin, a merchant, or a worker?’*";
P_HTM[4066]="*Iti puṭṭho ‘no’ti vadeyya.**Asked this, he’d say, ‘No.’*";
P_HTM[4067]="*Tamenaṃ evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**They’d say to him,*";
P_HTM[4068]="*‘ambho purisa, yaṃ tvaṃ janapadakalyāṇiṃ icchasi kāmesi, jānāsi taṃ janapadakalyāṇiṃ—evaṃnāmā evaṅgottāti vā, dīghā vā rassā vā majjhimā vā kāḷī vā sāmā vā maṅguracchavī vāti, amukasmiṃ gāme vā nigame vā nagare vā’ti?**‘Mister, that finest lady in the land who you desire—do you know her name or clan? Whether she’s tall or short or medium? Whether her skin is black, brown, or tawny? What village, town, or city she comes from?’*";
P_HTM[4069]="*Iti puṭṭho ‘no’ti vadeyya.**Asked this, he’d say, ‘No.’*";
P_HTM[4070]="*Tamenaṃ evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**They’d say to him,*";
P_HTM[4071]="*‘ambho purisa, yaṃ tvaṃ na jānāsi na passasi, taṃ tvaṃ icchasi kāmesī’ti?**‘Mister, do you desire someone who you’ve never even known or seen?’*";
P_HTM[4072]="*Iti puṭṭho ‘āmā’ti vadeyya.**Asked this, he’d say, ‘Yes.’*";
P_HTM[4073]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, vāseṭṭha,**What do you think, Vāseṭṭha?*";
P_HTM[4074]="*nanu evaṃ sante tassa purisassa appāṭihīrakataṃ bhāsitaṃ sampajjatī”ti?**This being so, doesn’t that man’s statement turn out to have no demonstrable basis?”*";
P_HTM[4075]="*“Addhā kho, bho gotama, evaṃ sante tassa purisassa appāṭihīrakataṃ bhāsitaṃ sampajjatī”ti.**“Clearly that’s the case, sir.”*";
P_HTM[4076]="*“Evameva kho, vāseṭṭha, na kira tevijjehi brāhmaṇehi brahmā sakkhidiṭṭho, napi kira tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ ācariyehi brahmā sakkhidiṭṭho, napi kira tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ ācariyapācariyehi brahmā sakkhidiṭṭho.**“In the same way,*";
P_HTM[4077]="*Napi kira tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ yāva sattamā ācariyāmahayugehi brahmā sakkhidiṭṭho.* **";
P_HTM[4078]="*Yepi kira tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ pubbakā isayo mantānaṃ kattāro mantānaṃ pavattāro, yesamidaṃ etarahi tevijjā brāhmaṇā porāṇaṃ mantapadaṃ gītaṃ pavuttaṃ samihitaṃ, tadanugāyanti, tadanubhāsanti, bhāsitamanubhāsanti, vācitamanuvācenti, seyyathidaṃ—aṭṭhako vāmako vāmadevo vessāmitto yamataggi aṅgīraso bhāradvājo vāseṭṭho kassapo bhagu, tepi na evamāhaṃsu:* **";
P_HTM[4079]="*‘mayametaṃ jānāma, mayametaṃ passāma, yattha vā brahmā, yena vā brahmā, yahiṃ vā brahmā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[4080]="*Teva tevijjā brāhmaṇā evamāhaṃsu:* **";
P_HTM[4081]="*‘yaṃ na jānāma, yaṃ na passāma, tassa sahabyatāya maggaṃ desema—ayameva ujumaggo ayamañjasāyano niyyāniko niyyāti takkarassa brahmasahabyatāyā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[4082]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, vāseṭṭha, nanu evaṃ sante tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ appāṭihīrakataṃ bhāsitaṃ sampajjatī”ti?**doesn’t the statement of those brahmins turn out to have no demonstrable basis?”*";
P_HTM[4083]="*“Addhā kho, bho gotama, evaṃ sante tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ appāṭihīrakataṃ bhāsitaṃ sampajjatī”ti.**“Clearly that’s the case, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[4084]="*“Sādhu, vāseṭṭha, te vata, vāseṭṭha, tevijjā brāhmaṇā yaṃ na jānanti, yaṃ na passanti, tassa sahabyatāya maggaṃ desessanti—ayameva ujumaggo ayamañjasāyano niyyāniko niyyāti takkarassa brahmasahabyatāyāti netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**“Good, Vāseṭṭha. For it is impossible that they should teach the path to that which they neither know nor see.*";
P_HTM[4085]="*2.2. Nisseṇīupamā**2.2. The Simile of the Ladder*";
P_HTM[4086]="*Seyyathāpi, vāseṭṭha, puriso cātumahāpathe nisseṇiṃ kareyya pāsādassa ārohaṇāya.**Suppose a man was to build a ladder at the crossroads for climbing up to a stilt longhouse.*";
P_HTM[4087]="*Tamenaṃ evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**They’d say to him,*";
P_HTM[4088]="*‘ambho purisa, yassa tvaṃ pāsādassa ārohaṇāya nisseṇiṃ karosi, jānāsi taṃ pāsādaṃ—puratthimāya vā disāya dakkhiṇāya vā disāya pacchimāya vā disāya uttarāya vā disāya ucco vā nīco vā majjhimo vā’ti?**‘Mister, that stilt longhouse that you’re building a ladder for—do you know whether it’s to the north, south, east, or west? Or whether it’s tall or short or medium?’*";
P_HTM[4089]="*Iti puṭṭho ‘no’ti vadeyya.**Asked this, he’d say, ‘No.’*";
P_HTM[4090]="*Tamenaṃ evaṃ vadeyyuṃ:**They’d say to him,*";
P_HTM[4091]="*‘ambho purisa, yaṃ tvaṃ na jānāsi, na passasi, tassa tvaṃ pāsādassa ārohaṇāya nisseṇiṃ karosī’ti?**‘Mister, are you building a ladder for a longhouse that you’ve never even known or seen?’*";
P_HTM[4092]="*Iti puṭṭho ‘āmā’ti vadeyya.**Asked this, he’d say, ‘Yes.’*";
P_HTM[4093]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, vāseṭṭha,**What do you think, Vāseṭṭha?*";
P_HTM[4094]="*nanu evaṃ sante tassa purisassa appāṭihīrakataṃ bhāsitaṃ sampajjatī”ti?**This being so, doesn’t that man’s statement turn out to have no demonstrable basis?”*";
P_HTM[4095]="*“Addhā kho, bho gotama, evaṃ sante tassa purisassa appāṭihīrakataṃ bhāsitaṃ sampajjatī”ti.**“Clearly that’s the case, sir.”*";
P_HTM[4096]="*“Evameva kho, vāseṭṭha, na kira tevijjehi brāhmaṇehi brahmā sakkhidiṭṭho, napi kira tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ ācariyehi brahmā sakkhidiṭṭho, napi kira tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ ācariyapācariyehi brahmā sakkhidiṭṭho, napi kira tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ yāva sattamā ācariyāmahayugehi brahmā sakkhidiṭṭho.**“In the same way,*";
P_HTM[4097]="*Yepi kira tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ pubbakā isayo mantānaṃ kattāro mantānaṃ pavattāro, yesamidaṃ etarahi tevijjā brāhmaṇā porāṇaṃ mantapadaṃ gītaṃ pavuttaṃ samihitaṃ, tadanugāyanti, tadanubhāsanti, bhāsitamanubhāsanti, vācitamanuvācenti, seyyathidaṃ—aṭṭhako vāmako vāmadevo vessāmitto yamataggi aṅgīraso bhāradvājo vāseṭṭho kassapo bhagu, tepi na evamāhaṃsu—* **";
P_HTM[4098]="*mayametaṃ jānāma, mayametaṃ passāma, yattha vā brahmā, yena vā brahmā, yahiṃ vā brahmāti.* **";
P_HTM[4099]="*Teva tevijjā brāhmaṇā evamāhaṃsu:* **";
P_HTM[4100]="*‘yaṃ na jānāma, yaṃ na passāma, tassa sahabyatāya maggaṃ desema, ayameva ujumaggo ayamañjasāyano niyyāniko niyyāti takkarassa brahmasahabyatāyā’ti.* **";
P_HTM[4101]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, vāseṭṭha, nanu evaṃ sante tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ appāṭihīrakataṃ bhāsitaṃ sampajjatī”ti?**doesn’t the statement of those brahmins turn out to have no demonstrable basis?”*";
P_HTM[4102]="*“Addhā kho, bho gotama, evaṃ sante tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ appāṭihīrakataṃ bhāsitaṃ sampajjatī”ti.**“Clearly that’s the case, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[4103]="*“Sādhu, vāseṭṭha, te vata, vāseṭṭha, tevijjā brāhmaṇā yaṃ na jānanti, yaṃ na passanti, tassa sahabyatāya maggaṃ desessanti. Ayameva ujumaggo ayamañjasāyano niyyāniko niyyāti takkarassa brahmasahabyatāyāti, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**“Good, Vāseṭṭha. For it is impossible that they should teach the path to that which they neither know nor see.*";
P_HTM[4104]="*2.3. Aciravatīnadīupamā**2.3. The Simile of the River Aciravatī*";
P_HTM[4105]="*Seyyathāpi, vāseṭṭha, ayaṃ aciravatī nadī pūrā udakassa samatittikā kākapeyyā.**Suppose the river Aciravatī was full to the brim so a crow could drink from it.*";
P_HTM[4106]="*Atha puriso āgaccheyya pāratthiko pāragavesī pāragāmī pāraṃ taritukāmo.**Then along comes a person who wants to cross over to the far shore.*";
P_HTM[4107]="*So orime tīre ṭhito pārimaṃ tīraṃ avheyya:**Standing on the near shore, they’d call out to the far shore,*";
P_HTM[4108]="*‘ehi pārāpāraṃ, ehi pārāpāran’ti.**‘Come here, far shore! Come here, far shore!’*";
P_HTM[4109]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, vāseṭṭha,**What do you think, Vāseṭṭha?*";
P_HTM[4110]="*api nu tassa purisassa avhāyanahetu vā āyācanahetu vā patthanahetu vā abhinandanahetu vā aciravatiyā nadiyā pārimaṃ tīraṃ orimaṃ tīraṃ āgaccheyyā”ti?**Would the far shore of the Aciravatī river come over to the near shore because of that man’s call, request, desire, or expectation?”*";
P_HTM[4111]="*“No hidaṃ, bho gotama”.**“No, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[4112]="*“Evameva kho, vāseṭṭha, tevijjā brāhmaṇā ye dhammā brāhmaṇakārakā te dhamme pahāya vattamānā, ye dhammā abrāhmaṇakārakā te dhamme samādāya vattamānā evamāhaṃsu:**“In the same way, Vāseṭṭha, the brahmins proficient in the three Vedas proceed having given up those things that make one a true brahmin, and having undertaken those things that make one not a true brahmin. Yet they say:*";
P_HTM[4113]="*‘indamavhayāma, somamavhayāma, varuṇamavhayāma, īsānamavhayāma, pajāpatimavhayāma, brahmamavhayāma, mahiddhimavhayāma, yamamavhayāmā’ti.**‘We call upon Inda! We call upon Soma! We call upon Īsāna! We call upon Pajāpati! We call upon Brahmā! We call upon Mahiddhi! We call upon Yama!’*";
P_HTM[4114]="*Te vata, vāseṭṭha, tevijjā brāhmaṇā ye dhammā brāhmaṇakārakā te dhamme pahāya vattamānā, ye dhammā abrāhmaṇakārakā te dhamme samādāya vattamānā avhāyanahetu vā āyācanahetu vā patthanahetu vā abhinandanahetu vā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā brahmānaṃ sahabyūpagā bhavissantīti, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**So long as they proceed in this way it’s impossible that they will, when the body breaks up, after death, be reborn in the company of Brahmā.*";
P_HTM[4115]="*Seyyathāpi, vāseṭṭha, ayaṃ aciravatī nadī pūrā udakassa samatittikā kākapeyyā.**Suppose the river Aciravatī was full to the brim so a crow could drink from it.*";
P_HTM[4116]="*Atha puriso āgaccheyya pāratthiko pāragavesī pāragāmī pāraṃ taritukāmo.**Then along comes a person who wants to cross over to the far shore.*";
P_HTM[4117]="*So orime tīre daḷhāya anduyā pacchābāhaṃ gāḷhabandhanaṃ baddho.**But while still on the near shore, their arms are tied tightly behind their back with a strong chain.*";
P_HTM[4118]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, vāseṭṭha,**What do you think, Vāseṭṭha?*";
P_HTM[4119]="*api nu so puriso aciravatiyā nadiyā orimā tīrā pārimaṃ tīraṃ gaccheyyā”ti?**Could that person cross over to the far shore?”*";
P_HTM[4120]="*“No hidaṃ, bho gotama”.**“No, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[4121]="*“Evameva kho, vāseṭṭha, pañcime kāmaguṇā ariyassa vinaye andūtipi vuccanti, bandhanantipi vuccanti.**“In the same way, the five kinds of sensual stimulation are called ‘chains’ and ‘fetters’ in the training of the noble one.*";
P_HTM[4122]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4123]="*Cakkhuviññeyyā rūpā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā.**Sights known by the eye that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[4124]="*Sotaviññeyyā saddā … pe …**Sounds known by the ear …*";
P_HTM[4125]="*ghānaviññeyyā gandhā …**Smells known by the nose …*";
P_HTM[4126]="*jivhāviññeyyā rasā …**Tastes known by the tongue …*";
P_HTM[4127]="*kāyaviññeyyā phoṭṭhabbā iṭṭhā kantā manāpā piyarūpā kāmūpasaṃhitā rajanīyā.**Touches known by the body that are likable, desirable, agreeable, pleasant, sensual, and arousing.*";
P_HTM[4128]="*Ime kho, vāseṭṭha, pañca kāmaguṇā ariyassa vinaye andūtipi vuccanti, bandhanantipi vuccanti.**These are the five kinds of sensual stimulation that are called ‘chains’ and ‘fetters’ in the training of the noble one.*";
P_HTM[4129]="*Ime kho, vāseṭṭha, pañca kāmaguṇe tevijjā brāhmaṇā gadhitā mucchitā ajjhopannā anādīnavadassāvino anissaraṇapaññā paribhuñjanti.**The brahmins proficient in the three Vedas enjoy these five kinds of sensual stimulation tied, infatuated, attached, blind to the drawbacks, and not understanding the escape.*";
P_HTM[4130]="*Te vata, vāseṭṭha, tevijjā brāhmaṇā ye dhammā brāhmaṇakārakā, te dhamme pahāya vattamānā, ye dhammā abrāhmaṇakārakā, te dhamme samādāya vattamānā pañca kāmaguṇe gadhitā mucchitā ajjhopannā anādīnavadassāvino anissaraṇapaññā paribhuñjantā kāmandubandhanabaddhā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā brahmānaṃ sahabyūpagā bhavissantīti, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**So long as they enjoy them it’s impossible that they will, when the body breaks up, after death, be reborn in the company of Brahmā.*";
P_HTM[4131]="*Seyyathāpi, vāseṭṭha, ayaṃ aciravatī nadī pūrā udakassa samatittikā kākapeyyā.**Suppose the river Aciravatī was full to the brim so a crow could drink from it.*";
P_HTM[4132]="*Atha puriso āgaccheyya pāratthiko pāragavesī pāragāmī pāraṃ taritukāmo.**Then along comes a person who wants to cross over to the far shore.*";
P_HTM[4133]="*So orime tīre sasīsaṃ pārupitvā nipajjeyya.**But they’d lie down wrapped in cloth from head to foot.*";
P_HTM[4134]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, vāseṭṭha,**What do you think, Vāseṭṭha?*";
P_HTM[4135]="*api nu so puriso aciravatiyā nadiyā orimā tīrā pārimaṃ tīraṃ gaccheyyā”ti?**Could that person cross over to the far shore?”*";
P_HTM[4136]="*“No hidaṃ, bho gotama”.**“No, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[4137]="*“Evameva kho, vāseṭṭha, pañcime nīvaraṇā ariyassa vinaye āvaraṇātipi vuccanti, nīvaraṇātipi vuccanti, onāhanātipi vuccanti, pariyonāhanātipi vuccanti.**“In the same way, the five hindrances are called ‘obstacles’ and ‘hindrances’ and ‘coverings’ and ‘shrouds’ in the training of the noble one.*";
P_HTM[4138]="*Katame pañca?**What five?*";
P_HTM[4139]="*Kāmacchandanīvaraṇaṃ, byāpādanīvaraṇaṃ, thinamiddhanīvaraṇaṃ, uddhaccakukkuccanīvaraṇaṃ, vicikicchānīvaraṇaṃ.**The hindrances of sensual desire, ill will, dullness and drowsiness, restlessness and remorse, and doubt.*";
P_HTM[4140]="*Ime kho, vāseṭṭha, pañca nīvaraṇā ariyassa vinaye āvaraṇātipi vuccanti, nīvaraṇātipi vuccanti, onāhanātipi vuccanti, pariyonāhanātipi vuccanti.**These five hindrances are called ‘obstacles’ and ‘hindrances’ and ‘coverings’ and ‘shrouds’ in the training of the noble one.*";
P_HTM[4141]="*Imehi kho, vāseṭṭha, pañcahi nīvaraṇehi tevijjā brāhmaṇā āvuṭā nivutā onaddhā pariyonaddhā.**The brahmins proficient in the three Vedas are hindered, obstructed, covered, and shrouded by these five hindrances.*";
P_HTM[4142]="*Te vata, vāseṭṭha, tevijjā brāhmaṇā ye dhammā brāhmaṇakārakā te dhamme pahāya vattamānā, ye dhammā abrāhmaṇakārakā te dhamme samādāya vattamānā pañcahi nīvaraṇehi āvuṭā nivutā onaddhā pariyonaddhā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā brahmānaṃ sahabyūpagā bhavissantīti, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**So long as they are so obstructed it’s impossible that they will, when the body breaks up, after death, be reborn in the company of Brahmā.*";
P_HTM[4143]="*3. Saṃsandanakathā**3. Converging*";
P_HTM[4144]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, vāseṭṭha,**What do you think, Vāseṭṭha?*";
P_HTM[4145]="*kinti te sutaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ vuddhānaṃ mahallakānaṃ ācariyapācariyānaṃ bhāsamānānaṃ, sapariggaho vā brahmā apariggaho vā”ti?**Have you heard that the brahmins who are elderly and senior, the teachers of teachers, say whether Brahmā is possessive or not?”*";
P_HTM[4146]="*“Apariggaho, bho gotama”.**“That he is not, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[4147]="*“Saveracitto vā averacitto vā”ti?**“Is his heart full of enmity or not?”*";
P_HTM[4148]="*“Averacitto, bho gotama”.**“It is not.”*";
P_HTM[4149]="*“Sabyāpajjacitto vā abyāpajjacitto vā”ti?**“Is his heart full of ill will or not?”*";
P_HTM[4150]="*“Abyāpajjacitto, bho gotama”.**“It is not.”*";
P_HTM[4151]="*“Saṅkiliṭṭhacitto vā asaṅkiliṭṭhacitto vā”ti?**“Is his heart corrupted or not?”*";
P_HTM[4152]="*“Asaṅkiliṭṭhacitto, bho gotama”.**“It is not.”*";
P_HTM[4153]="*“Vasavattī vā avasavattī vā”ti?**“Does he wield power or not?”*";
P_HTM[4154]="*“Vasavattī, bho gotama”.**“He does.”*";
P_HTM[4155]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, vāseṭṭha,**“What do you think, Vāseṭṭha?*";
P_HTM[4156]="*sapariggahā vā tevijjā brāhmaṇā apariggahā vā”ti?**Are the brahmins proficient in the three Vedas possessive or not?”*";
P_HTM[4157]="*“Sapariggahā, bho gotama”.**“They are.”*";
P_HTM[4158]="*“Saveracittā vā averacittā vā”ti?**“Are their hearts full of enmity or not?”*";
P_HTM[4159]="*“Saveracittā, bho gotama”.**“They are.”*";
P_HTM[4160]="*“Sabyāpajjacittā vā abyāpajjacittā vā”ti?**“Are their hearts full of ill will or not?”*";
P_HTM[4161]="*“Sabyāpajjacittā, bho gotama”.**“They are.”*";
P_HTM[4162]="*“Saṅkiliṭṭhacittā vā asaṅkiliṭṭhacittā vā”ti?**“Are their hearts corrupted or not?”*";
P_HTM[4163]="*“Saṅkiliṭṭhacittā, bho gotama”.**“They are.”*";
P_HTM[4164]="*“Vasavattī vā avasavattī vā”ti?**“Do they wield power or not?”*";
P_HTM[4165]="*“Avasavattī, bho gotama”.**“They do not.”*";
P_HTM[4166]="*“Iti kira, vāseṭṭha, sapariggahā tevijjā brāhmaṇā apariggaho brahmā.**“So it seems that the brahmins proficient in the three Vedas are possessive, but Brahmā is not.*";
P_HTM[4167]="*Api nu kho sapariggahānaṃ tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ apariggahena brahmunā saddhiṃ saṃsandati sametī”ti?**But would brahmins who are possessive come together and converge with Brahmā, who isn’t possessive?”*";
P_HTM[4168]="*“No hidaṃ, bho gotama”.**“No, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[4169]="*“Sādhu, vāseṭṭha, te vata, vāseṭṭha, sapariggahā tevijjā brāhmaṇā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apariggahassa brahmuno sahabyūpagā bhavissantīti, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**“Good, Vāseṭṭha! It’s impossible that the brahmins who are possessive will, when the body breaks up, after death, be reborn in the company of Brahmā, who isn’t possessive.*";
P_HTM[4170]="*Iti kira, vāseṭṭha, saveracittā tevijjā brāhmaṇā, averacitto brahmā … pe …**And it seems that the brahmins have enmity,*";
P_HTM[4171]="*sabyāpajjacittā tevijjā brāhmaṇā abyāpajjacitto brahmā …**ill will,*";
P_HTM[4172]="*saṅkiliṭṭhacittā tevijjā brāhmaṇā asaṅkiliṭṭhacitto brahmā …**corruption,*";
P_HTM[4173]="*avasavattī tevijjā brāhmaṇā vasavattī brahmā, api nu kho avasavattīnaṃ tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ vasavattinā brahmunā saddhiṃ saṃsandati sametī”ti?**and do not wield power, while Brahmā is the opposite in all these things. But would brahmins who are opposite to Brahmā in all things come together and converge with him?”*";
P_HTM[4174]="*“No hidaṃ, bho gotama”.**“No, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[4175]="*“Sādhu, vāseṭṭha, te vata, vāseṭṭha, avasavattī tevijjā brāhmaṇā kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā vasavattissa brahmuno sahabyūpagā bhavissantīti, netaṃ ṭhānaṃ vijjati.**“Good, Vāseṭṭha! It’s impossible that such brahmins will, when the body breaks up, after death, be reborn in the company of Brahmā.*";
P_HTM[4176]="*Idha kho pana te, vāseṭṭha, tevijjā brāhmaṇā āsīditvā saṃsīdanti, saṃsīditvā visāraṃ pāpuṇanti, sukkhataraṃ maññe taranti.**But here the brahmins proficient in the three Vedas sink down where they have sat, only to be torn apart; all the while imagining that they’re crossing over to drier ground.*";
P_HTM[4177]="*Tasmā idaṃ tevijjānaṃ brāhmaṇānaṃ tevijjāiriṇantipi vuccati, tevijjāvivanantipi vuccati, tevijjābyasanantipi vuccatī”ti.**That’s why the three Vedas of the brahmins are called a ‘salted land’ and a ‘barren land’ and a ‘disaster’.”*";
P_HTM[4178]="*Evaṃ vutte, vāseṭṭho māṇavo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, Vāseṭṭha said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[4179]="*“sutaṃ metaṃ, bho gotama, samaṇo gotamo brahmānaṃ sahabyatāya maggaṃ jānātī”ti.**“I have heard, Master Gotama, that you know the path to company with Brahmā.”*";
P_HTM[4180]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, vāseṭṭha.**“What do you think, Vāseṭṭha?*";
P_HTM[4181]="*Āsanne ito manasākaṭaṃ, na ito dūre manasākaṭan”ti?**Is the village of Manasākaṭa nearby?”*";
P_HTM[4182]="*“Evaṃ, bho gotama, āsanne ito manasākaṭaṃ, na ito dūre manasākaṭan”ti.**“Yes it is.”*";
P_HTM[4183]="*“Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, vāseṭṭha,**“What do you think, Vāseṭṭha?*";
P_HTM[4184]="*idhassa puriso manasākaṭe jātasaṃvaddho.**Suppose a person was born and raised in Manasākaṭa.*";
P_HTM[4185]="*Tamenaṃ manasākaṭato tāvadeva avasaṭaṃ manasākaṭassa maggaṃ puccheyyuṃ.**And as soon as they left the town some people asked them for the road to Manasākaṭa.*";
P_HTM[4186]="*Siyā nu kho, vāseṭṭha, tassa purisassa manasākaṭe jātasaṃvaddhassa manasākaṭassa maggaṃ puṭṭhassa dandhāyitattaṃ vā vitthāyitattaṃ vā”ti?**Would they be slow or hesitant to answer?”*";
P_HTM[4187]="*“No hidaṃ, bho gotama”.**“No, Master Gotama.*";
P_HTM[4188]="*“Taṃ kissa hetu”?**Why is that?*";
P_HTM[4189]="*“Amu hi, bho gotama, puriso manasākaṭe jātasaṃvaddho, tassa sabbāneva manasākaṭassa maggāni suviditānī”ti.**Because they were born and raised in Manasākaṭa. They’re well acquainted with all the roads to the village.”*";
P_HTM[4190]="*“Siyā kho, vāseṭṭha, tassa purisassa manasākaṭe jātasaṃvaddhassa manasākaṭassa maggaṃ puṭṭhassa dandhāyitattaṃ vā vitthāyitattaṃ vā, na tveva tathāgatassa brahmaloke vā brahmalokagāminiyā vā paṭipadāya puṭṭhassa dandhāyitattaṃ vā vitthāyitattaṃ vā.**“Still, it’s possible they might be slow or hesitant to answer. But the Realized One is never slow or hesitant when questioned about the Brahmā realm or the practice that leads to the Brahmā realm.*";
P_HTM[4191]="*Brahmānañcāhaṃ, vāseṭṭha, pajānāmi brahmalokañca brahmalokagāminiñca paṭipadaṃ, yathā paṭipanno ca brahmalokaṃ upapanno, tañca pajānāmī”ti.**I understand Brahmā, the Brahmā realm, and the practice that leads to the Brahmā realm, practicing in accordance with which one is reborn in the Brahmā realm.”*";
P_HTM[4192]="*Evaṃ vutte, vāseṭṭho māṇavo bhagavantaṃ etadavoca:**When he said this, Vāseṭṭha said to the Buddha,*";
P_HTM[4193]="*“sutaṃ metaṃ, bho gotama, samaṇo gotamo brahmānaṃ sahabyatāya maggaṃ desetī”ti.**“I have heard, Master Gotama, that you teach the path to company with Brahmā.*";
P_HTM[4194]="*“Sādhu no bhavaṃ gotamo brahmānaṃ sahabyatāya maggaṃ desetu ullumpatu bhavaṃ gotamo brāhmaṇiṃ pajan”ti.**Please teach us that path and elevate this generation of brahmins.”*";
P_HTM[4195]="*“Tena hi, vāseṭṭha, suṇāhi; sādhukaṃ manasi karohi; bhāsissāmī”ti.**“Well then, Vāseṭṭha, listen and pay close attention, I will speak.”*";
P_HTM[4196]="*“Evaṃ, bho”ti kho vāseṭṭho māṇavo bhagavato paccassosi.**“Yes, sir,” replied Vāseṭṭha.*";
P_HTM[4197]="*4. Brahmalokamaggadesanā**4. Teaching the Path to Brahmā*";
P_HTM[4198]="*Bhagavā etadavoca:**The Buddha said this:*";
P_HTM[4199]="*“idha, vāseṭṭha, tathāgato loke uppajjati arahaṃ, sammāsambuddho … pe …**“It’s when a Realized One arises in the world, perfected, a fully awakened Buddha …*";
P_HTM[4200]="*Evaṃ kho, vāseṭṭha, bhikkhu sīlasampanno hoti … pe …**That’s how a mendicant is accomplished in ethics. …*";
P_HTM[4201]="*tassime pañca nīvaraṇe pahīne attani samanupassato pāmojjaṃ jāyati, pamuditassa pīti jāyati, pītimanassa kāyo passambhati, passaddhakāyo sukhaṃ vedeti, sukhino cittaṃ samādhiyati.**Seeing that the hindrances have been given up in them, joy springs up. Being joyful, rapture springs up. When the mind is full of rapture, the body becomes tranquil. When the body is tranquil, they feel bliss. And when blissful, the mind becomes immersed.*";
P_HTM[4202]="*So mettāsahagatena cetasā ekaṃ disaṃ pharitvā viharati. Tathā dutiyaṃ. Tathā tatiyaṃ. Tathā catutthaṃ. Iti uddhamadho tiriyaṃ sabbadhi sabbattatāya sabbāvantaṃ lokaṃ mettāsahagatena cetasā vipulena mahaggatena appamāṇena averena abyāpajjena pharitvā viharati.**They meditate spreading a heart full of love to one direction, and to the second, and to the third, and to the fourth. In the same way above, below, across, everywhere, all around, they spread a heart full of love to the whole world—abundant, expansive, limitless, free of enmity and ill will.*";
P_HTM[4203]="*Seyyathāpi, vāseṭṭha, balavā saṅkhadhamo appakasireneva catuddisā viññāpeyya;**Suppose there was a powerful horn blower. They’d easily make themselves heard in the four directions.*";
P_HTM[4204]="*evameva kho, vāseṭṭha, evaṃ bhāvitāya mettāya cetovimuttiyā yaṃ pamāṇakataṃ kammaṃ na taṃ tatrāvasissati, na taṃ tatrāvatiṭṭhati.**In the same way, when the heart’s release by love has been developed and cultivated like this, any limited deeds they’ve done don’t remain or persist there.*";
P_HTM[4205]="*Ayampi kho, vāseṭṭha, brahmānaṃ sahabyatāya maggo.**This is a path to companionship with Brahmā.*";
P_HTM[4206]="*Puna caparaṃ, vāseṭṭha, bhikkhu karuṇāsahagatena cetasā … pe …**Furthermore, a mendicant meditates spreading a heart full of compassion …*";
P_HTM[4207]="*muditāsahagatena cetasā … pe …**They meditate spreading a heart full of rejoicing …*";
P_HTM[4208]="*upekkhāsahagatena cetasā ekaṃ disaṃ pharitvā viharati. Tathā dutiyaṃ. Tathā tatiyaṃ. Tathā catutthaṃ. Iti uddhamadho tiriyaṃ sabbadhi sabbattatāya sabbāvantaṃ lokaṃ upekkhāsahagatena cetasā vipulena mahaggatena appamāṇena averena abyāpajjena pharitvā viharati.**They meditate spreading a heart full of equanimity to one direction, and to the second, and to the third, and to the fourth. In the same way above, below, across, everywhere, all around, they spread a heart full of equanimity to the whole world—abundant, expansive, limitless, free of enmity and ill will.*";
P_HTM[4209]="*Seyyathāpi, vāseṭṭha, balavā saṅkhadhamo appakasireneva catuddisā viññāpeyya;**Suppose there was a powerful horn blower. They’d easily make themselves heard in the four directions.*";
P_HTM[4210]="*evameva kho, vāseṭṭha, evaṃ bhāvitāya upekkhāya cetovimuttiyā yaṃ pamāṇakataṃ kammaṃ na taṃ tatrāvasissati, na taṃ tatrāvatiṭṭhati.**In the same way, when the heart’s release by equanimity has been developed and cultivated like this, any limited deeds they’ve done don’t remain or persist there.*";
P_HTM[4211]="*Ayampi kho, vāseṭṭha, brahmānaṃ sahabyatāya maggo.**This too is a path to companionship with Brahmā.*";
P_HTM[4212]="*Taṃ kiṃ maññasi, vāseṭṭha,**What do you think, Vāseṭṭha?*";
P_HTM[4213]="*evaṃvihārī bhikkhu sapariggaho vā apariggaho vā”ti?**When a mendicant meditates like this, are they possessive or not?”*";
P_HTM[4214]="*“Apariggaho, bho gotama”.**“They are not.”*";
P_HTM[4215]="*“Saveracitto vā averacitto vā”ti?**“Is their heart full of enmity or not?”*";
P_HTM[4216]="*“Averacitto, bho gotama”.**“It is not.”*";
P_HTM[4217]="*“Sabyāpajjacitto vā abyāpajjacitto vā”ti?**“Is their heart full of ill will or not?”*";
P_HTM[4218]="*“Abyāpajjacitto, bho gotama”.**“It is not.”*";
P_HTM[4219]="*“Saṅkiliṭṭhacitto vā asaṅkiliṭṭhacitto vā”ti?**“Is their heart corrupted or not?”*";
P_HTM[4220]="*“Asaṅkiliṭṭhacitto, bho gotama”.**“It is not.”*";
P_HTM[4221]="*“Vasavattī vā avasavattī vā”ti?**“Do they wield power or not?”*";
P_HTM[4222]="*“Vasavattī, bho gotama”.**“They do.”*";
P_HTM[4223]="*“Iti kira, vāseṭṭha, apariggaho bhikkhu, apariggaho brahmā.**“So it seems that that mendicant is not possessive, and neither is Brahmā.*";
P_HTM[4224]="*Api nu kho apariggahassa bhikkhuno apariggahena brahmunā saddhiṃ saṃsandati sametī”ti?**Would a mendicant who is not possessive come together and converge with Brahmā, who isn’t possessive?”*";
P_HTM[4225]="*“Evaṃ, bho gotama”.**“Yes, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[4226]="*“Sādhu, vāseṭṭha, so vata vāseṭṭha apariggaho bhikkhu kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā apariggahassa brahmuno sahabyūpago bhavissatīti, ṭhānametaṃ vijjati.**“Good, Vāseṭṭha! It’s possible that a mendicant who is not possessive will, when the body breaks up, after death, be reborn in the company of Brahmā, who isn’t possessive.*";
P_HTM[4227]="*Iti kira, vāseṭṭha, averacitto bhikkhu, averacitto brahmā … pe …**And it seems that that mendicant has no enmity,*";
P_HTM[4228]="*abyāpajjacitto bhikkhu, abyāpajjacitto brahmā …**ill will,*";
P_HTM[4229]="*asaṅkiliṭṭhacitto bhikkhu, asaṅkiliṭṭhacitto brahmā …**corruption,*";
P_HTM[4230]="*vasavattī bhikkhu, vasavattī brahmā, api nu kho vasavattissa bhikkhuno vasavattinā brahmunā saddhiṃ saṃsandati sametī”ti?**and does wield power, while Brahmā is the same in all these things. Would a mendicant who is the same as Brahmā in all things come together and converge with him?”*";
P_HTM[4231]="*“Evaṃ, bho gotama”.**“Yes, Master Gotama.”*";
P_HTM[4232]="*“Sādhu, vāseṭṭha, so vata, vāseṭṭha, vasavattī bhikkhu kāyassa bhedā paraṃ maraṇā vasavattissa brahmuno sahabyūpago bhavissatīti, ṭhānametaṃ vijjatī”ti.**“Good, Vāseṭṭha! It’s possible that that mendicant will, when the body breaks up, after death, be reborn in the company of Brahmā.”*";
P_HTM[4233]="*Evaṃ vutte, vāseṭṭhabhāradvājā māṇavā bhagavantaṃ etadavocuṃ:**When he had spoken, Vāseṭṭha and Bhāradvāja said to him,*";
P_HTM[4234]="*“abhikkantaṃ, bho gotama, abhikkantaṃ, bho gotama.**“Excellent, Master Gotama! Excellent!*";
P_HTM[4235]="*Seyyathāpi, bho gotama, nikkujjitaṃ vā ukkujjeyya, paṭicchannaṃ vā vivareyya, mūḷhassa vā maggaṃ ācikkheyya, andhakāre vā telapajjotaṃ dhāreyya: ‘cakkhumanto rūpāni dakkhantī’ti; evamevaṃ bhotā gotamena anekapariyāyena dhammo pakāsito.**As if he were righting the overturned, or revealing the hidden, or pointing out the path to the lost, or lighting a lamp in the dark so people with good eyes can see what’s there, Master Gotama has made the teaching clear in many ways.*";
P_HTM[4236]="*Ete mayaṃ bhavantaṃ gotamaṃ saraṇaṃ gacchāma, dhammañca bhikkhusaṅghañca.**We go for refuge to Master Gotama, to the teaching, and to the mendicant Saṅgha.*";
P_HTM[4237]="*Upāsake no bhavaṃ gotamo dhāretu ajjatagge pāṇupete saraṇaṃ gate”ti.**From this day forth, may Master Gotama remember us as lay followers who have gone for refuge for life.”*";
P_HTM[4238]="*Tevijjasuttaṃ niṭṭhitaṃ terasamaṃ.* **";
P_HTM[4239]="*Sīlakkhandhavaggo niṭṭhito.* **";
P_HTM[4240]="*Brahmāsāmaññaambaṭṭha,* **";
P_HTM[4241]="*Soṇakūṭamahālijālinī;* **";
P_HTM[4242]="*Sīhapoṭṭhapādasubho kevaṭṭo,* **";
P_HTM[4243]="*Lohiccatevijjā terasāti.* **";
P_HTM[4244]="*Sīlakkhandhavaggapāḷi niṭṭhitā.* **";
